window.POST_CONTENTS = {
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_001-how-the-cycloid-saved-the-british-navy.md": "# how the cycloid saved the British navy\n\nDisclaimer #1: questo articolo è in inglese. La versione in italiano è qui.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!nOhi!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/248c7282-e634-4f06-8586-7ababd96471b_1572x1048.png)\n\nOn 29 September 1707 Admiral Sir Clowdisley Shovel with twenty-one ships of the Royal Navy sailed from Gibraltar for England.\n\nBritain was at war with France and, though Gibraltar had fallen into British hands in 1702, it was considered unwise for the larger ships of the fleet to remain in the Mediterranean during the winter.\n\nWeather on passage was not good. There were westerly gales from the 5th t o the first of October.\n\nThe 12nd and 13rd were squally, followed by two days of light winds.\n\nOn the 16th and 17th there were easterly gales and on the 19th north-westerly gales. On the 21st the sky cleared and several ships got observations for latitude, while sounding gave a depth of between 90 and 140 fathoms, showing that the fleet was on the edge of the Continental Shelf.\n\nThree ships having been detached to Falmouth for convoy duty on the 22nd, and no sun being visible all day, the remaining 18 ships hove to in the afternoon to obtain soundings.\n\nThen, satisfied that they were in the mouth of the English Channel and clear of all danger, the ships ran to the eastward before a favourable gale.\n\nAbout 7.30 p.m. the same day the Association, Eagle, and Romney struck the Gilstone Ledges in the Scilly Isles.\n\nOf the 1,200 men in the three ships, only one man was saved - the quartermaster of the Romney.\n\nSir Clowdisley’s body was found floating the following day and now lies in one of the largest and ugliest tombs in Westminster Abbey.\n\nThe St. George and Firebrand also struck the rocks but got off.\n\nThe latter, however, was badly holed and sank later, leaving only twenty-three survivors.\n\nThis is the beginning of chapter three of Derek Howse’s book, titled Greenwich Time and the Discovery of the Longitude , published in 19801. It is an account of the history of inventions and reasoning around the determination of longitude , mainly useful during navigation.\n\nThe disaster reported by the book’s author had been only the latest in a series for the English fleet, due not only to unfavourable weather conditions - fog, sudden ocean currents - but also to incorrect measurements of the position of landmasses.\n\nProblems of this type had been known for some time, and not only by the English navy: France, Spain, Holland, all nations that sailed the oceans. In any case, this particular disaster caused great concern among the English public, and its government decided to do something.\n\nThe Longitude Act\n\nThe story we will tell starts from the Longitude Act of 1714, one of the least controversial legislative acts proposed by the English Parliament, which took only 70 days to be transformed into law from the moment it was presented2, on June 17, 1714; Royal Assent was given on July 9 of the same year. The prize, for anyone who had “discovered longitude at sea,” was decided by the commission of experts called to decide on the responses to the petition: the commission included Isaac Newton , Samuel Clarke, Edmond Halley , and Roger Cotes.\n\nOn June 11 of that year Newton had presented to the House of Lords Committee the “state of the art” of methods - evidently insufficient, and some even impossible to implement - for measuring longitude at sea: he speaks first of a clock that measures time accurately, difficult to build so that it is precise despite the motion of the ship, temperature and humidity variations, and small variations in gravity at different latitudes.\n\nHe then moves on to a method already presented by Galileo that involved observing Jupiter’s satellites: the Italian scientist had proposed observing the planet’s moons during navigation, and recording their position comparing it with that recorded in “standard” situations - on land, that is.\n\nFrom the difference of the two measurements one would obtain the measurement of longitude.\n\nGalileo himself had realised that the proposal was unfeasible with the technology of the time due to the low precision of telescopes, and because of the ship’s motion.\n\nA third method uses the Moon, and the different moments when the Earth’s shadow covers the satellite during eclipses.\n\nThis method is also explained by Galileo, who however presents two contraindications: the first concerns the frequency with which eclipses occur, too few to allow precise navigation; while the second concerns errors in measurements that can reach even 8° of uncertainty3, too large to ensure correct navigation.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!T2Gf!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f9d116b2-b2a6-420d-893c-10424bb81d0f_1024x1212.jpeg)\n\nPortrait of Galileo Galilei, work by Justus Sustermans (1635).\n\nAfter enumerating them all, the Committee proposes the prize for the solution, based on its accuracy: a sum of £10,000 for a solution within 1°, £15,000 for a solution within two-thirds of a degree, and £20,000 for a solution within half a degree. Today, £20,000 is equivalent to approximately 3 million euros, and just over 3.5 million US dollars.\n\nImmediately many possible solutions arrive at the Committee, which implement even more precise clocks, or measurements related to lunar distances. Many of these solutions arrive, as is customary at that time, in the form of a cryptogram , in order to preserve the priority of an invention or discovery without publishing it “in clear,” thus avoiding undue appropriations.\n\nIn any case, these solutions do not solve the problem, and one will have to wait about twenty years for an invention to at least partially arrive at a solution.\n\nThe clockmaker\n\nThe character we will now talk about is John Harrison, son of a Yorkshire carpenter, born in 1693. After working with his father, together with his brother he begins from 1727 to build precision clocks: for example a pendulum called “gridiron,” whose apparatus is less affected by temperature variations4.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!I5Ep!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/0600f801-c8bf-4242-81d6-c42215ba5731_1280x1564.jpeg)\n\nPortrait of John Harrison, work by Thomas King.\n\nAfter learning the details of the competition presented by the Longitude Act, starting from 1730, and with the financial help of George Graham, one of the most famous clockmakers of his time, he begins the construction of the machines.\n\nToday they are identified with the abbreviations H1, H2, and so on, and are the various prototypes presented by Harrison to the Committee, and tested both on land and at sea. H1 was completed in 1735, H2 in 1739, H3 only in 1759, and tested during the Seven Years’ War, in 1761, together with the H4 machine, the most recent.\n\nDespite H4 fully satisfying the requirements to secure the largest prize proposed by the Committee, Harrison had to wait until 1773 to receive the entirety of the prize.\n\nMoreover, another method we have already discussed also proved to work: the method of lunar distances, which requires measuring the position of fixed stars relative to the Moon, and from the different values obtained in different parts of the globe calculate longitude.\n\nBoth these methods were initially impractical, the first because of the high cost of building such precise clocks, and the second because of the time needed to perform the necessary calculations.\n\nOver time, both methods became more widespread, because large-scale construction of clocks reduced their cost, and because of simplifications in calculations.\n\nIn all this, how does the cycloid intervene?\n\nThe Helen of geometry\n\nLet’s start with the pendulum, extensively studied by Galileo. The equation linking the period of the pendulum for small oscillations was obtained by Christiaan Huygens, a Dutch scientist of the XVII century CE, and is the following:\n\nwhere T is the period of the pendulum, that is the time that passes for the pendulum to pass through a point and then return to it, g is the acceleration of gravity, and L the length of the pendulum. As can be seen, the period of the pendulum depends on the length of the pendulum itself. This is one of the problems to solve if one wants to make the pendulum capable of measuring time precisely, independently of the length of the pendulum, which can vary, for example, due to temperature or humidity.\n\nHuygens is considered the inventor of the pendulum clock, having created the first example in 1656. Huygens himself however realizes, as Marin Mersenne had already done - a French scholar active a few decades before Huygens - that the pendulum does not have isochronous oscillations, that is, that the period of oscillations is not independent of the amplitude of oscillations, which Galileo instead thought.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!qm83!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1de2082d-6764-497b-9d55-9b331919b854_1280x1677.jpeg)\n\nChristiaan Huygens, work by Caspar Netscher (1671).\n\nFor this reason, Huygens studies a way to allow the isochronism of the pendulum, and finds it in a figure called the cycloid .\n\nThe cycloid is the curve that is formed when a point on a circumference rolls along a straight line (as in the figure below).\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!xNMR!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_lossy/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/0e67fe32-ef5f-461c-ac30-3d4f54db8963_400x200.gif)\n\nCycloid. Credits here.\n\nHuygens showed that when a pendulum is made to oscillate between two cycloidal curves, the pendulum obtained has the same period independent of the speed of oscillations.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!YRK2!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_lossy/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/37017733-9040-4d50-bf98-bb5b861aab75_360x232.gif)\n\n“Cycloidal” oscillations of the pendulum. Credits here here.\n\nThe equation of the cycloid, which allows it to be drawn on a Cartesian plane, is the following:\n\nwhere r is the radius of the circle we make “roll” on the x-axis.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Dp-k!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_lossy/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/7d83722a-0133-4c4f-8a5a-399fc6aad634_735x398.gif)\n\nCredits here.\n\nThe title of this paragraph is “the Helen of geometry,” and the reason is linked both to disputes over its discovery, which some date to the ancient Greeks, others to Galileo, still others to Mersenne, and to its marvelous properties.\n\nLet’s return to the clock built by Harrison. The English inventor uses the cycloid to make the mechanism isochronous, and improve performance from the H3 model to the H4 model. Below is the diagram published in “ The Principles of Mr. Harrison’s Timekeeper ”, published in 1767.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!mEsk!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ac6e370d-0065-4aa0-8aa0-90dcd9ab0133_595x881.jpeg)\n\nDrawings of the H4 clock. Credits here.\n\nIn Harrison’s design, the cycloid appears in the curves circled at the top left. Below is a detail of the image above.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!816s!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/952f1692-7f23-4fa2-8641-0d0cd15c6e56_468x548.png)\n\nInside the ellipse do you see those curves that start from the top and descend to form those kinds of triangles at whose center there is the letter b ? Those are branches of cycloids.\n\nIt is with this new mechanism, more stable and accurate, that Harrison manages to exceed the requirements requested by the Longitude Act of 1714 and to equip English ships with the necessary instruments to carry out research activities in the oceans. After a few decades, mass production of clocks of this type will allow their diffusion on all ships of the English fleet, and other countries will also use this invention.\n\nAs for Harrison, he dies on March 24, 1776, eight months after Captain Cook’s return from a voyage that had unequivocally demonstrated that that type of clock was effective during navigation5.\n\nToday the most advanced systems allow obtaining an accuracy that is on the order of centimeters, enough to avoid islets and rocks, enough to avoid the disaster of the Scilly Isles.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!fQwg!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/81674adf-2e63-4b29-82be-77d0e4fc88e2_2524x2500.jpeg)\n\nThe Scilly Isles off Great Britain. Credits here.\n\nRead the series “on the motion of the Earth”:\n\nBibliography:\n\nGreenwich time and the discovery of the longitude, by Howse, Derek (Oxford University Press 1980)\n\nThe quest for longitude : the proceedings of the Longitude Symposium (Harvard University Press 1996)\n\nNotes\n\n1 the text comes from “The Last Voyage of Sir Clowdisley Shovell,” by May W.E. (1960)\n\n2 as A.J. Turner writes in “In the Wake of the Act, but Mainly Before,” part of the book “The quest for longitude : the proceedings of the Longitude Symposium.”\n\n3 D. Howse, Greenwich time and the discovery of the longitude, p. 90.\n\n4 the precision of a pendulum when used as a time measuring apparatus depends on the uniformity of the pendulum’s movements, which has a certain length and in case of thermal variations tends to shorten and lengthen: since the length of the pendulum is the quantity linked to the precision of measurement, a good pendulum must undergo very small variations in length as temperature varies.\n\n5 D. Howse, Greenwich time and the discovery of the longitude, p. 72.\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_002-atomos-3.md": "Rimane nella lingua che utilizziamo riferirsi a qualcosa di singolo, non divisibile ulteriormente, come a un atomo .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b95a86fd-370a-4373-a83b-49d276606b7f_4000x1000.png)\n\nLa lingua Karitiana del popolo omonimo, nella regione Rondônia del Brasile, ha i tempi verbali divisi in modo binario: futuro , non-futuro .\n\nLa lingua Yagua della tribù omonima, nelle regioni vicino al Rio delle Amazzoni, ha otto tempi verbali, che includono tra gli altri: un tempo per descrivere avvenimenti accaduti tra un mese e un anno fa; un tempo per le cose che stanno per accadere; e un tempo per le cose lontane nel futuro.\n\nLa lingua Aymara delle popolazioni omonime che vivono nelle Ande e nell'Altiplano definisce l' anno scorso come nayra , ovvero \" l'anno che posso vedere \".\n\nL'espressione \" ancha nayra pachana \", che si traduce con \"tanto tempo fa\", significa \"il tempo molto davanti a me\". Il passato è davanti a chi parla, visibile, mentre il futuro, inaccessibile e oscuro, è dietro.\n\nWe still use the word atom to refer to something singular and no longer divisible.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/bba75f05-ad2b-407c-85fc-5576365cb03d_4000x1000.png)\n\nThe Karitiana language of the people of the same name, in the Rondônia region of Brazil, has verb tenses divided in a binary way: future , non-future .\n\nThe Yagua language of the tribe of the same name, in the regions near the Amazon River, has eight verb tenses, which include among others: a tense to describe events that happened between a month and a year ago; a tense for things that are about to happen; and a tense for things far in the future.\n\nThe Aymara language of the populations of the same name who live in the Andes and the Altiplano defines last year as nayra, meaning \" the year I can see \".\n\nThe expression \" ancha nayra pachana \", which translates to \"a long time ago\", means \"the time very much in front of me\". The past is in front of the speaker, visible, while the future, inaccessible and obscure, is behind.\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_003-atomos-2.md": "Rimane nella lingua che utilizziamo riferirsi a qualcosa di singolo, non divisibile ulteriormente, come a un atomo .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b95a86fd-370a-4373-a83b-49d276606b7f_4000x1000.png)\n\nTecnica come trucco [...] per sistemare il mondo così che non dobbiamo viverlo concretamente.\n\n- Max Frisch, Homo Faber\n\nWe still use the word atom to refer to something singular and no longer divisible.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/bba75f05-ad2b-407c-85fc-5576365cb03d_4000x1000.png)\n\nTechnology ... the knack of so arranging the world so that we need not experience it.\n\n- Max Frisch, Homo Faber\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_004-come-la-cicloide-salv-la-marina-inglese.md": "# come la cicloide salvò la marina inglese\n\nDisclaimer #1: this article is in Italian. The English is here.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!wKjD!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2be87920-05f4-4827-9bf9-ff185dc5e828_1572x1048.png)\n\nIl 29 settembre 1707 l’Ammiraglio Sir Clowdisley Shovel salpò da Gibilterra verso l’Inghilterra con ventuno navi della Royal Navy.\n\nLa Gran Bretagna era in guerra con la Francia e, sebbene Gibilterra fosse caduta in mani britanniche nel 1702, si riteneva imprudente che le navi più grandi della flotta [inglese] rimanessero nel Mediterraneo durante l’inverno.\n\nLe condizioni meteorologiche durante la traversata non furono buone.\n\nCi furono tempeste da ovest dal 5 al 10 ottobre.\n\nIl 12 e il 13 ci furono raffiche di vento, seguite da due giorni di venti leggeri.\n\nIl 16 e il 17 ci furono tempeste da est e il 19 tempeste da nord-ovest.\n\nIl 21 il cielo si schiarì e diverse navi riuscirono a effettuare osservazioni per la latitudine, mentre lo scandagli indicò una profondità tra i 90 e i 140 bracci, mostrando che la flotta si trovava sul bordo della piattaforma continentale.\n\nTre navi essendo state distaccate a Falmouth per servizio di scorta il 22, e non essendo visibile il sole per tutto il giorno, le restanti 18 navi si misero in panna nel pomeriggio per effettuare gli scandagli.\n\nPoi, convinti di trovarsi nell’imboccatura della Manica e al sicuro da ogni pericolo, le navi procedettero verso est spinte da una burrasca favorevole.\n\nVerso le 19:30 dello stesso giorno l’Association, l’Eagle e la Romney si schiantarono contro gli Scogli di Gilstone nelle Isole Scilly.\n\nDei 1.200 uomini nelle tre navi, si salvò un solo uomo - il quartiermastro della Romney.\n\nIl corpo di Sir Clowdisley fu ritrovato galleggiante il giorno seguente e ora giace in una delle tombe più grandi e brutte dell’Abbazia di Westminster.\n\nAnche la St. George e la Firebrand si schiantarono contro gli scogli ma riuscirono a liberarsi.\n\nQuest’ultima, tuttavia, era gravemente danneggiata e affondò successivamente, lasciando solo ventitrè sopravvissuti.\n\nQuesto è l’inizio del capitolo tre del libro di Derek Howse, intitolato Greenwich Time and the Discovery of the Longitude , pubblicato nel 19801. E’ un racconto sulla storia delle invenzioni e dei ragionamenti intorno alla determinazione della longitudine , principalmente utile durante la navigazione.\n\nIl disastro riportato dall’autore del libro era stato solo l’ultimo di una serie per la flotta inglese, a causa non solo condizioni meteo sfavorevoli - nebbia, correnti marine improvvise - ma anche di errate misurazioni della posizione delle terre emerse.\n\nProblemi di questo tipo erano conosciuti da tempo, e non solo dalla marina inglese: Francia, Spagna, Olanda, tutte le nazioni che navigavano gli oceani.\n\nAd ogni modo, questo disastro in particolare provocò grande preoccupazione nel pubblico inglese, e il suo governo si decise a fare qualcosa.\n\nQuest'anno, diventa un abbonato a pagamento per supportare questa pubblicazione!\n\nGrazie! E se vuoi, condividila!\n\nIl Longitude Act\n\nLa storia di cui parleremo parte dal Longitude Act del 1714, uno dei meno controversi atti legislativi proposti dal Parlamento inglese, che impiegò solo 70 giorni per essere trasformato in legge dal momento in cui fu presentata2, il 17 giugno del 1714; l’Assenso Reale fu posto il 9 luglio dello stesso anno.\n\nIl premio, per chiunque avesse “scoperto la longitudine in mare”, fu deciso dalla commissione di esperti chiamati a decidere delle risposte alla petizione: nella commissione comparivano Isaac Newton , Samuel Clarke, Edmond Halley , e Roger Cotes.\n\nL’11 giugno di quell’anno Newton aveva esposto alla Commissione della Camera dei Lord lo “stato dell’arte” dei metodi - evidentemente insufficienti, e alcuni persino impossibili da implementare - di misurare la longitudine in mare: parla per primo di un orologio che misuri il tempo in modo esatto, difficile da costruire in modo che sia preciso nonostante il moto della nave, le escursioni di temperatura e di umidità, e le piccole variazioni di gravità a differenti latitudini.\n\nPassa poi a un metodo già esposto da Galileo che prevedeva osservare i satelliti di Giove: lo scienziato italiano aveva proposto di osservare le lune del pianeta durante la navigazione, e registrarne la posizione confrontandola con quella registrata in situazioni “standard” - a terra, si intende. Dalla differenza delle due misure si sarebbe ottenuta la misura della longitudine. Galileo stesso si era reso conto che la proposta era irrealizzabile con la tecnologia del tempo per via della bassa precisione dei telescopi, e a causa del moto della nave.\n\nUn terzo metodo utilizza la Luna, e i differenti momenti in cui l’ombra della Terra copre il satellite durante le eclissi. Anche questo metodo è spiegato da Galileo, che però porta due controindicazioni: la prima riguarda la frequenza con cui le eclissi avvengono, troppo poche per permettere una navigazione precisa; mentre la seconda riguarda gli errori nelle misure che possono arrivare anche a 8° di incertezza3, troppo grandi per assicurare la corretta navigazione.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!T2Gf!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f9d116b2-b2a6-420d-893c-10424bb81d0f_1024x1212.jpeg)\n\nRitratto di Galileo Galilei, opera di Justus Sustermans (1635).\n\nDopo averli enumerati tutti, la Commissione propone il premio per la soluzione, in base all’accuratezza della stessa: una somma di 10’000 sterline per una soluzione entro 1°, di 15’000 sterline per una soluzione entro due terzi di grado, e di 20’000 sterline per una soluzione entro mezzo grado.\n\nAl giorno d’oggi, 20’000 sterline equivalgono all’incirca a 3milioni di euro, e poco più di 3,5milioni di dollari US.\n\nImmediatamente arrivano alla Commissione molte possibili soluzioni, che implementano degli orologi ancora più precisi, o delle misure legate alle distanze lunari. Molte di queste soluzioni arrivano, come è consuetudine a quel tempo, sotto forma di crittogramma , in modo da preservare la priorità di una invenzione o una scoperta senza però pubblicarla “in chiaro”, evitando quindi indebite appropriazioni.\n\nAd ogni modo, queste soluzioni non risolvono il problema, e si dovrà attendere una ventina d’anni affinché un’invenzione possa almeno in parte arrivare a una soluzione.\n\nIl costruttore di orologi\n\nIl personaggio di cui parleremo ora è John Harrison, figlio di un carpentiere dello Yorkshire, nato nel 1693. Dopo aver lavorato con il padre, insieme al fratello inizia nel 1727 a costruire orologi di precisione: ad esempio un pendolo detto “a griglia”, il cui apparato risente meno delle variazioni di temperatura4.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!I5Ep!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/0600f801-c8bf-4242-81d6-c42215ba5731_1280x1564.jpeg)\n\nRitratto di John Harrison, opera di Thomas King.\n\nDopo aver conosciuto i dettagli della competizione presentati dal Longitude Act, a partire dal 1730, e con l’aiuto economico di George Graham, uno dei costruttori di orologi più famosi del suo tempo, inizia la costruzione delle macchine. Oggi vengono identificate con le sigle H1, H2, e così via, e sono i diversi prototipi presentati da Harrison alla Commissione, e testati sia a terra che in mare. H1 viene completato nel 1735, H2 nel 1739, H3 solo nel 1759, e testato durante la Guerra dei Sette Anni, nel 1761, insieme alla macchina H4, la più recente.\n\nNonostante la H4 soddisfacesse appieno i requisiti per assicurarsi il premio più grande proposto dalla Commissione, Harrison dovette aspettare il 1773 per ricevere la totalità del premio.\n\nInoltre, anche un altro metodo di cui abbiamo già parlato dimostrò di funzionare: il metodo delle distanze lunari, che richiede di misurare la posizione delle stelle fisse rispetto alla Luna, e dai valori diversi che si ottengono in diversi parti del globo calcolare la longitudine.\n\nEntrambi questi metodi erano inizialmente poco praticabili, il primo per via dell’alto costo di costruzione di orologi così precisi, e il secondo per il tempo necessario per eseguire i calcoli necessari.\n\nCol tempo, entrambi i metodi diventarono più diffusi, perché la costruzione in scala degli orologi ne abbatté il costo, e per via di semplificazioni nei calcoli.\n\nIn tutto questo, come interviene la cicloide?\n\nL’Elena della geometria\n\nPartiamo dal pendolo, studiato estesamente da Galileo. L’equazione che lega il periodo del pendolo per piccole oscillazioni fu ottenuta da Christiaan Huygens, uno scienziato nederlandese del XVII secolo CE, ed è la seguente:\n\ndove T è il periodo del pendolo, ovvero il tempo che passa affinché il pendolo passi in un punto e poi vi ritorni, g è l’accelerazione di gravità, e L la lunghezza del pendolo.\n\nCome si vede, il periodo del pendolo dipende dalla lunghezza del pendolo stesso. Questo è uno dei problemi da risolvere se si vuole rendere il pendolo capace di misurare il tempo con precisione, indipendentemente dalla lunghezza del pendolo, che può variare, ad esempio, per via di temperatura o umidità.\n\nHuygens è considerato l’inventore dell’orologio a pendolo, avendo creato il primo esemplare nel 1656. Lo stesso Huygens però si rende conto, come aveva già fatto Marin Mersenne - studioso francese attivo qualche decennio prima di Huygens - che il pendolo non ha oscillazioni isocrone , ovvero che il periodo delle oscillazioni non è indipendente dalla ampiezza delle oscillazioni, cosa che invece pensava Galileo.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!qm83!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1de2082d-6764-497b-9d55-9b331919b854_1280x1677.jpeg)\n\nChristiaan Huygens, opera di Caspar Netscher (1671).\n\nPer questo motivo, Huygens studia un modo per permettere l’isocronismo del pendolo, e lo trova in una figura detta cicloide .\n\nLa cicloide è la curva che viene a formarsi quando un punto di una circonferenza rotola lungo una linea retta (come nella figura qui sotto).\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!xNMR!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_lossy/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/0e67fe32-ef5f-461c-ac30-3d4f54db8963_400x200.gif)\n\nCicloide. Crediti qui.\n\nHuygens mostrò che quando si fa oscillare un pendolo tra due curve cicloidi, il pendolo che si ottiene ha lo stesso periodo indipendentemente dalla velocità delle oscillazioni.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!YRK2!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_lossy/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/37017733-9040-4d50-bf98-bb5b861aab75_360x232.gif)\n\nOscillazioni “cicloidi” del pendolo. Crediti qui.\n\nL’equazione della cicloide, che permette di disegnarla su un piano cartesiano, è la seguente:\n\ndove r è il raggio del cerchio che facciamo “rotolare” sull’asse x.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Dp-k!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_lossy/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/7d83722a-0133-4c4f-8a5a-399fc6aad634_735x398.gif)\n\nCrediti qui.\n\nIl titolo di questo paragrafo è “l’Elena della geometria”, e il motivo è legato sia alle contese sulla sua scoperta, che alcuni datano agli antichi greci, altri a Galileo, altri ancora a Mersenne, che alle sue meravigliose proprietà.\n\nTorniamo all’orologio costruito da Harrison. L’inventore inglese utilizza la cicloide per rendere il meccanismo isocrono, e migliorare le prestazioni dal modello H3 al modello H4. Di seguito lo schema pubblicato ne “ I principi dell’orologio di Mr Harrison” , pubblicato nel 1767.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!mEsk!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ac6e370d-0065-4aa0-8aa0-90dcd9ab0133_595x881.jpeg)\n\nDisegni dell’orologio H4. Crediti qui.\n\nNel progetto di Harrison, la cicloide compare nelle curve sopra in cerchio in alto a sinistra. Di seguito un dettaglio dell’immagine di sopra.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!816s!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/952f1692-7f23-4fa2-8641-0d0cd15c6e56_468x548.png)\n\nall’interno dell’ellisse vedi quelle curve che partono dall’alto a scendono a formare quelle specie di triangoli al cui centro c’è la lettera b ? Quelle sono rami di cicloidi.\n\nE’ con questo nuovo meccanismo, più stabile e accurato, che Harrison riesce a superare i requisiti richiesti dal Longitude Act del 1714 e a dotare le navi inglesi degli strumenti necessari per svolgere le attività di ricerca negli oceani. Dopo alcuni decenni, la costruzione in serie degli orologi di questo tipo ne permetteranno la diffusione su tutte le navi della flotta inglese, e anche altri paesi utilizzeranno questa invenzione.\n\nQuanto ad Harrison, muore il 24 Marzo 1776, otto mesi dopo il ritorno del Capitano Cook da un viaggio che aveva dimostrato in modo inequivocabile che quel tipo di orologio era efficace durante la navigazione5.\n\nAl giorno d’oggi i sistemi più avanzati permettono di ottenere una accuratezza che è dell’ordine dei centimetri, abbastanza per evitare isolotti e scogli, abbastanza da evitare il disastro delle Isole di Scilly.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!fQwg!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/81674adf-2e63-4b29-82be-77d0e4fc88e2_2524x2500.jpeg)\n\nLe Isole di Scilly al largo della Gran Bretagna. Credits qui.\n\nArticoli della serie “sul moto della Terra”:\n\nBibliografia:\n\nGreenwich time and the discovery of the longitude, by Howse, Derek (Oxford University Press 1980)\n\nThe quest for longitude : the proceedings of the Longitude Symposium (Harvard University Press 1996)\n\nQuesta newsletter è una di tre: le altre due sono Last Scattering Surface, e Space of Sound.\n\nTutte le pubblicazioni sono gratuite e puoi consultare tutti gli articoli senza paywall.\n\nSe vuoi, puoi iscriverti qui e qui.\n\nInfine, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n\nCiao e a presto!\n\nNote\n\n1 il testo, qui proposto in traduzione, viene da “The Last Voyage of Sir Clowdisley Shovel”, di May W.E. (1960)\n\n2 come scrive A.J. Turner in “In the Wake of the Act, but Mainly Before”, parte del libro “The quest for longitude : the proceedings of the Longitude Symposium”.\n\n3 D. Howse, Greenwich time and the discovery of the longitude, p. 90.\n\n4 la precisione di un pendolo quando viene usato come apparato di misura del tempo dipende dalla uniformità dei movimenti del pendolo, che ha una certa lunghezza e nel caso di escursioni termiche tende ad accorciarsi e ad allungarsi: poiché è la lunghezza del pendolo la grandezza legata alla precisione della misura, un buon pendolo deve subire piccolissime variazioni di lunghezza al variare della temperatura.\n\n5 D. Howse, Greenwich time and the discovery of the longitude, p. 72.\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_005-atomos-1.md": "Rimane nella lingua che utilizziamo riferirsi a qualcosa di singolo, non divisibile ulteriormente, come a un atomo .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b95a86fd-370a-4373-a83b-49d276606b7f_4000x1000.png)\n\nC'era una volta un famoso scienziato che si chiamava Galileo Galilei. Fu processato dall'Inquisizione e costretto a ritrattare i propri insegnamenti. Ciò causò grande agitazione e per ben duecentocinquant'anni e più il caso continuò a suscitare indignazione ed eccitazione, molto tempo dopo che l'opinione pubblica aveva vinto la sua battaglia e la Chiesa era diventata tollerante nei confronti della scienza.\n\nMa adesso questa è una storia molto vecchia e io credo che abbia perso il suo interesse. La scienza galileiana non ha più nemici: la sua vita, d'ora in poi, è sicura. La vittoria ottenuta tanto tempo fa fu definitiva e tutto tace, ormai, su questo fronte. Così, al giorno d'oggi assumiamo un punto di vista distaccato a proposito della faccenda, perché abbiamo finalmente imparato a pensare in chiave storica e a comprendere ambo le parti di una disputa. E nessuno si dà la pena di ascoltare un seccatore che non può dimenticare i vecchi crucci.\n\n- Karl Popper, La scienza di Galileo e il suo nuovo tradimento , in Tre punti di vista a proposito della conoscenza umana . Pubblicato originariamente in Contemporary British Philosophy , terza serie, a cura di H. D. Lewis, 1956. (Traduzione di Mario Trinchero)\n\nWe still use the word atom to refer to something singular and no longer divisible.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/bba75f05-ad2b-407c-85fc-5576365cb03d_4000x1000.png)\n\nOnce upon a time there was a famous scientist whose name was Galileo Galilei. He\n\nwas tried by the Inquisition, and forced to recant his teaching. This caused a great stir;\n\nand for well over two hundred and fifty years the case continued to arouse indignation\n\nand excitement–long after public opinion had won its victory, and the Church had\n\nbecome tolerant of science.\n\nBut this is by now a very old story, and I fear it has lost its interest. For Galilean\n\nscience has no enemies left, it seems: its life hereafter is secure. The victory won long\n\nago was final, and all is quiet on this front. So we take a detached view of the affair\n\nnowadays, having learned at last to think historically and to understand both sides of a\n\ndispute. And nobody cares to listen to the bore who can't forget an old grievance.\n\n- Karl Popper, The science of Galileo and its most recent betrayal , in Three views concerning human knowledge . Originally published in Contemporary British Philosophy, third series, edited by H. D. Lewis, 1956.\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_006-atomos-0.md": "[Italian version here, the English version is below]\n\nGli atomi erano considerate le entità ultime e indivisibili della materia e dell’Universo da alcuni filosofi antichi, e anche se oggi sappiamo che non sono davvero indivisibili, che altre particelle più piccole compongono questi oggetti, rimane nella lingua che utilizziamo riferirsi a qualcosa di singolo, non divisibile ulteriormente, come a un atomo.\n\nBenvenuti,\n\nquesta è il numero 0 di una nuova rubrica della newsletter, chiamata ATOMOS .\n\nIn questa rubrica inseriremo\n\npiccole citazioni,\n\nminuscole storie,\n\nmicroscopiche descrizioni,\n\ninvisibili spiegazioni.\n\nSul mondo, sul tempo, sulla storia, sulle cose trasversali che ci attraversano.\n\nIniziamo, un passo alla volta.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b95a86fd-370a-4373-a83b-49d276606b7f_4000x1000.png)\n\nnon si inizia un poema\n\nsi abbandona la propria vita.\n\n- Mark Leidner\n\n[Qui sotto c’è la versione inglese, la versione in italiano è qui sopra]\n\nAncient philosophers considered atoms the ultimate and indivisible entities of matter and the Universe, and although we now know they are not truly indivisible, that even smaller particles compose these objects, we still use the word atom to refer to something singular and no longer divisible.\n\nWelcome,\n\nthis is issue 0 of a new section of the newsletter, called ATOMOS .\n\nIn this section we’ll feature\n\nbrief quotes,\n\ntiny stories,\n\nmicroscopic descriptions,\n\nand invisible explanations.\n\nAbout the world, about time, about history, about the crossing things that pass through us.\n\nLet’s begin, one step at a time.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/bba75f05-ad2b-407c-85fc-5576365cb03d_4000x1000.png)\n\none does not begin a poem\n\none abandon one’s life.\n\n- Mark Leidner\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_007-astronomical-history-of-christmas.md": "Disclaimer #1: questo articolo è in inglese. La versione italiana è arrivata insieme a questa newsletter. Puoi raggiungerla e leggerla anche sul mio profilo.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/acbfb585-0d7d-4235-b043-db233a73b0ec_1080x1350.png)\n\nAt Christmas, subscribe to this newsletter for free!\n\nGet 50% off for 1 year\n\nThanks!\n\nWelcome!\n\nIn this episode we will talk about the construction of the history of Christmas, trying to understand the connections of this holiday with other rituals from other mythologies, and then its astronomical foundations, which falls shortly after the darkest day of the year (in the northern hemisphere).\n\nWe will talk about stars that were not stars, and perhaps not even comets; of three kings who were not kings, and who were not three; of calendar choices dictated by the Sun and opposed to the Sun; of prophecies and astrologers, of planets and divinities.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2b46b663-399f-4be8-902a-d94414395fc4_4222x4177.jpeg)\n\nA Winter Scene with Skaters near a Castle, by Hendrick Averkamp (1607). Credits here.\n\nThe construction of Christmas\n\nThe Church of Rome and the branches of the Protestant Reformation celebrate on December 25 of the Gregorian calendar each year the feast of the Nativity, that is, the birth of Jesus, considered the Son of God by these religions.\n\nThe Russian Orthodox Church, the Serbian one, and the Church of Jerusalem also celebrate this feast on December 25, but since they adopt the Julian calendar, there is a difference of 13 days between the dates on which the same feast is celebrated between them and the rest of the Christian world, which is equivalent to January 7 of the Gregorian calendar.\n\nThe first things we can ask ourselves are:\n\n1) what exactly does the Christian religion celebrate on Christmas day?\n\n2) since when has December 25 been celebrated?\n\nTo answer these and other questions we will have to return to the initial sources of early Christianity, when this religion was not yet organised and hierarchical, and in which it seems it was not fundamental to understand the date of Jesus’ birth.\n\nThe Gospels, that is, the works we have available to obtain information about the life of Jesus, do not speak of the date of his birth. The Gospels that speak of the so-called “Nativity” are two: that of Matthew and that of Luke, two of the four figures defined as “evangelists.” The Gospel of Luke is dated around 80 CE, while that of Matthew dates around 70 CE.\n\nIn those years the common sentiment of the religious communities of Christian inspiration was directed more toward the death and resurrection of Christ than toward his birth. Initially therefore, that is, for the first century and a half after the death of Christ (datable around the year 30 CE) no one celebrated his birth on a specific day.\n\nOne of the first to pose the problem of Jesus’ birth is Origen , a theologian originally from Alexandria in Egypt born in 185 CE. Despite his opinion that “only pagans celebrated the day of their own birth,” he nonetheless has something to say about the story of the Nativity. We will encounter him again when we try to understand which celestial body the Magi observed during their journey to Bethlehem.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/949ffd4c-5e7a-4b60-8224-6d4dbf9339ea_799x613.jpeg)\n\nChristmas Cactus. Credits here.\n\nThe concept of Epiphany, that is, of the manifestation of divinity in the world, is a concept elaborated by the Christian Gnostic tradition, interested in obtaining salvation through knowledge, rather than through the tradition of orthodoxy.\n\nThe Gnostic sect of Egyptian Christians called the Basilideans, founded in Alexandria, Egypt in the II century CE, celebrated this manifestation on the day of Jesus’ baptism, and did so on January 6, spending the vigil of this feast reading sacred texts.\n\nSextus Julius Africanus , a Roman writer datable between the 2nd and 3rd centuries CE, wrote in the Chronographíai (chronography of the world), that the incarnation of Jesus had occurred on March 25, 1 CE, and that his birth had occurred exactly nine months later, that is, December 25.\n\nThis dating is influenced by two factors.\n\nThe first, of astronomical origin, is due to the fact that March 25 was considered at the time the day of the spring equinox, that is, the day from which the hours of daylight in a day exceeded those of darkness, a phenomenon that was well connected to the coming of Jesus, who would free the world from the darkness of paganism.\n\nThe second, properly literary, betrays the fact that in antiquity it was customary to trace the birth and death, and other relevant events in the life of an important individual, to the same day. Here we begin to glimpse the relationship that exists with astral mythologies and ritual calendars.\n\nA text from 243 CE, titled De Pascha computus , by an author who goes by the name of Pseudo-Cyprian , gives the date of Jesus’ birth as March 28. This work is presented as the improvement of a previous work by Hippolytus of Rome, a Roman theologian, who had arrived at the date of April 2 CE.\n\nWorks of this kind accumulate, until the IV century CE, when in the East the date accepted by all becomes January 6.\n\nIn the West the debate is also influenced by the presence of contemporary solar cults, similarly to what happens in the East.\n\nIn Rome, however, such cults are also embraced by the senatorial elite and the imperial court, which already with Elagabalus , emperor from 218 to 222 CE and by hereditary succession high priest of El-Gabal (the Sun god), had seen the cult of the sun introduced with the feast of Sol Invictus .\n\nIn the following decades the cult will be associated with other divinities we will discuss, such as Helios and Mithras .\n\nIn 274 CE the emperor Aurelian officially establishes the cult of Natalis Solis Invicti , that is, of the birth of the Unconquered Sun, which falls on December 25. In that period in fact the winter solstice fell precisely on that day, which therefore was perfect for celebrating a solar feast, and the return of the Sun god, never defeated.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d81e7a2e-5468-492b-afdc-3224e5aa234a_4000x3002.jpeg)\n\nPreparing for Christmas (Plucking Turkeys), by Francis William Edmonds American (1851). Credits here.\n\nIn 336 the local Church of Rome establishes December 25 as the Dies Natalis Christi . The overlap of this feast with the Natalis Solis Invicti is already noted by the Chronograph of 354 , a text on the Roman calendar.\n\nIn 379 the date is also attested by the Church of Constantinople, in 386 by that of Antioch, and subsequently in the 5th century CE by the Church of Egypt, and in the 6th by that of Jerusalem.\n\nToday the Armenian Church is one of the few to celebrate the Nativity of Jesus on January 6.\n\nThe contrast between the two feasts is also noted by the Doctors of the Church: Augustine of Hippo admonishes Christians who celebrate the Sun in the last days of the year, and exhorts them to worship not “the Sun, but [...] he who created the Sun.”\n\nLeo I , pope from 440 to 461 CE, exhorts the faithful not to worship the Sun. Despite this, beneath St. Peter’s Basilica, Jesus is depicted on a chariot, in a work titled Christo Sole (Christ the Sun).\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6e48da3e-226d-47bb-b604-717553432830_564x800.jpeg)\n\nCristo-Sole. Credits Fabbrica di S. Pietro.\n\nLet’s take a step back: why is it that, despite the multiplicity of dates proposed during the first centuries of Christian history, the most important Churches of East and West chose the two days of January 6 and December 25 as the dates of Jesus’ birth, and then (almost) all converged on the second?\n\nLet’s start with Epiphanius of Salamis , a 4th century CE bishop in Salamis, on the island of Cyprus, who in Adversus haereses (Against Heresies), speaks of the night between January 5 and 6, and of January 6 two years later as the arrival of the Magi. He goes so far as to suggest a specific date: the night of January 5, 2 BCE.\n\nBright note in the margin #11\n\nThe concept of the vigil of a feast, and its celebration starting from the night before it, is connected to the Jewish tradition, in which the following day began from the sunset of the previous one.\n\nIt is for this reason therefore that over time the tradition of celebrating the vigil of feasts has been codified.\n\nEpiphanius connects the birth of Jesus to the date of the winter solstice, shifting it 13 days from it; according to him this shift is explained by the fact that 13 is also the number of the apostles plus Jesus himself.\n\nMoreover, since pagans also celebrate on that date the birth of Aion ( Aeon ), a divinity linked to cyclical time and subsequently connected by Neoplatonic scholars with Dionysus , he recognizes in this the fact that even pagans “recognize a part of the truth.”\n\nRegarding the cult of Aion on the night between January 5 and 6, Epiphanius says:\n\n“In Alexandria, in the so-called Koreion: this is a large temple, seat of the sanctuary of Kore. All night long [the worshippers of the cult] stay awake and sing toward the idol with songs and flutes. At the end of the nocturnal celebration, at the crowing of the rooster, they descend into the underground sanctuary bearing torches and carry a wooden idol which they place naked on a litter.”\n\nand again:\n\n“Today, at this hour, Kore, the Virgin, gives birth to Aion. [...] And this also happens in the city of Petra... in the temple of the idol, they worship the Virgin in the Arabic language, calling her Khaabu, which translates to Kore or “virgin”; and the one who is born [they call] Dusares, which means “the only one begotten by the Lord”.”\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/37b56dd7-1775-436a-9934-7bbe22327538_960x751.jpeg)\n\nThe dance to the music of time, by Nicolas Poussin (1640). Credits here.\n\nJerome , bishop of Stridon in the IV century CE, is convinced that the birth of Jesus could only have occurred on the day of the solstice, because of cosmic harmony.\n\nThe tradition elaborates further, and John Chrysostom , patriarch of Constantinople in the IV century CE, writes a treatise titled “ De solstitiis et aequinoctiis ” ( On the Solstices and Equinoxes ) in which he associates with each “cardinal point of terrestrial astronomy” a biblical meaning: Jesus is conceived during the spring equinox and born on the day of the winter solstice, while John the Baptist is conceived during the autumn equinox, and born during the summer solstice (it is no coincidence that the feast celebrating John the Baptist falls on June 24).\n\nLet’s return to the feast of dies natalis solis invicti , which was celebrated on December 25: if we want to truly connect it to the winter solstice, then its origin must be even more ancient than the II century CE, because in the calendar in use at the time the winter solstice had been on December 25 during the 3rd and 2nd centuries BCE!\n\nIt is therefore probable that this celebration is in turn a revival of a more ancient cult: in Egypt the birth of Horus had long been celebrated around the winter solstice, preparing lentils , which still today are present during this period among typical foods.\n\nAll of this, together with the fact that all pagan celebrations linked to the solstice were celebrated at the end of December and not at the beginning of January, led the Church of Rome, and as we have seen also almost all the Eastern Churches, to converge on the date of December 25.\n\nBright note in the margin #12\n\nSolstice Ceremonies\n\nIt is known that prehistoric cultures of central and northern\n\nEurope gave great importance to the solstices.\n\nThis is testified by:\n\n- the Goseck circle in Germany (4800 BCE),\n\n- the mound and passage tomb of Newgrange in Ireland (3150 BCE),\n\n- Stonehenge (3rd millennium BCE),\n\n- the Sky Disc of Nebra (1600 BCE), to mention only the most famous examples.\n\nOther brief examples:\n\n- Point Barrow, in the north of Alaska: the Eksimos worshipped the moment when the sun reappears to chase away the evil spirit Tuna, during winter solstice.\n\n- the Yule log is said to lighten the labor that the sun makes to rekindle its sparkling light.\n\nThe Magi\n\nDieter Koch , in The Star of Bethlehem , speaks of the story of the Magi without committing himself to its veracity.\n\nNonetheless, the story of the Nativity concerns them, and an astronomical history of the Nativity cannot avoid discussing them.\n\nLet’s start with the meaning of Magi: the word we find in Matthew is μάγος ( magos ), which means magician, that is, one who performs magic.\n\nAt the time a magos was one who belonged to the class of priests of the Zoroastrian religion, which had its origins in Persia.\n\nIt does not therefore seem correct to translate them as “kings” or “wise men,” because the respective translations of βασιλεῖς ( basileus , kings) or σοφοί (wise men) are not found in Matthew. Why then has tradition reported the Magi as “wise men” or “kings”? Probably, says Koch, because of the evil nature that magic had for men of the Church, associated as it was by those same men with the work of an evil entity.\n\nMoreover, in various passages of the Old Testament there are prophecies concerning the way in which powerful men, that is, kings, will have to prostrate themselves to the “Son of God.” Despite this, there would be doubts about the origin of the Magi from Persia, deriving from an analysis of the gifts that Matthew says they brought to Jesus: myrrh and incense do not come from Persia, but from the lands of the Nabataeans, in northwestern Arabia.\n\nIf Matthew was referring, speaking of the Magi, to men coming from the east, as Isaiah also says with a parallel with the rising of the sun in the east, then the Nabataeans would also be a possible source for the Magi, since in the Old Testament the east is a way to indicate precisely Arabia.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/3b05f082-6d98-41b6-9cb5-6bdc795bbc9b_2172x3175.jpeg)\n\nHarper’s Magazine, Christmas, by Harvey Ellis (1898). Credits here.\n\nOrigen believes that the Magi come from Mesopotamia, Justin and Tertullian instead that they come from Damascus; Persian legends instead claim that they originated from Ecbatana , today Hamadan, which had been the capital of the Medes.\n\nIn any case, their nationality cannot be stated with certainty.\n\nOne can say however, returning to the etymology, that magos in ancient Persian is magush , which is the original name of an ancient tribe of the Medes.\n\nThe religion of this people was polytheistic, linked to the Indian Vedic religion, until about 1000 BCE, when Zoroaster introduced monotheism.\n\nAnd Zoroaster himself has a prophecy that serves our case, and that could explain why Magi who followed that doctrine would have decided to undertake a journey toward Palestine.\n\nZoroaster\n\nZoroaster himself had predicted that at a certain point a Saoshyant , that is a savior, would arrive on earth, defeating the forces of evil and bringing about a state of peace and blessing. He would then kill a bull, extract fat from it and produce a decoction (?) that would make humans immortal.\n\nMoreover, this man was to be born of a virgin. Once again etymology tells an interesting story: the word in Avestan saoshyant , which translates as “he who will save,” becomes sô-sont- in Greek, and also has connections with sô-têr , which translates as “saviour.”\n\nMithras\n\nPerhaps Matthew was alluding to Mithras ?\n\nMithras is an ancient god venerated by the Persians and ancient Indians. In the Zoroastrian religion, Mithras becomes the judge of souls, and the story told that Ahura Mazda, the wise god, the most powerful figure in the Zoroastrian religion, had created Mithras in his image, in analogy with what happens in the Christian religion. The cult of Mithras was long in competition, in the East but also in Rome, with the Christian religion of the time. And the analogies with the figure of Christ continue: Mithras is born in a cave, Jesus in a stable (but the stables of Bethlehem were carved into the rock).\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/c0b7f297-aad4-4ddb-adc4-8aec49f94cd0_1200x772.jpeg)\n\nDaniel’s Answer to the King, by Briton Riviere (1890). Credits here.\n\nJames George Frazer in The Golden Bough speaks of fertility cults in Western Asia (Near East) emphasising the points of contact between the cult of Mithras, that of the “mother of the gods,” and the Christian religion.\n\nSpeaking of the cult of the sun in Syria and Egypt, he speaks of the faithful who at midnight came out of the sanctuaries shouting “The Virgin has given birth! The Light grows!”\n\nHe speaks of the representations of the newly (re)born Sun as a child, and of the mother of the child Sun god as a Celestial Virgin, a divinity similar to the figures of Astarte (Ashtoreth, as in Deuteronomy).\n\nThe phenomenon in the sky\n\nWe have spoken of the date of Jesus’ birth, we have spoken of some analogies with Semitic cults and with Persian ones.\n\nWhere does astronomy enter into the story of the Nativity?\n\nWe will try to represent the various possibilities that astronomy proposes to us, starting from the texts we have available on the description of the Nativity that have within them some reference to some celestial object.\n\nFirst of all, most studies on the “star” of the Nativity speak of an extraordinary celestial phenomenon or a particular astrological configuration: this is motivated by the fact that it is improbable that a “simple” event or a usual astrological configuration would have motivated the Magi to undertake the journey described by Matthew.\n\nBut the possibilities are multiple, according to Koch:\n\n1) it could be an unusual and very rare event;\n\n2) it could be a special astrological configuration, difficult to interpret for common men, but interpretable by the Magi;\n\n3) it could have been a very ordinary phenomenon, which however had the function of indicating, in the right context - that of a Zoroastrian or Hebrew prophecy - the approach of a particularly special event.\n\nObviously, the possibility that there was nothing of all this and that the story of the “star” and the Magi is just a story hovers over us and over History. Despite this, the fact that it was told in this way, and not in another, could justify the desire to understand it thoroughly and try to interpret it.\n\nMatthew writes:\n\n“After Jesus was born in Bethlehem of Judea, in the time of King Herod, behold, some Magi came from the east to Jerusalem and said: ‘Where is he who has been born, the king of the Jews? We have seen his star rising [in the east] and have come to worship him’” (Matthew 2:1)\n\n“Then Herod, having secretly called the Magi, ascertained from them exactly the time when the star had appeared” (Matthew 2:7)\n\n“And behold, the star, which they had seen rising, went before them, until it came and stood over the place where the child was.” (Matthew 2:9)\n\nThese are the only phrases that speak of an object in the sky that “indicated” to the Magi that Jesus would be born in Bethlehem. Let’s try to understand what they tell us. Koch here speaks of the expression translated as “rising [in the east],” saying that the word for east, anatolê , can also be translated as “ rising ,” and not only as “east.” Anatolê in fact is used in relation to the rising of the Sun, the Moon, or a star. The word Anatolia indicates, from Greek, “the land of dawn.”\n\nSo the Magi say they saw a star rising in the east, not necessarily that they were in the east when they saw a star.\n\nNow, it is useful to understand what it means that a star rose in the east. Aren’t the same stars always in the sky, night after night?\n\nDuring the year, most stars, except the so-called “circumpolar stars,” or imperishable stars for the ancient Egyptians, disappear in the evening sky to the west and appear only after a few weeks in the morning sky. The moment when a star reappears is called heliacal rising , because the star is visible for a short time together with the rising Sun, which being brighter than any other object in the sky visible from Earth, covers the light of every other celestial body. After that first rising, the star will be visible every day a little earlier, until it is visible even before dawn. The heliacal rising of a star occurs on a specific date, and obviously depends on the star.\n\nWhen then Herod asks “exactly the time when the star had appeared,” it is because he wanted to know the exact day when the child was born, connecting the event in the sky to the birth.\n\nIn the case that the “star” was truly a heliacal rising, then the Magi, who were versed in astronomy, especially if coming from Babylon, would have had all the time to calculate the exact date and then prepare the journey to reach Palestine. On the contrary, in the case that the “star” had been a sudden event, the impossibility of calculating it in advance makes it impossible to prepare the journey in advance. But a journey of this kind (from Babylon to Palestine) would have taken a couple of months, and the text does not say this.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f8deb1fb-ccc5-42da-9da9-3785ca9cef02_2309x3025.jpeg)\n\nThe morning star personified, by G.H. Frezza (1704). Credits here.\n\nWhen the Magi leave Jerusalem to go toward Bethlehem, the text says that the star “went before them.” This should mean, given that Jerusalem and Bethlehem are on a north-south axis, that the star would have had to be found looking toward the south. But the star is to the south only in full daylight, because after the heliacal rising we said that the star always rises in the east, always a little before the Sun, until it is visible even at night.\n\nThe term for “went before” in Greek is προῆγεν ( proêgen ), which means “to bring forward.” Where else is this word used? Matthew uses it in its meaning of “to go ahead,” or “to bring before a judge.”\n\nHowever, in New Testament language the verb is also used in place of προηγεῖσθαι ( pro(h)egeisthai ), which it does mean “to precede,” but also, from an astronomical point of view, “to be retrograde,” referring to a retrograde motion of a planet.\n\nPtolemy in the Tetrabiblos and Geminus in Introduction to the Phenomena use it in this way.\n\nWhat is a retrograde motion ?\n\nThe planets move, observing them at night, in the same direction in which the Sun moves during the day. Moreover, all the planets known to the ancients moved in a band around the Sun, called the zodiacal band. Sometimes it seems however that some planets do not move in the “normal” direction, but seem to go backward - that is, they seem to “walk backward.”\n\nIf therefore we accept the astronomical interpretation of pro(h)egeisthai , the “star” cannot have been a star as we understand it, but only a planet, since stars do not show retrograde motion.\n\nMoreover, it had to be a planet that presents retrograde motion during its heliacal rising. This planet is Venus .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/690ed1b9-3848-4fcf-bf71-5a1c77ccb639_2157x2350.jpeg)\n\nHesperus, by Anton Raphael Mengs (1765). Credits here.\n\nWhen the text says that the star stopped over the place where the child was, we can interpret the text with a phenomenon known to ancient astrologers as “station of a planet.” This phenomenon occurs when a planet seems to “stop” relative to the motion of the other planets of the zodiacal band, to reverse its own motion, from retrograde to direct and vice versa.\n\nThis interpretation is in accordance with the planetary nature of the “star” we are looking for, and also with the fact that, the station of the planet occurring a few days after its heliacal rising, everything must have happened when the Magi were already in Palestine.\n\nKoch speaks of the fact that Matthew’s failure to use the astronomical term for planetary station, στηριγμός ( stērigmos ), is due to the fact that Matthew was not an astronomer.\n\nAccepting that the star was Venus, why doesn’t Matthew say its name? The most immediate reason seems to be that the name of the planet, Ashteret, was associated with a pagan divinity (Astarte), and that for this reason, as is often done in the Old Testament, its name is not written.\n\nMoreover, in Hebrew and Aramaic the planet Venus was also simply called “the star,” or the “she-star,” that is kōbāb/kōkäbät and kaukab/kaukabta , respectively.\n\nOther versions\n\nAfter interpreting the verses of Matthew reported above, C.J. Humphreys writes, in The Star of Bethlehem , that the characteristics of the star can be listed as follows:\n\n1) it is a new star, one that was not visible before;\n\n2) it moved slowly in the sky, appearing in different points of the sky at different times;\n\n3) at a certain point it seemed to stop above Bethlehem, in the sense that seen from Jerusalem, the star seemed to be located above the place where Bethlehem is.\n\nThe ideas that Humphreys initially proposes concern the conjunction of two planets, a nova, and a comet.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/78d8c6b0-65d8-4456-b6fd-a3639c08e1f2_744x1024.jpeg)\n\nPhosphorus and Hesperus, by Evelyn De Morgan (1881). Credits here.\n\nA conjunction\n\nStarting from the 8th century CE, the Jewish astronomer Māshāʾallāh speaks of a planetary conjunction of Jupiter and Saturn that occurred in the 7th century BCE. The problem, according to Humphreys, is that this explanation is not attested by anyone else before him; Koch adds that the problems also concern the very nature of the conjunction: at the moment of conjunction, the planets would have had to be distant on the celestial vault by a couple of lunar diameters, that is, a distance at which the planets are still distinguishable, and which therefore would hardly have made that conjunction a star.\n\nMoreover, accepting the interpretation of heliacal rising, retrograde motion, and stationarity, a planetary conjunction satisfies none of these.\n\nA nova\n\nJean-François Foucquet (1665-1741), French Jesuit and scientist, as a century earlier Johannes Kepler (1571-1630), German astronomer, writes that a nova could have been the star, in particular a nova that exploded in conjunction with the conjunction of Jupiter and Saturn in 7 BCE.\n\nA nova is a phenomenon that occurs when the brightness of a star suddenly increases, causing that same star, which before was perhaps barely visible, to appear much brighter than before to an observer.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/47b33caf-f88b-4bf6-92f5-07bc56a41d22_2560x1789.jpeg)\n\nCapricornus as a sea-goat from Urania’s Mirror , by Sidney Hall (1825). Credits here.\n\nThe problem with this theory is that events of this type are impossible to predict, and that therefore there was no way for the Magi to prepare a journey and then arrive in Jerusalem and observe the nova.\n\nMoreover, a nova is a phenomenon concerning stars, which do not have motions observable in an evident way, such as to make the Magi say that the star “guided” them.\n\nFurthermore, in Kepler’s time the difference between a nova and a comet was still imperceptible, since it was thought that novae were comets without tails. And it was precisely Kepler who hypothesised that novae, not moving relative to the sky of fixed stars, belonged to this same sphere, unlike comets, which instead inhabit the spheres closer to Earth.\n\nBut not only in Europe was this difference still imperceptible: there exist sources in China that speak of comets around 5 or 4 BCE, interpretable both in the current meaning of the term and as novae stars.\n\nAnd it is precisely a comet, the celestial body candidate, together with Venus, to play the role of “star” of the Nativity.\n\nA comet\n\nAlready starting from the 2nd century CE, Origen speaks of a comet as a possible candidate for the role of “star” present in the gospel of Matthew.\n\nThe theory on the nature of comets dated back to Aristotle, according to whom they were objects that belonged to the sub-lunar sphere, that lived in the upper part of the atmosphere.\n\nThey were signs of omen, not necessarily of bad omen, but for example Dio Cassius , when he describes the passage of a comet (which was probably Halley’s comet) does so by relating it to the death of Marcus Vipsanius Agrippa , Roman general (63 BCE -12 BCE).\n\nThe first comet whose passage can be predicted is Halley’s comet, named in relation to the English astronomer who hypothesised its predictability after observing it in 1705, confirmed in 1759.\n\nA prediction of this kind was not possible at the time of the 1st century BCE - and until the invention of the telescope, at least - therefore the Magi could not have used the prediction of a comet to prepare their journey. Koch uses this argument, among others, to speak of the impossibility that the “star” followed by the Magi was a comet.\n\nHumphreys is not of the same opinion, and investigates the phenomenon; he does so by searching the Chinese archives for a trace of phenomena attributable to comets dated around the years in which, from the accounts we have, the possible birth of Jesus is dated.\n\nHe reduces the search to three phenomena:\n\n(1) a comet, po-hsing , which passed around August 12 BCE (which is Halley’s comet), visible for just under 60 days;\n\n(2) a sui-hsing comet, visible between March and April of 5 BCE;\n\n(3) another po-hsing comet, visible around April 4 BCE.\n\nUsing the information contained in the gospel of Luke, Humphreys proceeds thus: since Jesus is said to have been about 30 years old at the time of baptism by John the Baptist (Luke 3:23), who had begun his ministry during the fifteenth year of Tiberius’ reign (Luke 3:1-2), a possible date for the aforementioned baptism could be the year 29 CE or the period between autumn 28 and autumn 29 CE. This means, interpreting the expression “about 30 years” as between 26 and 34 years, that the earliest date for Jesus’ birth is 7 BCE.\n\nThis eliminates the possibility that Halley’s comet in its passage of 12 BCE represents the “star” of the nativity.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/7fd77199-9d0c-478b-b06c-f929119299d7_1492x1036.jpeg)\n\nComet 1P/Halley photographed March 8, 1986, by W. Liller. Credits here.\n\nWhat instead is the latest date for the birth? It is obtained from the date of death of King Herod the Great, who is said to have died in March 4 BCE. Since the comet of April 4 BCE is subsequent to this date, and we know that Jesus, from the accounts of the gospels, was born during Herod’s reign, then we can also eliminate the comet dating to this date.\n\nTherefore remains the comet that appeared around March 5 BCE. Humphreys, from the accounts of the comet’s appearances, reconstructs the following: it seems to have appeared in the countries that today make up Arabia around early March, in an area of the sky that includes the zone where the constellation of Capricorn is drawn; it was visible from these countries in the first lights of dawn; its motion is compatible with the Jerusalem-Bethlehem axis, since it seems to have had its tail along that direction, moving toward the north.\n\nAccepting that this is the comet observed by the Magi, who from Babylon to Jerusalem had time to travel during the comet’s path in the sky, which lasted just under two months, was such an omen sufficient to mobilize them? Humphreys connects the comet to other celestial phenomena, in particular to two others: the first is the conjunction of Saturn and Jupiter in 7 BCE, the second the proximity of three planets in 6 BCE. These phenomena seemed to prepare the arrival of an additional and definitive symbol: the comet in Capricorn in 5 BCE.\n\nWhy?\n\nIsaac Abarbanel , Jewish philosopher of the XV century CE, writes that in the astrology and mythology of the Magi, Saturn represents the divine father, and Jupiter is his son. Moreover, the third planet of 6 BCE is Mars, which heralds the coming of a warrior king, according to Chaldean astrology (in Babylon); and the comet of 5 BCE crosses Capricorn, which is considered the seat of the Sun’s rebirth, and the daytime dwelling of Saturn.\n\nFurthermore, the Magi claim to have seen the star “from the east”: we already know that this interpretation is debated, but accepting it as part of the scholarly community does, Humphreys extracts from it the information that this was the reason for the Magi’s rapid departure. According to Ptolemy in fact, it was common knowledge among astrologers that a comet arriving “from the east” was a prediction of events of imminent realisation , while a comet arriving from the west spoke of events further ahead in time. Finally, even Daniel, Hebrew prophet in exile in Babylon, speaks of a king comparing him to an animal with horns (when he speaks of Alexander the Great).\n\nAccepting this interpretation, do the travel times of the Magi’s journey and the vision of the comet in the sky agree? According to Humphreys yes, since traveling between 50 and 100 miles per day, an acceptable average for the means and period, the route of the time from Babylon to Jerusalem first and then Bethlehem, is between 500 and 900 miles.\n\nMoreover, Matthew does not say that the Magi followed the comet for the entire journey, but only that it directed them westward, and that it went before them toward Bethlehem.\n\nKoch is skeptical about this interpretation for various reasons, among which the fact that comets are surprising phenomena when they are particularly visible, which does not seem to have happened for a comet in that time period, or that Halley’s comet returned to visit Earth in the year 66 CE, when Matthew was perfectly capable of observing it: if he did so, why didn’t he connect this comet to that of 5 BCE, perhaps announcing a second coming of Christ, as all Christians in those first years after his death expected?\n\nVenus as a star\n\nAccepting Koch’s interpretation on the nature of the “star” of the nativity as Venus, let’s try to understand why Matthew, despite never naming the planet, could have chosen such a celestial body as a symbol of Jesus’ birth.\n\nFirst of all, Koch connects the planet Venus to the divinities of Western Asia, particularly in Mesopotamia, with the goddess Ishtar, and in the kingdom of the Assyrians. In these regions the goddess had slightly different names, such as Ishtar, Astarte, Athart, and was associated with the role of protector and creator of kings.\n\nBright note in the margin #13\n\nIncidentally, the representation of the virgin woman with the child god, in the figure of the Virgin Mary with the Baby Jesus, falls within the tradition of the relationship between the king and the divinity that protects him, or in the representation of fertility. Examples are the divinities in Assyria and Babylon that protected the king from birth, and the relationship between the young Horus and the goddess Isis.\n\nThen, after framing the planet as the brightest celestial body in the sky after the Sun and Moon, and which precisely with the other two bodies in Babylon forms a triad of astral divinities (respectively Ishtar, Shamash and Sin), Koch speaks of Venus as the symbol of resurrection from death, due to the fact that it is at the same time Hesperus and Phosphorus, respectively the evening star, which goes to die toward the west, and the morning star, which is reborn in the east.\n\nBright note in the margin #14\n\nJerome, one of the fathers of the church, states that, in the place that tradition recognizes as the site of Jesus’ birth, the local community of faithful, from the times of Hadrian until the reign of Constantine - that is, just under two centuries - had erected a small sanctuary in honor of Tammuz, that is, Adonis.\n\nAdonis, which in Semitic means “lord, master,” was an ancient divinity venerated in Mesopotamia, and was the lover of Ishtar, that is, Venus.\n\nGeorge Frazer too, Scottish ethnologist of the 20th century CE, speaks of the “star” of Bethlehem as Venus, morning star, connecting it to the cult of Adonis observed in the area.\n\nVenus is a “star” of particular importance not only in traditions that Christians consider pagan: even in the Bible, despite not being called by name, there are references to this figure. In Revelation 22:16, the author reports the words of Jesus who states that he is ὁ ἀστὴρ ὁ λαμπρὸς ὁ πρωϊνός, that is, the bright morning star . Also in a verse from the second letter of Peter (II Peter 1:19), the author speaks of Jesus comparing him to the morning star, that is, Venus .\n\nWhich date, finally?\n\nWe have already spoken of the fact that it is unlikely that Jesus’ birth occurred on December 25, and we are far from being able to arrive at a specific date. The decision to select a specific date is usually attributed to the need to define an orthodoxy, in a period subsequent to the first centuries after the beginning of the Christian cult, aimed at differentiating the day of Jesus’ birth from that of his manifestation in the world, which first the Gnostics and then the Manichaeans had raised as a critical point of Christian historiography. The date of December 25 seems to have been agreed upon subsequently by the Church of Rome first, and then by almost all the others, for various reasons, mainly linked to the presence of previous or contemporary solar cults, such as the cult of Sol Invictus, or that of Mithras, and can be inserted within the tradition of celebrating the winter solstice.\n\nRead the series “ on the motion of the Earth” :\n\nBibliography:\n\nThe Star of Bethlehem - a Comet in 5 BC - and the Date of the Birth of Christ, by Humphreys, C. J., [Quarterly Journal of the Royal Astronomical Society, Vol. 32, NO.4/DEC, P.389] (1991)\n\nThe Star of Bethlehem, by Koch D. (2016)\n\nSol Invictus. The winter solstice and the origins of Christmas, by Hijmans S., [Mouseion, Series III, Vol. 3, 377-398] (2003)\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_008-storia-astronomica-del-natale.md": "Disclaimer #1: this article is in Italian. The English version should have arrived along with this one. You can reach it by visiting my profile.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5ee96e37-41a5-4287-8ef7-5c12e139717b_1080x1350.png)\n\nA Natale, iscriviti gratuitamente a questa newsletter!\n\nE se vuoi diventare un abbonato a pagamento per supportare questo lavoro, considera l'offerta qui sotto.\n\nGet 50% off for 1 year\n\nGrazie!\n\nBenvenuti!\n\nIn questo episodio parleremo della costruzione della storia del Natale, cercando di capire i collegamenti di questa festa con altri riti di altre mitologie, e perché cade poco dopo il giorno più buio dell’anno (nell’emisfero boreale).\n\nParleremo di stelle che non erano stelle, e forse neanche comete; di tre re che non erano re, e che non erano tre; di scelte di calendario dettate dal Sole e contrapposte al Sole; di profeti e astrologi, di pianeti e divinità.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2b46b663-399f-4be8-902a-d94414395fc4_4222x4177.jpeg)\n\nScena invernale con pattinatori vicino a un castello, opera di Hendrick Avercamp (1607). Credits qui.\n\nLa costruzione del Natale\n\nLa Chiesa di Roma e le filiazioni della riforma protestante celebrano il 25 dicembre del calendario gregoriano di ogni anno la festività della Natività, ovvero la nascita di Gesù, considerato il Figlio di Dio da queste religioni.\n\nAnche la Chiesa Ortodossa russa, quella serba, e la Chiesa di Gerusalemme celebrano il Natale in questa data, ma poiché adottano il calendario giuliano , c’è una differenza di 13 giorni tra le date in cui si celebra la stessa festività tra loro e il resto del mondo cristiano, che equivale al 7 gennaio del calendario gregoriano.\n\nLe prime cose che possiamo chiederci sono:\n\n1) cosa esattamente festeggia la religione cristiana il giorno di Natale?\n\n2) da quando si è iniziato a festeggiarlo nel giorno del 25 dicembre?\n\nPer rispondere a queste e altre domande dovremo tornare alle fonti iniziali del primo cristianesimo, quando questa religione non era ancora organizzata e gerarchica, e in cui sembra non fosse fondamentale capire la data della nascita di Gesù.\n\nI Vangeli, ovvero le opere che abbiamo a disposizione per ottenere informazioni sulla vita di Gesù, non parlano della data della sua nascita.\n\nI Vangeli che parlano della cosiddetta “Natività” sono due: quello di Matteo e quello di Luca, due delle quattro figure definite “evangelisti”.\n\nIl Vangelo di Luca è datato intorno all’80 CE, mentre quello di Matteo data intorno al 70 CE. In quegli anni il sentimento comune alle comunità religiose di ispirazione cristiana era rivolto più alla morte e alla resurrezione di Cristo che alla sua nascita. Inizialmente quindi, ovvero per il primo secolo e mezzo dopo la morte di Cristo (databile intorno agli anni 30 CE) nessuno celebrava la sua nascita in un giorno specifico.\n\nUno dei primi che pone il problema della nascita di Gesù è Origene , un teologo originario di Alessandria d’Egitto nato il 185 CE. Nonostante la sua opinione che “solo i pagani celebravano il giorno della propria nascita”, nondimeno ha qualcosa da dire sulla storia della Natività. Lo incontreremo di nuovo quando cercheremo di capire quale corpo celeste i magi abbiano osservato durante il loro viaggio verso Betlemme.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/949ffd4c-5e7a-4b60-8224-6d4dbf9339ea_799x613.jpeg)\n\nChristmas Cactus. Crediti qui.\n\nIl concetto di Epifania, ovvero della manifestazione della divinità nel mondo, è un concetto elaborato dalla tradizione gnostica cristiana, interessata all’ottenimento della salvezza attraverso la conoscenza, più che attraverso la tradizione dell’ortodossia.\n\nLa setta gnostica dei cristiani d’Egitto dei Basilidiani, fondata ad Alessandria d’Egitto nel II secolo CE, celebrava questa manifestazione il giorno del battesimo di Gesù, e lo faceva nel giorno del 6 gennaio, trascorrendo la vigilia di questa festa leggendo i testi sacri.\n\nSesto Giulio Africano , uno scrittore romano databile tra il II e il III secolo CE, scrisse nel Chronographíai (cronografia del mondo), che l’incarnazione di Gesù fosse avvenuta il giorno 25 marzo del 1 CE, e che la sua nascita fosse avvenuta esattamente nove mesi dopo, ovvero il 25 dicembre.\n\nQuesta datazione è influenzata da due fattori.\n\nIl primo, di origine astronomica, è dovuto al fatto che il 25 marzo era considerato all’epoca il giorno dell’equinozio di primavera, ovvero il giorno a partire dal quale le ore di luce di una giornata superavano quelle di buio, fenomeno che ben si legava alla venuta di Gesù, che avrebbe liberato il mondo dalle tenebre del paganesimo.\n\nIl secondo, propriamente letterario, tradisce il fatto che nell’antichità era in uso far risalire la nascita e la morte, e gli altri eventi rilevanti della vita di un individuo importante, allo stesso giorno. Iniziamo qui a intravedere la relazione che esiste con le mitologie astrali e i calendari rituali.\n\nUn testo del 243 CE, dal titolo De Pascha computus , di un autore che va sotto il nome di Pseudo-Cipriano , la data della nascita di Gesù è il 28 Marzo. Questo lavoro viene presentato come il miglioramento di un lavoro precedente da parte di Ippolito di Roma, teologo romano, che era arrivato alla data del 2 aprile CE.\n\nLavori del genere si accumulano, fino al IV secolo CE, quando in Oriente la data accettata da tutti diviene il 6 gennaio.\n\nIn Occidente il dibattito viene influenzato anche dalla presenza di contemporanei culti solari, analogamente a quanto avviene in Oriente. A Roma però tali culti vengono abbracciati anche dalla elite senatoria e dalla corte imperiale, che già con Eliogabalo , imperatore dal 218 al 222 CE e per successione ereditaria alto sacerdote di El-Gabal (il dio Sole), aveva visto introdotto il culto del sole con la festività del Sol Invictus . Nei decenni successivi il culto verrà associato ad altre divinità di cui parleremo, come Helios e Mitra . Nel 274 CE l’imperatore Aureliano istituisce ufficialmente il culto del Natalis Solis Invicti , ovvero della nascita del Sole Invitto, che cade il giorno del 25 dicembre. In quel periodo infatti il solstizio d’inverno cadeva proprio in quel giorno, che quindi era perfetto per festeggiare una festività solare, e il ritorno del dio Sole, mai sconfitto.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d81e7a2e-5468-492b-afdc-3224e5aa234a_4000x3002.jpeg)\n\nPreparing for Christmas (Plucking Turkeys), opera di Francis William Edmonds American (1851). Crediti qui.\n\nNel 336 la Chiesa locale di Roma istituisce il giorno del 25 dicembre come il Dies Natalis Christi . La sovrapposizione di questa festività con il Natalis Solis Invicti viene notata già dal Cronografo del 354 , un testo sul calendario romano. Nel 379 la data è attestata anche dalla Chiesa di Costantinopoli, nel 386 da quella di Antiochia, e successivamente nel V secolo CE dalla Chiesa d’Egitto, e nel VI da quella di Gerusalemme.\n\nOggi la Chiesa Armenia è una delle poche a festeggiare la Natività di Gesù il giorno del 6 gennaio.\n\nLa contrapposizione tra le due festività viene notata anche dai dottori della Chiesa: Agostino d’Ippona ammonisce i cristiani che celebrano il Sole negli ultimi giorni dell’anno, e li esorta ad adorare non \"il Sole, ma […] colui che creò il Sole\".\n\nLeone I , papa dal 440 al 461 CE, esorta i fedeli a non adorare il Sole.\n\nNonostante questo, sotto la basilica di San Pietro è raffigurato Gesù su un carro, in un’opera dal titolo Christo Sole .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6e48da3e-226d-47bb-b604-717553432830_564x800.jpeg)\n\nTomba del Cristo-Sole. Crediti Fabbrica di S. Pietro.\n\nFacciamo un passo indietro: come mai, nonostante la molteplicità di date proposte durante i primi secoli della storia cristiana, le più importanti Chiese d’Oriente e d’Occidente hanno scelto i due giorni del 6 gennaio e del 25 dicembre come le date della nascita di Gesù, per poi convergere (quasi) tutte sulla seconda?\n\nPartiamo da Epifanio di Salamina , un vescovo del IV secolo CE a Salamina, sull’isola di Cipro, che in Adversus haereses , (Contro le Eresie) , parla della notte tra il 5 e il 6 gennaio, e del 6 gennaio di due anni dopo come dell’arrivo dei magi.\n\nArriva a suggerire una data specifica: la notte del 5 gennaio del 2 BCE.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #11\n\nIl concetto della vigilia di una festa, e della sua celebrazione a partire dalla notte precedente alla stessa, è collegato dalla tradizione ebraica, in cui il giorno successivo iniziava a partire dal tramonto del precedente.\n\nE’ per questo quindi che nel tempo si è codificata la tradizione di celebrare la vigilia delle festività.\n\nEpifanio collega la nascita di Gesù alla data del solstizio d’inverno, spostandola di 13 giorni rispetto a essa; secondo lui questo spostamento è spiegato dal fatto che 13 è anche il numero degli apostoli più Gesù stesso.\n\nInoltre, poiché anche i pagani festeggiano in quella data la nascita di Aion ( Eone ), divinità legata al tempo ciclico e successivamente collegata dagli studiosi neoplatonici con Dioniso , egli riconosce in ciò il fatto che anche i pagani “riconoscano una parte della verità”.\n\nRiguardo il culto di Aion della notte tra il 5 e il 6 gennaio, Epifanio dice:\n\n”In Alessandria, nel così chiamato Koreion: questo è un grande tempio, sede del santuario di Kore. La notte intera [gli adoratori del culto] restano svegli e canta verso l’idolo con canzoni e flauti. Alla fine della celebrazione notturna, al cantare del gallo, scendono nel santuario sotterraneo imbracciando delle torce e trasportano un idolo di legno che posizionano nudo su una portantina.”\n\ne ancora:\n\n“Oggi, in questa ore, Kore, la Vergine, partorisce Aion. […] E questo avviene anche nella città di Petra… nel tempo dell’idolo, adorano la Vergine nella lingua araba, chiamandola Khaabu, che si traduce con Kore o \"vergine\"; e colui che nasce [lo chiamano] Dusares, che significa \"l’unico generato dal Signore\".\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/37b56dd7-1775-436a-9934-7bbe22327538_960x751.jpeg)\n\nLa danza della musica del tempo, opera di Nicolas Poussin (1640). Crediti qui.\n\nGirolamo , vescovo di Stridone del IV secolo CE, è convinto che la nascita di Gesù non possa che essere avvenuta il giorno del solstizio, a causa dell’armonia cosmica.\n\nLa tradizione elabora ulteriormente, e Giovanni Crisostomo , patriarca di Costantinopoli del IV secolo CE, scrive un trattato intitolato “ De solstitiis et aequinoctiis ” ( Sui Solstizi e gli Equinozi ) in cui associa a ogni “punto cardinale dell’astronomia terrestre” un significato biblico: Gesù viene concepito durante l’equinozio di primavera e nasce il giorno del solstizio d’inverno, mentre Giovanni Battista viene concepito durante l’equinozio d’autunno, e nasce durante il solstizio d’estate (non è un caso che la festa che celebra Giovanni Battista cada il 24 giugno).\n\nRitorniamo alla festa del dies natalis solis invicti , che veniva celebrata il 25 dicembre: se vogliamo collegarla davvero al solstizio d’inverno, allora la sua origine deve essere ancora più antica del II secolo CE, perché nel calendario in uso all’epoca il solstizio d’inverno c’era stato il 25 dicembre durante il II e il I secolo BCE!\n\nE’ probabile quindi che questa celebrazione è a sua volta una riproposizione di un culto più antico: in Egitto si celebrava da tempo la nascita di Horus intorno al solstizio d’inverno, preparando le lenticchie , che ancora oggi sono presenti in questo periodo tra i cibi tipici.\n\nTutto questo, insieme al fatto che tutte le celebrazioni pagane legate al solstizio si festeggiavano alla fine di dicembre e non all’inizio di gennaio, portò la Chiesa di Roma, e come abbiamo visto anche poi quasi tutte le Chiese d’Oriente, a convergere sulla data del 25 dicembre.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #12\n\nCerimonie del solstizio\n\nÈ noto che le culture preistoriche dell’Europa centrale e settentrionale davano grande importanza ai solstizi.\n\nQuesto è testimoniato da:\n\n- il cerchio di Goseck in Germania (4800 BCE),\n\n- il tumulo e tomba a corridoio di Newgrange in Irlanda (3150 BCE),\n\n- Stonehenge (III millennio BCE),\n\n- il Disco del Cielo di Nebra (1600 BCE)\n\nAltri brevi esempi:\n\n- Point Barrow, nel nord dell’Alaska: gli Eschimesi veneravano il momento in cui il sole riappare per scacciare lo spirito malvagio Tuna, durante il solstizio d’inverno.\n\n- si dice che il ceppo di Yule alleggerisca la fatica che il sole compie per riaccendere la sua luce scintillante.\n\nI Magi\n\nDieter Koch , in The Star of Bethlehem, parla della storia dei magi senza sbilanciarsi sulla sua veridicità.\n\nNondimeno, la storia della Natività li riguarda, e una storia astronomica della Natività non può esimersi dal parlarne.\n\nPartiamo dal significato di magi: la parola che troviamo in Matteo è μάγος (magos), che significa mago, ovvero colui che compie magie.\n\nAll’epoca un magos era colui che apparteneva alla classe dei preti di religione zoroastriana, che aveva le sue origini in Persia.\n\nNon sembra quindi corretto tradurli come “re” o “saggi”, perché le relative traduzioni di βασιλεῖς (basileus, re) o σοφοί (saggi) non si trovano in Matteo. Come mai allora la tradizione ha riportato i magi come “saggi uomini” o “re”? Probabilmente, dice Koch, per via della natura malvagia che per gli uomini di Chiesa la magia aveva, associata com’era da quegli stessi uomini all’opera di una entità malvagia.\n\nInoltre, in diversi passaggi del Vecchio Testamento ci sono profezie che riguardano il modo in cui gli uomini potenti, ovvero i re, dovranno prostrarsi al “Figlio di Dio”.\n\nNonostante ciò, sull’origine dei magi dalla Persia ci sarebbero dei dubbi, derivanti da un’analisi dei doni che Matteo dice hanno portato a Gesù: la mirra e l’incenso non provengono dalla Persia, ma dalle terre dei Nabatei, nel nord-ovest dell’Arabia.\n\nSe Matteo si riferiva parlando dei magi di uomini provenienti dall’est, come dice anche Isaia con un parallelo con il sorgere del sole a est, allora anche i Nabatei sarebbero una fonte possibile per i magi, poiché nel Vecchio Testamento l’est è un modo per indicare proprio l’Arabia.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/3b05f082-6d98-41b6-9cb5-6bdc795bbc9b_2172x3175.jpeg)\n\nHarper’s Magazine, Christmas, opera di Harvey Ellis (1898). Crediti qui.\n\nOrigene crede che i magi provengano dalla Mesopotamia, Giustino e Tertulliano invece che provengano da Damasco; leggende persiane affermano invece che siano originati di Ekbatana, oggi Hamadan, che era stata la capitale dei Medi.\n\nAd ogni modo, la loro nazionalità non si può affermare con certezza.\n\nSi può dire però, tornando all’etimologia, che magos in antico persiano è magush, che è il nome originario di una antica tribù dei Medi.\n\nLa religione di questo popolo era politeistica, legata alla religione vedica indiana, fino a circa il 1000 BCE, quando Zoroastro introdusse il monoteismo.\n\nE proprio Zoroastro ha una profezia che fa al caso nostro, e che potrebbe spiegare perché dei magi che seguissero quella dottrina avessero deciso di intraprendere un viaggio verso la Palestina.\n\nGet 50% off for 1 year\n\nZoroastro\n\nZoroastro stesso aveva predetto che a un certo punto un Saoshyant , ovvero un salvatore, sarebbe arrivato sulla terra, vincendo le forze del male e portando a uno stato di pace e benedizione. Avrebbe poi ucciso un toro, ne avrebbe estratto del grasso e prodotto un decotto (?) che avrebbe reso gli umani immortali. Inoltre, quest’uomo sarebbe dovuto nascere da una vergine.\n\nAncora una volta l’etimologia racconta una storia interessante: la parola in avestico saoshyant , che si traduce con “colui che salverà”, diventa sô-sont- in greco, e ha legami anche con sô-têr, che si traduce con “salvatore”.\n\nMitra\n\nForse Matteo alludeva a Mitra ?\n\nMitra è un antico dio venerato dai Persiani e dagli antichi Indiani. Nella religione zoroastriana, Mitra diventa il giudice delle anime, e la storia narrava che Ahura Mazda, il dio saggio, la figura più potente della religione zoroastriana, aveva creato Mitra a sua immagine, in analogia con quanto avviene nella religione cristiana.\n\nIl culto di Mitra è stato a lungo in concorrenza, in Oriente ma anche a Roma, con la religione cristiana del tempo. E le analogie con la figura di Cristo continuano: Mitra nasce in una caverna, Gesù in una stalla (ma le stalle di Betlemme erano scavate nella roccia).\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/c0b7f297-aad4-4ddb-adc4-8aec49f94cd0_1200x772.jpeg)\n\nDaniel’s Answer to the King, opera di Briton Riviere (1890). Crediti qui.\n\nJames George Frazer nel Ramo d’Oro parla dei culti della fertilità nell’Asia Occidentale (Vicino Oriente) sottolineando i punti di contatto tra il culto di Mitra, quello della “madre degli dei”, e la religione cristiana.\n\nParlando del culto del sole in Siria e in Egitto, parla dei fedeli che a mezzanotte uscivano dai santuari gridando “la Vergine ha partorito! la Luce cresce!”.\n\nParla delle raffigurazioni del Sole appena (ri)nato come un bambino, e della madre del dio Sole bambino come di una Vergine Celeste, divinità simile alle figure di Astarte (Ashtoreth, come nel Deuteronomio).\n\nIl fenomeno nel cielo\n\nAbbiamo parlato della data della nascita di Gesù, abbiamo parlato di alcune analogie con i culti semitici e con quelli persiani.\n\nDove entra l’astronomia nella storia della Natività?\n\nCercheremo di rappresentare le diverse possibilità che l’astronomia ci propone, partendo dai testi che abbiamo a disposizione sulla descrizione della Natività che abbiano all’interno qualche riferimento a qualche oggetto celeste.\n\nInnanzitutto, la maggior parte degli studi sulla “stella” della Natività parlano di un fenomeno celeste straordinario o di una configurazione astrologica particolare: ciò è motivato dal fatto che è improbabile che un “semplice” evento o una usuale configurazione astrologica abbiamo motivato i magi a compiere il viaggio descritto da Matteo. Ma le possibilità sono molteplici, secondo Koch:\n\n1) potrebbe trattarsi di un evento inusuale e molto raro;\n\n2) potrebbe essere una speciale configurazione astrologica, difficile da interpretare per gli uomini comuni, ma interpretabile dai magi;\n\n3) potrebbe essere stato un fenomeno molto ordinario, che però aveva la funzione di indicare, nel giusto contesto - quello di una profezia zoroastriana o ebraica - l’avvicinarsi di un evento particolarmente speciale.\n\nOvviamente, l’eventualità che non ci sia stato nulla di tutto questo e che la storia della “stella” e dei magi sia solo una storia aleggia su di noi e sulla Storia. Nonostante ciò, il fatto che sia stata raccontata in questo modo, e non in un altro, potrebbe giustificare la volontà di capirla a fondo e cercare di interpretarla.\n\nMatteo dice:\n\n”Nato Gesù a Betlemme di Giudea, al tempo del re Erode, ecco, alcuni Magi vennero da oriente a Gerusalemme e dicevano: «Dov’è colui che è nato, il re dei Giudei? Abbiamo visto spuntare la sua stella [ad est] e siamo venuti ad adorarlo»” (Matteo 2,1)\n\n”Allora Erode, chiamati segretamente i Magi, si fece dire da loro con esattezza il tempo in cui era apparsa la stella” (Matteo 2,7)\n\n”Ed ecco, la stella, che avevano visto spuntare, li precedeva, finché giunse e si fermò sopra il luogo dove si trovava il bambino.” (Matteo 2,9)\n\nQuesti sono le uniche frasi che parlano di un oggetto nel cielo che ha “indicato” ai magi che a Betlemme sarebbe nato Gesù. Cerchiamo di capire cosa ci dicono.\n\nKoch qui parla dell’espressione tradotta come “spuntare [ad est]”, dicendo che la parola per est, anatolê, si può tradurre anche con “ crescente ”, e non solo con “est”. Anatolê infatti si utilizza in relazione alla crescita del Sole, della Luna, o di una stella. La parola Anatolia indica, dal greco, “la terra dell’alba”.\n\nQuindi i magi dicono di aver visto una stella sorgere ad est, non necessariamente che loro si trovavano in oriente quando hanno visto una stella.\n\nOra, è utile capire cosa significa che una stella è spuntata ad est. Non ci sono in cielo sempre le stesse stelle, notte dopo notte?\n\nDurante l’anno, la maggior parte delle stelle, tranne le cosiddette “stelle circumpolari”, o stelle imperiture per gli antichi egizi, scompaiono nel cielo serale a occidente e appaiono solo dopo qualche settimana nel cielo mattutino. Il momento in cui una stella riappare si chiama levata eliaca, perché la stella è visibile per poco insieme al Sole nascente, che essendo più brillante di ogni altro oggetto in cielo visibile dalla Terra, copre la luce di ogni altro corpo celeste. Dopo quella prima levata, la stella sarà visibile ogni giorno sempre un po’ prima, fino a essere visibile anche prima dell’alba. La levata eliaca di una stella avviene in una data specifica, e ovviamente dipende dalla stella.\n\nQuando allora Erode chiede “con esattezza il tempo in cui era apparsa la stella”, è perché voleva conoscere il giorno esatto in cui il bambino era nato, collegando l’evento nel cielo alla nascita.\n\nNel caso in cui la “stella” sia stata davvero una levata eliaca, allora i magi, che erano versati in astronomia, soprattutto se proveniente da Babilonia, avrebbero potuto avere tutto il tempo per calcolare la data esatta e poi approntare il viaggio per raggiungere la Palestina. Al contrario, nel caso in cui la “stella” fosse stata un evento improvviso, l’impossibilità di calcolarla in anticipo rende impossibile preparare il viaggio in anticipo. Ma un viaggio del genere (da Babilonia alla Palestina) avrebbe impiegato un paio di mesi, e il testo non dice questo.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f8deb1fb-ccc5-42da-9da9-3785ca9cef02_2309x3025.jpeg)\n\nLa stella del mattino personificata, opera di G.H. Frezza (1704). Crediti qui.\n\nQuando i magi lasciano Gerusalemme per andare verso Betlemme, il testo dice che la stella “li precedeva”. Questo dovrebbe significare, visto che Gerusalemme e Betlemme sono su una direttrice nord-sud, che la stella avrebbe dovuto essere visibile guardando verso sud. Ma la stella è a sud solo in pieno giorno, perché dopo la levata eliaca abbiamo detto che la stella sorge sempre a est, sempre un po’ prima del Sole, fino a essere visibile anche di notte.\n\nIl termine per precedere in greco è προῆγεν (proêgen), che significa “portare avanti”. Dove altro è usata questa parola? Matteo la usa nel suo significato di “andare avanti”, o di “portare davanti a un giudice”.\n\nPerò, nel linguaggio neotestamentario il verbo viene utilizzato anche al posto di προηγεῖσθαι ( pro(h)egeisthai), che significa sì “precedere”, ma anche, dal punto di vista astronomico, “essere retrogrado”, riferito a un moto retrogrado di un pianeta. Tolomeo nel “ Tetrabiblos ” e Gemino in “ Introduzione ai Fenomeni ” lo utilizzano in questo modo. Cos’è un moto retrogrado?\n\nI pianeti si muovono, osservandoli di notte, nella stessa direzione in cui di giorno si muove il Sole. Inoltre, tutti i pianeti conosciuti dagli antichi si muovevano in una fascia intorno al Sole, detta fascia zodiacale. A volte sembra però che alcuni pianeti non si muovano nella direzione “normale”, ma sembra tornare indietro - ovvero sembrano “camminare all’indietro”.\n\nSe quindi accettiamo l’interpretazione astronomica di pro(h)egeisthai, la “stella” non può essere stata una stella per come la intendiamo noi, ma solo un pianeta, poiché le stelle non mostrano un moto retrogrado.\n\nInoltre, doveva essere un pianeta che presenta moto retrogrado durante la sua levata eliaca. Questo pianeta è Venere .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/690ed1b9-3848-4fcf-bf71-5a1c77ccb639_2157x2350.jpeg)\n\nHesperus, opera di Anton Raphael Mengs (1765). Crediti qui.\n\nQuando il testo dice che la stella si fermò sopra il luogo dove si trovava il bambino, possiamo interpretare il testo con un fenomeno noto agli astrologi antichi come “stazione di un pianeta”. Questo fenomeno avviene quando un pianeta sembra “fermarsi” rispetto al moto degli altri pianeti della fascia zodiacale, per invertire il proprio moto, da retrogrado a diretto e viceversa.\n\nQuesta interpretazione è in accordo con la natura di pianeta della “stella” che stiamo cercando, e anche con il fatto che, avvenendo la stazione del pianeta pochi giorni dopo la sua levata eliaca, il tutto debba essere avvenuto quando i magi erano già in Palestina.\n\nKoch parla del fatto che il mancato utilizzo del termine astronomico di stazione planetaria, στηριγμός ( stērigmos), da parte di Matteo , è dovuto al fatto che Matteo non era un astronomo.\n\nAccettando che la stella sia stata Venere, perché Matteo non ne dice il nome? La motivazione più immediata sembra essere che il nome del pianeta, Ashteret era associato a una divinità pagana (Astarte), e che per questo, come viene spesso fatto nel Vecchio Testamento, non se ne scriva il nome.\n\nInoltre, in Ebraico e Aramaico il pianeta Venere era anche chiamato semplicemente “la stella”, o la “lei-stella”, ovvero kōbāb/kōkäbät e kaukab/kaukabta, rispettivamente.\n\nLe altre versioni\n\nDopo aver interpretato i versetti di Matteo riportati sopra, C.J. Humpries scrive, in The Star of Bethlehem, che le caratteristiche della stella possono essere elencate come segue:\n\n1) è una nuova stella, una che prima non era visibile;\n\n2) si muoveva lentamente nel cielo, apparendo in punti diversi del cielo in momenti diversi;\n\n3) a un certo punto sembrò fermarsi sopra Betlemme, nel senso che vista da Gerusalemme, la stella sembrava trovarsi sopra il luogo in cui si trova Betlemme.\n\nLe idee che propone inizialmente Humpries riguardano la congiunzione di due pianeti, una nova, e una cometa.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/78d8c6b0-65d8-4456-b6fd-a3639c08e1f2_744x1024.jpeg)\n\nFosforo e Espero, ognuno con la sua torcia., opera di Evelyn De Morgan (1881). Crediti qui.\n\nUna congiunzione\n\nA partire dall’VIII secolo CE, l’astronomo ebreo Māshāʾallāh parla di una congiunzione planetaria di Giove e Saturno avvenuta nel 7 secolo BCE.\n\nIl problema, secondo Humpries, è che questa spiegazione non è attestata da nessun altro prima di lui; Koch aggiunge che i problemi riguardano anche la natura stessa della congiunzione: nel momento della congiunzione, i pianeti sarebbero dovuti essere distanti sulla volta celeste un paio di diametri lunari, ovvero una distanza a cui i pianeti sono ancora distinguibili, e che quindi difficilmente avrebbe reso quella congiunzione una stella.\n\nInoltre, accettando l’interpretazione della levata eliaca, del moto retrogrado, e della stazionarietà, una congiunzione planetaria non ne soddisfa nessuna.\n\nUna nova\n\nJean-François Foucquet (1665-1741), gesuita e scienziato francese, come un secolo prima anche Johannes Kepler (1571-1630), astronomo tedesco, scrive che una nova sarebbe potuta essere la stella, in particolare una nova esplosa in concotimanza con la congiunzione di Giove e Saturno del 7 BCE.\n\nUna nova è un fenomeno che avviene quando la luminosità di una stella aumenta improvvisamente, facendo in modo che per un osservatore quella stessa stella, prima magari poco visibile, appaia molto più luminosa di prima.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/47b33caf-f88b-4bf6-92f5-07bc56a41d22_2560x1789.jpeg)\n\nCapricorno, opera di Sidney Hall (1825). Crediti qui.\n\nIl problema con questa teoria è che eventi di questo tipo sono impossibili da prevedere, e che quindi non c’era modo da parte dei magi di preparare un viaggio per poi arrivare a Gerusalemme e osservare la nova.\n\nInoltre, una nova è un fenomeno che riguarda le stelle, che non hanno dei moti osservabili in modo evidente, tale da far dire ai magi che la stella li ha “guidati”.\n\nInoltre, ai tempi di Kepler la differenza tra una nova e una cometa era ancora impercettibile, in quanto si pensava che le novae fossero comete senza coda. E fu proprio Kepler a ipotizzare che le novae, non muovendosi rispetto al cielo delle stelle fisse, appartenessero a questa stessa sfera, a differenza delle comete, che invece abitano le sfere più vicine alla Terra.\n\nMa non solo in Europa questa differenza non era ancora percettibile: esistono fonti in Cina che parlano di comete intorno al 5 o al 4 BCE, interpretabili sia nel significato attuale del termine sia come stelle novae.\n\nEd è proprio una cometa il corpo celeste candidato, insieme a Venere, a ricoprire il ruolo di “stella” della Natività.\n\nUna cometa\n\nGià a partire dal II secolo CE, Origene parla di una cometa come di un possibile candidato per il ruolo di “stella” presente nel vangelo di Matteo.\n\nLa teoria sulla natura delle comete risaliva ad Aristotele, secondo cui erano oggetti che appartenevano alla sfera sub-lunare, che vivevano nella parte superiore dell’atmosfera.\n\nErano segni di presagio, non necessariamente di cattivo augurio, ma ad esempio Dione Cassio , quando descrive il passaggio di una cometa (che probabilmente era la cometa di Halley) lo fa mettendola in relazione alla morte di Marco Vipsanio Agrippa , generale romano (63 BCE -12 BCE).\n\nLa prima cometa di cui si riesce a predire il passaggio è la cometa di Halley, chiamata così in relazione all’astronomo inglese che ne ipotizzò la prevedibilità dopo averla osservata nel 1705, confermata nel 1759.\n\nUna previsione del genere non era possibile al tempo del I secolo BCE, - e fino all’invenzione del telescopio, perlomeno - quindi i magi non avrebbero potuto utilizzare la previsione di una cometa per preparare il proprio viaggio.\n\nKoch utilizza questo argomento, tra gli altri, per parlare dell’impossibilità che la “stella” seguita dai magi fosse una cometa.\n\nHumpries non è dello stesso avviso, e indaga il fenomeno; lo fa cercando negli archivi cinesi una traccia di fenomeni riconducibili a comete datati intorno agli anni in cui si data, dai resoconti che abbiamo, la possibile nascita di Gesù.\n\nRiduce la ricerca a tre fenomeni:\n\n(1) una cometa, po-hsing, passata intorno all’agosto del 12 BCE (che è la cometa di Halley), visibile per poco meno di 60 giorni;\n\n(2) una cometa sui-hsing, visibile tra marzo e aprile del 5 BCE;\n\n(3) un’altra cometa po-hsing, visibile intorno ad aprile del 4 BCE.\n\nUtilizzando le informazioni contenute nel vangelo di Luca, Humpries procede così: poiché Gesù si dice avesse circa 30 anni al tempo del battesimo da parte di Giovanni Battista (Luca 3, 23), il quale aveva iniziato il proprio ministero durante il quindicesimo anno di impero di Tiberio (Luca 3, 1-2), una data possibile per il battesimo sopracitato potrebbe essere l’anno del 29 CE o il periodo tra l’autunno del 28 e quello del 29 CE. Ciò significa, interpretando l’espressione “circa 30 anni” come tra i 26 e i 34 anni, che la data anteriore per la nascita di Gesù è il 7 BCE.\n\nQuesto elimina la possibilità che la cometa di Halley nel passaggio del 12 BCE rappresenti la “stella” della natività.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/7fd77199-9d0c-478b-b06c-f929119299d7_1492x1036.jpeg)\n\nComet 1P/Halley fotografata l’8 Marzo 1986, da W. Liller. Crediti qui.\n\nQual è invece la data posteriore per la nascita? La si ottiene dalla data della morte del re Erode il Grande, il quale si dice sia morto a marzo del 4 BCE.\n\nPoiché la cometa dell’aprile del 4 BCE è successiva a questa data, e sappiamo che Gesù, dai resoconti dei vangeli, è nato durante il regno di Erode, allora possiamo eliminare anche la cometa risalente a questa data.\n\nResta quindi la cometa apparsa intorno al marzo del 5 BCE. Humpries, dai resoconti delle apparizioni della cometa, ricostruisce quanto segue: pare che sia apparsa nei paesi che oggi compongono l’Arabia verso i primi di marzo, in un’area del cielo che include la zona in cui si disegna la costellazione del Capricorno; era visibile da questi paesi nelle prime luci dell’alba; il suo moto è compatibile con la direttrice Gerusalemme-Betlemme, poiché pare avesse la coda lungo quella direzione, muovendosi verso nord.\n\nAccettando che questa è la cometa osservata dai Magi, che da Babilonia a Gerusalemme avevano il tempo per viaggiare durante il percorso della cometa in cielo, durato poco meno di due mesi, un presagio del genere era sufficiente per mobilitarli?\n\nHumpries collega la cometa ad altri fenomeni celesti, in particolare ad altri due: il primo è la congiunzione di Saturno e Giove del 7 BCE, il secondo la vicinanza di tre pianeti nel 6 BCE. Questi fenomeni sembravano preparare l’arrivo di un simbolo ulteriore, e definitivo: la cometa in Capricorno del 5 BCE.\n\nCome mai?\n\nIsaac Abarbanel , filosofo ebreo del XV secolo CE, scrive che nella astrologia e mitologia dei magi, Saturno rappresenta il divino padre, e Giove è suo figlio.\n\nInoltre, il terzo pianeta del 6 BCE è Marte, il quale anticipa la venuta di un re guerriero, per l’astrologia caldea (in Babilonia); e la cometa del 5 BCE attraversa Capricorno, che è considerato sede della rinascita del Sole, e la dimora diurna di Saturno.\n\nAncora, i magi affermano di aver visto la stella “da est”: sappiamo già che questa interpretazione è dibattuta, ma accettandola come fa una parte della comunità degli studiosi, Humpries ne estrae l’informazione che fu quello il motivo della rapida partenza dei magi. Secondo Tolomeo infatti, era conoscenza comune agli astrologi che una cometa che arrivasse “da est” fosse previsione di eventi di imminente realizzazione , mentre una cometa che arrivasse da occidente parlasse di eventi più in là nel tempo.\n\nInfine anche Daniele, profeta ebreo in esilio a Babilonia, parla di un re comparandolo a un animale con le corna (quando parla di Alessandro Magno).\n\nAccettando questa interpretazione, concordano i tempi di percorrenza del tragitto dei magi e la visione della cometa in cielo? Secondo Humpries si, poiché percorrendo tra le 50 e le 100 miglia al giorno, una media accettabile per i mezzi e il periodo, il percorso dell’epoca da Babilonia a Gerusalemme prima e Betlemme poi, è compreso tra le 500 e le 900 miglia.\n\nInoltre, Matteo non dice che i magi seguirono la cometa per tutto il tragitto, ma solo che lì indirizzò verso occidente, e che li precedette verso Betlemme.\n\nKoch è scettico su questa interpretazione per diversi motivi, tra i quali il fatto che le comete sono fenomeni sorprendenti quando sono particolarmente visibili, cosa che non sembra sia successa per una cometa in quel periodo temporale, o che la cometa di Halley tornò a visitare la Terra nell’anno 66 CE, quando Matteo era perfettamente in grado di osservarla: se così fece, perché non collegò questa cometa a quella del 5 BCE, magari annunciando una seconda venuta di Cristo, come tutti i cristiani in quei primi anni dopo la sua morte si aspettavano?\n\nVenere come stella\n\nAccettando l’interpretazione di Koch sulla natura della “stella” della natività come Venere, cerchiamo di capire perché Matteo, nonostante non nomini mai il nome del pianeta, avrebbe potuto scegliere come simbolo della nascita di Gesù tale corpo celeste.\n\nInnanzitutto, Koch collega il pianeta Venere alle divinità dell’Asia occidentale, in particolare in Mesopotamia, con la dea Ishtar, e nel regno degli Assiri.\n\nIn queste regioni la dea aveva nomi leggermente diversi, come Ishtar, Astarte, Athart, ed era associata al ruolo di protettrice e creatrice di re.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #13\n\nIncidentalmente, la rappresentazione della donna vergine con il dio bambino, nella figura della Vergine Maria con Gesù Bambino, ricade nella tradizione della relazione tra il re e la divinità che lo protegge, o nella rappresentazione della fertilità. Esempi sono le divinità in Assiria e Babilonia che proteggevano il re fin dalla nascita, e il rapporto tra il piccolo Horus e la dea Iside.\n\nPoi, dopo aver inquadrato il pianeta come l’astro più luminoso del cielo dopo il Sole e la Luna, e che proprio con gli altri due astri a Babilonia forma una triade di divinità astrali (rispettivamente Ishtar, Shamash e Sin), Koch parla di Venere come del simbolo della resurrezione dalla morte, per via del fatto che è al contempo la Espero e Fosforo, rispettivamente la stella della sera, che va a morire verso occidente, e la stella del mattino, che rinasce a oriente.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #14\n\nGirolamo, uno dei padri della Chiesa, afferma che, nel luogo che la tradizione riconosce come la sede della nascita di Gesù la comunità locale di fedeli, dai tempi di Adriano e fino al regno di Costantino - ovvero poco meno di due secoli - avessero eretto un piccolo santuario in onore di Tammuz, ovvero di Adone.\n\nAdone, che in semitico significa “signore, padrone”, era una antica divinità venerata in Mesopotamia, ed era l’amante di Ishtar, ovvero Venere.\n\nAnche George Frazier, etnologo scozzese del XX secolo CE, parla della “stella” di Betlemme come di Venere, stella del mattino, collegandola al culto di Adone osservato nell’area.\n\nVenere è una “stella” di importanza particolare non solo nelle tradizioni che i cristiani considerano pagane: anche nella Bibbia, nonostante non venga chiamata per nome, ci sono riferimenti a questa figura.\n\nIn Apocalisse 22,16, l’autore riporta le parole di Gesù che afferma di essere ὁ ἀστὴρ ὁ λαμπρὸς ὁ πρωϊνός, ovvero la brillante stella del mattino . Anche in un verso della seconda lettera di Pietro (II Pietro, 1,19), l’autore parla di Gesù paragonandolo alla stella del mattino, ovvero Venere .\n\nQuale data, infine?\n\nAbbiamo già parlato del fatto che è improbabile che la nascita di Gesù sia avvenuta il 25 dicembre, e siamo lontani dal poter arrivare a una data specifica.\n\nLa decisione di selezionare una data specifica viene attribuita solitamente alla necessità di definire una ortodossia, in un periodo successivo ai primi secoli dopo l’inizio del culto cristiano, volta a differenziare il giorno della nascita di Gesù da quello della sua manifestazione nel mondo, che prima gli gnostici e poi i manichei avevano sollevato come punto critico della storiografia cristiana.\n\nLa data del 25 dicembre sembra essere stata concordata successivamente dalla Chiesa di Roma prima, e poi da quasi tutte le altre, per diversi motivi, legati principalmente alla presenza di culti solari precedenti o contemporanei, come il culto del Sole Invitto, o quello di Mitra, e si può inserire all’interno della tradizione di festeggiare il solstizio d’inverno.\n\nSe ti è piaciuto questo episodio, puoi condividerlo con chi vuoi.\n\nSe vuoi, puoi iscriverti per sostenere questa pubblicazione, utilizzando l’offerta qui sotto:\n\nGet 50% off for 1 year\n\nOppure, puoi iscriverti gratuitamente seguendo il link qui sotto:\n\nGrazie!\n\nLeggi la serie “ sul moto della Terra” :\n\nBibliografia:\n\nThe Star of Bethlehem - a Comet in 5 BC - and the Date of the Birth of Christ, by Humphreys, C. J., [Quarterly Journal of the Royal Astronomical Society, Vol. 32, NO.4/DEC, P.389] (1991)\n\nThe Star of Bethlehem, by Koch D. (2016)\n\nSol Invictus. The winter solstice and the origins of Christmas, by Hijmans S., [Mouseion, Series III, Vol. 3, 377-398] (2003)\n\nQuesta newsletter è una di tre: le altre due sono Last Scattering Surface, e Space of Sound. Tutte le pubblicazioni sono gratuite e puoi consultare tutti gli articoli senza paywall. Se vuoi, puoi iscriverti qui e qui.\n\nInfine, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n\nCiao e a presto!\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_009-the-responses-to-parmenides.md": "Disclaimer #1: questo articolo è in inglese, la versione in italiano si può leggere qui.\n\nDisclaimer #2: this episode is part of a series named “ on the motion of the Earth ”, published both on this publication, Heralding Time , and on Last Scattering Surface . If you want, you can follow them both. Here chapters I, II, III, IV, V, VI, VII.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/aef427ae-3bea-498a-af06-20d6d4ca1b12_1080x1350.png)\n\nWelcome back.\n\nWe left off in the last chapter with Parmenides’ ontological philosophy, for whom the senses are not sufficient to arrive at Truth - indeed, they can be harmful.\n\nIn this episode we will see how Parmenides’ contemporaries and especially his successors tried to answer his questions, and to resolve his doubts. There are those who will defend his theses, and those who will attack them: but both camps are included in the category of post-Parmenidean philosophers.\n\nGet 50% off for 1 year\n\nThe post-Parmenideans\n\nZeno\n\nWe will not talk too much about Zeno, because he himself was not interested in developing or commenting on cosmological models. We know he was born around 490 BCE1, and that he was a disciple of Parmenides in Elea, the city where he lived and taught. Plato informs us that he wrote to defend the theses of his master Parmenides, and Aristotle speaks of him as the father of dialectic2.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5a5e9600-5bb9-45a1-b4b4-131ab17e75ec_1240x1260.png)\n\nEmpedocles\n\nThe first of the two philosophers we will discuss who were critical of Parmenides, Empedocles has his acme around the LXXXIV Olympiad, so it seems he was born around 482 BCE3, or in 492 BCE, and died around 432 BCE. Originally from Agrigento, a Greek city in Sicily, he visits Thurii and probably meets the Pythagoreans; he is then exiled to the Peloponnese.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/701fde01-e347-4224-988f-70da5afe792e_1240x1178.png)\n\nDiogenes Laertius writes that to prove he was the son of a god, he threw himself into the crater of Mount Etna.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1ad9f455-9197-498d-8494-6d109c1e9209_1230x1664.jpeg)\n\nThe death of Empedocles, work by Salvator Rosa (1670). Image obtained fromPrivate collection (Helen Langdon, Salvator Rosa - Dulwich Picture Gallery). Credits here.\n\nHe writes two works, \"On Nature\" and \"Purifications\", although some maintain they are the same text. Only fragments remain, and accepting the division into two books, the first contains physical explanations about the Universe, while the second the explanation of the Pythagorean doctrine of the transmigration of souls. We will speak of the first work, which concerns his cosmological ideas.\n\nUndergoing an evident influence from Parmenides, Empedocles’ interest is first of all to answer the questions posed by him: (i) things exist because they have always existed, therefore there is no need for them to be born from nothing, which cannot exist; (iii) the plurality of the world does not come from Unity, but from the plurality of things, that is from water, air, earth and fire; (ii) these four elements completely fill the Universe, which therefore does not contain the void around it, since this cannot exist; (iv) motion is due to the presence of two “forces,” Love and Strife .\n\nBright note in the margin #9\n\nThe concept of perennial unity even in multiplicity serves Empedocles also to explain the birth of humanity.\n\nFor the philosopher the sexes are produced by the division of creatures “of full nature,” subsequently divided into males and females.\n\nIn the Brihadaranyaka Upanishad the Universe begins as a unity in human form, in a very similar way.\n\n“Now it was of the size of a man and a woman locked in an embrace. It divided itself in two, and from this man and woman were born.”\n\nEmpedocles’ cosmology begins with a single sphere that already contains the plurality of elements, since nothing can be born or perish, but only be altered . These elements are called “roots,” and are eternal, in fixed quantities, and do not transform or change in any way. However, they are not elements as we understand them today in physics and chemistry: we can consider them as we today understand the states of matter - solid, liquid, gaseous, plasma. To water is associated the divinity Nestis (Persephone), to fire Zeus, to air Hera , and to earth Aidoneus , probably Hades.\n\nThen comes the ether, fire, earth, and water. Last comes air, and all things are born: the firmament from ether, the sun from fire, terrestrial things from water, air and earth. From these elements, and thanks to Love and Strife, things assume their form: are these two concepts forces , or physical objects ? It is not clear, but it seems they represent tendencies, which are added to the natural ones of the elements: for example, fire and air naturally tend to rise , while water and earth tend to descend ; to this are added the tendencies of things to unite and dissolve according to the periods the world goes through, whether of greater Love or greater Strife .\n\nAëtius reports that for Empedocles the stars are made of fire, and are fixed on the celestial vault, as Anaximenes already said. The celestial vault, formed by air solidified or frozen\" by fire, is not a perfect sphere, but has the shape of an egg.\n\nWhile the stars are fixed, the planets are free to move around the Earth, and one of them is the Sun, which is not made of fire, but reflects part of it.\n\nThe alternation of day and night and of the seasons is explained by the existence of two hemispheres, one of fire and the other of air, in which there is some fire, which rotate around the Earth. Eclipses are due to the passage of the Earth in front of the Moon.\n\nThese two hemispheres do not have equal size, and this is the reason for the different length of the seasons during the year; moreover, it is precisely the revolutionary motion of these two hemispheres that keeps the Earth stationary in its place at the center of the Universe.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/8266ad8b-93c4-47f3-b6f5-a188c6daa575_800x954.jpeg)\n\nIllustration from a 1587 treatise on comets and meteors, created anonymously in Flanders (now northern France) and known as the Kometenbuch . Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / ORKA - Open Repository Kassel.\n\nThe Moon is a reflection of the light of the Sun, and is formed by frozen air, surrounded by a sphere of fire; it has the shape of a disk, and this comment does not allow us to understand if the shape of the celestial bodies - and of the Earth itself - is for Empedocles a flat disk or a sphere. In any case, the Sun is larger than the Moon, but despite this it is twice as far from Earth as the Moon is. The light of the celestial bodies reaches us after crossing the distance between the fire and the Earth.\n\nEmpedocles therefore does not completely reject Parmenides’ ideas, but affirms that change is observable, and that it really occurs in the world, generating new things from the mixture of different elements.\n\nAnaxagoras\n\nAnaxagoras of Clazomenae, a city in Ionia, was born around 500 BCE4. During his life he moves to Athens, bringing for the first time the philosophy of Asia Minor and Magna Graecia to the polis, and works closely with Pericles. He has the distinction of being the first philosopher of whom there is news to have been condemned for impiety , for having stated that the Sun is a burning stone, and not a divinity. Unlike Socrates, he goes into exile in Lampsacus - a city of the Troad in Asia Minor - and dies there around 428 BCE.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/8ef0fb0f-da75-42db-90a7-334a40ccf203_1240x1264.png)\n\nDiogenes Laertius reports that for Anaxagoras the task of humanity is \" to question the Sun, the Moon and the firmament\".\n\nFrom the information we have, it seems he wrote a work in prose titled “Physica,” that is “Studies on Nature.” Certainly later than Parmenides’ period of activity, from him he accepts the division between what is and what is not, and the renunciation of the concept of creation and destruction of things in the world.\n\nSimilarly to Empedocles, Anaxagoras considers change the work of separation and mixture , but unlike him, he considers separation the only cause of destruction , and mixture as the only cause for creation .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/fb2d62ce-fb0f-4d6f-869a-5572c3487b31_1070x1200.jpeg)\n\nA Representation of the Convexity, if I may call it so, work by Thomas Wright (1750). Image obtained from Public Domain Image Archive / Internet Archive / The Getty\n\nHis system provides for five entities: (1) macroscopic objects, (2) simple things, (3) portions , (4) seeds , (5) the Mind . Moreover, there are six principles that govern the world: (i) destruction and creation do not exist, (ii) there exist many, infinite in number, simple things, (iii) there is a portion of everything in everything, (iv) everything is mainly composed of the portion most present in that thing, (v) an infinitesimal portion does not exist, (vi) the NOUS is not mixed and (I) knows everything, (II) governs everything, (III) defines everything in order, (IV) causing its motion.\n\nIn the beginning all things were mixed; the Mind then causes the rotation of everything, creating first in a limited place, and then everywhere, the separation of identifiable objects from the initial mixture. The rotation leads the elements to separate: first the aer and the aether separate, air and ether, present in larger portions. Air tends toward the center, while ether, lighter, toward the periphery of the vortex.\n\nThe heavier things go toward the center, except for the celestial bodies, which although they are burning rocks, remain in the air thanks to the speed of rotation of the vortex, which increases more and more.\n\nBright note in the margin #10\n\nThe description of celestial bodies as burning rocks could have been suggested to Anaxagoras, or found confirmation in it, in the fall of a meteorite at Aegospotami in 467 BCE.\n\nFor Anaxagoras there exists an infinite number of portions, therefore they are not comparable to our chemical elements, and these portions, also called roots, are compressed by the rotation due to the vortex and form the solid bodies we find on Earth.\n\nThe Earth is flat, and remains stationary because it is very large, because air supports it, and because the void does not exist. The Sun, the Moon and the planets are burning rocks that orbit in the sky around the Earth, and when we do not see them they orbit beneath it. The Moon is formed of the same materials of which the Earth is made, and its light is a reflection of sunlight; lunar eclipses are caused both by the position of the Earth in relation to it and by smaller bodies that obscure it in their passages.\n\nIt is not clear if for Anaxagoras the contemporary worlds he speaks of are worlds different from Earth, or places of our Earth but inaccessible to us: in any case, he speaks of the Milky Way as a collection of stars, more visible than the other stars in the sky because wrapped in the shadow of the Earth when the Sun passes beneath it. It is not surprising that the Earth has movements: already Anaxagoras, who had also defined the Earth as stationary, supposes that earthquakes occur when the air on which it rests moves because of the rain that infiltrates into the Earth, causing a slight movement of it.\n\nMelissus\n\nOriginally from Samos, probably born around 500 BCE, in his treatise \"On Nature\" he speaks, like Parmenides, of Being as uncreated, indestructible, indivisible, unchangeable, without motion, and always equal to itself. Unlike Parmenides, however, he defines the world as infinite, not only in time, but also in space.\n\nThe Atomists\n\nLeucippus and Democritus\n\nFor Leucippus, a philosopher of whom we know almost nothing except that around 450 BCE he creates a school together with his disciple Democritus, the void exists, and matter is formed by an infinite number of small bodies, which are not divisible (atoms). Among these, the moister atoms with fire become stars. Change therefore is due to the accumulation in one place of particles that already exist from the beginning. The atoms moreover are infinite not only in number but also in shape and size.\n\nLeucippus’ theories are often proposed together with those of Democritus, since it is difficult to discern the individual contributions. Democritus was born, according to Apollodorus, around 458 BCE, and is as we said a disciple of Leucippus, both active in Abdera. The text of atomism he writes (or they write) is \"The Little World System\", and everything there is traced back to the shape and dimensions of atoms.\n\nThe cosmology that can be reconstructed for both is the following: two things exist, atoms and the void, and the former move within the latter. Moreover, there exists a distinction between the Universe, which is the totality of what exists, and the Cosmos, which is instead the world system limited in time and space. Infinite worlds exist, and each is born when many bodies of different shapes move toward the void, creating a vortex that makes things separate \"according to necessity\": the heavier bodies move toward the center, and the Earth is at the center.\n\nThe Sun and Moon rotate around the Earth. The order of celestial bodies for Leucippus is Sun, planets, stars, Moon, and Earth at the center, while for Democritus the order is slightly different: stars, planets, Sun, Moon, Venus and Earth. Eclipses occur when the Earth modifies its own inclination with respect to the zenith.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/c75614fd-2da8-46f3-9087-e7e81b809ea4_601x800.jpeg)\n\nColour wheel, featured in his treatise on colour Versuch eines Farbensystems , opera di Ignaz Schiffermüller (1772). Image obtained from Public Domain Image Archive / Internet Archive / The Getty\n\nIn conclusion, Leucippus creates a physical theory in response to Parmenides, introducing the idea of atoms, indivisible, and Democritus modifies Leucippus’ theory to describe different phenomena.\n\nThe cosmos of the atomists has nothing special, divine, or inevitable about it.\n\nDiogenes of Apollonia\n\nBorn in the Milesian colony of Apollonia in the 5th century BCE, he is considered by Theophrastus \"the last natural philosopher\", therefore in full tradition of the philosophers of Miletus. Diogenes Laertius counts him among the disciples of Anaximenes, and places his acme between 440 and 430 BCE.\n\nHe considers air divine and identifies it with the origin of the world, and in his cosmology the Earth is flat and stationary at the center of the world, supported by a vortex created by heat generated by the exhalations of the world. He resolves the inconsistency between the affirmation that interaction between bodies does not exist, and the evidence that this interaction occurs, by stating that all things derive from a single substance, which therefore can interact with a part of itself.\n\nIn his cosmology it is the first time we encounter the \"argument from design\": if all things are designed in the best possible way, at the origin of such an design there must be an intelligent designer\".\n\nThe celestial bodies are pumice stones, light and fiery some, light and invisible the others, which sometimes fall to Earth (also for Diogenes this description could concern the meteorite that fell at Aegospotami which we mentioned earlier).\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/4a693a3c-a157-4f4d-9d80-da6f099ac5b7_1240x1146.png)\n\nWe have spoken so far of schools in Miletus, in Elea; we have arrived as far as Athens with the first philosophers to bring cosmology to the polis; we have dealt with philosophers about whom nothing is known, and those for whom the information we have is discordant.\n\nArthur Koestler speaks of philosophy in Greece up to this moment as a musical ensemble in which everyone tries to tune their instrument. In the next episode we will talk about the one who managed to tune the orchestra .\n\nIn the next episode: tuning the orchestra\n\nRead the other episodes:\n\nBibliography:\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe, by Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, edited by C. Blacker and M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nGreek Cosmologies, by G.E.R. Lloyd\n\nAristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus, by Heath T. (Oxford 1913)\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, di Kirk G.S. and Raven J.E. (Cambridge 1957)\n\nEarly Greek Philosophy and the Orient, by West M.L. (Oxford 1971)\n\nPhilosophy before Socrates, by McKirahan R.D. (Hackett 1994)\n\nEarly Greek Science, by G.E.R. Lloyd (Chatto & Windus 1970)\n\nA history of astronomy from Thales to Kepler, by J.L.E Dreyer (Dover 1953)\n\nHeaven And Earth In Ancient Greek Cosmology, by D.L. Cuprie (Springer 2011)\n\nEarly Greek Cosmology: A Historiographical Review, by N.S. Hetherington\n\nBack to the Pre-Socratics: The Presidential Address, by K.R. Popper (1958)\n\nEarly Greek astronomy to Aristotle, by D.R. Dicks (Cornell University Press 1970)\n\nHistory of Philosophy Volume I: From the Beginning to Plato, edited by C.C.W. Taylor (Routledge 1997)\n\nThe Ionians, by Malcolm Schofield\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, by Jonathan Barnes (Routledge 1979)\n\nA Source Book In Greek Science by M.R. Cohen e I.E. Drabkin (Harvard University Press 1945)\n\nThe Physical World of the Greeks, by S. Sambursky (The Macmillan Company 1956)\n\nNotes\n\n1 Plato, Parmenides .\n\n2 Diogenes Laertius, Lives of Philosophers .\n\n3 Diogenes Laertius, Lives of Philosophers .\n\n4 Diogenes Laertius, Lives of Philosophers .\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_010-le-risposte-a-parmenide.md": "Disclaimer #1: this article is in Italian. I will publish the English version next Wednesday.\n\nDisclaimer #2: questo pezzo fa parte di una serie, pubblicata sia su questa newsletter, Heralding Time , che su Last Scattering Surface . Se vuoi, puoi seguirle entrambe. Qui i capitoli I, II, III, IV, V, VI, VII.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/fbf28050-0233-4bb2-9ee2-96f4b800acbe_1080x1350.png)\n\nBentornati.\n\nCi siamo lasciati nell’ultimo capitolo con la filosofia ontologica di Parmenide, per il quale i sensi non sono sufficienti per arrivare alla Verità - anzi, possono essere dannosi.\n\nIn questo episodio vedremo come i contemporanei e sopratutto i successori di Parmenide abbiano cercato di rispondere ai suoi quesiti, e di sciogliere i suoi dubbi. C’è chi difenderà le sue tesi, e chi le attaccherà: entrambi gli schieramenti sono però racchiusi nella categoria dei filosofi post-parmenidei .\n\nIscriviti gratuitamente a questa newsletter, e considera questa offerta per diventare abbonato a pagamento e supportare quello che faccio!\n\nGet 40% off for 1 year\n\nGrazie! (questa offerta si autodistruggerà il primo dicembre)\n\nI post-Parmenidei\n\nZenone\n\nDi Zenone non parleremo troppo, perché lui stesso non si è interessato di sviluppare o commentare modelli di cosmologia. Sappiamo che è nato intorno al 490 BCE1, e che è stato discepolo di Parmenide a Elea, la città in cui ha vissuto e insegnato. Platone ci informa che scrisse per difendere le tesi del maestro Parmenide, e Aristotele parla di lui come del padre della dialettica2.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5a5e9600-5bb9-45a1-b4b4-131ab17e75ec_1240x1260.png)\n\nEmpedocle\n\nPrimo dei due filosofi di cui parleremo critici nei confronti di Parmenide, Empedocle ha il suo acme intorno alla LXXXIV Olimpiade, dunque pare sia nato intorno al 482 BCE3, o nel 492 BCE, e morto intorno al 432 BCE. Originario di Agrigento, una città greca in Sicilia, visita Thurii e probabilmente conosce i pitagorici; viene poi esiliato nel Peloponneso.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/701fde01-e347-4224-988f-70da5afe792e_1240x1178.png)\n\nDiogene Laerzio scrive che per dimostrare di essere figlio di un dio, si lanciò dal cratere dell’Etna.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1ad9f455-9197-498d-8494-6d109c1e9209_1230x1664.jpeg)\n\nLa morte di Empedocle, opera di Salvator Rosa (1670). Immagine ottenuta da Private collection (Helen Langdon, Salvator Rosa - Dulwich Picture Gallery). Credits qui.\n\nScrive due opere, \"Sulla Natura\" e \"Purificazioni\", anche se alcuni sostengono che siano lo stesso testo. Ne restano solo dei frammenti, e accettando la divisione in due libri, il primo contiene spiegazioni fisiche sull’Universo, mentre il secondo la spiegazione della dottrina pitagorica della trasmigrazione delle anime. Parleremo della prima opera, che riguarda le sue idee cosmologiche.\n\nSubendo una evidente influenza da Parmenide, l’interesse di Empedocle è innanzitutto rispondere alle domande poste da questi: (i) le cose esistono perché sono sempre esistite, dunque non c’è bisogno che nascano dal nulla, che non può esistere; (ii) la pluralità del mondo non arriva dall’Unità, ma dalla pluralità delle cose, ovvero da acqua, aria, terra e fuoco; (iii) questi quattro elementi riempiono completamente l’Universo, che quindi non contiene il vuoto al suo intorno, poiché questo non può esistere; (iv) il moto è dovuto alla presenza di due \"forze\", Amore e Conflitto .\n\nNota luminosa a margine #9\n\nIl concetto di perenne unità anche nella molteplicità serve a Empedocle anche per spiegare la nascita dell'umanità.\n\nPer il filosofo i sessi sono prodotti dalla divisione di creature \"di piena natura\", divisi successivamente in maschi e femmine.\n\nNel Brihadaranyaka Upanishad, testo sacro indu, l'Universo inizia come una unità in forma umana, in modo molto simile.\n\n\"Ora esso era della grandezza di un uomo e di una donna stretti in un abbraccio. Esso divise sé in due, e da questo nacquero l'uomo e la donna\".\n\nLa cosmologia di Empedocle inizia con una unica sfera che già contiene la pluralità degli elementi, poiché nulla può nascere o perire, ma solo alterarsi . Questi elementi sono chiamati \"radici\", e sono eterni, in quantità fisse, e non si trasformano o cambiano in alcun modo. Non sono però elementi come li intendiamo oggi in fisica e in chimica: possiamo considerarli come oggi intendiamo gli stati della materia - solido, liquido, gassoso, plasma. All’acqua è associata la divinità Nestis (Persefone), al fuoco Zeus , all’aria Era , e alla terra Aidone , probabilmente Ade.\n\nPoi arriva l’etere, il fuoco, la terra, e l’acqua. Per ultima arriva l’aria, e tutte le cose nascono: il firmamento dall’etere, il sole dal fuoco, le cose terrestri dall’acqua, l’aria e la terra. Da questi elementi, e grazie ad Amore e Conflitto, le cose assumono la loro forma: questi due concetti sono delle forze , o sono oggetti fisici ? Non è chiaro, ma pare che rappresentino delle tendenze, che si sommano a quelle naturali degli elementi: ad esempio, il fuoco e l’aria tendono naturalmente a salire , mentre l’acqua e la terra tendono a scendere ; a questo si aggiungono le tendenze delle cose ad unirsi e dissolversi a seconda dei periodi che il mondo attraversa, se di maggior Amore o maggior Conflitto .\n\nAezio riporta che per Empedocle le stelle sono fatte di fuoco, e sono fisse sulla volta celeste, come già diceva Anassimene. La volta celeste, formata da aria solida o \"congelata\" dal fuoco, non è una sfera perfetta, ma ha la forma di un uovo.\n\nMentre le stelle sono fisse, i pianeti sono liberi di muoversi intorno alla Terra, e uno di essi è il Sole, che non è fatto di fuoco, ma ne riflette una parte.\n\nL’alternanza del giorno e della notte e delle stagioni è spiegato con l’esistenza di due emisferi, uno di fuoco e l’altro di aria, in cui c’è un po’ di fuoco, che ruotano intorno alla Terra. Le eclissi sono dovute al passaggio della Terra davanti alla Luna.\n\nQuesti due emisferi non hanno uguale grandezza, e questo è il motivo della diversa lunghezza delle stagioni durante l’anno; inoltre, è proprio il moto di rivoluzione di questi due emisferi a mantenere ferma la Terra al suo posto al centro dell’Universo.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/8266ad8b-93c4-47f3-b6f5-a188c6daa575_800x954.jpeg)\n\nIllustration from a 1587 treatise on comets and meteors, created anonymously in Flanders (now northern France) and known as the Kometenbuch . Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / ORKA - Open Repository Kassel.\n\nLa Luna è un riflesso della luce del Sole, ed è formata da aria congelata, circondata da una sfera di fuoco; ha la forma di un disco, e questo commento non ci permette di capire se la forma degli astri - e della Terra stessa - sia per Empedocle un disco piatto o una sfera. Ad ogni modo, il Sole è più grande della Luna, ma nonostante ciò è due volte più lontano dalla Terra di quanto non lo sia la Luna. La luce degli astri ci raggiunge dopo aver attraversato la distanza tra il fuoco e la Terra.\n\nEmpedocle quindi non rigetta completamente le idee di Parmenide, ma afferma che il cambiamento sia osservabile, e che avvenga realmente nel mondo, generando nuove cose dalla miscela di elementi diversi.\n\nAnassagora\n\nAnassagora di Clazomene, città della Ionia, nasce intorno al 500 BCE4. Durante la vita si trasferisce ad Atene, portando per la prima volta la filosofia dell’Asia Minore e della Magna Grecia nella polis, e lavora a stretto contatto con Pericle. Ha il primato di essere stato il primo filosofo di cui si hanno notizie ad essere stato condannato per empietà , per aver affermato che il Sole è una pietra infuocata, e non una divinità. A differenza di Socrate, va in esilio a Làmpsaco - città della Troade in Asia Minore - e lì muore intorno al 428 BCE.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/8ef0fb0f-da75-42db-90a7-334a40ccf203_1240x1264.png)\n\nDiogene Laerzio riporta che per Anassagora il compito dell’umanità è \" interrogare il Sole, la Luna e il firmamento \".\n\nDalle informazioni che abbiamo, pare che abbia scritto un’opera in prosa dal titolo \"Physica\", ovvero \"Studi sulla Natura\". Sicuramente posteriore al periodo di attività di Parmenide, da questi accetta la divisione tra ciò che è e ciò che non è, e la rinuncia del concetto di creazione e distruzione delle cose del mondo.\n\nSimilmente a Empedocle, Anassagora considera il cambiamento opera di separazione e commistione, ma a differenza di questi, considera la separazione l’unica causa della distruzione , e la commistione come l’unica causa per la creazione .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/fb2d62ce-fb0f-4d6f-869a-5572c3487b31_1070x1200.jpeg)\n\nUna rappresentazione della convessità, se posso definirla così”, opera di Thomas Wright (1750). Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / Internet Archive / The Getty\n\nIl suo sistema prevede cinque entità: (1) gli oggetti macroscopici , (2) le cose semplici , (3) le porzioni , (4) i semi , (5) la Mente . Inoltre, ci sono sei principi che governano il mondo: (i) non esiste la distruzione e la creazione, (ii) esistono molte, in numero infinito, cose semplici , (iii) c’è una porzione di ogni cosa in ogni cosa , (iv) ogni cosa è principalmente composta dalla porzione maggiormente presente in quella cosa, (v) non esiste una porzione infinitesima, (vi) il NOUS non è mischiato e (I) conosce tutto, (II) governa tutto, (III) definisce tutto in ordine, (IV) causandone il moto.\n\nIn principio tutte le cose erano mischiate; la Mente causa poi la rotazione di tutto, creando prima in un luogo limitato, e poi ovunque, la separazione di oggetti identificabili dalla miscela iniziale. La rotazione porta gli elementi a separarsi: si separano prima l’aer e l’aether, l’aria e l’etere, presenti in più grandi porzioni. L’aria tende verso il centro, mentre l’etere, più leggero, verso la periferia del vortice.\n\nLe cose più pesanti vanno verso il centro, ad eccezione dei corpi celesti, che nonostante siano rocce infuocate, restano in aria grazie alla velocità di rotazione del vortice, che aumenta sempre di più.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #10\n\nLa descrizione dei corpi celesti come rocce infuocate potrebbe essere stata suggerita ad Anassagora, o averne trovato conferma, nella caduta di un meteorite ad Aegospotami nel 467 BCE.\n\nPer Anassagora esiste un numero infinito di porzioni, quindi non sono assimilabili ai nostri elementi chimici, e queste porzioni, dette anche radici , sono compresse dalla rotazione dovuta al vortice e formano i corpi solidi che troviamo sulla Terra.\n\nLa Terra è piatta, e rimane ferma perché è molto grande, perché l’aria la supporta, e perché non esiste il vuoto. Il Sole, la Luna e i pianeti sono rocce infuocate che orbitano nel cielo intorno alla Terra, e quando non le vediamo orbitano sotto di essa. La Luna è formata degli stessi materiali di cui è fatta la Terra, e la sua luce è un riflesso della luce solare; le eclissi lunari sono causate sia dalla posizione della Terra rispetto ad essa che da corpi minori che la oscurano nei loro passaggi.\n\nNon è chiaro se per Anassagora i mondi contemporanei di cui parla siano dei mondi diversi dalla Terra, o luoghi della nostra Terra ma a noi inaccessibili: ad ogni modo, parla della Via Lattea come di un insieme di stelle, visibili più delle altre stelle del cielo perché avvolte dall’ombra della Terra quando il Sole vi passa sotto. Non è da stupirsi che la Terra abbia dei movimenti: già Anassagora, che anche aveva definito la Terra ferma, suppone che i terremoti avvengano quando l’aria su cui essa poggia si muove a causa della pioggia che si infiltra dentro la Terra, causandone un leggero movimento.\n\nMelisso\n\nOriginario di Samo, nato probabilmente intorno al 500 BCE, nel suo trattato \"Sulla Natura\" parla, come Parmenide, dell’Essere come non creato, indistruttibile, indivisibile, immodificabile, senza moto, e sempre uguale a sé stesso. A differenza di Parmenide, però, definisce il mondo infinito, oltre che nel tempo, anche nello spazio.\n\nGli atomisti\n\nLeucippo e Democrito\n\nPer Leucippo, filosofo di cui non sappiamo quasi nulla se non che intorno al 450 BCE crea una scuola insieme al discepolo Democrito, il vuoto esiste, e la materia è formata da un numero infinito di piccoli corpi, che non sono divisibili (atomi). Tra questi, gli atomi più umidi con il fuoco diventano stelle. Il cambiamento quindi è dovuto all’accumularsi in un luogo di particelle che già esistono dall’inizio. Gli atomi inoltre sono infiniti non solo in numero ma anche in forma e dimensione.\n\nLe teorie di Leucippo sono spesso proposte insieme a quelle di Democrito, poiché è difficile discernere i singoli contributi. Democrito nasce, secondo Apollodoro, intorno al 458 BCE, ed è come abbiamo detto un discepolo di Leucippo, entrambi attivi ad Abdera. Il testo dell’atomismo che scrive (o scrivono) è “Il Piccolo Sistema del Mondo”, e tutto lì si riconduce alla forma e alle dimensioni degli atomi.\n\nLa cosmologia che si riesce a ricostruire per entrambi è la seguente: esistono due cose, gli atomi e il vuoto, e i primi si muovono all’interno del secondo. Inoltre, esiste una distinzione tra l’Universo, che è la totalità di ciò che esiste, e il Cosmo, che è invece il sistema del mondo limitato nel tempo e nello spazio. Esistono infiniti mondi, e ognuno nasce quando molti corpi di forma diversa si muovono verso il vuoto, creando un vortice che fa separare le cose \"secondo necessità\": i corpi più pesanti si muovono verso il centro, e la Terra è al centro. Il Sole e la Luna ruotano intorno alla Terra. L’ordine dei corpi celesti per Leucippo è Sole, pianeti, stelle, Luna, e Terra al centro, mentre per Democrito l’ordine è leggermente diverso: stelle, pianeti, Sole, Luna, Venere e la Terra. Le eclissi avvengono quando la Terra modifica la propria inclinazione rispetto alo zenit.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/c75614fd-2da8-46f3-9087-e7e81b809ea4_601x800.jpeg)\n\nColour wheel, featured in his treatise on colour Versuch eines Farbensystems , opera di Ignaz Schiffermüller (1772). Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / Internet Archive / The Getty\n\nIn conclusione, Leucippo crea una teoria fisica in risposta a Parmenide, introducendo l’idea degli atomi, indivisibili, e Democrito modifica la teoria di Leucippo per descrivere fenomeni diversi.\n\nIl cosmo degli atomisti non ha nulla di speciale, di divino, o di inevitabile.\n\nDiogene di Apollonia\n\nNato nella colonia milesiana di Apollonia nel V secolo BCE, viene considerato da Teofrasto \"l’ultimo filosofo naturale\", quindi in piena tradizione dei filosofi di Mileto. Diogene Laerzio lo annovera tra i discepoli di Anassimene, e pone il suo acme tra il 440 e il 430 BCE.\n\nConsidera l’aria divina e la identifica con l’origine del mondo, e nella sua cosmologia la Terra è piatta e ferma al centro del mondo, sostenuta da un vortice creato dal calore generato dalle esalazioni del mondo. Risolve la incoerenza tra l’affermazione che l’interazione tra corpi non esiste, e l’evidenza che questa interazione avviene, affermando che tutte le cose derivano da una singola sostanza, che quindi può interagire con una sua parte.\n\nNella sua cosmologia è la prima volta che incontriamo l’\"argomento del disegno\": se tutte le cose sono organizzate nel modo migliore possibile, all’origine di siffatta organizzazione deve esserci un \"organizzatore\" intelligente.\n\nI corpi celesti sono pietre pomici, leggere e infuocate alcune, leggere e invisibili le altre, che a volte cadono sulla Terra (anche per Diogene questa descrizione potrebbe riguardare il meteorite caduto ad Aegospotami di cui abbiamo detto prima).\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/4a693a3c-a157-4f4d-9d80-da6f099ac5b7_1240x1146.png)\n\nAbbiamo parlato finora di scuole a Mileto, a Elea; siamo arrivati fino ad Atene con i primi filosofi a portare la cosmologia nella polis; abbiamo trattato i filosofi di cui non si sa nulla, e quelli per cui le informazioni che abbiamo sono discordanti.\n\nArthur Koestler parla della filosofia in Grecia fino a questo momento come di un ensemble musicale in cui ognuno prova ad accordare il suo strumento. Nel prossimo episodio parleremo di colui il quale è riuscito ad accordare l’orchestra .\n\nNel prossimo episodio: accordare l’orchestra\n\nArticoli della serie:\n\nBibliografia:\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe, di Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, raccolta di saggi ad opera di C. Blacker e M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nGreek Cosmologies, di G.E.R. Lloyd\n\nAristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus, di T. Heath(Oxford 1913)\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, di Kirk G.S. e Raven J.E. (Cambridge 1957)\n\nEarly Greek Philosophy and the Orient, di M.L. West (Oxford 1971)\n\nPhilosophy before Socrates, di R.D. McKirahan (Hackett 1994)\n\nEarly Greek Science, di G.E.R. Lloyd (Chatto & Windus 1970)\n\nA history of astronomy from Thales to Kepler, di J.L.E Dreyer (Dover 1953)\n\nHeaven And Earth In Ancient Greek Cosmology, di D.L. Cuprie (Springer 2011)\n\nEarly Greek Cosmology: A Historiographical Review, di N.S. Hetherington\n\nBack to the Pre-Socratics: The Presidential Address, di K.R. Popper (1958)\n\nEarly Greek astronomy to Aristotle, di D.R. Dicks (Cornell University Press 1970)\n\nHistory of Philosophy Volume I: From the Beginning to Plato, raccolta di C.C.W. Taylor (Routledge 1997)\n\nThe Ionians, di Malcolm Schofield\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, di Jonathan Barnes (Routledge 1979)\n\nA Source Book In Greek Science di M.R. Cohen e I.E. Drabkin (Harvard University Press 1945)\n\nThe Physical World of the Greeks, di S. Sambursky (The Macmillan Company 1956)\n\nQuesta newsletter è una di tre: le altre due sono Last Scattering Surface, e Space of Sound. Tutte le pubblicazioni sono gratuite e puoi consultare tutti gli articoli senza paywall. Se vuoi, puoi iscriverti qui e qui.\n\nInfine, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n\nCiao e a presto!\n\nNote\n\n1 Platone, Parmenide .\n\n2 Diogene Laerzio, Vite dei filosofi .\n\n3 Diogene Laerzio, Vite dei filosofi .\n\n4 Diogene Laerzio, Vite dei filosofi .\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_011-the-problem-of-change.md": "Disclaimer #1: questo articolo è in inglese, la versione in italiano si può leggere qui.\n\nDisclaimer #2: this episode is part of a series named “ on the motion of the Earth ”, published both on this publication, Heralding Time , and on Last Scattering Surface . If you want, you can follow them both. Here chapters I, II, III, IV, V, VI.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/274965b4-2a62-4b0f-95f3-9b0b102da8b8_1080x1350.png)\n\nWelcome back.\n\nIn previous episodes we talked about Miletus and Thales, the first philosopher according to the tradition of philosophy in Greece, and about Anaximander and Anaximenes, the other two philosophers of Miletus. Earlier we described the cosmologies of various ancient peoples, from the Egyptians to the Babylonians, from the Chinese to the peoples of Scandinavia, up to Greek mythology.\n\nThis November, subscribe for free to this newsletter!\n\n--------------\n\nQuesto novembre, iscriviti gratuitamente a questa newsletter!\n\nE se vuoi diventare un abbonato a pagamento per supportarmi, considera questa offerta!\n\nGet 40% off for 1 year\n\nThanks!\n\n--------------\n\nGrazie!\n\nIn this episode we will talk about what happens when one tries to answer the question: can we trust our senses?\n\nXenophanes of Colophon\n\nXenophanes is considered the founder of the school of Elea, a polis in southern Italy where he lived and taught. Diogenes Laertius reports 570 BCE as his date of birth, and places the philosopher’s death at 95 years old, in 475 BCE. Originally from Colophon, a city in Ionia, he lives in Zancle (which today is Messina) and in Catania, and then precisely in Elea.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/02e085da-eaf8-419a-b44c-178e7a85a3f4_1240x1228.png)\n\nAlthough he is not a philosopher from Miletus, his place of origin (Colophon is a few dozen kilometers from Miletus) and his philosophy place him in direct contact with the philosophies of the three philosophers we talked about in the two previous episodes.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/104ff0ab-b36a-490e-ba7e-39ea7133e18b_900x1300.jpeg)\n\nXenophanes, figure by Thomas Stanley (1655). The history of philosophy: containing the lives, opinions, actions and Discourses of the Philosophers of every Sect, illustrated with effigies of divers of them. Credits here.\n\nFrom the few fragments (40 fragments for a total of about 100 verses) of a poetic work of his, and from other secondhand and thirdhand citations, we know that his idea of the world is in contrast with the vision of Homer and Hesiod based on the anthropomorphism of the gods: for Xenophanes “God is one,” there is no longer room for divine intervention in the world in human affairs or in the creation of natural elements and phenomena. For Xenophanes “God” is immortal, eternal, does not have human appearance, but is not immaterial for this reason. He therefore poses the question: “Is He the world, or only a substance in it?” To answer, he looks at the world and sees that it is full of movements: since God cannot move, then He must not be part of the world, but only permeate it - but he does not explain how.\n\nXenophanes does not create a cosmogony, but according to Aristotele1, he believes in the eternity of the world.\n\nHe too, like the philosophers of Miletus, searches for an original substance, and according to him there are two primordial substances: earth, dry, and water, moist.\n\nA trait that emerges from his writings and from the testimonies of the doxographers is his frequent use of examples: for example, to justify his idea that the world is born from water and earth, and will dissolve into these two \"elements\", he cites as an example marine fossils found on mountains. In addition, from mud the earth will reform, and the cycle will begin again.\n\nRegarding his strictly astronomical ideas, he emancipates himself from the Milesian tradition and sees no evidence of the necessity for the Earth to have to rest on something: his Earth is infinite in extension and depth. This generates a consequence for which commentators attribute to him the solution as follows: since such an Earth would be too large for the Sun and Moon to illuminate it all, there exist innumerable celestial bodies called Sun and Moon in different parts of the world, at different latitudes2.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5101a4d4-7384-43f1-ac7a-4d413e0479fa_864x1200.jpeg)\n\nAtlas sustains the Firmament, work by Bernard Picart (1731). Image obtained from Public Domain Image Archive / Rijksmuseum.\n\nAgain, he sees no evidence of why there should be a solid celestial vault: in his Universe the air extends indefinitely upward.\n\nHippolytus reports that for Xenophanes the Sun is \"new every day\", and the Moon every month, and both are formed from small tongues of fire united together, like bright clouds; they form from small exhalations due to the humidity of the air, and therefore come from the Earth. The Sun moreover moves in a straight line, but from Earth it seems to move in a circle around it.\n\nWhat emerges from Xenophanes, and from the other philosophers of Miletus, is the trust, indeed the certainty, that a rational order exists in the world, and that humanity is able to gain knowledge from it. From Hesiod, whom Xenophanes does not love but whom the others do not despise, they nevertheless obtain confirmation that it is necessary to try to understand the world. The fundamental idea is that applying reason to cosmology can be enough, and that nothing else is needed - tradition, religion, dogma - to explain the world. McKirahan writes that for Xenophanes \"Hesiod is not suitable\"3.\n\nThe four philosophers seek and find objections to each other’s theories, and produce new theories that are immune from those criticisms (even if others could be raised). They certainly make some \"bold generalisations\" that today would not be acceptable, but without the possibility of verifying hypotheses with experiments, or with more accurate observations, it was probably difficult to do better.\n\nAs we also said in the previous episode, they do not use deductive proof\" to advance their reasoning: it is necessary, to accept a theory, that its reasoning be plausible.\n\nOn the other hand, when one trusts one’s means of observation, all that is needed is for the reasoning to be coherent and plausible.\n\nBut what if our eyes were not reliable?\n\nHeraclitus\n\nThe world of the philosophers of Miletus was made of water, or air; the Earth was guarded by these elements, like an embryo in a placenta.\n\nPopper writes that with Heraclitus, \"the house catches fire\"4 . There is no longer room for stability, things are no longer things, they become processes , and the \"apparent stability of the world is due to the laws and processes to which the world is subject\".\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/de078371-9d99-450e-89dc-9f621241e9b3_500x617.jpeg)\n\nHeraclitus, by Hendrick ter Brugghen (1628). Image obtained from Rijksmuseum Amsterdam. Credits here.\n\nOf Heraclitus we know his place of origin, Ephesus, where he remained for his entire life, and some imprecise information about the dates of birth and death: it seems he was born around 535 BCE, and died around 475 BCE. Diogenes Laertius speaks of his acme around the LXIX Olympiad.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/04c33b1d-f63c-4d47-9eeb-0ebb6d74d81c_1240x1178.png)\n\nAt the basis of his philosophy is the concept of Logos, the word, the meaning of the world. In it everything is contained, everything contains. The unity of the world is not a rhetorical artifice: all things are in reality only one same thing, and we see different manifestations of it thanks to the change of everything into its opposite. This thought expresses the idea that the world has simultaneously plurality and unity.\n\nAn example is day and night: there is no precise moment in which there is day and not night, and then the opposite occurs; what happens is that day slowly changes into night, thus gradually becoming its opposite. And so, all things are actually equal, but appear to us different from one another. While affirming this, Heraclitus shares a thought, among the approximately 100 fragments found of his works, that \"those who do not expect the unexpected will not find it, since for them it will remain hidden and incomprehensible\".\n\nIf the philosophers of Miletus assumed they could trust their own senses, Heraclitus doubts it: one must use one’s senses with attention , since everything is in change.\n\nIs it then useless to try to know the world and its movements? Heraclitus does not say this, on the contrary he constructs his own cosmology, which has stability precisely because it is in constant change : he identifies in the original material principle fire, from which the world is born, and by which the world will be consumed when the world itself ends. With change, which also occurs in the firmament, fire transforms into water, and then into earth; from this air is formed, and again fire. This cycle is the reason for the exchange of matter between sky and Earth, and is the reason for the apparent movements of the celestial bodies, which in reality do not move.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/76ad2549-0741-483c-aa1a-ddd0c0aeab3d_1152x1200.jpeg)\n\nThe real Magnitude of the Globe of the Earth, by Thomas Wright (1750). Image obtained from ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / Internet Archive / The Getty\n\nWhy precisely fire? Among all the elements that are normally identified with the original principle (water, air, fire), it is precisely fire that comes closest to the concept of process .\n\nFire also generates the light that illuminates the Sun and Moon, which are fiery bowls, like the stars: the Sun and Moon are close to us, the Moon more than the Sun because it is less pure than the latter; the stars instead are very far away, and this is the reason why we do not receive their heat. The reciprocal positions of the Moon and Sun create the phenomena of eclipses.\n\nHeraclitus enjoys posthumous fame immediately after his death, in the tradition of Plato, Aristotle and the sophists: Plato indicates Heraclitus as the author of πάντα ῥεῖ ( pánta rheî ), everything flows5; Aristotle considers him a monist of the Milesian school; finally the sophists, uniting the concepts of Logos, fire and God, consider him the initiator of their philosophy.\n\nRemember the analogy with the tortuous and rough path that brought us from myth to philosophy? We leave with Heraclitus a mysterious figure, ready to continue the journey.\n\nWe will immediately see how his point of view on the pervasiveness of change in the world will be overturned by another figure, who awaits us in the shadows at a crossroads between two Ways.\n\nParmenides\n\nAccording to Plato6, Parmenides was born around 513 BCE, while Apollodorus places his birth thirty years earlier. It seems certain however that he died in 450 BCE. Born in the Greek colony of Elea from an aristocratic family, it seems he wrote the laws of his city; again Plato tells us that he was a disciple of Xenophanes, and that he had connections with Pythagorean circles.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/91efc357-d54e-4420-9843-1dba3ef3cd1d_1240x1142.png)\n\nHe wrote a work, titled On Nature, which we have almost completely thanks to Simplicius who copied it in the 6th CE from Aristotle’s Physics .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1dfcc9fc-21c3-4c0c-8171-2279511a291a_476x1137.jpeg)\n\nParmenides, detail from “The School of Athens,” fresco by Raphael Sanzio(1511). Crediti here.\n\nThe poem is divided into a prologue and then into two sections, one titled “the way of Truth ,” and the other “the way of mortal men .” The Truth of the first way is not revealed by a goddess or muse, but is reached through deductions and logical statements that make logic itself divine , insofar as it is independent of men.\n\nMcKirahan speaking of Parmenides states that he \"introduced deductive arguments into philosophy\", and in fact his work leads one to continually ask questions like what conditions must existing things satisfy? Do our senses truly perceive reality as it is?\", and his attacks on the senses and their not being suitable for searching for reality mark a fundamental watershed in the history of thought between experience and reasoning.\n\nFor Parmenides the world of change is an illusion, because change entails that something changes into something else that did not exist before: but this cannot happen, because what is not cannot exist . Reality exists only thanks to Being, which is uninterrupted (the void does not exist) and unchangeable (change does not exist).\n\nMoreover, the division of his work into two ways is also the division of the world into what is objective, and what is instead subjective.\n\nSince the only statement we can express is that a thing exists\", but we cannot say that the same thing \"does not exist\", then the past and future, which respectively no longer exist or do not yet exist, are in reality an illusion.\n\nIf therefore even the void does not exist, the world is full .\n\nThe universe moreover is finite, since it cannot have a dimension that cannot be defined, and cannot be incomplete; it is spherical, that is equal in all its parts, and because it cannot be interrupted in any direction.\n\nBright note in the margin #8\n\nThe division of the world into subjectivity and objectivity, and the personal sensation of time and space return, more than two thousand years later, in Richard Jeffries, in The Story of my Heart:\n\n“Now is eternity. I am in the midst of it... Nothing has yet to happen: it is now. Now is eternity, now is immortal life.”\n\nDespite Parmenides’ cosmology being obscure, and being described in the part of the poem dedicated to the way of Mortal Men, we can try to reconstruct it: the Earth is equidistant from every other body, and does not move; it formed from the condensation of air, while the stars form with the compression of fire, as happens for the Sun and the Milky Way; the Moon instead is formed by both air and fire7.\n\nThe stars are circles of fire that shine in some points rather than others; the Moon receives light from the Sun, and the Milky Way contains both hotter and more rarefied elements, and colder and denser elements8.\n\nOutside the Universe there is Olympus, then Venus (which according to Diogenes Laertius was precisely Parmenides who first identified it with the Morning Star and Evening Star), then the Sun and finally the Moon. At the center of the Earth there is a daimon (perhaps Aphrodite, perhaps Ananke - Necessity) who generates everything and who created Eros, the first among the gods.\n\nParmenides sowed doubt about the possibility of knowledge: for this reason he is considered the founder of ontology in Greece, and every philosopher after him had to answer questions like (i) the Existent cannot come from the Non-Existent, since what Is cannot be, at a certain point, Not to Have Been; (ii) the Void cannot exist, because it represents what Does Not Exist; (iii) Plurality must come from Unity; (iv) motion cannot be considered a natural quality of things, it must be explained.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6c43bdb4-8428-48c0-90a8-ee288c19fcc1_800x954.jpeg)\n\nIllustration from a 1587 treatise on comets and meteors, created anonymously in Flanders (now northern France) and known as the Kometenbuch (1587). Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / ORKA - Open Repository Kassel.\n\nWe will immediately see that there are those who will defend Parmenides’ thesis, and those who will oppose it: but his contribution to the debate is so important that both his supporters and his detractors are defined as post-Parmenideans.\n\nIn the next episode: the responses to Parmenides\n\nRead the other episodes:\n\nBibliography:\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe, by Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, edited by C. Blacker and M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nGreek Cosmologies, by G.E.R. Lloyd\n\nAristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus, by Heath T. (Oxford 1913)\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, di Kirk G.S. and Raven J.E. (Cambridge 1957)\n\nEarly Greek Philosophy and the Orient, by West M.L. (Oxford 1971)\n\nPhilosophy before Socrates, by McKirahan R.D. (Hackett 1994)\n\nEarly Greek Science, by G.E.R. Lloyd (Chatto & Windus 1970)\n\nA history of astronomy from Thales to Kepler, by J.L.E Dreyer (Dover 1953)\n\nHeaven And Earth In Ancient Greek Cosmology, by D.L. Cuprie (Springer 2011)\n\nEarly Greek Cosmology: A Historiographical Review, by N.S. Hetherington\n\nBack to the Pre-Socratics: The Presidential Address, by K.R. Popper (1958)\n\nEarly Greek astronomy to Aristotle, by D.R. Dicks (Cornell University Press 1970)\n\nHistory of Philosophy Volume I: From the Beginning to Plato, edited by C.C.W. Taylor (Routledge 1997)\n\nThe Ionians, by Malcolm Schofield\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, by Jonathan Barnes (Routledge 1979)\n\nA Source Book In Greek Science by M.R. Cohen e I.E. Drabkin (Harvard University Press 1945)\n\nThe Physical World of the Greeks, by S. Sambursky (The Macmillan Company 1956)\n\nNotes\n\n1 Aristotle, Metaphysics .\n\n2 Hippolytus, Refutationes .\n\n3 McKirahan, Philosophy before Socrates .\n\n4 Popper, Back to the Pre-Socratics: a presidential address .\n\n5 Plato, Theaetetus e Cratylus .\n\n6 Plato, Parmenides .\n\n7 Diogenes Laertius, Lives of Philosophers .\n\n8 Diogenes Laertius, Lives of Philosophers .\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_012-il-problema-del-cambiamento.md": "Disclaimer #1: this article is in Italian. I will publish the English version next Sunday.\n\nDisclaimer #2: questo pezzo fa parte di una serie, pubblicata sia su questa newsletter, Heralding Time , che su Last Scattering Surface . Se vuoi, puoi seguirle entrambe. Qui i capitoli I, II, III, IV, V, VI.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b45264b5-90bd-4205-b643-3630565fde93_1080x1350.png)\n\nBentornati.\n\nNei precedenti episodi abbiamo parlato di Mileto e di Talete, il primo filosofo secondo la tradizione della filosofia in Grecia, e di Anassimandro e Anassimene, gli altri due filosofi di Mileto. Ancora prima abbiamo descritto le cosmologie di vari popoli antichi, dagli Egiziani ai Babilonesi, dai Cinesi ai popoli della Scandinavia, fino alla mitologia greca.\n\nIn questo episodio parleremo di quello che succede quando si prova a rispondere alla domanda: possiamo fidarci dei nostri sensi?\n\nThis November, subscribe for free to this newsletter!\n\n--------------\n\nQuesto novembre, iscriviti gratuitamente a questa newsletter!\n\nE se vuoi diventare un abbonato a pagamento per supportarmi, considera questa offerta!\n\nGet 40% off for 1 year\n\nThanks!\n\n--------------\n\nGrazie!\n\nSenofane di Colofone\n\nSenofane è considerato il fondatore della scuola di Elea, polis nell’Italia meridionale in cui visse e insegnò. Diogene Laerzio riporta come data di nascita il 570 BCE, e pone la morte del filosofo a 95 anni, nel 475 BCE. Originario di Colofone, una città nella Ionia, vive a Zancle (che oggi è Messina) e a Catania, e poi appunto a Elea.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/02e085da-eaf8-419a-b44c-178e7a85a3f4_1240x1228.png)\n\nNonostante non sia un filosofo di Mileto, il luogo di origine (Colofone dista qualche decina di chilometri da Mileto) e la sua filosofia lo pongono in diretto contatto con le filosofie dei tre filosofi di cui abbiamo parlato nei due precedenti episodi.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/104ff0ab-b36a-490e-ba7e-39ea7133e18b_900x1300.jpeg)\n\nXenophanes, figura di Thomas Stanley (1655). The history of philosophy: containing the lives, opinions, actions and Discourses of the Philosophers of every Sect, illustrated with effigies of divers of them . Credits qui.\n\nDai pochi frammenti (40 frammenti per un totale di circa 100 versi) di una sua opera poetica, e da altre citazioni di seconda e terza mano, sappiamo che la sua idea del mondo è in contrasto con la visione di Omero e di Esiodo basata sulla antropomorfizzazione degli dei: per Senofane \"Dio è uno\", non c’è più spazio per l’intervento divino nel mondo negli affari umani o nella creazione di elementi e fenomeni naturali. Per Senofane \"Dio\" è immortale, eterno, non ha sembianze umane, ma non per questo è immateriale . Si pone quindi la domanda: \"Egli è il mondo, o solo una sostanza in esso?\" Per rispondere, guarda il mondo e vede che è pieno di movimenti: poiché Dio non può muoversi, allora non deve essere parte del mondo, ma solo permearlo - ma non spiega come.\n\nSenofane non crea una cosmogonia, ma secondo Aristotele1, crede nell’eternità del mondo.\n\nAnch’egli, come i filosofi di Mileto, ricerca una sostanza originaria, e secondo lui ci sono due sostanze primigenie: la terra, asciutta, e l’acqua, umida.\n\nUn tratto che emerge dai suoi scritti e dalle testimonianze dei dossografi è il suo uso frequente di esempi: ad esempio, per giustificare la sua idea che il mondo nasce dall’acqua e dalla terra, e in questi due \"elementi\" si dissolverà, cita come esempio i fossili marini ritrovati sulle montagne. In aggiunta, dal fango si riformerà la terra, e il ciclo ricomincerà.\n\nRiguardo le sue idee strettamente astronomiche, si emancipa dalla tradizione di Mileto e non vede nessuna evidenza della necessità della Terra di dover poggiare su qualcosa: la sua Terra è infinita in estensione e in profondità. Questo genera una conseguenza di cui i commentatori gli attribuiscono la soluzione come segue: poiché una Terra del genere sarebbe troppo grande perché Sole e Luna possano illuminarla tutta, esistono innumerevoli corpi celesti detti Sole e Luna in diverse parti del mondo, a diverse latitudini2.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5101a4d4-7384-43f1-ac7a-4d413e0479fa_864x1200.jpeg)\n\nAtlante sostiene il Firmamento, opera di Bernard Picart (1731). Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / Rijksmuseum.\n\nAncora, non vede nessuna evidenza del perché ci debba essere una volta celeste solida: nel suo Universo l’aria si estende in modo indefinito verso l’alto.\n\nIppolito riporta che per Senofane il Sole è \"nuovo ogni giorno\", e la Luna ogni mese, ed entrambi sono formati da piccoli lingue di fuoco unite insieme, come nuvole brillanti; si formano da piccole esalazioni dovute all’umidità dell’aria, e quindi provengono dalla Terra. Il Sole inoltre si muove in linea retta, ma dalla Terra sembra che si muova in cerchio intorno ad essa.\n\nQuello che emerge da Senofane, e dagli altri filosofi di Mileto, è la fiducia, anzi la certezza, che esista un ordine razionale nel mondo, e che all’umanità sia possibile trarne conoscenza. Da Esiodo, che Senofane non ama ma che gli altri non disprezzano, comunque ottengono la conferma che sia necessario cercare di capire il mondo. L’idea fondamentale è che applicare la ragione alla cosmologia possa bastare, e che non ci sia bisogno di null’altro - tradizione, religione, dogma - per spiegare il mondo. McKirahan scrive che per Senofane “Esiodo non è adatto”3.\n\nI quattro filosofi cercano e trovano obiezioni alle teorie degli altri, e producono nuove teorie che sono immuni da quelle critiche (anche se altre se ne potrebbero sollevare). Effettuano certamente delle \"coraggiose generalizzazioni\" che oggi non sarebbero accettabili, ma senza la possibilità di verificare le ipotesi con degli esperimenti, o con delle più accurate osservazioni, probabilmente era difficile fare di meglio.\n\nCome abbiamo detto anche nell’episodio precedente, non utilizzano la \"prova deduttiva\" per avanzare il loro ragionamento: è necessario, per accettare una teoria, che il suo ragionamento sia plausibile.\n\nD’altronde, quando ci si fida dei propri mezzi di osservazione, serve solo che il ragionamento sia coerente e plausibile.\n\nMa se i nostri occhi non fossero affidabili?\n\nEraclito\n\nIl mondo dei filosofi di Mileto era fatto d’acqua, o d’aria; la Terra era custodita da questi elementi, come un embrione in una placenta.\n\nPopper scrive che con Eraclito, \"la casa prende fuoco\"4. Non c’è più spazio per la stabilità, le cose non sono più cose , diventano processi , e la \"apparente stabilità del mondo è dovuta alle leggi e ai processi a cui il mondo è soggetto\".\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/de078371-9d99-450e-89dc-9f621241e9b3_500x617.jpeg)\n\nEraclito, di Hendrick ter Brugghen (1628). Immagine ottenuta da Rijksmuseum Amsterdam. Credits qui.\n\nDi Eraclito conosciamo il luogo d’origine, Efeso, in cui ha dimorato per tutta la vita, e qualche informazione poco precisa sulle date di nascita e morte: pare sia nato intorno al 535 BCE, e morto intorno al 475 BCE. Diogene Laerzio parla del suo acme intorno alla LXIX Olimpiade.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/04c33b1d-f63c-4d47-9eeb-0ebb6d74d81c_1240x1178.png)\n\nAlla base della sua filosofia c’è il concetto di Logos, la parola, il senso del mondo. In esso è contenuto tutto, tutto contiene. L’unità del mondo non è un artificio retorico: tutte le cose sono in realtà solo una stessa cosa, e noi ne vediamo diverse manifestazioni grazie al cambiamento di ogni cosa nel suo opposto. Questo pensiero esprime l’idea che il mondo ha contemporaneamente pluralità e unità.\n\nUn esempio è il giorno e la notte: non c’è un momento preciso in cui c’è il giorno e non la notte, e poi avviene il contrario; quello che avviene è che il giorno cambia lentamente nella notte, diventando così gradualmente il suo opposto. E così, tutte le cose in realtà sono uguali, ma appaiono a noi diverse le une dalle altre. Mentre afferma questo, Eraclito condivide un pensiero, tra i circa 100 frammenti ritrovati delle sue opere, che “coloro che non si aspettano l’inaspettato non lo troveranno, poiché per loro rimarrà nascosto e incomprensibile”.\n\nSe i filosofi di Mileto assumevano di potersi fidare dei propri sensi, Eraclito ne dubita: bisogna utilizzare i propri sensi con attenzione , poiché tutto è in mutamento.\n\nE’ allora inutile cercare di conoscere il mondo e i suoi movimenti? Eraclito non dice questo, anzi costruisce una sua cosmologia, che ha una stabilità proprio perché è in costante cambiamento : individua nel principio materiale originale il fuoco, da cui nasce il mondo, e da cui il mondo verrà consumato quando il mondo stesso finirà. Con il cambiamento, che avviene anche nel firmamento, il fuoco si trasforma in acqua, e poi in terra; da questa si forma l’aria, e di nuovo il fuoco. Questo ciclo è il motivo dello scambio di materia tra il cielo e la Terra, ed è il motivo per i movimenti apparenti degli astri, che in realtà non si muovono.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/76ad2549-0741-483c-aa1a-ddd0c0aeab3d_1152x1200.jpeg)\n\nLa vera grandezza del globo della Terra, opera di Thomas Wright (1750). Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / Internet Archive / The Getty\n\nPerché proprio il fuoco? Tra tutti gli elementi che normalmente si identificano con il principio originario (acqua, aria, fuoco), è proprio il fuoco quello che si avvicina di più al concetto di processo .\n\nIl fuoco genera anche la luce che illumina il Sole e la Luna, che sono ciotole infuocate, come le stelle: il Sole e la Luna sono vicine a noi, la Luna più del Sole poiché è meno pura di quest’ultimo; le stelle sono invece molto lontane, ed è questo il motivo per cui non riceviamo il loro calore. Le posizioni reciproche della Luna e del Sole creano i fenomeni delle eclissi.\n\nRefer a friend\n\nEraclito gode di una fama postuma subito successiva alla sua morte, nella tradizione di Platone, Aristotele e i sofisti: Platone indica Eraclito come l’autore di πάντα ῥεῖ (pánta rheî), tutto scorre 5; Aristotele lo considera un monista6 della scuola di Mileto; infine i sofisti, unendo i concetti di Logos, di fuoco e di Dio, lo considerano l’iniziatore della loro filosofia.\n\nRicordate l’analogia con il percorso tortuoso e accidentato che ci ha portati dal mito alla filosofia? Abbandoniamo con Eraclito una figura misteriosa, pronti a continuare il viaggio.\n\nVedremo subito come il suo punto di vista sulla pervasività del cambiamento nel mondo verrà rovesciato da un’altra figura, che ci aspetta nell’ombra ad un bivio tra due Vie.\n\nParmenide\n\nSecondo Platone7, Parmenide è nato intorno al 513 BCE, mentre Apollodoro pone la sua nascita trent’anni prima. Sembra accertato però che sia morto nel 450 BCE. Nato nella colonia greca di Elea da famiglia aristocratica, pare che abbia scritto le leggi della sua città; Sempre Platone ci dice che sia stato un discepolo di Senofane, e che abbia avuto connessioni con ambienti pitagorici.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/91efc357-d54e-4420-9843-1dba3ef3cd1d_1240x1142.png)\n\nHa scritto un’opera, intitolata Sulla Natura , che abbiamo quasi completamente grazie a Simplicio che lo copiò nel VI CE dalla Fisica di Aristotele.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1dfcc9fc-21c3-4c0c-8171-2279511a291a_476x1137.jpeg)\n\nParmenide, particolare de “La scuola di Atene“ , affresco di Raffaello Sanzio (1511). Crediti qui.\n\nIl poema è diviso in un prologo e poi in due sezioni, una intitolata “la via della Verità ”, e l’altra “la via degli uomini mortali ”. La Verità della prima via non è rivelata dalla dea o da una musa, ma viene raggiunta attraverso deduzioni e enunciati logici che rendono la logica stessa divina , in quanto indipendente dagli uomini.\n\nMcKirahan parlando di Parmenide afferma che \"ha introdotto le argomentazioni deduttive nella filosofia\", e infatti la sua opera porta a chiedersi continuamente domande del tipo \"quali condizioni devono soddisfare le cose esistenti? I nostri sensi percepiscono davvero la realtà per come essa è?\", e i suoi attacchi ai sensi e al loro non essere adatti a ricercare la realtà segnano uno spartiacque fondamentale nella storia del pensiero tra esperienza e ragionamento.\n\nPer Parmenide il mondo del cambiamento è un’illusione, perché il cambiamento comporta che qualcosa cambi in qualcos’altro che prima non esisteva: ma ciò non può accadere, perché non può esistere ciò che non è . La Realtà esiste solo grazie all’Essere, che è ininterrotto (il vuoto non esiste) e immodificabile (il cambiamento non esiste).\n\nInoltre, la divisione della sua opera in due vie è anche la divisione del mondo in quello che è oggettivo, e quello che è invece soggettivo.\n\nGet 40% off a group subscription\n\nPoiché l’unica affermazione che possiamo esprimere è che \"una cosa esiste\", ma non possiamo dire che quella stessa cosa \"non esiste\", allora il passato e il futuro, che rispettivamente non esistono più o ancora non esistono, in realtà sono una illusione.\n\nSe quindi anche il vuoto non esiste, il mondo è pieno .\n\nL’universo inoltre è finito, poiché non può avere una dimensione che non si può definire, e non può essere incompleto; è sferico, ovvero uguale in tutte le sue parti, e perché non può essere interrotto in nessuna direzione.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #8\n\nLa divisione del mondo in soggettività e oggettività, e la sensazione personale del tempo e dello spazio ritornano, più di duemila anni dopo, da Richard Jeffries, in The Story of my heart\":\n\n\"Ora è l'eternità. Io mi ci trovo in mezzo... Nulla deve ancora accadere: è ora. Ora è l'eternità, ora è la vita immortale.\"\n\nNonostante la cosmologia di Parmenide sia oscura, e venga descritta nella parte del poema dedicato alla via degli Uomini Mortali, possiamo provare a ricostruirla: la Terra è equidistante da ogni altro corpo, e non si muove; si è formata dalla condensazione dell’aria, mentre le stelle si formano con la compressione del fuoco, così come avviene per il Sole e la Via Lattea; la Luna invece è formata sia da aria che da fuoco8.\n\nLe stelle sono cerchi di fuoco che brillano in alcuni punti piuttosto che in altri; la Luna riceve la luce dal Sole, e la Via Lattea contiene sia elementi più caldi e rarefatti, che elementi più freddi e densi9.\n\nAll’esterno dell’Universo c’è Olimpo, poi Venere (che secondo Diogene Laerzio fu proprio Parmenide a identificare per la prima volta con la Stella del Mattino e la Stella della Sera), poi il Sole e infine la Luna. Al centro della Terra c’è un daimon (forse Afrodite, forse Ananke - la Necessità) che genera tutto e che ha creato Eros, il primo tra gli dei.\n\nParmenide ha seminato il dubbio della possibilità della conoscenza: per questo è considerato il fondatore della ontologia in Grecia, e ogni filosofo dopo di lui ha dovuto rispondere a quesiti del tipo (i) l’Esistente non può arrivare dal Non Esistente, poiché ciò che E’ non può essere, a un certo punto, Non Essere Stato; (ii) il Vuoto non può esistere, perché rappresenta ciò che Non Esiste; (iii) la Pluralità deve arrivare dall’Unità; (iv) il moto non si può considerare una qualità naturale delle cose, deve essere spiegato.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6c43bdb4-8428-48c0-90a8-ee288c19fcc1_800x954.jpeg)\n\nIllustration from a 1587 treatise on comets and meteors, created anonymously in Flanders (now northern France) and known as the Kometenbuch (1587). Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / ORKA - Open Repository Kassel.\n\nNel prossimo episodio vedremo che c’è chi difenderà la tesi di Parmenide, e chi la osteggerà: ma il suo contributo al dibattito è talmente importante che sia i suoi sostenitori che i suoi detrattori sono definiti post-Parmenidei.\n\nNel prossimo episodio: le risposte a Parmenide\n\nArticoli della serie:\n\nBibliografia:\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe, di Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, raccolta di saggi ad opera di C. Blacker e M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nGreek Cosmologies, di G.E.R. Lloyd\n\nAristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus, di T. Heath(Oxford 1913)\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, di Kirk G.S. e Raven J.E. (Cambridge 1957)\n\nEarly Greek Philosophy and the Orient, di M.L. West (Oxford 1971)\n\nPhilosophy before Socrates, di R.D. McKirahan (Hackett 1994)\n\nEarly Greek Science, di G.E.R. Lloyd (Chatto & Windus 1970)\n\nA history of astronomy from Thales to Kepler, di J.L.E Dreyer (Dover 1953)\n\nHeaven And Earth In Ancient Greek Cosmology, di D.L. Cuprie (Springer 2011)\n\nEarly Greek Cosmology: A Historiographical Review, di N.S. Hetherington\n\nBack to the Pre-Socratics: The Presidential Address, di K.R. Popper (1958)\n\nEarly Greek astronomy to Aristotle, di D.R. Dicks (Cornell University Press 1970)\n\nHistory of Philosophy Volume I: From the Beginning to Plato, raccolta di C.C.W. Taylor (Routledge 1997)\n\nThe Ionians, di Malcolm Schofield\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, di Jonathan Barnes (Routledge 1979)\n\nA Source Book In Greek Science di M.R. Cohen e I.E. Drabkin (Harvard University Press 1945)\n\nThe Physical World of the Greeks, di S. Sambursky (The Macmillan Company 1956)\n\nQuesta newsletter è una di tre: le altre due sono Last Scattering Surface, e Space of Sound. Tutte le pubblicazioni sono gratuite e puoi consultare tutti gli articoli senza paywall. Se vuoi, puoi iscriverti qui e qui.\n\nInfine, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n\nCiao e a presto!\n\nNote\n\n1 Aristotele, Metafisica .\n\n2 Ippolito, Refutationes .\n\n3 McKirahan, Philosophy before Socrates .\n\n4 Popper, Back to the Pre-Socratics: a presidential address .\n\n5 Platone, Teeteto e Cratilo .\n\n6 ovvero un pensatore che riduce la molteplicità degli eventi a un unico principio.\n\n7 Platone, Parmenide .\n\n8 Diogene Laerzio, Vite dei filosofi .\n\n9 Diogene Laerzio, Vite dei filosofi .\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_013-anaximander-s-indefinite-principle-and-anaximenes-cosmic-breath.md": "# Anaximander’s indefinite principle and Anaximenes’ cosmic breath\n\nDisclaimer #1: questo articolo è in inglese, la versione in italiano si può leggere qui.\n\nDisclaimer #2: this episode is part of a series named “ on the motion of the Earth ”, published both on this publication, Heralding Time , and on Last Scattering Surface . If you want, you can follow them both. Here chapters I, II, III, IV, V.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!n44D!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/25bb1116-004f-43d4-8858-aecca20c2d86_1080x1350.png)\n\nWelcome back.\n\nIn the previous episode we talked about Miletus and Thales, the first philosopher according to the tradition of philosophy in Greece.\n\nIn this episode we will talk about the other two philosophers from Miletus, we will hear what they have to say, we will understand how they answer questions about the origin of the world and its composition.\n\nHeralding Time is on Instagram. You can follow it here.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Zhbh!,w_640,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/__ss-rehost__IG-meta-DQgnHW1jFsY.jpg)\n\nAnaximander\n\nDiogenes Laertius1 informs us that Anaximander, son of Praxiades, is the first to have built \"clocks\", and in the Byzantine encyclopedia (the Suda , therefore a very late source) Anaximander is spoken of as the one who invented the gnomon, a useful instrument for measuring the position of the Sun, and who “measured” the equinoxes and solstices. Furthermore, according to Diogenes he was the first to draw a map of lands and seas. The Suda also cites some writings he would have composed: “ On Nature ,” “ The Circuit of the Earth ,” “ On the Fixed Stars ,” “ The Celestial Globe ”; regarding the first Barnes speaks of a \"naturalistic version of Hesiod’s Theogony\"2. A legend tells that the philosopher warned the Spartans of an imminent earthquake.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!mGv1!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/4c388a53-37d9-42ab-9c3c-f594d9874a4b_2491x2500.jpeg)\n\nAnaximander - 1493 - Rijksmuseum, Netherlands - Public Domain.\n\nDiogenes places the date of the philosopher’s death shortly after the LVIII Olympiad (547 BCE), around age 64. Apollodorus instead speaks of Anaximander born 14 years after Thales (therefore around 610 BCE) and died in the same year as his death (which occurred around 545 BCE). There is therefore a discrepancy between the two datings, but it is certain that the two philosophers were contemporary at a certain point, and it is said that Anaximander was a \"student\" of Thales, that is, that he heard his teachings.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!2OId!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1ad4bff3-7d9f-4f3c-b164-320828083873_1240x1126.png)\n\nRegarding the gnomon devised by Anaximander: as we saw in the previous chapter, the gnomon is a Babylonian invention, and perhaps was already known to Thales, therefore the \"discovery\" attributed to Anaximander can at most refer to the fact that he made use of it during his life.\n\nRegarding the map drawn by the second philosopher of Miletus: this was indeed one of the first after Homer’s, and was perfected by Hecataeus, geographer of Miletus, following Herodotus as a source, a Greek historian of the V century BCE.\n\nDiogenes, citing Theophrastus, states that for Anaximander the principle is the ἄπειρον ( apeiron ) which we translate as Unlimited, Indefinite, Infinite.\n\nWhen he speaks of principle, Anaximander probably does not refer to the ἀρχή of which we spoke regarding Thales, cited by Aristotle: the philosopher therefore does not refer to the force that generates the world, but to the substance of which the world is initially formed.\n\nThe ἄπειρον is translatable as infinite but does not represent the spatial infinity still used today in physics: and in fact together with infinite we insert indefinite , meaning by this that this \"primordial\" substance lacks boundary, limit, definition.\n\nThat is, it cannot be confined, delimited, defined.\n\nApeiron has as its root a-peiras , that is without limit, and peir has the meaning of \"to cross\". It seems therefore that the term ἄπειρον represents something that is impossible to cross from side to side .\n\nFor Anaximander what is not defined has no distinction , in the sense that it is a substance that contains everything without distinction .\n\nAristotle speaks of this, saying that this principle is an element beyond the elements, and that it contains an infinite reserve that behaves like a spring from which to generate all the elements.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!7XzT!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/def8d9b4-200b-484f-b3c1-39242eb43f0b_800x519.jpeg)\n\nMeteorite observed on June 11, 1867, illustration from 1875. Image obtained from Public Domain Image Archive / Internet Archive / California Digital Library\n\nIn any case, we are not sure what the interpretation was for Anaximander. It seems however, from the fragments we have3, that this Indefinite is for him the place where opposites pay \"one to the other the penalty according to the order of time\", and from which the same opposites originate4.\n\nThe Indefinite guides everything and \"steers\" everything, creation and its opposite, that is destruction , which both occur by necessity. This happens cyclically and without end, and one after another innumerable worlds are created and destroyed. The ἄπειρον is most likely in motion, otherwise how could the latter be born from something that does not contain it?\n\nAnd what type of motion does it contain? It seems that it should not have any particular type, because if it had a defined one, how could all the others be born? All the different characteristics of things emerge from the ἄπειρον, each separating from its opposite, but they are not initially contained in it.\n\nThe world as we can observe it today emerges, for Anaximander, after a process of separation and differentiation of everything from its opposite .\n\nKoestler5 speaks of Anaximander as the first who conceived a mechanistic system for the Universe. Let’s see why.\n\nWe have a fairly clear vision of his idea of the world, following various sources. According to Pseudo-Plutarch, Anaximander describes the Earth as a cylinder three times as wide as its length; Hippolytus also agrees6. According to Aristotle, the Earth for Anaximander is stationary at the center of the Universe, and is freely suspended without being supported by anything (unlike in Thales’ world, where the Earth is suspended by water), and this happens because and thanks to its “ being equally bound to all things ”7.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!DZB1!,w_56,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ec711e97-0367-4221-a708-51af6c518dff_1280x1280.png)\n\nLast Scattering Surface\n\nA story of a star - Part I Chasing the Sun…\n\nRead more\n\n3 years ago · 3 likes · Antonio Viscusi\n\nThe firmament is spherical, and the planets and stars are wheels of fire, surrounded by a bubble of air: they contain openings, from which fire escapes, which is the source of brightness of these celestial objects.\n\nWhen these openings are occluded - in what way is not said - in the Sun or Moon, it is at that moment that solar and lunar eclipses occur8.\n\nThe Moon is luminous because it contains fire like all the other stars, and does not take its brightness from the Sun.\n\nBright note in the margin #5\n\nThe wheels full of fire and surrounded by air present in Anaximander’s cosmology had been \"seen\" a few years earlier by the Hebrew prophet Ezekiel, son of Buzi, around 593 BCE in Mesopotamia:\n\nEzekiel 1:20: \"Wherever the spirit wanted to go, they went, and the wheels rose along with them, because the spirit of the living creatures was in the wheels\"\n\nIf the gods are in heaven, and in heaven there are the stars, do the gods not dwell in the stars?\n\nThe position of the celestial bodies is innovative: according to Hippolytus and Aetius, Anaximander places the fixed stars not in a sphere on the outside, but in the circle closest to Earth; then the circle of the Moon, at a distance equal to 18 times the diameter of the Earth; finally the Sun, at a distance equal to 27 times the diameter of the Earth. The Sun is as large as the Earth, and regarding the planets known at the time (Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter, Saturn) we do not know if Anaximander places them together with the fixed stars or at an intermediate distance between the fixed stars and the Moon.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!yuZu!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/335a0039-e12d-4522-8253-4e3485009346_960x930.png)\n\nDescription of Anaximander’s world. Illustration by D.L. Couprie in Heaven And Earth In Ancient Greek Cosmology . In the illustration, which follows that of Diels and Naddaf, the circle of stars is at nine Earth diameters, the circle of the Moon at 18, that of the Sun at 27. Credits here.\n\nWe know however that the movements in the sky all occur around the Earth, and that they are due to the wind generated by the moist exhalations of the Earth when it is heated by the heat of the Sun. It is also to the wind that the obliquity of the ecliptic is owed, that is, of the path that the Sun makes in its orbit around the Earth9.\n\nBright note in the margin #6\n\nIn Babylon, the numbers 3 and 9 had particular importance. In Egypt, astronomers selected 36 δεκανοί (decans), stars in the sky arranged so that their rising in the sky was distant from one another by ten degrees over periods of ten days, in order to divide the year into months.\n\nAnaximander’s cosmology has the first circle 9 times the diameter of the Earth, the circle of the Moon 18 times that of the Earth, the circle of the Sun 27 times.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!swTX!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/09b6a396-3f77-47ef-adb3-8bc3c9a0462e_1612x826.png)\n\nCopy of Mugler’s illustration with the description of Anaximander’s universe. The Earth is the cylinder at the center, which forms an angle with the vertical axis - the inclination of the ecliptic. The sphere is the sphere of stars, the first circle is that of the Moon, the outermost circle that of the Sun. Credits here.\n\nAnaximander’s universe is measured in \"terrestrial\" dimensions: it is the first time this happens outside of a mythical tale, in which philosophy becomes slightly more quantitative and assigns a role to numbers in terms of proportion. We will see with Pythagoras that this is perhaps the foundation of Greek astronomy.\n\nBright note in the margin #7\n\nThe order Earth, stars, Moon, Sun is innovative for ancient Greece, but is not original in human history: it was the standard in Persian cosmology.\n\nIn the sacred texts of the Dāmdāt Nask and the Pahlavi Dēnkart one reads that beyond the Sun there is imperishable light. In Persian the expression anayra- means \"without beginning\", that is without ayra.\n\nIf ἀρχή is the principle, ayra also has a similar meaning.\n\nIt is strange, we said innovative earlier, the choice to place the circle of fixed stars in front of the circle of the Moon; it also seems like an idea easy to refute, in fact: how many times are the stars of the Pleiades occulted by the presence of the Moon, thus demonstrating that it is the Moon that is closer to Earth, and not the contrary?\n\nBut this decision could be due not so much to some specific astronomical observation, as to the idea that Anaximander has of the nature of these bodies. If they are composed of fire, and the \"purer\" the fire the higher it rises, then the brightest fire there is, and the purest - that is the Sun - will be in the highest place, followed by the Moon, and only after by the faint lights seen in the sky at night on a moonless night: the stars.\n\nThere remains the unresolved doubt about the behavior of the mist , which exhales from the Earth and creates the stars: if the Sun and Moon are visible even beyond this mist, then is its behavior such as to make partially visible and partially invisible beyond itself? This is not clear.\n\nFor Anaximander, the cause of the birth of the world already contains the forces that cause its movements. For this reason, McKirahan states that the philosopher is an ante litteram exponent of Uniformitarianism10, that is, of that doctrine born between the XVIII and XIX centuries CE according to which the geological processes that occur in the world today are the same as those that occurred in remote times.\n\nFinally, with his idea of the Earth suspended at the center of the Universe, Anaximander allowed celestial bodies to rotate all around it, without worrying about accepting \"passages\" from Okeanos or visiting or not the kingdom of souls, echoes of Egyptian and Babylonian mythologies.\n\nThe Universe becomes more and more something that humanity can describe in an a-human way, becoming however increasingly intertwined with the concepts of proportion, meaning, ultimate destination - very human concepts.\n\nAnaximenes\n\nAnaximenes, son of Eurystratus11, is a student of Anaximander, probably also of Parmenides12. We do not know much about his life, except that his acme is around the fall of Sardis after the conquest of Cyrus the Great - which occurred around 546 BCE. He could therefore have been born around 585 BCE13. He probably died in the LXIII Olympiad, therefore between 528 and 524 BCE.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!sA8C!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/30bea483-ae5e-41b6-83df-ab94ec5e5e6d_2500x2456.jpeg)\n\nAnaximenes - 1493 - Rijksmuseum, Netherlands - Public Domain.\n\nOf him we know nothing else, except that it is said he wrote at least one book.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!uMPP!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/494f7763-fdcd-4ad9-b6a2-e4f60f391879_1240x1126.png)\n\nAnaximenes’ philosophy is transmitted by Aristotle, and we know that his ἀρχή, his creative principle, is air .\n\nThe term air must not be misleading. The Greeks distinguish between aer and aether : the first term refers to breath, and comes from a term meaning \"dark mist\", and can be hot or cold; the second term instead represents crystalline air, and is the pure element that will then become the material of which the celestial spheres are filled.\n\nAir is infinite like the ἄπειρον, but it is not indefinite . From air in fact come all the elements, thanks to a process of rarefaction and condensation: when water becomes rarefied, fire is created; when it becomes denser, it becomes wind; and then again clouds, finally water. From this, it becomes earth, and finally rock.\n\nThese changes occur because of the movement of the ἄπειρον, which is eternal.\n\nAir, which is the πνεῦμα ( pneuma ) of the world, is the reason for its existence and its diversity: from the exhalations of air come the Sun, the Moon and the stars, but also the gods14.\n\nAnaximenes is the first to state that the fixed stars are truly fixed , in the sense that they are bound to the celestial vault, which is crystalline because it allows one to see what is beyond.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!7Zzj!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a5070138-a1dc-47f7-96b5-8697c3e19ab6_1024x690.jpeg)\n\nStudie af skyer, work by Christen Købke. Image obtained from National Gallery of Denmark, Denmark - Public Domain.\n\nAll commentators agree in stating that Anaximenes’ Earth is flat15, that it is stationary at the center of the Universe16, and that it is supported by air; that all celestial bodies rotate around it, and are also flat \" like a leaf\" 17; that the Sun is in motion because of the wind generated by air, and that this movement is the reason why it is so hot; that the stars are also in motion - although they are fixed to the celestial vault , they move because the celestial vault itself is in motion - and we do not feel their heat because they are very distant; moreover, they could host other worlds like the Sun with Earth.\n\nUnlike Anaximander, however, Anaximenes does not describe the motion of celestial bodies as a complete revolution around the Earth: when they are not visible to us, this is not due to their motion under the Earth , but to the fact that those bodies - the Sun at night, the stars by day - cross distant regions of the world that are higher than the rest of the world, and therefore invisible to observation, almost as if the table that is the Earth were also a bit oblique.\n\nThe phenomenon of eclipses is due to smaller bodies that obscure the light of the Moon or Sun.\n\nAnaximenes explains the world by tracing everything back to the ἀρχή, and in this he unites the teachings of his two predecessors and fellow citizens: the ἀρχή is the cause of everything (the ἄπειρον for Anaximander), but it is also a visible element of the world, air (what for Thales was water).\n\nFurthermore, he operates a reduction of multiple phenomena, from the presence of celestial bodies to the diversity of elements, to a single cause: air and its behaviours. He associates two opposite qualities - hot and cold, light and heavy, rarefied and dense - with a single quantity .\n\nFrom terrestrial events like earthquakes, due according to Anaximenes to the Earth drying out and cracking18, to the gods who are born and preside over the world, everything in the Universe has air as its principle.\n\nTraces of the Near East\n\nWe have already spoken several times about the relationship between the first Greek philosophers and Egyptian, Babylonian and in general, the mythologies of the peoples and civilisations of the east. Anaximander and Anaximenes make no exception.\n\nAnaximander speaks of the ἄπειρον as the negation of what is limited . This Indefinite creates infinite worlds, all equidistant in time, and in which each lasts for a defined time. The world is formed with the perpetual movement of the Indefinite, first as a generative unity, which contains everything and its contrary, and then as the sphere that contains the Earth and the wheels of fire surrounded by air that are the celestial bodies. With his mechanistic vision he explains eclipses, the angulation of the ecliptic, the presence of celestial bodies.\n\nThe shape of the Earth, a cylinder wider than it is tall, is slightly concave, as if in this description there remained the echo of Babylonian, Chaldean, Iranian and Egyptian mythologies about the mountains that surround the world.\n\nWe have seen in the bright notes in the margin of this chapter that many times the ideas of Greek philosophers find a mythical origin or a religious explanation in eastern myths: the creation of Anaximander’s world is no exception, which occurs in a way similar to the Iranian one in which Ohrmazd creates the world from \"what is moist and what is fiery\".\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!z6wv!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/cae3efbc-0132-4cdf-97a8-69bba7b7de3b_2412x2010.jpeg)\n\nFuoco, work by Maerten de Vos, Adriaen Collaert, 1580-1584. Image obtained from Public Domain Image Archive / Rijksmuseum\n\nAnaximenes instead speaks of air, of aer , of ἀήρ: mist, vapor. It is a visible substance, but which has the properties of the Indefinite. In relation to air as breath, in a hymn to Prâna contained in the Atharva Veda texts, it is said that everything obeys Prâna, which is breath . In the Pahlavi texts one reads that eclipses are due to smaller bodies in the sky that interpose between the world of Earth and the stars.\n\nThe three philosophers, finally\n\nThe three philosophers of Miletus, Thales, Anaximander and Anaximenes , are the first in Greece to try to discover the functioning and origin of Nature through reasoning : they observe the world, try to trace back to first principles, to generalise , to make analogies , to compare different phenomena to find their common origins .\n\nBenjamin Farrington, historian of science and Marxist-inspired academic (Science in Antiquity, Science and Politics in the Ancient World), speaks of the philosophers of Miletus saying that they \"leave out the gods\" from their explanations of natural phenomena. This is certainly true insofar as what happens in the world is not the result of the will of the gods, and in which neither the creation of the world nor its end are the work of a creative or destructive divinity. Despite this, the three philosophers do not reject the existence of the gods, who are even subjected to the same process of creation as all the other things there are in the world, and who are subject to the same rules, and the same principles. Anaximander’s ἄπειρον could represent the spirit of creation of the world, but already in Anaximenes this spirit is indeed indefinite, but observable in action even on Earth.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!vWNs!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/db435f8d-7659-447f-9442-ccda3f7b1bf3_800x902.jpeg)\n\nIllustration from a 1587 treatise on comets and meteors, known as Kometenbuch - work by an anonymous artist, 1587. Image obtained from Public Domain Image Archive / ORKA - Open Repository Kassel\n\nWhat they seek is the general, not the particular; it is the primary cause, the universal and essential, the material cause. Now Barnes asks himself: do they do it as \"scientists\", in the sense we define it today?\n\nThere are three possible ways to sketch an answer: one can think that \"none of the philosophers of Miletus proposed “true” theories\", that \"they did not compose a Royal Society [ante litteram] in Greece\", and that \"none of these philosophers intended to achieve the precision that is required of scientific theories today\"19; in doing so, they are seen as representatives of the last poets interested in Nature, rather than the first initiators of Western science.\n\nThis vision is encouraged by the problems in the uncertain assignment of ideas and interpretations of the same due to the second, third, even fourth level sources that are the only ones we have; but also by the fact that as far as we know these philosophers did not (i) perform experiments, (ii) did not use the inductive method to build their theories nor (iii) the critical method towards each other, (iv) did not use the data at their disposal to advance hypotheses.\n\nOn the other hand there is the vision, among others proposed by Popper, according to which their works prepared the way for scientific research as we understand it, and that indeed they did the best they could do with the means at their disposal: Popper speaks in particular of Anaximander, who arrived at his idea by criticising Thales’ theory, using speculative arguments, proper to philosophy, to assert that if the Earth lies on water, one should have explained what the water rests on, and so on; and judging these infinite explanations unacceptable, he proposed a new one, which is interesting insofar as it seems to prepare for the concept of action at a distance, with his description of the Earth stationary because equally \"attracted\" by everything simultaneously. And it matters little if then Anaximander himself states that the Earth is flat: this is due to observational arguments, proper to science, and equally important as speculative ones.\n\nCertainly, Thales and the other two philosophers were wrong in their ideas, but their importance, says Coleman20, does not lie in the models they proposed, rather in the fact that they began, each improving the model of the previous one, to \"establish a long chain of progressively [increasingly] correct interpretation of scientific discoveries\".\n\nFinally, the third way unites the two previous ones, and presenting the three philosophers as those who allowed science as naturalistic and no longer mythical inquiry to be born, but who did not manage to adhere to the dictates that modern science considers necessary to define science as speculative and observational inquiry.\n\nAll this is not a fault that we can attribute to the three philosophers, whom we can well define - for our understanding of the terms - therefore, if not Astronomers, Cosmologists, Physicists, at least full-fledged investigators of Nature.\n\nHowever, one should not think that their inquiries were homogeneous, uniform, directed by a specific idea: the concept of principle alone, for example, is not proper to the VI century BCE, but is connected a posteriori by Aristotle searching for it in the philosophers before him.\n\nThe search for the causes of movements in the sky and the origin of the world continues as a search by single individuals: who debate each other’s ideas - without undermining the theories at their core, but who do not belong to a school. Not yet.\n\nIn the next episode: the problem of change.\n\nRead the other episodes:\n\nBibliography:\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe, by Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, edited by C. Blacker and M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nGreek Cosmologies, by G.E.R. Lloyd\n\nAristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus, by Heath T. (Oxford 1913)\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, di Kirk G.S. and Raven J.E. (Cambridge 1957)\n\nEarly Greek Philosophy and the Orient, by West M.L. (Oxford 1971)\n\nPhilosophy before Socrates, by McKirahan R.D. (Hackett 1994)\n\nEarly Greek Science, by G.E.R. Lloyd (Chatto & Windus 1970)\n\nA history of astronomy from Thales to Kepler, by J.L.E Dreyer (Dover 1953)\n\nHeaven And Earth In Ancient Greek Cosmology, by D.L. Cuprie (Springer 2011)\n\nEarly Greek Cosmology: A Historiographical Review, by N.S. Hetherington\n\nBack to the Pre-Socratics: The Presidential Address, by K.R. Popper (1958)\n\nEarly Greek astronomy to Aristotle, by D.R. Dicks (Cornell University Press 1970)\n\nHistory of Philosophy Volume I: From the Beginning to Plato, edited by C.C.W. Taylor (Routledge 1997)\n\nThe Ionians, by Malcolm Schofield\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, by Jonathan Barnes (Routledge 1979)\n\nA Source Book In Greek Science by M.R. Cohen e I.E. Drabkin (Harvard University Press 1945)\n\nThe Physical World of the Greeks, by S. Sambursky (The Macmillan Company 1956)\n\nNotes\n\n1 Diogenes Laertius, Lives of Philosophers.\n\n2 Jonathan Barnes, The Presocratic Philosophers.\n\n3 Simplicius, Commentary on Aristotle’s Physics.\n\n4 Simplicius also cites Theophrastus in the Commentary on Aristotle’s Physics, and also Hermias of Alexandria, Pseudo-Plutarch and Aetius agree on Simplicius’ idea of the indefinite.\n\n5 Arthur Koestler, Sleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe.\n\n6 Hippolytus, Refutationes.\n\n7 Pseudo-Plutarch, Stromata.\n\n8 Hippolytus, Refutationes.\n\n9 Pseudo-Plutarch, Stromata.\n\n10 McKirahan, Philosophy before Socrates\n\n11 Diogenes Laertius, Lives of the Philosophers.\n\n12 We will also talk about him.\n\n13 The acme of a philosopher was generally placed around his fortieth year of age.\n\n14 Hippolytus, Refutationes.\n\n15 Pseudo-Plutarch, Stromata.\n\n16 Aristotle, De Cælo.\n\n17 Aristotle, Meteorologica.\n\n18 Aristotle, Meteorologica.\n\n19 N.S. Hetherington, Early Greek Cosmology: A Historiographical Review.\n\n20 Coleman, Early Theories of the Universe\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_014-il-principio-indefinito-di-anassimandro-e-il-respiro-cosmico-di-anassime.md": "# il principio indefinito di Anassimandro e il respiro cosmico di Anassimene\n\nDisclaimer #1: this article is in Italian. I will publish the English version next Wednesday.\n\nDisclaimer #2: questo pezzo fa parte di una serie, pubblicata sia su questa newsletter, Heralding Time , che su Last Scattering Surface . Se vuoi, puoi seguirle entrambe. Qui i capitoli I, II, III, IV, V.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!eqNs!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/86bf5b8f-21f4-4b22-a340-bde9cfd9b18e_1080x1350.png)\n\nBentornati.\n\nNel precedente episodio abbiamo parlato di Mileto e di Talete, il primo filosofo secondo la tradizione della filosofia in Grecia.\n\nIn questo episodio parleremo degli altri due filosofi provenienti da Mileto, sentiremo cosa hanno da dire, capiremo come rispondono alle domande sull’origine del mondo e sulla sua composizione.\n\nHeralding Time è su Instagram. Puoi seguirlo qui.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!qq0U!,w_640,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/__ss-rehost__IG-meta-DP_M6usDF1N.jpg)\n\nAnassimandro\n\nDiogene Laerzio1 ci informa che Anassimandro, figlio di Prassiade, è il primo ad aver costruito degli \"orologi\", e nell’enciclopedia bizantina (la Suda , fonte quindi molto tarda) si parla di Anassimandro come di colui che ha inventato lo gnomone, strumento utile per la misurare la posizione del Sole, e che ha \"misurato\" gli equinozi e i solstizi. Inoltre, secondo Diogene fu il primo a disegnare una mappa delle terre e dei mari. La Suda cita inoltre alcuni scritti che avrebbe composto: “ Sulla Natura” , “ Il giro della Terra” , “ Sulle stelle fisse” , “ Il globo celeste” ; a proposito del primo, Barnes di una “versione naturalistica della Teogonia di Esiodo”2. Una leggenda narra che il filosofo abbia avvertito gli spartani di un imminente terremoto.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!mGv1!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/4c388a53-37d9-42ab-9c3c-f594d9874a4b_2491x2500.jpeg)\n\nAnaximander - 1493 - Rijksmuseum, Netherlands - Public Domain.\n\nDiogene inserisce la data della morte del filosofo poco dopo la LVIII Olimpiade (547 BCE), intorno ai 64 anni. Apollodoro invece parla di Anassimandro nato 14 anni dopo Talete (quindi intorno al 610 BCE) e morto nello stesso anno della morte di questi (avvenuta intorno al 545 BCE). C’è quindi una discrepanza tra le due datazioni, ma è certo che i due filosofi fossero contemporanei a un certo punto, e si dice che Anassimandro sia stato “allievo” di Talete, ovvero che ne abbia sentito gli insegnamenti.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!2OId!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1ad4bff3-7d9f-4f3c-b164-320828083873_1240x1126.png)\n\nRiguardo lo gnomone ideato da Anassimandro: come abbiamo visto nel capitolo precedente, lo gnomone è una invenzione babilonese, e forse era già conosciuto da Talete, dunque la \"scoperta\" attribuita ad Anassimandro può al più riferirsi al fatto che ne abbia fatto uso durante la sua vita.\n\nRiguardo la mappa disegnata dal secondo filosofo di Mileto: questa fu effettivamente una delle prime dopo quella di Omero, e fu perfezionata da Ecateo, geografo di Mileto, seguendo come fonte Erodoto, storico greco del V secolo BCE.\n\nDiogene, citando Teofrasto, afferma che per Anassimandro il principio è l’ἄπειρον (apeiron) che traduciamo con Illimitato, Indefinito, Infinito .\n\nQuando parla di principio, probabilmente Anassimandro non si riferisce all’ἀρχή di cui abbiamo parlato a proposito di Talete, citato da Aristotele: il filosofo quindi non si riferisce alla forza che genera il mondo, ma alla sostanza di cui il mondo inizialmente è formato.\n\nL’ἄπειρον è traducibile con infinito ma non rappresenta l’infinito spaziale usato ancora oggi in fisica: e infatti insieme a infinito si inserisce indefinito , intendendo con questo che questa sostanza “primigenia” manca di confine, di limite, di definizione.\n\nOvvero che non può essere confinato, delimitato, definito.\n\nApeiron ha come radice a-peiras , ovvero senza limite, e peir ha il significato di \"attraversare\". Sembra quindi che il termine ἄπειρον rappresenti qualcosa che è impossibile da attraversare da parte a parte .\n\nPer Anassimandro ciò che non è definito non ha distinzione , nel senso che è una sostanza che contiene tutto senza distinzione .\n\nAristotele parla di ciò, dicendo che questo principio è un elemento al di là degli elementi, e che contiene una riserva infinita che si comporta come una sorgente da cui generare tutti gli elementi.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!7XzT!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/def8d9b4-200b-484f-b3c1-39242eb43f0b_800x519.jpeg)\n\nMeteorite osservata l’11 Giugno 1867, illustrazione del 1875. Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / Internet Archive / California Digital Library\n\nAd ogni modo, non siamo sicuri di quale fosse l’interpretazione per Anassimandro. Sembra però, dai frammenti che abbiamo3, che questo Indefinito è per lui il luogo in cui gli opposti pagano \" l’uno all’altro la pena secondo l’ordine del tempo \", e da cui gli stessi opposti hanno origine4.\n\nL’Indefinito guida tutto e controlla tutto, la creazione e il suo opposto, ovvero la distruzione , che avvengono entrambe per necessità. Ciò avviene ciclicamente e senza fine, e uno dopo l’altro si creano e si distruggono innumerevoli mondi. L’ἄπειρον è molto probabilmente in moto, altrimenti come potrebbe quest’ultimo nascere da qualcosa che non lo contiene?\n\nE che tipo di moto contiene? Sembra che non debba averne di nessun tipo in particolare, perché se ne avesse uno definito, tutti gli altri come potrebbero nascere? Tutte le diverse caratteristiche delle cose emergono dall’ἄπειρον, separandosi ognuna dal proprio opposto, ma non sono contenute in esso inizialmente.\n\nIl mondo come possiamo osservarlo oggi emerge, per Anassimandro, dopo un processo di separazione e di differenziazione di ogni cosa dal suo opposto .\n\nKoestler5 parla di Anassimandro come del primo che ha ideato un sistema meccanicistico per l’Universo. Vediamo perché.\n\nAbbiamo una visione abbastanza chiara della sua idea di mondo, seguendo diverse fonti. Secondo Pseudo-Plutarco, Anassimandro descrive la Terra come un cilindro largo tre volte la sua lunghezza; concorde è anche Ippolito6. Secondo Aristotele, la Terra per Anassimandro è ferma al centro dell’Universo, ed è sospesa liberamente senza essere sostenuta da nulla (come invece avviene nel mondo di Talete, in cui la Terra è sospesa dall’acqua), e questo avviene per causa e merito del suo \" essere legata in modo uguale a tutte le cose \"7.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!DZB1!,w_56,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ec711e97-0367-4221-a708-51af6c518dff_1280x1280.png)\n\nLast Scattering Surface\n\nA story of a star - Part I Chasing the Sun…\n\nRead more\n\n3 years ago · 3 likes · Antonio Viscusi\n\nIl firmamento è sferico, e i pianeti e le stelle sono ruote di fuoco, circondate da una bolla d’aria: contengono delle aperture, da cui fuoriesce del fuoco, che è la fonte di luminosità di questi oggetti celesti.\n\nQuando queste aperture sono occultate - in che modo non viene detto - nel Sole o nella Luna, è in quel momento che avvengono le eclissi solari e lunari 8.\n\nLa Luna è luminosa in quanto contiene il fuoco come tutte le altre stelle, e non prende la sua luminosità dal Sole.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #5\n\nLe ruote piene di fuoco e circondate dall’aria presenti nella cosmologia di Anassimandro erano state \"viste\" qualche anno prima dal profeta ebreo Ezechiele, figlio di Buzì, intorno al 593 BCE in Mesopotamia:\n\nEzechiele 1,20: \"Dovunque lo spirito le avesse sospinte, le ruote andavano e ugualmente si alzavano, perché lo spirito degli esseri viventi era nelle ruote\"\n\nSe gli dei sono in cielo, e in cielo ci sono le stelle, non abitano forse nelle stelle gli dei?\n\nLa posizione degli astri è innovativa: secondo Ippolito e Aezio, Anassimandro pone le stelle fisse non in una sfera all’esterno, ma nel cerchio più vicino alla Terra; poi il cerchio della Luna, a una distanza pari a 18 volte il diametro della Terra; infine il Sole, a una distanza pari a 27 volte il diametro della Terra. Il Sole è grande tanto quanto la Terra, e in merito ai pianeti conosciuti all’epoca (Mercurio, Venere, Marte, Giove, Saturno) non sappiamo se Anassimandro li pone insieme alle stelle fisse o a una distanza intermedia tra le stelle fisse e la Luna.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!yuZu!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/335a0039-e12d-4522-8253-4e3485009346_960x930.png)\n\nDescrizione del mondo di Anassimandro. Illustrazione di D.L. Couprie in Heaven And Earth In Ancient Greek Cosmology. Nell’illustrazione, che segue quella di Diels e Naddaf, il cerchio delle stelle è a nove diametri terrestri, il cerchio della Luna a 18, quello del Sole a 27. Credits qui.\n\nSappiamo però che i movimenti nel cielo avvengono tutti intorno alla Terra, e che sono dovuti al vento generato dalle esalazioni umide della Terra quando essa viene riscaldata dal calore del Sole. E’ al vento inoltre che si deve l’obliquità della eclittica, ovvero del percorso che il Sole compie nella sua orbita intorno alla Terra9.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #6\n\nA Babilonia, i numeri 3 e 9 avevano particolare importanza. In Egitto, gli astronomi selezionavano 36 δεκανοί (decani), stelle nel cielo disposte in modo tale che il loro sorgere nel cielo fosse distante l'uno dall'altro dieci gradi lungo periodi di dieci giorni, in modo da dividere l'anno in mesi.\n\nLa cosmologia di Anassimandro ha il primo cerchio 9 volte il diametro della Terra, il cerchio della Luna 18 volte quello della Terra, il cerchio del Sole 27 volte.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!swTX!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/09b6a396-3f77-47ef-adb3-8bc3c9a0462e_1612x826.png)\n\nCopia dell’illustrazione di Mugler con la descrizione dell’universo di Anassimandro. La Terra è il cilindro al centro, che forma un angolo con l’asse verticale - l’inclinazione dell’eclittica. La sfera è la sfera delle stelle, il primo cerchio è quello della Luna, il cerchio più esterno quello del Sole. Credits qui.\n\nL’universo di Anassimandro è a misura di dimensioni \"terrestri\": è la prima volta che accade fuori da un racconto mitico, in cui la filosofia si fa leggermente più quantitativa e assegna un ruolo ai numeri in termini di proporzione. Vedremo con Pitagora che ciò è forse il fondamento della astronomia greca.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #7\n\nL'ordine Terra, stelle, Luna, Sole è innovativo per la Grecia antica, ma non è originale nella storia umana: era lo standard nella cosmologia persiana.\n\nNei testi sacri del Dāmdāt Nask e del Pahlavi Dēnkart si legge che oltre il Sole c'è la luce imperitura. In persiano l'espressione anayra- significa \"senza inizio\", ovvero senza ayra.\n\nSe ἀρχή è il principio, anche ayra ha un significato simile.\n\nE’ strana, prima abbiamo detto innovativa, la scelta di porre il cerchio delle stelle fisse davanti il cerchio della Luna; sembra anche un’idea facile da confutare, in effetti: quante volte le stelle delle Pleiadi vengono occultate dalla presenza della Luna, dimostrando quindi che è la Luna a trovarsi più vicina alla Terra, e non il contrario?\n\nMa questa decisione potrebbe essere dovuta non tanto a qualche specifica osservazione astronomica, quanto all’idea che Anassimandro ha della natura di questi corpi. Se sono composti di fuoco, e più il fuoco è \"puro\" più sale in alto, allora il fuoco più luminoso che c’è, e il più puro - ovvero il Sole - si troverà nel posto più alto, seguito dalla Luna, e solo dopo dalle fioche luci che si vedono in cielo di notte in una notte senza Luna: le stelle.\n\nResta il dubbio insoluto sul comportamento della nebbia , che esala dalla Terra e crea le stelle: se il Sole e la Luna sono visibili anche oltre questa nebbia, dunque il suo comportamento è tale da rendere in parte visibile e in parte invisibile oltre di sé? Ciò non è chiaro.\n\nPer Anassimandro, la causa della nascita del mondo contiene già le forze che ne causano i movimenti. Per questo, McKirahan afferma che il filosofo è un esponente ante litteram dell’Uniformitarismo10, ovvero di quella dottrina nata tra il XVIII e il XIX secolo CE secondo la quale i processi geologici che oggi avvengono nel mondo sono gli stessi che sono avvenuti in tempi remoti.\n\nInfine, con la sua idea della Terra sospesa al centro dell’Universo, Anassimandro ha permesso ai corpi celesti di ruotare tutto intorno ad essa, senza preoccuparsi di accettare \"passaggi\" da Okeanos o di visitare o meno il regno delle anime, eco di mitologie egizie e babilonesi.\n\nL’Universo diventa sempre di più qualcosa che l’umanità può descrivere in modo a-umano , diventando però sempre più intrecciato con i concetti di proporzione, di senso, di destinazione ultima - concetti molto umani.\n\nAnassimene\n\nAnassimene, figlio di Euristrato11, è un allievo di Anassimandro, probabilmente anche di Parmenide12. Non sappiamo molto della sua vita, se non che il suo acme è intorno alla caduta di Sardi dopo la conquista di Ciro il Grande - avvenuta intorno al 546 BCE. Potrebbe dunque essere nato intorno al 585 BCE13. Morì probabilmente nella LXIII Olimpiade, quindi tra il 528 e il 524 BCE.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!sA8C!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/30bea483-ae5e-41b6-83df-ab94ec5e5e6d_2500x2456.jpeg)\n\nAnaximenes - 1493 - Rijksmuseum, Netherlands - Public Domain.\n\nDi lui non sappiamo nient’altro, se non che si dice abbia scritto almeno un libro.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!uMPP!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/494f7763-fdcd-4ad9-b6a2-e4f60f391879_1240x1126.png)\n\nLa filosofia di Anassimene è tramandata da Aristotele, e sappiamo che il suo ἀρχή, il suo principio creatore, è l’ aria .\n\nIl termine aria non deve trarre in inganno. I Greci fanno distinzione tra aer e aether: il primo termine si riferisce al respiro, e viene da un termine che significa \"nebbia oscura\", e può essere caldo o freddo; il secondo termine invece rappresenta l’aria cristallina, ed è l’elemento puro che poi diventerà il materiale di cui sono piene le sfere celesti.\n\nL’aria è infinita come l’ἄπειρον, ma non è indefinita . Dall’aria infatti vengono tutti gli elementi, grazie a un processo di rarefazione e condensazione: quando l’aria diviene rarefatta, si crea il fuoco; quando si fa più densa, diventa vento; e poi ancora nuvole, infine acqua. Da questa, diventa terra, e infine roccia.\n\nQuesti cambiamenti avvengono a causa del movimento dell’ἄπειρον, che è eterno.\n\nL’aria, che è lo πνεῦμα ( pneuma ) del mondo, è il motivo della sua esistenza e della sua diversità: dalle esalazioni dell’aria arrivano il Sole, la Luna e le stelle, ma anche gli dei14.\n\nAnassimene è il primo ad affermare che le stelle fisse sono davvero fisse , nel senso che sono legate alla volta celeste, che è cristallina perché permette di vedere ciò che c’è al di là.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!7Zzj!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a5070138-a1dc-47f7-96b5-8697c3e19ab6_1024x690.jpeg)\n\nStudie af skyer, opera di Christen Købke. Immagine ottenuta da National Gallery of Denmark, Denmark - Public Domain.\n\nTutti i commentatori sono concordi nell’affermare che la Terra di Anassimene è piatta15, che è ferma al centro dell’Universo16, e che è supportata dall’aria; che tutti i corpi celesti ruotano intorno a essa, e sono anch’essi piatti \" come una foglia \"17; che il Sole è in movimento a causa del vento generato dall’aria, e che questo movimento è il motivo per cui è così caldo; che anche le stelle sono in movimento - nonostante siano fisse alla volta celeste , si muovono poiché la volta celeste stessa è in movimento - e non ne sentiamo il calore poiché sono molto distanti; inoltre, potrebbero ospitare altri mondi come il Sole con la Terra.\n\nA differenza di Anassimandro, però, Anassimene non descrive il moto dei corpi celesti come una rivoluzione completa intorno alla Terra: quando essi non sono visibili da noi, ciò non è dovuto al loro moto sotto la Terra , ma al fatto che quei corpi - il Sole di notte, le stelle di giorno - attraversano delle regioni distanti del mondo che sono più in alto rispetto al resto del mondo, e quindi invisibili all’osservazione, quasi come se la tavola che è la Terra fosse anche un po’ obliqua.\n\nIl fenomeno delle eclissi è dovuto a corpi minori che oscurano la luce della Luna o del Sole.\n\nAnassimene spiega il mondo riconducendo tutto all’ἀρχή, e in questo unisce gli insegnamenti dei due predecessori e concittadini: l’ἀρχή è la causa di tutto (l’ἄπειρον per Anassimandro), ma è anche un elemento visibile del mondo, l’aria (ciò che per Talete era l’acqua).\n\nInoltre, opera una riduzione di più fenomeni, dalla presenza dei corpi celesti alla diversità degli elementi, ad una sola causa: l’aria e i suoi comportamenti. Associa due qualità opposte - caldo e freddo, leggere e pesante, rarefatto e denso - ad un’unica quantità .\n\nDagli eventi terrestri come i terremoti, dovuti secondo Anassimene alla Terra che si asciuga e spacca18, agli dei che nascono e presiedono il mondo, tutto nell’Universo ha come principio l’aria.\n\nTracce del vicino oriente\n\nAbbiamo già parlato più volte del rapporto tra i primi filosofi greci e le mitologie egiziane, babilonesi e in generale, dei popoli e delle civiltà dell’ oriente . Anassimandro e Anassimene non fanno eccezione.\n\nAnassimandro parla dell’ἄπειρον come della negazione di ciò che è limitato . Questo Indefinito crea infiniti mondi, tutti equidistanti nel tempo, e in cui ognuno dura per un tempo definito. Il mondo si forma con il movimento perpetuo dell’Indefinito, prima come unità generativa, che contiene tutto e il suo contrario, e poi come la sfera che contiene la Terra e le ruote di fuoco circondate dall’aria che sono i corpi celesti. Con la sua visione meccanicistica spiega le eclissi, l’angolazione dell’eclittica, la presenza dei corpi celesti.\n\nLa forma della Terra, un cilindro più largo che alto, è leggermente concava, come se restasse in questa descrizione l’eco delle mitologie babilonesi, caldee, iraniane e egiziane sulle montagne che circondano il mondo.\n\nAbbiamo visto nelle note luminose a margine di questo capitolo che più volte le idee dei filosofi greci trovano una origine mitica o una spiegazione religiosa nei miti orientali: non fa eccezione la creazione del mondo di Anassimandro, che avviene in modo simile a quella iraniana in cui Ohrmazd crea il mondo da \"ciò che è umido e ciò che è infuocato\".\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!z6wv!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/cae3efbc-0132-4cdf-97a8-69bba7b7de3b_2412x2010.jpeg)\n\nFuoco, opera di Maerten de Vos, Adriaen Collaert, 1580-1584. Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / Rijksmuseum\n\nAnassimene invece parla dell’aria, dell’ aer , di ἀήρ: nebbia, vapore. E’ una sostanza visibile, ma che ha le proprietà dell’Indefinito. In relazione all’aria come respiro, in un inno a Prâna contenuto nei testi Atharva Veda , si dice che tutto obbedisce a Prâna , che è il respiro . Nei testi Pahlavi si legge che le eclissi sono dovute a corpi minori nel cielo che si frappongono tra il mondo della Terra e le stelle.\n\nI tre filosofi, infine\n\nI tre filosofi di Mileto, Talete , Anassimandro e Anassimene , sono i primi in Grecia a cercare di scoprire il funzionamento e l’origine della Natura attraverso il ragionamento : osservano il mondo, provano a risalire a principi primi , a generalizzare , a compiere analogie , a comparare fenomeni diversi per trovarne delle comuni origini .\n\nBenjamin Farrington, storico della scienza e accademico di ispirazione marxista (Science in Antiquity, Science and Politics in the Ancient World), parla dei filosofi di Mileto dicendo che \"lasciano fuori gli dei\" dalle loro spiegazioni sui fenomeni naturali. E’ certamente vero nella misura in cui ciò che accade nel mondo non è frutto del volere degli dei, e in cui né la creazione del mondo né la sua fine sono opera di una divinità creatrice o distruttrice. Nonostante questo, i tre filosofi non rifiutano l’esistenza degli dei, che sono addirittura sottoposti allo stesso processo di creazione di tutte le altre cose che ci sono nel mondo, e che sono sottoposti alle stesse regole, e agli stessi principi. L’ἄπειρον di Anassimandro potrebbe rappresentare lo spirito di creazione del mondo, ma già in Anassimene questo spirito è sì indefinito, ma osservabile in azione persino sulla Terra.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!vWNs!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/db435f8d-7659-447f-9442-ccda3f7b1bf3_800x902.jpeg)\n\nIllustrazione da un trattato del 1587 sulle comete e le meteore, conosciuto come Kometenbuch - opera di un anonimo, 1587. Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / ORKA - Open Repository Kassel\n\nQuello che ricercano è il generale, non il particolare; è la causa primaria, l’universale e l’essenziale, la causa materiale . Ora Barnes si chiede: lo fanno da \"scienziati\", nel senso in cui lo definiamo oggi?\n\nCi sono tre vie possibili per abbozzare una risposta: si può pensare che \"nessuno dei filosofi di Mileto propose teorie “vere”\", che \"non composero una Royal Society [ante litteram] in Grecia”, e che \"nessuno di questi filosofi aveva intenzione di raggiungere la precisione che oggi viene richiesta alle teorie scientifiche\"19; così facendo, li si vede come i rappresentanti degli ultimi poeti interessati alla Natura, piuttosto che i primi iniziatori della scienza occidentale.\n\nQuesta visione è incoraggiata dai problemi nella assegnazione incerta delle idee e delle interpretazioni delle stesse dovuta alle fonti di secondo, terzo, addirittura quarto livello che sono le uniche di cui disponiamo; ma anche dal fatto che per quanto ne sappiamo questi filosofi non (i) effettuarono esperimenti, (ii) non utilizzarono né il metodo induttivo per costruire le proprie teorie né (iii) il metodo critico nei confronti gli uni verso gli altri, (iv) non utilizzarono i dati a propria disposizione per avanzare ipotesi.\n\nDall’altra c’è la visione, tra gli altri proposta da Popper, secondo cui le loro opere hanno preparato la strada alla ricerca scientifica come la intendiamo, e che anzi hanno fatto il meglio che potessero fare con i mezzi a loro disposizione: Popper parla in particolare di Anassimandro, che arrivò alla sua idea criticando la teoria di Talete, utilizzando argomenti speculativi , propri della filosofia, per affermare che se la Terra giace sull’acqua, si sarebbe dovuto spiegare su cosa poggia l’acqua, e così via; e giudicando inaccettabile queste infinite spiegazioni, ne propose una nuova, che è interessante in quanto sembra preparare al concetto di azione a distanza, con la sua descrizione della Terra ferma perché ugualmente \"attratta\" da tutto contemporaneamente. E poco importa se poi sempre Anassimandro afferma che la Terra è piatta: ciò è dovuto ad argomenti osservativi , propri della scienza, e altrettanto importanti di quelli speculativi.\n\nCerto, Talete e gli altri due filosofi erano in errore nelle loro idee, ma la loro importanza, dice Coleman20, non risiede nei modelli che hanno proposto, piuttosto nel fatto che hanno iniziato, migliorando ognuno il modello del precedente, a \"stabilire una lunga catena di interpretazione progressivamente [sempre più] corrette di scoperte scientifiche\".\n\nInfine, la terza via unisce le due precedenti, e presentando i tre filosofi come coloro che hanno permesso alla scienza come indagine naturalistica e non più mitica di nascere, ma che non sono riusciti ad attenersi ai dettami che la scienza moderna considera necessari per definire scienza l’indagine speculativa e osservativa.\n\nTutto ciò non è una colpa che possiamo attribuire ai tre filosofi, che possiamo ben definire - per la nostra accezione dei termini - pertanto, se non Astronomi, Cosmologi, Fisici, perlomeno indagatori della Natura a pieno titolo.\n\nNon bisogna però pensare che le loro indagini fossero omogenee, uniformi, direzionate da un’idea specifica: il solo concetto di principio, ad esempio. non è proprio del VI secolo BCE, ma viene collegato a posteriori da Aristotele ricercandolo nei filosofi a lui precedenti.\n\nLa ricerca delle cause dei movimenti nel cielo e dell’origine del mondo procede ancora come ricerca di singoli individui: che dibattono l’uno le idee dell’altro - senza scalfire le teorie nel loro nucleo, ma che non appartengono a una scuola. Non ancora.\n\nNel prossimo episodio: il problema del cambiamento\n\nArticoli della serie:\n\nBibliografia:\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe, di Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, raccolta di saggi ad opera di C. Blacker e M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nGreek Cosmologies, di G.E.R. Lloyd\n\nAristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus, di T. Heath(Oxford 1913)\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, di Kirk G.S. e Raven J.E. (Cambridge 1957)\n\nEarly Greek Philosophy and the Orient, di M.L. West (Oxford 1971)\n\nPhilosophy before Socrates, di R.D. McKirahan (Hackett 1994)\n\nEarly Greek Science, di G.E.R. Lloyd (Chatto & Windus 1970)\n\nA history of astronomy from Thales to Kepler, di J.L.E Dreyer (Dover 1953)\n\nHeaven And Earth In Ancient Greek Cosmology, di D.L. Cuprie (Springer 2011)\n\nEarly Greek Cosmology: A Historiographical Review, di N.S. Hetherington\n\nBack to the Pre-Socratics: The Presidential Address, di K.R. Popper (1958)\n\nEarly Greek astronomy to Aristotle, di D.R. Dicks (Cornell University Press 1970)\n\nHistory of Philosophy Volume I: From the Beginning to Plato, raccolta di C.C.W. Taylor (Routledge 1997)\n\nThe Ionians, di Malcolm Schofield\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, di Jonathan Barnes (Routledge 1979)\n\nA Source Book In Greek Science di M.R. Cohen e I.E. Drabkin (Harvard University Press 1945)\n\nThe Physical World of the Greeks, di S. Sambursky (The Macmillan Company 1956)\n\nQuesta newsletter è una di tre: le altre due sono Last Scattering Surface, e Space of Sound. Tutte le pubblicazioni sono gratuite e puoi consultare tutti gli articoli senza paywall. Se vuoi, puoi iscriverti qui e qui.\n\nInfine, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n\nCiao e a presto!\n\nNote\n\n1 Diogene Laerzio, Vite dei filosofi.\n\n2 Jonathan Barnes, The Presocratic Philosophers.\n\n3 Simplicio, Commentario alla fisica di Aristotele.\n\n4 Anche Simplicio cita Teofrasto nel Commento alla Fisica di Aristotele, e anche Ermia di Alessandria, Pseudo-Plutarco e Aezio concordano sull’idea di indefinito di Simplicio.\n\n5 Arthur Koestler, Sleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe.\n\n6 Ippolito, Refutationes.\n\n7 Pseudo-Plutarco, Stromata.\n\n8 Ippolito, Refutationes.\n\n9 Pseudo-Plutarco, Stromata.\n\n10 McKirahan, Philosophy before Socrates\n\n11 Diogene Laerzio, Vite dei filosofi.\n\n12 Parleremo anche di lui.\n\n13 L’acme di un filosofo veniva posto generalmente intorno al suo quarantesimo anno di età.\n\n14 Ippolito, Refutationes.\n\n15 Pseudo-Plutarco, Stromata.\n\n16 Aristotele, De Cælo.\n\n17 Aristotele, Meteorologica.\n\n18 Aristotele, Meteorologica\n\n19 N.S. Hetherington, Early Greek Cosmology: A Historiographical Review.\n\n20 Coleman, Early Theories of the Universe\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_015-thales-and-the-water.md": "# Thales and the water\n\nDisclaimer #1: questo articolo è in inglese, la versione in italiano si può leggere qui.\n\nDisclaimer #2: this episode is part of a series named “ on the motion of the Earth ”, published both on this publication, Heralding Time , and on Last Scattering Surface . If you want, you can follow them both. Here chapters I, II, III, IV.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!fJl6!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9447bdf5-5146-49cc-863c-37be72347cbb_1080x1350.png)\n\nWelcome back.\n\nIn previous episodes, ancient skies full of gods appeared, rivers and mountains in Egypt and Babylon, upturned bowls and sacred texts in China, India and Scandinavia.\n\nHaving returned to Asia Minor, we have traveled the border between mythology and cosmology in Greece. Having left behind a blind poet, a narrator of the birth of the gods, and a syncretic proto-philosopher, it is time to talk about the first philosophers who appeared in Greece, and the worlds they described and the place of the Earth in them.\n\nToo many questions?\n\nBefore setting off, let’s try to clarify the reason for the title of this series: why, to understand what the answers have been to an apparently technical question like “what is the motion of the Earth?”, have we talked about a bronze age artifact , divinities and sacred texts, to arrive in Greece to talk about philosophy?\n\nBecause the Greek philosophers are the first to try to answer this question in a way similar to how we do, posing questions valid in every time, and they respond by questioning Nature, no longer the gods. The two interpretations of the world can indeed coexist - not all philosophers reject the concept of the existence of gods, obviously - but philosophy in Greece proceeds in the direction of “filling the gaps” of inexplicable natural events with logical, rational explanations, even if not necessarily “scientific”: the concept of scientific experiment as we understand it today is not born in the classical Greek world, but in some cases one can glimpse an attitude that we could define as “replicable” or “quantifiable”.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!umwW!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b2809861-0dd4-4bd5-bf9a-80cbab7a22a9_800x780.jpeg)\n\nLight Flowing Forth from the Blackness. Picture taken from Public Domain Image Archive / Internet Archive / The Getty.\n\nThe questions that the Greek philosophers ask themselves, from Miletus to Athens, from Croton to Samos, concern the world, now conceived as a unity , autonomous unto itself; the material constitution of the world itself, continuous unity or formed by discrete elements; its birth or creation as the product of an accident , a design or a necessity ; the possibility that its Creator is a transcendent or immanent figure; its duration, whether finite or endless ; the number of worlds, one or innumerable , and in this case whether contemporary or successive to one another.\n\nThese and other questions bounce from island to island, from city to city, transported by the lives of these thinkers, and by the concept common to all of them, that ideas are discussed and do not constitute dogma .\n\nArthur Koestler, whom we have already encountered in previous episodes, speaks of the 6th century BCE as a period in which humanity awakened and began to seek answers to the questions we still ask ourselves today: he speaks of figures like Buddha, Confucius, Lao-Tze, and then of Ionian philosophers and Pythagoreans.\n\nThe first three are mystical, religious figures, of authority and not men of science, however wise and fundamental in morality and philosophy.\n\nWe will now speak of the philosophers of Miletus - the Ionians of whom Koestler speaks, the philosophers of Nature, starting with Thales.\n\nBut first, let’s talk about Miletus.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!pHvn!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2bf887d5-e02f-47ac-96e7-b720c71091e7_1240x1126.png)\n\nMiletus\n\nThe polis of Miletus exists, at the time of the philosophers we will discuss in this episode, for more than 300 years. Like other cities of the Aegean Sea islands, it was founded after the collapse of the Mycenaean civilization of the bronze age.\n\nStarting from the dall’VIII century BCE these cities create colonies in Southern Italy, to the west, and on the coasts of the Black Sea, to the north. Especially in this way, and with the settlements in Asia Minor, the citizens of the poleis come into contact with other populations, coming from Mesopotamia, or from Egypt, or from Asia Minor itself.\n\nMiletus is governed by aristocratic men not belonging to any religious cult; religion is kept separate from political life, despite both being public activities. Moreover, although the poems of Homer and Hesiod are a common heritage of all Greek cities, the absence of a single and hereditary caste of priestly class (as happens in Egypt for millennia) does not facilitate the creation of a dogma common to all of Greece, to be followed and from which not to deviate. Each city enjoys its own albeit not total autonomy. To put it with McKirahan1, there is no Bible in the Greek world.\n\nIt is in this polis, in this cultural, mercantile, political, religious environment, that the three philosophers of this episode live, in which they expound their own visions of the world, of its birth and its nature.\n\nThales\n\nRemember Pherecydes, the proto-philosopher from the previous episode? It was said of him that he had secret knowledge learned from the Phoenicians.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!jWfE!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/17c883eb-7b2d-4eb6-8bcb-3da0c9adb759_2700x3768.jpeg)\n\nThalész by Büky Béla - 1963 - Rippl-Rónai Municipal Museum con County Scope - Kaposvár, Hungary - CC BY.\n\nAlso for Thales it is told2 that he had a possible descent from this people: perhaps not on his mother Cleobulina’s side - which seems to be a Greek name, but his father, Examyes, is said to be from a Phoenician family. More likely that his family was originally from Cadmea, a city of Boeotia (mainland Greece) who moved to Boeotia (a region of Asia Minor). In any case, whether he was actually of Phoenician lineage, or whether this belonging was imposed on him later, the link between Greek science and technology and the Phoenicians does not end with the mythical period.\n\nThales was born around 624 BCE, in his city he is a man of government and an “engineer”: various stories are told about him, to represent him in often opposite ways; all tell us something about him as a philosopher.\n\nIn a dialogue by Plato3 it is reported that a slave from Thrace tells of when Thales ended up in a well, because he was more engaged in observing the sky than in realising what was happening under his feet. Another tale speaks of when he managed to foresee that he would profit from the yield of oil and bought many olive groves of the time at low prices, drawing great profit from it.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!qmHG!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9260683f-0e09-4c7c-b116-7039e2decf18_591x800.jpeg)\n\nNovember Meteors, by Étienne Léopold Trouvelot, 1882 . Picture taken from Public Domain Image Archive / New York Public Library.\n\nBoth of these stories speak of practical consequences of Thales’ “philosophical” life: even if probably legendary, the first tells of the “philosopher in the clouds,” far from common life; the second of a man who with his studies and calculations could have drawn enormous riches. On this point, Aristotle explains that Thales was not attracted to it, despite being more than well-off - after all, he was a member of the city aristocracy - since it is not in his interest to enrich himself thanks to his ingenuity.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!DZB1!,w_56,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ec711e97-0367-4221-a708-51af6c518dff_1280x1280.png)\n\nLast Scattering Surface\n\nAnnals of LSS: why is dark at night? E.A.Poe and Olbers's Paradox The darkness of the sky looks natural. The Sunsets is at the horizon, maybe there is a new moon and you are left with the light of stars (and light pollution, unfortunately…\n\nRead more\n\n3 years ago · 3 likes\n\nRegarding his philosophical activity, his travels to Egypt are recounted. This is not hard to believe, since during this period Miletus has some colonies in those areas, including Naucratis4. According to Diogenes Laertius, who cites Eudemus, Thales wrote “ On the Solstice ” and “ On the Equinox ” - texts we do not have. As will also happen with others among the philosophers we will discuss, their theories are known exclusively through secondhand or thirdhand accounts, with all the imprecisions and modifications to the original thought that this entails.\n\nHerodotus reports that Thales is famous for being the first in Greece to predict a solar eclipse, between 585 and 584 BCE, the period in which his acme is placed, that is, the highest point of his philosophical activity. This is debatable, and it is even more so if one imagines that he predicted the exact day5.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!YGsF!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/46ad5b86-68e6-431a-bf9c-bba26310ba92_1005x1200.jpeg)\n\nEclipse Diagram, from Illustrated Astronomy di Asa Smith, 1849. Picture taken from Public Domain Image Archive / Smithsonian Libraries and Archives.\n\nThales is the one who brought abstract geometry to Greece , affirms A. Koestler6. From where? From Egypt and Mesopotamia. Precisely in Mesopotamia it is at least since 721 BCE that solstices and lunations are recorded7, from which one can calculate approximately when an eclipse will occur8; it is not strange for a scholar of that era in Greece to visit the city of Sardis, in Asia Minor, which the Hittites called Uda, thus contacts with Babylonian civilisation are achievable. This is recorded in a similar way also by Theon of Smyrna, who reports Thales’ knowledge of the different duration that the different seasons have during the course of the year.\n\nFor Thales, solar eclipses occur when the Sun is covered by the Moon; similarly, when the Earth is between the Moon and the Sun, lunar eclipses occur.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!u_J7!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/931d02be-b0cd-42d1-81ac-28a5d4406fdb_586x799.jpeg)\n\nPartial Eclipse of the Moon, by Étienne Léopold Trouvelot, 1882 . Picture taken from Public Domain Image Archive / New York Public Library.\n\nThales knows when the solstices will occur: this seems feasible, with a suitable instrument, the gnomon, of Babylonian derivation and which Eudemus recounts allowed the philosopher to measure the height of the pyramids, using the principle of proportions between the length of the shadow of an object and that of the pyramid at the same hour of the day, with the actual measurements of that object and the pyramid.\n\nAccording to Callimachus9, Thales observes Ursa Minor starting from Ursa Major, as the Phoenicians do, and advises Greek sailors to use this method to orient themselves and find north10.\n\nThe study of Babylonian tables to predict upcoming eclipses; the measurement of the days that pass between a solstice and the following equinox; the study of the positions of stars in asterisms and constellations: all these things compose the study of ἀστρονομία, astronomy.\n\nThales goes further, and constructs a cosmological model. We know its (few) details from the works in which it is described (and criticised) by Aristotle: the “De cælo” and the “Metaphysics.” Aristotle attributes to Thales the phrase “all things are full of gods,” McKirahan speaks of a Thales with a Janus face, dual. The Thales of whom Aristotle speaks describes a world in which the things that happen are the work of Nature: the Earth floats on water, and the principle of all things is water.\n\nThe first conception is probably of Egyptian and Babylonian derivation. The second is an interpretation by Aristotle, who connects the concept of ἀρχή, the first principle, to water for Thales as an answer to the question: what is the principle of all things? The questions seem to be two in reality, namely: what generates all things ? and where do all things come from ?\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!EsVz!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6858b4e6-14d9-4057-b1ab-551fd4bf97da_2448x1992.jpeg)\n\nWater, by Maerten de Vos, Adriaen Collaert, 1580-1584 . Picture taken from Public Domain Image Archive / Rijksmuseum.\n\nThe answer therefore for Thales is water, understood not only as the liquid we drink or that flows in a river or that forms the sea, but as a fluid that generates life: it is connected to rain, to semen, to bodily fluids and to everything that flows. Here Thales evokes the Babylonian tradition of water as generating power, and the Egyptian one of creative water. But in Thales there is nothing magical or religious: water is part of the Nature from which everything comes. It is the origin of everything, but it has an origin that is part of this world and that we can observe.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Rn5U!,w_56,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a9daf835-0536-4732-a0bc-8750f2ae2ae7_1280x1280.png)\n\nSpace of Sound\n\nsingle space: About Today, by The National I said I would be back in September: a promise is a promise. But I didn’t sit idly by…\n\nRead more\n\n6 months ago · 2 likes · Antonio Viscusi\n\nHow is the world formed starting from water? Thales does not say, and we do not know his cosmogony, but we know that the Sun and Moon are made of the same substance that composes the Earth, having detached from it after creation. The Earth is a cylindrical disk, perhaps a bit concave - this vision would be consistent with the Babylonian vision of the world according to which the Earth is surrounded by mountains, before being surrounded by Okeanos - which rests on water.\n\nIt is stationary in the Universe, and the Sun, Moon and stars perform their motions around it, and when they are no longer visible beyond the horizon they circle around the Earth to return to rise in the east. The light of the Moon is the reflection of the light that arrives from the Sun, and air is formed from the evaporation of water.\n\nThales shares the vision not only of Babylon and Egypt, but also that of Homer and Hesiod, who tell of a flat Earth that rests on water.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!3Ta-!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f10eeaf8-b914-441b-be07-5ab10d572f53_1200x938.jpeg)\n\nUniverse with Earth, Sun, Moon, and Stars, by Caspar Luyken, 1712. Picture taken from Public Domain Image Archive / Rijksmuseum.\n\nUnlike them, and this is why we define him a philosopher , he wonders what lies beyond , seeks explanations in Nature and not in myths, tries to imagine causes . He does this for example with earthquakes, whose cause he attributes to the movement of the water that supports the Earth. This is a surprising novelty: Thales attempts to explain an observable event by resorting to a non-observable hypothesis , but consistent with his vision of the world. What is missing to complete the requirements of the scientific method? The experiment to be performed to verify the hypothesis - which in any case would have refuted the hypothesis11.\n\nThales searches for the raw material that composes the world. That he was wrong in identifying it is not important, for the journey we have undertaken.\n\nIn the next episode: the other Milesians philosophers.\n\nRead the other episodes:\n\nBibliography:\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe, by Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, edited by C. Blacker and M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nGreek Cosmologies, by G.E.R. Lloyd\n\nAristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus, by Heath T. (Oxford 1913)\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, by Kirk G.S. and Raven J.E. (Cambridge 1957)\n\nEarly Greek Philosophy and the Orient, by West M.L. (Oxford 1971)\n\nPhilosophy before Socrates, by McKirahan R.D. (Hackett 1994)\n\nEarly Greek Science, by G.E.R. Lloyd (Chatto & Windus 1970)\n\nA history of astronomy from Thales to Kepler, by J.L.E Dreyer (Dover 1953)\n\nNotes\n\n1 McKirahan R.D., Philosophy before Socrates, pg. 21\n\n2 Herodotus, histories, I.\n\n3 Plato, Theaetetus , 174.\n\n4 Ætius, Proclus, Plutarch. Plutarch underlines that water plays an important role in Egyptian mythology.\n\n5 Theon of Smyrne, Diogenes Laertius (quoting Eudemus) and Clemens of Alexandria, reporting this episode. Martin, in Revue Archéologique, underlines that it looks then Thales discovered rather than predict, the solar eclipse.\n\n6 A. Koestler, Sleepwalkers: : A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe\n\n7 “synodic” month, which is the period of time the Moon takes to complete a cycle of its phases. It lasts about 29 days, 12 hours and 44 minutes.\n\n8 Diogenes Laertius, quoting Eudemus.\n\n9 Diogenes Laertius, quoting Callimachus.\n\n10 Eudemus quotes another book, “Nautical star guide”.\n\n11 Or maybe not completely? Today we know that earthquakes are mainly caused by the movements of tectonic plates, but there also are earthquakes caused by magma flowing - like water!\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_016-talete-e-l-acqua.md": "# Talete e l'acqua\n\nDisclaimer #1: this article is in Italian. I will publish the English version next Wednesday.\n\nDisclaimer #2: questo pezzo fa parte di una serie, pubblicata sia su questa newsletter, Heralding Time , che su Last Scattering Surface . Se vuoi, puoi seguirle entrambe. Qui i capitoli I, II, III, IV.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!4sl4!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f03118ee-9d19-45b4-a07a-861ad782a875_1080x1350.png)\n\nBentornati.\n\nNei precedenti episodi sono comparsi antichi cieli pieni di dei, fiumi e montagne in Egitto e Babilonia, ciotole rovesciate e testi sacri in Cina, India e in Scandinavia.\n\nTornati in Asia Minore, abbiamo percorso il confine tra mitologia e cosmologia in Grecia. Abbandonati un poeta cieco, un narratore della nascita degli dei, e un sincretico proto-filosofo, è il momento di parlare dei primi filosofi comparsi in Grecia, e dei mondi che hanno descritto e del posto della Terra in essi.\n\nTroppe domande?\n\nPrima di partire, cerchiamo di chiarire il motivo del titolo di questa serie: perché, per capire quali sono state le risposte a una domanda apparentemente tecnica come “qual è il moto della Terra?”, abbiamo parlato di un reperto dell’età del bronzo, di divinità e testi sacri, per arrivare in Grecia a parlare di filosofia?\n\nPerché i filosofi greci sono i primi a cercare di rispondere a questa domanda in modo simile a come facciamo noi, ponendo domande valide in ogni tempo, e rispondono interpellando la Natura, non più gli dei. Le due interpretazioni del mondo possono sì coesistere - non tutti i filosofi rifiutano il concetto dell’esistenza degli dei, ovviamente - ma la filosofia in Grecia procede nella direzione di “riempire i buchi” degli eventi naturali inspiegabili con spiegazioni logiche, razionali, anche se non necessariamente “scientifiche”: il concetto di esperimento scientifico come lo intendiamo oggi non nasce nel mondo greco classico, ma in alcuni casi si può intravedere un atteggiamento che potremmo definire “replicabile” o “quantificabile”.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!umwW!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b2809861-0dd4-4bd5-bf9a-80cbab7a22a9_800x780.jpeg)\n\nLight Flowing Forth from the Blackness. Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / Internet Archive / The Getty.\n\nLe domande che i filosofi greci si pongono, da Mileto ad Atene, da Crotone a Samo, riguardano il mondo, concepito ora come unità, autonoma a sé stessa ; la costituzione materiale del mondo stesso, unità continua o formata da elementi discreti ; la sua nascita o creazione come prodotto di un accidente , di un disegno o di una necessità ; l’eventualità che il suo Creatore sia una figura trascendente o immanente ; la sua durata, se finita o senza fine ; il numero dei mondi, uno o innumerevoli , e in questo caso se contemporanei o successivi l’uno all’altro.\n\nQueste e altre domande rimbalzano da isola a isola, di città in città, trasportate dalla vita di questi pensatori, e dal concetto comune a tutti loro, che le idee si discutono e non costituiscono dogma .\n\nArthur Koestler, che abbiamo già incontrato nei precedenti episodi, parla del VI secolo BCE come di un periodo in cui l’umanità si è destata e ha iniziato a cercare le risposte alle domande che ancora oggi ci poniamo: parla di figure come Buddha, Confucio, Lao-Tze, e poi di filosofi Ionici e di Pitagorici.\n\nI primi tre sono figure mistiche, religiose, di autorità e non uomini di scienza, per quanto saggi e fondamentali nella morale e nella filosofia.\n\nNoi parleremo ora dei filosofi di Mileto - gli Ioniani di cui parla Koestler, i filosofi della Natura, partendo da Talete.\n\nMa prima, parliamo di Mileto.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!pHvn!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2bf887d5-e02f-47ac-96e7-b720c71091e7_1240x1126.png)\n\nMileto\n\nLa polis di Mileto esiste, ai tempi dei filosofi di cui parleremo in questo episodio, da più di 300 anni. Come altre città delle isole del Mar Egeo, venne fondata dopo il collasso della civiltà Micenea dell’età del bronzo.\n\nA partire dall’VIII secolo BCE queste città creano colonie nell’Italia del Sud, a ovest, e sulle coste del Mar Nero, a nord. Soprattutto in questo modo, e con gli insediamenti in Asia Minore, i cittadini delle polis entrano in contatto con altre popolazioni, provenienti dalla Mesopotamia, o dall’Egitto, o proprio dall’Asia Minore.\n\nMileto è governata da aristocratici uomini non appartenenti a nessun culto religioso; la religione è tenuta separata dalla vita politica, nonostante entrambe siano attività pubbliche. Inoltre, benché i poemi di Omero e di Esiodo siano una eredità comune a tutte le città greche, l’assenza di una casta unica e ereditaria di classe sacerdotale (come accade in Egitto da millenni) non facilita la creazione di un dogma comune a tutta la Grecia, da seguire e da cui non allontanarsi. Ogni città gode di una sua seppur non totale autonomia. Per dirla con McKirahan1, non c’è una Bibbia nel mondo greco.\n\nE’ in questa polis, in questo ambiente culturale, mercantile, politico, religioso, che i tre filosofi di questo episodio vivono, in cui espongono le proprie visioni del mondo, della sua nascita e della sua natura.\n\nTalete\n\nRicordate Ferecide, il proto-filosofo dell’episodio precedente? Di lui si diceva che avesse conoscenze segrete apprese dai Fenici.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!jWfE!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/17c883eb-7b2d-4eb6-8bcb-3da0c9adb759_2700x3768.jpeg)\n\nThalész di Büky Béla - 1963 - Rippl-Rónai Municipal Museum con County Scope - Kaposvár, Hungary - CC BY.\n\nAnche per Talete si racconta2 di una sua possibile discendenza da questo popolo: forse non da parte della madre Cleobulina - che sembra essere un nome greco, ma il padre, Essamio, si racconta essere di una famiglia fenicia. Più probabile che la sua famiglia fosse originaria di Cadmea, una città della Beozia (Grecia continentale) trasferitisi in Beozia (una regione dell’Asia Minore). Ad ogni modo, che fosse effettivamente di stirpe fenicia, o che questa appartenenza gli sia stata imposta successivamente, il legame della scienza e della tecnica greca con i Fenici non termina con il periodo mitico.\n\nTalete nasce intorno al 624 BCE, nella sua città è un uomo di governo e un “ingegnere”: si raccontano diverse storie su di lui, per rappresentarlo in modi spesso opposti; tutti ci dicono qualcosa su di lui come filosofo.\n\nIn un dialogo di Platone3 si riporta che una schiava proveniente dalla Tracia racconta di quando Talete è finito in un pozzo, poiché più impegnato ad osservare il cielo che a rendersi conto di quello che succedeva sotto i suoi piedi. Un altro racconto parla di quando è riuscito a prevedere che avrebbe avuto profitto dalla resa dell’olio e acquistò molti oliveti del tempo a prezzi bassi, traendone grande profitto.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!qmHG!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9260683f-0e09-4c7c-b116-7039e2decf18_591x800.jpeg)\n\nLe Meteore di Novembre, opera di Étienne Léopold Trouvelot, 1882 . Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / New York Public Library.\n\nEntrambe queste storie parlano di conseguenze pratiche della vita “filosofica” di Talete: anche se probabilmente leggendarie, la prima racconta del “filosofo sulle nuvole”, lontano dalla vita comune; la seconda di un uomo che con i suoi studi e i suoi calcoli avrebbe potuto trarre enormi ricchezze. Su questo punto, Aristotele spiega che Talete non ne era attratto, nonostante fosse più che benestante - dopotutto, era un membro dell’aristocrazia cittadina - poiché non è nel suo interesse arricchirsi grazie al suo ingegno.\n\nRiguardo la sua attività filosofica, si racconta dei suoi viaggi in Egitto. Questo non è difficile a credersi, poiché in questo periodo Mileto ha alcune colonie in quelle zone, tra cui Naucrati4. Secondo Diogene Laerzio, che cita Eudemo, Talete ha scritto “ Sul solstizio ” e “ Sull’equinozio ” - testi che non abbiamo. Come avverrà anche per altri tra i filosofi di cui parleremo, le loro teorie sono conosciute esclusivamente attraverso resoconti di seconda o terza mano, con tutte le imprecisioni e le modifiche al pensiero originale che ciò comporta.\n\nErodoto riporta che Talete è famoso per essere stato il primo in Grecia a predire una eclisse solare, tra il 585 e il 584 BCE, periodo in cui è posto il suo acme , ovvero il punto più alto della sua attività filosofica. Ciò è discutibile, e lo è ancora di più se si immagina che abbia predetto il giorno esatto5.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!YGsF!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/46ad5b86-68e6-431a-bf9c-bba26310ba92_1005x1200.jpeg)\n\nDiagramma di un eclisse, da Illustrated Astronomy di Asa Smith, 1849. Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / Smithsonian Libraries and Archives.\n\nTalete è colui che porta la geometria astratta in Grecia , afferma A. Koestler6. Da dove? Dall’Egitto e dalla Mesopotamia. Proprio in Mesopotamia è almeno dal 721 BCE che si registrano i solstizi e le lunazioni7, da cui si può calcolare quando avverrà all’incirca una eclisse8; non è strano per un sapiente di quell’epoca in Grecia visitare la città di Sardi, in Asia Minore, che gli Ittiti chiamavano Uda, dunque i contatti con la civiltà babilonese sono realizzabili. Questo è registrato in modo simile anche da Teone di Smirne, che riporta la conoscenza da parte di Talete della durata diversa che le diverse stagioni hanno nel corso dell’anno.\n\nPer Talete, le eclissi solari avvengono quando il Sole è coperto dalla Luna; in modo analogo, quando la Terra è tra la Luna e il Sole, avvengono le eclissi lunari.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!u_J7!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/931d02be-b0cd-42d1-81ac-28a5d4406fdb_586x799.jpeg)\n\nEclisse parziale di Luna, opera di Étienne Léopold Trouvelot, 1882 . Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / New York Public Library.\n\nTalete conosce quando avverranno i solstizi: ciò sembra fattibile, con uno strumento adatto, lo gnomone, di derivazione babilonese e che Eudemo racconta abbia permesso al filosofo di misurare l’altezza delle piramidi, utilizzando il principio delle proporzioni tra la lunghezza dell’ombra di un oggetto e di quella della piramide alla stessa ora del giorno, con le misure reali di quell’oggetto e della piramide.\n\nSecondo Callimaco9, Talete osserva l’Orsa Minore partendo dall’Orsa Maggiore, come fanno i Fenici, e consiglia ai naviganti greci di utilizzare questo metodo per orientarsi e trovare il nord10.\n\nLo studio delle tavole babilonesi per predire le prossime eclissi; la misurazione dei giorni che passano tra un solstizio e l’equinozio successivo; lo studio delle posizioni delle stelle negli asterismi e nelle costellazioni: tutte queste cose compongono lo studio della ἀστρονομία, l’astronomia.\n\nTalete va oltre, e costruisce un modello cosmologico. Ne conosciamo i (pochi) dettagli dalle opere in cui è descritto (e criticato) da Aristotele: il “ De cælo ” e la “ Metafisica ”. Aristotele attribuisce a Talete la frase “ tutte le cose sono piene di dei ”, McKirahan parla di un Talete dal volto gianico , duale. Il Talete di cui parla Aristotele descrive un mondo in cui le cose che accadono sono opera della Natura: la Terra galleggia sull’acqua, e il principio di tutte le cose è l’acqua.\n\nLa prima concezione è di derivazione egiziana e babilonese, probabilmente. La seconda è una interpretazione di Aristotele, che collega il concetto di ἀρχή, il principio primo, all’acqua per Talete come risposta alla domanda: qual è il principio di ogni cosa? Le domande sembrano essere due in realtà, ovvero: cosa genera tutte le cose ? e da dove arrivano tutte le cose?\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!EsVz!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6858b4e6-14d9-4057-b1ab-551fd4bf97da_2448x1992.jpeg)\n\nAcqua, opera di Maerten de Vos, Adriaen Collaert, 1580-1584 . Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / Rijksmuseum.\n\nLa risposta quindi per Talete è l’acqua, intesa non solo come il liquido che beviamo o che scorre in un fiume o che forma il mare, ma come un fluido che genera vita: è collegato alla pioggia, allo sperma, ai fluidi corporei e a tutto quello che fluisce. Qui Talete evoca la tradizione babilonese dell’acqua come potenza generatrice, e quella egiziana dell’acqua creatrice. Ma in Talete non c’è nulla di magico o religioso: l’acqua è parte della Natura da cui arriva tutto. E’ l’origine di tutto, ma ha una origine che fa parte di questo mondo e che possiamo osservare.\n\nCome si forma il mondo a partire dall’acqua? Talete non lo dice, e non conosciamo la sua cosmogonia, ma sappiamo che il Sole e la Luna sono fatti della stessa sostanza che compone la Terra, staccatesi da essa dopo la creazione. La Terra è un disco cilindrico, forse un po’ concavo - questa visione sarebbe coerente con la visione babilonese del mondo secondo cui la Terra è circondata da montagne, prima di essere circondata da Okeanos - il quale poggia sull’acqua.\n\nE’ ferma nell’Universo, e il Sole, la Luna e le stelle compiono i loro moti intorno a essa, e quando non sono più visibili oltre l’orizzonte girano intorno alla Terra per tornare a sorgere a oriente. La luce della Luna è il riflesso della luce che arriva dal Sole, e l’aria si forma dall’evaporazione dell’acqua.\n\nTalete condivide la visione non solo di Babilonia e dell’Egitto, ma anche quella di Omero e Esiodo, che raccontano di una Terra piatta che riposa sull’acqua.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!3Ta-!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f10eeaf8-b914-441b-be07-5ab10d572f53_1200x938.jpeg)\n\nUniverso con la Terra, il Sole, la Luna, e le stelle, opera di Caspar Luyken, 1712. Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / Rijksmuseum.\n\nA differenza loro, ed è il motivo per cui lo definiamo filosofo , si domanda cosa ci sia oltre , cerca spiegazioni nella Natura e non nei miti, prova a immaginare delle cause . Lo fa ad esempio con i terremoti, la cui causa attribuisce al movimento dell’acqua che sostiene la Terra.\n\nQuesta è una sorprendente novità: Talete tenta di spiegare un evento osservabile facendo ricorso a una ipotesi non osservabile , ma coerente con la sua visione del mondo. Cosa manca per soddisfare i requisiti del metodo scientifico? L’esperimento da compiere per verificare l’ipotesi - che comunque avrebbe confutato l’ipotesi11.\n\nTalete cerca il materiale grezzo che compone il mondo. Che abbia sbagliato a individuarlo non è importante, per il percorso che abbiamo intrapreso.\n\nNel prossimo episodio: gli altri filosofi di Mileto.\n\nArticoli della serie:\n\nBibliografia:\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe, di Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, raccolta di saggi ad opera di C. Blacker e M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nGreek Cosmologies, di G.E.R. Lloyd\n\nAristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus, di Heath T. (Oxford 1913)\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, di Kirk G.S. e Raven J.E. (Cambridge 1957)\n\nEarly Greek Philosophy and the Orient, di West M.L. (Oxford 1971)\n\nPhilosophy before Socrates, di McKirahan R.D. (Hackett 1994)\n\nEarly Greek Science, di G.E.R. Lloyd (Chatto & Windus 1970)\n\nA history of astronomy from Thales to Kepler, di J.L.E Dreyer (Dover 1953)\n\nQuesta newsletter è una di tre: le altre due sono Last Scattering Surface, e Space of Sound. Tutte le pubblicazioni sono gratuite e puoi consultare tutti gli articoli senza paywall. Se vuoi, puoi iscriverti qui e qui.\n\nInfine, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n\nCiao e a presto!\n\nNote\n\n1 McKirahan R.D., Philosophy before Socrates, pg. 21\n\n2 Erodoto, storie, I.\n\n3 Platone, Teeteto, 174.\n\n4 Aezio, Proclo, Plutarco. Plutarco inoltre sottolinea che l’acqua ha un ruolo importante nella mitologia egizia.\n\n5 Teone di Smirne, Diogene Laerzio (citando Eudemo) e Clemente di Alessandria, citano questo episodio. Martin, in Revue Archéologique, sottolinea che sembra quindi che Talete l’abbia scoperta, più che predetta, l’eclissi solare.\n\n6 A. Koestler, Sleepwalkers: : A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe\n\n7 mese “sinodico”, è il periodo di tempo che la Luna impiega per compiere un ciclo complete delle sue fasi. Dura all’incirca 29 giorni, 12 ore e 44 minuti.\n\n8 Diogene Laerzio, citando Eudemo.\n\n9 Diogene Laerzio, citando Callimaco.\n\n10 Eudemo cita un altro libro, una “Guida stellare ai naviganti”.\n\n11 O forse non del tutto? Oggi sappiamo che i terremoti sono causati in larga parte dai movimenti delle placche tettoniche, ma ci sono terremoti causati dal moto del magma che scorre - come l’acqua, quindi!\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_017-homer-hesiod-and-a-proto-philosopher.md": "# Homer, Hesiod, and a proto-philosopher\n\nDisclaimer #1: questo articolo è in inglese, la versione in italiano si può leggere qui.\n\nDisclaimer #2: this episode is part of a series named “ on the motion of the Earth ”, published both on this publication, Heralding Time , and on Last Scattering Surface . If you want, you can follow them both. The first chapter is here. The second is here. The third here.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Dz4U!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d0639ebc-5e82-428a-916b-7e75cda03681_1080x1350.png)\n\nIn previous episodes we talked about the first conception of the sky among ancient peoples, the cosmologies of the Egyptians, the Babylonians, of Judaism and Islam, and those developed in China, India, and Scandinavia.\n\nStarting from this episode, we will begin a long journey in search of philosophy in Greece, and why it is connected to the theme of this series. We will see that it is precisely with cosmology that the first Greek thinkers launched the philosophical tradition in Greece.\n\nTo begin the journey into Greek philosophy, we must first cross the border that separates it from mythology. Taking a look at the map, constructing the itinerary, we see that this border is not a straight line, nor even a clear boundary: it has indentations and protrusions, enclaves and unexplored territories.\n\nThe sources of Greek mythology spring from the oral tales of Minoan and Mycenaean singers between the II and I millennium BCE: stories of men and gods, heroes and muses, wars and passions, stories about the origin of places and the origin of humanity; these sources flow throughout Greece, and into the various settlements and colonies that the Greeks founded in Asia Minor and Italy, and are collected, defined, and summarised in texts presented to the public around the VIII and VII centuries BCE. The first encounter we make following this river of myths and words is with a blind man, who is perhaps more than a man, and perhaps never existed.\n\nA blind man who perhaps never existed\n\nThe man we encounter is a blind bard who lived in Ionia in the VIII century before our era, and probably died in Ios , an island in the Cyclades in the Aegean Sea, around the middle of the following century. The man we encounter is the one to whom we attribute the two epic poems that began the Greek epic tradition, the Iliad and the Odyssey . But when questioned about how, when, and why he wrote these texts, the man vanishes.\n\nAs far as we know, Homer was never a historical figure. It is the common opinion of scholars that the two poems are not by the same author1, and that they were composed by a succession of authors and singers, who performed them publicly throughout Greece.\n\nIn any case, we can let ourselves be accompanied by the Homer of tradition, and speak of the unknown authors of the two poems as part of the figure of the legendary Homer.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!zVpO!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9c14d495-d993-4d1c-8a41-eafe7c48d208_1240x1126.png)\n\nThe Iliad and the Odyssey contain the complete set of tools necessary to know the world, its pitfalls and dangers, its possibilities and riches. Among the stories they contain, there are also myths and stories about the creation of the world, about the shape it has and the forces that govern it.\n\nHomer describes the sky as a hemisphere , a bowl turned upside down, that looms over the Earth, a flat, circular disk. Between the Earth and the sky, in the part closest to the former, there is mist , while in the upper part there is more rarefied air - ether .\n\nUnder the roots of the Earth is Tartarus, which is as far from the Earth as the Earth is from the sky, and all around the Earth is the river Okeanos , “which encircles the Earth and flows into itself”2. Okeanos is at the same time, and depending on the description, a river, a spring, an ocean, composed of fresh sweet waters, the source of all the waters of the Earth, and a salty sea. From what experience could the idea of a multiform river around the world come? Probably not from Greece, but from the traditions of the kingdoms of Egypt and Mesopotamia, which arrived in the Greek world through contacts between different populations in previous centuries.\n\nTo the west, beyond the Pillars of Hercules , located at the boundary between what we today call the Mediterranean Sea and the Atlantic Ocean, rises Erebus , the place where the souls of the dead wait to enter Tartarus.\n\nThe epic poems do not raise the question of the Earth’s motion, which is evidently stationary: this is a common experience for every member of ancient Greece. The Sun, the Moon, and the stars rise in the east, and move across the sky every day, each day falling in the west. Since they return to the east each day to rise again and again, they must somehow get back there: but Tartarus is always dark , and never illuminated by any light, so the celestial bodies cannot cross through it .\n\nIt is the task then of the river Okeanos to transport the Sun, the Moon, and the stars from west back to east, circling around the Earth. As in the Egyptian tradition, here too the celestial bodies navigate on water, after death and before being reborn.\n\nAnd which stars does Homer know, which ones can men at sea use to orient themselves? Homer knows the morning star, Phosphorus, and the evening star, Hesperus; he knows the asterism of the Pleiades, that of the Hyades and the Big Dipper, and then the constellation Orion, and the stars Sirius and Arcturus.\n\nThe celestial vault is also stationary, and the motion of the celestial bodies is a reflection of the order of the world.\n\nBright marginal note #1\n\n- an asterism is a group of stars that forms a recognisable geometric shape, and which may or may not be part of a constellation. Famous asterisms are the Summer Triangle, formed by Altair, Deneb and Vega, or the Big Dipper, part of the constellation Ursa Major.\n\n- the brightest stars (called the Seven Sisters) of the Pleiades asterism are also present on a bronze age metal plate, the Nebra Disk, discovered in Germany in 1999.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!-4T_!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/39dbd62f-a4e6-4599-9420-1ec00cd5242d_1611x1584.jpeg)\n\nNebra Disk. The circular figure on the left could be the Sun, or the full Moon. On the right, the crescent Moon. Above between the two, the seven luminous stars of the Pleiades. Credits here.\n\nHomer bids us farewell, and returns to the obscurity in which his passage on Earth and through History is shrouded.\n\nA singer of the birth of the gods\n\nAfter taking leave of the figure of Homer, the journey from myth to the physical description of the world continues with the awareness that the world is full of gods: anthropomorphic, certainly, but also allegories of human concepts and emotions. To answer the question “How are the gods born?” we approach Hesiod, a singer who lived between the VIII and VII centuries BCE, and probably originally from Cyme (Aeolian Cyme), a city in the region of Aeolia, in Asia Minor. This man, who lived in Boeotia - a region of mainland Greece - wrote three works that we can read in their entirety: “ Theogony ,” “ Works and Days ”, and “ The Shield of Heracles ”. A poem titled “On Astronomy”3 is also attributed to him, of which we read only fragments, which in any case do not inform us about what we wish to know.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!-1-v!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6f36bea8-dc21-4a50-a50d-3c68c8ea6496_1240x1126.png)\n\nWe are in fact gripped by the problem of the birth of the forces that govern the world, and of the gods who exercise those forces. We are freed by the song of Hesiod, who in the Theogony, the Birth of the Gods, recounts the beginning of the world and everything that follows.\n\nThe first thing that happened to the world, the first event, is the separation of Earth and Sky, into two distinct entities, since they were united. Therefore the first event is not the creation of something nonexistent , but the separation of something already pre-existing .\n\n[...] Verily at the first Chaos came to be, but next\n\nwide-bosomed Earth , the ever-sure foundations of all\n\nthe deathless ones who hold the peaks of snowy Olympus,\n\nand dim Tartarus in the depth of the wide-pathed Earth,\n\nand Eros , fairest among the deathless gods,\n\nwho unnerves the limbs and overcomes the mind and wise counsels of all\n\ngods and all men within them.\n\nFrom Chaos came forth Erebus and black Night ,\n\nbut of Night were born Aether and Day ,\n\nwhom she conceived and bare from union in love with Erebus .\n\nAnd Earth first bare starry Heaven , equal to herself,\n\nto cover her on every side,\n\n[...]\n\nBut afterwards she lay with Heaven and bare deep-swirling Oceanus [...]\n\nHesiod, Theogony , 116-127, 129. Hesiod, the Homeric hymns, and Homerica; with an English translation by Hugh G. Evelyn-White . Credits here.\n\nThe world pre-exists the birth of the gods, who are born as representations of the Places and States of the world: Sky, Earth, Night, Erebus (the Underworld), Ether, Day, Ocean; but also Emotions and Sensations such as Shame, Anguish, Strife, Famine, Work, Lies. Only later will the gods of Olympus arrive to dethrone Kronos, who in turn dethroned Ouranos, with the help of Gaia, consort of Ouranos, and Rhea, consort of Kronos.\n\nIn the beginning, however, there is Chaos : in the Greek tradition this term means what it also means for us, a synonym for disorder and confusion.\n\nHere, Hesiod gives the name Chaos to that which separates Sky from Earth, the first separation. The first act of the world, therefore, is the birth of Chaos understood as the action of separation, of distinction .\n\nBright marginal note #2\n\nThe conception of the distinction between Sky and Earth is present in many cultures:\n\n- for the Maori people, Rangi (the sky) and Papa (the earth) are separated;\n\n- we have seen in the Egyptian myth that Nut and Geb are separated by Shu;\n\n- the same happens in the Song of Ullikummi, a myth from Hittite-Hurrian mythology that seems to have many (subsequent) parallels in Greece;\n\n- in the Babylonian myth of the Enuma Elish, the hero-god Marduk tears Tiamat into two pieces: the sky and the earth;\n\n- Genesis: “Let there be a firmament in the midst of the waters to separate the waters from the waters.” Also due to the strong Babylonian influences on the biblical myth of the creation of the world, at a certain point the creator god of the Bible creates the firmament to separate the earth and the sky.\n\nHesiod does not speak of what existed before this separation, nor of why it occurred. The Theogony speaks of the gods, and they are the origin of order in the world, the κόσμος (cosmos). Each divinity has its own “department” to control and over which to reign; this control is not always exclusive: in some cases an event, a force, a place are contested by multiple divinities, and this creates a world that is not totally ordered .\n\nThe Theogony does not contain original or new ideas: it is a collection of stories and myths already present, which it undertakes to codify. But as will also happen with the first thinkers we call philosophers, Hesiod too firmly believes in an ordered world, in a divine presence in the world, which permeates both the physical and moral aspects of humanity.\n\nHesiod’s world is a flat, circular disk, as in Homer, and above it is the Sky, populated by the Sun, the Moon, and the stars; below it is Tartarus, never illuminated by any light. The space between sky and earth is bright by day, and dark by night. As in Homer, and as in the myths of other peoples of the Mediterranean, the celestial bodies move across the sky; after setting beyond the horizon, they navigate Ocean to return each day to the place where they will rise again, again and again.\n\nNow Hesiod departs, and the gods he sang of remain, transforming themselves.\n\nA syncretic and mysterious proto-philosopher\n\nWe have almost reached the end of the first stage, which from the territories of mythology arrives at the threshold of natural philosophy. The next character we encounter is a proto-philosopher, a man who transported ideas and influences from Asia to Greece, and who from Greece will bring ideas and influences back to Asia. With him we will cross the centuries straddling the eras, and the borders between kingdoms and peoples.\n\nApollodorus of Athens maintains that Pherecydes of Syros was a contemporary of Anaximander of Miletus, and places his floruit - the period of greatest prominence for his contemporaries - around 540 BCE; but this is not confirmed. We know that he lived in the VI century BCE, and that a legend from the IV century BCE represents him as the teacher of Pythagoras, who in his final years would have remained with him and would have buried him4. We are not certain of this, but it is true that his texts circulated in Pythagorean circles, and there are similarities between the teachings of Pythagoras and Pherecydes.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!-WHF!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1e891fe5-1cd3-484d-a112-8ee6065d96ef_1240x1076.png)\n\nUnlike the other philosophers, and adding to the strength of his legendary figure, it is said that he received no teaching from a master, but that he consulted a secret book of the Phoenicians , and the prophecy of Ham , (that is, Zoroaster). In any case, contacts with Phoenicia are evident from his father’s name, Babis or Babys , a clear name of Asian origin (probably coming from Phrygia, Pisidia or Galatia - all regions of Asia Minor).\n\nIn his work The Seven Niches , Pherecydes speaks of three divinities who have always existed: Zeus, whom he calls Zas, and whom he might - but it is not clear - associate with the Sun; Kronos, who although he has the same name as the god of Time dwells in and governs the Isles of the Blessed; and Chthonie, the goddess who represents the Earth.\n\nAfter the union between Zas and Chthonie, the Earth becomes Ge, and she is given by Zas, now also become Eros, a mantle that she wears forming the earth, but which according to a subsequent passage ends up hanging on a “ World Tree ”.\n\nBright marginal note #3\n\nThis is a story that serves two purposes: to represent the birth of the world, and to describe a human activity, the anakalyptenia , or the ritual gift from husband to bride that takes place on the third day of the wedding. Once again, the myths simultaneously represent what happens here on earth and what is hidden, and this and from this they influence and are influenced.\n\nZas and Ge produce the other gods together; Chronos does so “in union with himself”: the birth of the world or a part of it as the result of an action of this type is common in Asian myths and cosmologies, and is another piece that composes the picture of Pherecydes as syncretic between Greece and Asia. We will talk about this further on.\n\nChronos creates fire, wind, and water from his seed, and distributes them in the world, in the five nooks of the title (”The Seven Niches” is in Greek Ἑπτάμυχος, and μυχος has among other possible meanings also nook ). We do not know which places Pherecydes refers to, but they are probably the places from which the gods spring forth, the following five provinces: the sky, the Earth, Ogenos, Hades and Tartarus). The first two are obvious, while about the others we will have to speak: Ogenos is another spelling of a term we have already encountered, Okeanos. Hades and Tartarus instead are the dwelling of the dead and the place where there is no light, respectively. The evil gods defeated by Chronos, led by Ophioneus, a god whose origin can be linked to the primordial serpents of Babylonian mythologies, and who is also found in the biblical Genesis, are thrown back into the sea formed by Ogenos at the edge of the world.\n\nIn Pherecydes’ cosmology, finally, the gods live on the Moon, the Earth is inhabited and all around it has Ogenos, and beneath it is the world of the dead, which in turn looms over Tartarus.\n\nBright marginal note #4\n\nWe have spoken of Pherecydes as syncretic. Here’s why:\n\n- Eudemus of Argos connects Pherecydes to the cosmology of Sidon, a Phoenician settlement. Here in the beginning there are Chronos (time), Pothos (wind), and Omichle (darkness). In various cosmologies of Phoenician culture, the primordial wind is represented by Aither and Aer, who generate Ulōmos, which comes from the late Phoenician ‘ūlōm, ‘ōlām for the Hebrews, which means Remote Time or Eternity. From these is born an egg, from which heaven and earth are generated.\n\n- in Zoroastrian cosmology, in the beginning there is nothing but Zurvan, Time. He too generates alone , Ohrmazd, the Good, and Ahriman, the Evil. The first creates the material world, forming the egg-shaped firmament, in which everything is contained.\n\n- In the sacred Indian hymns Atharvaveda, Kala (Time) autonomously generates heaven and earth.\n\nPherecydes is a proto-philosopher, in the sense that in his work there is a principle that was missing in previous poets, and that we will encounter in those we call philosophers: the preference for prose over verse, the will to speak of the gods, even accepting their existence, only as an allegory of the forces that regulate the world; the description of the world as ordered from the beginning , without an order that arrives after the action of one or more gods.\n\nFrom now on, even the gods will have to answer the question that philosophers pose: why? Pherecydes asks it of us too, and disappears into the Time that is already Past.\n\nCrossing the border\n\nWe have crossed the plains of myth, and the paths of the gods. We have discovered connections, bonds, syncretisms, but also individualities, both singular and collective. It will seem in the future that we have returned to these lands; it will seem we recognize the scent of flowers, and the taste of fruits: but we will return, if we do, with a new awareness.\n\nThat myths are, have always been, and perhaps still will be, waiting for new hypotheses and theories.\n\nThe next steps will take us toward a mountain chain, in which each one represents the thought of a philosopher: these mountains have tunnels and passes that connect one to another, unique glaciers made eternal by time on unreachable peaks, streams that flow from one mountain and from another receive new water to transform into rivers of thought, lakes that collect those rivers, and the Ocean of the Earth all around, to remind us that after all, this Earth whose movement we want to understand, is Alone and One, and all around there is the Rest, and the Darkness.\n\nIn the next episode: the philosophers from Miletus.\n\nRead the other episodes:\n\nBibliography:\n\nAristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus, by Heath T. (Oxford 1913)\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, by Kirk G.S. e Raven J.E. (Cambridge 1957)\n\nEarly Greek Philosophy and the Orient, by West M.L. (Oxford 1971)\n\nPhilosophy before Socrates, by McKirahan R.D. (Hackett 1994)\n\nThanks to EB for revising the text.\n\nFootnotes\n\n1 “The Invention of Homer”, West, M.L. (1999); Classical Quarterly 49 (2)\n\n2 “Aristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus”, Heath T. (1913)\n\n3 ibid.\n\n4 “Early Greek Philosophy and the Orient”, West M.L. (1971)\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_018-omero-esiodo-e-un-proto-filosofo.md": "# Omero, Esiodo, e un proto-filosofo\n\nDisclaimer #1: this article is in Italian. I will publish the English version next Wednesday.\n\nDisclaimer #2: questo pezzo fa parte di una serie, pubblicata sia su questa newsletter, Heralding Time , che su Last Scattering Surface . Se vuoi, puoi seguirle entrambe. Il primo capitolo si legge qui. Il secondo qui. Il terzo qui.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!FnMN!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/14890a96-a731-4109-a450-20425b11d52e_1080x1350.png)\n\nNei precedenti episodi abbiamo parlato della prima concezione del cielo nei popoli antichi, delle cosmologie di Egiziani, Babilonesi, Ebrei e Islamici, e di quelle sviluppatesi in Cina, India e in Scandinavia.\n\nA partire da questo episodio inizieremo un lungo viaggio nella filosofia greca, e del perché è legata al tema di questa serie. Vedremo che è proprio con la cosmologia che i primi pensatori greci hanno dato il via alla tradizione filosofica occidentale.\n\nPer iniziare questo viaggio, dobbiamo prima attraversare il confine che la separa dalla mitologia. Gettando una sguardo alla mappa, costruendo l’itinerario, vediamo che questo confine non è una linea retta, e neanche un confine netto: presenta rientranze e sporgenze, enclavi e territori inesplorati.\n\nLe sorgenti della mitologia greca nascono dai racconti orali dei cantori minoici e micenei tra il II e il I millennio BCE: storie di uomini e dei, eroi e muse, guerre e passioni, storie sull’origine dei luoghi e sull’origine dell’umanità; queste sorgenti fluiscono in tutta la Grecia, e nei vari insediamenti e nelle varie colonie che i Greci fondano in Asia Minore e in Italia, e sono raccolte, definite e riassunte in testi esposti al pubblico intorno all’VIII e al VII secolo BCE. Il primo incontro che facciamo seguendo questo fiume di miti e di parole è un uomo cieco, che è forse più di un uomo, e forse non è mai esistito.\n\nUn uomo cieco che forse non è mai esistito\n\nL’uomo che incontriamo è un bardo cieco vissuto nella Ionia del VIII secolo prima della nostra era, e morto probabilmente a Ios (Io), un’isola delle Cicladi nel Mar Egeo, intorno alla metà del secolo successivo. L’uomo che incontriamo è colui a cui attribuiamo i due poemi epici che hanno dato inizio alla tradizione epica greca, l’ Iliade e l’ Odissea . Ma interrogato su come, quando, e perché abbia scritto questi testi, l’uomo scompare.\n\nPer quanto ne sappiamo, Omero non è mai stato una figura storica. E’ opinione comune degli studiosi che i due poemi non siano dello stesso autore1, e che siano stati composti da una successione di autori e di cantori, che li esponevano in pubblico in tutta la Grecia.\n\nAd ogni modo, possiamo farci accompagnare dall’Omero della tradizione, e parlare degli sconosciuti autori dei due poemi come di parte della figura di Omero leggendario.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!zVpO!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9c14d495-d993-4d1c-8a41-eafe7c48d208_1240x1126.png)\n\nL’Iliade e l’Odissea contengono l’insieme degli strumenti necessari per conoscere il mondo, le sue insidie e i suoi pericoli, le sue possibilità e le sue ricchezze. Tra le storie che contengono, ci sono anche i miti e le storie sulla creazione del mondo, sulla forma che esso ha e sulle forze che lo governano.\n\nOmero descrive il cielo come una emisfera , una ciotola rovesciata, che sovrasta la Terra, un disco piatto e circolare. Tra la Terra e il cielo, nella parte più vicina alla prima, c’è la nebbia , mentre nella parte superiore c’è aria più rarefatta, l’ etere .\n\nSotto le radici della Terra c’è il Tartaro, che è lontano dalla Terra tanto quanto la Terra è lontana dal cielo, e tutto intorno alla Terra c’è il fiume Okeanos , “che circonda la Terra e fluisce dentro sé stesso”2. Okeanos è allo stesso tempo, e a seconda della descrizione, un fiume, una sorgente, un oceano, composto di fresche acque dolci, la fonte di tutte le acque della Terra, un mare salato. Da quale esperienza può venire l’idea di un fiume multiforme intorno al mondo? Probabilmente non dalla Grecia, ma dalle tradizioni dei regni d’Egitto e della Mesopotamia, arrivate nel mondo greco tramite i contatti tra le diverse popolazioni nei secoli precedenti.\n\nAd ovest, oltre le Colonne d’Ercole , situate al confine tra quelli che oggi chiamiamo Mar Mediterraneo e Oceano Atlantico, sorge l’ Erebo , il luogo in cui le anime dei morti attendono di entrare nel Tartaro.\n\nI poemi epici non pongono la questione del moto della Terra, che è evidentemente ferma: ciò è una comune esperienza per ogni membro della Grecia antica. Il Sole, la Luna e le stelle sorgono a oriente, e si muovono nel cielo ogni giorno, ogni giorno cadendo a occidente. Poiché ogni giorno ritornano a oriente per sorgere ancora e ancora, devono in qualche modo tornarvi: ma il Tartaro è sempre buio , e mai illuminato da nessuna luce, dunque gli astri non possono attraversarlo.\n\nE’ compito allora del fiume Okeanos trasportare il Sole, la Luna e le stelle da ovest di nuovo a est, girando intorno alla Terra. Come nella tradizione egizia, anche qui i corpi celesti navigano sull’acqua, dopo la morte e prima di rinascere.\n\nE quali stelle conosce Omero, quali possono sfruttare gli uomini in mare per orientarsi? Omero conosce la stella del mattino, Phosphorus, e la stella della sera, Hesperus; conosce l’asterismo delle Pleiadi, quello delle Iadi e del Grande Carro, e poi la costellazione Orione, le stelle Sirio e Arturo.\n\nAnche la volta celeste è ferma, e il moto dei corpi celesti è un riflesso dell’ordine del mondo.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #1\n\n- un asterismo è un gruppo di stelle che forma una riconoscibile forma geometrica, e che può o meno far parte di una costellazione. Famosi asterismi sono il Triangolo dell'Estate , formato da Altair, Deneb e Vega, o il Grande Carro , parte della costellazione Orsa Maggiore.\n\n- le stelle (dette Sette Sorelle ) più luminose dell'asterismo delle Pleiadi sono presenti anche su una lastra in metallo dell'età del bronzo, il Disco di Nebra , rinvenuto in Germania nel 1999.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!-4T_!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/39dbd62f-a4e6-4599-9420-1ec00cd5242d_1611x1584.jpeg)\n\nDisco di Nebra. La figura circolare a sinistra potrebbe essere il Sole, o la Luna piena. A destra, la Luna crescente. In alto tra le due, le sette stelle luminose delle Pleiadi. Crediti qui.\n\nOmero ci saluta, e ritorna nell’oscurità in cui è immerso il suo passaggio sulla Terra e nella Storia.\n\nUn cantore della nascita degli dei\n\nDopo aver preso commiato dalla figura di Omero, il percorso dal mito alla descrizione fisica del mondo continua con la consapevolezza che il mondo è pieno di dei: antropomorfi, certo, ma anche allegorie di concetti e emozioni umane. Per rispondere alla domanda “Come nascono gli dei?” ci avviciniamo a Esiodo, un cantore vissuto tra il VIII e il VII secolo BCE, e probabilmente originario di Cyme (Cuma Eolica), una città nella regione dell’Eolia, in Asia Minore. Quest’uomo, vissuto in Beozia, - una regione della Grecia continentale - ha scritto tre opere che possiamo leggere interamente: “ Teogonia” , “ Le Opere e i Giorni” e “ Lo scudo di Eracle ”. Gli viene attribuito anche un poema dal titolo “Sull’Astronomia”3, di cui leggiamo solo dei frammenti, che comunque non ci informano su quello che desideriamo conoscere.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!-1-v!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6f36bea8-dc21-4a50-a50d-3c68c8ea6496_1240x1126.png)\n\nCi attanaglia infatti il problema della nascita delle forze che governano il mondo, e degli dei che esercitano quelle forze. Ci libera il canto di Esiodo, che nella Teogonia, la Nascita degli Dei, racconta l’inizio del mondo e quello che ne segue.\n\nLa prima cosa che è successa al mondo, il primo evento , è la separazione della Terra e del Cielo, in due entità distinte, dacché erano unite. Dunque il primo evento non è la creazione di qualcosa di inesistente , ma la separazione di qualcosa di già preesistente .\n\n[...] Prima di tutto certo fu Caos , poi\n\nTerra dall’ampio seno, sempre sede sicura di tutti\n\ngli immortali, che abitano la vetta dell’Olimpo nevoso\n\ne il Tartaro caliginoso nel fondo della Terra dalle ampie vie,\n\ne Eros , il più bello fra gli dèi immortali,\n\nche scioglie le membra, e che di tutti gli dèi e degli uomini tutti\n\ndoma nel petto la mente e la saggia volontà.\n\nDa Caos nacquero Erebo e la Notte nera,\n\ne da Notte , poi, Etere e Giorno nacquero,\n\nche concepì e generò unitasi a Erebo in amore.\n\nTerra per primo generò, uguale a sé,\n\nCielo stellato, affinché tutt’intorno la coprisse,\n\n[...]\n\ncongiuntasi a Cielo , partorì Oceano dai vortici profondi [...]\n\nEsiodo, Teogonia , 116-127, 129. Traduzione di Gabriella Ricciardelli per l’edizione Fondazione Lorenzo Valla/Mondadori\n\nIl mondo è preesistente alla nascita degli dei, che nascono come raffigurazione dei Luoghi e degli Stati del mondo: Cielo, Terra, Notte, Erebo (l’Oltretomba), Etere, Giorno, Oceano; ma anche Emozioni e Sensazioni come Vergogna, Angoscia, Litigio, Carestia, Lavoro, Menzogne. Solo successivamente arriveranno gli dei dell’Olimpo a spodestare Kronos, che a sua volta ha spodestato Ouranos, con l’aiuto di Gaia, consorte di Ouranos, e Rhea, consorte di Kronos.\n\nIn principio, però, c’è il Chaos : nella tradizione greca questo termine sta a significare ciò che significa anche per noi, un sinonimo di disordine e confusione.\n\nQui, Esiodo dà il nome di Chaos a ciò che separa il Cielo dalla Terra, la prima separazione. Il primo atto del mondo, quindi, è la nascita del Chaos inteso come azione della separazione, della distinzione .\n\nNota luminosa a margine #2\n\nLa concezione della distinzione del Cielo e della Terra è presente in molte culture:\n\n- per il popolo Maori, si separano Rangi (il cielo) e Papa (la terra);\n\n- abbiamo visto nel mito egizio che Nut e Geb vengono separati da Shu ;\n\n- avviene lo stesso nella Canzone di Ullikummi , un mito della mitologia Ittita-Urrita che sembra avere molti paralleli (successivi) in Grecia;\n\n- nel mito babilonese dell’ Enuma Elish , l’eroe-dio Marduk dilania Ti’amat in due pezzi: il cielo e la terra;\n\n- la Genesi: “Sia il firmamento in mezzo alle acque per separare le acque dalle acque”. Anche a causa delle forti influenze babilonesi sul mito biblico della creazione del mondo, a un certo punto il dio creatore della Bibbia crea il firmamento per separare la terra e il cielo.\n\nEsiodo non parla di ciò che c’era prima di questa separazione, né del perché essa sia avvenuta. La Teogonia parla degli dei, ed essi sono l’origine dell’ordine nel mondo, il κόσμος (cosmo). Ogni divinità ha il suo “dipartimento” da controllare e su cui regnare; questo controllo non è sempre esclusivo: in alcuni casi un evento, una forza, un luogo sono contesi da più divinità, e questo crea un mondo non totalmente ordinato .\n\nLa Teogonia non contiene idee originali o nuove: è una raccolta di storie e miti già presenti, che si impegna a codificare. Ma come succederà anche per i primi pensatori che chiamiamo filosofi, anche Esiodo crede fermamente in un mondo ordinato, in una presenza divina nel mondo, che permea gli aspetti sia fisici che morali dell’umanità.\n\nIl mondo di Esiodo è un disco piatto e circolare, come per Omero, e su di esso c’è il Cielo, popolato dal Sole, dalla Luna e dalle stelle; sotto di esso c’è il Tartaro, mai illuminato da nessuna luce. Lo spazio tra cielo e terra è luminoso di giorno, e buio di notte. Come in Omero, e come nei miti degli altri popoli del Mediterraneo, i corpi celesti si muovono nel cielo; dopo essere tramontati oltre l’orizzonte, navigano Oceano per ritornare ogni giorno nel luogo in cui sorgeranno di nuovo, ancora e ancora.\n\nOra Esiodo si allontana, e gli dei che ha cantato restano, trasformandosi.\n\nUn proto-filosofo sincretico e misterioso\n\nSiamo quasi arrivati alla fine della prima tappa, che dai territori della mitologia arriva alla soglia della filosofia naturale. Il prossimo personaggio che incontriamo è un proto-filosofo, un uomo che ha trasportato idee e suggestioni dall’Asia alla Grecia, e che dalla Grecia farà ritornare in Asia idee e suggestioni. Con lui attraverseremo i secoli a cavallo tra le ere, e i confini tra regni e popoli.\n\nApollodoro di Atene sostiene che Ferecide di Siro sia un contemporaneo di Anassimandro di Mileto, e pone il suo floruit - il periodo di maggior rilievo per i contemporanei - intorno al 540 BCE; ma ciò non è confermato. Sappiamo che è vissuto nel VI secolo BCE, e che una leggenda del IV secolo BCE lo rappresenta come il maestro di Pitagora, che negli ultimi anni sarebbe rimasto da lui e lo avrebbe sepolto4. Non ne siamo sicuri, ma è vero che tra i pitagorici i suoi testi circolavano, e ci sono delle similitudini tra gli insegnamenti di Pitagora e di Ferecide.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!-WHF!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1e891fe5-1cd3-484d-a112-8ee6065d96ef_1240x1076.png)\n\nA differenza degli altri filosofi, e a rafforzare la sua figura leggendaria, si dice che non abbia ricevuto nessun insegnamento da un maestro, ma che abbia consultato il libro segreto dei Fenici , e la profezia di Ham (ovvero di Zoroastro). Ad ogni modo, i contatti con la Fenicia sono evidenti dal nome del padre, Babis o Babys , chiaro nome di origine asiatica (probabilmente proveniente dalla Frigia, dalla Pisidia o dalla Galazia - tutte regioni dell’Asia minore).\n\nNella sua opera Le sette caverne , Ferecide parla di tre divinità che sono sempre esistite: Zeus, che lui chiama Zas, e che assocerebbe - ma non è chiaro - al Sole; Kronos, che anche se ha lo stesso nome del dio del Tempo abita e governa le Isole dei Beati; e Chtonie, la dea che rappresenta la Terra.\n\nDopo l’unione tra Zas e Chtonie, la Terra diventa Ge, e le viene fatto dono da Zas, adesso diventato anche Eros, di un mantello che lei indossa formando la terra, ma che secondo un successivo passaggio finisce per appendere ad un ” Albero del mondo ”.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #3\n\nQuesta è una storia che serve due scopi: rappresenta la nascita del mondo, e descrive un’attività umana, la anakalyptenia , ovvero il dono rituale del marito alla sposa che avviene al terzo giorno di nozze. Ancora una volta, i miti rappresentano contemporaneamente ciò che accade sulla terra e ciò che qui vi è di nascosto, e questo e da questo influenzano e si fanno influenzare.\n\nZas e Ge generano gli altri dei insieme; Chronos lo fa “in unione con sé stesso”: la nascita del mondo o di una parte di esso come risultato di una azione di questo tipo è comune nei miti e nelle cosmologie asiatiche, ed è un altro tassello che compone in quadro di Ferecide sincretico tra la Grecia e l’Asia. Ne parleremo più avanti.\n\nChronos crea il fuoco, il vento e l’acqua dal suo seme, e li distribuisce nel mondo, nei cinque angoli del titolo (“Le Sette Caverne” è in greco Ἑπτάμυχος, e μυχος ha tra gli altri significati possibili anche angolo ). Non sappiamo a quali luoghi Ferecide si riferisca, ma probabilmente sono i luoghi da cui scaturiscono gli dei, le cinque province seguenti: il cielo, la Terra, Ogenos, Ade e il Tartaro. I primi due sono evidenti, mentre degli altri dovremo parlare: Ogenos è un’altra scrittura di un termine che abbiamo già incontrato, Okeanos; Ade e Tartaro invece sono la dimora dei morti e il luogo in cui non c’è luce, rispettivamente. Gli dei malvagi sconfitti da Chronos, guidati da Ophioneus, un dio la cui origine è accostabile ai serpenti primordiali delle mitologie babilonesi, e che si ritrova anche nella Genesi biblica, vengono ributtati nel mare formato da Ogenos al confine del mondo.\n\nNella cosmologia di Ferecide, infine, gli dei vivono sulla Luna, la Terra è abitata e tutto intorno ha Ogenos, e sotto di essa c’è il mondo dei morti, che a sua volta sovrasta il Tartaro.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #4\n\nAbbiamo parlato di Ferecide sincretico. Ecco perché:\n\n- Eudemo di Argo collega Ferecide alla cosmologia di Sidone, stanziamento fenicio. Qui in origine ci sono Chronos (il tempo), Pothos (il vento), e Omichle (le tenebre). In diverse cosmologie di cultura fenicia, il vento primordiale è rappresentato da Aither e Aer, che generano Ulōmos, che viene dal tardo fenicio 'ūlōm, 'ōlām per gli Ebrei, che significa Tempo Remoto o Eternità. Da questi nasce un uovo, da cui si generano il cielo e la terra.\n\n- nella cosmologia zoroastriana, in principio non c'è nulla se non Zurran, il Tempo. Anch'esso genera da solo , Ohrmazd, il Bene, e Ahriman, il Male. Il primo crea il mondo materiale, formando il firmamento a forma di uovo, in cui tutto è contenuto.\n\n- Negli inni sacri indiani Atharraveda, Kala (il Tempo) genera autonomamente il cielo e la terra.\n\nFerecide è un proto-filosofo, nel senso che nella sua opera c’è un principio che mancava nei poeti precedenti, e che incontreremo in coloro che chiamiamo filosofi: la predilezione della prosa sul verso, la volontà di parlare degli dei, anche accettandone l’esistenza, solo come allegoria delle forze che regolano il mondo; la descrizione del mondo come ordinato già dal principio , senza un ordine che arriva dopo l’azione di uno o più dei.\n\nD’ora in poi, anche gli dei dovranno rispondere alla domanda che i filosofi si pongono: perché? Ferecide lo domanda anche a noi, e scompare nel Tempo che è già Passato.\n\nSuperare il confine\n\nAbbiamo attraversato le pianure del mito, e i sentieri degli dei. Abbiamo scoperto connessioni, legami, sincretismi, ma anche individualità, singole e di gruppo. Sembrerà nel futuro di esservi tornati, in queste lande; sembrerà di riconoscere il profumo dei fiori, e il sapore dei frutti: ma torneremo, se lo faremo, con una nuova consapevolezza.\n\nChe i miti sono, sono sempre stati, e forse ancora saranno, ad aspettare nuove ipotesi e teorie.\n\nI prossimi passi ci porteranno verso una catena di montagne, in cui ognuna rappresenta il pensiero di un filosofo: queste montagne hanno gallerie e valichi che collegano l’una all’altra, ghiacciai unici resi eterni dal tempo su vette irraggiungibili, ruscelli che da una montagna scorrono e dall’altra ricevono nuova acqua per trasformarsi in fiumi di pensiero, laghi che raccolgono quei fiumi, e l’Oceano della Terra tutto intorno, a ricordarci che dopotutto, questa Terra di cui vogliamo capire il movimento, è Sola e Una, e tutto intorno c’è il Resto, e il Buio.\n\nNel prossimo episodio: i filosofi di Mileto.\n\nArticoli della serie:\n\nBibliografia:\n\nAristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus, di Heath T. (Oxford 1913)\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, di Kirk G.S. e Raven J.E. (Cambridge 1957)\n\nEarly Greek Philosophy and the Orient, di West M.L. (Oxford 1971)\n\nPhilosophy before Socrates, di McKirahan R.D. (Hackett 1994)\n\nQuesta newsletter è una di tre: le altre due sono Last Scattering Surface, e Space of Sound. Tutte le pubblicazioni sono gratuite e puoi consultare tutti gli articoli senza paywall. Se vuoi, puoi iscriverti qui e qui.\n\nInfine, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n\nCiao e a presto!\n\nPer la revisione del testo si ringrazia EB.\n\nNote\n\n1 “The Invention of Homer”, West, M.L. (1999); Classical Quarterly 49 (2)\n\n2 “Aristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus”, Heath T. (1913)\n\n3 ibid.\n\n4 “Early Greek Philosophy and the Orient”, West M.L. (1971)\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_019-constants-collections-synthesis.md": "# constants, collections, synthesis\n\nDisclaimer #1: questo articolo è in inglese, la versione in italiano si può leggere qui.\n\nDisclaimer #2: this episode is part of a series named \" on the motion of the Earth ”, published both on this publication, Heralding Time , and on Last Scattering Surface . If you want, you can follow them both. The first chapter is here. The second is here.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!-EBo!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/38856813-8b5e-4512-ba6b-496bcaba6f3c_1080x1350.png)\n\nIn previous episodes we talked about humanity’s first steps under the sky, the Sun, the planets and the stars, and the cosmologies of the Egyptians, the Babylonians, the Hebrews and the Islamic world.\n\nIn this episode we’ll talk about three other cultures that built a cosmology describing the place of Earth in the world: China, India, and Scandinavia.\n\nChina\n\nIn China’s millennia-long history, the first concepts of astronomy and the first cosmological conceptions arrive with the kai thien school of thought, which is succeeded by the hsuan yen , to finally arrive at the hun thien , which will supplant the other two.\n\nChinese astronomers recognize the ecliptic, perform measurements of celestial events, from comets to supernovae to solar or lunar eclipses; however, the lack of a deductive geometry like the one that will develop in Greece prevents the development of celestial mechanics.\n\nKai thien\n\nor “celestial cover,” represents a vaulted universe. The oldest school of those we’ll discuss, formed according to tradition during the time of the Shang dynasty (around 2000 BCE), describes the sky as a square-shaped bowl, upon which sits a circular hemisphere representing the sky. Sky and Earth are 80 thousand li apart (about 40 thousand kilometers).\n\nEarth is surrounded at its borders by a “border ocean,” into which the rains flow. The celestial sphere rotates around Earth from right to left, and the Sun and Moon, bound to this movement, also have their own proper motion. The setting and rising of the Moon and Sun are illusions, however, like the circumpolar stars: they’re no longer visible because they’ve moved too far away.\n\nHsuan yen\n\nstands for “infinite vacuity,” or infinite empty space. This doctrine describes the sky, the firmament, as completely empty and devoid of substance. The sky is immensely distant, immensely high, it has no limit whatsoever. Celestial bodies like the Sun and Moon are nothing but condensed vapor, and they wander through empty space, probably moving, or standing still. They’re not bound to one another, and fixed too is the star that determines the North Pole. The Big Dipper too, the constellation useful for finding North, never falls below the horizon.\n\nHun thien\n\nor “celestial circles,” is the doctrine that later replaced the two more ancient doctrines. The sky is like a chicken egg, and is spherical like a crossbow bolt. Earth is like the egg yolk, and lies at its center, at the center of the Universe. In the lower parts of the sky there is water, upon which Earth rests, and the heavens rest upon vapour.\n\nThe center of Earth is traversed by a celestial axis around which the sky rotates; this axis was initially located in China, which is the center of the world, but now it is no longer: it’s the result of a battle between the monster Kung Kung and China’s fourth mythical emperor, Yao , who shifted the sky in their battle, thus also changing the position of the world’s rotation axis.\n\nThis theory became around 180 CE the theory considered “true” in China, since as Chang Heng , a Chinese astronomer of the 1st century CE, formulates it, “there is no one alive currently who promotes this theory [hsuan yeh],” and “[kai thien] has been proven to be wrong and lacking many proofs and experiments.”\n\nAccumulation, not synthesis\n\nIndian cosmology, which R.F. Gombrich emphasises is different from Indian astronomy, can be divided into four strands, which follow the different doctrines that have visited the Asian continent over the millennia.\n\nVedic and Indu, Buddhist and Jain\n\nThe Purāṇas , among the first Hindu sacred texts, contain two themes linked to cosmology: the universe in space and the universe in time, and contain countless theories about human history, linked to different origins of the world. The complexity of these texts is due to the necessity and will to add descriptions, origins and explanations to already existing texts, rather than operating a synthesis of all previous knowledge.\n\nIn the Rig Veda , a collection of sacred texts dated approximately to the second half of the II millennium BCE, the universe is divided between earth, feminine, and sky, masculine, and the elements that compose it are earth, atmosphere, and sky; the universe begins with fire contained in primordial water.\n\nIn the sacred Brahmanas texts, the world is a shell divided in half, formed by two materials and two parts: gold is the sky, and silver represents Earth. The distance of earth from sky is “ 1000 days of travel by horse, and equals the height reached by 1000 cows arranged one on top of another .”\n\nFrom the Inquiry of Suka , a text describing the creation of time, we know that from Brahma, the great being, originates thought that creates the elements: ether, wind, fire, water and finally earth.\n\nEarth is a mass at the center of the Universe; it’s a flat disc, divided from being a single mass by oceans and continents. At the center of Earth is Mount Meru, a divine mountain located at the center of the world.\n\nFor the Jains, time is eternal, and Earth is a disc. In Buddhist philosophy, space and time are infinite; and infinite is the number of Earths.\n\nEarth rests upon water, and water upon air, and air upon space. The world, that is the Universe, expands and contracts.\n\n“Edo,” or “I write”\n\nThe cosmology of Scandinavian peoples originates in the time of pagan worship, and can be traced back to the Scandinavian Bronze Age (2000 - 500 BCE). It arises from oral culture, and its main text is the Prose Edda (to which is added the Poetic Edda ) compiled by Icelandic historian Snorri Sturluson in the XIII century CE.\n\nAt the center of the world, which is a flat disc, there is a tree, and all around Earth there is an ocean, which joins with underground primordial waters. Under the roots of the tree at the center of the world lies an enormous serpent. The tree’s name is Yggdrasil , and before the beginning of time there was only a formless abyss, Ginnuugagap . Life emerged from ice, and the first giant was named Ymir , which means being with two natures, because he was formed by spark and embers.\n\nThree legendary men kill the giant and form the world: from his body the Earth, from his blood the ocean, from his skin the sky. The sky is supported at the four corners of the world by four dwarves: Austri , Vestri , Nordri , and Sudri . East, West, North, South.\n\nThe gods of Scandinavian mythology are themselves representations of celestial powers, and the main ones are Thor and Odin , who are Aesir , and Freyr and Freyja , who are Vanir . The Aesir (or Asi) are the warrior deities, the Vanir are instead the deities linked to meteorological and natural events.\n\nOnce again, the sky and what happens there find explanation on Earth, and serve a purpose.\n\nIf in a kingdom order must remain as such, everything stays fixed, as in heaven, so on Earth; a land that is instead constantly invaded by other peoples, whose order is continuously modified and indeed overturned, tends to transport this dynamism into a cosmology that proceeds by accumulation and not by synthesis; again, an oral culture that recognises itself in a couple of works that have the purpose of summarising and making them consistent from beginning to end will create with those works an encyclopedia of previous myths and theories.\n\nIn the next episode: Hesiod, Homer, and the first philosophers.\n\nBibliography:\n\nEchoes of the Ancient Skies, by E. C. Tubb (Harper & Row 1983)\n\nAn Encyclopedia of Cosmologies and Myth in Ancient Astronomy, by Clive Ruggles (ABC-CLIO 2005)\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe, by Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, edited by C. Blacker and M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nCosmology of Ancient Egypt, by J.M. Plumley\n\nCosmology of Sumer and Babylon, by W.G. Lambert\n\nJewish Cosmology, by Louis Jacobs\n\nIslamic Cosmology, by Edith Jachimowicz\n\nCosmology of Early China, by Joseph Needham\n\nAncient Indian Cosmology, by R. F. Gombrich\n\nScandinavian Cosmology, by H. R. Ellis Davidson\n\nAncient Light: our changing view of the Universe, by Alan Lightman (Cambridge 1991)\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_020-costanti-raccolte-sintesi.md": "# costanti, raccolte, sintesi\n\nDisclaimer #1: this article is in Italian. I will publish the English version next Wednesday.\n\nDisclaimer #2: questo pezzo fa parte di una serie, pubblicata sia su questa newsletter, Heralding Time , che su Last Scattering Surface . Se vuoi, puoi seguirle entrambe. Il primo capitolo si legge qui. Il secondo qui.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!DRvR!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/7181c20c-c1b5-4fbd-ac3a-b68dbc6da148_1080x1350.png)\n\nNei precedenti episodi abbiamo parlato dei primi passi dell’umanità sotto il cielo, il Sole, i pianeti e le stelle, e delle cosmologie degli Egiziani, dei Babilonesi, degli Ebrei e degli Islamici.\n\nIn questo episodio parleremo di altre tre culture che hanno costruito una cosmologia descrivendo il posto della Terra nel mondo: Cina, India, e Scandinavia.\n\nCina\n\nNella millenaria storia della Cina i primi concetti di astronomia e le prime concezioni cosmologiche arrivano con la scuola di pensiero del kai thien , a cui succede la hsuan yen , per arrivare infine alla hun thien, che soppianterà le altre due.\n\nGli astronomi cinesi riconoscono l’eclittica, effettuano misurazioni degli eventi celesti, dalle comete alle supernovae alle eclissi solari o lunari; la mancanza però di una geometria deduttiva come si svilupperà in Grecia non permette lo sviluppo di una meccanica celeste.\n\nKai thien\n\no “copertura celeste”, sta a rappresentare un universo a volta. La più antica scuola di quelle di cui parleremo, formatasi secondo la tradizione all’epoca della dinastia Shang (intorno al 2000 BCE), descrive il cielo come una ciotola di forma quadrata, su cui c’è un emisfero circolare che rappresenta il cielo. Il cielo e la Terra sono distanti 80mila li (circa 40mila chilometri).\n\nLa Terra è circondata ai suoi confini da un ”oceano bordo”, in cui defluiscono le piogge. La sfera celeste ruota intorno alla Terra da destra verso sinistra, e il Sole e la Luna, solidali a questo movimento, hanno anche un loro moto proprio. Il tramontare e il sorgere della Luna e del Sole sono però illusioni, come le stelle circumpolari: non si vedono più poiché si sono allontanate troppo.\n\nHsuan yen\n\nsta per “infinita vacuità”, o spazio vuoto infinito. Questa dottrina descrive il cielo, il firmamento, come completamente vuoto e privo di sostanza. Il cielo è immensamente lontano, immensamente in alto, non ha alcun limite. I corpi celesti come il Sole e la Luna non sono altro che vapore condensato, e vagano nello spazio vuoto, probabilmente muovendosi, o stando fermi. Non sono legati l’uno all’altro, e fissa è anche la stella che determina il Polo Nord. Anche l’Orsa Maggiore, la costellazione utile per trovare il Nord, non cade mai sotto l’orizzonte.\n\nHun thien\n\no “cerchi celesti”, è la dottrina che ha poi sostituito le due dottrine più antiche. Il cielo è come un uovo di gallina, ed è sferico come un proiettile di balestra. La Terra è come il tuorlo dell’uovo, e giace nel suo centro, al centro dell’Universo. Nelle parti inferiori del cielo c’è acqua, su cui giace la Terra, e i cieli riposano sul vapore.\n\nIl centro della Terra è attraversato da un asse celeste intorno a cui ruota il cielo; questo asse inizialmente si trovava in Cina, che è il centro del mondo, ma ora non lo è più: è il risultato di una battaglia tra il mostro Kung Kung e il quarto imperatore mitico della Cina, Yao , che hanno spostato il cielo nella loro battaglia, cambiando così anche la posizione dell’asse di rotazione del mondo.\n\nQuesta teoria è diventata intorno al 180 CE la teoria considerata “vera” in Cina, poiché come formula Chang Heng , astronomo cinese del I secolo CE, “non c’è nessuno vivo attualmente che promuove questa teoria [hsuan yeh]”, e “[kai thien] è stata provata essere sbagliata e mancante di molti prove ed esperimenti”.\n\nAccumulazione, non sintesi\n\nLa cosmologia indiana, che R.F. Gombrich sottolinea essere diversa dall’astronomia indiana, può essere divisa in quattro filoni, che seguono le diverse dottrine che nei millenni hanno visitato il continente asiatico.\n\nVedica e Indu, Buddista e Jain\n\nI Purāṇa , tra i primi testi sacri hindu, contengono due temi legati alla cosmologia: l’universo nello spazio e l’universo nel tempo, e contengono innumerevoli teorie sulla storia umana, legata a diverse origini del mondo. La complessità di questi testi è dovuta alla necessità e alla volontà di aggiungere descrizioni, origini e spiegazioni ai testi già presenti, piuttosto che operare una sintesi di tutte le precedenti conoscenze.\n\nNei Rig Veda , collezione di testi sacri datati all’incirca alla seconda metà del II millennio BCE, l’universo è diviso tra la terra, femminile, e il cielo, maschile, e gli elementi che lo compongono sono la terra, l’atmosfera, e il cielo; l’universo inizia con il fuoco contenuto nell’acqua primordiale.\n\nNei testi sacri Brahmanas il mondo è un guscio diviso a metà, formato da due materiali e da due parti: l’oro è il cielo, e l’argento rappresenta la Terra. La distanza della terra dal cielo è di “ 1000 giorni di viaggio a cavallo, ed è pari all’altezza che raggiungono 1000 mucche disposte una sull’altra” .\n\nDall’ Indagine di Suka, testo che descrive la creazione del tempo, sappiamo che da Brahma, il grande essere, si origina il pensiero che crea gli elementi: l’etere, il vento, il fuoco, l’acqua e infine la terra.\n\nLa Terra è una massa al centro dell’Universo; è un disco piatto, diviso dall’essere un’unica massa da oceani e continenti. Al centro della Terra c’è il Monte Meru, un monte divino che si trova al centro del mondo.\n\nPer i Giainisti il tempo è eterno, e la Terra è un disco. Nella filosofia buddista, spazio e tempo sono infiniti; e infinito è il numero di Terre.\n\nLa Terra giace sull’acqua, e l’acqua sull’aria, e l’aria sullo spazio. Il mondo, ovvero l’Universo, si espande e si contrae.\n\n“Edo”, o “io scrivo”\n\nLa cosmologia dei popoli scandinavi nasce al tempo del culto pagano, e si può ricondurre all’Età del Bronzo Scandinava (2000 - 500 BCE). Nasce dalla cultura orale, e il suo testo principale è l’ Edda in Prosa (a cui si aggiunge l’ Edda Poetica ) riunite dallo storico islandese Snorri Sturluson nel XIII secolo CE.\n\nAl centro del mondo, che è un disco piatto, c’è un albero, e tutto intorno alla Terra c’è un oceano, che si riunisce con le acque primordiali sotterranee. Sotto le radici dell’albero al centro del mondo giace un enorme serpente. Il nome dell’albero è Yggdrasil , e prima dell’inizio del tempo c’era solo un abisso informe, Ginnuugagap . La vita è emersa dal ghiacccio, e il primo gigante aveva nome Ymir , che significa essere con due nature, poiché era formato dalla scintilla e dalle braci.\n\nTre uomini leggendari uccidono il gigante e formano il mondo: dal suo corpo la Terra, dal suo sangue l’oceano, dalla sua pelle il cielo. Il cielo è sorretto ai quattro angoli del mondo da quattro nani: Austri , Vestri , Nordri , and Sudri . Est, Ovest, Nord, Sud.\n\nGli dei della mitologia scandinava sono anch’essi raffigurazioni delle potenze celesti, e i principali sono Thor e Odino , che sono Aesir , e Freyr e Freyja , che sono Vaenir . Gli Aesir (o Asi) sono le divinità guerriere, i Vaenir sono invece le divinità legate agli eventi meteorologici e naturali.\n\nAncora una volta, il cielo e ciò che vi accade trovano spiegazione sulla Terra, e servono a uno scopo.\n\nSe in un regno l’ordine deve rimanere tale, tutto resta fermo, come in cielo, così sulla Terra ; una terra che invece viene costantemente invasa da altri popoli, il cui ordine viene continuamente modificato e anzi stravolto, tende a trasportare questo dinamismo in una cosmologia che procede per accumulazione e non per sintesi; ancora, una cultura orale che si riconosce in un paio di opere che hanno lo scopo di riassumerle e renderle consistenti dall’inizio alla fine creerà con quelle opere una enciclopedia dei miti e delle teorie precedenti.\n\nNel prossimo episodio: Esiodo, Omero, e i primi filosofi.\n\nArticoli della serie:\n\nBibliografia:\n\nEchoes of the Ancient Skies, di E. C. Tubb (Harper & Row 1983)\n\nAn Encyclopedia of Cosmologies and Myth in Ancient Astronomy, di Clive Ruggles (ABC-CLIO 2005)\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe, di Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, raccolta di saggi ad opera di C. Blacker e M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nCosmology of Ancient Egypt, di J.M. Plumley\n\nCosmology of Sumer and Babylon, di W.G. Lambert\n\nJewish Cosmology, di Louis Jacobs\n\nIslamic Cosmology, di Edith Jachimowicz\n\nCosmology of Early China, di Joseph Needham\n\nAncient Indian Cosmology, di R. F. Gombrich\n\nScandinavian Cosmology, di H. R. Ellis Davidson\n\nAncient Light: our changing view of the Universe, di Alan Lightman (Cambridge 1991)\n\nQuesta newsletter è una di tre: le altre due sono Last Scattering Surface, e Space of Sound. Tutte le pubblicazioni sono gratuite e puoi consultare tutti gli articoli senza paywall. Se vuoi, puoi iscriverti qui e qui.\n\nInfine, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n\nCiao e a presto!\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_anaximanders-indefinite-principle.md": "# Anaximander’s indefinite principle and Anaximenes’ cosmic breath\n\nDisclaimer #1: questo articolo è in inglese, la versione in italiano si può leggere qui.\n\nDisclaimer #2: this episode is part of a series named “ on the motion of the Earth ”, published both on this publication, Heralding Time , and on Last Scattering Surface . If you want, you can follow them both. Here chapters I, II, III, IV, V.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/25bb1116-004f-43d4-8858-aecca20c2d86_1080x1350.png)\n\nWelcome back.\n\nIn the previous episode we talked about Miletus and Thales, the first philosopher according to the tradition of philosophy in Greece.\n\nIn this episode we will talk about the other two philosophers from Miletus, we will hear what they have to say, we will understand how they answer questions about the origin of the world and its composition.\n\nHeralding Time is on Instagram. You can follow it here.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/__ss-rehost__IG-meta-DQgnHW1jFsY.jpg)\n\nAnaximander\n\nDiogenes Laertius1 informs us that Anaximander, son of Praxiades, is the first to have built \"clocks\", and in the Byzantine encyclopedia (the Suda , therefore a very late source) Anaximander is spoken of as the one who invented the gnomon, a useful instrument for measuring the position of the Sun, and who “measured” the equinoxes and solstices. Furthermore, according to Diogenes he was the first to draw a map of lands and seas. The Suda also cites some writings he would have composed: “ On Nature ,” “ The Circuit of the Earth ,” “ On the Fixed Stars ,” “ The Celestial Globe ”; regarding the first Barnes speaks of a \"naturalistic version of Hesiod’s Theogony\"2. A legend tells that the philosopher warned the Spartans of an imminent earthquake.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/4c388a53-37d9-42ab-9c3c-f594d9874a4b_2491x2500.jpeg)\n\nAnaximander - 1493 - Rijksmuseum, Netherlands - Public Domain.\n\nDiogenes places the date of the philosopher’s death shortly after the LVIII Olympiad (547 BCE), around age 64. Apollodorus instead speaks of Anaximander born 14 years after Thales (therefore around 610 BCE) and died in the same year as his death (which occurred around 545 BCE). There is therefore a discrepancy between the two datings, but it is certain that the two philosophers were contemporary at a certain point, and it is said that Anaximander was a \"student\" of Thales, that is, that he heard his teachings.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1ad4bff3-7d9f-4f3c-b164-320828083873_1240x1126.png)\n\nRegarding the gnomon devised by Anaximander: as we saw in the previous chapter, the gnomon is a Babylonian invention, and perhaps was already known to Thales, therefore the \"discovery\" attributed to Anaximander can at most refer to the fact that he made use of it during his life.\n\nRegarding the map drawn by the second philosopher of Miletus: this was indeed one of the first after Homer’s, and was perfected by Hecataeus, geographer of Miletus, following Herodotus as a source, a Greek historian of the V century BCE.\n\nDiogenes, citing Theophrastus, states that for Anaximander the principle is the ἄπειρον ( apeiron ) which we translate as Unlimited, Indefinite, Infinite.\n\nWhen he speaks of principle, Anaximander probably does not refer to the ἀρχή of which we spoke regarding Thales, cited by Aristotle: the philosopher therefore does not refer to the force that generates the world, but to the substance of which the world is initially formed.\n\nThe ἄπειρον is translatable as infinite but does not represent the spatial infinity still used today in physics: and in fact together with infinite we insert indefinite , meaning by this that this \"primordial\" substance lacks boundary, limit, definition.\n\nThat is, it cannot be confined, delimited, defined.\n\nApeiron has as its root a-peiras , that is without limit, and peir has the meaning of \"to cross\". It seems therefore that the term ἄπειρον represents something that is impossible to cross from side to side .\n\nFor Anaximander what is not defined has no distinction , in the sense that it is a substance that contains everything without distinction .\n\nAristotle speaks of this, saying that this principle is an element beyond the elements, and that it contains an infinite reserve that behaves like a spring from which to generate all the elements.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/def8d9b4-200b-484f-b3c1-39242eb43f0b_800x519.jpeg)\n\nMeteorite observed on June 11, 1867, illustration from 1875. Image obtained from Public Domain Image Archive / Internet Archive / California Digital Library\n\nIn any case, we are not sure what the interpretation was for Anaximander. It seems however, from the fragments we have3, that this Indefinite is for him the place where opposites pay \"one to the other the penalty according to the order of time\", and from which the same opposites originate4.\n\nThe Indefinite guides everything and \"steers\" everything, creation and its opposite, that is destruction , which both occur by necessity. This happens cyclically and without end, and one after another innumerable worlds are created and destroyed. The ἄπειρον is most likely in motion, otherwise how could the latter be born from something that does not contain it?\n\nAnd what type of motion does it contain? It seems that it should not have any particular type, because if it had a defined one, how could all the others be born? All the different characteristics of things emerge from the ἄπειρον, each separating from its opposite, but they are not initially contained in it.\n\nThe world as we can observe it today emerges, for Anaximander, after a process of separation and differentiation of everything from its opposite .\n\nKoestler5 speaks of Anaximander as the first who conceived a mechanistic system for the Universe. Let’s see why.\n\nWe have a fairly clear vision of his idea of the world, following various sources. According to Pseudo-Plutarch, Anaximander describes the Earth as a cylinder three times as wide as its length; Hippolytus also agrees6. According to Aristotle, the Earth for Anaximander is stationary at the center of the Universe, and is freely suspended without being supported by anything (unlike in Thales’ world, where the Earth is suspended by water), and this happens because and thanks to its “ being equally bound to all things ”7.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ec711e97-0367-4221-a708-51af6c518dff_1280x1280.png)\n\nLast Scattering Surface\n\nA story of a star - Part I Chasing the Sun…\n\nRead more\n\n3 years ago · 3 likes · Antonio Viscusi\n\nThe firmament is spherical, and the planets and stars are wheels of fire, surrounded by a bubble of air: they contain openings, from which fire escapes, which is the source of brightness of these celestial objects.\n\nWhen these openings are occluded - in what way is not said - in the Sun or Moon, it is at that moment that solar and lunar eclipses occur8.\n\nThe Moon is luminous because it contains fire like all the other stars, and does not take its brightness from the Sun.\n\nBright note in the margin #5\n\nThe wheels full of fire and surrounded by air present in Anaximander’s cosmology had been \"seen\" a few years earlier by the Hebrew prophet Ezekiel, son of Buzi, around 593 BCE in Mesopotamia:\n\nEzekiel 1:20: \"Wherever the spirit wanted to go, they went, and the wheels rose along with them, because the spirit of the living creatures was in the wheels\"\n\nIf the gods are in heaven, and in heaven there are the stars, do the gods not dwell in the stars?\n\nThe position of the celestial bodies is innovative: according to Hippolytus and Aetius, Anaximander places the fixed stars not in a sphere on the outside, but in the circle closest to Earth; then the circle of the Moon, at a distance equal to 18 times the diameter of the Earth; finally the Sun, at a distance equal to 27 times the diameter of the Earth. The Sun is as large as the Earth, and regarding the planets known at the time (Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter, Saturn) we do not know if Anaximander places them together with the fixed stars or at an intermediate distance between the fixed stars and the Moon.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/335a0039-e12d-4522-8253-4e3485009346_960x930.png)\n\nDescription of Anaximander’s world. Illustration by D.L. Couprie in Heaven And Earth In Ancient Greek Cosmology . In the illustration, which follows that of Diels and Naddaf, the circle of stars is at nine Earth diameters, the circle of the Moon at 18, that of the Sun at 27. Credits here.\n\nWe know however that the movements in the sky all occur around the Earth, and that they are due to the wind generated by the moist exhalations of the Earth when it is heated by the heat of the Sun. It is also to the wind that the obliquity of the ecliptic is owed, that is, of the path that the Sun makes in its orbit around the Earth9.\n\nBright note in the margin #6\n\nIn Babylon, the numbers 3 and 9 had particular importance. In Egypt, astronomers selected 36 δεκανοί (decans), stars in the sky arranged so that their rising in the sky was distant from one another by ten degrees over periods of ten days, in order to divide the year into months.\n\nAnaximander’s cosmology has the first circle 9 times the diameter of the Earth, the circle of the Moon 18 times that of the Earth, the circle of the Sun 27 times.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/09b6a396-3f77-47ef-adb3-8bc3c9a0462e_1612x826.png)\n\nCopy of Mugler’s illustration with the description of Anaximander’s universe. The Earth is the cylinder at the center, which forms an angle with the vertical axis - the inclination of the ecliptic. The sphere is the sphere of stars, the first circle is that of the Moon, the outermost circle that of the Sun. Credits here.\n\nAnaximander’s universe is measured in \"terrestrial\" dimensions: it is the first time this happens outside of a mythical tale, in which philosophy becomes slightly more quantitative and assigns a role to numbers in terms of proportion. We will see with Pythagoras that this is perhaps the foundation of Greek astronomy.\n\nBright note in the margin #7\n\nThe order Earth, stars, Moon, Sun is innovative for ancient Greece, but is not original in human history: it was the standard in Persian cosmology.\n\nIn the sacred texts of the Dāmdāt Nask and the Pahlavi Dēnkart one reads that beyond the Sun there is imperishable light. In Persian the expression anayra- means \"without beginning\", that is without ayra.\n\nIf ἀρχή is the principle, ayra also has a similar meaning.\n\nIt is strange, we said innovative earlier, the choice to place the circle of fixed stars in front of the circle of the Moon; it also seems like an idea easy to refute, in fact: how many times are the stars of the Pleiades occulted by the presence of the Moon, thus demonstrating that it is the Moon that is closer to Earth, and not the contrary?\n\nBut this decision could be due not so much to some specific astronomical observation, as to the idea that Anaximander has of the nature of these bodies. If they are composed of fire, and the \"purer\" the fire the higher it rises, then the brightest fire there is, and the purest - that is the Sun - will be in the highest place, followed by the Moon, and only after by the faint lights seen in the sky at night on a moonless night: the stars.\n\nThere remains the unresolved doubt about the behavior of the mist , which exhales from the Earth and creates the stars: if the Sun and Moon are visible even beyond this mist, then is its behavior such as to make partially visible and partially invisible beyond itself? This is not clear.\n\nFor Anaximander, the cause of the birth of the world already contains the forces that cause its movements. For this reason, McKirahan states that the philosopher is an ante litteram exponent of Uniformitarianism10, that is, of that doctrine born between the XVIII and XIX centuries CE according to which the geological processes that occur in the world today are the same as those that occurred in remote times.\n\nFinally, with his idea of the Earth suspended at the center of the Universe, Anaximander allowed celestial bodies to rotate all around it, without worrying about accepting \"passages\" from Okeanos or visiting or not the kingdom of souls, echoes of Egyptian and Babylonian mythologies.\n\nThe Universe becomes more and more something that humanity can describe in an a-human way, becoming however increasingly intertwined with the concepts of proportion, meaning, ultimate destination - very human concepts.\n\nAnaximenes\n\nAnaximenes, son of Eurystratus11, is a student of Anaximander, probably also of Parmenides12. We do not know much about his life, except that his acme is around the fall of Sardis after the conquest of Cyrus the Great - which occurred around 546 BCE. He could therefore have been born around 585 BCE13. He probably died in the LXIII Olympiad, therefore between 528 and 524 BCE.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/30bea483-ae5e-41b6-83df-ab94ec5e5e6d_2500x2456.jpeg)\n\nAnaximenes - 1493 - Rijksmuseum, Netherlands - Public Domain.\n\nOf him we know nothing else, except that it is said he wrote at least one book.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/494f7763-fdcd-4ad9-b6a2-e4f60f391879_1240x1126.png)\n\nAnaximenes’ philosophy is transmitted by Aristotle, and we know that his ἀρχή, his creative principle, is air .\n\nThe term air must not be misleading. The Greeks distinguish between aer and aether : the first term refers to breath, and comes from a term meaning \"dark mist\", and can be hot or cold; the second term instead represents crystalline air, and is the pure element that will then become the material of which the celestial spheres are filled.\n\nAir is infinite like the ἄπειρον, but it is not indefinite . From air in fact come all the elements, thanks to a process of rarefaction and condensation: when water becomes rarefied, fire is created; when it becomes denser, it becomes wind; and then again clouds, finally water. From this, it becomes earth, and finally rock.\n\nThese changes occur because of the movement of the ἄπειρον, which is eternal.\n\nAir, which is the πνεῦμα ( pneuma ) of the world, is the reason for its existence and its diversity: from the exhalations of air come the Sun, the Moon and the stars, but also the gods14.\n\nAnaximenes is the first to state that the fixed stars are truly fixed , in the sense that they are bound to the celestial vault, which is crystalline because it allows one to see what is beyond.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a5070138-a1dc-47f7-96b5-8697c3e19ab6_1024x690.jpeg)\n\nStudie af skyer, work by Christen Købke. Image obtained from National Gallery of Denmark, Denmark - Public Domain.\n\nAll commentators agree in stating that Anaximenes’ Earth is flat15, that it is stationary at the center of the Universe16, and that it is supported by air; that all celestial bodies rotate around it, and are also flat \" like a leaf\" 17; that the Sun is in motion because of the wind generated by air, and that this movement is the reason why it is so hot; that the stars are also in motion - although they are fixed to the celestial vault , they move because the celestial vault itself is in motion - and we do not feel their heat because they are very distant; moreover, they could host other worlds like the Sun with Earth.\n\nUnlike Anaximander, however, Anaximenes does not describe the motion of celestial bodies as a complete revolution around the Earth: when they are not visible to us, this is not due to their motion under the Earth , but to the fact that those bodies - the Sun at night, the stars by day - cross distant regions of the world that are higher than the rest of the world, and therefore invisible to observation, almost as if the table that is the Earth were also a bit oblique.\n\nThe phenomenon of eclipses is due to smaller bodies that obscure the light of the Moon or Sun.\n\nAnaximenes explains the world by tracing everything back to the ἀρχή, and in this he unites the teachings of his two predecessors and fellow citizens: the ἀρχή is the cause of everything (the ἄπειρον for Anaximander), but it is also a visible element of the world, air (what for Thales was water).\n\nFurthermore, he operates a reduction of multiple phenomena, from the presence of celestial bodies to the diversity of elements, to a single cause: air and its behaviours. He associates two opposite qualities - hot and cold, light and heavy, rarefied and dense - with a single quantity .\n\nFrom terrestrial events like earthquakes, due according to Anaximenes to the Earth drying out and cracking18, to the gods who are born and preside over the world, everything in the Universe has air as its principle.\n\nTraces of the Near East\n\nWe have already spoken several times about the relationship between the first Greek philosophers and Egyptian, Babylonian and in general, the mythologies of the peoples and civilisations of the east. Anaximander and Anaximenes make no exception.\n\nAnaximander speaks of the ἄπειρον as the negation of what is limited . This Indefinite creates infinite worlds, all equidistant in time, and in which each lasts for a defined time. The world is formed with the perpetual movement of the Indefinite, first as a generative unity, which contains everything and its contrary, and then as the sphere that contains the Earth and the wheels of fire surrounded by air that are the celestial bodies. With his mechanistic vision he explains eclipses, the angulation of the ecliptic, the presence of celestial bodies.\n\nThe shape of the Earth, a cylinder wider than it is tall, is slightly concave, as if in this description there remained the echo of Babylonian, Chaldean, Iranian and Egyptian mythologies about the mountains that surround the world.\n\nWe have seen in the bright notes in the margin of this chapter that many times the ideas of Greek philosophers find a mythical origin or a religious explanation in eastern myths: the creation of Anaximander’s world is no exception, which occurs in a way similar to the Iranian one in which Ohrmazd creates the world from \"what is moist and what is fiery\".\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/cae3efbc-0132-4cdf-97a8-69bba7b7de3b_2412x2010.jpeg)\n\nFuoco, work by Maerten de Vos, Adriaen Collaert, 1580-1584. Image obtained from Public Domain Image Archive / Rijksmuseum\n\nAnaximenes instead speaks of air, of aer , of ἀήρ: mist, vapor. It is a visible substance, but which has the properties of the Indefinite. In relation to air as breath, in a hymn to Prâna contained in the Atharva Veda texts, it is said that everything obeys Prâna, which is breath . In the Pahlavi texts one reads that eclipses are due to smaller bodies in the sky that interpose between the world of Earth and the stars.\n\nThe three philosophers, finally\n\nThe three philosophers of Miletus, Thales, Anaximander and Anaximenes , are the first in Greece to try to discover the functioning and origin of Nature through reasoning : they observe the world, try to trace back to first principles, to generalise , to make analogies , to compare different phenomena to find their common origins .\n\nBenjamin Farrington, historian of science and Marxist-inspired academic (Science in Antiquity, Science and Politics in the Ancient World), speaks of the philosophers of Miletus saying that they \"leave out the gods\" from their explanations of natural phenomena. This is certainly true insofar as what happens in the world is not the result of the will of the gods, and in which neither the creation of the world nor its end are the work of a creative or destructive divinity. Despite this, the three philosophers do not reject the existence of the gods, who are even subjected to the same process of creation as all the other things there are in the world, and who are subject to the same rules, and the same principles. Anaximander’s ἄπειρον could represent the spirit of creation of the world, but already in Anaximenes this spirit is indeed indefinite, but observable in action even on Earth.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/db435f8d-7659-447f-9442-ccda3f7b1bf3_800x902.jpeg)\n\nIllustration from a 1587 treatise on comets and meteors, known as Kometenbuch - work by an anonymous artist, 1587. Image obtained from Public Domain Image Archive / ORKA - Open Repository Kassel\n\nWhat they seek is the general, not the particular; it is the primary cause, the universal and essential, the material cause. Now Barnes asks himself: do they do it as \"scientists\", in the sense we define it today?\n\nThere are three possible ways to sketch an answer: one can think that \"none of the philosophers of Miletus proposed “true” theories\", that \"they did not compose a Royal Society [ante litteram] in Greece\", and that \"none of these philosophers intended to achieve the precision that is required of scientific theories today\"19; in doing so, they are seen as representatives of the last poets interested in Nature, rather than the first initiators of Western science.\n\nThis vision is encouraged by the problems in the uncertain assignment of ideas and interpretations of the same due to the second, third, even fourth level sources that are the only ones we have; but also by the fact that as far as we know these philosophers did not (i) perform experiments, (ii) did not use the inductive method to build their theories nor (iii) the critical method towards each other, (iv) did not use the data at their disposal to advance hypotheses.\n\nOn the other hand there is the vision, among others proposed by Popper, according to which their works prepared the way for scientific research as we understand it, and that indeed they did the best they could do with the means at their disposal: Popper speaks in particular of Anaximander, who arrived at his idea by criticising Thales’ theory, using speculative arguments, proper to philosophy, to assert that if the Earth lies on water, one should have explained what the water rests on, and so on; and judging these infinite explanations unacceptable, he proposed a new one, which is interesting insofar as it seems to prepare for the concept of action at a distance, with his description of the Earth stationary because equally \"attracted\" by everything simultaneously. And it matters little if then Anaximander himself states that the Earth is flat: this is due to observational arguments, proper to science, and equally important as speculative ones.\n\nCertainly, Thales and the other two philosophers were wrong in their ideas, but their importance, says Coleman20, does not lie in the models they proposed, rather in the fact that they began, each improving the model of the previous one, to \"establish a long chain of progressively [increasingly] correct interpretation of scientific discoveries\".\n\nFinally, the third way unites the two previous ones, and presenting the three philosophers as those who allowed science as naturalistic and no longer mythical inquiry to be born, but who did not manage to adhere to the dictates that modern science considers necessary to define science as speculative and observational inquiry.\n\nAll this is not a fault that we can attribute to the three philosophers, whom we can well define - for our understanding of the terms - therefore, if not Astronomers, Cosmologists, Physicists, at least full-fledged investigators of Nature.\n\nHowever, one should not think that their inquiries were homogeneous, uniform, directed by a specific idea: the concept of principle alone, for example, is not proper to the VI century BCE, but is connected a posteriori by Aristotle searching for it in the philosophers before him.\n\nThe search for the causes of movements in the sky and the origin of the world continues as a search by single individuals: who debate each other’s ideas - without undermining the theories at their core, but who do not belong to a school. Not yet.\n\nIn the next episode: the problem of change.\n\nRead the other episodes:\n\nBibliography:\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe, by Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, edited by C. Blacker and M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nGreek Cosmologies, by G.E.R. Lloyd\n\nAristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus, by Heath T. (Oxford 1913)\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, di Kirk G.S. and Raven J.E. (Cambridge 1957)\n\nEarly Greek Philosophy and the Orient, by West M.L. (Oxford 1971)\n\nPhilosophy before Socrates, by McKirahan R.D. (Hackett 1994)\n\nEarly Greek Science, by G.E.R. Lloyd (Chatto & Windus 1970)\n\nA history of astronomy from Thales to Kepler, by J.L.E Dreyer (Dover 1953)\n\nHeaven And Earth In Ancient Greek Cosmology, by D.L. Cuprie (Springer 2011)\n\nEarly Greek Cosmology: A Historiographical Review, by N.S. Hetherington\n\nBack to the Pre-Socratics: The Presidential Address, by K.R. Popper (1958)\n\nEarly Greek astronomy to Aristotle, by D.R. Dicks (Cornell University Press 1970)\n\nHistory of Philosophy Volume I: From the Beginning to Plato, edited by C.C.W. Taylor (Routledge 1997)\n\nThe Ionians, by Malcolm Schofield\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, by Jonathan Barnes (Routledge 1979)\n\nA Source Book In Greek Science by M.R. Cohen e I.E. Drabkin (Harvard University Press 1945)\n\nThe Physical World of the Greeks, by S. Sambursky (The Macmillan Company 1956)\n\nNotes\n\n1 Diogenes Laertius, Lives of Philosophers.\n\n2 Jonathan Barnes, The Presocratic Philosophers.\n\n3 Simplicius, Commentary on Aristotle’s Physics.\n\n4 Simplicius also cites Theophrastus in the Commentary on Aristotle’s Physics, and also Hermias of Alexandria, Pseudo-Plutarch and Aetius agree on Simplicius’ idea of the indefinite.\n\n5 Arthur Koestler, Sleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe.\n\n6 Hippolytus, Refutationes.\n\n7 Pseudo-Plutarch, Stromata.\n\n8 Hippolytus, Refutationes.\n\n9 Pseudo-Plutarch, Stromata.\n\n10 McKirahan, Philosophy before Socrates\n\n11 Diogenes Laertius, Lives of the Philosophers.\n\n12 We will also talk about him.\n\n13 The acme of a philosopher was generally placed around his fortieth year of age.\n\n14 Hippolytus, Refutationes.\n\n15 Pseudo-Plutarch, Stromata.\n\n16 Aristotle, De Cælo.\n\n17 Aristotle, Meteorologica.\n\n18 Aristotle, Meteorologica.\n\n19 N.S. Hetherington, Early Greek Cosmology: A Historiographical Review.\n\n20 Coleman, Early Theories of the Universe\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_come-la-cicloide-salvo-la-marina.md": "# come la cicloide salvò la marina inglese\n\nDisclaimer #1: this article is in Italian. The English is here.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2be87920-05f4-4827-9bf9-ff185dc5e828_1572x1048.png)\n\nIl 29 settembre 1707 l’Ammiraglio Sir Clowdisley Shovel salpò da Gibilterra verso l’Inghilterra con ventuno navi della Royal Navy.\n\nLa Gran Bretagna era in guerra con la Francia e, sebbene Gibilterra fosse caduta in mani britanniche nel 1702, si riteneva imprudente che le navi più grandi della flotta [inglese] rimanessero nel Mediterraneo durante l’inverno.\n\nLe condizioni meteorologiche durante la traversata non furono buone.\n\nCi furono tempeste da ovest dal 5 al 10 ottobre.\n\nIl 12 e il 13 ci furono raffiche di vento, seguite da due giorni di venti leggeri.\n\nIl 16 e il 17 ci furono tempeste da est e il 19 tempeste da nord-ovest.\n\nIl 21 il cielo si schiarì e diverse navi riuscirono a effettuare osservazioni per la latitudine, mentre lo scandagli indicò una profondità tra i 90 e i 140 bracci, mostrando che la flotta si trovava sul bordo della piattaforma continentale.\n\nTre navi essendo state distaccate a Falmouth per servizio di scorta il 22, e non essendo visibile il sole per tutto il giorno, le restanti 18 navi si misero in panna nel pomeriggio per effettuare gli scandagli.\n\nPoi, convinti di trovarsi nell’imboccatura della Manica e al sicuro da ogni pericolo, le navi procedettero verso est spinte da una burrasca favorevole.\n\nVerso le 19:30 dello stesso giorno l’Association, l’Eagle e la Romney si schiantarono contro gli Scogli di Gilstone nelle Isole Scilly.\n\nDei 1.200 uomini nelle tre navi, si salvò un solo uomo - il quartiermastro della Romney.\n\nIl corpo di Sir Clowdisley fu ritrovato galleggiante il giorno seguente e ora giace in una delle tombe più grandi e brutte dell’Abbazia di Westminster.\n\nAnche la St. George e la Firebrand si schiantarono contro gli scogli ma riuscirono a liberarsi.\n\nQuest’ultima, tuttavia, era gravemente danneggiata e affondò successivamente, lasciando solo ventitrè sopravvissuti.\n\nQuesto è l’inizio del capitolo tre del libro di Derek Howse, intitolato Greenwich Time and the Discovery of the Longitude , pubblicato nel 19801. E’ un racconto sulla storia delle invenzioni e dei ragionamenti intorno alla determinazione della longitudine , principalmente utile durante la navigazione.\n\nIl disastro riportato dall’autore del libro era stato solo l’ultimo di una serie per la flotta inglese, a causa non solo condizioni meteo sfavorevoli - nebbia, correnti marine improvvise - ma anche di errate misurazioni della posizione delle terre emerse.\n\nProblemi di questo tipo erano conosciuti da tempo, e non solo dalla marina inglese: Francia, Spagna, Olanda, tutte le nazioni che navigavano gli oceani.\n\nAd ogni modo, questo disastro in particolare provocò grande preoccupazione nel pubblico inglese, e il suo governo si decise a fare qualcosa.\n\nQuest'anno, diventa un abbonato a pagamento per supportare questa pubblicazione!\n\nGrazie! E se vuoi, condividila!\n\nIl Longitude Act\n\nLa storia di cui parleremo parte dal Longitude Act del 1714, uno dei meno controversi atti legislativi proposti dal Parlamento inglese, che impiegò solo 70 giorni per essere trasformato in legge dal momento in cui fu presentata2, il 17 giugno del 1714; l’Assenso Reale fu posto il 9 luglio dello stesso anno.\n\nIl premio, per chiunque avesse “scoperto la longitudine in mare”, fu deciso dalla commissione di esperti chiamati a decidere delle risposte alla petizione: nella commissione comparivano Isaac Newton , Samuel Clarke, Edmond Halley , e Roger Cotes.\n\nL’11 giugno di quell’anno Newton aveva esposto alla Commissione della Camera dei Lord lo “stato dell’arte” dei metodi - evidentemente insufficienti, e alcuni persino impossibili da implementare - di misurare la longitudine in mare: parla per primo di un orologio che misuri il tempo in modo esatto, difficile da costruire in modo che sia preciso nonostante il moto della nave, le escursioni di temperatura e di umidità, e le piccole variazioni di gravità a differenti latitudini.\n\nPassa poi a un metodo già esposto da Galileo che prevedeva osservare i satelliti di Giove: lo scienziato italiano aveva proposto di osservare le lune del pianeta durante la navigazione, e registrarne la posizione confrontandola con quella registrata in situazioni “standard” - a terra, si intende. Dalla differenza delle due misure si sarebbe ottenuta la misura della longitudine. Galileo stesso si era reso conto che la proposta era irrealizzabile con la tecnologia del tempo per via della bassa precisione dei telescopi, e a causa del moto della nave.\n\nUn terzo metodo utilizza la Luna, e i differenti momenti in cui l’ombra della Terra copre il satellite durante le eclissi. Anche questo metodo è spiegato da Galileo, che però porta due controindicazioni: la prima riguarda la frequenza con cui le eclissi avvengono, troppo poche per permettere una navigazione precisa; mentre la seconda riguarda gli errori nelle misure che possono arrivare anche a 8° di incertezza3, troppo grandi per assicurare la corretta navigazione.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f9d116b2-b2a6-420d-893c-10424bb81d0f_1024x1212.jpeg)\n\nRitratto di Galileo Galilei, opera di Justus Sustermans (1635).\n\nDopo averli enumerati tutti, la Commissione propone il premio per la soluzione, in base all’accuratezza della stessa: una somma di 10’000 sterline per una soluzione entro 1°, di 15’000 sterline per una soluzione entro due terzi di grado, e di 20’000 sterline per una soluzione entro mezzo grado.\n\nAl giorno d’oggi, 20’000 sterline equivalgono all’incirca a 3milioni di euro, e poco più di 3,5milioni di dollari US.\n\nImmediatamente arrivano alla Commissione molte possibili soluzioni, che implementano degli orologi ancora più precisi, o delle misure legate alle distanze lunari. Molte di queste soluzioni arrivano, come è consuetudine a quel tempo, sotto forma di crittogramma , in modo da preservare la priorità di una invenzione o una scoperta senza però pubblicarla “in chiaro”, evitando quindi indebite appropriazioni.\n\nAd ogni modo, queste soluzioni non risolvono il problema, e si dovrà attendere una ventina d’anni affinché un’invenzione possa almeno in parte arrivare a una soluzione.\n\nIl costruttore di orologi\n\nIl personaggio di cui parleremo ora è John Harrison, figlio di un carpentiere dello Yorkshire, nato nel 1693. Dopo aver lavorato con il padre, insieme al fratello inizia nel 1727 a costruire orologi di precisione: ad esempio un pendolo detto “a griglia”, il cui apparato risente meno delle variazioni di temperatura4.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/0600f801-c8bf-4242-81d6-c42215ba5731_1280x1564.jpeg)\n\nRitratto di John Harrison, opera di Thomas King.\n\nDopo aver conosciuto i dettagli della competizione presentati dal Longitude Act, a partire dal 1730, e con l’aiuto economico di George Graham, uno dei costruttori di orologi più famosi del suo tempo, inizia la costruzione delle macchine. Oggi vengono identificate con le sigle H1, H2, e così via, e sono i diversi prototipi presentati da Harrison alla Commissione, e testati sia a terra che in mare. H1 viene completato nel 1735, H2 nel 1739, H3 solo nel 1759, e testato durante la Guerra dei Sette Anni, nel 1761, insieme alla macchina H4, la più recente.\n\nNonostante la H4 soddisfacesse appieno i requisiti per assicurarsi il premio più grande proposto dalla Commissione, Harrison dovette aspettare il 1773 per ricevere la totalità del premio.\n\nInoltre, anche un altro metodo di cui abbiamo già parlato dimostrò di funzionare: il metodo delle distanze lunari, che richiede di misurare la posizione delle stelle fisse rispetto alla Luna, e dai valori diversi che si ottengono in diversi parti del globo calcolare la longitudine.\n\nEntrambi questi metodi erano inizialmente poco praticabili, il primo per via dell’alto costo di costruzione di orologi così precisi, e il secondo per il tempo necessario per eseguire i calcoli necessari.\n\nCol tempo, entrambi i metodi diventarono più diffusi, perché la costruzione in scala degli orologi ne abbatté il costo, e per via di semplificazioni nei calcoli.\n\nIn tutto questo, come interviene la cicloide?\n\nL’Elena della geometria\n\nPartiamo dal pendolo, studiato estesamente da Galileo. L’equazione che lega il periodo del pendolo per piccole oscillazioni fu ottenuta da Christiaan Huygens, uno scienziato nederlandese del XVII secolo CE, ed è la seguente:\n\ndove T è il periodo del pendolo, ovvero il tempo che passa affinché il pendolo passi in un punto e poi vi ritorni, g è l’accelerazione di gravità, e L la lunghezza del pendolo.\n\nCome si vede, il periodo del pendolo dipende dalla lunghezza del pendolo stesso. Questo è uno dei problemi da risolvere se si vuole rendere il pendolo capace di misurare il tempo con precisione, indipendentemente dalla lunghezza del pendolo, che può variare, ad esempio, per via di temperatura o umidità.\n\nHuygens è considerato l’inventore dell’orologio a pendolo, avendo creato il primo esemplare nel 1656. Lo stesso Huygens però si rende conto, come aveva già fatto Marin Mersenne - studioso francese attivo qualche decennio prima di Huygens - che il pendolo non ha oscillazioni isocrone , ovvero che il periodo delle oscillazioni non è indipendente dalla ampiezza delle oscillazioni, cosa che invece pensava Galileo.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1de2082d-6764-497b-9d55-9b331919b854_1280x1677.jpeg)\n\nChristiaan Huygens, opera di Caspar Netscher (1671).\n\nPer questo motivo, Huygens studia un modo per permettere l’isocronismo del pendolo, e lo trova in una figura detta cicloide .\n\nLa cicloide è la curva che viene a formarsi quando un punto di una circonferenza rotola lungo una linea retta (come nella figura qui sotto).\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/0e67fe32-ef5f-461c-ac30-3d4f54db8963_400x200.gif)\n\nCicloide. Crediti qui.\n\nHuygens mostrò che quando si fa oscillare un pendolo tra due curve cicloidi, il pendolo che si ottiene ha lo stesso periodo indipendentemente dalla velocità delle oscillazioni.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/37017733-9040-4d50-bf98-bb5b861aab75_360x232.gif)\n\nOscillazioni “cicloidi” del pendolo. Crediti qui.\n\nL’equazione della cicloide, che permette di disegnarla su un piano cartesiano, è la seguente:\n\ndove r è il raggio del cerchio che facciamo “rotolare” sull’asse x.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/7d83722a-0133-4c4f-8a5a-399fc6aad634_735x398.gif)\n\nCrediti qui.\n\nIl titolo di questo paragrafo è “l’Elena della geometria”, e il motivo è legato sia alle contese sulla sua scoperta, che alcuni datano agli antichi greci, altri a Galileo, altri ancora a Mersenne, che alle sue meravigliose proprietà.\n\nTorniamo all’orologio costruito da Harrison. L’inventore inglese utilizza la cicloide per rendere il meccanismo isocrono, e migliorare le prestazioni dal modello H3 al modello H4. Di seguito lo schema pubblicato ne “ I principi dell’orologio di Mr Harrison” , pubblicato nel 1767.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ac6e370d-0065-4aa0-8aa0-90dcd9ab0133_595x881.jpeg)\n\nDisegni dell’orologio H4. Crediti qui.\n\nNel progetto di Harrison, la cicloide compare nelle curve sopra in cerchio in alto a sinistra. Di seguito un dettaglio dell’immagine di sopra.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/952f1692-7f23-4fa2-8641-0d0cd15c6e56_468x548.png)\n\nall’interno dell’ellisse vedi quelle curve che partono dall’alto a scendono a formare quelle specie di triangoli al cui centro c’è la lettera b ? Quelle sono rami di cicloidi.\n\nE’ con questo nuovo meccanismo, più stabile e accurato, che Harrison riesce a superare i requisiti richiesti dal Longitude Act del 1714 e a dotare le navi inglesi degli strumenti necessari per svolgere le attività di ricerca negli oceani. Dopo alcuni decenni, la costruzione in serie degli orologi di questo tipo ne permetteranno la diffusione su tutte le navi della flotta inglese, e anche altri paesi utilizzeranno questa invenzione.\n\nQuanto ad Harrison, muore il 24 Marzo 1776, otto mesi dopo il ritorno del Capitano Cook da un viaggio che aveva dimostrato in modo inequivocabile che quel tipo di orologio era efficace durante la navigazione5.\n\nAl giorno d’oggi i sistemi più avanzati permettono di ottenere una accuratezza che è dell’ordine dei centimetri, abbastanza per evitare isolotti e scogli, abbastanza da evitare il disastro delle Isole di Scilly.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/81674adf-2e63-4b29-82be-77d0e4fc88e2_2524x2500.jpeg)\n\nLe Isole di Scilly al largo della Gran Bretagna. Credits qui.\n\nArticoli della serie “sul moto della Terra”:\n\nBibliografia:\n\nGreenwich time and the discovery of the longitude, by Howse, Derek (Oxford University Press 1980)\n\nThe quest for longitude : the proceedings of the Longitude Symposium (Harvard University Press 1996)\n\nQuesta newsletter è una di tre: le altre due sono Last Scattering Surface, e Space of Sound.\n\nTutte le pubblicazioni sono gratuite e puoi consultare tutti gli articoli senza paywall.\n\nSe vuoi, puoi iscriverti qui e qui.\n\nInfine, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n\nCiao e a presto!\n\nNote\n\n1 il testo, qui proposto in traduzione, viene da “The Last Voyage of Sir Clowdisley Shovel”, di May W.E. (1960)\n\n2 come scrive A.J. Turner in “In the Wake of the Act, but Mainly Before”, parte del libro “The quest for longitude : the proceedings of the Longitude Symposium”.\n\n3 D. Howse, Greenwich time and the discovery of the longitude, p. 90.\n\n4 la precisione di un pendolo quando viene usato come apparato di misura del tempo dipende dalla uniformità dei movimenti del pendolo, che ha una certa lunghezza e nel caso di escursioni termiche tende ad accorciarsi e ad allungarsi: poiché è la lunghezza del pendolo la grandezza legata alla precisione della misura, un buon pendolo deve subire piccolissime variazioni di lunghezza al variare della temperatura.\n\n5 D. Howse, Greenwich time and the discovery of the longitude, p. 72.\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_eng-on-the-motion-of-the-earth-sun.md": "Disclaimer #1: questo articolo è in inglese, la versione in italiano si può leggere qui.\n\nDisclaimer #1: this episode is the first of a series which will contain more historical and philosophical episodes, alongside more astrophysical pieces. The former will be published on this newsletter, Heralding Time , while the latter will be published on Last Scattering Surface . If you want, you can subscribe to both.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/02c8246e-4225-423b-af9e-2e7c7d49f4a4_1080x1350.png)\n\nAt dawn or dusk, look for a luminous point in the sky. It won’t be flashing like an airplane, and it won’t move so quickly. It crosses the sky in just under five minutes, and it might become as bright as Jupiter or Venus.\n\nI would be very happy if any of the readers of this series titled on the motion of the Earth were not currently on the planet, but rather on that luminous point. I don’t think this is actually happening (if I were wrong, I’d be happy to know!). If I had written this piece before October 31, 2000, I would be certain; since November 2000, however, not all humans live on Earth. Anyway, whether you inhabit the terrestrial ground or are astronauts on the ISS, we are all bound to the planet we inhabit or return to: Earth. And we have been since the dawn of human history, since when the relationship with Nature was much more intimate and direct than in contemporary society.\n\nThe sky\n\nFor a member of any human community, the relationship with Earth was expressed not only in the relationship with the soil and everything it offered, plants, trunks, trees, stones, rocks, animals, prey and predators, but also with the sky above them.\n\nThe daytime sky, dominated by the Sun and atmospheric agents, which for a long time were “celestial” objects just as much as the planets and stars; but also the Moon and planets, which sometimes visit the daytime sky, perhaps shortly before sunset or shortly after dawn.\n\nAnd the nighttime sky, full of stars and illuminated by the Moon. Night comes at the end of each day, and for a member of an ancient society the stars are always there, night after night, apparently still up in the sky; observing them for a sufficient number of nights, however, one notices that they follow a path: some always remain above the horizon, others after a while are no longer visible because they die below the horizon. And the Moon has an even more easily observable cycle: in about 28 days it is a disk, then it begins to fade, becomes a crescent, and then disappears. After a few days it reappears, and it is a new Moon, regenerated, reborn, or is it always itself?\n\n“ The sky is an instrument for ancient societies ,” writes astronomer E. C. Tubb in Echoes of the Ancient Times (1983), who used and consulted the sky to obtain a sense of cyclicity of time, to enjoy the symmetry of movements that celestial bodies painted on it, and to trust that Nature was predictable . Every civilisation, complex or simple, has devised a theory about the movements of the sky, and by reflection about the place that Earth occupies in the world, understood as we today understand the Cosmos or Universe.\n\nThe Sun\n\nThe cycles that every human can observe within one terrestrial day are the diurnal rotation of Earth, that is, the Sun moving from east to west during the day, and the stars doing likewise during the night. The word orient has its etymology in the Latin solem orientem , which means rising Sun ( orientem comes from the verb orior , which means to rise); occident, similarly, comes from the Latin solem occidentem , which means dying Sun ( occidentem comes from the verb occido , which means—among various meanings—to fall or die). For an observer who lived only one day, having risen shortly before dawn, the Sun rises in the east, fire red, travels its path in the sky during the day, shines and burns and warms the earth, then falls in the west, colors red again before disappearing, symmetrically to what had happened at dawn. Other names for east and west are from Old Norse: the origin of these names, together with those of north and south, refers to the names with which four dwarfs of Norse mythology are presented in the Poetic Edda , a collection of poems useful for knowing Norse mythology. We will talk about this.\n\nThe Night\n\nThe stars, then. Observing them day after day, for an entire year, an Egyptian priest observes and records that some stars never descend below the horizon line, that line that delimits the dome, the vault, the canvas on which the movements of the stars occur. These are the imperishable stars , and it is there that the pharaohs go after death. Today we call them circumpolar stars, since they follow a circular path in the sky, around an ideal point, called the celestial pole . In our era, the star that performs the function of pole star (in the northern hemisphere) is part of the constellation Ursa Minor , Polaris .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/21d945dc-0adf-4c4a-bd4e-3096b421701a_3000x2400.jpeg)\n\nTop left, the constellation of Ursa Minor to which Polaris belongs. Actually, Polaris is a system of three stars, Polaris A, Polaris Ab, and Polaris B, 430 light-years away from the Solar System. The first two orbit on average at a distance of 18.5 Astronomical Units (AU) from each other, while Polaris A is 2400 AU away from Polaris B. One AU is the average distance of Earth from the Sun, about 150 million kilometers. Credits here.\n\nThe southern hemisphere does not have a star as bright as Polaris near the south pole: therefore a constellation, the Southern Cross , is used as a reference point.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2754a677-c1c0-44d6-a385-eefa2025b134_1800x1200.jpeg)\n\nThe four brightest stars represent the Southern Cross, the asterism used in the southern hemisphere in the same way that Polaris is used in the northern hemisphere. Credits here.\n\nThe role of pole star is temporary: due to Earth’s movement, the position of stars in the sky changes, and in the past and future, stars different from Polaris have assumed and will assume the function of reference point for the north pole.\n\nWhat is the pole for ancient civilisations? It is a cosmic axis, a real pole, raised to the sky, a tree, a mountain, a staff. Today it is an imaginary axis that represents Earth’s axis of rotation, and which intercepts the celestial sphere at two points: the north pole and the south pole.\n\nThe fourth brightest star in the sky, Arcturus , is called Marpeankurrk in Aboriginal culture, and is associated with the ancestor who had discovered the bittur , or termite larvae, considered an excellent source of protein. The bittur was available from August to the end of September, the same period when Marpeankurrk was visible. For this society, which as far as we know did not use stars to navigate at night, the stars represent ancestors, and are the mirror of things that could be found on Earth.\n\nThe first use of symbolic notation to represent the sky was found in the Dordogne region of France. Abri Blanchard , the site of the discovery, dated around 36000 BCE, contains an eagle bone on which signs are carved, which have been associated with a sequence of days: the entire sequence seems to represent a lunar cycle.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/47483444-6615-4b13-8457-6cc29c7b5ea4_3892x1444.jpeg)\n\nThe plaque at Abri Blanchard. On the left: the signs representing the sequence associable with the lunar cycle. Credits Don Hitchcock.\n\nDuring the year the position of the Sun changes, not only during the day, but day after day. There are two moments during the year when this movement seems not to exist, or to be somewhat less visible: on these days the sun seems to rise always in the same point, and so it happens at sunset. The solstice, which comes from the Latin sol sistere , represents the “ stopping of the Sun ,” and occurs around June 21, when in the northern hemisphere the Sun reaches its maximum “height” in the sky, and around December 21, when the Sun occupies the minimum “height.”\n\nThe two solstices are the reversal points of the Sun’s path in the ecliptic, which is the apparent path that the Sun takes during the year.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/deada32d-675f-44d5-bc54-2f18d2b37f6e_1760x620.png)\n\nVisualization of the solar analemma (the shape resembling an 8) obtained for every hour of the day in a location in Iceland (Longitude: -18.15 Latitude: 64.00). Credits here.\n\nThe ancient astronomer who observes the Moon and traces its changes, its phases , divides the year into 12 lunar cycles, called months . The word month in English has its roots in the Proto-Indo-European * meh₁- , which means to measure. In Italian, mese comes from the Latin menses , from the Greek ménē , arriving at the same root * meh₁- ; Men is a lunar divinity venerated in the Anatolian peninsula from the times of Babylonian civilisations until the Roman conquest.\n\nThe Sun and Moon are not the only objects that wander in the sky; other planets also err: planet in fact comes from the Greek plànētes astéres , wandering stars . For a Babylonian astronomer, and until the Copernican revolution, planet meant any celestial body different from fixed stars, and from comets , which were considered differently. Therefore, the Sun , Moon , Mercury , Venus , Mars , Jupiter , Saturn were planets. The other two planets of the Solar System (Uranus and Neptune) were not known, and would be observed only in the modern era. The path of the planets is close to that of the sun, in a band that composes the Zodiac .\n\nThe Chaldean astronomer, an active member of society, had the task of observing the sky and recording the position of stars and planets. Already around 3800 BCE in the kingdom of Sargon of Akkad, priest astronomers transcribed stellar accounts on clay tablets. The length of the terrestrial year was measured within 0.01% of the current correct value. From the accounts of clay tablets dated from 650 BCE to 50 BCE, we know that Babylonian astronomers steadily recorded the position of 30 stars to measure celestial coordinates. As Arthur Koestler writes in Sleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe , these observations were Exact Science, and allowed predictions to be made, despite the mythological character being the theoretical basis of the observations themselves.\n\nThe Gods\n\nFor a member of an ancient society, the planets had unique qualities and properties: their regular motions (the Sun and Moon), the greater brightness compared to fixed stars, the relative positions they occupied in the sky, all this placed them in a particular category.\n\nThey were gods who governed the sky, not limiting themselves to inhabiting it.\n\nFor the Egyptians, the Sun and Moon are the eyes of Horus, and the goddess of the sky, Nut, has a name that means “She who shines.” The supreme god of the Sumerians, Any (or An ) shares the symbol with which it is written with Diugir , which means “shining.” Any translates to sky , or high . In Indo-European languages Djevos means “He who governs the sky”; from this word comes Dyaus in Sanskrit, Jovis in Latin, and Zeus in Greek. Jupiter comes from Dyauspitar , or Zeuspater , which means father Zeus, and Zeus is connected to the idea of “shining,” “brilliant.” The Inti people, in the Inca region of Peru, call the Sun Tonatiuh , “ He who advances shining ”.\n\nThe Moon in Ancient Egypt is Khosnu , the runner . In Babylon it was Sin , the lord of knowledge. For the Desana people of South America the moon is the nocturnal sun.\n\nJupiter is associated with gods who govern the world with law: this is due to its “regular” character in the sky, as it is the planet (known to the ancients) that more than any other follows the ecliptic.\n\nVenus, to which the cult of Ishtar in Mesopotamia is associated, is simultaneously the morning star and the evening star, since it is particularly visible at dawn and sunset. To Ishtar and consequently to Venus was associated the symbol of Bennu , a bird similar to a heron that belongs to Osiris, the god of death and resurrection. It is no coincidence that Ishtar is also the goddess of the afterlife, dying at each sunset and being born again with the following dawn.\n\nMercury is Set for the Egyptians, and Nebo in Babylon. To these divinities was associated the role of messenger of the gods, and probably this role was due to the behavior of the planet, observed year after year: it is the fastest planet to travel from west to east along the ecliptic, to overtake the Sun and return in the opposite direction.\n\nMars is visible to the naked eye as a planet redder than others: this would be enough to associate its color with blood, and therefore with war. In Babylon they associated it with Nergal , god of war; so also the analogous Greek god Ares and the Roman god Mars .\n\nSaturn was Ninib for the Babylonians, Horus for the Egyptians and Cronos for the Greeks.\n\nStars were also associated with divinities, sometimes minor ones. For the Aztecs the warrior god Tezcatlipoca was associated with Ursa Major; however, it did not represent a bear, but rather the warrior whose name means Smoking Mirror: the god was represented with the left foot missing, because during the year a part of the constellation of Ursa descends below the horizon, and is not entirely visible. Even the gods are subject to the limits of our observations.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/e1b35582-311f-4a44-a121-74dbd7feb1a9_722x722.png)\n\nTezcatlipoca, the warrior-god, associated with Ursa Major. Do you see them?(Credits here)\n\nEvery civilisation has investigated the skies, then: whether they are seen as the dwelling of gods or ancestors, or places of symmetry and regularity, or all these things together. A. Koestler states that “ Science emerges in the form of Janus ,” that is, it simultaneously contains the objective rigor of scientific research and the personal desire to connect Nature to myth. In the next episodes we will see that every astronomical theory about the nature of the world and the motion of Earth rests on the knowledge and thought of the time in which it was formulated, but also on all the theories that preceded it, whether they are in agreement or disagreement with the theory itself.\n\nAstronomy has as many faces as there are skies it scrutinizes: countless, yet united in a single vault.\n\nBibliography:\n\nEchoes of the Ancient Skies, by E. C. Tubb (New York: Harper & Row 1983)\n\nAn Encyclopedia of Cosmologies and Myth in Ancient Astronomy, by Clive Ruggles (ABC-CLIO 2005)\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man's Changing Vision of the Universe, by Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_eng-on-the-motion-of-the-earth-three.md": "Disclaimer #1: questo articolo è in inglese, la versione in italiano si può leggere qui.\n\nDisclaimer #2: this episode is the first of a series which will contain more historical and philosophical episodes, alongside more astrophysical pieces. The former will be published on this newsletter, Heralding Time , while the latter will be published on Last Scattering Surface . If you want, you can subscribe to both. The first chapter is here.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/796c5941-4043-4ac1-a4bc-33adaf0d62ad_1080x1350.png)\n\nIn the first episode, Egyptian priests, Babylonian astronomers, gods and warriors appeared to populate the sky, with order governed by shining divinities.\n\nIn this episode, we encounter the civilisations of Asia between the Mediterranean, the Red Sea, and the Persian Gulf: Egypt and the river, Mesopotamia and the rivers, the Hebrew world and the Arab world with the one creator god.\n\nFor the civilisations of Mesopotamia, the world is circular; for the kingdom of Egypt, a rectangular box: for the peoples of these kingdoms, the world could be anything they imagined, says A. Koestler, whom we already met in the first episode.\n\nThe objects in the sky have paths that are overall comprehensible, repetitive, cyclical, and quite predictable. One could then seek meaning in all this, and we have already seen that this is indeed what humanity has always tried to do: seek a celestial order that reflected the desired social order, or be influenced by it to build one on Earth that mirrored it.\n\nThe Nile within me, and the Milky Way above me\n\nCosmology and astronomy in Egypt span the over three thousand years of the country’s history (~3000 BCE - ~30 CE) as an independent kingdom, continuously transforming and adding ideas and suggestions: if the sky represents the order of the world, and pharaohs live in the sky after death, then what changes on Earth will be reflected in the sky. Furthermore, the kingdom is vast enough to allow different cosmological streams to flourish in as many cities.\n\nFirst of all, the Egyptians are (almost never) disturbed by neighbouring populations. The Nile valley is the privileged direction toward which an Egyptian pharaoh looks to administer the kingdom; he doesn’t need to worry about anything else; the Mediterranean Sea is a border. The kingdom is desert and oasis, and all around there are mountains that enclose and protect the country; the mountains are so important as to define the natural border: “foreign country” has as its symbol a stylised mountain range, 𓈉.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9e00c53e-8484-4549-965c-0801b4aa1a88_1090x556.jpeg)\n\nThe symbol for foreign lands in hieroglyphic writing. Credits here.\n\nThe kingdom extends to the “Gate of the South,” near Elephantine, Cebu or Abu for the Egyptians, in the Aswan region. At the four corners of the kingdom are four mountains that support the sky. The two boundaries of the North-South axis are water boundaries, and water is also everything that surrounds the world: the Great Circuit , or the Great Circular Ocean contain the world, which the Nile divides in two. The water of the Ocean, the Nile, and rain all come from the first of the gods, Num .\n\nThe Milky Way is the river in the sky, like the Nile on Earth.\n\nThe Sun and Moon move in the sky, and when the Sun sets, death arrives, until a new dawn, which is the moment when the Sun, after traveling under the Earth, returns to illuminate Egypt. The Sun lives a human life every day, and the Moon is also alive and changeable, changing shape during the month. The Sun is the god Râ , and the Moon Yââhu Aûhû , and sometimes they are attacked by a serpent: when this happens, eclipses occur. The stars move in the sky, and sometimes disappear. Some are linked to what happens on Earth: Sirius is visible in the days preceding the annual flooding of the Nile. The five known planets were Bonû , which at sunset was Ûati and at dawn Tiû-nûtiri , or “the god who greets the Sun before its arrival” (Venus), Sobkû (Mercury), Doshiri (Mars), Ûapshetatûi (Jupiter), and Kahiri (Saturn).\n\nIn the beginning there were primordial waters, and a primordial abyss of waters: “ in infinity, nothingness, nowhere, and darkness .” After this introduction, and the idea that the world is governed by Ma’at, that is, by order, personified by a goddess with a headdress of ostrich feathers, cosmogonies differ depending on the place where they are born. For an Egyptian astronomer, the stories of the world come from Khnum (Hermopolis), Iunu (Heliopolis), and Men-Nefer (Memphis).\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/350b45b8-c7ca-4682-b656-0a38f0b32ef0_1240x1290.png)\n\nThe three religious sites we discuss in this section: Khnum (Hermopolis), Iunu (Heliopolis), and Men-Nefer (Memphis).\n\nKhnum\n\nThe Greek name comes from the divinity of wisdom, which for the Egyptians was Thot, and which the Greeks associated with Hermes Trismegistus, but Khnum translates as “the eighth city.” The genies of the world were Nau and Naunet , lords of what is deep; Huh and Hauhet , gods of what has no limit; Kuk and Kakwet , guardians of what is darkness; and Amun and Amaunet , sovereigns of what is invisible. These genies formed the primordial egg of Num, from which light and air emerged. In Thebes it is told that this egg was produced by a goose symbol of the Great Primordial Spirit, Kenken Wer , which was the first being to produce a sound (Kenken Wer can be translated as “he who cackles”).\n\nIn another version of this story, the waters came from a lotus flower from which an infant was born, the Sun. At dawn the Sun is born from the lotus flower, and returns to it after sunset, when the flower closes its petals.\n\nIunu\n\nThe Greek name means “city of the sun,” and Iunu means “the Pillars.” Here the god is Atum, “He who is Complete,” who emerged from the primordial waters in the form of a hill (according to other sources, sitting or standing on a hill). For some, he is the son of Nun . He represents the small elevations of terrain that form when water retreats after Nile floods. The hill, the symbol of this divinity, is remembered by the Egyptians in the construction of pyramids, to symbolise the Primordial Hill.\n\nIn Utterance #600, one of the Pyramid Texts, that is, the oldest religious utterance texts found of Egyptian civilisation, dating around 2400 BCE, it is told that Atum made the world starting from himself (in his image?). He created Shu and Tefenet by spitting. This action designates a characteristic of Egyptian philosophy, for which evoking the name of something corresponds to creating that something. As testimony to this, Shu and Tefenet originate in ishish , a verb that also translates as “to spit.” Shu represents air, and Tefenet humidity. The first a masculine divinity, and the second feminine, together they generate Geb , the god of earth, and Nut , the goddess of sky. The generation of green Geb and blue Nut occurs when Shu separates the two siblings from their embrace.\n\nIn another story, Nut marries Geb, but the sun-god Râ disagrees: for this reason he separates them, cursing them never to be able to conceive offspring in the future on any day of the year. Yet another story tells that the god Thoth , taking pity on Nut, managed to win from the Moon, after playing the game of checkers, 1/70 of the planet’s light time. He thus creates five additional days, to add to the Egyptian year; and it is in these additional days that Nut conceives Osiris , Horus , Set , Isis , and Nephthys . The Egyptian year was until that moment 360 days: it thus becomes the astronomical year of 365 days.\n\nWater surrounds the world; before the world there was only water. Humanity also comes from water: the word for humanity, romet , comes from remeyet, the tears of Neb-er-Djer , the Universal Lord.\n\nMen-Nefer\n\nAt Khnum it is told that Atum has no consort, and that he generated his own children “with his own hand”; at Men-Nefer the Primordial Hill is Ta-tjenen , the land that rises.\n\nMen-Nefer has as god Ptah, who generates Nun and Nuret. The old gods are also contained in Ptah and generated by him. The creation of the world occurs through the heart of Ptah, seat of intelligence, from which Horus is born, and from his tongue, from which descends command and the power of the word, which gave rise to Thoth.\n\nOnce the creation of the world has occurred, and humanity has populated the Earth, the order of the world must be maintained as it has always been. The chaos that is exiled to the borders of the world must be kept there, and it is the actions of man and the gods that allow it. A balance, therefore: we return to the concept of Ma’at, to cosmic order, to earthly order, finally to ethics. In the world it represents truth and justice. Every day must be preserved, from its creation to its departure with night; the pharaoh reigns for this, and his temples are a testimony to it.\n\nBetween the Tigris and Euphrates, the Earth is Flat\n\nThe region of Mesopotamia is inseparably linked to the fertile plains bordering the Tigris and Euphrates rivers, and its extension today would cover Iraq, Iran, Syria, and Turkey. The civilisation we will discuss, and the cuneiform texts that still speak to us today, are dated between 3000 BCE and 300 BCE. Cosmological ideas come from texts of the first millennium BCE.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f84e083a-67d4-41ba-a15c-a0dc62c201dc_1240x1076.png)\n\nThe region of Mesopotamia. In addition to the two rivers Tigris and Euphrates, some important cities of the region are also highlighted.\n\nThe region, so fertile and crossed by the rivers we have discussed, was at the center of the world for a Sumerian farmer, or a priest of Babylon, or an Assyrian warrior. The Babylonian story of the creation of the world, Enuma Elish , speaks of a world born from liquid chaos. In the beginning there is no sky, but only fresh waters, Apsu , and salt waters, Ti’amat .\n\nThe presence of water as a creative element is common to sources in Mesopotamia, and therefore in Syria, but also in Egypt, Palestine, and Egypt. The presence of such fertile land, where vegetation grows spontaneously, does not lead the creator of myths to imagine a paradise in the sky that produces what humanity needs through rain, precisely because plants grow alongside the Tigris and Euphrates rivers. These rivers had their sources in underground springs, primordial springs created by Apsu, the master god, called Enki in Sumerian and Ea in Babylon.\n\nAfter Apsu and Ti’amat come Lahmu and Lahamu , who form the horizon with silt. The sky is the dwelling of Anshar , from whom Anu is born, paradise; under the earth dwells Kishar , from whom Nudimut is born, the earth. Anu and Nudimut are imprisoned by Ti’amat, but are freed by Marduk , descendant of Kishar and Anshar, when he cuts Ti’amat in two in her dwelling, separating them. Thus the sky and earth are formed. In some texts, the earth is Nippur , and Eridu is water.\n\nCosmology in Mesopotamia describes the Earth at the center, the sky and celestial bodies above it, and cosmic waters and the afterlife below it. The stars are fixed, the planets move.\n\nThe Earth is a disk - although in the northern region the Earth is instead “a mountain”; with the extension of the kingdom, it becomes a large disk, but of limited extension, due to the motion of the Sun and other celestial bodies. The Sun travels under the Earth every night; so does the Moon. The extension of the Earth is surrounded by a Khubur , Salt River, beyond which there are (8?) “ triangular regions .”\n\nBabylonian astronomy reached a dead end; the problem lies, according to Lambert, in the fact that it was not easily extendable and generalizable: one example above all, the presence of a flat Earth instead of a spherical one. Most of the important contributions we receive from cosmology coming from this area come from Chaldean astronomy, which we will discuss briefly when we talk about Greek philosophers. It is from here indeed that many geometric and astronomical theories developed by the Greeks come.\n\nCreatio ex nihilo?\n\nThe Hebrew cosmological tradition is as ancient as its people, and extends to the beginning of the Late Middle Ages. One thing that is evident is that Hebrew culture adopted the cosmological framework of the civilisation in which it lived.\n\nIf for the Babylonians the Earth is flat, then the biblical narrative is also consistent with this description: the Earth is a flat disk, and at the end of the world there are four kanefot , corners. Above the Earth there is shamayin , the sky, and rakia, the firmament. The Earth lies on pillars, and the firmament has an end. The Sun and Moon move in the firmament, or under it. Under the Earth there is Sheol , the dwelling of the dead. Waters (remember the Babylonians?) live both above the firmament and under the Earth; the latter formed the seas and oceans at the moment of creation. In the depths of the Earth there is Tehom (doesn’t it remind you of Ti’amat?), the great depth, from which the waters of the flood come.\n\nThe creation of the world occurs thanks to God, the Creator; the root of the verb bara, to create, does not mean creatio ex nihilo , creation from nothing, but creation “out of something (or someone).” Only later will the concept of creation from nothing arrive (in the Books of Maccabees, around the I-II century BCE).\n\nIn rabbinic literature, cosmic speculation is not encouraged; nevertheless, various theories about the nature of the world are born. Perhaps God created the world we inhabit after having created and destroyed many others; perhaps the Sun and Moon had the same size, but the Moon, protesting that it wanted to be larger, was made smaller.\n\nThe distance from Earth to the firmament is a unit of time, 500 years. If there are three firmaments, each will be 500 years away from the other. The Creator has 12 constellations for each host, and for each 30 legions, for each of which 30 cohorts, and again 30 maniples, and all have each 30 camps, and in each camp 365 thousand stars, a thousand for each day of the year.\n\nHow long will the Universe last? 6000 years, then it will be desolate for the next thousand, or 2000.\n\nAs we have said, Hebrew cosmology is influenced by the peoples with whom the Jews come into contact; in the 12th century BCE, Maimonides develops a cosmology starting from the neo-Platonic conception of the world, with nine spheres, for the Moon, Mercury, Venus, the Sun, Mars, Jupiter, Saturn, the stars, and the zodiac. In this vision, the spheres rotate around the Earth from East to West, and the color of the sky is an optical illusion; the spheres are transparent, without weight, without color. The Earth has a surface 40 times the surface of the Moon, and the Sun has a surface 170 times the surface of the Earth.\n\nOne Universe for One God\n\nIslamic cosmology is the set of Aristotelian and Ptolemaic theories, filtered through neo-Platonism and hermeticism, with characteristics of Gnostic worship. Thus summarises the source we used for this section, in which we speak of the vision of Islamic scholars.\n\nThe starting point is the creation of the Universe by the Creator God. There is no agreement, as in the Hebrew tradition, whether this occurred starting from the existing, or whether creation was ex nihilo . God created everything that is, and separated heaven from Earth, because before they were united. Heaven and Earth are formed respectively by seven heavens and seven Earths: this explains the presence of seven different climatic zones; and of the seven layers of Hell; above the layers of heaven there is a footstool, on which sits the throne of God. The Earth and the sub-lunar region are the place where minerals, plants, animals reside, formed by fire, air, water, and earth.\n\nThe celestial spheres host, in order of proximity from Earth: the Moon, Mercury, Venus, the Sun, Mars, Jupiter, Saturn, the fixed stars divided into the 12 regions of the zodiac, a ninth sphere. Called the “Encompassing Sphere” by Thabit ibn Kuwa , this sphere serves to explain the equinoxes.\n\nDespite observations disproving the presence of circular motions for planets, the geometric instruments of epicycles, eccentrics, and equants are used to save the phenomena : how often this has been done in history, we will see soon! Muslim scholars are divided between supporters of Ptolemy , like Ibn al-Hatham , who studies planetary motion with homocentric spheres, and the theory of solid spheres, because the void does not exist; and the Islamic Peripatetics, who critics of Ptolemy publish “A Correction to the Almagest,” they too however using the theory of homocentric spheres (which we will discuss when we meet the Greeks in this story).\n\nThe love for hypotheses and reasoning leads scholars to wonder if other types of motion could work: if for example, in addition to circular revolutionary motion, there could not be elliptical motions. In any case, as al-Biruni says, this type of debate is mainly intellectual, and the question of the nature of motions in the sky is a physical question, not astronomical. For these and other reasons, including a growing departure from philosophical rationality in favor of irrational mysticism, and reasons of political and religious order, from the X to the XVI century also in the Islamic world the cosmological debate stagnates, while it is slowly rediscovered in medieval Europe. But we will talk about this later.\n\nBibliography:\n\nEchoes of the Ancient Skies, by E. C. Tubb (Harper & Row 1983)\n\nAn Encyclopedia of Cosmologies and Myth in Ancient Astronomy, by Clive Ruggles (ABC-CLIO 2005)\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man's Changing Vision of the Universe, by Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, edited by C. Blacker and M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nCosmology of Ancient Egypt, by J.M. Plumley\n\nCosmology of Sumer and Babylon, by W.G. Lambert\n\nJewish Cosmology, by Louis Jacobs\n\nIslamic Cosmology, by Edith Jachimowicz\n\nAncient Light: our changing view of the Universe, by Alan Lightman (Cambridge 1991)\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_how-the-cycloid-saved-the-british.md": "# how the cycloid saved the British navy\n\nDisclaimer #1: questo articolo è in inglese. La versione in italiano è qui.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/248c7282-e634-4f06-8586-7ababd96471b_1572x1048.png)\n\nOn 29 September 1707 Admiral Sir Clowdisley Shovel with twenty-one ships of the Royal Navy sailed from Gibraltar for England.\n\nBritain was at war with France and, though Gibraltar had fallen into British hands in 1702, it was considered unwise for the larger ships of the fleet to remain in the Mediterranean during the winter.\n\nWeather on passage was not good. There were westerly gales from the 5th t o the first of October.\n\nThe 12nd and 13rd were squally, followed by two days of light winds.\n\nOn the 16th and 17th there were easterly gales and on the 19th north-westerly gales. On the 21st the sky cleared and several ships got observations for latitude, while sounding gave a depth of between 90 and 140 fathoms, showing that the fleet was on the edge of the Continental Shelf.\n\nThree ships having been detached to Falmouth for convoy duty on the 22nd, and no sun being visible all day, the remaining 18 ships hove to in the afternoon to obtain soundings.\n\nThen, satisfied that they were in the mouth of the English Channel and clear of all danger, the ships ran to the eastward before a favourable gale.\n\nAbout 7.30 p.m. the same day the Association, Eagle, and Romney struck the Gilstone Ledges in the Scilly Isles.\n\nOf the 1,200 men in the three ships, only one man was saved - the quartermaster of the Romney.\n\nSir Clowdisley’s body was found floating the following day and now lies in one of the largest and ugliest tombs in Westminster Abbey.\n\nThe St. George and Firebrand also struck the rocks but got off.\n\nThe latter, however, was badly holed and sank later, leaving only twenty-three survivors.\n\nThis is the beginning of chapter three of Derek Howse’s book, titled Greenwich Time and the Discovery of the Longitude , published in 19801. It is an account of the history of inventions and reasoning around the determination of longitude , mainly useful during navigation.\n\nThe disaster reported by the book’s author had been only the latest in a series for the English fleet, due not only to unfavourable weather conditions - fog, sudden ocean currents - but also to incorrect measurements of the position of landmasses.\n\nProblems of this type had been known for some time, and not only by the English navy: France, Spain, Holland, all nations that sailed the oceans. In any case, this particular disaster caused great concern among the English public, and its government decided to do something.\n\nThe Longitude Act\n\nThe story we will tell starts from the Longitude Act of 1714, one of the least controversial legislative acts proposed by the English Parliament, which took only 70 days to be transformed into law from the moment it was presented2, on June 17, 1714; Royal Assent was given on July 9 of the same year. The prize, for anyone who had “discovered longitude at sea,” was decided by the commission of experts called to decide on the responses to the petition: the commission included Isaac Newton , Samuel Clarke, Edmond Halley , and Roger Cotes.\n\nOn June 11 of that year Newton had presented to the House of Lords Committee the “state of the art” of methods - evidently insufficient, and some even impossible to implement - for measuring longitude at sea: he speaks first of a clock that measures time accurately, difficult to build so that it is precise despite the motion of the ship, temperature and humidity variations, and small variations in gravity at different latitudes.\n\nHe then moves on to a method already presented by Galileo that involved observing Jupiter’s satellites: the Italian scientist had proposed observing the planet’s moons during navigation, and recording their position comparing it with that recorded in “standard” situations - on land, that is.\n\nFrom the difference of the two measurements one would obtain the measurement of longitude.\n\nGalileo himself had realised that the proposal was unfeasible with the technology of the time due to the low precision of telescopes, and because of the ship’s motion.\n\nA third method uses the Moon, and the different moments when the Earth’s shadow covers the satellite during eclipses.\n\nThis method is also explained by Galileo, who however presents two contraindications: the first concerns the frequency with which eclipses occur, too few to allow precise navigation; while the second concerns errors in measurements that can reach even 8° of uncertainty3, too large to ensure correct navigation.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f9d116b2-b2a6-420d-893c-10424bb81d0f_1024x1212.jpeg)\n\nPortrait of Galileo Galilei, work by Justus Sustermans (1635).\n\nAfter enumerating them all, the Committee proposes the prize for the solution, based on its accuracy: a sum of £10,000 for a solution within 1°, £15,000 for a solution within two-thirds of a degree, and £20,000 for a solution within half a degree. Today, £20,000 is equivalent to approximately 3 million euros, and just over 3.5 million US dollars.\n\nImmediately many possible solutions arrive at the Committee, which implement even more precise clocks, or measurements related to lunar distances. Many of these solutions arrive, as is customary at that time, in the form of a cryptogram , in order to preserve the priority of an invention or discovery without publishing it “in clear,” thus avoiding undue appropriations.\n\nIn any case, these solutions do not solve the problem, and one will have to wait about twenty years for an invention to at least partially arrive at a solution.\n\nThe clockmaker\n\nThe character we will now talk about is John Harrison, son of a Yorkshire carpenter, born in 1693. After working with his father, together with his brother he begins from 1727 to build precision clocks: for example a pendulum called “gridiron,” whose apparatus is less affected by temperature variations4.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/0600f801-c8bf-4242-81d6-c42215ba5731_1280x1564.jpeg)\n\nPortrait of John Harrison, work by Thomas King.\n\nAfter learning the details of the competition presented by the Longitude Act, starting from 1730, and with the financial help of George Graham, one of the most famous clockmakers of his time, he begins the construction of the machines.\n\nToday they are identified with the abbreviations H1, H2, and so on, and are the various prototypes presented by Harrison to the Committee, and tested both on land and at sea. H1 was completed in 1735, H2 in 1739, H3 only in 1759, and tested during the Seven Years’ War, in 1761, together with the H4 machine, the most recent.\n\nDespite H4 fully satisfying the requirements to secure the largest prize proposed by the Committee, Harrison had to wait until 1773 to receive the entirety of the prize.\n\nMoreover, another method we have already discussed also proved to work: the method of lunar distances, which requires measuring the position of fixed stars relative to the Moon, and from the different values obtained in different parts of the globe calculate longitude.\n\nBoth these methods were initially impractical, the first because of the high cost of building such precise clocks, and the second because of the time needed to perform the necessary calculations.\n\nOver time, both methods became more widespread, because large-scale construction of clocks reduced their cost, and because of simplifications in calculations.\n\nIn all this, how does the cycloid intervene?\n\nThe Helen of geometry\n\nLet’s start with the pendulum, extensively studied by Galileo. The equation linking the period of the pendulum for small oscillations was obtained by Christiaan Huygens, a Dutch scientist of the XVII century CE, and is the following:\n\nwhere T is the period of the pendulum, that is the time that passes for the pendulum to pass through a point and then return to it, g is the acceleration of gravity, and L the length of the pendulum. As can be seen, the period of the pendulum depends on the length of the pendulum itself. This is one of the problems to solve if one wants to make the pendulum capable of measuring time precisely, independently of the length of the pendulum, which can vary, for example, due to temperature or humidity.\n\nHuygens is considered the inventor of the pendulum clock, having created the first example in 1656. Huygens himself however realizes, as Marin Mersenne had already done - a French scholar active a few decades before Huygens - that the pendulum does not have isochronous oscillations, that is, that the period of oscillations is not independent of the amplitude of oscillations, which Galileo instead thought.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1de2082d-6764-497b-9d55-9b331919b854_1280x1677.jpeg)\n\nChristiaan Huygens, work by Caspar Netscher (1671).\n\nFor this reason, Huygens studies a way to allow the isochronism of the pendulum, and finds it in a figure called the cycloid .\n\nThe cycloid is the curve that is formed when a point on a circumference rolls along a straight line (as in the figure below).\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/0e67fe32-ef5f-461c-ac30-3d4f54db8963_400x200.gif)\n\nCycloid. Credits here.\n\nHuygens showed that when a pendulum is made to oscillate between two cycloidal curves, the pendulum obtained has the same period independent of the speed of oscillations.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/37017733-9040-4d50-bf98-bb5b861aab75_360x232.gif)\n\n“Cycloidal” oscillations of the pendulum. Credits here here.\n\nThe equation of the cycloid, which allows it to be drawn on a Cartesian plane, is the following:\n\nwhere r is the radius of the circle we make “roll” on the x-axis.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/7d83722a-0133-4c4f-8a5a-399fc6aad634_735x398.gif)\n\nCredits here.\n\nThe title of this paragraph is “the Helen of geometry,” and the reason is linked both to disputes over its discovery, which some date to the ancient Greeks, others to Galileo, still others to Mersenne, and to its marvelous properties.\n\nLet’s return to the clock built by Harrison. The English inventor uses the cycloid to make the mechanism isochronous, and improve performance from the H3 model to the H4 model. Below is the diagram published in “ The Principles of Mr. Harrison’s Timekeeper ”, published in 1767.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ac6e370d-0065-4aa0-8aa0-90dcd9ab0133_595x881.jpeg)\n\nDrawings of the H4 clock. Credits here.\n\nIn Harrison’s design, the cycloid appears in the curves circled at the top left. Below is a detail of the image above.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/952f1692-7f23-4fa2-8641-0d0cd15c6e56_468x548.png)\n\nInside the ellipse do you see those curves that start from the top and descend to form those kinds of triangles at whose center there is the letter b ? Those are branches of cycloids.\n\nIt is with this new mechanism, more stable and accurate, that Harrison manages to exceed the requirements requested by the Longitude Act of 1714 and to equip English ships with the necessary instruments to carry out research activities in the oceans. After a few decades, mass production of clocks of this type will allow their diffusion on all ships of the English fleet, and other countries will also use this invention.\n\nAs for Harrison, he dies on March 24, 1776, eight months after Captain Cook’s return from a voyage that had unequivocally demonstrated that that type of clock was effective during navigation5.\n\nToday the most advanced systems allow obtaining an accuracy that is on the order of centimeters, enough to avoid islets and rocks, enough to avoid the disaster of the Scilly Isles.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/81674adf-2e63-4b29-82be-77d0e4fc88e2_2524x2500.jpeg)\n\nThe Scilly Isles off Great Britain. Credits here.\n\nRead the series “on the motion of the Earth”:\n\nBibliography:\n\nGreenwich time and the discovery of the longitude, by Howse, Derek (Oxford University Press 1980)\n\nThe quest for longitude : the proceedings of the Longitude Symposium (Harvard University Press 1996)\n\nNotes\n\n1 the text comes from “The Last Voyage of Sir Clowdisley Shovell,” by May W.E. (1960)\n\n2 as A.J. Turner writes in “In the Wake of the Act, but Mainly Before,” part of the book “The quest for longitude : the proceedings of the Longitude Symposium.”\n\n3 D. Howse, Greenwich time and the discovery of the longitude, p. 90.\n\n4 the precision of a pendulum when used as a time measuring apparatus depends on the uniformity of the pendulum’s movements, which has a certain length and in case of thermal variations tends to shorten and lengthen: since the length of the pendulum is the quantity linked to the precision of measurement, a good pendulum must undergo very small variations in length as temperature varies.\n\n5 D. Howse, Greenwich time and the discovery of the longitude, p. 72.\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_il-principio-indefinito-di-anassimandro.md": "# il principio indefinito di Anassimandro e il respiro cosmico di Anassimene\n\nDisclaimer #1: this article is in Italian. I will publish the English version next Wednesday.\n\nDisclaimer #2: questo pezzo fa parte di una serie, pubblicata sia su questa newsletter, Heralding Time , che su Last Scattering Surface . Se vuoi, puoi seguirle entrambe. Qui i capitoli I, II, III, IV, V.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/86bf5b8f-21f4-4b22-a340-bde9cfd9b18e_1080x1350.png)\n\nBentornati.\n\nNel precedente episodio abbiamo parlato di Mileto e di Talete, il primo filosofo secondo la tradizione della filosofia in Grecia.\n\nIn questo episodio parleremo degli altri due filosofi provenienti da Mileto, sentiremo cosa hanno da dire, capiremo come rispondono alle domande sull’origine del mondo e sulla sua composizione.\n\nHeralding Time è su Instagram. Puoi seguirlo qui.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/__ss-rehost__IG-meta-DP_M6usDF1N.jpg)\n\nAnassimandro\n\nDiogene Laerzio1 ci informa che Anassimandro, figlio di Prassiade, è il primo ad aver costruito degli \"orologi\", e nell’enciclopedia bizantina (la Suda , fonte quindi molto tarda) si parla di Anassimandro come di colui che ha inventato lo gnomone, strumento utile per la misurare la posizione del Sole, e che ha \"misurato\" gli equinozi e i solstizi. Inoltre, secondo Diogene fu il primo a disegnare una mappa delle terre e dei mari. La Suda cita inoltre alcuni scritti che avrebbe composto: “ Sulla Natura” , “ Il giro della Terra” , “ Sulle stelle fisse” , “ Il globo celeste” ; a proposito del primo, Barnes di una “versione naturalistica della Teogonia di Esiodo”2. Una leggenda narra che il filosofo abbia avvertito gli spartani di un imminente terremoto.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/4c388a53-37d9-42ab-9c3c-f594d9874a4b_2491x2500.jpeg)\n\nAnaximander - 1493 - Rijksmuseum, Netherlands - Public Domain.\n\nDiogene inserisce la data della morte del filosofo poco dopo la LVIII Olimpiade (547 BCE), intorno ai 64 anni. Apollodoro invece parla di Anassimandro nato 14 anni dopo Talete (quindi intorno al 610 BCE) e morto nello stesso anno della morte di questi (avvenuta intorno al 545 BCE). C’è quindi una discrepanza tra le due datazioni, ma è certo che i due filosofi fossero contemporanei a un certo punto, e si dice che Anassimandro sia stato “allievo” di Talete, ovvero che ne abbia sentito gli insegnamenti.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1ad4bff3-7d9f-4f3c-b164-320828083873_1240x1126.png)\n\nRiguardo lo gnomone ideato da Anassimandro: come abbiamo visto nel capitolo precedente, lo gnomone è una invenzione babilonese, e forse era già conosciuto da Talete, dunque la \"scoperta\" attribuita ad Anassimandro può al più riferirsi al fatto che ne abbia fatto uso durante la sua vita.\n\nRiguardo la mappa disegnata dal secondo filosofo di Mileto: questa fu effettivamente una delle prime dopo quella di Omero, e fu perfezionata da Ecateo, geografo di Mileto, seguendo come fonte Erodoto, storico greco del V secolo BCE.\n\nDiogene, citando Teofrasto, afferma che per Anassimandro il principio è l’ἄπειρον (apeiron) che traduciamo con Illimitato, Indefinito, Infinito .\n\nQuando parla di principio, probabilmente Anassimandro non si riferisce all’ἀρχή di cui abbiamo parlato a proposito di Talete, citato da Aristotele: il filosofo quindi non si riferisce alla forza che genera il mondo, ma alla sostanza di cui il mondo inizialmente è formato.\n\nL’ἄπειρον è traducibile con infinito ma non rappresenta l’infinito spaziale usato ancora oggi in fisica: e infatti insieme a infinito si inserisce indefinito , intendendo con questo che questa sostanza “primigenia” manca di confine, di limite, di definizione.\n\nOvvero che non può essere confinato, delimitato, definito.\n\nApeiron ha come radice a-peiras , ovvero senza limite, e peir ha il significato di \"attraversare\". Sembra quindi che il termine ἄπειρον rappresenti qualcosa che è impossibile da attraversare da parte a parte .\n\nPer Anassimandro ciò che non è definito non ha distinzione , nel senso che è una sostanza che contiene tutto senza distinzione .\n\nAristotele parla di ciò, dicendo che questo principio è un elemento al di là degli elementi, e che contiene una riserva infinita che si comporta come una sorgente da cui generare tutti gli elementi.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/def8d9b4-200b-484f-b3c1-39242eb43f0b_800x519.jpeg)\n\nMeteorite osservata l’11 Giugno 1867, illustrazione del 1875. Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / Internet Archive / California Digital Library\n\nAd ogni modo, non siamo sicuri di quale fosse l’interpretazione per Anassimandro. Sembra però, dai frammenti che abbiamo3, che questo Indefinito è per lui il luogo in cui gli opposti pagano \" l’uno all’altro la pena secondo l’ordine del tempo \", e da cui gli stessi opposti hanno origine4.\n\nL’Indefinito guida tutto e controlla tutto, la creazione e il suo opposto, ovvero la distruzione , che avvengono entrambe per necessità. Ciò avviene ciclicamente e senza fine, e uno dopo l’altro si creano e si distruggono innumerevoli mondi. L’ἄπειρον è molto probabilmente in moto, altrimenti come potrebbe quest’ultimo nascere da qualcosa che non lo contiene?\n\nE che tipo di moto contiene? Sembra che non debba averne di nessun tipo in particolare, perché se ne avesse uno definito, tutti gli altri come potrebbero nascere? Tutte le diverse caratteristiche delle cose emergono dall’ἄπειρον, separandosi ognuna dal proprio opposto, ma non sono contenute in esso inizialmente.\n\nIl mondo come possiamo osservarlo oggi emerge, per Anassimandro, dopo un processo di separazione e di differenziazione di ogni cosa dal suo opposto .\n\nKoestler5 parla di Anassimandro come del primo che ha ideato un sistema meccanicistico per l’Universo. Vediamo perché.\n\nAbbiamo una visione abbastanza chiara della sua idea di mondo, seguendo diverse fonti. Secondo Pseudo-Plutarco, Anassimandro descrive la Terra come un cilindro largo tre volte la sua lunghezza; concorde è anche Ippolito6. Secondo Aristotele, la Terra per Anassimandro è ferma al centro dell’Universo, ed è sospesa liberamente senza essere sostenuta da nulla (come invece avviene nel mondo di Talete, in cui la Terra è sospesa dall’acqua), e questo avviene per causa e merito del suo \" essere legata in modo uguale a tutte le cose \"7.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ec711e97-0367-4221-a708-51af6c518dff_1280x1280.png)\n\nLast Scattering Surface\n\nA story of a star - Part I Chasing the Sun…\n\nRead more\n\n3 years ago · 3 likes · Antonio Viscusi\n\nIl firmamento è sferico, e i pianeti e le stelle sono ruote di fuoco, circondate da una bolla d’aria: contengono delle aperture, da cui fuoriesce del fuoco, che è la fonte di luminosità di questi oggetti celesti.\n\nQuando queste aperture sono occultate - in che modo non viene detto - nel Sole o nella Luna, è in quel momento che avvengono le eclissi solari e lunari 8.\n\nLa Luna è luminosa in quanto contiene il fuoco come tutte le altre stelle, e non prende la sua luminosità dal Sole.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #5\n\nLe ruote piene di fuoco e circondate dall’aria presenti nella cosmologia di Anassimandro erano state \"viste\" qualche anno prima dal profeta ebreo Ezechiele, figlio di Buzì, intorno al 593 BCE in Mesopotamia:\n\nEzechiele 1,20: \"Dovunque lo spirito le avesse sospinte, le ruote andavano e ugualmente si alzavano, perché lo spirito degli esseri viventi era nelle ruote\"\n\nSe gli dei sono in cielo, e in cielo ci sono le stelle, non abitano forse nelle stelle gli dei?\n\nLa posizione degli astri è innovativa: secondo Ippolito e Aezio, Anassimandro pone le stelle fisse non in una sfera all’esterno, ma nel cerchio più vicino alla Terra; poi il cerchio della Luna, a una distanza pari a 18 volte il diametro della Terra; infine il Sole, a una distanza pari a 27 volte il diametro della Terra. Il Sole è grande tanto quanto la Terra, e in merito ai pianeti conosciuti all’epoca (Mercurio, Venere, Marte, Giove, Saturno) non sappiamo se Anassimandro li pone insieme alle stelle fisse o a una distanza intermedia tra le stelle fisse e la Luna.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/335a0039-e12d-4522-8253-4e3485009346_960x930.png)\n\nDescrizione del mondo di Anassimandro. Illustrazione di D.L. Couprie in Heaven And Earth In Ancient Greek Cosmology. Nell’illustrazione, che segue quella di Diels e Naddaf, il cerchio delle stelle è a nove diametri terrestri, il cerchio della Luna a 18, quello del Sole a 27. Credits qui.\n\nSappiamo però che i movimenti nel cielo avvengono tutti intorno alla Terra, e che sono dovuti al vento generato dalle esalazioni umide della Terra quando essa viene riscaldata dal calore del Sole. E’ al vento inoltre che si deve l’obliquità della eclittica, ovvero del percorso che il Sole compie nella sua orbita intorno alla Terra9.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #6\n\nA Babilonia, i numeri 3 e 9 avevano particolare importanza. In Egitto, gli astronomi selezionavano 36 δεκανοί (decani), stelle nel cielo disposte in modo tale che il loro sorgere nel cielo fosse distante l'uno dall'altro dieci gradi lungo periodi di dieci giorni, in modo da dividere l'anno in mesi.\n\nLa cosmologia di Anassimandro ha il primo cerchio 9 volte il diametro della Terra, il cerchio della Luna 18 volte quello della Terra, il cerchio del Sole 27 volte.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/09b6a396-3f77-47ef-adb3-8bc3c9a0462e_1612x826.png)\n\nCopia dell’illustrazione di Mugler con la descrizione dell’universo di Anassimandro. La Terra è il cilindro al centro, che forma un angolo con l’asse verticale - l’inclinazione dell’eclittica. La sfera è la sfera delle stelle, il primo cerchio è quello della Luna, il cerchio più esterno quello del Sole. Credits qui.\n\nL’universo di Anassimandro è a misura di dimensioni \"terrestri\": è la prima volta che accade fuori da un racconto mitico, in cui la filosofia si fa leggermente più quantitativa e assegna un ruolo ai numeri in termini di proporzione. Vedremo con Pitagora che ciò è forse il fondamento della astronomia greca.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #7\n\nL'ordine Terra, stelle, Luna, Sole è innovativo per la Grecia antica, ma non è originale nella storia umana: era lo standard nella cosmologia persiana.\n\nNei testi sacri del Dāmdāt Nask e del Pahlavi Dēnkart si legge che oltre il Sole c'è la luce imperitura. In persiano l'espressione anayra- significa \"senza inizio\", ovvero senza ayra.\n\nSe ἀρχή è il principio, anche ayra ha un significato simile.\n\nE’ strana, prima abbiamo detto innovativa, la scelta di porre il cerchio delle stelle fisse davanti il cerchio della Luna; sembra anche un’idea facile da confutare, in effetti: quante volte le stelle delle Pleiadi vengono occultate dalla presenza della Luna, dimostrando quindi che è la Luna a trovarsi più vicina alla Terra, e non il contrario?\n\nMa questa decisione potrebbe essere dovuta non tanto a qualche specifica osservazione astronomica, quanto all’idea che Anassimandro ha della natura di questi corpi. Se sono composti di fuoco, e più il fuoco è \"puro\" più sale in alto, allora il fuoco più luminoso che c’è, e il più puro - ovvero il Sole - si troverà nel posto più alto, seguito dalla Luna, e solo dopo dalle fioche luci che si vedono in cielo di notte in una notte senza Luna: le stelle.\n\nResta il dubbio insoluto sul comportamento della nebbia , che esala dalla Terra e crea le stelle: se il Sole e la Luna sono visibili anche oltre questa nebbia, dunque il suo comportamento è tale da rendere in parte visibile e in parte invisibile oltre di sé? Ciò non è chiaro.\n\nPer Anassimandro, la causa della nascita del mondo contiene già le forze che ne causano i movimenti. Per questo, McKirahan afferma che il filosofo è un esponente ante litteram dell’Uniformitarismo10, ovvero di quella dottrina nata tra il XVIII e il XIX secolo CE secondo la quale i processi geologici che oggi avvengono nel mondo sono gli stessi che sono avvenuti in tempi remoti.\n\nInfine, con la sua idea della Terra sospesa al centro dell’Universo, Anassimandro ha permesso ai corpi celesti di ruotare tutto intorno ad essa, senza preoccuparsi di accettare \"passaggi\" da Okeanos o di visitare o meno il regno delle anime, eco di mitologie egizie e babilonesi.\n\nL’Universo diventa sempre di più qualcosa che l’umanità può descrivere in modo a-umano , diventando però sempre più intrecciato con i concetti di proporzione, di senso, di destinazione ultima - concetti molto umani.\n\nAnassimene\n\nAnassimene, figlio di Euristrato11, è un allievo di Anassimandro, probabilmente anche di Parmenide12. Non sappiamo molto della sua vita, se non che il suo acme è intorno alla caduta di Sardi dopo la conquista di Ciro il Grande - avvenuta intorno al 546 BCE. Potrebbe dunque essere nato intorno al 585 BCE13. Morì probabilmente nella LXIII Olimpiade, quindi tra il 528 e il 524 BCE.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/30bea483-ae5e-41b6-83df-ab94ec5e5e6d_2500x2456.jpeg)\n\nAnaximenes - 1493 - Rijksmuseum, Netherlands - Public Domain.\n\nDi lui non sappiamo nient’altro, se non che si dice abbia scritto almeno un libro.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/494f7763-fdcd-4ad9-b6a2-e4f60f391879_1240x1126.png)\n\nLa filosofia di Anassimene è tramandata da Aristotele, e sappiamo che il suo ἀρχή, il suo principio creatore, è l’ aria .\n\nIl termine aria non deve trarre in inganno. I Greci fanno distinzione tra aer e aether: il primo termine si riferisce al respiro, e viene da un termine che significa \"nebbia oscura\", e può essere caldo o freddo; il secondo termine invece rappresenta l’aria cristallina, ed è l’elemento puro che poi diventerà il materiale di cui sono piene le sfere celesti.\n\nL’aria è infinita come l’ἄπειρον, ma non è indefinita . Dall’aria infatti vengono tutti gli elementi, grazie a un processo di rarefazione e condensazione: quando l’aria diviene rarefatta, si crea il fuoco; quando si fa più densa, diventa vento; e poi ancora nuvole, infine acqua. Da questa, diventa terra, e infine roccia.\n\nQuesti cambiamenti avvengono a causa del movimento dell’ἄπειρον, che è eterno.\n\nL’aria, che è lo πνεῦμα ( pneuma ) del mondo, è il motivo della sua esistenza e della sua diversità: dalle esalazioni dell’aria arrivano il Sole, la Luna e le stelle, ma anche gli dei14.\n\nAnassimene è il primo ad affermare che le stelle fisse sono davvero fisse , nel senso che sono legate alla volta celeste, che è cristallina perché permette di vedere ciò che c’è al di là.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a5070138-a1dc-47f7-96b5-8697c3e19ab6_1024x690.jpeg)\n\nStudie af skyer, opera di Christen Købke. Immagine ottenuta da National Gallery of Denmark, Denmark - Public Domain.\n\nTutti i commentatori sono concordi nell’affermare che la Terra di Anassimene è piatta15, che è ferma al centro dell’Universo16, e che è supportata dall’aria; che tutti i corpi celesti ruotano intorno a essa, e sono anch’essi piatti \" come una foglia \"17; che il Sole è in movimento a causa del vento generato dall’aria, e che questo movimento è il motivo per cui è così caldo; che anche le stelle sono in movimento - nonostante siano fisse alla volta celeste , si muovono poiché la volta celeste stessa è in movimento - e non ne sentiamo il calore poiché sono molto distanti; inoltre, potrebbero ospitare altri mondi come il Sole con la Terra.\n\nA differenza di Anassimandro, però, Anassimene non descrive il moto dei corpi celesti come una rivoluzione completa intorno alla Terra: quando essi non sono visibili da noi, ciò non è dovuto al loro moto sotto la Terra , ma al fatto che quei corpi - il Sole di notte, le stelle di giorno - attraversano delle regioni distanti del mondo che sono più in alto rispetto al resto del mondo, e quindi invisibili all’osservazione, quasi come se la tavola che è la Terra fosse anche un po’ obliqua.\n\nIl fenomeno delle eclissi è dovuto a corpi minori che oscurano la luce della Luna o del Sole.\n\nAnassimene spiega il mondo riconducendo tutto all’ἀρχή, e in questo unisce gli insegnamenti dei due predecessori e concittadini: l’ἀρχή è la causa di tutto (l’ἄπειρον per Anassimandro), ma è anche un elemento visibile del mondo, l’aria (ciò che per Talete era l’acqua).\n\nInoltre, opera una riduzione di più fenomeni, dalla presenza dei corpi celesti alla diversità degli elementi, ad una sola causa: l’aria e i suoi comportamenti. Associa due qualità opposte - caldo e freddo, leggere e pesante, rarefatto e denso - ad un’unica quantità .\n\nDagli eventi terrestri come i terremoti, dovuti secondo Anassimene alla Terra che si asciuga e spacca18, agli dei che nascono e presiedono il mondo, tutto nell’Universo ha come principio l’aria.\n\nTracce del vicino oriente\n\nAbbiamo già parlato più volte del rapporto tra i primi filosofi greci e le mitologie egiziane, babilonesi e in generale, dei popoli e delle civiltà dell’ oriente . Anassimandro e Anassimene non fanno eccezione.\n\nAnassimandro parla dell’ἄπειρον come della negazione di ciò che è limitato . Questo Indefinito crea infiniti mondi, tutti equidistanti nel tempo, e in cui ognuno dura per un tempo definito. Il mondo si forma con il movimento perpetuo dell’Indefinito, prima come unità generativa, che contiene tutto e il suo contrario, e poi come la sfera che contiene la Terra e le ruote di fuoco circondate dall’aria che sono i corpi celesti. Con la sua visione meccanicistica spiega le eclissi, l’angolazione dell’eclittica, la presenza dei corpi celesti.\n\nLa forma della Terra, un cilindro più largo che alto, è leggermente concava, come se restasse in questa descrizione l’eco delle mitologie babilonesi, caldee, iraniane e egiziane sulle montagne che circondano il mondo.\n\nAbbiamo visto nelle note luminose a margine di questo capitolo che più volte le idee dei filosofi greci trovano una origine mitica o una spiegazione religiosa nei miti orientali: non fa eccezione la creazione del mondo di Anassimandro, che avviene in modo simile a quella iraniana in cui Ohrmazd crea il mondo da \"ciò che è umido e ciò che è infuocato\".\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/cae3efbc-0132-4cdf-97a8-69bba7b7de3b_2412x2010.jpeg)\n\nFuoco, opera di Maerten de Vos, Adriaen Collaert, 1580-1584. Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / Rijksmuseum\n\nAnassimene invece parla dell’aria, dell’ aer , di ἀήρ: nebbia, vapore. E’ una sostanza visibile, ma che ha le proprietà dell’Indefinito. In relazione all’aria come respiro, in un inno a Prâna contenuto nei testi Atharva Veda , si dice che tutto obbedisce a Prâna , che è il respiro . Nei testi Pahlavi si legge che le eclissi sono dovute a corpi minori nel cielo che si frappongono tra il mondo della Terra e le stelle.\n\nI tre filosofi, infine\n\nI tre filosofi di Mileto, Talete , Anassimandro e Anassimene , sono i primi in Grecia a cercare di scoprire il funzionamento e l’origine della Natura attraverso il ragionamento : osservano il mondo, provano a risalire a principi primi , a generalizzare , a compiere analogie , a comparare fenomeni diversi per trovarne delle comuni origini .\n\nBenjamin Farrington, storico della scienza e accademico di ispirazione marxista (Science in Antiquity, Science and Politics in the Ancient World), parla dei filosofi di Mileto dicendo che \"lasciano fuori gli dei\" dalle loro spiegazioni sui fenomeni naturali. E’ certamente vero nella misura in cui ciò che accade nel mondo non è frutto del volere degli dei, e in cui né la creazione del mondo né la sua fine sono opera di una divinità creatrice o distruttrice. Nonostante questo, i tre filosofi non rifiutano l’esistenza degli dei, che sono addirittura sottoposti allo stesso processo di creazione di tutte le altre cose che ci sono nel mondo, e che sono sottoposti alle stesse regole, e agli stessi principi. L’ἄπειρον di Anassimandro potrebbe rappresentare lo spirito di creazione del mondo, ma già in Anassimene questo spirito è sì indefinito, ma osservabile in azione persino sulla Terra.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/db435f8d-7659-447f-9442-ccda3f7b1bf3_800x902.jpeg)\n\nIllustrazione da un trattato del 1587 sulle comete e le meteore, conosciuto come Kometenbuch - opera di un anonimo, 1587. Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / ORKA - Open Repository Kassel\n\nQuello che ricercano è il generale, non il particolare; è la causa primaria, l’universale e l’essenziale, la causa materiale . Ora Barnes si chiede: lo fanno da \"scienziati\", nel senso in cui lo definiamo oggi?\n\nCi sono tre vie possibili per abbozzare una risposta: si può pensare che \"nessuno dei filosofi di Mileto propose teorie “vere”\", che \"non composero una Royal Society [ante litteram] in Grecia”, e che \"nessuno di questi filosofi aveva intenzione di raggiungere la precisione che oggi viene richiesta alle teorie scientifiche\"19; così facendo, li si vede come i rappresentanti degli ultimi poeti interessati alla Natura, piuttosto che i primi iniziatori della scienza occidentale.\n\nQuesta visione è incoraggiata dai problemi nella assegnazione incerta delle idee e delle interpretazioni delle stesse dovuta alle fonti di secondo, terzo, addirittura quarto livello che sono le uniche di cui disponiamo; ma anche dal fatto che per quanto ne sappiamo questi filosofi non (i) effettuarono esperimenti, (ii) non utilizzarono né il metodo induttivo per costruire le proprie teorie né (iii) il metodo critico nei confronti gli uni verso gli altri, (iv) non utilizzarono i dati a propria disposizione per avanzare ipotesi.\n\nDall’altra c’è la visione, tra gli altri proposta da Popper, secondo cui le loro opere hanno preparato la strada alla ricerca scientifica come la intendiamo, e che anzi hanno fatto il meglio che potessero fare con i mezzi a loro disposizione: Popper parla in particolare di Anassimandro, che arrivò alla sua idea criticando la teoria di Talete, utilizzando argomenti speculativi , propri della filosofia, per affermare che se la Terra giace sull’acqua, si sarebbe dovuto spiegare su cosa poggia l’acqua, e così via; e giudicando inaccettabile queste infinite spiegazioni, ne propose una nuova, che è interessante in quanto sembra preparare al concetto di azione a distanza, con la sua descrizione della Terra ferma perché ugualmente \"attratta\" da tutto contemporaneamente. E poco importa se poi sempre Anassimandro afferma che la Terra è piatta: ciò è dovuto ad argomenti osservativi , propri della scienza, e altrettanto importanti di quelli speculativi.\n\nCerto, Talete e gli altri due filosofi erano in errore nelle loro idee, ma la loro importanza, dice Coleman20, non risiede nei modelli che hanno proposto, piuttosto nel fatto che hanno iniziato, migliorando ognuno il modello del precedente, a \"stabilire una lunga catena di interpretazione progressivamente [sempre più] corrette di scoperte scientifiche\".\n\nInfine, la terza via unisce le due precedenti, e presentando i tre filosofi come coloro che hanno permesso alla scienza come indagine naturalistica e non più mitica di nascere, ma che non sono riusciti ad attenersi ai dettami che la scienza moderna considera necessari per definire scienza l’indagine speculativa e osservativa.\n\nTutto ciò non è una colpa che possiamo attribuire ai tre filosofi, che possiamo ben definire - per la nostra accezione dei termini - pertanto, se non Astronomi, Cosmologi, Fisici, perlomeno indagatori della Natura a pieno titolo.\n\nNon bisogna però pensare che le loro indagini fossero omogenee, uniformi, direzionate da un’idea specifica: il solo concetto di principio, ad esempio. non è proprio del VI secolo BCE, ma viene collegato a posteriori da Aristotele ricercandolo nei filosofi a lui precedenti.\n\nLa ricerca delle cause dei movimenti nel cielo e dell’origine del mondo procede ancora come ricerca di singoli individui: che dibattono l’uno le idee dell’altro - senza scalfire le teorie nel loro nucleo, ma che non appartengono a una scuola. Non ancora.\n\nNel prossimo episodio: il problema del cambiamento\n\nArticoli della serie:\n\nBibliografia:\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe, di Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, raccolta di saggi ad opera di C. Blacker e M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nGreek Cosmologies, di G.E.R. Lloyd\n\nAristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus, di T. Heath(Oxford 1913)\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, di Kirk G.S. e Raven J.E. (Cambridge 1957)\n\nEarly Greek Philosophy and the Orient, di M.L. West (Oxford 1971)\n\nPhilosophy before Socrates, di R.D. McKirahan (Hackett 1994)\n\nEarly Greek Science, di G.E.R. Lloyd (Chatto & Windus 1970)\n\nA history of astronomy from Thales to Kepler, di J.L.E Dreyer (Dover 1953)\n\nHeaven And Earth In Ancient Greek Cosmology, di D.L. Cuprie (Springer 2011)\n\nEarly Greek Cosmology: A Historiographical Review, di N.S. Hetherington\n\nBack to the Pre-Socratics: The Presidential Address, di K.R. Popper (1958)\n\nEarly Greek astronomy to Aristotle, di D.R. Dicks (Cornell University Press 1970)\n\nHistory of Philosophy Volume I: From the Beginning to Plato, raccolta di C.C.W. Taylor (Routledge 1997)\n\nThe Ionians, di Malcolm Schofield\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, di Jonathan Barnes (Routledge 1979)\n\nA Source Book In Greek Science di M.R. Cohen e I.E. Drabkin (Harvard University Press 1945)\n\nThe Physical World of the Greeks, di S. Sambursky (The Macmillan Company 1956)\n\nQuesta newsletter è una di tre: le altre due sono Last Scattering Surface, e Space of Sound. Tutte le pubblicazioni sono gratuite e puoi consultare tutti gli articoli senza paywall. Se vuoi, puoi iscriverti qui e qui.\n\nInfine, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n\nCiao e a presto!\n\nNote\n\n1 Diogene Laerzio, Vite dei filosofi.\n\n2 Jonathan Barnes, The Presocratic Philosophers.\n\n3 Simplicio, Commentario alla fisica di Aristotele.\n\n4 Anche Simplicio cita Teofrasto nel Commento alla Fisica di Aristotele, e anche Ermia di Alessandria, Pseudo-Plutarco e Aezio concordano sull’idea di indefinito di Simplicio.\n\n5 Arthur Koestler, Sleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe.\n\n6 Ippolito, Refutationes.\n\n7 Pseudo-Plutarco, Stromata.\n\n8 Ippolito, Refutationes.\n\n9 Pseudo-Plutarco, Stromata.\n\n10 McKirahan, Philosophy before Socrates\n\n11 Diogene Laerzio, Vite dei filosofi.\n\n12 Parleremo anche di lui.\n\n13 L’acme di un filosofo veniva posto generalmente intorno al suo quarantesimo anno di età.\n\n14 Ippolito, Refutationes.\n\n15 Pseudo-Plutarco, Stromata.\n\n16 Aristotele, De Cælo.\n\n17 Aristotele, Meteorologica.\n\n18 Aristotele, Meteorologica\n\n19 N.S. Hetherington, Early Greek Cosmology: A Historiographical Review.\n\n20 Coleman, Early Theories of the Universe\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_ita-sul-moto-della-terra-il-sole.md": "Disclaimer #1: this article is in Italian. You can read the English version here.\n\nDisclaimer #2: questo pezzo è il primo di una serie che conterrà capitoli di genere storico o filosofico, e altri di genere più astrofisico. I primi saranno pubblicati su questa newsletter, Heralding Time , mentre gli altri verranno pubblicati su Last Scattering Surface . Se vuoi, puoi seguirle entrambe.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a964b728-e26b-4f88-894f-d8d704ff710d_1080x1350.png)\n\nAll’alba o al tramonto, cercate un puntino luminoso nel cielo. Non sarà lampeggiante come un aereo, e non si muoverà così velocemente. Attraversa il cielo in poco meno di cinque minuti, e potrebbe diventare luminoso come Giove o Venere.\n\nEcco, sarei molto contento se uno qualunque dei lettori di questa serie intitolata sul moto della Terra non si trovasse al momento sul pianeta, bensì su quel puntino luminoso. Non credo stia succedendo davvero (se dovessi sbagliarmi, sarei felice di saperlo!). Se avessi scritto questo pezzo prima del 31 ottobre 2000, ne sarei sicuro; dal novembre del 2000, però, non tutti gli umani vivono sulla Terra. Ad ogni modo, sia che voi abitiate il suolo terrestre, o siate astronauti sulla ISS , siamo tutti legati al pianeta che abitiamo o a cui torniamo: la Terra. E lo siamo dall’alba della storia umana, da quando il rapporto con la Natura era molto più intimo e diretto che nella società contemporanea.\n\nIl cielo\n\nPer un membro di una qualsiasi comunità umana, il rapporto con la Terra si declinava, non solo nel rapporto con il suolo e tutto ciò che offriva, piante, tronchi, alberi, pietre, rocce, animali, prede e predatori, ma anche con il cielo sopra di lui.\n\nIl cielo di giorno, dominato dal Sole e dagli agenti atmosferici, che per molto tempo sono stati oggetti “celesti” tanto quanto i pianeti e le stelle; ma anche la Luna e i pianeti, che a volte visitano il cielo di giorno, magari poco prima del tramonto o poco dopo l’alba.\n\nE il cielo di notte, pieno di stelle e illuminato dalla Luna. La notte arriva al termine di ogni giorno, e per il membro di una società antica le stelle sono sempre lì, notte dopo notte, apparentemente ferme su nel cielo; osservandole per un numero di notti sufficiente, si accorge però che seguono un percorso: alcune restano sempre sopra l’orizzonte, altre dopo un po’ non sono più visibili perché muoiono sotto l’orizzonte. E la Luna ha un ciclo ancora più facilmente osservabile: nel giro di circa 28 giorni è un disco, poi inizia a svanire, diventa una falce, e poi scompare. Dopo qualche giorno riappare, ed è una nuova Luna, rigenerata, rinata, o è sempre sé stessa?\n\n“Il cielo è uno strumento per le società antiche” , scrive l’astronomo Edwin. chariesC. Tubb in Echoes of the Ancient Times (1983), che il cielo lo utilizzavano e lo consultavano per ottenere un senso di ciclicità del tempo, per godere della simmetria dei movimenti che su di esso i corpi celesti dipingevano, e per confidare che la Natura fosse prevedibile . Ogni civiltà, complessa o semplice che fosse, ha ideato una teoria sui movimenti del cielo, e di riflesso del posto che la Terra occupa nel mondo, inteso come oggi noi intendiamo il Cosmo o l’Universo.\n\nIl Sole\n\nI cicli che ogni umano può osservare nel giro di un giorno terrestre sono la rotazione diurna della Terra, ovvero il Sole che si sposta da oriente verso occidente durante il giorno, e le stelle che fanno altrettanto durante la notte. La parola oriente ha la sua etimologia nel latino solem orientem , che significa Sole nascente ( orientem viene dal verbo orior , che significa sorgere ); occidente , in modo analogo, viene dal latino solem occidentem , che significa Sole morente ( occidentem viene dal verbo occido , che significa - tra i vari significati - cadere o morire). Per un osservatore che vivesse un solo giorno, alzatosi poco prima dell’alba, il Sole nasce a oriente, rosso fuoco, percorre il suo tragitto nel cielo durante il giorno, brilla e brucia e riscalda la terra, poi cade a occidente, si colora di rosso di nuovo prima di sparire, in modo simmetrico a ciò che era avvenuto all’alba. Altri nomi per oriente e occidente sono est e ovest , che arrivano dal norreno: l’origine di questi nomi, insieme a quelli di nord e sud, è da riferirsi ai nomi con cui quattro nani della mitologia norrena vengono presentati nella Edda poetica , una raccolta di poemi utile per conoscere la mitologia norrena. Ne parleremo.\n\nLa notte\n\nLe stelle, dicevamo. Osservandole giorno dopo giorno, per un intero anno, un sacerdote egizio osserva e registra che alcune stelle non scendono mai sotto la linea dell’orizzonte, quella linea che delimita la cupola, la volta, la tela su cui avvengono i movimenti degli astri. Sono le stelle imperiture , ed è lì che i faraoni vanno dopo la morte. Oggi le chiamiamo stelle circumpolari , poiché seguono un percorso circolare nel cielo, attorno a un punto ideale, detto polo celeste . Nella nostra era la stella che svolge la funzione di stella polare (nell’emisfero boreale) è parte della costellazione dell’ Ursa Minor (Orsa Minore), Polaris .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/21d945dc-0adf-4c4a-bd4e-3096b421701a_3000x2400.jpeg)\n\nA sinistra in alto, la costellazione dell’Orsa Minore a cui appartiene Polaris. In realtà, Polaris è un sistema di tre stelle, Polaris A, Polaris Ab, e Polaris B, lontane 430 anni luce dal Sistema Solare. Le prime due orbitano mediamente a una distanza di 18.5 Unità Astronomiche (UA) l’una dall’altra, mentre Polaris A è lontana da Polaris B 2400 UA. Una UA è la distanza media della Terra dal Sole, circa 150 milioni di chilometri. Crediti qui.\n\nL’emisfero australe non ha una stella luminosa tanto quanto Polaris nelle vicinanze del polo sud: si usa quindi una costellazione, la Croce del Sud , come punto di riferimento\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2754a677-c1c0-44d6-a385-eefa2025b134_1800x1200.jpeg)\n\nLe quattro stelle più luminose rappresentano la Croce del Sud, l’asterismo che si utilizza nell’emisfero australe alla stessa stregua con cui si utilizza Polaris nell’emisfero boreale. Crediti qui.\n\nIl ruolo di stella polare è temporaneo: a causa del movimento della Terra, la posizione delle stelle in cielo cambia, e in passato e nel futuro stelle diverse da Polaris hanno assunto e assumeranno la funzione di punto di riferimento per il polo nord.\n\nCos’è il polo per le civiltà antiche? E’ un asse cosmico, un vero e proprio palo, innalzato fino al cielo, un albero, una montagna, un bastone. Oggi è un asse immaginario che rappresenta l’asse di rotazione della Terra, e che intercetta la sfera celeste in due punti: il polo nord e il polo sud .\n\nLa quarta stella più luminosa del cielo, Arturo , viene chiamata nella cultura aborigena Marpeankurrk , ed è associata all’antenato che aveva scoperto il bittur , o larva delle termiti, ritenuta una ottima fonte di proteine. Il bittur era disponibile da agosto alla fine di settembre, lo stesso periodo in cui Marpeankurrk era visibile. Per questa società, che a quanto ne sappiamo non utilizzava le stelle per orientarsi di notte, le stelle rappresentano gli antenati, e sono lo specchio di cose che si potevano trovare sulla Terra.\n\nIl primo utilizzo di notazione simbolica per rappresentare il cielo è stato trovato nella regione della Dordogne, in Francia. Abri Blanchard , il sito della scoperta, datata intorno al 36000 BCE, contiene un osso di aquila su cui sono incisi dei segni, che sono stati associati a una sequenza di giorni: l’intera sequenza sembra rappresenta un ciclo lunare.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/47483444-6615-4b13-8457-6cc29c7b5ea4_3892x1444.jpeg)\n\nLa placca ritrovata a Abri Blanchard. Sulla sinistra si possono osservare i segni che rappresentano la sequenza associabile al ciclo lunare. Crediti Don Hitchcock.\n\nDurante l’anno la posizione del Sole cambia, non solo durante il giorno, ma giorno dopo giorno. Ci sono due momenti durante l’anno in cui però questo movimento sembra non esserci, o esserci di meno: in questi giorni il sole sembra sorgere sempre nello stesso punto, e così avviene al tramonto. Il solstizio, che viene dal latino sol sistere , rappresenta il \" fermarsi del Sole ”, e avviene intorno al 21 giugno, quando nell’emisfero boreale il Sole raggiunge la sua “altezza” massima nel cielo, e intorno al 21 dicembre, quando il Sole occupa la “altezza” minima.\n\nI due solstizi sono i punti di inversione del percorso del Sole nell’eclittica, che è il percorso apparente che il Sole compie durante l’anno.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/deada32d-675f-44d5-bc54-2f18d2b37f6e_1760x620.png)\n\nVisualizzazione dell’analemma solare (la figura a forma di 8) ottenuto per ogni ora del giorno in una località in Islanda (Longitudine: -18.15 Latitudine: 64.00). Crediti qui.\n\nL’astronomo antico che osserva la Luna e ne traccia i cambiamenti, le sue fasi , divide l’anno in 12 cicli lunari, chiamati mesi . La parola mese in inglese (month) ha le sue radici nel proto-indo-europeo *meh₁- , che significa misurare. In italiano, mese viene dal latino menses , dal greco ménē , arrivando alla stessa radice *meh₁- ; Men è una divinità lunare venerata nella penisola anatolica dai tempi delle civiltà babilonesi fino al tempo della conquista romana.\n\nIl Sole e la Luna non sono i soli oggetti a vagare nel cielo; a errare sono anche altri pianeti: pianeta viene infatti dal greco plànētes astéres , stelle vagabonde . Per un astronomo babilonese, e fino alla rivoluzione copernicana, con pianeta si intendeva qualunque corpo celeste diverso dalle stelle fisse , e dalle comete , che venivano considerati diversamente. Erano quindi pianeti il Sole , la Luna , Mercurio , Venere , Marte , Giove , Saturno . Gli altri due pianeti del Sistema Solare (Urano e Nettuno) non erano conosciuti, e verranno osservati solo nell’era moderna. Il percorso dei pianeti è vicino a quello del sole, in una fascia che compone lo Zodiaco .\n\nL’astronomo caldeo, membro attivo della società, aveva il compito di osservare il cielo e di registrare la posizione delle stelle e dei pianeti. Già intorno al 3800 BCE nel regno di Sargon di Akkad i sacerdoti astronomi trascrivevano i resoconti stellari su tavolette di argilla. La lunghezza dell’anno terrestre fu misurato entro lo 0.01% del valore corretto attuale. Dai resoconti di tavolette di argilla datate dal 650 BCE al 50 BCE, sappiamo che gli astronomi babilonesi registravano stabilmente la posizione di 30 stelle per misurare le coordinate celesti. Come scrive Arthur Koestler in Sleepwalkers: A History of Man's Changing Vision of the Universe, queste osservazioni erano Scienza Esatta, e permettevano di fare previsioni, nonostante il carattere mitologico fosse la base teorica delle osservazioni stesse.\n\nGli dei\n\nPer un membro di una antica società i pianeti avevano qualità e proprietà uniche: i loro moti regolari (il Sole e la Luna), la maggiore luminosità rispetto alle stelle fisse, le posizioni relative che occupavano nel cielo, tutto ciò li poneva in una categoria particolare.\n\nErano dei che governavano il cielo, non limitandosi ad abitarlo.\n\nPer gli Egizi, il Sole e la Luna sono gli occhi di Horus , e la dea del cielo, Nut, ha un nome che significa “Colei che brilla”. Il supremo dio dei Sumeri, Any (o An ) condivide il simbolo con cui viene scritto con Diugir , che significa “splendente”. Any si traduce con cielo , o alto . Nelle lingue indo-europee Djevos significa “Colui che governa il cielo”; da questa parola viene Dyaus in sanscrito, Jovis in latino, e Zeus in greco. Jupiter viene da Dyauspitar , o Zeuspater , che significa padre Zeus, e Zeus è collegato all’idea di “splendente”, “brillante”. Il popolo degli Inti, nella regione Inca del Perù, chiama il Sole Tonatiuh , “ Colui che avanza brillando ”.\n\nLa Luna nell’Antico Egitto è Khosnu , il corridore . In Babilonia era Sin, il signore della conoscenza. Per il popolo Desana del Sudamerica la luna è il sole notturno.\n\nGiove è associato agli dei che governano il mondo con la legge: ciò è dovuto al suo carattere “regolare” nel cielo, in quanto è il pianeta (noto agli antichi) che più di ogni altro segue l’eclittica.\n\nVenere, a cui viene associato il culto di Ishtar in Mesopotamia, è contemporaneamente la stella del mattino, e la stella della sera, poiché è particolarmente visibile all’alba e al tramonto. A Ishtar e di conseguenza a Venere era associato il simbolo di Bennu , un uccello simile a un airone che appartiene a Osiride, il dio della morte e della resurrezione. Non è un caso che Ishtar sia anche la dea dell’aldilà, morendo ad ogni tramonto e nascendo nuovamente con l’alba successiva.\n\nMercurio è Set per gli Egizi, e Nebo in Babilonia. A queste divinità era associato il ruolo di messaggero degli dei, e probabilmente questo ruolo era dovuto al comportamento del pianeta, osservato anno dopo anno: è il pianeta più veloce a percorrere da ovest a est l’eclittica, a superare il Sole e a tornare in direzione opposta.\n\nMarte è visibile a occhio nudo come un pianeta più rosso degli altri: questo basterebbe per associarne il colore al sangue, e quindi alla guerra. In Babilonia gli si associava Nergal, dio della guerra; così anche l’analogo dio greco Ares e il dio romano Marte.\n\nSaturno era Ninib per i Babilonesi, Horus per gli Egizi e Cronos per i Greci.\n\nAnche le stelle erano associate alle divinità, talvolta minori. Per gli Atzechi il dio guerriero Tezcatlipoca era associato al’Orsa Maggiore; non rappresentava però un orso, bensì il guerriero il cui nome significa Specchio Fumante: il dio veniva rappresentato con il piede sinistro mancante, poiché durante l’anno una parte della costellazione dell’Orsa scende sotto l’orizzonte, e non è visibile interamente. Anche gli dei sono soggetti ai limiti delle nostri osservazioni.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/e1b35582-311f-4a44-a121-74dbd7feb1a9_722x722.png)\n\nTezcatlipoca, il dio-guerriero, associato all’Orsa Maggiore. Li vedete? (Crediti qui)\n\nOgni civiltà ha indagato i cieli, quindi: siano essi visti come dimora degli dei o degli antenati, o luoghi di simmetria e regolarità, o tutte queste cose insieme. A. Koestler afferma che “ la Scienza emerge nella forma di Giano ”, ovvero contiene contemporaneamente il rigore oggettivo della ricerca scientifica e il personale desiderio di collegare la Natura al mito. Nei prossimi episodi vedremo che ogni teoria astronomica sulla natura del mondo e sul moto della Terra riposa sulle conoscenze e sul pensiero del tempo in cui è stata formulata, ma anche di tutte le teorie che l’hanno preceduta, siano esse in accordo o in disaccordo con la teoria stessa.\n\nL’Astronomia ha tanti volti quanti sono i cieli che scruta: innumerevoli, eppure riuniti in una unica volta.\n\nBibliografia:\n\nEchoes of the Ancient Skies, di E. C. Tubb (New York: Harper & Row 1983)\n\nAn Encyclopedia of Cosmologies and Myth in Ancient Astronomy, di Clive Ruggles (ABC-CLIO 2005)\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man's Changing Vision of the Universe, di Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nQuesta newsletter è una di tre: le altre due sono Last Scattering Surface, e Space of Sound. Tutte le pubblicazioni sono gratuite e puoi consultare tutti gli articoli senza paywall. Se vuoi, puoi iscriverti qui e qui.\n\nInfine, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n\nCiao e a presto!\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_ita-sul-moto-della-terra-tre-fiumi.md": "Disclaimer #1: this article is in Italian. I will publish the English version soon.\n\nDisclaimer #2: questo pezzo fa parte di una serie, pubblicata sia su questa newsletter, Heralding Time , che su Last Scattering Surface . Se vuoi, puoi seguirle entrambe. Il primo capitolo si legge qui.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/4e267b32-c80a-42fe-9d92-926ed958bb2a_1080x1350.png)\n\nNel primo episodio sono comparsi sacerdoti egizi, astronomi babilonesi, dei e guerrieri a popolare il cielo, e ordine governato da divinità splendenti.\n\nIn questo episodio incontriamo le civiltà dell’Asia tra il Mediterraneo, il Mar Rosso e il Golfo Persico: l’Egitto e il fiume, la Mesopotamia e i fiumi, il mondo ebraico e quello arabo con l’unico dio creatore.\n\nPer le civiltà della Mesopotamia il mondo è circolare, per il regno d’Egitto una scatola rettangolare: per i popoli di questi regni il mondo poteva essere tutto ciò che immaginassero, dice A. Koestler, che abbiamo già incontrato nel primo episodio.\n\nGli oggetti nel cielo hanno percorsi tutto sommato comprensibili, ripetitivi, ciclici e abbastanza prevedibili. Si poteva allora cercare un senso a tutto ciò, e abbiamo già visto che è in effetti ciò che l’umanità ha cercato di fare, da sempre: cercare un ordine celeste che rispecchiasse l’ordine sociale desiderato, o farsene influenzare costruendone uno sulla Terra che lo rispecchiasse.\n\nIl Nilo dentro di sé, e la Via Lattea sopra di sé\n\nLa cosmologia e l’astronomia in Egitto attraversano gli oltre tremila anni di storia del paese (~3000 BCE - ~30 CE) come regno indipendente trasformandosi continuamente, aggiungendo idee e suggestioni: se il cielo rappresenta l’ordine del mondo, e i faraoni vivono nel cielo dopo la morte, allora ciò che cambia sulla Terra verrà riflesso in cielo. Inoltre, il regno è abbastanza vasto da permettere il fiorire di diversi filoni cosmologici in altrettante città.\n\nInnanzitutto, gli Egizi non vengono (quasi mai) disturbati dalle popolazioni vicine. La valle del Nilo è la direzione privilegiata verso cui un faraone egizio guarda per amministrare il regno, non deve preoccuparsi d’altro; il Mar Mediterraneo è un confine. Il regno è deserto e oasi, e tutto intorno ci sono montagne che racchiudono e proteggono il paese; le montagne sono così importanti da definire il confine naturale: “paese straniero” ha come simbolo una linea montuosa stilizzata, 𓈉.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9e00c53e-8484-4549-965c-0801b4aa1a88_1090x556.jpeg)\n\nIl simbolo per le lande straniere in segno geroglifico. Crediti qui.\n\nIl regno si estende fino alla “Porta del Sud”, nei pressi di Elefantina, Cebu o Abu per gli egizi, nella regione di Assuan. Ai quattro angoli del regno ci sono quattro monti che sorreggono il cielo. I due confini dell’asse Nord-Sud sono confini d’acqua, e l’acqua è anche tutto ciò che circonda il mondo: il Grande Circuito , o il Grande Oceano Circolare contengono il mondo, che il Nilo divide in due. L’acqua dell’Oceano, il Nilo e la pioggia, tutte arrivano dal primo degli dei, Num .\n\nLa Via Lattea è il fiume nel cielo, come il Nilo sulla Terra.\n\nIl Sole e la Luna si muovono in cielo, e quando il Sole tramonta, arriva la morte, fino a una nuova alba, che è il momento in cui il Sole, dopo aver viaggiato sotto la Terra, ritorna a illuminare l’Egitto. Il Sole vive ogni giorno una vita umana, e viva e mutevole è anche la Luna, che cambia forma durante il mese. Il Sole è il dio Râ , e la Luna Yââhu Aûhû , e a volte vengono attaccati da un serpente: quando ciò avviene, si verificano le eclissi . Le stelle si muovono in cielo, e a volte spariscono. Alcune sono legate a ciò che avviene sulla Terra: Sirio è visibile nei giorni che precedono la annuale inondazione del Nilo. I cinque pianeti conosciuti erano Bonû, che al tramonto era Ûati e all’alba Tiû-nûtiri, ovvero il “dio che saluta il Sole prima del suo arrivo” (Venere), Sobkû (Mercurio), Doshiri (Marte), Ûapshetatûi (Giove), e Kahiri (Saturn).\n\nIn principio c’erano le acque primigenie, e un abisso primordiale di acque: “ nell’infinito, il nulla, il nessun luogo, e le tenebre .” Dopo questo incipit, e l’idea che il mondo sia governato da Ma’at, ovvero dall’ordine, impersonato da una dea con un copricapo di piume di struzzo, le cosmogonie differiscono a seconda del luogo in cui nascono. Per un astronomo egiziano, le storie del mondo vengono da Khnum (Ermopoli), Iunu (Eliopoli) e Men-Nefer (Menfi).\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/350b45b8-c7ca-4682-b656-0a38f0b32ef0_1240x1290.png)\n\nI tre siti religiosi di cui parliamo in questa sezione: Khnum (Ermopoli), Iunu (Eliopoli), e Men-Nefer (Menfi).\n\nKhnum\n\nIl nome greco viene dalla divinità della sapienza, che per gli egizi era Thot, e che i greci associavano a Ermete Trismegisto, ma Khnum si traduce con “l’ottava città”. I geni del mondo erano Nau e Naunet , signori di ciò che è profondo; Huh e Hauhet , dei di ciò che non ha limite; Kuk e Kakwet , custodi di ciò che è tenebra; e Amun e Amaunet , sovrani di ciò che è invisibile. Questi geni hanno formato l’uovo primordiale di Num, da cui è scaturita la luce e l’aria. A Tebe si narra che questo uovo sia stato prodotto da un’oca simbolo del Grande Spirito Primigenio, Kenken Wer , che fu il primo essere a produrre un suono (Kenken Wer si può tradurre come “colui che schiamazza”).\n\nIn un’altra versione di questa storia, le acque arrivarono da un fiore di loto da cui nacque un infante, il Sole. All’alba il Sole nasce dal fiore di loto, e a esso ritorna dopo il tramonto, quando il fiore richiude i petali.\n\nIunu\n\nIl nome greco significa “città del sole”, e Iunu significa “i Pilastri”. Qui il dio è Atum , “Colui che è Completo”, che è emerso dalle acque primigenie sotto forma di collina (secondo altre fonti, seduto o in piedi su di una collina). Per alcuni, è il figlio di Nun . Rappresenta i piccoli innalzamenti del terreno che si formano quando l’acqua si ritira dopo le inondazioni del Nilo. La collina, il simbolo di questa divinità, è ricordata dagli egizi nelle costruzioni delle piramidi, a simboleggiare la Collina Primordiale.\n\nNel Pronunciamento #600, uno dei Testi delle Piramidi, ovvero i testi di pronunciamenti religiosi più antichi ritrovati della civiltà egizia, datati intorno al 2400 BCE, si narra che Atum ha fatto il mondo a partire da sé (a sua immagine?). Ha creato Shu e Tefenet espettorando. Questa azione designa una caratteristica della filosofia egizia, per la quale evocare il nome di qualcosa corrisponde al creare quel qualcosa. A testimonianza di ciò, Shu a Tefenet hanno origine in ishish , verbo che si traduce anche con “sputare”. Shu rappresenta l’aria, e Tefenet l’umidità. La prima una divinità maschile, e la seconda femminile, insieme generano Geb , il dio della terra, e Nut , la dea del cielo. La generazione della verde Geb e della blu Nut avviene quando Shu s epara dall’abbraccio i due fratelli.\n\nIn un’altra storia, Nut sposa Geb, ma il dio-sole Râ non è d’accordo: per questo li separa, maledicendoli di non poter mai in futuro concepire una progenie in nessun giorno dell’anno. Un’altra storia ancora narra che il dio Thoth , impietosito di Nut, riuscì a vincere dalla Luna, dopo aver giocato al gioco della dama, 1/70 del tempo di luce del pianeta. Crea così cinque giorni in più, da aggiungere all’anno egiziano; ed è in questi giorni ulteriori che Nut concepisce Osiride , Horus , Set , Iside e Nefti . L’anno egiziano era fino a quel momento di 360 giorni: diventa così l’anno astronomico di 365 giorni.\n\nL’acqua circonda il mondo, prima del mondo c’era solo acqua. Anche l’umanità viene dall’acqua: la parola per umanità, romet , viene da remeyet, le lacrime di Neb-er-Djer , il Signore Universale.\n\nMen-Nefer\n\nA Khnum si narra che Atum non abbia una consorte, e che abbia generato i propri figli “con la propria mano”; a Men-Nefer la Collina Primordiale è Ta-tjenen , la terra che sale.\n\nMen-Nefer ha come dio Ptah, che genera Nun e Nuret. I vecchi dei, anch’essi sono contenuti in Ptah, e da lui generati. La creazione del mondo avviene mediante il cuore di Ptah, sede dell’intelligenza, e da cui nasce Horus, e dalla sua lingua, da cui discende il comando e il potere della parola, che ha dato origine a Thoth.\n\nUna volta che la creazione del mondo è avvenuta, e l’umanità ha popolato la Terra, l’ordine del mondo va mantenuto come è sempre stato. Il caos che è esiliato ai confini del mondo va tenuto lì, e sono le azioni dell’uomo e degli dei a permetterlo. Un equilibrio, dunque: torniamo al concetto di Ma’at, all’ordine cosmico, all’ordine terreno, infine all’etica. Nel mondo rappresenta la verità e la giustizia. Ogni giorno va preservato, dalla sua creazione alla sua dipartita con la notte; il faraone regna per questo, e i suoi templi ne sono una testimonianza.\n\nTra il Tigri e l’Eufrate, la Terra è piatta\n\nLa regione della Mesopotamia è indissolubilmente legata alle fertili pianure limitrofe ai fiumi Tigre e Eufrate, e la sua estensione oggi coprirebbe l’Iraq, l’Iran, la Siria e la Turchia. La civiltà di cui parleremo, e i testi cuneiformi che ci parlano ancora oggi, sono datati tra il 3000 BCE e il 300 BCE. Le idee cosmologiche arrivano dai testi del primo millennio BCE.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f84e083a-67d4-41ba-a15c-a0dc62c201dc_1240x1076.png)\n\nLa regione della Mesopotamia. Oltre ai due fiumi Tigri ed Eufrate, sono evidenziate anche alcune importanti città della regione.\n\nLa regione, così fertile e attraversata dai fiumi di cui abbiamo parlato, era al centro del mondo per un contadino sumero, o un sacerdote di Babilonia, o un guerriero assiro. La storia babilonese della creazione del mondo, Enuma Elish , parla di un mondo che nasce dal caos liquido. In principio non c’è un cielo, ma solo le acque dolci, Apsu , e le acque salate, Ti’amat .\n\nLa presenza dell’acqua come elemento creatore è comune alle fonti in Mesopotamia, e quindi in Siria, ma anche in Egitto, in Palestina e in Egitto. La presenza di una terra così fertile, in cui la vegetazione cresce spontaneamente, non porta il creatore dei miti a immaginare un paradiso in cielo che produca il necessario all’umanità attraverso la pioggia, proprio perché le piante crescono ai lati dei fiumi Tigre e Eufrate. Questi fiumi avevano le loro sorgenti nelle sorgenti sotterranee, sorgenti primordiali create da Apsu, il dio padrone, chiamato Enki in Sumero e Ea a Babilonia.\n\nDopo Apsu e Ti’amat arrivano Lahmu e Lahamu , che formano l’orizzonte con il limo. Il cielo è la dimora di Anshar , da cui nasce Anu , il paradiso; sotto la terra dimora Kishar , da cui nasce Nudimut , la terra. Anu e Nudimut sono imprigionati da Ti’amat, ma vengono liberati da Marduk , discendente di Kishar e Anshar, quando questi taglia in due Ti’amat nella sua dimora, separandoli. Si formano così il cielo e la terra. In alcuni testi, la terra è Nippur , e Eridu è l’acqua.\n\nLa cosmologia in Mesopotamia descrive la Terra al centro, il cielo e i corpi celesti sopra di essa, e le acque cosmiche e l’aldilà sotto di essa. Le stelle sono ferme, i pianeti si muovono.\n\nLa Terra è un disco - anche se nella regione settentrionale la Terra è invece “una montagna”; con l’estensione del regno, diventa un grande disco, ma di estensione limitata, a causa del moto del Sole e degli altri corpi celesti. Il Sole viaggia sotto la Terra ogni notte; così fa anche la Luna. L’estensione della Terra è circondata da un Khubur , Fiume Salato, oltre le quali ci sono (8?) “ regioni triangolari ”.\n\nL’astronomia babilonese è arrivata a un vicolo cieco; il problema risiede, secondo Lambert, al fatto che non era facilmente estendibile e generalizzabile: un esempio su tutti, la presenza di una Terra piatta anziché sferica. La maggior parte degli importanti contributi che riceviamo dalla cosmologia provenienti da quest’area provengono dall’astronomia caldea, di cui parleremo brevemente quando parleremo dei filosofi greci. E’ da qui infatti che molte teorie geometriche e astronomiche sviluppate dai greci provengono.\n\nCreatio ex nihilo?\n\nLa tradizione cosmologica ebraica è antica quanto il suo popolo, e arriva fino all’inizio del Basso Medioevo. Una cosa che è evidente è che la cultura ebraica ha adottato la cornice cosmologica della civiltà in cui essa viveva.\n\nSe per i Babilonesi la Terra è piatta, allora anche la narrazione biblica è coerente con questa descrizione: la Terra è un disco piatto, e alla fine del mondo ci sono quattro kanefot , angoli. Sopra la Terra c’è shamayin , il cielo, e rakia , il firmamento. La Terra giace su dei pilastri, e il firmamento ha una fine. Il Sole e la Luna si muovono nel firmamento, o sotto di esso. Sotto la Terra c’è Sheol , la dimora dei morti. Le acque (ricordate i Babilonesi?) vivono sia sopra il firmamento che sotto la Terra; queste ultime hanno formato i mari e gli oceani al momento della creazione. Nelle profondità della Terra c’è Tehom (non ricorda Ti’amat?), la grande profondità, da cui arrivano le acque del diluvio.\n\nLa creazione del mondo avviene grazie a Dio, il Creatore; la radice del verbo bara , creare, non significa creatio ex nihilo , creazione dal nulla, ma creazione “fuori da qualcosa (o qualcuno)”. Solo successivamente arriverà il concetto di creazione dal nulla (nei Libri dei Maccabei, intorno al I-II secondo BCE).\n\nNella letteratura rabbinica la speculazione cosmica non è incoraggiata; ciononostante nascono diverse teorie sulla natura del mondo. Forse Dio ha creato il mondo che abitiamo dopo averne creati e distrutti molti altri; forse il Sole e la Luna avevano la stessa grandezza, ma la Luna protestando di voler essere più grande, venne resa più piccola.\n\nLa distanza della Terra dal firmamento è una unità di tempo, 500 anni. Se i firmamenti sono tre, ognuno sarà lontano dall’altro 500 anni. Il Creatore ha 12 costellazione per ogni ospite, e per ognuno 30 legioni, per ognuna delle quali 30 coorti, e ancora 30 manipoli, e tutti hanno ognuno 30 campi, e in ogni campo 365mila stelle, mille per ogni giorno dell’anno\n\nQuanto durerà ancora l’Universo? 6000 anni, poi sarà desolato per i successivi mille, o 2000.\n\nCome abbiamo detto, la cosmologia ebraica viene influenzata dai popoli con cui gli ebrei vengono a contatto; nel XII secolo BCE, Maimonide sviluppa una cosmologia a partire dalla concezione neo-platonica del mondo, con nove sfere, per la Luna, Mercurio, Venere, il Sole, Marte, Giove, Saturno, le stelle, e lo zodiaco. In questa visione, le sfere ruotano intorno alla Terra da Est verso Ovest, e il colore del cielo è una illusione ottica; le sfere sono trasparenti, senza pesi, senza colore. La Terra ha una superficie 40 volte la superficie della Luna, e il Sole ha una superficie 170 volte la superficie della Terra.\n\nUn solo Universo per un solo dio\n\nLa cosmologia islamica è l’insieme di teorie aristoteliche e tolemaiche, filtrate attraverso il neoplatonismo e l’ermetismo, con caratteristiche di culto gnostico. Così riassume la fonte che abbiamo utilizzato per questa sezione, in cui parliamo della visione dei dotti islamici.\n\nIl punto di partenza è la creazione dell’Universo da parte del Dio Creatore. Non ci si accorda, come nella tradizione ebraica, se ciò sia avvenuto a partire dall’esistente, o se la creazione sia stata ex nihilo . Dio ha creato tutto ciò che è, e separato il cielo dalla Terra, poiché prima erano unite. Il cielo e la Terra sono formati rispettivamente da sette cieli e sette Terre: in questo modo si spiega la presenza di sette diverse zone climatiche; e dei sette strati dell’Inferno; sopra gli strati del cielo c’è un piedistallo, sul quale siede il trono di Dio. La Terra e la regione sub-lunare sono il luogo in cui risiedono i minerali, le piante, gli animali, formati da fuoco, aria, acqua, e terra.\n\nLe sfere celesti ospitano, in ordine di vicinanza dalla Terra: la Luna, Mercurio, Venere, il Sole, Marte, Giove, Saturno, le stelle fisse divise nelle 12 regioni dello zodiaco, una nova sfera. Chiamata la “Sfera che ingloba” da Thabit ibn Kuwa , questa sfera serve a spiegare gli equinozi.\n\nNonostante le osservazioni sconfessano la presenza di moti circolari per i pianeti, si utilizzano gli strumenti geometrici degli epicicli, degli eccentrici e degli equanti per salvare i fenomeni : quanto spesso lo si è fatto nella storia, lo vedremo presto! I dotti musulmani si dividono tra i sostenitori di Tolomeo , come Ibn al-Hatham , il quale studia il moto planetario con le sfere omocentriche, e la teoria delle sfere solide, poiché il vuoto non esiste; e i Peripatetici Islamici, che critici di Tolomeo pubblicano “Una rettifica all’Almagesto”, anche loro però utilizzando la teoria delle sfere omocentriche (di cui parleremo quando incontreremo i Greci in questa storia).\n\nL’amore per le ipotesi e il ragionamento porta i dotti a domandarsi se altri tipi di moto possano funzionare: se ad esempio oltre al moto di rivoluzione circolare non possano esserci moti ellittici. Ad ogni modo, come dice al-Biruni , questo tipo di dibattiti è principalmente intellettuale, e la questione della natura dei moti nel cielo è una questione fisica, non astronomica. Per queste e altre ragioni, tra cui un crescente allontanamento dalla razionalità filosofica in favore di un irrazionale misticismo, e motivi di ordine politico e religioso, dal X al XVI secolo anche nel mondo islamico il dibattito cosmologico stagna, mentre viene lentamente riscoperto nell’Europa medioevale. Ma di questo parleremo più in là.\n\nArticoli della serie:\n\nBibliografia:\n\nEchoes of the Ancient Skies, di E. C. Tubb (Harper & Row 1983)\n\nAn Encyclopedia of Cosmologies and Myth in Ancient Astronomy, di Clive Ruggles (ABC-CLIO 2005)\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man's Changing Vision of the Universe, di Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, raccolta di saggi ad opera di C. Blacker e M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nCosmology of Ancient Egypt, di J.M. Plumley\n\nCosmology of Sumer and Babylon, di W.G. Lambert\n\nJewish Cosmology, di Louis Jacobs\n\nIslamic Cosmology, di Edith Jachimowicz\n\nAncient Light: our changing view of the Universe, di Alan Lightman (Cambridge 1991)\n\nQuesta newsletter è una di tre: le altre due sono Last Scattering Surface, e Space of Sound. Tutte le pubblicazioni sono gratuite e puoi consultare tutti gli articoli senza paywall. Se vuoi, puoi iscriverti qui e qui.\n\nInfine, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n\nCiao e a presto!\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_on-the-motion-of-the-earth-constants.md": "# constants, collections, synthesis\n\nDisclaimer #1: questo articolo è in inglese, la versione in italiano si può leggere qui.\n\nDisclaimer #2: this episode is part of a series named \" on the motion of the Earth ”, published both on this publication, Heralding Time , and on Last Scattering Surface . If you want, you can follow them both. The first chapter is here. The second is here.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/38856813-8b5e-4512-ba6b-496bcaba6f3c_1080x1350.png)\n\nIn previous episodes we talked about humanity’s first steps under the sky, the Sun, the planets and the stars, and the cosmologies of the Egyptians, the Babylonians, the Hebrews and the Islamic world.\n\nIn this episode we’ll talk about three other cultures that built a cosmology describing the place of Earth in the world: China, India, and Scandinavia.\n\nChina\n\nIn China’s millennia-long history, the first concepts of astronomy and the first cosmological conceptions arrive with the kai thien school of thought, which is succeeded by the hsuan yen , to finally arrive at the hun thien , which will supplant the other two.\n\nChinese astronomers recognize the ecliptic, perform measurements of celestial events, from comets to supernovae to solar or lunar eclipses; however, the lack of a deductive geometry like the one that will develop in Greece prevents the development of celestial mechanics.\n\nKai thien\n\nor “celestial cover,” represents a vaulted universe. The oldest school of those we’ll discuss, formed according to tradition during the time of the Shang dynasty (around 2000 BCE), describes the sky as a square-shaped bowl, upon which sits a circular hemisphere representing the sky. Sky and Earth are 80 thousand li apart (about 40 thousand kilometers).\n\nEarth is surrounded at its borders by a “border ocean,” into which the rains flow. The celestial sphere rotates around Earth from right to left, and the Sun and Moon, bound to this movement, also have their own proper motion. The setting and rising of the Moon and Sun are illusions, however, like the circumpolar stars: they’re no longer visible because they’ve moved too far away.\n\nHsuan yen\n\nstands for “infinite vacuity,” or infinite empty space. This doctrine describes the sky, the firmament, as completely empty and devoid of substance. The sky is immensely distant, immensely high, it has no limit whatsoever. Celestial bodies like the Sun and Moon are nothing but condensed vapor, and they wander through empty space, probably moving, or standing still. They’re not bound to one another, and fixed too is the star that determines the North Pole. The Big Dipper too, the constellation useful for finding North, never falls below the horizon.\n\nHun thien\n\nor “celestial circles,” is the doctrine that later replaced the two more ancient doctrines. The sky is like a chicken egg, and is spherical like a crossbow bolt. Earth is like the egg yolk, and lies at its center, at the center of the Universe. In the lower parts of the sky there is water, upon which Earth rests, and the heavens rest upon vapour.\n\nThe center of Earth is traversed by a celestial axis around which the sky rotates; this axis was initially located in China, which is the center of the world, but now it is no longer: it’s the result of a battle between the monster Kung Kung and China’s fourth mythical emperor, Yao , who shifted the sky in their battle, thus also changing the position of the world’s rotation axis.\n\nThis theory became around 180 CE the theory considered “true” in China, since as Chang Heng , a Chinese astronomer of the 1st century CE, formulates it, “there is no one alive currently who promotes this theory [hsuan yeh],” and “[kai thien] has been proven to be wrong and lacking many proofs and experiments.”\n\nAccumulation, not synthesis\n\nIndian cosmology, which R.F. Gombrich emphasises is different from Indian astronomy, can be divided into four strands, which follow the different doctrines that have visited the Asian continent over the millennia.\n\nVedic and Indu, Buddhist and Jain\n\nThe Purāṇas , among the first Hindu sacred texts, contain two themes linked to cosmology: the universe in space and the universe in time, and contain countless theories about human history, linked to different origins of the world. The complexity of these texts is due to the necessity and will to add descriptions, origins and explanations to already existing texts, rather than operating a synthesis of all previous knowledge.\n\nIn the Rig Veda , a collection of sacred texts dated approximately to the second half of the II millennium BCE, the universe is divided between earth, feminine, and sky, masculine, and the elements that compose it are earth, atmosphere, and sky; the universe begins with fire contained in primordial water.\n\nIn the sacred Brahmanas texts, the world is a shell divided in half, formed by two materials and two parts: gold is the sky, and silver represents Earth. The distance of earth from sky is “ 1000 days of travel by horse, and equals the height reached by 1000 cows arranged one on top of another .”\n\nFrom the Inquiry of Suka , a text describing the creation of time, we know that from Brahma, the great being, originates thought that creates the elements: ether, wind, fire, water and finally earth.\n\nEarth is a mass at the center of the Universe; it’s a flat disc, divided from being a single mass by oceans and continents. At the center of Earth is Mount Meru, a divine mountain located at the center of the world.\n\nFor the Jains, time is eternal, and Earth is a disc. In Buddhist philosophy, space and time are infinite; and infinite is the number of Earths.\n\nEarth rests upon water, and water upon air, and air upon space. The world, that is the Universe, expands and contracts.\n\n“Edo,” or “I write”\n\nThe cosmology of Scandinavian peoples originates in the time of pagan worship, and can be traced back to the Scandinavian Bronze Age (2000 - 500 BCE). It arises from oral culture, and its main text is the Prose Edda (to which is added the Poetic Edda ) compiled by Icelandic historian Snorri Sturluson in the XIII century CE.\n\nAt the center of the world, which is a flat disc, there is a tree, and all around Earth there is an ocean, which joins with underground primordial waters. Under the roots of the tree at the center of the world lies an enormous serpent. The tree’s name is Yggdrasil , and before the beginning of time there was only a formless abyss, Ginnuugagap . Life emerged from ice, and the first giant was named Ymir , which means being with two natures, because he was formed by spark and embers.\n\nThree legendary men kill the giant and form the world: from his body the Earth, from his blood the ocean, from his skin the sky. The sky is supported at the four corners of the world by four dwarves: Austri , Vestri , Nordri , and Sudri . East, West, North, South.\n\nThe gods of Scandinavian mythology are themselves representations of celestial powers, and the main ones are Thor and Odin , who are Aesir , and Freyr and Freyja , who are Vanir . The Aesir (or Asi) are the warrior deities, the Vanir are instead the deities linked to meteorological and natural events.\n\nOnce again, the sky and what happens there find explanation on Earth, and serve a purpose.\n\nIf in a kingdom order must remain as such, everything stays fixed, as in heaven, so on Earth; a land that is instead constantly invaded by other peoples, whose order is continuously modified and indeed overturned, tends to transport this dynamism into a cosmology that proceeds by accumulation and not by synthesis; again, an oral culture that recognises itself in a couple of works that have the purpose of summarising and making them consistent from beginning to end will create with those works an encyclopedia of previous myths and theories.\n\nIn the next episode: Hesiod, Homer, and the first philosophers.\n\nBibliography:\n\nEchoes of the Ancient Skies, by E. C. Tubb (Harper & Row 1983)\n\nAn Encyclopedia of Cosmologies and Myth in Ancient Astronomy, by Clive Ruggles (ABC-CLIO 2005)\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe, by Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, edited by C. Blacker and M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nCosmology of Ancient Egypt, by J.M. Plumley\n\nCosmology of Sumer and Babylon, by W.G. Lambert\n\nJewish Cosmology, by Louis Jacobs\n\nIslamic Cosmology, by Edith Jachimowicz\n\nCosmology of Early China, by Joseph Needham\n\nAncient Indian Cosmology, by R. F. Gombrich\n\nScandinavian Cosmology, by H. R. Ellis Davidson\n\nAncient Light: our changing view of the Universe, by Alan Lightman (Cambridge 1991)\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_on-the-motion-of-the-earth-homer.md": "# Homer, Hesiod, and a proto-philosopher\n\nDisclaimer #1: questo articolo è in inglese, la versione in italiano si può leggere qui.\n\nDisclaimer #2: this episode is part of a series named “ on the motion of the Earth ”, published both on this publication, Heralding Time , and on Last Scattering Surface . If you want, you can follow them both. The first chapter is here. The second is here. The third here.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d0639ebc-5e82-428a-916b-7e75cda03681_1080x1350.png)\n\nIn previous episodes we talked about the first conception of the sky among ancient peoples, the cosmologies of the Egyptians, the Babylonians, of Judaism and Islam, and those developed in China, India, and Scandinavia.\n\nStarting from this episode, we will begin a long journey in search of philosophy in Greece, and why it is connected to the theme of this series. We will see that it is precisely with cosmology that the first Greek thinkers launched the philosophical tradition in Greece.\n\nTo begin the journey into Greek philosophy, we must first cross the border that separates it from mythology. Taking a look at the map, constructing the itinerary, we see that this border is not a straight line, nor even a clear boundary: it has indentations and protrusions, enclaves and unexplored territories.\n\nThe sources of Greek mythology spring from the oral tales of Minoan and Mycenaean singers between the II and I millennium BCE: stories of men and gods, heroes and muses, wars and passions, stories about the origin of places and the origin of humanity; these sources flow throughout Greece, and into the various settlements and colonies that the Greeks founded in Asia Minor and Italy, and are collected, defined, and summarised in texts presented to the public around the VIII and VII centuries BCE. The first encounter we make following this river of myths and words is with a blind man, who is perhaps more than a man, and perhaps never existed.\n\nA blind man who perhaps never existed\n\nThe man we encounter is a blind bard who lived in Ionia in the VIII century before our era, and probably died in Ios , an island in the Cyclades in the Aegean Sea, around the middle of the following century. The man we encounter is the one to whom we attribute the two epic poems that began the Greek epic tradition, the Iliad and the Odyssey . But when questioned about how, when, and why he wrote these texts, the man vanishes.\n\nAs far as we know, Homer was never a historical figure. It is the common opinion of scholars that the two poems are not by the same author1, and that they were composed by a succession of authors and singers, who performed them publicly throughout Greece.\n\nIn any case, we can let ourselves be accompanied by the Homer of tradition, and speak of the unknown authors of the two poems as part of the figure of the legendary Homer.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9c14d495-d993-4d1c-8a41-eafe7c48d208_1240x1126.png)\n\nThe Iliad and the Odyssey contain the complete set of tools necessary to know the world, its pitfalls and dangers, its possibilities and riches. Among the stories they contain, there are also myths and stories about the creation of the world, about the shape it has and the forces that govern it.\n\nHomer describes the sky as a hemisphere , a bowl turned upside down, that looms over the Earth, a flat, circular disk. Between the Earth and the sky, in the part closest to the former, there is mist , while in the upper part there is more rarefied air - ether .\n\nUnder the roots of the Earth is Tartarus, which is as far from the Earth as the Earth is from the sky, and all around the Earth is the river Okeanos , “which encircles the Earth and flows into itself”2. Okeanos is at the same time, and depending on the description, a river, a spring, an ocean, composed of fresh sweet waters, the source of all the waters of the Earth, and a salty sea. From what experience could the idea of a multiform river around the world come? Probably not from Greece, but from the traditions of the kingdoms of Egypt and Mesopotamia, which arrived in the Greek world through contacts between different populations in previous centuries.\n\nTo the west, beyond the Pillars of Hercules , located at the boundary between what we today call the Mediterranean Sea and the Atlantic Ocean, rises Erebus , the place where the souls of the dead wait to enter Tartarus.\n\nThe epic poems do not raise the question of the Earth’s motion, which is evidently stationary: this is a common experience for every member of ancient Greece. The Sun, the Moon, and the stars rise in the east, and move across the sky every day, each day falling in the west. Since they return to the east each day to rise again and again, they must somehow get back there: but Tartarus is always dark , and never illuminated by any light, so the celestial bodies cannot cross through it .\n\nIt is the task then of the river Okeanos to transport the Sun, the Moon, and the stars from west back to east, circling around the Earth. As in the Egyptian tradition, here too the celestial bodies navigate on water, after death and before being reborn.\n\nAnd which stars does Homer know, which ones can men at sea use to orient themselves? Homer knows the morning star, Phosphorus, and the evening star, Hesperus; he knows the asterism of the Pleiades, that of the Hyades and the Big Dipper, and then the constellation Orion, and the stars Sirius and Arcturus.\n\nThe celestial vault is also stationary, and the motion of the celestial bodies is a reflection of the order of the world.\n\nBright marginal note #1\n\n- an asterism is a group of stars that forms a recognisable geometric shape, and which may or may not be part of a constellation. Famous asterisms are the Summer Triangle, formed by Altair, Deneb and Vega, or the Big Dipper, part of the constellation Ursa Major.\n\n- the brightest stars (called the Seven Sisters) of the Pleiades asterism are also present on a bronze age metal plate, the Nebra Disk, discovered in Germany in 1999.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/39dbd62f-a4e6-4599-9420-1ec00cd5242d_1611x1584.jpeg)\n\nNebra Disk. The circular figure on the left could be the Sun, or the full Moon. On the right, the crescent Moon. Above between the two, the seven luminous stars of the Pleiades. Credits here.\n\nHomer bids us farewell, and returns to the obscurity in which his passage on Earth and through History is shrouded.\n\nA singer of the birth of the gods\n\nAfter taking leave of the figure of Homer, the journey from myth to the physical description of the world continues with the awareness that the world is full of gods: anthropomorphic, certainly, but also allegories of human concepts and emotions. To answer the question “How are the gods born?” we approach Hesiod, a singer who lived between the VIII and VII centuries BCE, and probably originally from Cyme (Aeolian Cyme), a city in the region of Aeolia, in Asia Minor. This man, who lived in Boeotia - a region of mainland Greece - wrote three works that we can read in their entirety: “ Theogony ,” “ Works and Days ”, and “ The Shield of Heracles ”. A poem titled “On Astronomy”3 is also attributed to him, of which we read only fragments, which in any case do not inform us about what we wish to know.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6f36bea8-dc21-4a50-a50d-3c68c8ea6496_1240x1126.png)\n\nWe are in fact gripped by the problem of the birth of the forces that govern the world, and of the gods who exercise those forces. We are freed by the song of Hesiod, who in the Theogony, the Birth of the Gods, recounts the beginning of the world and everything that follows.\n\nThe first thing that happened to the world, the first event, is the separation of Earth and Sky, into two distinct entities, since they were united. Therefore the first event is not the creation of something nonexistent , but the separation of something already pre-existing .\n\n[...] Verily at the first Chaos came to be, but next\n\nwide-bosomed Earth , the ever-sure foundations of all\n\nthe deathless ones who hold the peaks of snowy Olympus,\n\nand dim Tartarus in the depth of the wide-pathed Earth,\n\nand Eros , fairest among the deathless gods,\n\nwho unnerves the limbs and overcomes the mind and wise counsels of all\n\ngods and all men within them.\n\nFrom Chaos came forth Erebus and black Night ,\n\nbut of Night were born Aether and Day ,\n\nwhom she conceived and bare from union in love with Erebus .\n\nAnd Earth first bare starry Heaven , equal to herself,\n\nto cover her on every side,\n\n[...]\n\nBut afterwards she lay with Heaven and bare deep-swirling Oceanus [...]\n\nHesiod, Theogony , 116-127, 129. Hesiod, the Homeric hymns, and Homerica; with an English translation by Hugh G. Evelyn-White . Credits here.\n\nThe world pre-exists the birth of the gods, who are born as representations of the Places and States of the world: Sky, Earth, Night, Erebus (the Underworld), Ether, Day, Ocean; but also Emotions and Sensations such as Shame, Anguish, Strife, Famine, Work, Lies. Only later will the gods of Olympus arrive to dethrone Kronos, who in turn dethroned Ouranos, with the help of Gaia, consort of Ouranos, and Rhea, consort of Kronos.\n\nIn the beginning, however, there is Chaos : in the Greek tradition this term means what it also means for us, a synonym for disorder and confusion.\n\nHere, Hesiod gives the name Chaos to that which separates Sky from Earth, the first separation. The first act of the world, therefore, is the birth of Chaos understood as the action of separation, of distinction .\n\nBright marginal note #2\n\nThe conception of the distinction between Sky and Earth is present in many cultures:\n\n- for the Maori people, Rangi (the sky) and Papa (the earth) are separated;\n\n- we have seen in the Egyptian myth that Nut and Geb are separated by Shu;\n\n- the same happens in the Song of Ullikummi, a myth from Hittite-Hurrian mythology that seems to have many (subsequent) parallels in Greece;\n\n- in the Babylonian myth of the Enuma Elish, the hero-god Marduk tears Tiamat into two pieces: the sky and the earth;\n\n- Genesis: “Let there be a firmament in the midst of the waters to separate the waters from the waters.” Also due to the strong Babylonian influences on the biblical myth of the creation of the world, at a certain point the creator god of the Bible creates the firmament to separate the earth and the sky.\n\nHesiod does not speak of what existed before this separation, nor of why it occurred. The Theogony speaks of the gods, and they are the origin of order in the world, the κόσμος (cosmos). Each divinity has its own “department” to control and over which to reign; this control is not always exclusive: in some cases an event, a force, a place are contested by multiple divinities, and this creates a world that is not totally ordered .\n\nThe Theogony does not contain original or new ideas: it is a collection of stories and myths already present, which it undertakes to codify. But as will also happen with the first thinkers we call philosophers, Hesiod too firmly believes in an ordered world, in a divine presence in the world, which permeates both the physical and moral aspects of humanity.\n\nHesiod’s world is a flat, circular disk, as in Homer, and above it is the Sky, populated by the Sun, the Moon, and the stars; below it is Tartarus, never illuminated by any light. The space between sky and earth is bright by day, and dark by night. As in Homer, and as in the myths of other peoples of the Mediterranean, the celestial bodies move across the sky; after setting beyond the horizon, they navigate Ocean to return each day to the place where they will rise again, again and again.\n\nNow Hesiod departs, and the gods he sang of remain, transforming themselves.\n\nA syncretic and mysterious proto-philosopher\n\nWe have almost reached the end of the first stage, which from the territories of mythology arrives at the threshold of natural philosophy. The next character we encounter is a proto-philosopher, a man who transported ideas and influences from Asia to Greece, and who from Greece will bring ideas and influences back to Asia. With him we will cross the centuries straddling the eras, and the borders between kingdoms and peoples.\n\nApollodorus of Athens maintains that Pherecydes of Syros was a contemporary of Anaximander of Miletus, and places his floruit - the period of greatest prominence for his contemporaries - around 540 BCE; but this is not confirmed. We know that he lived in the VI century BCE, and that a legend from the IV century BCE represents him as the teacher of Pythagoras, who in his final years would have remained with him and would have buried him4. We are not certain of this, but it is true that his texts circulated in Pythagorean circles, and there are similarities between the teachings of Pythagoras and Pherecydes.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1e891fe5-1cd3-484d-a112-8ee6065d96ef_1240x1076.png)\n\nUnlike the other philosophers, and adding to the strength of his legendary figure, it is said that he received no teaching from a master, but that he consulted a secret book of the Phoenicians , and the prophecy of Ham , (that is, Zoroaster). In any case, contacts with Phoenicia are evident from his father’s name, Babis or Babys , a clear name of Asian origin (probably coming from Phrygia, Pisidia or Galatia - all regions of Asia Minor).\n\nIn his work The Seven Niches , Pherecydes speaks of three divinities who have always existed: Zeus, whom he calls Zas, and whom he might - but it is not clear - associate with the Sun; Kronos, who although he has the same name as the god of Time dwells in and governs the Isles of the Blessed; and Chthonie, the goddess who represents the Earth.\n\nAfter the union between Zas and Chthonie, the Earth becomes Ge, and she is given by Zas, now also become Eros, a mantle that she wears forming the earth, but which according to a subsequent passage ends up hanging on a “ World Tree ”.\n\nBright marginal note #3\n\nThis is a story that serves two purposes: to represent the birth of the world, and to describe a human activity, the anakalyptenia , or the ritual gift from husband to bride that takes place on the third day of the wedding. Once again, the myths simultaneously represent what happens here on earth and what is hidden, and this and from this they influence and are influenced.\n\nZas and Ge produce the other gods together; Chronos does so “in union with himself”: the birth of the world or a part of it as the result of an action of this type is common in Asian myths and cosmologies, and is another piece that composes the picture of Pherecydes as syncretic between Greece and Asia. We will talk about this further on.\n\nChronos creates fire, wind, and water from his seed, and distributes them in the world, in the five nooks of the title (”The Seven Niches” is in Greek Ἑπτάμυχος, and μυχος has among other possible meanings also nook ). We do not know which places Pherecydes refers to, but they are probably the places from which the gods spring forth, the following five provinces: the sky, the Earth, Ogenos, Hades and Tartarus). The first two are obvious, while about the others we will have to speak: Ogenos is another spelling of a term we have already encountered, Okeanos. Hades and Tartarus instead are the dwelling of the dead and the place where there is no light, respectively. The evil gods defeated by Chronos, led by Ophioneus, a god whose origin can be linked to the primordial serpents of Babylonian mythologies, and who is also found in the biblical Genesis, are thrown back into the sea formed by Ogenos at the edge of the world.\n\nIn Pherecydes’ cosmology, finally, the gods live on the Moon, the Earth is inhabited and all around it has Ogenos, and beneath it is the world of the dead, which in turn looms over Tartarus.\n\nBright marginal note #4\n\nWe have spoken of Pherecydes as syncretic. Here’s why:\n\n- Eudemus of Argos connects Pherecydes to the cosmology of Sidon, a Phoenician settlement. Here in the beginning there are Chronos (time), Pothos (wind), and Omichle (darkness). In various cosmologies of Phoenician culture, the primordial wind is represented by Aither and Aer, who generate Ulōmos, which comes from the late Phoenician ‘ūlōm, ‘ōlām for the Hebrews, which means Remote Time or Eternity. From these is born an egg, from which heaven and earth are generated.\n\n- in Zoroastrian cosmology, in the beginning there is nothing but Zurvan, Time. He too generates alone , Ohrmazd, the Good, and Ahriman, the Evil. The first creates the material world, forming the egg-shaped firmament, in which everything is contained.\n\n- In the sacred Indian hymns Atharvaveda, Kala (Time) autonomously generates heaven and earth.\n\nPherecydes is a proto-philosopher, in the sense that in his work there is a principle that was missing in previous poets, and that we will encounter in those we call philosophers: the preference for prose over verse, the will to speak of the gods, even accepting their existence, only as an allegory of the forces that regulate the world; the description of the world as ordered from the beginning , without an order that arrives after the action of one or more gods.\n\nFrom now on, even the gods will have to answer the question that philosophers pose: why? Pherecydes asks it of us too, and disappears into the Time that is already Past.\n\nCrossing the border\n\nWe have crossed the plains of myth, and the paths of the gods. We have discovered connections, bonds, syncretisms, but also individualities, both singular and collective. It will seem in the future that we have returned to these lands; it will seem we recognize the scent of flowers, and the taste of fruits: but we will return, if we do, with a new awareness.\n\nThat myths are, have always been, and perhaps still will be, waiting for new hypotheses and theories.\n\nThe next steps will take us toward a mountain chain, in which each one represents the thought of a philosopher: these mountains have tunnels and passes that connect one to another, unique glaciers made eternal by time on unreachable peaks, streams that flow from one mountain and from another receive new water to transform into rivers of thought, lakes that collect those rivers, and the Ocean of the Earth all around, to remind us that after all, this Earth whose movement we want to understand, is Alone and One, and all around there is the Rest, and the Darkness.\n\nIn the next episode: the philosophers from Miletus.\n\nRead the other episodes:\n\nBibliography:\n\nAristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus, by Heath T. (Oxford 1913)\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, by Kirk G.S. e Raven J.E. (Cambridge 1957)\n\nEarly Greek Philosophy and the Orient, by West M.L. (Oxford 1971)\n\nPhilosophy before Socrates, by McKirahan R.D. (Hackett 1994)\n\nThanks to EB for revising the text.\n\nFootnotes\n\n1 “The Invention of Homer”, West, M.L. (1999); Classical Quarterly 49 (2)\n\n2 “Aristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus”, Heath T. (1913)\n\n3 ibid.\n\n4 “Early Greek Philosophy and the Orient”, West M.L. (1971)\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_on-the-motion-of-the-earth-thales.md": "# Thales and the water\n\nDisclaimer #1: questo articolo è in inglese, la versione in italiano si può leggere qui.\n\nDisclaimer #2: this episode is part of a series named “ on the motion of the Earth ”, published both on this publication, Heralding Time , and on Last Scattering Surface . If you want, you can follow them both. Here chapters I, II, III, IV.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9447bdf5-5146-49cc-863c-37be72347cbb_1080x1350.png)\n\nWelcome back.\n\nIn previous episodes, ancient skies full of gods appeared, rivers and mountains in Egypt and Babylon, upturned bowls and sacred texts in China, India and Scandinavia.\n\nHaving returned to Asia Minor, we have traveled the border between mythology and cosmology in Greece. Having left behind a blind poet, a narrator of the birth of the gods, and a syncretic proto-philosopher, it is time to talk about the first philosophers who appeared in Greece, and the worlds they described and the place of the Earth in them.\n\nToo many questions?\n\nBefore setting off, let’s try to clarify the reason for the title of this series: why, to understand what the answers have been to an apparently technical question like “what is the motion of the Earth?”, have we talked about a bronze age artifact , divinities and sacred texts, to arrive in Greece to talk about philosophy?\n\nBecause the Greek philosophers are the first to try to answer this question in a way similar to how we do, posing questions valid in every time, and they respond by questioning Nature, no longer the gods. The two interpretations of the world can indeed coexist - not all philosophers reject the concept of the existence of gods, obviously - but philosophy in Greece proceeds in the direction of “filling the gaps” of inexplicable natural events with logical, rational explanations, even if not necessarily “scientific”: the concept of scientific experiment as we understand it today is not born in the classical Greek world, but in some cases one can glimpse an attitude that we could define as “replicable” or “quantifiable”.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b2809861-0dd4-4bd5-bf9a-80cbab7a22a9_800x780.jpeg)\n\nLight Flowing Forth from the Blackness. Picture taken from Public Domain Image Archive / Internet Archive / The Getty.\n\nThe questions that the Greek philosophers ask themselves, from Miletus to Athens, from Croton to Samos, concern the world, now conceived as a unity , autonomous unto itself; the material constitution of the world itself, continuous unity or formed by discrete elements; its birth or creation as the product of an accident , a design or a necessity ; the possibility that its Creator is a transcendent or immanent figure; its duration, whether finite or endless ; the number of worlds, one or innumerable , and in this case whether contemporary or successive to one another.\n\nThese and other questions bounce from island to island, from city to city, transported by the lives of these thinkers, and by the concept common to all of them, that ideas are discussed and do not constitute dogma .\n\nArthur Koestler, whom we have already encountered in previous episodes, speaks of the 6th century BCE as a period in which humanity awakened and began to seek answers to the questions we still ask ourselves today: he speaks of figures like Buddha, Confucius, Lao-Tze, and then of Ionian philosophers and Pythagoreans.\n\nThe first three are mystical, religious figures, of authority and not men of science, however wise and fundamental in morality and philosophy.\n\nWe will now speak of the philosophers of Miletus - the Ionians of whom Koestler speaks, the philosophers of Nature, starting with Thales.\n\nBut first, let’s talk about Miletus.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2bf887d5-e02f-47ac-96e7-b720c71091e7_1240x1126.png)\n\nMiletus\n\nThe polis of Miletus exists, at the time of the philosophers we will discuss in this episode, for more than 300 years. Like other cities of the Aegean Sea islands, it was founded after the collapse of the Mycenaean civilization of the bronze age.\n\nStarting from the dall’VIII century BCE these cities create colonies in Southern Italy, to the west, and on the coasts of the Black Sea, to the north. Especially in this way, and with the settlements in Asia Minor, the citizens of the poleis come into contact with other populations, coming from Mesopotamia, or from Egypt, or from Asia Minor itself.\n\nMiletus is governed by aristocratic men not belonging to any religious cult; religion is kept separate from political life, despite both being public activities. Moreover, although the poems of Homer and Hesiod are a common heritage of all Greek cities, the absence of a single and hereditary caste of priestly class (as happens in Egypt for millennia) does not facilitate the creation of a dogma common to all of Greece, to be followed and from which not to deviate. Each city enjoys its own albeit not total autonomy. To put it with McKirahan1, there is no Bible in the Greek world.\n\nIt is in this polis, in this cultural, mercantile, political, religious environment, that the three philosophers of this episode live, in which they expound their own visions of the world, of its birth and its nature.\n\nThales\n\nRemember Pherecydes, the proto-philosopher from the previous episode? It was said of him that he had secret knowledge learned from the Phoenicians.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/17c883eb-7b2d-4eb6-8bcb-3da0c9adb759_2700x3768.jpeg)\n\nThalész by Büky Béla - 1963 - Rippl-Rónai Municipal Museum con County Scope - Kaposvár, Hungary - CC BY.\n\nAlso for Thales it is told2 that he had a possible descent from this people: perhaps not on his mother Cleobulina’s side - which seems to be a Greek name, but his father, Examyes, is said to be from a Phoenician family. More likely that his family was originally from Cadmea, a city of Boeotia (mainland Greece) who moved to Boeotia (a region of Asia Minor). In any case, whether he was actually of Phoenician lineage, or whether this belonging was imposed on him later, the link between Greek science and technology and the Phoenicians does not end with the mythical period.\n\nThales was born around 624 BCE, in his city he is a man of government and an “engineer”: various stories are told about him, to represent him in often opposite ways; all tell us something about him as a philosopher.\n\nIn a dialogue by Plato3 it is reported that a slave from Thrace tells of when Thales ended up in a well, because he was more engaged in observing the sky than in realising what was happening under his feet. Another tale speaks of when he managed to foresee that he would profit from the yield of oil and bought many olive groves of the time at low prices, drawing great profit from it.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9260683f-0e09-4c7c-b116-7039e2decf18_591x800.jpeg)\n\nNovember Meteors, by Étienne Léopold Trouvelot, 1882 . Picture taken from Public Domain Image Archive / New York Public Library.\n\nBoth of these stories speak of practical consequences of Thales’ “philosophical” life: even if probably legendary, the first tells of the “philosopher in the clouds,” far from common life; the second of a man who with his studies and calculations could have drawn enormous riches. On this point, Aristotle explains that Thales was not attracted to it, despite being more than well-off - after all, he was a member of the city aristocracy - since it is not in his interest to enrich himself thanks to his ingenuity.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ec711e97-0367-4221-a708-51af6c518dff_1280x1280.png)\n\nLast Scattering Surface\n\nAnnals of LSS: why is dark at night? E.A.Poe and Olbers's Paradox The darkness of the sky looks natural. The Sunsets is at the horizon, maybe there is a new moon and you are left with the light of stars (and light pollution, unfortunately…\n\nRead more\n\n3 years ago · 3 likes\n\nRegarding his philosophical activity, his travels to Egypt are recounted. This is not hard to believe, since during this period Miletus has some colonies in those areas, including Naucratis4. According to Diogenes Laertius, who cites Eudemus, Thales wrote “ On the Solstice ” and “ On the Equinox ” - texts we do not have. As will also happen with others among the philosophers we will discuss, their theories are known exclusively through secondhand or thirdhand accounts, with all the imprecisions and modifications to the original thought that this entails.\n\nHerodotus reports that Thales is famous for being the first in Greece to predict a solar eclipse, between 585 and 584 BCE, the period in which his acme is placed, that is, the highest point of his philosophical activity. This is debatable, and it is even more so if one imagines that he predicted the exact day5.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/46ad5b86-68e6-431a-bf9c-bba26310ba92_1005x1200.jpeg)\n\nEclipse Diagram, from Illustrated Astronomy di Asa Smith, 1849. Picture taken from Public Domain Image Archive / Smithsonian Libraries and Archives.\n\nThales is the one who brought abstract geometry to Greece , affirms A. Koestler6. From where? From Egypt and Mesopotamia. Precisely in Mesopotamia it is at least since 721 BCE that solstices and lunations are recorded7, from which one can calculate approximately when an eclipse will occur8; it is not strange for a scholar of that era in Greece to visit the city of Sardis, in Asia Minor, which the Hittites called Uda, thus contacts with Babylonian civilisation are achievable. This is recorded in a similar way also by Theon of Smyrna, who reports Thales’ knowledge of the different duration that the different seasons have during the course of the year.\n\nFor Thales, solar eclipses occur when the Sun is covered by the Moon; similarly, when the Earth is between the Moon and the Sun, lunar eclipses occur.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/931d02be-b0cd-42d1-81ac-28a5d4406fdb_586x799.jpeg)\n\nPartial Eclipse of the Moon, by Étienne Léopold Trouvelot, 1882 . Picture taken from Public Domain Image Archive / New York Public Library.\n\nThales knows when the solstices will occur: this seems feasible, with a suitable instrument, the gnomon, of Babylonian derivation and which Eudemus recounts allowed the philosopher to measure the height of the pyramids, using the principle of proportions between the length of the shadow of an object and that of the pyramid at the same hour of the day, with the actual measurements of that object and the pyramid.\n\nAccording to Callimachus9, Thales observes Ursa Minor starting from Ursa Major, as the Phoenicians do, and advises Greek sailors to use this method to orient themselves and find north10.\n\nThe study of Babylonian tables to predict upcoming eclipses; the measurement of the days that pass between a solstice and the following equinox; the study of the positions of stars in asterisms and constellations: all these things compose the study of ἀστρονομία, astronomy.\n\nThales goes further, and constructs a cosmological model. We know its (few) details from the works in which it is described (and criticised) by Aristotle: the “De cælo” and the “Metaphysics.” Aristotle attributes to Thales the phrase “all things are full of gods,” McKirahan speaks of a Thales with a Janus face, dual. The Thales of whom Aristotle speaks describes a world in which the things that happen are the work of Nature: the Earth floats on water, and the principle of all things is water.\n\nThe first conception is probably of Egyptian and Babylonian derivation. The second is an interpretation by Aristotle, who connects the concept of ἀρχή, the first principle, to water for Thales as an answer to the question: what is the principle of all things? The questions seem to be two in reality, namely: what generates all things ? and where do all things come from ?\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6858b4e6-14d9-4057-b1ab-551fd4bf97da_2448x1992.jpeg)\n\nWater, by Maerten de Vos, Adriaen Collaert, 1580-1584 . Picture taken from Public Domain Image Archive / Rijksmuseum.\n\nThe answer therefore for Thales is water, understood not only as the liquid we drink or that flows in a river or that forms the sea, but as a fluid that generates life: it is connected to rain, to semen, to bodily fluids and to everything that flows. Here Thales evokes the Babylonian tradition of water as generating power, and the Egyptian one of creative water. But in Thales there is nothing magical or religious: water is part of the Nature from which everything comes. It is the origin of everything, but it has an origin that is part of this world and that we can observe.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a9daf835-0536-4732-a0bc-8750f2ae2ae7_1280x1280.png)\n\nSpace of Sound\n\nsingle space: About Today, by The National I said I would be back in September: a promise is a promise. But I didn’t sit idly by…\n\nRead more\n\n6 months ago · 2 likes · Antonio Viscusi\n\nHow is the world formed starting from water? Thales does not say, and we do not know his cosmogony, but we know that the Sun and Moon are made of the same substance that composes the Earth, having detached from it after creation. The Earth is a cylindrical disk, perhaps a bit concave - this vision would be consistent with the Babylonian vision of the world according to which the Earth is surrounded by mountains, before being surrounded by Okeanos - which rests on water.\n\nIt is stationary in the Universe, and the Sun, Moon and stars perform their motions around it, and when they are no longer visible beyond the horizon they circle around the Earth to return to rise in the east. The light of the Moon is the reflection of the light that arrives from the Sun, and air is formed from the evaporation of water.\n\nThales shares the vision not only of Babylon and Egypt, but also that of Homer and Hesiod, who tell of a flat Earth that rests on water.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f10eeaf8-b914-441b-be07-5ab10d572f53_1200x938.jpeg)\n\nUniverse with Earth, Sun, Moon, and Stars, by Caspar Luyken, 1712. Picture taken from Public Domain Image Archive / Rijksmuseum.\n\nUnlike them, and this is why we define him a philosopher , he wonders what lies beyond , seeks explanations in Nature and not in myths, tries to imagine causes . He does this for example with earthquakes, whose cause he attributes to the movement of the water that supports the Earth. This is a surprising novelty: Thales attempts to explain an observable event by resorting to a non-observable hypothesis , but consistent with his vision of the world. What is missing to complete the requirements of the scientific method? The experiment to be performed to verify the hypothesis - which in any case would have refuted the hypothesis11.\n\nThales searches for the raw material that composes the world. That he was wrong in identifying it is not important, for the journey we have undertaken.\n\nIn the next episode: the other Milesians philosophers.\n\nRead the other episodes:\n\nBibliography:\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe, by Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, edited by C. Blacker and M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nGreek Cosmologies, by G.E.R. Lloyd\n\nAristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus, by Heath T. (Oxford 1913)\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, by Kirk G.S. and Raven J.E. (Cambridge 1957)\n\nEarly Greek Philosophy and the Orient, by West M.L. (Oxford 1971)\n\nPhilosophy before Socrates, by McKirahan R.D. (Hackett 1994)\n\nEarly Greek Science, by G.E.R. Lloyd (Chatto & Windus 1970)\n\nA history of astronomy from Thales to Kepler, by J.L.E Dreyer (Dover 1953)\n\nNotes\n\n1 McKirahan R.D., Philosophy before Socrates, pg. 21\n\n2 Herodotus, histories, I.\n\n3 Plato, Theaetetus , 174.\n\n4 Ætius, Proclus, Plutarch. Plutarch underlines that water plays an important role in Egyptian mythology.\n\n5 Theon of Smyrne, Diogenes Laertius (quoting Eudemus) and Clemens of Alexandria, reporting this episode. Martin, in Revue Archéologique, underlines that it looks then Thales discovered rather than predict, the solar eclipse.\n\n6 A. Koestler, Sleepwalkers: : A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe\n\n7 “synodic” month, which is the period of time the Moon takes to complete a cycle of its phases. It lasts about 29 days, 12 hours and 44 minutes.\n\n8 Diogenes Laertius, quoting Eudemus.\n\n9 Diogenes Laertius, quoting Callimachus.\n\n10 Eudemus quotes another book, “Nautical star guide”.\n\n11 Or maybe not completely? Today we know that earthquakes are mainly caused by the movements of tectonic plates, but there also are earthquakes caused by magma flowing - like water!\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_sul-moto-della-terra-costanti-raccolte.md": "# costanti, raccolte, sintesi\n\nDisclaimer #1: this article is in Italian. I will publish the English version next Wednesday.\n\nDisclaimer #2: questo pezzo fa parte di una serie, pubblicata sia su questa newsletter, Heralding Time , che su Last Scattering Surface . Se vuoi, puoi seguirle entrambe. Il primo capitolo si legge qui. Il secondo qui.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/7181c20c-c1b5-4fbd-ac3a-b68dbc6da148_1080x1350.png)\n\nNei precedenti episodi abbiamo parlato dei primi passi dell’umanità sotto il cielo, il Sole, i pianeti e le stelle, e delle cosmologie degli Egiziani, dei Babilonesi, degli Ebrei e degli Islamici.\n\nIn questo episodio parleremo di altre tre culture che hanno costruito una cosmologia descrivendo il posto della Terra nel mondo: Cina, India, e Scandinavia.\n\nCina\n\nNella millenaria storia della Cina i primi concetti di astronomia e le prime concezioni cosmologiche arrivano con la scuola di pensiero del kai thien , a cui succede la hsuan yen , per arrivare infine alla hun thien, che soppianterà le altre due.\n\nGli astronomi cinesi riconoscono l’eclittica, effettuano misurazioni degli eventi celesti, dalle comete alle supernovae alle eclissi solari o lunari; la mancanza però di una geometria deduttiva come si svilupperà in Grecia non permette lo sviluppo di una meccanica celeste.\n\nKai thien\n\no “copertura celeste”, sta a rappresentare un universo a volta. La più antica scuola di quelle di cui parleremo, formatasi secondo la tradizione all’epoca della dinastia Shang (intorno al 2000 BCE), descrive il cielo come una ciotola di forma quadrata, su cui c’è un emisfero circolare che rappresenta il cielo. Il cielo e la Terra sono distanti 80mila li (circa 40mila chilometri).\n\nLa Terra è circondata ai suoi confini da un ”oceano bordo”, in cui defluiscono le piogge. La sfera celeste ruota intorno alla Terra da destra verso sinistra, e il Sole e la Luna, solidali a questo movimento, hanno anche un loro moto proprio. Il tramontare e il sorgere della Luna e del Sole sono però illusioni, come le stelle circumpolari: non si vedono più poiché si sono allontanate troppo.\n\nHsuan yen\n\nsta per “infinita vacuità”, o spazio vuoto infinito. Questa dottrina descrive il cielo, il firmamento, come completamente vuoto e privo di sostanza. Il cielo è immensamente lontano, immensamente in alto, non ha alcun limite. I corpi celesti come il Sole e la Luna non sono altro che vapore condensato, e vagano nello spazio vuoto, probabilmente muovendosi, o stando fermi. Non sono legati l’uno all’altro, e fissa è anche la stella che determina il Polo Nord. Anche l’Orsa Maggiore, la costellazione utile per trovare il Nord, non cade mai sotto l’orizzonte.\n\nHun thien\n\no “cerchi celesti”, è la dottrina che ha poi sostituito le due dottrine più antiche. Il cielo è come un uovo di gallina, ed è sferico come un proiettile di balestra. La Terra è come il tuorlo dell’uovo, e giace nel suo centro, al centro dell’Universo. Nelle parti inferiori del cielo c’è acqua, su cui giace la Terra, e i cieli riposano sul vapore.\n\nIl centro della Terra è attraversato da un asse celeste intorno a cui ruota il cielo; questo asse inizialmente si trovava in Cina, che è il centro del mondo, ma ora non lo è più: è il risultato di una battaglia tra il mostro Kung Kung e il quarto imperatore mitico della Cina, Yao , che hanno spostato il cielo nella loro battaglia, cambiando così anche la posizione dell’asse di rotazione del mondo.\n\nQuesta teoria è diventata intorno al 180 CE la teoria considerata “vera” in Cina, poiché come formula Chang Heng , astronomo cinese del I secolo CE, “non c’è nessuno vivo attualmente che promuove questa teoria [hsuan yeh]”, e “[kai thien] è stata provata essere sbagliata e mancante di molti prove ed esperimenti”.\n\nAccumulazione, non sintesi\n\nLa cosmologia indiana, che R.F. Gombrich sottolinea essere diversa dall’astronomia indiana, può essere divisa in quattro filoni, che seguono le diverse dottrine che nei millenni hanno visitato il continente asiatico.\n\nVedica e Indu, Buddista e Jain\n\nI Purāṇa , tra i primi testi sacri hindu, contengono due temi legati alla cosmologia: l’universo nello spazio e l’universo nel tempo, e contengono innumerevoli teorie sulla storia umana, legata a diverse origini del mondo. La complessità di questi testi è dovuta alla necessità e alla volontà di aggiungere descrizioni, origini e spiegazioni ai testi già presenti, piuttosto che operare una sintesi di tutte le precedenti conoscenze.\n\nNei Rig Veda , collezione di testi sacri datati all’incirca alla seconda metà del II millennio BCE, l’universo è diviso tra la terra, femminile, e il cielo, maschile, e gli elementi che lo compongono sono la terra, l’atmosfera, e il cielo; l’universo inizia con il fuoco contenuto nell’acqua primordiale.\n\nNei testi sacri Brahmanas il mondo è un guscio diviso a metà, formato da due materiali e da due parti: l’oro è il cielo, e l’argento rappresenta la Terra. La distanza della terra dal cielo è di “ 1000 giorni di viaggio a cavallo, ed è pari all’altezza che raggiungono 1000 mucche disposte una sull’altra” .\n\nDall’ Indagine di Suka, testo che descrive la creazione del tempo, sappiamo che da Brahma, il grande essere, si origina il pensiero che crea gli elementi: l’etere, il vento, il fuoco, l’acqua e infine la terra.\n\nLa Terra è una massa al centro dell’Universo; è un disco piatto, diviso dall’essere un’unica massa da oceani e continenti. Al centro della Terra c’è il Monte Meru, un monte divino che si trova al centro del mondo.\n\nPer i Giainisti il tempo è eterno, e la Terra è un disco. Nella filosofia buddista, spazio e tempo sono infiniti; e infinito è il numero di Terre.\n\nLa Terra giace sull’acqua, e l’acqua sull’aria, e l’aria sullo spazio. Il mondo, ovvero l’Universo, si espande e si contrae.\n\n“Edo”, o “io scrivo”\n\nLa cosmologia dei popoli scandinavi nasce al tempo del culto pagano, e si può ricondurre all’Età del Bronzo Scandinava (2000 - 500 BCE). Nasce dalla cultura orale, e il suo testo principale è l’ Edda in Prosa (a cui si aggiunge l’ Edda Poetica ) riunite dallo storico islandese Snorri Sturluson nel XIII secolo CE.\n\nAl centro del mondo, che è un disco piatto, c’è un albero, e tutto intorno alla Terra c’è un oceano, che si riunisce con le acque primordiali sotterranee. Sotto le radici dell’albero al centro del mondo giace un enorme serpente. Il nome dell’albero è Yggdrasil , e prima dell’inizio del tempo c’era solo un abisso informe, Ginnuugagap . La vita è emersa dal ghiacccio, e il primo gigante aveva nome Ymir , che significa essere con due nature, poiché era formato dalla scintilla e dalle braci.\n\nTre uomini leggendari uccidono il gigante e formano il mondo: dal suo corpo la Terra, dal suo sangue l’oceano, dalla sua pelle il cielo. Il cielo è sorretto ai quattro angoli del mondo da quattro nani: Austri , Vestri , Nordri , and Sudri . Est, Ovest, Nord, Sud.\n\nGli dei della mitologia scandinava sono anch’essi raffigurazioni delle potenze celesti, e i principali sono Thor e Odino , che sono Aesir , e Freyr e Freyja , che sono Vaenir . Gli Aesir (o Asi) sono le divinità guerriere, i Vaenir sono invece le divinità legate agli eventi meteorologici e naturali.\n\nAncora una volta, il cielo e ciò che vi accade trovano spiegazione sulla Terra, e servono a uno scopo.\n\nSe in un regno l’ordine deve rimanere tale, tutto resta fermo, come in cielo, così sulla Terra ; una terra che invece viene costantemente invasa da altri popoli, il cui ordine viene continuamente modificato e anzi stravolto, tende a trasportare questo dinamismo in una cosmologia che procede per accumulazione e non per sintesi; ancora, una cultura orale che si riconosce in un paio di opere che hanno lo scopo di riassumerle e renderle consistenti dall’inizio alla fine creerà con quelle opere una enciclopedia dei miti e delle teorie precedenti.\n\nNel prossimo episodio: Esiodo, Omero, e i primi filosofi.\n\nArticoli della serie:\n\nBibliografia:\n\nEchoes of the Ancient Skies, di E. C. Tubb (Harper & Row 1983)\n\nAn Encyclopedia of Cosmologies and Myth in Ancient Astronomy, di Clive Ruggles (ABC-CLIO 2005)\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe, di Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, raccolta di saggi ad opera di C. Blacker e M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nCosmology of Ancient Egypt, di J.M. Plumley\n\nCosmology of Sumer and Babylon, di W.G. Lambert\n\nJewish Cosmology, di Louis Jacobs\n\nIslamic Cosmology, di Edith Jachimowicz\n\nCosmology of Early China, di Joseph Needham\n\nAncient Indian Cosmology, di R. F. Gombrich\n\nScandinavian Cosmology, di H. R. Ellis Davidson\n\nAncient Light: our changing view of the Universe, di Alan Lightman (Cambridge 1991)\n\nQuesta newsletter è una di tre: le altre due sono Last Scattering Surface, e Space of Sound. Tutte le pubblicazioni sono gratuite e puoi consultare tutti gli articoli senza paywall. Se vuoi, puoi iscriverti qui e qui.\n\nInfine, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n\nCiao e a presto!\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_sul-moto-della-terra-omero-esiodo.md": "# Omero, Esiodo, e un proto-filosofo\n\nDisclaimer #1: this article is in Italian. I will publish the English version next Wednesday.\n\nDisclaimer #2: questo pezzo fa parte di una serie, pubblicata sia su questa newsletter, Heralding Time , che su Last Scattering Surface . Se vuoi, puoi seguirle entrambe. Il primo capitolo si legge qui. Il secondo qui. Il terzo qui.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/14890a96-a731-4109-a450-20425b11d52e_1080x1350.png)\n\nNei precedenti episodi abbiamo parlato della prima concezione del cielo nei popoli antichi, delle cosmologie di Egiziani, Babilonesi, Ebrei e Islamici, e di quelle sviluppatesi in Cina, India e in Scandinavia.\n\nA partire da questo episodio inizieremo un lungo viaggio nella filosofia greca, e del perché è legata al tema di questa serie. Vedremo che è proprio con la cosmologia che i primi pensatori greci hanno dato il via alla tradizione filosofica occidentale.\n\nPer iniziare questo viaggio, dobbiamo prima attraversare il confine che la separa dalla mitologia. Gettando una sguardo alla mappa, costruendo l’itinerario, vediamo che questo confine non è una linea retta, e neanche un confine netto: presenta rientranze e sporgenze, enclavi e territori inesplorati.\n\nLe sorgenti della mitologia greca nascono dai racconti orali dei cantori minoici e micenei tra il II e il I millennio BCE: storie di uomini e dei, eroi e muse, guerre e passioni, storie sull’origine dei luoghi e sull’origine dell’umanità; queste sorgenti fluiscono in tutta la Grecia, e nei vari insediamenti e nelle varie colonie che i Greci fondano in Asia Minore e in Italia, e sono raccolte, definite e riassunte in testi esposti al pubblico intorno all’VIII e al VII secolo BCE. Il primo incontro che facciamo seguendo questo fiume di miti e di parole è un uomo cieco, che è forse più di un uomo, e forse non è mai esistito.\n\nUn uomo cieco che forse non è mai esistito\n\nL’uomo che incontriamo è un bardo cieco vissuto nella Ionia del VIII secolo prima della nostra era, e morto probabilmente a Ios (Io), un’isola delle Cicladi nel Mar Egeo, intorno alla metà del secolo successivo. L’uomo che incontriamo è colui a cui attribuiamo i due poemi epici che hanno dato inizio alla tradizione epica greca, l’ Iliade e l’ Odissea . Ma interrogato su come, quando, e perché abbia scritto questi testi, l’uomo scompare.\n\nPer quanto ne sappiamo, Omero non è mai stato una figura storica. E’ opinione comune degli studiosi che i due poemi non siano dello stesso autore1, e che siano stati composti da una successione di autori e di cantori, che li esponevano in pubblico in tutta la Grecia.\n\nAd ogni modo, possiamo farci accompagnare dall’Omero della tradizione, e parlare degli sconosciuti autori dei due poemi come di parte della figura di Omero leggendario.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9c14d495-d993-4d1c-8a41-eafe7c48d208_1240x1126.png)\n\nL’Iliade e l’Odissea contengono l’insieme degli strumenti necessari per conoscere il mondo, le sue insidie e i suoi pericoli, le sue possibilità e le sue ricchezze. Tra le storie che contengono, ci sono anche i miti e le storie sulla creazione del mondo, sulla forma che esso ha e sulle forze che lo governano.\n\nOmero descrive il cielo come una emisfera , una ciotola rovesciata, che sovrasta la Terra, un disco piatto e circolare. Tra la Terra e il cielo, nella parte più vicina alla prima, c’è la nebbia , mentre nella parte superiore c’è aria più rarefatta, l’ etere .\n\nSotto le radici della Terra c’è il Tartaro, che è lontano dalla Terra tanto quanto la Terra è lontana dal cielo, e tutto intorno alla Terra c’è il fiume Okeanos , “che circonda la Terra e fluisce dentro sé stesso”2. Okeanos è allo stesso tempo, e a seconda della descrizione, un fiume, una sorgente, un oceano, composto di fresche acque dolci, la fonte di tutte le acque della Terra, un mare salato. Da quale esperienza può venire l’idea di un fiume multiforme intorno al mondo? Probabilmente non dalla Grecia, ma dalle tradizioni dei regni d’Egitto e della Mesopotamia, arrivate nel mondo greco tramite i contatti tra le diverse popolazioni nei secoli precedenti.\n\nAd ovest, oltre le Colonne d’Ercole , situate al confine tra quelli che oggi chiamiamo Mar Mediterraneo e Oceano Atlantico, sorge l’ Erebo , il luogo in cui le anime dei morti attendono di entrare nel Tartaro.\n\nI poemi epici non pongono la questione del moto della Terra, che è evidentemente ferma: ciò è una comune esperienza per ogni membro della Grecia antica. Il Sole, la Luna e le stelle sorgono a oriente, e si muovono nel cielo ogni giorno, ogni giorno cadendo a occidente. Poiché ogni giorno ritornano a oriente per sorgere ancora e ancora, devono in qualche modo tornarvi: ma il Tartaro è sempre buio , e mai illuminato da nessuna luce, dunque gli astri non possono attraversarlo.\n\nE’ compito allora del fiume Okeanos trasportare il Sole, la Luna e le stelle da ovest di nuovo a est, girando intorno alla Terra. Come nella tradizione egizia, anche qui i corpi celesti navigano sull’acqua, dopo la morte e prima di rinascere.\n\nE quali stelle conosce Omero, quali possono sfruttare gli uomini in mare per orientarsi? Omero conosce la stella del mattino, Phosphorus, e la stella della sera, Hesperus; conosce l’asterismo delle Pleiadi, quello delle Iadi e del Grande Carro, e poi la costellazione Orione, le stelle Sirio e Arturo.\n\nAnche la volta celeste è ferma, e il moto dei corpi celesti è un riflesso dell’ordine del mondo.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #1\n\n- un asterismo è un gruppo di stelle che forma una riconoscibile forma geometrica, e che può o meno far parte di una costellazione. Famosi asterismi sono il Triangolo dell'Estate , formato da Altair, Deneb e Vega, o il Grande Carro , parte della costellazione Orsa Maggiore.\n\n- le stelle (dette Sette Sorelle ) più luminose dell'asterismo delle Pleiadi sono presenti anche su una lastra in metallo dell'età del bronzo, il Disco di Nebra , rinvenuto in Germania nel 1999.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/39dbd62f-a4e6-4599-9420-1ec00cd5242d_1611x1584.jpeg)\n\nDisco di Nebra. La figura circolare a sinistra potrebbe essere il Sole, o la Luna piena. A destra, la Luna crescente. In alto tra le due, le sette stelle luminose delle Pleiadi. Crediti qui.\n\nOmero ci saluta, e ritorna nell’oscurità in cui è immerso il suo passaggio sulla Terra e nella Storia.\n\nUn cantore della nascita degli dei\n\nDopo aver preso commiato dalla figura di Omero, il percorso dal mito alla descrizione fisica del mondo continua con la consapevolezza che il mondo è pieno di dei: antropomorfi, certo, ma anche allegorie di concetti e emozioni umane. Per rispondere alla domanda “Come nascono gli dei?” ci avviciniamo a Esiodo, un cantore vissuto tra il VIII e il VII secolo BCE, e probabilmente originario di Cyme (Cuma Eolica), una città nella regione dell’Eolia, in Asia Minore. Quest’uomo, vissuto in Beozia, - una regione della Grecia continentale - ha scritto tre opere che possiamo leggere interamente: “ Teogonia” , “ Le Opere e i Giorni” e “ Lo scudo di Eracle ”. Gli viene attribuito anche un poema dal titolo “Sull’Astronomia”3, di cui leggiamo solo dei frammenti, che comunque non ci informano su quello che desideriamo conoscere.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6f36bea8-dc21-4a50-a50d-3c68c8ea6496_1240x1126.png)\n\nCi attanaglia infatti il problema della nascita delle forze che governano il mondo, e degli dei che esercitano quelle forze. Ci libera il canto di Esiodo, che nella Teogonia, la Nascita degli Dei, racconta l’inizio del mondo e quello che ne segue.\n\nLa prima cosa che è successa al mondo, il primo evento , è la separazione della Terra e del Cielo, in due entità distinte, dacché erano unite. Dunque il primo evento non è la creazione di qualcosa di inesistente , ma la separazione di qualcosa di già preesistente .\n\n[...] Prima di tutto certo fu Caos , poi\n\nTerra dall’ampio seno, sempre sede sicura di tutti\n\ngli immortali, che abitano la vetta dell’Olimpo nevoso\n\ne il Tartaro caliginoso nel fondo della Terra dalle ampie vie,\n\ne Eros , il più bello fra gli dèi immortali,\n\nche scioglie le membra, e che di tutti gli dèi e degli uomini tutti\n\ndoma nel petto la mente e la saggia volontà.\n\nDa Caos nacquero Erebo e la Notte nera,\n\ne da Notte , poi, Etere e Giorno nacquero,\n\nche concepì e generò unitasi a Erebo in amore.\n\nTerra per primo generò, uguale a sé,\n\nCielo stellato, affinché tutt’intorno la coprisse,\n\n[...]\n\ncongiuntasi a Cielo , partorì Oceano dai vortici profondi [...]\n\nEsiodo, Teogonia , 116-127, 129. Traduzione di Gabriella Ricciardelli per l’edizione Fondazione Lorenzo Valla/Mondadori\n\nIl mondo è preesistente alla nascita degli dei, che nascono come raffigurazione dei Luoghi e degli Stati del mondo: Cielo, Terra, Notte, Erebo (l’Oltretomba), Etere, Giorno, Oceano; ma anche Emozioni e Sensazioni come Vergogna, Angoscia, Litigio, Carestia, Lavoro, Menzogne. Solo successivamente arriveranno gli dei dell’Olimpo a spodestare Kronos, che a sua volta ha spodestato Ouranos, con l’aiuto di Gaia, consorte di Ouranos, e Rhea, consorte di Kronos.\n\nIn principio, però, c’è il Chaos : nella tradizione greca questo termine sta a significare ciò che significa anche per noi, un sinonimo di disordine e confusione.\n\nQui, Esiodo dà il nome di Chaos a ciò che separa il Cielo dalla Terra, la prima separazione. Il primo atto del mondo, quindi, è la nascita del Chaos inteso come azione della separazione, della distinzione .\n\nNota luminosa a margine #2\n\nLa concezione della distinzione del Cielo e della Terra è presente in molte culture:\n\n- per il popolo Maori, si separano Rangi (il cielo) e Papa (la terra);\n\n- abbiamo visto nel mito egizio che Nut e Geb vengono separati da Shu ;\n\n- avviene lo stesso nella Canzone di Ullikummi , un mito della mitologia Ittita-Urrita che sembra avere molti paralleli (successivi) in Grecia;\n\n- nel mito babilonese dell’ Enuma Elish , l’eroe-dio Marduk dilania Ti’amat in due pezzi: il cielo e la terra;\n\n- la Genesi: “Sia il firmamento in mezzo alle acque per separare le acque dalle acque”. Anche a causa delle forti influenze babilonesi sul mito biblico della creazione del mondo, a un certo punto il dio creatore della Bibbia crea il firmamento per separare la terra e il cielo.\n\nEsiodo non parla di ciò che c’era prima di questa separazione, né del perché essa sia avvenuta. La Teogonia parla degli dei, ed essi sono l’origine dell’ordine nel mondo, il κόσμος (cosmo). Ogni divinità ha il suo “dipartimento” da controllare e su cui regnare; questo controllo non è sempre esclusivo: in alcuni casi un evento, una forza, un luogo sono contesi da più divinità, e questo crea un mondo non totalmente ordinato .\n\nLa Teogonia non contiene idee originali o nuove: è una raccolta di storie e miti già presenti, che si impegna a codificare. Ma come succederà anche per i primi pensatori che chiamiamo filosofi, anche Esiodo crede fermamente in un mondo ordinato, in una presenza divina nel mondo, che permea gli aspetti sia fisici che morali dell’umanità.\n\nIl mondo di Esiodo è un disco piatto e circolare, come per Omero, e su di esso c’è il Cielo, popolato dal Sole, dalla Luna e dalle stelle; sotto di esso c’è il Tartaro, mai illuminato da nessuna luce. Lo spazio tra cielo e terra è luminoso di giorno, e buio di notte. Come in Omero, e come nei miti degli altri popoli del Mediterraneo, i corpi celesti si muovono nel cielo; dopo essere tramontati oltre l’orizzonte, navigano Oceano per ritornare ogni giorno nel luogo in cui sorgeranno di nuovo, ancora e ancora.\n\nOra Esiodo si allontana, e gli dei che ha cantato restano, trasformandosi.\n\nUn proto-filosofo sincretico e misterioso\n\nSiamo quasi arrivati alla fine della prima tappa, che dai territori della mitologia arriva alla soglia della filosofia naturale. Il prossimo personaggio che incontriamo è un proto-filosofo, un uomo che ha trasportato idee e suggestioni dall’Asia alla Grecia, e che dalla Grecia farà ritornare in Asia idee e suggestioni. Con lui attraverseremo i secoli a cavallo tra le ere, e i confini tra regni e popoli.\n\nApollodoro di Atene sostiene che Ferecide di Siro sia un contemporaneo di Anassimandro di Mileto, e pone il suo floruit - il periodo di maggior rilievo per i contemporanei - intorno al 540 BCE; ma ciò non è confermato. Sappiamo che è vissuto nel VI secolo BCE, e che una leggenda del IV secolo BCE lo rappresenta come il maestro di Pitagora, che negli ultimi anni sarebbe rimasto da lui e lo avrebbe sepolto4. Non ne siamo sicuri, ma è vero che tra i pitagorici i suoi testi circolavano, e ci sono delle similitudini tra gli insegnamenti di Pitagora e di Ferecide.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1e891fe5-1cd3-484d-a112-8ee6065d96ef_1240x1076.png)\n\nA differenza degli altri filosofi, e a rafforzare la sua figura leggendaria, si dice che non abbia ricevuto nessun insegnamento da un maestro, ma che abbia consultato il libro segreto dei Fenici , e la profezia di Ham (ovvero di Zoroastro). Ad ogni modo, i contatti con la Fenicia sono evidenti dal nome del padre, Babis o Babys , chiaro nome di origine asiatica (probabilmente proveniente dalla Frigia, dalla Pisidia o dalla Galazia - tutte regioni dell’Asia minore).\n\nNella sua opera Le sette caverne , Ferecide parla di tre divinità che sono sempre esistite: Zeus, che lui chiama Zas, e che assocerebbe - ma non è chiaro - al Sole; Kronos, che anche se ha lo stesso nome del dio del Tempo abita e governa le Isole dei Beati; e Chtonie, la dea che rappresenta la Terra.\n\nDopo l’unione tra Zas e Chtonie, la Terra diventa Ge, e le viene fatto dono da Zas, adesso diventato anche Eros, di un mantello che lei indossa formando la terra, ma che secondo un successivo passaggio finisce per appendere ad un ” Albero del mondo ”.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #3\n\nQuesta è una storia che serve due scopi: rappresenta la nascita del mondo, e descrive un’attività umana, la anakalyptenia , ovvero il dono rituale del marito alla sposa che avviene al terzo giorno di nozze. Ancora una volta, i miti rappresentano contemporaneamente ciò che accade sulla terra e ciò che qui vi è di nascosto, e questo e da questo influenzano e si fanno influenzare.\n\nZas e Ge generano gli altri dei insieme; Chronos lo fa “in unione con sé stesso”: la nascita del mondo o di una parte di esso come risultato di una azione di questo tipo è comune nei miti e nelle cosmologie asiatiche, ed è un altro tassello che compone in quadro di Ferecide sincretico tra la Grecia e l’Asia. Ne parleremo più avanti.\n\nChronos crea il fuoco, il vento e l’acqua dal suo seme, e li distribuisce nel mondo, nei cinque angoli del titolo (“Le Sette Caverne” è in greco Ἑπτάμυχος, e μυχος ha tra gli altri significati possibili anche angolo ). Non sappiamo a quali luoghi Ferecide si riferisca, ma probabilmente sono i luoghi da cui scaturiscono gli dei, le cinque province seguenti: il cielo, la Terra, Ogenos, Ade e il Tartaro. I primi due sono evidenti, mentre degli altri dovremo parlare: Ogenos è un’altra scrittura di un termine che abbiamo già incontrato, Okeanos; Ade e Tartaro invece sono la dimora dei morti e il luogo in cui non c’è luce, rispettivamente. Gli dei malvagi sconfitti da Chronos, guidati da Ophioneus, un dio la cui origine è accostabile ai serpenti primordiali delle mitologie babilonesi, e che si ritrova anche nella Genesi biblica, vengono ributtati nel mare formato da Ogenos al confine del mondo.\n\nNella cosmologia di Ferecide, infine, gli dei vivono sulla Luna, la Terra è abitata e tutto intorno ha Ogenos, e sotto di essa c’è il mondo dei morti, che a sua volta sovrasta il Tartaro.\n\nNota luminosa a margine #4\n\nAbbiamo parlato di Ferecide sincretico. Ecco perché:\n\n- Eudemo di Argo collega Ferecide alla cosmologia di Sidone, stanziamento fenicio. Qui in origine ci sono Chronos (il tempo), Pothos (il vento), e Omichle (le tenebre). In diverse cosmologie di cultura fenicia, il vento primordiale è rappresentato da Aither e Aer, che generano Ulōmos, che viene dal tardo fenicio 'ūlōm, 'ōlām per gli Ebrei, che significa Tempo Remoto o Eternità. Da questi nasce un uovo, da cui si generano il cielo e la terra.\n\n- nella cosmologia zoroastriana, in principio non c'è nulla se non Zurran, il Tempo. Anch'esso genera da solo , Ohrmazd, il Bene, e Ahriman, il Male. Il primo crea il mondo materiale, formando il firmamento a forma di uovo, in cui tutto è contenuto.\n\n- Negli inni sacri indiani Atharraveda, Kala (il Tempo) genera autonomamente il cielo e la terra.\n\nFerecide è un proto-filosofo, nel senso che nella sua opera c’è un principio che mancava nei poeti precedenti, e che incontreremo in coloro che chiamiamo filosofi: la predilezione della prosa sul verso, la volontà di parlare degli dei, anche accettandone l’esistenza, solo come allegoria delle forze che regolano il mondo; la descrizione del mondo come ordinato già dal principio , senza un ordine che arriva dopo l’azione di uno o più dei.\n\nD’ora in poi, anche gli dei dovranno rispondere alla domanda che i filosofi si pongono: perché? Ferecide lo domanda anche a noi, e scompare nel Tempo che è già Passato.\n\nSuperare il confine\n\nAbbiamo attraversato le pianure del mito, e i sentieri degli dei. Abbiamo scoperto connessioni, legami, sincretismi, ma anche individualità, singole e di gruppo. Sembrerà nel futuro di esservi tornati, in queste lande; sembrerà di riconoscere il profumo dei fiori, e il sapore dei frutti: ma torneremo, se lo faremo, con una nuova consapevolezza.\n\nChe i miti sono, sono sempre stati, e forse ancora saranno, ad aspettare nuove ipotesi e teorie.\n\nI prossimi passi ci porteranno verso una catena di montagne, in cui ognuna rappresenta il pensiero di un filosofo: queste montagne hanno gallerie e valichi che collegano l’una all’altra, ghiacciai unici resi eterni dal tempo su vette irraggiungibili, ruscelli che da una montagna scorrono e dall’altra ricevono nuova acqua per trasformarsi in fiumi di pensiero, laghi che raccolgono quei fiumi, e l’Oceano della Terra tutto intorno, a ricordarci che dopotutto, questa Terra di cui vogliamo capire il movimento, è Sola e Una, e tutto intorno c’è il Resto, e il Buio.\n\nNel prossimo episodio: i filosofi di Mileto.\n\nArticoli della serie:\n\nBibliografia:\n\nAristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus, di Heath T. (Oxford 1913)\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, di Kirk G.S. e Raven J.E. (Cambridge 1957)\n\nEarly Greek Philosophy and the Orient, di West M.L. (Oxford 1971)\n\nPhilosophy before Socrates, di McKirahan R.D. (Hackett 1994)\n\nQuesta newsletter è una di tre: le altre due sono Last Scattering Surface, e Space of Sound. Tutte le pubblicazioni sono gratuite e puoi consultare tutti gli articoli senza paywall. Se vuoi, puoi iscriverti qui e qui.\n\nInfine, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n\nCiao e a presto!\n\nPer la revisione del testo si ringrazia EB.\n\nNote\n\n1 “The Invention of Homer”, West, M.L. (1999); Classical Quarterly 49 (2)\n\n2 “Aristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus”, Heath T. (1913)\n\n3 ibid.\n\n4 “Early Greek Philosophy and the Orient”, West M.L. (1971)\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_sul-moto-della-terra-talete-e-lacqua.md": "# Talete e l'acqua\n\nDisclaimer #1: this article is in Italian. I will publish the English version next Wednesday.\n\nDisclaimer #2: questo pezzo fa parte di una serie, pubblicata sia su questa newsletter, Heralding Time , che su Last Scattering Surface . Se vuoi, puoi seguirle entrambe. Qui i capitoli I, II, III, IV.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f03118ee-9d19-45b4-a07a-861ad782a875_1080x1350.png)\n\nBentornati.\n\nNei precedenti episodi sono comparsi antichi cieli pieni di dei, fiumi e montagne in Egitto e Babilonia, ciotole rovesciate e testi sacri in Cina, India e in Scandinavia.\n\nTornati in Asia Minore, abbiamo percorso il confine tra mitologia e cosmologia in Grecia. Abbandonati un poeta cieco, un narratore della nascita degli dei, e un sincretico proto-filosofo, è il momento di parlare dei primi filosofi comparsi in Grecia, e dei mondi che hanno descritto e del posto della Terra in essi.\n\nTroppe domande?\n\nPrima di partire, cerchiamo di chiarire il motivo del titolo di questa serie: perché, per capire quali sono state le risposte a una domanda apparentemente tecnica come “qual è il moto della Terra?”, abbiamo parlato di un reperto dell’età del bronzo, di divinità e testi sacri, per arrivare in Grecia a parlare di filosofia?\n\nPerché i filosofi greci sono i primi a cercare di rispondere a questa domanda in modo simile a come facciamo noi, ponendo domande valide in ogni tempo, e rispondono interpellando la Natura, non più gli dei. Le due interpretazioni del mondo possono sì coesistere - non tutti i filosofi rifiutano il concetto dell’esistenza degli dei, ovviamente - ma la filosofia in Grecia procede nella direzione di “riempire i buchi” degli eventi naturali inspiegabili con spiegazioni logiche, razionali, anche se non necessariamente “scientifiche”: il concetto di esperimento scientifico come lo intendiamo oggi non nasce nel mondo greco classico, ma in alcuni casi si può intravedere un atteggiamento che potremmo definire “replicabile” o “quantificabile”.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b2809861-0dd4-4bd5-bf9a-80cbab7a22a9_800x780.jpeg)\n\nLight Flowing Forth from the Blackness. Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / Internet Archive / The Getty.\n\nLe domande che i filosofi greci si pongono, da Mileto ad Atene, da Crotone a Samo, riguardano il mondo, concepito ora come unità, autonoma a sé stessa ; la costituzione materiale del mondo stesso, unità continua o formata da elementi discreti ; la sua nascita o creazione come prodotto di un accidente , di un disegno o di una necessità ; l’eventualità che il suo Creatore sia una figura trascendente o immanente ; la sua durata, se finita o senza fine ; il numero dei mondi, uno o innumerevoli , e in questo caso se contemporanei o successivi l’uno all’altro.\n\nQueste e altre domande rimbalzano da isola a isola, di città in città, trasportate dalla vita di questi pensatori, e dal concetto comune a tutti loro, che le idee si discutono e non costituiscono dogma .\n\nArthur Koestler, che abbiamo già incontrato nei precedenti episodi, parla del VI secolo BCE come di un periodo in cui l’umanità si è destata e ha iniziato a cercare le risposte alle domande che ancora oggi ci poniamo: parla di figure come Buddha, Confucio, Lao-Tze, e poi di filosofi Ionici e di Pitagorici.\n\nI primi tre sono figure mistiche, religiose, di autorità e non uomini di scienza, per quanto saggi e fondamentali nella morale e nella filosofia.\n\nNoi parleremo ora dei filosofi di Mileto - gli Ioniani di cui parla Koestler, i filosofi della Natura, partendo da Talete.\n\nMa prima, parliamo di Mileto.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2bf887d5-e02f-47ac-96e7-b720c71091e7_1240x1126.png)\n\nMileto\n\nLa polis di Mileto esiste, ai tempi dei filosofi di cui parleremo in questo episodio, da più di 300 anni. Come altre città delle isole del Mar Egeo, venne fondata dopo il collasso della civiltà Micenea dell’età del bronzo.\n\nA partire dall’VIII secolo BCE queste città creano colonie nell’Italia del Sud, a ovest, e sulle coste del Mar Nero, a nord. Soprattutto in questo modo, e con gli insediamenti in Asia Minore, i cittadini delle polis entrano in contatto con altre popolazioni, provenienti dalla Mesopotamia, o dall’Egitto, o proprio dall’Asia Minore.\n\nMileto è governata da aristocratici uomini non appartenenti a nessun culto religioso; la religione è tenuta separata dalla vita politica, nonostante entrambe siano attività pubbliche. Inoltre, benché i poemi di Omero e di Esiodo siano una eredità comune a tutte le città greche, l’assenza di una casta unica e ereditaria di classe sacerdotale (come accade in Egitto da millenni) non facilita la creazione di un dogma comune a tutta la Grecia, da seguire e da cui non allontanarsi. Ogni città gode di una sua seppur non totale autonomia. Per dirla con McKirahan1, non c’è una Bibbia nel mondo greco.\n\nE’ in questa polis, in questo ambiente culturale, mercantile, politico, religioso, che i tre filosofi di questo episodio vivono, in cui espongono le proprie visioni del mondo, della sua nascita e della sua natura.\n\nTalete\n\nRicordate Ferecide, il proto-filosofo dell’episodio precedente? Di lui si diceva che avesse conoscenze segrete apprese dai Fenici.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/17c883eb-7b2d-4eb6-8bcb-3da0c9adb759_2700x3768.jpeg)\n\nThalész di Büky Béla - 1963 - Rippl-Rónai Municipal Museum con County Scope - Kaposvár, Hungary - CC BY.\n\nAnche per Talete si racconta2 di una sua possibile discendenza da questo popolo: forse non da parte della madre Cleobulina - che sembra essere un nome greco, ma il padre, Essamio, si racconta essere di una famiglia fenicia. Più probabile che la sua famiglia fosse originaria di Cadmea, una città della Beozia (Grecia continentale) trasferitisi in Beozia (una regione dell’Asia Minore). Ad ogni modo, che fosse effettivamente di stirpe fenicia, o che questa appartenenza gli sia stata imposta successivamente, il legame della scienza e della tecnica greca con i Fenici non termina con il periodo mitico.\n\nTalete nasce intorno al 624 BCE, nella sua città è un uomo di governo e un “ingegnere”: si raccontano diverse storie su di lui, per rappresentarlo in modi spesso opposti; tutti ci dicono qualcosa su di lui come filosofo.\n\nIn un dialogo di Platone3 si riporta che una schiava proveniente dalla Tracia racconta di quando Talete è finito in un pozzo, poiché più impegnato ad osservare il cielo che a rendersi conto di quello che succedeva sotto i suoi piedi. Un altro racconto parla di quando è riuscito a prevedere che avrebbe avuto profitto dalla resa dell’olio e acquistò molti oliveti del tempo a prezzi bassi, traendone grande profitto.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9260683f-0e09-4c7c-b116-7039e2decf18_591x800.jpeg)\n\nLe Meteore di Novembre, opera di Étienne Léopold Trouvelot, 1882 . Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / New York Public Library.\n\nEntrambe queste storie parlano di conseguenze pratiche della vita “filosofica” di Talete: anche se probabilmente leggendarie, la prima racconta del “filosofo sulle nuvole”, lontano dalla vita comune; la seconda di un uomo che con i suoi studi e i suoi calcoli avrebbe potuto trarre enormi ricchezze. Su questo punto, Aristotele spiega che Talete non ne era attratto, nonostante fosse più che benestante - dopotutto, era un membro dell’aristocrazia cittadina - poiché non è nel suo interesse arricchirsi grazie al suo ingegno.\n\nRiguardo la sua attività filosofica, si racconta dei suoi viaggi in Egitto. Questo non è difficile a credersi, poiché in questo periodo Mileto ha alcune colonie in quelle zone, tra cui Naucrati4. Secondo Diogene Laerzio, che cita Eudemo, Talete ha scritto “ Sul solstizio ” e “ Sull’equinozio ” - testi che non abbiamo. Come avverrà anche per altri tra i filosofi di cui parleremo, le loro teorie sono conosciute esclusivamente attraverso resoconti di seconda o terza mano, con tutte le imprecisioni e le modifiche al pensiero originale che ciò comporta.\n\nErodoto riporta che Talete è famoso per essere stato il primo in Grecia a predire una eclisse solare, tra il 585 e il 584 BCE, periodo in cui è posto il suo acme , ovvero il punto più alto della sua attività filosofica. Ciò è discutibile, e lo è ancora di più se si immagina che abbia predetto il giorno esatto5.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/46ad5b86-68e6-431a-bf9c-bba26310ba92_1005x1200.jpeg)\n\nDiagramma di un eclisse, da Illustrated Astronomy di Asa Smith, 1849. Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / Smithsonian Libraries and Archives.\n\nTalete è colui che porta la geometria astratta in Grecia , afferma A. Koestler6. Da dove? Dall’Egitto e dalla Mesopotamia. Proprio in Mesopotamia è almeno dal 721 BCE che si registrano i solstizi e le lunazioni7, da cui si può calcolare quando avverrà all’incirca una eclisse8; non è strano per un sapiente di quell’epoca in Grecia visitare la città di Sardi, in Asia Minore, che gli Ittiti chiamavano Uda, dunque i contatti con la civiltà babilonese sono realizzabili. Questo è registrato in modo simile anche da Teone di Smirne, che riporta la conoscenza da parte di Talete della durata diversa che le diverse stagioni hanno nel corso dell’anno.\n\nPer Talete, le eclissi solari avvengono quando il Sole è coperto dalla Luna; in modo analogo, quando la Terra è tra la Luna e il Sole, avvengono le eclissi lunari.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/931d02be-b0cd-42d1-81ac-28a5d4406fdb_586x799.jpeg)\n\nEclisse parziale di Luna, opera di Étienne Léopold Trouvelot, 1882 . Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / New York Public Library.\n\nTalete conosce quando avverranno i solstizi: ciò sembra fattibile, con uno strumento adatto, lo gnomone, di derivazione babilonese e che Eudemo racconta abbia permesso al filosofo di misurare l’altezza delle piramidi, utilizzando il principio delle proporzioni tra la lunghezza dell’ombra di un oggetto e di quella della piramide alla stessa ora del giorno, con le misure reali di quell’oggetto e della piramide.\n\nSecondo Callimaco9, Talete osserva l’Orsa Minore partendo dall’Orsa Maggiore, come fanno i Fenici, e consiglia ai naviganti greci di utilizzare questo metodo per orientarsi e trovare il nord10.\n\nLo studio delle tavole babilonesi per predire le prossime eclissi; la misurazione dei giorni che passano tra un solstizio e l’equinozio successivo; lo studio delle posizioni delle stelle negli asterismi e nelle costellazioni: tutte queste cose compongono lo studio della ἀστρονομία, l’astronomia.\n\nTalete va oltre, e costruisce un modello cosmologico. Ne conosciamo i (pochi) dettagli dalle opere in cui è descritto (e criticato) da Aristotele: il “ De cælo ” e la “ Metafisica ”. Aristotele attribuisce a Talete la frase “ tutte le cose sono piene di dei ”, McKirahan parla di un Talete dal volto gianico , duale. Il Talete di cui parla Aristotele descrive un mondo in cui le cose che accadono sono opera della Natura: la Terra galleggia sull’acqua, e il principio di tutte le cose è l’acqua.\n\nLa prima concezione è di derivazione egiziana e babilonese, probabilmente. La seconda è una interpretazione di Aristotele, che collega il concetto di ἀρχή, il principio primo, all’acqua per Talete come risposta alla domanda: qual è il principio di ogni cosa? Le domande sembrano essere due in realtà, ovvero: cosa genera tutte le cose ? e da dove arrivano tutte le cose?\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6858b4e6-14d9-4057-b1ab-551fd4bf97da_2448x1992.jpeg)\n\nAcqua, opera di Maerten de Vos, Adriaen Collaert, 1580-1584 . Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / Rijksmuseum.\n\nLa risposta quindi per Talete è l’acqua, intesa non solo come il liquido che beviamo o che scorre in un fiume o che forma il mare, ma come un fluido che genera vita: è collegato alla pioggia, allo sperma, ai fluidi corporei e a tutto quello che fluisce. Qui Talete evoca la tradizione babilonese dell’acqua come potenza generatrice, e quella egiziana dell’acqua creatrice. Ma in Talete non c’è nulla di magico o religioso: l’acqua è parte della Natura da cui arriva tutto. E’ l’origine di tutto, ma ha una origine che fa parte di questo mondo e che possiamo osservare.\n\nCome si forma il mondo a partire dall’acqua? Talete non lo dice, e non conosciamo la sua cosmogonia, ma sappiamo che il Sole e la Luna sono fatti della stessa sostanza che compone la Terra, staccatesi da essa dopo la creazione. La Terra è un disco cilindrico, forse un po’ concavo - questa visione sarebbe coerente con la visione babilonese del mondo secondo cui la Terra è circondata da montagne, prima di essere circondata da Okeanos - il quale poggia sull’acqua.\n\nE’ ferma nell’Universo, e il Sole, la Luna e le stelle compiono i loro moti intorno a essa, e quando non sono più visibili oltre l’orizzonte girano intorno alla Terra per tornare a sorgere a oriente. La luce della Luna è il riflesso della luce che arriva dal Sole, e l’aria si forma dall’evaporazione dell’acqua.\n\nTalete condivide la visione non solo di Babilonia e dell’Egitto, ma anche quella di Omero e Esiodo, che raccontano di una Terra piatta che riposa sull’acqua.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f10eeaf8-b914-441b-be07-5ab10d572f53_1200x938.jpeg)\n\nUniverso con la Terra, il Sole, la Luna, e le stelle, opera di Caspar Luyken, 1712. Immagine ottenuta da Public Domain Image Archive / Rijksmuseum.\n\nA differenza loro, ed è il motivo per cui lo definiamo filosofo , si domanda cosa ci sia oltre , cerca spiegazioni nella Natura e non nei miti, prova a immaginare delle cause . Lo fa ad esempio con i terremoti, la cui causa attribuisce al movimento dell’acqua che sostiene la Terra.\n\nQuesta è una sorprendente novità: Talete tenta di spiegare un evento osservabile facendo ricorso a una ipotesi non osservabile , ma coerente con la sua visione del mondo. Cosa manca per soddisfare i requisiti del metodo scientifico? L’esperimento da compiere per verificare l’ipotesi - che comunque avrebbe confutato l’ipotesi11.\n\nTalete cerca il materiale grezzo che compone il mondo. Che abbia sbagliato a individuarlo non è importante, per il percorso che abbiamo intrapreso.\n\nNel prossimo episodio: gli altri filosofi di Mileto.\n\nArticoli della serie:\n\nBibliografia:\n\nSleepwalkers: A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe, di Arthur Koestler (Hutchinson 1959)\n\nAncient cosmologies, raccolta di saggi ad opera di C. Blacker e M. Loewe (Allen and Unwin 1975)\n\nGreek Cosmologies, di G.E.R. Lloyd\n\nAristarchus of Samos, the ancient Copernicus, di Heath T. (Oxford 1913)\n\nThe Presocratic Philosophers, di Kirk G.S. e Raven J.E. (Cambridge 1957)\n\nEarly Greek Philosophy and the Orient, di West M.L. (Oxford 1971)\n\nPhilosophy before Socrates, di McKirahan R.D. (Hackett 1994)\n\nEarly Greek Science, di G.E.R. Lloyd (Chatto & Windus 1970)\n\nA history of astronomy from Thales to Kepler, di J.L.E Dreyer (Dover 1953)\n\nQuesta newsletter è una di tre: le altre due sono Last Scattering Surface, e Space of Sound. Tutte le pubblicazioni sono gratuite e puoi consultare tutti gli articoli senza paywall. Se vuoi, puoi iscriverti qui e qui.\n\nInfine, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n\nCiao e a presto!\n\nNote\n\n1 McKirahan R.D., Philosophy before Socrates, pg. 21\n\n2 Erodoto, storie, I.\n\n3 Platone, Teeteto, 174.\n\n4 Aezio, Proclo, Plutarco. Plutarco inoltre sottolinea che l’acqua ha un ruolo importante nella mitologia egizia.\n\n5 Teone di Smirne, Diogene Laerzio (citando Eudemo) e Clemente di Alessandria, citano questo episodio. Martin, in Revue Archéologique, sottolinea che sembra quindi che Talete l’abbia scoperta, più che predetta, l’eclissi solare.\n\n6 A. Koestler, Sleepwalkers: : A History of Man’s Changing Vision of the Universe\n\n7 mese “sinodico”, è il periodo di tempo che la Luna impiega per compiere un ciclo complete delle sue fasi. Dura all’incirca 29 giorni, 12 ore e 44 minuti.\n\n8 Diogene Laerzio, citando Eudemo.\n\n9 Diogene Laerzio, citando Callimaco.\n\n10 Eudemo cita un altro libro, una “Guida stellare ai naviganti”.\n\n11 O forse non del tutto? Oggi sappiamo che i terremoti sono causati in larga parte dai movimenti delle placche tettoniche, ma ci sono terremoti causati dal moto del magma che scorre - come l’acqua, quindi!\n",
  "../posts/heralding_time/ht_post_welcome-to-heralding-time.md": "Heralding Time parlerà di storia, filosofia, scienza. Esiste per collegare tutte le cose che sappiamo come umanità. Ci prova, almeno.\n\nHeralding Time publishes on history, philosophy, science. It lives to connect all the things mankind knows. At least, it tries to do so.\n",
  "../posts/lss/lss_post_001-a-story-of-a-star-part-v.md": "# A story of a star - Part V\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Ff5T!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1672a724-7b16-4aac-9d7d-974ec2881263_1572x1048.png)\n\nWe know from the previous episodes that stars need some form of energy to counter the gravitational force that would tend to make the structure collapse.\n\nIn the case of protostars, the responsibility for such a scenario lies on “controlled collapse”; in the case of stars, the main source of energy is thermonuclear reactions, which have timescales of the order of tens of billions of years.\n\nThen, you can easily understand why the main sequence is the configuration in which stars live most of their lives.\n\nThus the main sequence will also be the main subject of this episode.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!vcTI!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/e9add7a6-7ae1-4dc5-8aec-a42c8ac0821d_2039x2039.jpeg)\n\nM2 globular cluster. Credits: NASA\n\nReady, set, go\n\nYou already know that the zero-age main sequence is a diagonal line in the H-R diagram: from this line depart the tracks for stars of different masses. In particular, stars above 1.2 solar masses have convective cores and are dominated by CNO reactions (we talked about those here), whereas stars below this mass are dominated by pp chains1, and have radiative cores2.\n\nWhat happens to a low-mass star?\n\nWell, it will burn hydrogen: by doing so, it will have more and more helium, which will make the mean molecular weight heavier. This leads to a compression of the core because the temperature or the density (or both) of the core does not increase as much as to counter the weight of the outer layers of the star.\n\nOf course, with the core compressed, density does increase, and this results in a gravitational potential release3 that increases the temperature of the gas: now more gas undergoes thermonuclear reactions.\n\nWith the increase in temperature, it also increases the rate at which the pp chain occurs: this results in the temperature increasing, along with the radius.\n\nOk, stars burn hydrogen in their main sequence lifetime.\n\nWhat happens when hydrogen ends? Well, for low-mass stars, the pp chain stops in the core, but the high temperature all around the core enables the envelope of the core to burn hydrogen: there is an onion-like configuration, with a core now completely made of helium, and an outer shell made of hydrogen, that as soon as becomes helium increases the core.\n\nThe reactions in the shell produce more energy than those in the core: this leads to an increase in luminosity. This does not lead to an increase in temperature: what happens is that the temperature decreases slightly, because the energy produced makes the envelope expand, thus cooling the effective temperature.\n\nThis new phase ends when the helium core gets too massive compared to the total mass of the star. This limit is known as Schonberg-Chandrasekhar limit, and it is related to the fact that hydrostatic equilibrium depends on the molecular weight of the core and the envelope. To show the results would require a long (very long) amount of calculations, so if interested you can look it up (here, for example).\n\nWhat is the order of magnitude of such a limit? In the case of a star with a chemical composition similar to that of the Sun, the limit would be reached when the isothermal core exceeds 8% of the star’s total mass.\n\nWhat we said until now assumes that the gas in the core of the stars can be regarded as ideal; but when the density becomes sufficiently high, the gas becomes degenerate , meaning that the pressure is not controlled anymore by the temperature of the gas, instead the dominant factor becomes the quantum nature of electrons, that now occupy all the space available according to quantum mechanics.\n\nThis complication in our story has the visible effect that the Schonberg-Chandrasekhar limit gets shifted up at 13% (in the case of a star of the Sun’s mass).\n\nWhat happens to a high-mass star?\n\nThe process is somewhat similar to the low-mass stars, but the presence of a convective core mixes things (the elements in the outer envelope and those in the inner core), making the chemical composition of the star homogeneous. The convection zone disappears eventually before the total depletion of hydrogen, and the stars encounter contraction like the other low-mass stars.\n\nWhat awaits in the future?\n\nIn the next episode, we will continue to follow the life of stars in the main sequence and also encounter a new group of stars: globular clusters.\n\n1 remember, CNO reactions are driven mostly by high temperatures, whereas pp chains are related to (relatively) lower temperatures.\n\n2 below 0.3 solar masses actually, the star is entirely convective.\n\n3 thanks to the virial theorem (we talked about it here).\n",
  "../posts/lss/lss_post_002-a-story-of-a-star-part-iv.md": "# A story of a star - Part IV\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!dbKb!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9666f14d-b278-4668-8c1a-2588bd0b3cbf_1572x1048.png)\n\nLast time we talked about the depletion of deuterium, and now the status of the protostar is at stake. This happens because this object is not controlled anymore in its evolution by the free-fall timescale; instead, the timescale is now governed by the balance between gravity (which is always present) and the thermal properties of the star’s core. This new timescale goes by the name of Kelvin-Helmoltz timescale.\n\nThis timescale is way longer than the free-fall one: for instance, a molecular cloud of one solar mass takes 150 thousand years to arrive at the state of protostar that burns deuterium but takes 40 million years to contract into a proper star.\n\nThe road that protostars have to follow to reach the main-sequence is known as the Hayashi track , after C. Hayashi who demonstrated in 1961 that there is a boundary (a vertical line in the H-R diagram) that separates a stellar model that is indeed observed and those who are not observed (due to hydrostatic “impossibilities”).\n\nThis impossibility is because, at the right of the Hayashi track, no mechanism can transport the luminosity in the outer parts of the stellar envelope; on the other part of the track, convection, and radiation can indeed transport said luminosity.\n\nThe contraction time for protostars is heavily influenced by their initial masses. For a protostar of 0.8 solar masses, the time on the Hayashi track is something around 70 million years, whereas a protostar of 60 solar masses stays on the track for as short as 30 thousand years. The figure below shows the evolutionary tracks for a series of (simulated) stars: on the right is visible the vertical Hayashi track, which ends where luminosity reaches its minimum value. At this point radiative core of the star allows energy to travel into the (convective) envelope, and luminosity again increases. But the star is also shrinking, and then the temperature rises as well. At a certain point, the high temperature leads to the deuterium burning phase (the squares on the line). The long-dashed line represents the point where convection stops and the envelope of the star becomes radiative; whereas the short-dashed line represents the start of convection in the core.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!ma4p!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6101756a-cd38-4e2e-a8dc-2338d0e6e25b_1248x1670.png)\n\nCredits: Carroll and Ostlie, An Introduction to Modern Astrophysics\n\nAfter passing the deuterium-burning phase, the star has two main roads to produce energy via nuclear fusion: the PP chain and the CNO reactions: the former is the conversion of hydrogen into helium, whereas the latter converts carbon into nitrogen. Both reactions can happen in stars at the same time, but only one will dominate the other, ultimately setting the fate of the star.\n\nIn the phase on the plot where luminosity and temperature are rising, the core is at a temperature at which the CNO reactions are heavily favored, and thus these reactions dominate: the energy originated in such a way leads the core to expand. This leads to a decrease in total luminosity and also in the temperature (in the graph, this is noticeable near the short-dashed lines).\n\nWhen carbon is exhausted in the core, the dominating reaction becomes the PP chain, which stabilizes the system and becomes the dominant source of energy for the star, which can now forget about gravitational energy while this source of energy, associated with the shrinking and the expanding of the star, becomes negligible (for now!).\n\nDigression: little stars and where to find them\n\nNot every star does reach the main-sequence phase.\n\nIf the mass of the protostar is less than 0.072 solar masses (72 times the mass of Jupiter) the core cannot reach the necessary temperature to ignite the nuclear reactions to stabilize the star.\n\nBelow this mass, some nuclear reactions still occur, nonetheless: at about 0.060 solar masses, the core can burn lithium1, whereas at 0.013 solar masses, it can burn deuterium.\n\nIf your favorite star has a mass ranging between 0.013 and 0.072 solar masses, astronomers classify it as a brown dwarf. Here’s one:\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!V6RM!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/e4916f30-76b5-4727-bb29-acbc5c1d2175_800x565.jpeg)\n\nThe brown dwarf is the little dot in the center of the right panel, and it is called Gliese 229B. The source that occupies the left portion of both panels is called Gliese 229. Credits: NASA\n\nThe image shows the very first brown star ever observed (in 1995); nowadays, hundreds of such objects have been observed, despite their low luminosity and their low radii, prevalently in the near-infrared part of the electromagnetic spectrum (and primarily in the Milky Way).\n\nStars at the Olympics: the start line of the main-sequence\n\nAs you can see from the plot at the start of this episode, each final point of every star track can be connected to the others, making them all reside on a diagonal line: this is called the zero-age main sequence ( ZAMS ), and it is the start of the hydrogen-burning phase of the star that renders it energetically stable.\n\nThis will be our starting point to follow the star in its evolution. But first, we have to talk about stellar groups.\n\nStellar consortia and space unions\n\nH II regions\n\nMassive stars heat their surroundings: they do so by emitting radiation primarily in the ultraviolet band of the electromagnetic spectrum. This radiation messes up with atoms in the cloud of gas surrounding the star, which afterward recombines with electrons to form neutral hydrogen; when doing so, more photons are created, this time in the visible band of the spectrum. These regions are called HII regions, and below there are some images obtained by different space telescopes.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Yfkh!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9b1bcc9d-ec53-467a-95e7-926571c56e48_1127x1201.jpeg)\n\nThis HII region is called NGC 604 and was first observed by William Herschel in 1784. It is located inside the Triangulum Galaxy, approximately 2.7 million light years from our galaxy. Credits: NASA/ESA\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!1TSk!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/cc86389e-7fd3-411e-bf78-72b0ec5fd4fe_5764x3481.jpeg)\n\nThis image shows a HII region in the Large Magellanic Cloud, one of the satellites of our galaxy Milky Way. It is located 160’000 light years away, and it spans 150 light years in diameter Credits: Hubble, NASA\n\nSometimes it can happen that more massive stars, which drive radiation out in the cloud when forming, deplete the region of mass, necessary to form less massive stars. This is what happens for example at the Pillars of Creation , a giant structure in the Eagle Nebula (M16).\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Oka4!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/35326298-a847-4754-99e7-62949446dbc2_1155x2000.png)\n\nPillars of Creation, in the Eagle Nebula. Credits: James Webb Space Telescope, NASA\n\nOB associations\n\nThese groups of stars are made primarily of O and B stars, and resemble a single structure, but are not gravitationally bound together: the velocities of stars is too high, and soon (in astronomical times, that is) these clusters of stars will become unbound.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!UB6w!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/388f9bb1-e692-45a3-901b-3672e6353684_1500x1192.jpeg)\n\nOrio’s belt. In the background you can see a sheet of stars: that is an example of OB association. Credits: ESA/NASA\n\nT Tauri stars\n\nThese kinds of stars show a high degree of variability in luminosity, with timescales of the order of days. They represent a class of pre-main-sequence stars and have masses in the range of 0.5 - 2 solar masses. One interesting property is the fact that they appear to be losing mass at a rate that is much more rapid (again, in astronomical timescales) than that of the Sun, for example.\n\nThey are called T Tauri because the prototype of this type of object is T Tauri, a star in the constellation Taurus (the one below):\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!RI-8!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d974bdf5-d0aa-4d81-8724-35c36f1d8804_300x333.jpeg)\n\nT Tauri. Credits: NASA\n\nFU Orionis stars\n\nWhen a T Tauri star does not observe mass loss, but rather mass accretion, its luminosity increases This object is known as FU Orionis.\n\nWhat will happen now?\n\nIn the next episode, we will encounter stars during their main sequence.\n\nSee you next time!\n\n1 (hydrogen, helium, lithium, …)\n",
  "../posts/lss/lss_post_003-a-story-of-a-star-part-iii.md": "# A story of a star - Part III\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!S3NL!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/72129a4b-857e-4fac-9726-d82baef2c202_1572x1048.png)\n\nIn the previous episodes we have encountered a giant molecular cloud, the birthplace of hundreds of stars.\n\nNow, we turn our attention to one single spherical cloud, of one solar mass. Let’s see what happens.\n\nStellar nursery\n\nWe start with a free-fall collapse (the one we encountered here and here). Photons1 can travel great distances before being absorbed by “dust”2, so we are in an optically thin environment: this means that the collapse is isothermal . But the density is not homogeneous, hence there is a slight increase of the free-fall velocity in the center than in the outer parts: this is what we call an inside-out collapse ). At some point, the density in the center of the cloud becomes high enough3 that the region becomes optically thick4 and the collapse is more adiabatic.\n\nNow in the inner parts of the cloud, the pressure rises, and the adiabatic collapse reduces the rate of the collapse. This region enters hydrostatic equilibrium5 and has a radius of 5 AU6.\n\nDid you come this far? Congratulations, you saw the birth of a protostar .\n\nThis object is now observable as a single entity and can be put on maybe the most important plot that a stellar physicist encounters in their life: that is, the Hertzsprung-Russel diagram.\n\nWhat is it? What does it tell us? Why it is important?\n\nAll these questions (that I’m sure you were asking yourselves) will be answered swiftly.\n\nDigression: Hertzsprung-Russell diagram\n\nor, how to draw points and curves on a plot\n\nThe idea of putting stars on a plot arrived in the early twentieth century when astronomers noticed that the observed stars varied in luminosities and absolute magnitudes. This led to the idea that stars begin their “life” with a certain amount of “ fuel” , that is, material that can be transformed in luminosity and energy, and as they age they cool off, becoming colder and colder.\n\nThis idea is nowadays considered wrong; nonetheless, it helped astronomy progress.\n\nIn 1905 Danish amateur astronomer Ejnar Hertzsprung (1873-1967) confirmed that there was indeed a correlation between the absolute magnitudes7 and the spectral type8 of a sample of stars. He noticed also that stars with the same spectral type had different magnitudes, i.e. had different levels of brightness.\n\nHe named the brighter stars giants because if you consider stars as great converters of energy in luminosity, then if two stars have the same temperature, and the most luminous must also be the bigger one9.\n\nThis relation was still not plotted on a graph. Then Henry Norris Russell (1877-1957), who independently arrived at the same conclusion, also naming dwarfs the dimmer stars, published a diagram, initially known by astronomers as “ Russell diagram “.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!v9bG!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/7325f1d8-1c12-4f81-be03-2f6bc7a6b5a2_960x1260.png)\n\nRussell diagram. On the horizontal and vertical axis are listed the spectral types (BAFGKMN) and the absolute magnitudes, respectively. Image from Russell, Nature, 93, 252,1914.\n\nAs you can see, most of the points, each representing a star, are displayed between the two solid bands, that define a band called the main sequence , which is the home of the vast majority of stars in the Hertzsprung-Russell (H-R) diagram.\n\nIn the lower left, there is one star which is a white dwarf while in the upper right corner, there are the giant stars.\n\nBelow there is a newer version of the H-R diagram.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!9Or1!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/c751eeef-c0b7-458f-b46c-f141ba86b1f5_1374x1174.png)\n\nAnother (newer) H-R diagram. Stars displayed as points come from the Hipparcos catalog. Credits: ESA\n\nIn this second plot you can see the main sequence at the center, and again the white dwarfs in the lower left, with the giants in the upper right.\n\nLet’s return to our protostar.\n\nOur hypothetical cloud resulted in a protostar with a radius of 5 AU, and now we can put it on a H-R diagram. The quantity we need is the luminosity, which can be computed by considering the protostar as a “ blackbody ”10, and the formula to do so is the following:\n\nBelow is displayed the last plot for this episode, which shows the track that different clouds (with different masses) take within the H-R diagram: they all start in the lower right part of the plot, almost parallel to one another.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!8xsP!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2541da2c-ad94-41c8-97c9-fd4a566e5f44_2084x1530.png)\n\nTheoretical evolutionary tracks for different clouds, with diverse masses. Figure from BoB (who is BoB?).\n\nYou can see that initially the luminosity increases, as well as the temperature (mind the logarithmic scale and the temperature that increases going from right to left). The collapse continues, and then material above the inner part of the protostar is in free-fall. When said material reaches the core of the protostar, the shock generated by the impact between this material and the core itself generates a lot of luminosity11.\n\nThe dust that surrounds the core, when the temperature rises, gets hot and vaporizes. This means that now photons can wander freely out of the cloud: opacity drops and the cloud/protostar becomes optically thin.\n\nOk, now luminosity and temperature continue to rise. When the temperature reaches 2000 K, the molecular hydrogen12 gets divided (dissociated) into two atoms.\n\nThis process uses energy that can not be used to maintain hydrostatic equilibrium. Result? The core becomes unstable and there is a second collapse.\n\nAfter this collapse, returns hydrostatic equilibrium: now the core is smaller, and once again outer material falls into the core. This means another shock, but now luminosity does not rise as much as it did with the first shock (this is because now the surrounding cloud is not as optically thick - opaque - as before); nonetheless, the temperature rises albeit a constant luminosity, and at some point is high enough to burn deuterium, which is an atom of hydrogen with one proton and one neutron (plus one electron).\n\nThis type of process becomes the most favored process in the protostar to create energy (and become luminous), but initially, there is only a small amount of deuterium to burn: this means that luminosity drops.\n\nWhen all the deuterium amount is burnt out, the track finishes with a decrease in temperature.\n\nOk, but do we see some protostars after all?\n\nWell, the short answer is: it depends.\n\nAs we said earlier, the protostar core is shielded by dust. This makes it difficult to observe: astronomers need to observe in the infrared band. Moreover, these objects are relatively small and short-lived, so observing them is not trivial.\n\nWhat comes next?\n\nWe will continue to follow the evolutionary track of the protostar up to the formation of the proper star. It will be a voyage full of funny names and original denominations, so prepare!\n\nSee you next time!\n\n1 they are the particles that constitute light.\n\n2 this is not the kind of dust you encounter in your house; it is made of chemical elements heavier than atomic hydrogen.\n\n3 to give a scale is something like one-tenth of a trillionth times the density of distilled water. space IS empty.\n\n4 that is, now the photon gets rapidly absorbed by dust, and can not freely wander towards the outer parts of the cloud.\n\n5 pressure force = gravitational force.\n\n6 1 AU is the (mean) distance that separates the Earth from the Sun, and it is approximately 150 million kilometers.\n\n7 absolute magnitude is the quantity astronomers use to describe how a celestial object is luminous; it does not take into account how far away the object is but is indeed related to the luminosity the object has when we, here from Earth, observe it.\n\n8 spectral types are the different kinds of shapes the spectra of the stars can have: you can visualize them as different skylines, whereas a single skyscraper or a mountaintop is unique for a spectral type.\n\n9 this is called Stefan-Boltzmann law:\n\n10 a blackbody can be thought of as an object that is very capable of transforming its energy in “temperature” (for the physicists reading this: forgive me).\n\n11 that we don’t see in reality! Because the material surrounding the core blocks the light coming from the inner parts.\n\n12 which is a molecule made up of two hydrogen atoms, viz.:\n\n13 see, I told you!\n",
  "../posts/lss/lss_post_004-a-story-of-a-star-part-ii.md": "# A story of a star - Part II\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Rq9X!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a6232fa4-fab8-46c3-b892-103a5da36067_1572x1048.png)\n\nIn the last episode, we departed from our star when it was undergoing a balanced duel between gravitational collapse and pressure gradients.\n\nWhen this battle is won by gravity, the star will collapse (in the absence of rotation, magnetic fields, and other secondary effects that can favor one or the other).\n\nAt this point, we can consider for the sake of simplicity that the pressure gradients (that is, the velocity with which quantities change, pressure in the specific case) become small. If such a scenario occurs, pressure can not influence the protostar's formation and we can consider the cloud in free-fall1.\n\nDuring this free-fall, the temperature of the gas remains almost constant, and the collapse is called isothermal. This happens even though the cloud is shrinking because the cloud is said to be “ optically thin ”, that is, the photons emitted can travel a lot before encountering a particle and interacting with it. In this fashion, the gravitational potential of the collapse is radiated away .\n\nThen, assuming that the sphere of cloud that soon will become our star is spherically symmetric (this is a good assumption), the next thing to do is to solve a differential equation of the second order. This is a relatively simple thing to do, and indeed it is done with a few substitutions and some mathematical manipulation, resulting in a relation for the free-fall time that is, viz.:\n\nwhere G is the gravitational constant and the other term is the initial density.\n\nOne interesting feature of this relation is that the free-fall timescale is independent of the initial radius of the cloud. This means that every time the initial density is a good indication of the density throughout the entire cloud, i.e. the cloud has a uniform initial density, then every patch of the cloud will take the same time to collapse.\n\nCongratulations, you (hopefully) grasped the concept of homologous collapse.\n\nNonetheless, when the cloud has an overdense region in the center, the free-fall time for the material inside the cloud will be inevitably shorter than for the outer parts. This is then called inside-out collapse .\n\nBut when does the collapse happen? Is there a minimum mass the cloud has to achieve to shrink and become a star? The answer is yes, and lies again in the work of Sir James Jeans (our old friend from this episode). The minimum mass necessary to initiate the collapse is called Jeans mass , viz.:\n\nwhere the quantities are the temperature, the molecular weight, the hydrogen mass, and again the initial density.\n\nLarge molecular clouds can easily exceed this limit: does this mean that stars have the same mass as these clouds? This is not the case, simply because we do not observe such a huge number of very massive stars (with 1500 solar masses). What does happen, you could ask?\n\nWhat happens is a process called fragmentation, which is due to the inhomogeneities in the initial density: these subdense and overdense regions act like single clouds, each with a single Jeans mass and a different free-fall timescale.\n\nOk, suppose that this does happen; what stops this time the cloud from going under extreme fragmentation?\n\nThe answer lies naturally in the temperature!\n\nWe considered this quantity constant throughout the collapse, but this is not the case in the clouds we observe. In particular, at the other extreme of the isothermal collapse resides the adiabatic collapse, the one in which energy cannot be radiated away and remains in the infalling cloud, thus making the temperature rise.\n\nWhen this happens, the Jeans mass goes like this:\n\nthis means that for adiabatic collapse, when the cloud shrinks, and the density goes up, the same thing happens for the Jeans mass needed to collapse!2\n\nThis results in a minimum Jeans mass when adiabatic effects become important (this scenario happens at some point when the cloud shrinks, as we said):\n\nfor a temperature of 1000 K, this means a Jeans mass of one-half of a solar mass.\n\nThis brief description has discarded many complications and features that are taken care of, like the velocity of the cloud, which we considered static at each point in our description.3\n\nTaking care of (almost) everything, the limit of fragmentation, i.e. the minimum mass for a newborn star is 0.01 solar masses.\n\nWhat lies ahead?\n\nEquipped with our results and armed with the knowledge that simplificative assumptions ought to be made to continue, we will follow the life of a cloud of one solar mass, starting with the nearly isothermal collapse.\n\nIt will be fun, see you next time!\n\n1 free-fall is the condition that is experienced by a body that feels solely the force of gravity.\n\n2 the relation above is correct for atomic hydrogen (which is most of the cloud). In general, the relation goes like this:\n\n3 it was requested by the Jeans criterion, take it out on him.\n\n4 this time won’t pass a year, I promise.\n",
  "../posts/lss/lss_post_005-a-story-of-a-star-part-i.md": "# A story of a star - Part I\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Zs5Z!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f19cb45e-75a7-4c7f-a201-acad78f9514f_1572x1048.png)\n\nChasing the Sun\n\nLooking into the heavens, we could be tempted to assume that stars don’t change. Yes, there is a change in the sky season after season, but that may be due to the motion of the Earth around the Sun.\n\nThe Sun looks like a stable, unaltered, never-changing object in the sky. But with the advent of astronomical observations, and therefore with the advent of the telescope, the enhanced observation of the Sun showed that the Sun has spots (sunspots) : the stars were changing.\n\nThe history of Solar and especially the sunspot’s observations is very intriguing: it appears for the first time in written text in the I Ching (the Books of Changes), a Chinese divination text written in the late 9th century BCE1, where it’s found\n\na dou is seen in the Sun\n\na mei is seen in the Sun\n\nwhere dou and mei are darkening or obscuration.\n\nAlso in ancient Greek, around 300 BCE, Theophrastus mentioned, first in the West, this type of event. Then other intellectuals (whether they be proper astronomers, monks, jurists, or historians) noted or cited this strange phenomenon.\n\nThe first observation of a sunspot with a telescope was made by Thomas Harriot , an English astronomer, on 18 December 1610. On 9 March 1611, Frisian Johann Goldsmid (latinised Johannes Fabricius) also observed sunspots.\n\nThese two discoveries were shadowed by the claims made by Galileo Galilei and Christoph Scheiner to have discovered these sunspots in 1612. Whoever discovered first between the two astronomers, they were beaten (without knowing it) by Harriot.\n\nWhere we came, there we’ll go\n\nThis brief introduction served to describe the realization that came with the discovery, thanks to the telescope (that rendered unlikely to infer that the sunspots were instead planetary transits), of little changes in the structures, or at least the appearances, of our star the Sun.\n\nWe will now delve into minute details in order to understand how stars are made, how they evolve, how they change, and ultimately how they die.\n\nWe could say that the evolution of stars is somewhat cyclic.\n\nStars are formed from Interstellar Medium (ISM) and during their life they expel much of their mass back to the ISM itself, even returning completely to the ISM in the case of Supernovae explosions.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!ktc4!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/c4119804-d75a-45a5-a387-854365844c95_1800x1164.jpeg)\n\nThe Milky Way at 5000 Meters. Credit & Copyright: Serge Brunier\n\nThe dominant component (approximately 70% of the mass) of the ISM is hydrogen gas, in the form of neutral hydrogen (HI), ionized hydrogen (HII), and molecular hydrogen (H2). The other 30% comprises essentially helium; metals2 account for a few percent of the total.\n\nISM presents in different ranges of density, masses, and temperatures, mostly because of the different ways for the hydrogen gas.\n\nIn clouds of gas where the hydrogen is primarily atomic, also called diffuse HI clouds , with the following properties:\n\ntemperatures vary from 30 to 80 K;\n\ndensities between 100 and 800 million particles per cubic meter;\n\nmasses between 1-100 solar masses3.\n\nWhen in these clouds one can find molecular hydrogen in the inner regions, these are called diffuse molecular clouds , with\n\ntemperatures vary from 15 to 50 K;\n\ndensities between 500 million and 5 billion particles per cubic meter;\n\nmasses between 3-100 solar masses;\n\nthese clouds measure several parsecs4.\n\nThere are also Giant molecular clouds, huge complexes of dust and gas with\n\ntemperatures typically of 15 K;\n\ndensities between 100 and 300 million particles per cubic meter;\n\nmasses between 100’000 solar masses (up to 1 million solar masses);\n\nthese clouds measure 50 parsecs.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!mpMx!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1b6c1e95-cbdc-4235-8031-daf1c572d191_3019x2968.jpeg)\n\nHorseHead Nebula, part of the Orion giant molecular cloud. The specific “horsehead” figure is due to dust entering the H II environment. (Credit: Ken Crawford)\n\nThe grand structure of the Giant Molecular Clouds is often divided into superdense regions, like dark cloud complexes (10’000 solar masses, density of 500 million particles per cubic meter, temperatures of 10 K, scale of 10 pc); clumps (30 solar masses, density of 1 billion particles per cubic meter, temperatures of 10 K, scale of a couple of pc); dense cores (10 solar masses, density of 10 billion particles per cubic meter, temperatures of 10 K, scale of a 0.1 pc); hot cores (10 to 3000 solar masses, density of 10-10’000 thousand of billion particles per cubic meter, temperatures of 100 to 300 K, scale of 0.05 to 0.1 pc).\n\nOutside of large molecular clouds, there are clouds of almost spherical shape known as Bok 5 globules, with densities of over 10 billion particles per cubic meter, masses from 1 to 1000 solar masses, temperatures around 10 K, and sizes of less than 1 pc.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!vhk4!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5b34a276-5aad-45ae-995b-49656aaec7df_4193x4193.jpeg)\n\nBarnard 68, one of the nearest Bok globules. Credit: ESO (http://www.eso.org/public/images/eso0102a/)\n\nHow does the temperature change in all these clouds? Much of the temperature rise comes from cosmic rays , mostly charged particles that come from supernova explosions and that heat the ISM in the clouds6.\n\nThe formation of Protostars\n\nThe question we would like to tackle now is the following:\n\nwhat are the conditions that lead to the collapse of the globules and cores in order to create the so-called protostars ?\n\nOne way to describe this was found by English Astronomer Sir James Jeans, who considered what would happen if a star that doesn’t rotate, not affected by galactic magnetic fields, and without turbulent motion, deviated from hydrostatic equilibrium. The concept used is very simple: if there are two main sources of motion, gravitational potential energy and kinetic energy of the molecular clouds, these two energies will compete to dominate; if the former dominates, the cloud will collapse, but if the latter prevails, the cloud will expand7.\n\nNow all it takes is to understand what is the value of these energies.\n\nIf one assumes the cloud of spherical shape, and of constant density, then the gravitational potential energy is approximable to\n\nwhere G is the gravitational constant, M is the mass of the cloud, and R is its radius.\n\nThe kinetic energy can be estimated to be\n\nwhere N is the total number of particles that compose the cloud, k is the Boltzmann constant, and T is the temperature. The number of particles is derived from the mass of the cloud, divided by the mass of the hydrogen atom and by the mean molecular weight (that is a quantity used to describe what kind of elements compose the cloud).\n\nWhen equating these two relations one can find the so-called Jeans criterion, both for mass and for size, that decides the maximum mass and the maximum radius the cloud can have in order to not encounter collapse. You can, of course, view them as the minimum mass and radius in order for the cloud to collapse (your choice).\n\nLet’s report an example from BoB 8: for a cloud with a temperature of 50K, entirely composed of neutral Hydrogen and a number density of 500 million particles per cubic meter, the minimum Jeans mass for collapse is 1500 solar masses.\n\nBut this value is many times the maximum observed mass of the HI clouds: this means that these clouds are stable against gravitational collapse.\n\nThe situation may be somewhat different for a giant molecular cloud, with a temperature of 10K and a number density of ionized hydrogen of 10 billion particles per cubic meter. In this case, the Jeans mass for collapse is 8 solar masses, similar to the order of 10 solar masses for these objects: that’s why GMCs are possible sites of star formation, being unstable against gravitational collapse.\n\nWhat will happen?\n\nIn the next chapter, we will go on tackling the collapse of unstable molecular clouds and their fragmentation, and follow the first step of the protostar .\n\nStay tuned!\n\nSome links for further reading:\n\nhttps://web.archive.org/web/20060301083022/http://web.hao.ucar.edu/public/education/sp/great_moments.html\n\nhttps://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-iarticle_query?bibcode=2007JBAA..117..346V&db_key=AST&page_ind=0&data_type=GIF&type=SCREEN_VIEW&classic=YES\n\nhttps://web.archive.org/web/20150102174227/http://www.hao.ucar.edu/education/TimelineB.php\n\n1 Before Current Era; also known as Before Christ. We will stick to BCE and CE (Current Era, instead of AD).\n\n2 In Astrophysics, metals are all the chemical elements that are not Hydrogen or Helium.\n\n3\n\n4\n\n5 Bok globules are named after Bart Bok, a Dutch-American astronomer who studied these objects (https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1947ApJ...105..255B/abstract).\n\n6 Reactions that occur between protons (CR protons) and hydrogen atoms are listed below:\n\nWhen an atom of hydrogen gets ionized, this means that an electron is ejected from the atom, with some of the energy of the initial proton. When the electron interacts with the ISM molecules, the energy gets transferred to the ISM. The energy gets then redistributed and the temperature rises in the cloud.\n\n7 actually, it’s a bit more complicated than that; the condition for equilibrium is described by the virial theorem , which states that twice the kinetic energy plus the potential energy is equal to zero. Nonetheless, the simple frame still stands.\n\n8 aka Big Orange Book, aka An Introduction to Modern Astrophysics , Bradley W. Carroll & Dale A. Ostile, Cambridge University Press.\n",
  "../posts/lss/lss_post_006-proceedings-of-lss-the-steady-state-universe.md": "# Proceedings of LSS: the Steady-State Universe\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!19Hf!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f2901cb7-d12c-44c5-83f6-23cd3293d578_1572x1048.png)\n\nWe all have heard of the Big Bang Theory, at least once. We all have deep into our imagination the depiction of the birth of the cosmos like the explosion (wrong) of a little atom (wrong) at the instant zero of time (wrong).\n\nWell, this is a little far from the actual theory, hence all the wrong instances in the last sentence.\n\nNevertheless, we seem to grasp the basic idea, the fact that the Universe was once smaller (and hotter) and denser and that if we go enough back in time, we will reach a point (in time, not a physical one) where laws of physics break down: this is known as the Planck scale, and has a size of 10-to-the-minus-35 m1; a temperature of 10-to-the-322 K3 , and a mass of 10-to-the-minus-8 kg4 .\n\nEven at this scale, things are not quite clear. Below this scale, we don’t know what happens.\n\nThe Big Bang Theory says that the Universe expanded, things got cooler, space got bigger and less dense, and in about fifteen minutes there was Hydrogen and Helium (and some trace of Lithium, alongside isotopes of Hydrogen and Helium).\n\nOkay, this is the BB theory. What about the Steady State Theory? What is this theory, what does it describe, and most importantly: why today is not accepted as the standard theory?\n\nWhy so steady?\n\nThe idea behind the Steady-State model is the following: consider the Universe as a whole, at the scale of hundreds of Megaparsecs5 ; the Universe at this scale is rather homogeneous and isotropic, meaning that is made up more or less of the same things (homogeneous) and that looks the same in every direction one observes it (isotropic).\n\nSo, with this consideration (named the Cosmological Principle ) the Universe has these two properties in space. But is it true also in time?\n\nThis is a question answered by the Perfect Cosmological Principle , that states the homogeneity and isotropy of the Universe both in space and time.\n\nThe Steady-State Theory of the Universe follows from this principle.\n\nThis theory was developed in 1948 by H. Bondi and T. Gold, and Fred Hoyle in two separate articles.\n\nEmbracing the Perfect Cosmological Principle, Bondi and Gold state that the universe would expand, because an infinitely old static universe would reach some point of thermal equilibrium and everything would be at the same temperature (which is not the case). Technically there would be the possibility of a contracting universe, but they discard it due to the excess of radiation over matter that this would imply.\n\nThen they move on to the observed evidence of distant galaxies, whose velocities are interpreted as the motion of expansions (proportional to distance). In a frame of valid hydrodynamic continuity then, density matter should decrease. Hence it is clear that to have a static Universe matter must be continuously created. The rate of creation can be estimated to be at most one proton per liter per billion years. (it’s not so much matter anyway).\n\nIn this type of Universe, the velocity between distant objects (cosmological distances, to be precise) has to increase as the distance increases.\n\nFurthermore, the ratio between uncondensed and condensed matter must remain constant, so that new galaxies form as older ones move away from each other. In this depiction, one observer could not be able to distinguish a “universal cosmic time”, or derive a unique description of this quantity6.\n\nIt’s natural to grasp the logical evidence that the age distribution of galaxies in any volume will be independent of the time of observations (the Universe is always “the same”!) and it will hence be the same for both distant and near galaxies. This was the master way to construct the interpretation of observations of distant galaxies.\n\nAnother point they discussed is the thermodynamics of the Universe and the evidence that our Universe is in thermal disequilibrium. To obtain this, one would need an expanding Universe. The recession of nebulae (as stated in the paper in 1948 - we now know they are galaxies) indicates then the correct explanation for thermal disequilibrium - i.e. expansion.\n\nObservational Tests\n\nThe idea behind the observational tests necessary to test this theory is that relying on the electromagnetic spectrum is not possible, due to the limitations that this theory has in regard to the field equations. Therefore the observational tests rely largely on kinematical arguments, assuming total homogeneity and isotropy.\n\nNevertheless, the tests resulted in similar problems as the ones from different (and “standard”) cosmologies: data were incomplete and loose enough to contemplate the possibility that either of the theories was correct.\n\nWith the advent of radio telescopes (that were largely improved in the 1950s and consolidated in the 1960s), observations showed that the number of radio sources (objects that emit primarily in the radio band of the electromagnetic spectrum) was not constant with the distance from the site of the observations, meaning that there were more distant radio sources far away from the Milky Way than the theory predicted. This meant that there were more radio sources in the past: the Universe was changing in time!\n\nThe end was not near: another class of astrophysical (cosmological, to be fair) objects did discredit the steady-state theory: it is known as a quasar, a type of active galactic nuclei (AGNs), that are galactic cores where gas and dust that fall into the black hole at the center of the galaxy emit electromagnetic radiation. They are extremely luminous but are found only in the early universe. We don’t see a quasar nearer than 600 million light-years from Earth.\n\nThe final observation that falsified the steady-state theory was the discovery of Cosmic Microwave Background Radiation in 1965. This is the electromagnetic radiation emitted roughly 300000 years after the start of the metric that describes the Universe in the Standard Model (the start of the metric is also known as the Big Bang, but it was not Big and was not a Bang) and today peaked at the microwave, due to the expansion of the Universe. This means one more time that the Universe does change over time, and that the only Cosmological Principle that seems to fit is the plain one, not the Perfect one.\n\nIt was a good run\n\nScientific theories must be falsifiable. They must provide explanations for some phenomena, and possibly make predictions: only this way knowledge can go forward.\n\nThe Steady-State Theory had the audacity to propose an infinite, never-changing universe: these qualities were disproven.\n\nIt certainly has some fascination to think about the Universe as this infinite sea of perfect homogeneity, where the absence of a center is sostituted to the awareness that this portion of the Universe is replicated in its general properties someplace else. Unfortunately for the theory and its supporters, it does not seem to be the right one (as we could ever find it, a “right” one).\n\nSome links for further reading:\n\nH. Bondi , T. Gold, The Steady-State Theory of the Expanding Universe, Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society , Volume 108, Issue 3, June 1948, Pages 252–270, https://doi.org/10.1093/mnras/108.3.252;\n\nF. Hoyle, A New Model for the Expanding Universe, Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society , Volume 108, Issue 5, October 1948, Pages 372–382, https://doi.org/10.1093/mnras/108.5.372;\n\n1\n\nfor comparison, an atomic nucleus has a typical size of\n\n2\n\nto get a sense of this number, note that the temperature of the Sun’s core is\n\n3 Kelvin, one way of defining temperature (if you ask a physicist, THE way to measure temperature). To convert from K to °C all you need is subtract -273.15 °C. You can understand that at the high temperature considered here, the distinction is somewhat unimportant.\n\n4 I won’t pester you anymore with scientific notation; for comparison the mass of a human cell is\n\n5\n\n6 Cosmic time: is the time one observer could measure if bound to the expansion of the Universe, hence with zero peculiar velocity. You can imagine it like the time that is associated with the expansion of the Universe.\n\nDid you imagine it? Very good.\n",
  "../posts/lss/lss_post_007-annals-of-lss-why-is-dark-at-night-e-a-poe-and-olbers-s-paradox.md": "# Annals of LSS: why is dark at night? E.A.Poe and Olbers's Paradox\n\nThe darkness of the sky looks natural. The Sunsets is at the horizon, maybe there is a new moon and you are left with the light of stars (and light pollution, unfortunately).\n\nBut why is that so?\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!z2UO!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/220188d4-9eb5-4ccc-b566-c7d249c83228_1572x1048.png)\n\nFrom a paper left in the drawer to the Steady-State Universe: 125 years of ignoring citations - and footnotes.\n\nOlbers’s paradox can be stated as follows:\n\n[…] that extreme clarity of ideas and expressions accompanied by a most simple yet exact analysis that distinguish all the works of that great astronomer.\n\nOne of the scientists that posed enough attention to this problem to write a paper1 about it was Heinrich W.M. Olbers (1758-1840), a German physician-then-astronomer, who in 1823 submitted an article to the Astronomisches Jahrbuch of Berlin (that didn’t take him seriously, at least at first glance, because the article was published only three years later).\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!8yhP!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/49ada9a3-2d8c-4f09-abc9-db7a3191f505_2500x2868.jpeg)\n\nThis article was not considered in Germany, where Rudolf Wolf made no mention of it in his “Geschichte der Astronomie”2, nor the British George B. Airy in his “Six Lectures on Astronomy”; not even in France, with the sole expectation of Gustave-Adolphe Hirn, that in his “Constitution de l’espace celeste”3 argued that space was empty, not filled with any medium of interaction between celestial bodies. He nonetheless tried to solve the problem of the darkness of the night sky in an infinite Universe using the same concept, stating that the infinite extent of the Universe itself rendered the question of the dark sky irrelevant because celestial bodies like the Earth would not intercept light in enough quantity to make the sky bright as the Sun.\n\nThe greatest reaction to Olbers’s work of 1826 came from Friedrich G. W. von Struve, who stated4 that Olbers’s article was\n\n[…] that extreme clarity of ideas and expressions accompanied by a most simple yet exact analysis that distinguish all the works of that great astronomer.\n\nAccording to Struve the only “problem” in Olbers’s paper was the assumption and the subsequent absence of a demonstration of the absorption of light from interstellar matter.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!xTgz!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/06db9a61-e79a-43d8-a5eb-72f7d33c41bf_1130x1300.jpeg)\n\nFriedrich G. W. von Struve.\n\nOn the other side of the Atlantic Ocean, American astronomer Simon Newcomb discussed the same paradox (without directly citing Olbers). He stated that most of the light disappeared in the infinite Universe (even though an infinite number of stars in the Universe might be a problem with this reasoning).\n\nThis way of resolving a “problem-with-the-infinite” with another infinite was something close to the \" Zeitgeist” of the century: Lord Kelvin himself was the spokesperson of this “infinity/intelligibility” duality5.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!n3la!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/144c4798-2d20-4f0c-9573-cebea59b2e88_500x633.jpeg)\n\nLord Kelvin. Image credit: University of Glasgow\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!iX-W!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/06ba1130-2224-4e1e-92bb-d6de1c396ffe_931x1265.jpeg)\n\nCarl V. L. Charlier\n\nThe Swedish scientist made the mistake of not to read thoroughly Olbers’s paper: he says that Olbers what himself the first to have pointed out this paradox, not realizing that in the very same paper, Olbers states that the problem was discussed beforehand by Edmund Halley.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!zr0y!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6fef1f85-8ba8-413f-aa19-7961f86d2a3d_294x389.jpeg)\n\nEdmund Halley\n\nAnyway, Charlier’s solution (in 1922) to the problem of the infinite Universe was that “the total luminosity of the universe and the total attraction of the universe both are finite, if the radii R(i) of different galaxies are so chosen that the inequality\n\nis satisfied”6. This was essentially the same result found by the Soviet astronomer B. Fessenkov 15 years later.\n\nThis solution provided the Universe with spiral galaxies residing outside the Milky Way, building the world in a “spherically ordered group of Galaxies […]”.\n\nThis conclusion did not attract great attention in England, alongside Olbers’s paradox. The same didn’t happen in Germany, where independently from Charlier a German cosmologist, Selety, argued that the distribution of matter implied in the inequality could harmonize an infinite world with general relativity.\n\nWrapping up, we can say that Olbers’s paradox was not very known or cited in scientific literature until half of the 20th century, and when this was the case was discussed filtered by the following works of different scientists, like Struve, Charlier, and others.\n\nIn a paper7 of 1948 named “The Steady-State Theory of the Expanding Universe” by H. Bondi and T. Gold , this more-than-a-century-old paradox was brushed up. But this version of the paradox was somewhat reimagined.\n\nF. Hoyle (another advocate of the steady-state theory) claimed that was due to Bondi that the interest in Olbers’s paradox was revived. But at what cost? With how many alterations and changes, and to what extent?\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!q09F!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d5d3eaa6-e397-4cee-9a1c-c75e8637401d_450x292.jpeg)\n\nTommy Gold (left) with Hermann Bondi (center) and Fred Hoyle (right), circa 1960. Image credit: uncertain.\n\nFor example, Hoyle stated8 that the problem of the darkness of the sky was “first asked by Olbers in 1826”. Is this true?\n\nWas Olbers the first?\n\nAccording to Olbers himself, no.\n\nHe explicitly states in his paper of 1826 that Edmund Halley has discussed the paradox and its cosmological implications.\n\nNot that Olbers’s angle on this situation is strikingly transparent, to be honest. He failed to mention the work of Loys de Cheseaux, author of “Sur la force de la lumiere et sa propagation dans l’ether”9, where the French scientist arrives at a similar result that Olbers’s. It’s really difficult to understand why, especially when one realizes that the very same work of Cheseaux was in Olbers’s private library10 and that Olbers is quite clear had to read at some point, based (Cheseaux’s work) on the same topic Olbers’s astronomical research, i.e. the orbits of comets.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!zdRS!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b22aee19-a762-4d69-98cc-c3998d45933a_477x599.jpeg)\n\nJean Phillippe Loys de Cheseaux.\n\nAnyway, Halley stated, in his papers “Of the Infinitt of the Sphere of Fix’d Stars” and in “of the Number, Order, and Light of Fix’d Stars”11, that:\n\nI have heard urged that if the number of Fixt Stars were more than finite, the whole superficies of their apparent Sphere would be luminous\n\nIt’s technically the same paradox described by Olbers.\n\nAt this point, one should not be surprised that the story doesn’t end with Halley.\n\nWhen Halley proposed his paradox, the same question was over a century years old. In 1610 Johannes Kepler (1571-1630) replied to Galileo’s “Sidereus Nuncius”12 with a letter that soon became a little book entitled “Conversations with the Sidereal Messenger”13, where he was more interested in rejecting the concept of an infinite Universe (proposed by Thomas Digges in 1576 and soon admired by Giordano Bruno) than in creating a 400 years old set of paradoxes-and-(soon-to-be-forgotten)-solutions.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!ttnf!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9db6080d-dd15-4da3-8952-b487f7c517c6_836x1200.jpeg)\n\nJohannes Kepler\n\nIn his book14 the French philosopher Alexandre Koyré sums up Kepler’s view:\n\nIndeed, if our sun were not incommensurably brighter than the fixed stars, or these so much less bright than it, the celestial vault would be as luminous as the sun.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!ly4I!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/16908205-69af-4188-aeb6-a577873582c9_900x1200.jpeg)\n\nAlexandre Koyré. Image credit to the owner.\n\nThis is the short version of Kepler’s motivation to reject the idea of an infinite Universe; to put this using Harrison’s words15, “the choice was clear: either a cosmic edge and a dark night sky, or no cosmic edge and a blazing sky.”\n\nOne could say that Olbers’s Paradox is no less Kepler’s paradox than Olbers himself.\n\nAnd what about E. A. Poe?\n\nIt’s quite striking noticing that Olbers’s Paradox was solved by the American author E.A.Poe, who in his “Eureka - A Prose Poem” described the possibility that the world was finite and not infinite. He states16:\n\nNo astronomical fallacy is more untenable, and none has been more pertinaciously adhered to, than that of the absolute illimitation of the Universe of Stars. The reasons for limitation, as I have already assigned them, a priori, seem to me unanswerable; but, not to speak of these, observation assures us that there is, in numerous directions around us, certainly, if not in all, a positive limit -- or, at the very least, affords us no basis whatever for thinking otherwise. Were the succession of stars endless, then the background of the sky would present us an uniform luminosity, like that displayed by the Galaxy -- since there could be absolutely no point, in all that background, at which would not exist a star . The only mode, therefore, in which, under such a state of affairs, we could comprehend the voids which our telescopes find in innumerable directions, would be by supposing the distance of the invisible background so immense that no ray from it has yet been able to reach us at all. That this may be so, who shall venture to deny? I maintain, simply, that we have not even the shadow of a reason for believing that it is so.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!EAGn!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/c3f8987c-8d9d-4798-8b87-9bf0ee808256_1024x1440.jpeg)\n\nE.A.Poe not smiling.\n\nTo Poe, the solution is that the Universe is indeed limited, so that exists a distance whence light is unable to reach us.\n\nWhat cosmologists did in the second half of the 1900s, Poe had accomplished over a century years before in the literary form.\n\nThe solution (?)\n\nNow we use some mathematical tools in order to resolve this paradox (if it is possible).\n\nOne way to solve this is to make the hypotheses that the Universe is infinite, that every star is similar to the Sun, and that the distribution of stars is uniform. In this context, we neglect the expansion of the Universe and the fact that stars are in reality distributed primarily in galaxies.\n\nIf we occupy a position in space, we can calculate the contributions of the stars around us dividing the Universe into shells of equal thickness: the inner shells will be less populated but every star will be more luminous, while less luminous stars will more and more populate the outer shells.\n\nThe result combines the fact that the volume of each shell increases with the square distance - hence the number of stars increases with the square of the distance - with the luminosity of a star that conversely diminishes with the same trend; resulting in having each shell that contributes equally to the total luminosity.\n\nIt’s easy to notice now that the total luminosity is the luminosity of a shell multiplied by the number of shells. In an infinite Universe, this number is infinite, hence the luminosity is infinite. This is obviously not the case, hence the paradox.\n\nAnother way, maybe more sophisticated, is to consider the size of the stars. This means that there is a limited number of stars that one can observe from a given point in space. With this argument, the line of sight of any given space ends up on a star’s surface with the same temperature as the Sun’s. This means that the entire sky should appear as a surface at 5000 K. This is still not the case.\n\nOne way to solve this paradox is to consider the density required to produce a night sky. It’s known (or maybe not) that the universe has a mean density of one hydrogen atom per cubic meter. The density required to have a bright sky even at dark is 10^13 (ten thousand of billions) hydrogen atoms per cubic meter. Clearly, that’s a bit too much.\n\nBut the best solution depends on the lifetime of the stars. Even in a Universe where the look-back time is of orders of billions of billions of years (and is not the case in our Universe, which is less than 15 billion years old) one eventually arrives at a “surface” where there is no star.\n\nBut overall, another answer is that the luminosity of stars is not enough to render the sky bright.\n\nTo sum up every aspect of this paradox, one could say that the reason why the sky is not bright at night is indeed different reasons.\n\nBut that is not the case (as I hope was rendered clear): it is not due to absorption effects, nor to the clustering of stars into galaxies that leaves voids, nor to the fact that the Universe is finite or expanding.\n\nIt’s simply because starlight is too weak to compete with the darkness of the sky.\n\nThat’s it. Here comes the end. Below there is some music to help you gaze in the night sky, and the bibliography (here more than ever useful to really grasp the stories behind every idea of these last four centuries). Hope to hear from you soon!\n\nhttps://adsabs.harvard.edu/full/1990IAUS..139....3H\n\nhttps://xroads.virginia.edu/~Hyper/POE/eureka.html\n\n1 \"Uber die Durchsichtigkeit des Weltraumes” (“On the Transparency of Space”), Astronomisches Jahrb. 1826, 110-121 (1825).\n\n2 History of Astronomy.\n\n3 Constitution of the Celestial Space.\n\n4 in “Sur l’extinction de la lumiere des etoiles fixes dans son passage par l’espace celeste” (On the extinction of the light of fixed stars in its passage through celestial space), 1847, St. Peterbourg.\n\n5 Lord Kelvin was quite famous for his quotes. Like this one, in “Baltimore Lectures”:\n\nI do not like the words “paradoxical phenomenom. […] There are no paradoxes in science.\n\n6 Charlier, “How an Infinite World May Be Built Up”, Arkiv Mat. Astronomi Fysik. 16, No. 22, 1.44 (1922).\n\n7 H. Bondi and T. Gold, “The Steady-State Theory of the Expanding Universe”, Monthly Notices Roy. Astron. Soc. 108, 252-270 (1948).\n\n8 F. Hoyle, “Frontiers of Astronomy” (Harper and Brothers, New York, 1955).\n\n9 Part of the “Traité de la comète qui a paru en décembre 1743, of the same author.\n\n10 this information comes from Struve, who acquired the library as part of the collection of the Pulkovo Observatory, near St. Petersburg.\n\n11 Phil. Trns. Roy. Soc.. (London), 31, 22-24 (1720) and 24-26. (1721).\n\n12 “Sidereal Message” (not to be confounded, as Kepler did, with sidereal messenger).\n\n13 see? What did I tell you?\n\n14 A. Koyré, From the Closed World to the Infinite Universe (Harper, New York, 1958), p.75.\n\n15 E.R. Harrison, The Dark Night Sky Paradox , American Journal of Physics 45, 119–124 (1977).\n\n16 https://xroads.virginia.edu/~Hyper/POE/eureka.html\n",
  "../posts/lss/lss_post_008-but-what-is-exactly-the-last-scattering-surface.md": "# But what is exactly the \"Last Scattering Surface\"?\n\nund einsam\n\nUnter dem Himmel, wie immer, bin ich.\n\nFriedrich Hölderlin - Abendphantasie\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!OFF6!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ea5a00fb-6b44-41fc-8701-7f1ab7df3c74_1572x1048.png)\n\nTo understand why this project is called this way, we need to clarify what means in Cosmology to have a surface of last scattering.\n\nTo get this, we need to understand what happens in the Universe - actually, what happened in the first millennia of its life.1\n\nIn this scenario, the Universe is characterisable as a relativistic2 fluid. In addition, every component interacts with every other, and the fluid is in thermal equilibrium (there is not any heat flow).\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!6MhY!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/881c508a-07bc-4f7a-8996-ed7c6f254721_2372x1200.jpeg)\n\nThe anisotropies of the Cosmic microwave background (CMB) as observed by the COBE mission. Image credit: NASA\n\nAs time passes, the Universe expands and cools down, rendering it possible for electrons to bond with protons to form the simplest atom (spoiler - Hydrogen atom ).\n\nThis era of the history of the Universe is often called the “ recombination era ”, even though there was not a previous time when these components “combined”. So “recombination era” is just a funny name.\n\nThe components of the Universe at the time of our investigation are primarily photons, protons, electrons, and hydrogen atoms.\n\nUnlike the early days, a colder Universe is not fully ionized. There are single charges freely flowing in space, and that’s why the rate of scattering3 falls.\n\nWhen the rate of ionization has fallen, the photons have nothing to interact with and don’t scatter with the matter, starting to “ free stream 4” into the Universe as it expands.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!bcCk!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d6b8c6e7-4e99-4b30-bab2-0b0f738cef47_4396x2548.jpeg)\n\nThe anisotropies of the Cosmic microwave background (CMB) as observed by the WMAP mission. Image credit: NASA\n\nFrom now on photons will travel in the Universe, containing as a whole the information about their temperature (photons are the basic constituents of the electromagnetic radiation, that displays in a spectrum, with a more probable temperature and a high energy tail at the end of their spectrum), that drops as the Universe expands.\n\nThe Temperature of this “ Cosmic Background Radiation ” (CBR) is measured to be:\n\nwhere K stands for Kelvin (the only correct way to measure temperatures - sorry Celsius, not sorry Fahrenheit).\n\nWe said that the CMB cools down with the expansion. This means that when recombination started, and finished the era of matter-radiation interaction, the CMB had a different temperature.\n\nOne can calculate the time t this happened, the temperature T at which this happened, and the relative redshift 5.\n\nNow, let’s be said that is not like CMB photons won’t ever interact with anything anymore. It’s just that this won’t happen as frequently as when the radiation was coupled with matter.\n\nSo this sea of photons will continue to travel through the Universe as it expands, cooling and expanding.\n\nTo visualize this surface, we could first try to look at the best image we have of the background radiation (parametrized by its temperature) as it is today. Here it is:\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!PSrt!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/fe521ab9-c2ff-46c4-9aeb-796b3544fadc_946x710.jpeg)\n\nThe anisotropies of the Cosmic microwave background (CMB) as observed by the Planck space telescope. Image credit: ESA and the Planck Collaboration\n\nWe said that the temperature is almost 3 K: then why are there differences in this image, and it’s not just one color?\n\nThat’s because there are indeed some little anisotropies, due to various phenomena, but primarily because different parts of the Universe evolved in slightly different ways. The different colors show that there are cooler and hotter parts of the Universe.\n\nSo what is the last scattering surface? It’s this huge wall of photons that continuously travel towards the outer parts of the Universe (why, are there also inner parts of the Universe? Is there a center6? ) like an opaque window that renders it impossible to look beyond.\n\nThat's it for today. We hope to have motivated you to look upon this subject. If you want to look closely and deeply into the rabbit hole, here are some books/articles/links to enjoy. Hope to hear from you soon!\n\nCosmology - The Origin and Evolution of Cosmic Structure; Peter Coles, Francesco Lucchin; Wiley\n\nCosmological Physics; John A. Peacock; Cambridge\n\nhttps://www.mpg.de/7044245/Planck_cmb_universe\n\n1 With “life of the Universe” we technically mean the time that flows from the start of the metric.\n\n2 Relativistic means that its components have energy almost entirely made out of their momentum and that their mass is negligible.\n\n3 Scattering is when particles (or particles and radiation) interact.\n\nOne example of scattering is aurora borealis , which happens when cosmic rays interact with the atoms and molecules of the atmosphere - in many ways - hence the many nuances of the northern skies.\n\n4 free streaming is what happens when a component of a fluid (i.e. the components of the Universe) does not interact anymore. You can visualize it like this: interaction in an expanding fluid can happen when the time the interaction takes place is lower than the time of expansion - this is the time the fluid expands at some fixed velocity. But at some time something happens and the role is reversed: now the time of interaction is bigger than the time of the expansion. This means that it would take more time for the interaction to happen than the time the fluid takes to expand. So the particles don’t interact.\n\n5 redshift z is defined in general as the difference between the measured wavelength of the radiation and the emitted wavelength, divided by the emitted wavelength.\n\nthis quantity is often interpreted in Cosmology as being related to the recession velocity of the Universe. We’ll probably talk about this some other time.\n\n6 not really.\n",
  "../posts/lss/lss_post_009-this-is-last-scattering-surface.md": "Beginnings are hard. Especially for the Universe.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9a7995d0-9558-4a23-87de-4c22b76ae990_1572x1048.png)\n\nWelcome to the new, first, only place where you can look up to the immensity of the cosmic structures.\n\n1. Why Last, why Scattering\n\nThe idea behind the name “Last Scattering Surface” came to me while I was studying for my Cosmology exam during my ongoing Master’s Studies in Astrophysics.\n\nThe idea behind the project is to talk about whatever fascinates me about the Universe. It’s going to be a long journey.\n\n2. Do you feel like you should join this project?\n\nDo you feel anything at all when you gaze upon the stars (abused expression, pardon me)?\n\nIf this is the case for you, here you can find something to enjoy yourself while gazing. Whenever you decide to stop staring at the sky and decide to use the Internet, he said.\n",
  "../posts/lss/lss_post_but-what-is-exactly-the-last-scattering.md": "und einsam\n\nUnter dem Himmel, wie immer, bin ich.\n\nFriedrich Hölderlin - Abendphantasie\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ea5a00fb-6b44-41fc-8701-7f1ab7df3c74_1572x1048.png)\n\nTo understand why this project is called this way, we need to clarify what means in Cosmology to have a surface of last scattering.\n\nTo get this, we need to understand what happens in the Universe - actually, what happened in the first millennia of its life.1\n\nIn this scenario, the Universe is characterisable as a relativistic2 fluid. In addition, every component interacts with every other, and the fluid is in thermal equilibrium (there is not any heat flow).\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/881c508a-07bc-4f7a-8996-ed7c6f254721_2372x1200.jpeg)\n\nThe anisotropies of the Cosmic microwave background (CMB) as observed by the COBE mission. Image credit: NASA\n\nAs time passes, the Universe expands and cools down, rendering it possible for electrons to bond with protons to form the simplest atom (spoiler - Hydrogen atom ).\n\nThis era of the history of the Universe is often called the “ recombination era ”, even though there was not a previous time when these components “combined”. So “recombination era” is just a funny name.\n\nThe components of the Universe at the time of our investigation are primarily photons, protons, electrons, and hydrogen atoms.\n\nUnlike the early days, a colder Universe is not fully ionized. There are single charges freely flowing in space, and that’s why the rate of scattering3 falls.\n\nWhen the rate of ionization has fallen, the photons have nothing to interact with and don’t scatter with the matter, starting to “ free stream 4” into the Universe as it expands.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d6b8c6e7-4e99-4b30-bab2-0b0f738cef47_4396x2548.jpeg)\n\nThe anisotropies of the Cosmic microwave background (CMB) as observed by the WMAP mission. Image credit: NASA\n\nFrom now on photons will travel in the Universe, containing as a whole the information about their temperature (photons are the basic constituents of the electromagnetic radiation, that displays in a spectrum, with a more probable temperature and a high energy tail at the end of their spectrum), that drops as the Universe expands.\n\nThe Temperature of this “ Cosmic Background Radiation ” (CBR) is measured to be:\n\nwhere K stands for Kelvin (the only correct way to measure temperatures - sorry Celsius, not sorry Fahrenheit).\n\nWe said that the CMB cools down with the expansion. This means that when recombination started, and finished the era of matter-radiation interaction, the CMB had a different temperature.\n\nOne can calculate the time t this happened, the temperature T at which this happened, and the relative redshift 5.\n\nNow, let’s be said that is not like CMB photons won’t ever interact with anything anymore. It’s just that this won’t happen as frequently as when the radiation was coupled with matter.\n\nSo this sea of photons will continue to travel through the Universe as it expands, cooling and expanding.\n\nTo visualize this surface, we could first try to look at the best image we have of the background radiation (parametrized by its temperature) as it is today. Here it is:\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/fe521ab9-c2ff-46c4-9aeb-796b3544fadc_946x710.jpeg)\n\nThe anisotropies of the Cosmic microwave background (CMB) as observed by the Planck space telescope. Image credit: ESA and the Planck Collaboration\n\nWe said that the temperature is almost 3 K: then why are there differences in this image, and it’s not just one color?\n\nThat’s because there are indeed some little anisotropies, due to various phenomena, but primarily because different parts of the Universe evolved in slightly different ways. The different colors show that there are cooler and hotter parts of the Universe.\n\nSo what is the last scattering surface? It’s this huge wall of photons that continuously travel towards the outer parts of the Universe (why, are there also inner parts of the Universe? Is there a center6? ) like an opaque window that renders it impossible to look beyond.\n\nThat's it for today. We hope to have motivated you to look upon this subject. If you want to look closely and deeply into the rabbit hole, here are some books/articles/links to enjoy. Hope to hear from you soon!\n\nCosmology - The Origin and Evolution of Cosmic Structure; Peter Coles, Francesco Lucchin; Wiley\n\nCosmological Physics; John A. Peacock; Cambridge\n\nhttps://www.mpg.de/7044245/Planck_cmb_universe\n\n1 With “life of the Universe” we technically mean the time that flows from the start of the metric.\n\n2 Relativistic means that its components have energy almost entirely made out of their momentum and that their mass is negligible.\n\n3 Scattering is when particles (or particles and radiation) interact.\n\nOne example of scattering is aurora borealis , which happens when cosmic rays interact with the atoms and molecules of the atmosphere - in many ways - hence the many nuances of the northern skies.\n\n4 free streaming is what happens when a component of a fluid (i.e. the components of the Universe) does not interact anymore. You can visualize it like this: interaction in an expanding fluid can happen when the time the interaction takes place is lower than the time of expansion - this is the time the fluid expands at some fixed velocity. But at some time something happens and the role is reversed: now the time of interaction is bigger than the time of the expansion. This means that it would take more time for the interaction to happen than the time the fluid takes to expand. So the particles don’t interact.\n\n5 redshift z is defined in general as the difference between the measured wavelength of the radiation and the emitted wavelength, divided by the emitted wavelength.\n\nthis quantity is often interpreted in Cosmology as being related to the recession velocity of the Universe. We’ll probably talk about this some other time.\n\n6 not really.\n",
  "../posts/lss/lss_post_just-a-story-of-a-star-part-i.md": "![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f19cb45e-75a7-4c7f-a201-acad78f9514f_1572x1048.png)\n\nChasing the Sun\n\nLooking into the heavens, we could be tempted to assume that stars don’t change. Yes, there is a change in the sky season after season, but that may be due to the motion of the Earth around the Sun.\n\nThe Sun looks like a stable, unaltered, never-changing object in the sky. But with the advent of astronomical observations, and therefore with the advent of the telescope, the enhanced observation of the Sun showed that the Sun has spots (sunspots) : the stars were changing.\n\nThe history of Solar and especially the sunspot’s observations is very intriguing: it appears for the first time in written text in the I Ching (the Books of Changes), a Chinese divination text written in the late 9th century BCE1, where it’s found\n\na dou is seen in the Sun\n\na mei is seen in the Sun\n\nwhere dou and mei are darkening or obscuration.\n\nAlso in ancient Greek, around 300 BCE, Theophrastus mentioned, first in the West, this type of event. Then other intellectuals (whether they be proper astronomers, monks, jurists, or historians) noted or cited this strange phenomenon.\n\nThe first observation of a sunspot with a telescope was made by Thomas Harriot , an English astronomer, on 18 December 1610. On 9 March 1611, Frisian Johann Goldsmid (latinised Johannes Fabricius) also observed sunspots.\n\nThese two discoveries were shadowed by the claims made by Galileo Galilei and Christoph Scheiner to have discovered these sunspots in 1612. Whoever discovered first between the two astronomers, they were beaten (without knowing it) by Harriot.\n\nWhere we came, there we’ll go\n\nThis brief introduction served to describe the realization that came with the discovery, thanks to the telescope (that rendered unlikely to infer that the sunspots were instead planetary transits), of little changes in the structures, or at least the appearances, of our star the Sun.\n\nWe will now delve into minute details in order to understand how stars are made, how they evolve, how they change, and ultimately how they die.\n\nWe could say that the evolution of stars is somewhat cyclic.\n\nStars are formed from Interstellar Medium (ISM) and during their life they expel much of their mass back to the ISM itself, even returning completely to the ISM in the case of Supernovae explosions.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/c4119804-d75a-45a5-a387-854365844c95_1800x1164.jpeg)\n\nThe Milky Way at 5000 Meters. Credit & Copyright: Serge Brunier\n\nThe dominant component (approximately 70% of the mass) of the ISM is hydrogen gas, in the form of neutral hydrogen (HI), ionized hydrogen (HII), and molecular hydrogen (H2). The other 30% comprises essentially helium; metals2 account for a few percent of the total.\n\nISM presents in different ranges of density, masses, and temperatures, mostly because of the different ways for the hydrogen gas.\n\nIn clouds of gas where the hydrogen is primarily atomic, also called diffuse HI clouds , with the following properties:\n\ntemperatures vary from 30 to 80 K;\n\ndensities between 100 and 800 million particles per cubic meter;\n\nmasses between 1-100 solar masses3.\n\nWhen in these clouds one can find molecular hydrogen in the inner regions, these are called diffuse molecular clouds , with\n\ntemperatures vary from 15 to 50 K;\n\ndensities between 500 million and 5 billion particles per cubic meter;\n\nmasses between 3-100 solar masses;\n\nthese clouds measure several parsecs4.\n\nThere are also Giant molecular clouds, huge complexes of dust and gas with\n\ntemperatures typically of 15 K;\n\ndensities between 100 and 300 million particles per cubic meter;\n\nmasses between 100’000 solar masses (up to 1 million solar masses);\n\nthese clouds measure 50 parsecs.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1b6c1e95-cbdc-4235-8031-daf1c572d191_3019x2968.jpeg)\n\nHorseHead Nebula, part of the Orion giant molecular cloud. The specific “horsehead” figure is due to dust entering the H II environment. (Credit: Ken Crawford)\n\nThe grand structure of the Giant Molecular Clouds is often divided into superdense regions, like dark cloud complexes (10’000 solar masses, density of 500 million particles per cubic meter, temperatures of 10 K, scale of 10 pc); clumps (30 solar masses, density of 1 billion particles per cubic meter, temperatures of 10 K, scale of a couple of pc); dense cores (10 solar masses, density of 10 billion particles per cubic meter, temperatures of 10 K, scale of a 0.1 pc); hot cores (10 to 3000 solar masses, density of 10-10’000 thousand of billion particles per cubic meter, temperatures of 100 to 300 K, scale of 0.05 to 0.1 pc).\n\nOutside of large molecular clouds, there are clouds of almost spherical shape known as Bok 5 globules, with densities of over 10 billion particles per cubic meter, masses from 1 to 1000 solar masses, temperatures around 10 K, and sizes of less than 1 pc.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5b34a276-5aad-45ae-995b-49656aaec7df_4193x4193.jpeg)\n\nBarnard 68, one of the nearest Bok globules. Credit: ESO (http://www.eso.org/public/images/eso0102a/)\n\nHow does the temperature change in all these clouds? Much of the temperature rise comes from cosmic rays , mostly charged particles that come from supernova explosions and that heat the ISM in the clouds6.\n\nThe formation of Protostars\n\nThe question we would like to tackle now is the following:\n\nwhat are the conditions that lead to the collapse of the globules and cores in order to create the so-called protostars ?\n\nOne way to describe this was found by English Astronomer Sir James Jeans, who considered what would happen if a star that doesn’t rotate, not affected by galactic magnetic fields, and without turbulent motion, deviated from hydrostatic equilibrium. The concept used is very simple: if there are two main sources of motion, gravitational potential energy and kinetic energy of the molecular clouds, these two energies will compete to dominate; if the former dominates, the cloud will collapse, but if the latter prevails, the cloud will expand7.\n\nNow all it takes is to understand what is the value of these energies.\n\nIf one assumes the cloud of spherical shape, and of constant density, then the gravitational potential energy is approximable to\n\nwhere G is the gravitational constant, M is the mass of the cloud, and R is its radius.\n\nThe kinetic energy can be estimated to be\n\nwhere N is the total number of particles that compose the cloud, k is the Boltzmann constant, and T is the temperature. The number of particles is derived from the mass of the cloud, divided by the mass of the hydrogen atom and by the mean molecular weight (that is a quantity used to describe what kind of elements compose the cloud).\n\nWhen equating these two relations one can find the so-called Jeans criterion, both for mass and for size, that decides the maximum mass and the maximum radius the cloud can have in order to not encounter collapse. You can, of course, view them as the minimum mass and radius in order for the cloud to collapse (your choice).\n\nLet’s report an example from BoB 8: for a cloud with a temperature of 50K, entirely composed of neutral Hydrogen and a number density of 500 million particles per cubic meter, the minimum Jeans mass for collapse is 1500 solar masses.\n\nBut this value is many times the maximum observed mass of the HI clouds: this means that these clouds are stable against gravitational collapse.\n\nThe situation may be somewhat different for a giant molecular cloud, with a temperature of 10K and a number density of ionized hydrogen of 10 billion particles per cubic meter. In this case, the Jeans mass for collapse is 8 solar masses, similar to the order of 10 solar masses for these objects: that’s why GMCs are possible sites of star formation, being unstable against gravitational collapse.\n\nWhat will happen?\n\nIn the next chapter, we will go on tackling the collapse of unstable molecular clouds and their fragmentation, and follow the first step of the protostar .\n\nStay tuned!\n\nSome links for further reading:\n\nhttps://web.archive.org/web/20060301083022/http://web.hao.ucar.edu/public/education/sp/great_moments.html\n\nhttps://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-iarticle_query?bibcode=2007JBAA..117..346V&db_key=AST&page_ind=0&data_type=GIF&type=SCREEN_VIEW&classic=YES\n\nhttps://web.archive.org/web/20150102174227/http://www.hao.ucar.edu/education/TimelineB.php\n\n1 Before Current Era; also known as Before Christ. We will stick to BCE and CE (Current Era, instead of AD).\n\n2 In Astrophysics, metals are all the chemical elements that are not Hydrogen or Helium.\n\n3\n\n4\n\n5 Bok globules are named after Bart Bok, a Dutch-American astronomer who studied these objects (https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1947ApJ...105..255B/abstract).\n\n6 Reactions that occur between protons (CR protons) and hydrogen atoms are listed below:\n\nWhen an atom of hydrogen gets ionized, this means that an electron is ejected from the atom, with some of the energy of the initial proton. When the electron interacts with the ISM molecules, the energy gets transferred to the ISM. The energy gets then redistributed and the temperature rises in the cloud.\n\n7 actually, it’s a bit more complicated than that; the condition for equilibrium is described by the virial theorem , which states that twice the kinetic energy plus the potential energy is equal to zero. Nonetheless, the simple frame still stands.\n\n8 aka Big Orange Book, aka An Introduction to Modern Astrophysics , Bradley W. Carroll & Dale A. Ostile, Cambridge University Press.\n",
  "../posts/lss/lss_post_just-a-story-of-a-star-part-ii.md": "![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a6232fa4-fab8-46c3-b892-103a5da36067_1572x1048.png)\n\nIn the last episode, we departed from our star when it was undergoing a balanced duel between gravitational collapse and pressure gradients.\n\nWhen this battle is won by gravity, the star will collapse (in the absence of rotation, magnetic fields, and other secondary effects that can favor one or the other).\n\nAt this point, we can consider for the sake of simplicity that the pressure gradients (that is, the velocity with which quantities change, pressure in the specific case) become small. If such a scenario occurs, pressure can not influence the protostar's formation and we can consider the cloud in free-fall1.\n\nDuring this free-fall, the temperature of the gas remains almost constant, and the collapse is called isothermal. This happens even though the cloud is shrinking because the cloud is said to be “ optically thin ”, that is, the photons emitted can travel a lot before encountering a particle and interacting with it. In this fashion, the gravitational potential of the collapse is radiated away .\n\nThen, assuming that the sphere of cloud that soon will become our star is spherically symmetric (this is a good assumption), the next thing to do is to solve a differential equation of the second order. This is a relatively simple thing to do, and indeed it is done with a few substitutions and some mathematical manipulation, resulting in a relation for the free-fall time that is, viz.:\n\nwhere G is the gravitational constant and the other term is the initial density.\n\nOne interesting feature of this relation is that the free-fall timescale is independent of the initial radius of the cloud. This means that every time the initial density is a good indication of the density throughout the entire cloud, i.e. the cloud has a uniform initial density, then every patch of the cloud will take the same time to collapse.\n\nCongratulations, you (hopefully) grasped the concept of homologous collapse.\n\nNonetheless, when the cloud has an overdense region in the center, the free-fall time for the material inside the cloud will be inevitably shorter than for the outer parts. This is then called inside-out collapse .\n\nBut when does the collapse happen? Is there a minimum mass the cloud has to achieve to shrink and become a star? The answer is yes, and lies again in the work of Sir James Jeans (our old friend from this episode). The minimum mass necessary to initiate the collapse is called Jeans mass , viz.:\n\nwhere the quantities are the temperature, the molecular weight, the hydrogen mass, and again the initial density.\n\nLarge molecular clouds can easily exceed this limit: does this mean that stars have the same mass as these clouds? This is not the case, simply because we do not observe such a huge number of very massive stars (with 1500 solar masses). What does happen, you could ask?\n\nWhat happens is a process called fragmentation, which is due to the inhomogeneities in the initial density: these subdense and overdense regions act like single clouds, each with a single Jeans mass and a different free-fall timescale.\n\nOk, suppose that this does happen; what stops this time the cloud from going under extreme fragmentation?\n\nThe answer lies naturally in the temperature!\n\nWe considered this quantity constant throughout the collapse, but this is not the case in the clouds we observe. In particular, at the other extreme of the isothermal collapse resides the adiabatic collapse, the one in which energy cannot be radiated away and remains in the infalling cloud, thus making the temperature rise.\n\nWhen this happens, the Jeans mass goes like this:\n\nthis means that for adiabatic collapse, when the cloud shrinks, and the density goes up, the same thing happens for the Jeans mass needed to collapse!2\n\nThis results in a minimum Jeans mass when adiabatic effects become important (this scenario happens at some point when the cloud shrinks, as we said):\n\nfor a temperature of 1000 K, this means a Jeans mass of one-half of a solar mass.\n\nThis brief description has discarded many complications and features that are taken care of, like the velocity of the cloud, which we considered static at each point in our description.3\n\nTaking care of (almost) everything, the limit of fragmentation, i.e. the minimum mass for a newborn star is 0.01 solar masses.\n\nWhat lies ahead?\n\nEquipped with our results and armed with the knowledge that simplificative assumptions ought to be made to continue, we will follow the life of a cloud of one solar mass, starting with the nearly isothermal collapse.\n\nIt will be fun, see you next time!\n\n1 free-fall is the condition that is experienced by a body that feels solely the force of gravity.\n\n2 the relation above is correct for atomic hydrogen (which is most of the cloud). In general, the relation goes like this:\n\n3 it was requested by the Jeans criterion, take it out on him.\n\n4 this time won’t pass a year, I promise.\n",
  "../posts/lss/lss_post_just-a-story-of-a-star-part-iii.md": "![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/72129a4b-857e-4fac-9726-d82baef2c202_1572x1048.png)\n\nIn the previous episodes we have encountered a giant molecular cloud, the birthplace of hundreds of stars.\n\nNow, we turn our attention to one single spherical cloud, of one solar mass. Let’s see what happens.\n\nStellar nursery\n\nWe start with a free-fall collapse (the one we encountered here and here). Photons1 can travel great distances before being absorbed by “dust”2, so we are in an optically thin environment: this means that the collapse is isothermal . But the density is not homogeneous, hence there is a slight increase of the free-fall velocity in the center than in the outer parts: this is what we call an inside-out collapse ). At some point, the density in the center of the cloud becomes high enough3 that the region becomes optically thick4 and the collapse is more adiabatic.\n\nNow in the inner parts of the cloud, the pressure rises, and the adiabatic collapse reduces the rate of the collapse. This region enters hydrostatic equilibrium5 and has a radius of 5 AU6.\n\nDid you come this far? Congratulations, you saw the birth of a protostar .\n\nThis object is now observable as a single entity and can be put on maybe the most important plot that a stellar physicist encounters in their life: that is, the Hertzsprung-Russel diagram.\n\nWhat is it? What does it tell us? Why it is important?\n\nAll these questions (that I’m sure you were asking yourselves) will be answered swiftly.\n\nDigression: Hertzsprung-Russell diagram\n\nor, how to draw points and curves on a plot\n\nThe idea of putting stars on a plot arrived in the early twentieth century when astronomers noticed that the observed stars varied in luminosities and absolute magnitudes. This led to the idea that stars begin their “life” with a certain amount of “ fuel” , that is, material that can be transformed in luminosity and energy, and as they age they cool off, becoming colder and colder.\n\nThis idea is nowadays considered wrong; nonetheless, it helped astronomy progress.\n\nIn 1905 Danish amateur astronomer Ejnar Hertzsprung (1873-1967) confirmed that there was indeed a correlation between the absolute magnitudes7 and the spectral type8 of a sample of stars. He noticed also that stars with the same spectral type had different magnitudes, i.e. had different levels of brightness.\n\nHe named the brighter stars giants because if you consider stars as great converters of energy in luminosity, then if two stars have the same temperature, and the most luminous must also be the bigger one9.\n\nThis relation was still not plotted on a graph. Then Henry Norris Russell (1877-1957), who independently arrived at the same conclusion, also naming dwarfs the dimmer stars, published a diagram, initially known by astronomers as “ Russell diagram “.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/7325f1d8-1c12-4f81-be03-2f6bc7a6b5a2_960x1260.png)\n\nRussell diagram. On the horizontal and vertical axis are listed the spectral types (BAFGKMN) and the absolute magnitudes, respectively. Image from Russell, Nature, 93, 252,1914.\n\nAs you can see, most of the points, each representing a star, are displayed between the two solid bands, that define a band called the main sequence , which is the home of the vast majority of stars in the Hertzsprung-Russell (H-R) diagram.\n\nIn the lower left, there is one star which is a white dwarf while in the upper right corner, there are the giant stars.\n\nBelow there is a newer version of the H-R diagram.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/c751eeef-c0b7-458f-b46c-f141ba86b1f5_1374x1174.png)\n\nAnother (newer) H-R diagram. Stars displayed as points come from the Hipparcos catalog. Credits: ESA\n\nIn this second plot you can see the main sequence at the center, and again the white dwarfs in the lower left, with the giants in the upper right.\n\nLet’s return to our protostar.\n\nOur hypothetical cloud resulted in a protostar with a radius of 5 AU, and now we can put it on a H-R diagram. The quantity we need is the luminosity, which can be computed by considering the protostar as a “ blackbody ”10, and the formula to do so is the following:\n\nBelow is displayed the last plot for this episode, which shows the track that different clouds (with different masses) take within the H-R diagram: they all start in the lower right part of the plot, almost parallel to one another.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2541da2c-ad94-41c8-97c9-fd4a566e5f44_2084x1530.png)\n\nTheoretical evolutionary tracks for different clouds, with diverse masses. Figure from BoB (who is BoB?).\n\nYou can see that initially the luminosity increases, as well as the temperature (mind the logarithmic scale and the temperature that increases going from right to left). The collapse continues, and then material above the inner part of the protostar is in free-fall. When said material reaches the core of the protostar, the shock generated by the impact between this material and the core itself generates a lot of luminosity11.\n\nThe dust that surrounds the core, when the temperature rises, gets hot and vaporizes. This means that now photons can wander freely out of the cloud: opacity drops and the cloud/protostar becomes optically thin.\n\nOk, now luminosity and temperature continue to rise. When the temperature reaches 2000 K, the molecular hydrogen12 gets divided (dissociated) into two atoms.\n\nThis process uses energy that can not be used to maintain hydrostatic equilibrium. Result? The core becomes unstable and there is a second collapse.\n\nAfter this collapse, returns hydrostatic equilibrium: now the core is smaller, and once again outer material falls into the core. This means another shock, but now luminosity does not rise as much as it did with the first shock (this is because now the surrounding cloud is not as optically thick - opaque - as before); nonetheless, the temperature rises albeit a constant luminosity, and at some point is high enough to burn deuterium, which is an atom of hydrogen with one proton and one neutron (plus one electron).\n\nThis type of process becomes the most favored process in the protostar to create energy (and become luminous), but initially, there is only a small amount of deuterium to burn: this means that luminosity drops.\n\nWhen all the deuterium amount is burnt out, the track finishes with a decrease in temperature.\n\nOk, but do we see some protostars after all?\n\nWell, the short answer is: it depends.\n\nAs we said earlier, the protostar core is shielded by dust. This makes it difficult to observe: astronomers need to observe in the infrared band. Moreover, these objects are relatively small and short-lived, so observing them is not trivial.\n\nWhat comes next?\n\nWe will continue to follow the evolutionary track of the protostar up to the formation of the proper star. It will be a voyage full of funny names and original denominations, so prepare!\n\nSee you next time!\n\n1 they are the particles that constitute light.\n\n2 this is not the kind of dust you encounter in your house; it is made of chemical elements heavier than atomic hydrogen.\n\n3 to give a scale is something like one-tenth of a trillionth times the density of distilled water. space IS empty.\n\n4 that is, now the photon gets rapidly absorbed by dust, and can not freely wander towards the outer parts of the cloud.\n\n5 pressure force = gravitational force.\n\n6 1 AU is the (mean) distance that separates the Earth from the Sun, and it is approximately 150 million kilometers.\n\n7 absolute magnitude is the quantity astronomers use to describe how a celestial object is luminous; it does not take into account how far away the object is but is indeed related to the luminosity the object has when we, here from Earth, observe it.\n\n8 spectral types are the different kinds of shapes the spectra of the stars can have: you can visualize them as different skylines, whereas a single skyscraper or a mountaintop is unique for a spectral type.\n\n9 this is called Stefan-Boltzmann law:\n\n10 a blackbody can be thought of as an object that is very capable of transforming its energy in “temperature” (for the physicists reading this: forgive me).\n\n11 that we don’t see in reality! Because the material surrounding the core blocks the light coming from the inner parts.\n\n12 which is a molecule made up of two hydrogen atoms, viz.:\n\n13 see, I told you!\n",
  "../posts/lss/lss_post_just-a-story-of-a-star-part-iv.md": "![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9666f14d-b278-4668-8c1a-2588bd0b3cbf_1572x1048.png)\n\nLast time we talked about the depletion of deuterium, and now the status of the protostar is at stake. This happens because this object is not controlled anymore in its evolution by the free-fall timescale; instead, the timescale is now governed by the balance between gravity (which is always present) and the thermal properties of the star’s core. This new timescale goes by the name of Kelvin-Helmoltz timescale.\n\nThis timescale is way longer than the free-fall one: for instance, a molecular cloud of one solar mass takes 150 thousand years to arrive at the state of protostar that burns deuterium but takes 40 million years to contract into a proper star.\n\nThe road that protostars have to follow to reach the main-sequence is known as the Hayashi track , after C. Hayashi who demonstrated in 1961 that there is a boundary (a vertical line in the H-R diagram) that separates a stellar model that is indeed observed and those who are not observed (due to hydrostatic “impossibilities”).\n\nThis impossibility is because, at the right of the Hayashi track, no mechanism can transport the luminosity in the outer parts of the stellar envelope; on the other part of the track, convection, and radiation can indeed transport said luminosity.\n\nThe contraction time for protostars is heavily influenced by their initial masses. For a protostar of 0.8 solar masses, the time on the Hayashi track is something around 70 million years, whereas a protostar of 60 solar masses stays on the track for as short as 30 thousand years. The figure below shows the evolutionary tracks for a series of (simulated) stars: on the right is visible the vertical Hayashi track, which ends where luminosity reaches its minimum value. At this point radiative core of the star allows energy to travel into the (convective) envelope, and luminosity again increases. But the star is also shrinking, and then the temperature rises as well. At a certain point, the high temperature leads to the deuterium burning phase (the squares on the line). The long-dashed line represents the point where convection stops and the envelope of the star becomes radiative; whereas the short-dashed line represents the start of convection in the core.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6101756a-cd38-4e2e-a8dc-2338d0e6e25b_1248x1670.png)\n\nCredits: Carroll and Ostlie, An Introduction to Modern Astrophysics\n\nAfter passing the deuterium-burning phase, the star has two main roads to produce energy via nuclear fusion: the PP chain and the CNO reactions: the former is the conversion of hydrogen into helium, whereas the latter converts carbon into nitrogen. Both reactions can happen in stars at the same time, but only one will dominate the other, ultimately setting the fate of the star.\n\nIn the phase on the plot where luminosity and temperature are rising, the core is at a temperature at which the CNO reactions are heavily favored, and thus these reactions dominate: the energy originated in such a way leads the core to expand. This leads to a decrease in total luminosity and also in the temperature (in the graph, this is noticeable near the short-dashed lines).\n\nWhen carbon is exhausted in the core, the dominating reaction becomes the PP chain, which stabilizes the system and becomes the dominant source of energy for the star, which can now forget about gravitational energy while this source of energy, associated with the shrinking and the expanding of the star, becomes negligible (for now!).\n\nDigression: little stars and where to find them\n\nNot every star does reach the main-sequence phase.\n\nIf the mass of the protostar is less than 0.072 solar masses (72 times the mass of Jupiter) the core cannot reach the necessary temperature to ignite the nuclear reactions to stabilize the star.\n\nBelow this mass, some nuclear reactions still occur, nonetheless: at about 0.060 solar masses, the core can burn lithium1, whereas at 0.013 solar masses, it can burn deuterium.\n\nIf your favorite star has a mass ranging between 0.013 and 0.072 solar masses, astronomers classify it as a brown dwarf. Here’s one:\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/e4916f30-76b5-4727-bb29-acbc5c1d2175_800x565.jpeg)\n\nThe brown dwarf is the little dot in the center of the right panel, and it is called Gliese 229B. The source that occupies the left portion of both panels is called Gliese 229. Credits: NASA\n\nThe image shows the very first brown star ever observed (in 1995); nowadays, hundreds of such objects have been observed, despite their low luminosity and their low radii, prevalently in the near-infrared part of the electromagnetic spectrum (and primarily in the Milky Way).\n\nStars at the Olympics: the start line of the main-sequence\n\nAs you can see from the plot at the start of this episode, each final point of every star track can be connected to the others, making them all reside on a diagonal line: this is called the zero-age main sequence ( ZAMS ), and it is the start of the hydrogen-burning phase of the star that renders it energetically stable.\n\nThis will be our starting point to follow the star in its evolution. But first, we have to talk about stellar groups.\n\nStellar consortia and space unions\n\nH II regions\n\nMassive stars heat their surroundings: they do so by emitting radiation primarily in the ultraviolet band of the electromagnetic spectrum. This radiation messes up with atoms in the cloud of gas surrounding the star, which afterward recombines with electrons to form neutral hydrogen; when doing so, more photons are created, this time in the visible band of the spectrum. These regions are called HII regions, and below there are some images obtained by different space telescopes.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9b1bcc9d-ec53-467a-95e7-926571c56e48_1127x1201.jpeg)\n\nThis HII region is called NGC 604 and was first observed by William Herschel in 1784. It is located inside the Triangulum Galaxy, approximately 2.7 million light years from our galaxy. Credits: NASA/ESA\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/cc86389e-7fd3-411e-bf78-72b0ec5fd4fe_5764x3481.jpeg)\n\nThis image shows a HII region in the Large Magellanic Cloud, one of the satellites of our galaxy Milky Way. It is located 160’000 light years away, and it spans 150 light years in diameter Credits: Hubble, NASA\n\nSometimes it can happen that more massive stars, which drive radiation out in the cloud when forming, deplete the region of mass, necessary to form less massive stars. This is what happens for example at the Pillars of Creation , a giant structure in the Eagle Nebula (M16).\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/35326298-a847-4754-99e7-62949446dbc2_1155x2000.png)\n\nPillars of Creation, in the Eagle Nebula. Credits: James Webb Space Telescope, NASA\n\nOB associations\n\nThese groups of stars are made primarily of O and B stars, and resemble a single structure, but are not gravitationally bound together: the velocities of stars is too high, and soon (in astronomical times, that is) these clusters of stars will become unbound.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/388f9bb1-e692-45a3-901b-3672e6353684_1500x1192.jpeg)\n\nOrio’s belt. In the background you can see a sheet of stars: that is an example of OB association. Credits: ESA/NASA\n\nT Tauri stars\n\nThese kinds of stars show a high degree of variability in luminosity, with timescales of the order of days. They represent a class of pre-main-sequence stars and have masses in the range of 0.5 - 2 solar masses. One interesting property is the fact that they appear to be losing mass at a rate that is much more rapid (again, in astronomical timescales) than that of the Sun, for example.\n\nThey are called T Tauri because the prototype of this type of object is T Tauri, a star in the constellation Taurus (the one below):\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d974bdf5-d0aa-4d81-8724-35c36f1d8804_300x333.jpeg)\n\nT Tauri. Credits: NASA\n\nFU Orionis stars\n\nWhen a T Tauri star does not observe mass loss, but rather mass accretion, its luminosity increases This object is known as FU Orionis.\n\nWhat will happen now?\n\nIn the next episode, we will encounter stars during their main sequence.\n\nSee you next time!\n\n1 (hydrogen, helium, lithium, …)\n",
  "../posts/lss/lss_post_story-of-a-star-part-v.md": "![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1672a724-7b16-4aac-9d7d-974ec2881263_1572x1048.png)\n\nWe know from the previous episodes that stars need some form of energy to counter the gravitational force that would tend to make the structure collapse.\n\nIn the case of protostars, the responsibility for such a scenario lies on “controlled collapse”; in the case of stars, the main source of energy is thermonuclear reactions, which have timescales of the order of tens of billions of years.\n\nThen, you can easily understand why the main sequence is the configuration in which stars live most of their lives.\n\nThus the main sequence will also be the main subject of this episode.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/e9add7a6-7ae1-4dc5-8aec-a42c8ac0821d_2039x2039.jpeg)\n\nM2 globular cluster. Credits: NASA\n\nReady, set, go\n\nYou already know that the zero-age main sequence is a diagonal line in the H-R diagram: from this line depart the tracks for stars of different masses. In particular, stars above 1.2 solar masses have convective cores and are dominated by CNO reactions (we talked about those here), whereas stars below this mass are dominated by pp chains1, and have radiative cores2.\n\nWhat happens to a low-mass star?\n\nWell, it will burn hydrogen: by doing so, it will have more and more helium, which will make the mean molecular weight heavier. This leads to a compression of the core because the temperature or the density (or both) of the core does not increase as much as to counter the weight of the outer layers of the star.\n\nOf course, with the core compressed, density does increase, and this results in a gravitational potential release3 that increases the temperature of the gas: now more gas undergoes thermonuclear reactions.\n\nWith the increase in temperature, it also increases the rate at which the pp chain occurs: this results in the temperature increasing, along with the radius.\n\nOk, stars burn hydrogen in their main sequence lifetime.\n\nWhat happens when hydrogen ends? Well, for low-mass stars, the pp chain stops in the core, but the high temperature all around the core enables the envelope of the core to burn hydrogen: there is an onion-like configuration, with a core now completely made of helium, and an outer shell made of hydrogen, that as soon as becomes helium increases the core.\n\nThe reactions in the shell produce more energy than those in the core: this leads to an increase in luminosity. This does not lead to an increase in temperature: what happens is that the temperature decreases slightly, because the energy produced makes the envelope expand, thus cooling the effective temperature.\n\nThis new phase ends when the helium core gets too massive compared to the total mass of the star. This limit is known as Schonberg-Chandrasekhar limit, and it is related to the fact that hydrostatic equilibrium depends on the molecular weight of the core and the envelope. To show the results would require a long (very long) amount of calculations, so if interested you can look it up (here, for example).\n\nWhat is the order of magnitude of such a limit? In the case of a star with a chemical composition similar to that of the Sun, the limit would be reached when the isothermal core exceeds 8% of the star’s total mass.\n\nWhat we said until now assumes that the gas in the core of the stars can be regarded as ideal; but when the density becomes sufficiently high, the gas becomes degenerate , meaning that the pressure is not controlled anymore by the temperature of the gas, instead the dominant factor becomes the quantum nature of electrons, that now occupy all the space available according to quantum mechanics.\n\nThis complication in our story has the visible effect that the Schonberg-Chandrasekhar limit gets shifted up at 13% (in the case of a star of the Sun’s mass).\n\nWhat happens to a high-mass star?\n\nThe process is somewhat similar to the low-mass stars, but the presence of a convective core mixes things (the elements in the outer envelope and those in the inner core), making the chemical composition of the star homogeneous. The convection zone disappears eventually before the total depletion of hydrogen, and the stars encounter contraction like the other low-mass stars.\n\nWhat awaits in the future?\n\nIn the next episode, we will continue to follow the life of stars in the main sequence and also encounter a new group of stars: globular clusters.\n\n1 remember, CNO reactions are driven mostly by high temperatures, whereas pp chains are related to (relatively) lower temperatures.\n\n2 below 0.3 solar masses actually, the star is entirely convective.\n\n3 thanks to the virial theorem (we talked about it here).\n",
  "../posts/lss/lss_post_the-steady-state-universe.md": "![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f2901cb7-d12c-44c5-83f6-23cd3293d578_1572x1048.png)\n\nWe all have heard of the Big Bang Theory, at least once. We all have deep into our imagination the depiction of the birth of the cosmos like the explosion (wrong) of a little atom (wrong) at the instant zero of time (wrong).\n\nWell, this is a little far from the actual theory, hence all the wrong instances in the last sentence.\n\nNevertheless, we seem to grasp the basic idea, the fact that the Universe was once smaller (and hotter) and denser and that if we go enough back in time, we will reach a point (in time, not a physical one) where laws of physics break down: this is known as the Planck scale, and has a size of 10-to-the-minus-35 m1; a temperature of 10-to-the-322 K3 , and a mass of 10-to-the-minus-8 kg4 .\n\nEven at this scale, things are not quite clear. Below this scale, we don’t know what happens.\n\nThe Big Bang Theory says that the Universe expanded, things got cooler, space got bigger and less dense, and in about fifteen minutes there was Hydrogen and Helium (and some trace of Lithium, alongside isotopes of Hydrogen and Helium).\n\nOkay, this is the BB theory. What about the Steady State Theory? What is this theory, what does it describe, and most importantly: why today is not accepted as the standard theory?\n\nWhy so steady?\n\nThe idea behind the Steady-State model is the following: consider the Universe as a whole, at the scale of hundreds of Megaparsecs5 ; the Universe at this scale is rather homogeneous and isotropic, meaning that is made up more or less of the same things (homogeneous) and that looks the same in every direction one observes it (isotropic).\n\nSo, with this consideration (named the Cosmological Principle ) the Universe has these two properties in space. But is it true also in time?\n\nThis is a question answered by the Perfect Cosmological Principle , that states the homogeneity and isotropy of the Universe both in space and time.\n\nThe Steady-State Theory of the Universe follows from this principle.\n\nThis theory was developed in 1948 by H. Bondi and T. Gold, and Fred Hoyle in two separate articles.\n\nEmbracing the Perfect Cosmological Principle, Bondi and Gold state that the universe would expand, because an infinitely old static universe would reach some point of thermal equilibrium and everything would be at the same temperature (which is not the case). Technically there would be the possibility of a contracting universe, but they discard it due to the excess of radiation over matter that this would imply.\n\nThen they move on to the observed evidence of distant galaxies, whose velocities are interpreted as the motion of expansions (proportional to distance). In a frame of valid hydrodynamic continuity then, density matter should decrease. Hence it is clear that to have a static Universe matter must be continuously created. The rate of creation can be estimated to be at most one proton per liter per billion years. (it’s not so much matter anyway).\n\nIn this type of Universe, the velocity between distant objects (cosmological distances, to be precise) has to increase as the distance increases.\n\nFurthermore, the ratio between uncondensed and condensed matter must remain constant, so that new galaxies form as older ones move away from each other. In this depiction, one observer could not be able to distinguish a “universal cosmic time”, or derive a unique description of this quantity6.\n\nIt’s natural to grasp the logical evidence that the age distribution of galaxies in any volume will be independent of the time of observations (the Universe is always “the same”!) and it will hence be the same for both distant and near galaxies. This was the master way to construct the interpretation of observations of distant galaxies.\n\nAnother point they discussed is the thermodynamics of the Universe and the evidence that our Universe is in thermal disequilibrium. To obtain this, one would need an expanding Universe. The recession of nebulae (as stated in the paper in 1948 - we now know they are galaxies) indicates then the correct explanation for thermal disequilibrium - i.e. expansion.\n\nObservational Tests\n\nThe idea behind the observational tests necessary to test this theory is that relying on the electromagnetic spectrum is not possible, due to the limitations that this theory has in regard to the field equations. Therefore the observational tests rely largely on kinematical arguments, assuming total homogeneity and isotropy.\n\nNevertheless, the tests resulted in similar problems as the ones from different (and “standard”) cosmologies: data were incomplete and loose enough to contemplate the possibility that either of the theories was correct.\n\nWith the advent of radio telescopes (that were largely improved in the 1950s and consolidated in the 1960s), observations showed that the number of radio sources (objects that emit primarily in the radio band of the electromagnetic spectrum) was not constant with the distance from the site of the observations, meaning that there were more distant radio sources far away from the Milky Way than the theory predicted. This meant that there were more radio sources in the past: the Universe was changing in time!\n\nThe end was not near: another class of astrophysical (cosmological, to be fair) objects did discredit the steady-state theory: it is known as a quasar, a type of active galactic nuclei (AGNs), that are galactic cores where gas and dust that fall into the black hole at the center of the galaxy emit electromagnetic radiation. They are extremely luminous but are found only in the early universe. We don’t see a quasar nearer than 600 million light-years from Earth.\n\nThe final observation that falsified the steady-state theory was the discovery of Cosmic Microwave Background Radiation in 1965. This is the electromagnetic radiation emitted roughly 300000 years after the start of the metric that describes the Universe in the Standard Model (the start of the metric is also known as the Big Bang, but it was not Big and was not a Bang) and today peaked at the microwave, due to the expansion of the Universe. This means one more time that the Universe does change over time, and that the only Cosmological Principle that seems to fit is the plain one, not the Perfect one.\n\nIt was a good run\n\nScientific theories must be falsifiable. They must provide explanations for some phenomena, and possibly make predictions: only this way knowledge can go forward.\n\nThe Steady-State Theory had the audacity to propose an infinite, never-changing universe: these qualities were disproven.\n\nIt certainly has some fascination to think about the Universe as this infinite sea of perfect homogeneity, where the absence of a center is sostituted to the awareness that this portion of the Universe is replicated in its general properties someplace else. Unfortunately for the theory and its supporters, it does not seem to be the right one (as we could ever find it, a “right” one).\n\nSome links for further reading:\n\nH. Bondi , T. Gold, The Steady-State Theory of the Expanding Universe, Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society , Volume 108, Issue 3, June 1948, Pages 252–270, https://doi.org/10.1093/mnras/108.3.252;\n\nF. Hoyle, A New Model for the Expanding Universe, Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society , Volume 108, Issue 5, October 1948, Pages 372–382, https://doi.org/10.1093/mnras/108.5.372;\n\n1\n\nfor comparison, an atomic nucleus has a typical size of\n\n2\n\nto get a sense of this number, note that the temperature of the Sun’s core is\n\n3 Kelvin, one way of defining temperature (if you ask a physicist, THE way to measure temperature). To convert from K to °C all you need is subtract -273.15 °C. You can understand that at the high temperature considered here, the distinction is somewhat unimportant.\n\n4 I won’t pester you anymore with scientific notation; for comparison the mass of a human cell is\n\n5\n\n6 Cosmic time: is the time one observer could measure if bound to the expansion of the Universe, hence with zero peculiar velocity. You can imagine it like the time that is associated with the expansion of the Universe.\n\nDid you imagine it? Very good.\n",
  "../posts/lss/lss_post_why-is-dark-at-night-eapoe-and-the.md": "The darkness of the sky looks natural. The Sunsets is at the horizon, maybe there is a new moon and you are left with the light of stars (and light pollution, unfortunately).\n\nBut why is that so?\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/220188d4-9eb5-4ccc-b566-c7d249c83228_1572x1048.png)\n\nFrom a paper left in the drawer to the Steady-State Universe: 125 years of ignoring citations - and footnotes.\n\nOlbers’s paradox can be stated as follows:\n\n[…] that extreme clarity of ideas and expressions accompanied by a most simple yet exact analysis that distinguish all the works of that great astronomer.\n\nOne of the scientists that posed enough attention to this problem to write a paper1 about it was Heinrich W.M. Olbers (1758-1840), a German physician-then-astronomer, who in 1823 submitted an article to the Astronomisches Jahrbuch of Berlin (that didn’t take him seriously, at least at first glance, because the article was published only three years later).\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/49ada9a3-2d8c-4f09-abc9-db7a3191f505_2500x2868.jpeg)\n\nThis article was not considered in Germany, where Rudolf Wolf made no mention of it in his “Geschichte der Astronomie”2, nor the British George B. Airy in his “Six Lectures on Astronomy”; not even in France, with the sole expectation of Gustave-Adolphe Hirn, that in his “Constitution de l’espace celeste”3 argued that space was empty, not filled with any medium of interaction between celestial bodies. He nonetheless tried to solve the problem of the darkness of the night sky in an infinite Universe using the same concept, stating that the infinite extent of the Universe itself rendered the question of the dark sky irrelevant because celestial bodies like the Earth would not intercept light in enough quantity to make the sky bright as the Sun.\n\nThe greatest reaction to Olbers’s work of 1826 came from Friedrich G. W. von Struve, who stated4 that Olbers’s article was\n\n[…] that extreme clarity of ideas and expressions accompanied by a most simple yet exact analysis that distinguish all the works of that great astronomer.\n\nAccording to Struve the only “problem” in Olbers’s paper was the assumption and the subsequent absence of a demonstration of the absorption of light from interstellar matter.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/06db9a61-e79a-43d8-a5eb-72f7d33c41bf_1130x1300.jpeg)\n\nFriedrich G. W. von Struve.\n\nOn the other side of the Atlantic Ocean, American astronomer Simon Newcomb discussed the same paradox (without directly citing Olbers). He stated that most of the light disappeared in the infinite Universe (even though an infinite number of stars in the Universe might be a problem with this reasoning).\n\nThis way of resolving a “problem-with-the-infinite” with another infinite was something close to the \" Zeitgeist” of the century: Lord Kelvin himself was the spokesperson of this “infinity/intelligibility” duality5.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/144c4798-2d20-4f0c-9573-cebea59b2e88_500x633.jpeg)\n\nLord Kelvin. Image credit: University of Glasgow\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/06ba1130-2224-4e1e-92bb-d6de1c396ffe_931x1265.jpeg)\n\nCarl V. L. Charlier\n\nThe Swedish scientist made the mistake of not to read thoroughly Olbers’s paper: he says that Olbers what himself the first to have pointed out this paradox, not realizing that in the very same paper, Olbers states that the problem was discussed beforehand by Edmund Halley.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6fef1f85-8ba8-413f-aa19-7961f86d2a3d_294x389.jpeg)\n\nEdmund Halley\n\nAnyway, Charlier’s solution (in 1922) to the problem of the infinite Universe was that “the total luminosity of the universe and the total attraction of the universe both are finite, if the radii R(i) of different galaxies are so chosen that the inequality\n\nis satisfied”6. This was essentially the same result found by the Soviet astronomer B. Fessenkov 15 years later.\n\nThis solution provided the Universe with spiral galaxies residing outside the Milky Way, building the world in a “spherically ordered group of Galaxies […]”.\n\nThis conclusion did not attract great attention in England, alongside Olbers’s paradox. The same didn’t happen in Germany, where independently from Charlier a German cosmologist, Selety, argued that the distribution of matter implied in the inequality could harmonize an infinite world with general relativity.\n\nWrapping up, we can say that Olbers’s paradox was not very known or cited in scientific literature until half of the 20th century, and when this was the case was discussed filtered by the following works of different scientists, like Struve, Charlier, and others.\n\nIn a paper7 of 1948 named “The Steady-State Theory of the Expanding Universe” by H. Bondi and T. Gold , this more-than-a-century-old paradox was brushed up. But this version of the paradox was somewhat reimagined.\n\nF. Hoyle (another advocate of the steady-state theory) claimed that was due to Bondi that the interest in Olbers’s paradox was revived. But at what cost? With how many alterations and changes, and to what extent?\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d5d3eaa6-e397-4cee-9a1c-c75e8637401d_450x292.jpeg)\n\nTommy Gold (left) with Hermann Bondi (center) and Fred Hoyle (right), circa 1960. Image credit: uncertain.\n\nFor example, Hoyle stated8 that the problem of the darkness of the sky was “first asked by Olbers in 1826”. Is this true?\n\nWas Olbers the first?\n\nAccording to Olbers himself, no.\n\nHe explicitly states in his paper of 1826 that Edmund Halley has discussed the paradox and its cosmological implications.\n\nNot that Olbers’s angle on this situation is strikingly transparent, to be honest. He failed to mention the work of Loys de Cheseaux, author of “Sur la force de la lumiere et sa propagation dans l’ether”9, where the French scientist arrives at a similar result that Olbers’s. It’s really difficult to understand why, especially when one realizes that the very same work of Cheseaux was in Olbers’s private library10 and that Olbers is quite clear had to read at some point, based (Cheseaux’s work) on the same topic Olbers’s astronomical research, i.e. the orbits of comets.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b22aee19-a762-4d69-98cc-c3998d45933a_477x599.jpeg)\n\nJean Phillippe Loys de Cheseaux.\n\nAnyway, Halley stated, in his papers “Of the Infinitt of the Sphere of Fix’d Stars” and in “of the Number, Order, and Light of Fix’d Stars”11, that:\n\nI have heard urged that if the number of Fixt Stars were more than finite, the whole superficies of their apparent Sphere would be luminous\n\nIt’s technically the same paradox described by Olbers.\n\nAt this point, one should not be surprised that the story doesn’t end with Halley.\n\nWhen Halley proposed his paradox, the same question was over a century years old. In 1610 Johannes Kepler (1571-1630) replied to Galileo’s “Sidereus Nuncius”12 with a letter that soon became a little book entitled “Conversations with the Sidereal Messenger”13, where he was more interested in rejecting the concept of an infinite Universe (proposed by Thomas Digges in 1576 and soon admired by Giordano Bruno) than in creating a 400 years old set of paradoxes-and-(soon-to-be-forgotten)-solutions.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/9db6080d-dd15-4da3-8952-b487f7c517c6_836x1200.jpeg)\n\nJohannes Kepler\n\nIn his book14 the French philosopher Alexandre Koyré sums up Kepler’s view:\n\nIndeed, if our sun were not incommensurably brighter than the fixed stars, or these so much less bright than it, the celestial vault would be as luminous as the sun.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/16908205-69af-4188-aeb6-a577873582c9_900x1200.jpeg)\n\nAlexandre Koyré. Image credit to the owner.\n\nThis is the short version of Kepler’s motivation to reject the idea of an infinite Universe; to put this using Harrison’s words15, “the choice was clear: either a cosmic edge and a dark night sky, or no cosmic edge and a blazing sky.”\n\nOne could say that Olbers’s Paradox is no less Kepler’s paradox than Olbers himself.\n\nAnd what about E. A. Poe?\n\nIt’s quite striking noticing that Olbers’s Paradox was solved by the American author E.A.Poe, who in his “Eureka - A Prose Poem” described the possibility that the world was finite and not infinite. He states16:\n\nNo astronomical fallacy is more untenable, and none has been more pertinaciously adhered to, than that of the absolute illimitation of the Universe of Stars. The reasons for limitation, as I have already assigned them, a priori, seem to me unanswerable; but, not to speak of these, observation assures us that there is, in numerous directions around us, certainly, if not in all, a positive limit -- or, at the very least, affords us no basis whatever for thinking otherwise. Were the succession of stars endless, then the background of the sky would present us an uniform luminosity, like that displayed by the Galaxy -- since there could be absolutely no point, in all that background, at which would not exist a star . The only mode, therefore, in which, under such a state of affairs, we could comprehend the voids which our telescopes find in innumerable directions, would be by supposing the distance of the invisible background so immense that no ray from it has yet been able to reach us at all. That this may be so, who shall venture to deny? I maintain, simply, that we have not even the shadow of a reason for believing that it is so.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/c3f8987c-8d9d-4798-8b87-9bf0ee808256_1024x1440.jpeg)\n\nE.A.Poe not smiling.\n\nTo Poe, the solution is that the Universe is indeed limited, so that exists a distance whence light is unable to reach us.\n\nWhat cosmologists did in the second half of the 1900s, Poe had accomplished over a century years before in the literary form.\n\nThe solution (?)\n\nNow we use some mathematical tools in order to resolve this paradox (if it is possible).\n\nOne way to solve this is to make the hypotheses that the Universe is infinite, that every star is similar to the Sun, and that the distribution of stars is uniform. In this context, we neglect the expansion of the Universe and the fact that stars are in reality distributed primarily in galaxies.\n\nIf we occupy a position in space, we can calculate the contributions of the stars around us dividing the Universe into shells of equal thickness: the inner shells will be less populated but every star will be more luminous, while less luminous stars will more and more populate the outer shells.\n\nThe result combines the fact that the volume of each shell increases with the square distance - hence the number of stars increases with the square of the distance - with the luminosity of a star that conversely diminishes with the same trend; resulting in having each shell that contributes equally to the total luminosity.\n\nIt’s easy to notice now that the total luminosity is the luminosity of a shell multiplied by the number of shells. In an infinite Universe, this number is infinite, hence the luminosity is infinite. This is obviously not the case, hence the paradox.\n\nAnother way, maybe more sophisticated, is to consider the size of the stars. This means that there is a limited number of stars that one can observe from a given point in space. With this argument, the line of sight of any given space ends up on a star’s surface with the same temperature as the Sun’s. This means that the entire sky should appear as a surface at 5000 K. This is still not the case.\n\nOne way to solve this paradox is to consider the density required to produce a night sky. It’s known (or maybe not) that the universe has a mean density of one hydrogen atom per cubic meter. The density required to have a bright sky even at dark is 10^13 (ten thousand of billions) hydrogen atoms per cubic meter. Clearly, that’s a bit too much.\n\nBut the best solution depends on the lifetime of the stars. Even in a Universe where the look-back time is of orders of billions of billions of years (and is not the case in our Universe, which is less than 15 billion years old) one eventually arrives at a “surface” where there is no star.\n\nBut overall, another answer is that the luminosity of stars is not enough to render the sky bright.\n\nTo sum up every aspect of this paradox, one could say that the reason why the sky is not bright at night is indeed different reasons.\n\nBut that is not the case (as I hope was rendered clear): it is not due to absorption effects, nor to the clustering of stars into galaxies that leaves voids, nor to the fact that the Universe is finite or expanding.\n\nIt’s simply because starlight is too weak to compete with the darkness of the sky.\n\nThat’s it. Here comes the end. Below there is some music to help you gaze in the night sky, and the bibliography (here more than ever useful to really grasp the stories behind every idea of these last four centuries). Hope to hear from you soon!\n\nhttps://adsabs.harvard.edu/full/1990IAUS..139....3H\n\nhttps://xroads.virginia.edu/~Hyper/POE/eureka.html\n\n1 \"Uber die Durchsichtigkeit des Weltraumes” (“On the Transparency of Space”), Astronomisches Jahrb. 1826, 110-121 (1825).\n\n2 History of Astronomy.\n\n3 Constitution of the Celestial Space.\n\n4 in “Sur l’extinction de la lumiere des etoiles fixes dans son passage par l’espace celeste” (On the extinction of the light of fixed stars in its passage through celestial space), 1847, St. Peterbourg.\n\n5 Lord Kelvin was quite famous for his quotes. Like this one, in “Baltimore Lectures”:\n\nI do not like the words “paradoxical phenomenom. […] There are no paradoxes in science.\n\n6 Charlier, “How an Infinite World May Be Built Up”, Arkiv Mat. Astronomi Fysik. 16, No. 22, 1.44 (1922).\n\n7 H. Bondi and T. Gold, “The Steady-State Theory of the Expanding Universe”, Monthly Notices Roy. Astron. Soc. 108, 252-270 (1948).\n\n8 F. Hoyle, “Frontiers of Astronomy” (Harper and Brothers, New York, 1955).\n\n9 Part of the “Traité de la comète qui a paru en décembre 1743, of the same author.\n\n10 this information comes from Struve, who acquired the library as part of the collection of the Pulkovo Observatory, near St. Petersburg.\n\n11 Phil. Trns. Roy. Soc.. (London), 31, 22-24 (1720) and 24-26. (1721).\n\n12 “Sidereal Message” (not to be confounded, as Kepler did, with sidereal messenger).\n\n13 see? What did I tell you?\n\n14 A. Koyré, From the Closed World to the Infinite Universe (Harper, New York, 1958), p.75.\n\n15 E.R. Harrison, The Dark Night Sky Paradox , American Journal of Physics 45, 119–124 (1977).\n\n16 https://xroads.virginia.edu/~Hyper/POE/eureka.html\n",
  "../posts/post_1.md": "<p> \n    Today I'm sharing a poem by Matsuo Basho. <br>\n    It's a haiku. <br>\n    </p>\n    いざ行かむ <br>\n    雪見 <br>\n    に <br>\n    ころぶ <br>\n    所 <br>\n    まで <br>\n    </p>\n    <p>\n    which sounds like: <br>\n    </p>\n    <p>\n    iza yukan <br>\n    yukimi ni korobu<br>\n    tokoro made <br>\n    </p>\n    <p>\n    and it means, translated in <a href = 'https://www.ucpress.edu/books/basho-2/paper', target='_blank'> English</a> by Andrew Fitzsimons: <br>\n    </p>\n    Let's get up and go <br>\n    view the snow till we come to <br>\n    wherever we fall <br>\n    </p>\n    I stumbled on this haiku while reading <a href='https://www.baldinicastoldi.it/collana/linus/' target='_blank'> Linus</a>, <br> \n    a magazine about books and graphic novels, <br> in a piece named \"Paese delle Nevi\", <br> \n    by Giovanni Piliarvu. <br>\n</p>\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_001-sound-orbits-8-this-week-in-music.md": "The name sound orbits is inspired to the weekly rotation of streaming services: this is no rotation, it’s an orbit, and we are all on that.\n\nThis week\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/4df905b1-ad69-416a-96ed-0094fea70290_1572x1048.png)\n\n:\n\nJohn Vincent III: Walking Through The Water\n\nProduced by: Blue June Music\n\nPublished by: Concord Records\n\nPublished: Mar 6, 2026\n\nSinger-songwriter from Houston, Texas, John Vincent III goes out in the fields with a hoodie or a raincoat.\n\nThis song feels like waiting for a spring rain.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b0ecb017-e677-4d32-ae9b-3558074918c9_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nJohn Vincent III on Bandcamp, Walking Through The Water on Spotify, on Apple Music, on Youtube.\n\nThe Brook & The Bluff: Can’t Figure It Out\n\nProduced by: Dualtone Music Group\n\nPublished by: Dualtone Music Group\n\nPublished: Mar 6, 2026\n\nThis band from Nashville, Tennessee is joyful and funny. This song is a breather.\n\nDon’t come looking for me, I don’t want to be found.\n\nThe song is part of of the LP Werewolf , published March 6, 2026.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ab43cd77-8498-4b8c-a828-918ae77f6438_1000x1000.webp)\n\nThe Brook & The Bluff on Bandcamp, Can’t Figure It Out on Spotify, on Apple Music, on Youtube.\n\nDelayed Orbit: a song/record/soundtrack not published this week, and that I encountered in these days.\n\nThis week, more than just one song.\n\nJasmine Myra: Reflections\n\nProduced by: Gondwana Records\n\nPublished by: Gondwana Records\n\nPublished: Feb 27, 2026\n\nThe composer from Leeds, UK, performs a gentle introduction to her forthcoming album. Feels like a magic realm, then reality catches up.\n\nThe song is part of of the LP Where Lights Settles , to be published May 15, 2026.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6174a479-2bfb-4a13-94ea-891e23b6f6b1_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nJasmine Myra on Bandcamp, Reflections on Spotify, on Apple Music, on Youtube.\n\nCatching Flies: When It’s Late\n\nProduced by: Indigo Soul\n\nPublished by: Indigo Soul\n\nPublished: Feb 18, 2026\n\nThis producer under the pseudonym Catching Flies brings energy to the dancefloor, a place I never went to.\n\nThe song is part of the LP Beat & Pieces II, to be released on March 27, 2026.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/75015ca7-4eb0-40a9-8a58-e7f17d9b567d_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nCatching Flies on Bandcamp, When It’s Late on Spotify, on Apple Music, on Youtube.\n\nSee you next time.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_002-sound-orbits-7-this-week-in-music.md": "The name sound orbits is inspired to the weekly rotation of streaming services: this is no rotation, it’s an orbit, and we are all on that.\n\nThis week:\n\nÓlafur Arnalds: Echoes - Sunrise Session III\n\nProduced by: Ólafur Arnalds\n\nPublished by: Universal\n\nPublished: Feb 27, 2026\n\nNothing to say here, the last work of Icelandic composer Ólafur Arnalds together with some friends during the winter solstice. The sun rises.\n\nThe song is part of of the LP Sunrise Session III , published February 27, 2026.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/95f15844-b01d-48b5-9dee-5862dcb1895b_1172x1178.png)\n\nÓlafur Arnalds on Bandcamp, Echoes - Sunrise Session III on Spotify, on Apple Music, on Youtube.\n\nVoxtrot: Another Fire\n\nProduced by: Voxtrot\n\nPublished by: Voxtrot\n\nPublished: Feb 27, 2026\n\nFrom the rock band based in Austin, Texas: 11 new songs. Another Fire: the first one, defining the album, in a simple life .\n\nThe song is part of of the LP Dreamers in Exile , published February 27, 2026.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6f9beafb-6a8c-4990-b789-7d694a25e71e_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nVoxtrot on Bandcamp, Another Fire on Spotify, on Apple Music, on Youtube.\n\nThe Guest List : Something Real\n\nProduced by: Artist Theory\n\nPublished by: Artist Theory\n\nPublished: February, 27 2025\n\nThis band from Manchester (but don’t call them a Manchester band) published a new song as a single, and it’s all about a look in your eyes .\n\nThe Guest List on the web, Sold Out on Spotify, on Apple Music, on Youtube.\n\nSee you next time.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_003-sound-orbits-6-this-week-in-music.md": "The name sound orbits is inspired to the weekly rotation of streaming services: this is no rotation, it’s an orbit, and we are all on that.\n\nThis week:\n\nGodblesscomputers: Bassa Marea\n\nProduced by: Délicieuse Records\n\nPublished by: Délicieuse Records\n\nPublished: Feb 13, 2026\n\nItalian producer Lorenzo Nada, now based in Berlin, records this album blending a beach, a forest, and an art exhibition.\n\nThe song is part of of the LP Dance Until Dawn , published February 13, 2026.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/8167aa02-a6ea-43c7-887c-8c67de7c2612_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nGodblesscomputers on Bandcamp, Bassa Marea on Spotify, on Apple Music, on Youtube.\n\nAmir Bresler: Lesoto (feat. Rejoicer)\n\nProduced by: Raw Tapes Records\n\nPublished by: Raw Tapes Records\n\nPublished: February 13, 2026\n\nDrummer from Tel Aviv, Amir Bresler releases a new LP and this song has a summer-y vibe, even in the cold of February.\n\nThe song is part of the records See What Happens, published February 13, 2026.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d1b0fc3a-0a4c-4115-aba0-03fc9e3588a4_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nAmir Bresler on Bandcamp, Lesoto on Spotify, on Apple Music.\n\nvegas water taxi: new irish boyfriend\n\nProduced by: PNKSLM Recordings\n\nPublished by: PNKSLM Recordings\n\nPublished: February 6, 2026\n\nLondon based band, vegas water taxi release this album and some needed sadness.\n\nThe song is part of the LP long time caller, first time listener , published February 6, 2026.\n\nvegas water taxi on Bandcamp, on Spotify, on Apple Music, on Youtube.\n\nDelayed Orbit: a song/record/soundtrack not published this week, and that I encountered in these days.\n\nGracie Abrams: Sold Out (feat. Bon Iver & Aaron Dessner)\n\nProduced by: Gracie Abrams, Aaron Dessner, Justin Vernon\n\nPublished by: Gracie Abrams, Aaron Dessner, Justin Vernon\n\nPublished: December 22, 2025\n\nThis song was made “in the wake of a school shooting”. The three artists support Everytown , an organization dedicated to ending gun violence in America.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5b0660e2-fbdf-4c9e-a0dc-8a4642b5e550_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nGracie Abrams on Bandcamp, Sold Out on Bandcamp.\n\nSold Out is not Apple Music.\n\nSold Out is not on Spotify.\n\nSold Out is not on Youtube.\n\nSee you next time.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_004-sound-orbits-5-this-week-in-music.md": "The name sound orbits is inspired to the weekly rotation of streaming services: this is no rotation, it’s an orbit, and we are all on that.\n\nThis week:\n\nBleachers: you and forever\n\nProduced by: Dirty Hit\n\nPublished by: Dirty Hit\n\nPublished: Feb 11, 2026\n\nJack Antonoff and the band - aka Bleachers - come back for another anthem of pop-rock. This time, it’s a compliment.\n\nThe song is part of of the LP everyone for ten minutes , to be published May 22, 2026.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/fb127a8b-d497-4a9c-9bf3-4837fdc38962_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nBleachers on Bandcamp, you and forever on Spotify, on Apple Music, on Youtube.\n\nHere the piece on Bleachers’ live LP:\n\nRunnner: Branch bent\n\nProduced by: Rose Garden\n\nPublished by: Rose Garden\n\nPublished: Feb 11, 2026\n\nNoah Weinman from Los Angeles, California comes back with a new song, heartbroken as his previous ones.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b915053a-9138-4e60-8359-26cf58a611b6_1000x1000.png)\n\nRunnner on Bandcamp, Branch bent on Spotify, on Apple Music, on Youtube.\n\nLast Dinosaurs: Kebabs\n\nProduced by: LOS DINOS PTY LTD\n\nPublished by: Nettwerk Music Group\n\nPublished: Feb 13, 2026\n\nThis band from Brisbane, Australia comes back with an album named after Wellness. Ten years later, it’s Wellnxss. Kebabs is almost psychedelic - it’s been a long night .\n\nThe song is part of the EP Wellnxss , published February 13, 2026.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a291f05d-8d16-4789-9355-61d083130adf_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nLast Dinosaurs on Bandcamp, Kebabs on Spotify, on Apple Music, on Youtube.\n\nDelayed Orbit: a song/record/soundtrack not published this week, and that I encountered in these days.\n\nJoshua Burnside: Something Else\n\nProduced by: Nettwerk Music Group\n\nPublished by: Nettwerk Music Group\n\nPublished: Jan 2, 2026\n\nFolk artist from Belfast, UK, Joshua Burnside catches you off guard: starts delicately, then it hits you at the end of the X-files .\n\nThe song is part of the EP It’s Not Going To Be Okay , to be published March 20, 2026.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/054d22bd-96e8-476f-9a58-2b705ec7a055_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nJoshua Burnside on Bandcamp, Something Else on Spotify, on Apple Music, on Youtube.\n\nSee you next time.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_005-sound-orbits-4-this-week-in-music.md": "The name sound orbits is inspired to the weekly rotation of streaming services: this is no rotation, it’s an orbit, and we are all on that.\n\nThis week:\n\nDua Saleh: The Flood (feat. Bon Iver)\n\nProduced by: Dua Saleh\n\nPublished by: Ghostly International\n\nPublished: Feb 3, 2026\n\nSudanese-American artist Dua Saleh features Bon Iver in their new project.\n\nI had not listened to any songs from the former, but I evidently recognize the latter.\n\nFresh water coming all at once: a flood.\n\nThe song is part of of the LP Of Earth & Wires , to be published May 15, 2026.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/46e3dcc0-77f2-4e05-aeed-ee127807303e_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nDua Saleh on Bandcamp, Bon Iver on Bandcamp, The Flood on Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nHere the piece on Bon Iver’s last LP:\n\nIron & Wine: Roses\n\nProduced by: Sub Pop Records\n\nPublished by: Sub Pop Records\n\nPublished: Feb 5, 2026\n\nSamuel Ervin Beam prints another page of his book of full-of-words songs, and the new cover is a story all by itself.\n\nThe song is part of the LP Hen’s Teeth , to be published February 27, 2026.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/da8a131b-d56a-4e10-b924-c67dc106ba01_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nIron & Wine on Bandcamp, Roses on Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nHere the piece on another song by Iron & Wine:\n\nYoung The Giant: Different Kind of Love\n\nProduced by: Jungle Youth Records\n\nPublished by: Concord\n\nPublished: Feb 6, 2026\n\nThe band from Irvine, California are preparing for a great year.\n\nThis song is solid alt-rock. Truly.\n\nThe song is part of the EP Victory Garden , to be published May 1, 2026.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/bbac7ee5-bc4d-4458-a478-8247267e4189_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nYoung The Giant on Bandcamp, Different Kind of Love on Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nDelayed Orbit: a song/record/soundtrack not published this week, and that I encountered in these days.\n\nJames Blake: Death of Love\n\nProduced by: Good Boy Records\n\nPublished by: Good Boy Records\n\nPublished: Jan 22, 2026\n\nThe artist from England (now in Los Angeles) is still embedded in spikes of sounds, surrounding him like in the cover photo of the new album.\n\nHis art on a pike: these are trying times .\n\nThe song is part of the LP Trying Times , to be published March 13, 2026.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2b229203-9326-43d4-93ba-c1cffafbc61e_1200x1200.webp)\n\nJames Blake on the web, Death of Love on Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nFrom James Blake, you can read this episode:\n\nSee you next time.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_006-sound-orbits-3-this-week-in-music.md": "The name sound orbits is inspired to the weekly rotation of streaming services: this is no rotation, it’s an orbit, and we are all on that.\n\nThis week:\n\nTom Misch: Sisters With Me\n\nProduced by: Beyond The Groove\n\nPublished by: AWAL Recordings Ltd\n\nPublished: Jan 28, 2026\n\nYoung English musician Tom Misch gives a funky tour of what to expect from the new record, out in a couple of months.\n\nThe song is part of of the LP Full Circle , to be published March 27, 2026.\n\nThe artist on Bandcamp, the song on Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nNoah Kahan: The Great Divide\n\nProduced by: Mercury Records\n\nPublished by: UMG Recordings, Inc.\n\nPublished: Jan 30, 2026\n\nAmerican songwriter is heart-broken in this new song:\n\nthat’s the price you pay for this kind of heartfelt songs.\n\nThe song is part of the LP The Great Divide , to be published April 24, 2026.\n\nThe artist’s website, the song on Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nThe Man The Myth The Meatslab: (1000(1)000): one in a million\n\nProduced by: The Man The Myth The Meatslab\n\nPublished by: Mutual Friends\n\nPublished: Jan 30, 2026\n\nThis folk project created by Jamie Clarke grows once more, and the chances he listened to Bon Iver are not one in a million - he admits Bon Iver is an inspiration, so it’s all good.\n\nThe song is part of the EP Until The Comet Came , published January 30, 2026.\n\nThe artist’s website, the record on Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nJosé Gonzàlez: Against The Dying Of The Light\n\nProduced by: Imperial Recordings\n\nPublished by: City Slang\n\nPublished: Jan 23, 2026\n\nSwedish songwriter and guitarist José Gabriel González conveys a new stunning trait to its canvas, following in the steps of its previous records.\n\nThe song is part of the LP Against The Dying Of The Light , to be published March 27, 2026.\n\nThe record on Bandcamp, Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nDelayed Orbit: a song/record/soundtrack not published this week, and that I encountered in these days.\n\nHania Rani : Sentimental Value\n\nProduced by: Gondwana Records\n\nPublished by: Gondwana Records\n\nPublished: Jan 9, 2026\n\nComposer from Poland, Hania Rani creates a garden of sound for the house that has such a central part in the film.\n\nThe soundtrack on Bandcamp, Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nFrom the same record label, you can read this episode:\n\nSee you next time.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_007-sound-orbits-2-this-week-in-music.md": "The name sound orbits is inspired to the weekly rotation of streaming services: this is no rotation, it’s an orbit, and we are all on that.\n\nThis week:\n\nMaster Peace : Fuck It Up (with Declan McKenna)\n\nProduced by: Big Family Music\n\nPublished by: Stem\n\nPublished: Jan 16, 2026\n\nPeace Okienze, real name of Master Peace, is set out to return to the British public with a few new energetic songs.\n\n“ Be happy, don’t worry, that’s a lie and I know it is ”.\n\nThe song is part of of the self-titled EP, published January 16, 2026.\n\nThe artist’s website, the song on Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nThe Milk Carton Kids : A Friend Like You\n\nProduced by: Big Family Music\n\nPublished by: Stem\n\nPublished: Jan 16, 2026\n\nThis folk duo from California composed of singer-guitarists Kenneth Pattengale and Joey Ryan comes back after three years with new lyrics and the same soothing and delicate sounds.\n\nThe song is part of the LP Lost Cause Lover Fool , to be published April 24, 2026.\n\nThe band on Bandcamp, the song on Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nThe Paper Kites: If You Go There, I Hope You Find It\n\nProduced by: The Paper Kites\n\nPublished by: Nettwerk Music Group\n\nPublished: Jan 23, 2026\n\nThis folk band from Australia (composed of David Powys, Sam Bentley, Sam Rasmussen, Christina Lacy, Josh Bentley) enters the new year with a new record, but the feelings are unaltered: the kites are made of cozy, soft wool.\n\nThe band’s website, the record on Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nChristian Löffler: Until We Meet Again\n\nProduced by: Ki Records\n\nPublished by: Ki Records\n\nPublished: Jan 23, 2026\n\nGerman musician Christian Löffler comes back with another touching soundscape.\n\nEvery sound creates vibrations that build up to embrace your body.\n\nOn speakers, on headphones: just listen to it while doing nothing.\n\nThe record on Bandcamp, Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nHere the review on another song by Löffler, Myiami.\n\nEdwin Raphael : First Time On Earth\n\nProduced by: Favourite Library\n\nPublished by: Favourite Library\n\nPublished: Jan 20, 2026\n\nEdwin Raphael, Indian musician based in Toronto, brings synthesis and refrains-that-make-your-head-move to the turntable.\n\nThe song is part of the self-titled EP, published April 20, 2026.\n\nThe band on Bandcamp, the song on Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nSee you next time.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_008-sound-orbits-1-this-week-in-music.md": "This newsletter, as you probably know, is part of a three publications here on Substack - here and here the others.\n\nWe’ll see what the future brings: let’s get back to the newsletter, for the first episode of 2026.\n\nsound orbits is a new section of this newsletter: every week (hopefully) there will be a new episode of this newsletter with the music published that particular week.\n\nThere is so much music coming out these days, one gets humbled by the amount there is and tends to go back to their usual listenings.\n\nWhich is fine, except one could miss some good stuff.\n\nThe name sound orbits is inspired to the weekly rotation of streaming services: this is no rotation, it’s an orbit, and we are all on that.\n\nThis week a deluxe edition, to cover also the first days of the year.\n\nLouis Matute : Dolce Vita\n\nProduced by: Association Encontro\n\nLabel - Naïve Believe\n\nPublished: Jan 9, 2026\n\nA guitarist from Geneva, Switzerland, Louis Matute produces Dolce Vita with many suggestions: among them, his family history of exile from Honduras.\n\nContemporary Jazz and a feeling of music free of borders.\n\nThe record on Bandcamp, Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nMidori Hirano : Rainwalk\n\nProduced by: Thrill Jockey Music\n\nPublished by: Erased Tapes Music\n\nPublished: Jan 14, 2026\n\nA composer and pianist born in Kyoto and based in Berlin, Midori Hirano created ethereal soundscapes, and synthesises abstract music in real form.\n\nThe song anticipates the record Otonoma , out February 20, 2026.\n\nThe record on Bandcamp, Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nÁsgeir : Against the Current - EP\n\nProduced by: one little independent records\n\nPublished by: one little independent records\n\nPublished: Jan 14, 2026\n\nSinger-songwriter from Iceland, Ásgeir publishes this EP to warm your heart in this ice-cold Europe.\n\nThe EP anticipates the full LP Julia , out February 13, 2026.\n\nThe record on Bandcamp, Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nDaughter : Not Enough\n\nProduced by: 4AD.\n\nPublished by: 4AD.\n\nPublished: Jan 15, 2026\n\nBand of three from London, Daughter publishes the single Not Enough , and Elena Tonra still has one of the most soothing voices in alternative/indie/folk music.\n\nYou’ll get sad by listening to it, and you’ll be lulled by it.\n\nThe band on Bandcamp, the songs on Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nYellow Days : I Cannot Believe in Tomorrow\n\nProduced by: Independent Co.\n\nPublished by: Independent Co.\n\nPublished: Jan 16, 2026\n\nSinger-songwriter from Haslemere, England, Yellow Days drops three songs to remind us of his incredible voice.\n\nThe EP anticipates the full LP Rock And A Hard Place , out February 13, 2026.\n\nThe artist on Bandcamp, the songs on Spotify, Apple Music, Youtube.\n\nSee you next time.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_009-my-favourite-albums-of-2025.md": "Disclaimer: Space of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the page by clicking here.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/366e219c-9eca-447e-ab62-372149262f17_1080x1350.png)\n\nIn this episode, a list of albums I found and listened to in 2025.\n\nIt does not contain exclusively albums published this year, much like the same thing I did for my favourite songs of 2025.\n\nFor every album, there will be a one-line comment that (hopefully) will make you listen to that song.\n\nEnjoy!\n\nFirst, some albums that you probably already know, if you follow this newsletter.\n\n- SABLE, fABLE, by Bon Iver. Listen it here. Read it here.\n\n- A Study of Losses, by Beirut. Listen it here. Read it here.\n\n- Singles, by Future Islands. Listen it here. Read it here.\n\nNext, some \"new\" records (at least for me)!\n\n(They are not presented in any particular order.)\n\nCaptured Spirits,\n\nby Mammal Hands\n\n(published in 2020 with Gondwana Records).\n\nthis record will grow on you. it will literally capture your spirit .\n\nSongs of the Earth (Instrumentals),\n\nby David Longstreth / Dirty Projectors / s t a r g a z e\n\n(published in 2025 by David Longstreth with Transgressive Records).\n\na soundtrack for our planet. I hope it will not become a eulogy soon.\n\nRiver Calls,\n\nby Message to Bears\n\n(published in 2025 by Lost Birds).\n\na hidden gem. every listening session is a warm embrace.\n\nFolk Traffic,\n\nby Pietro Paris ( with Andrea Beninati, Ruggero Fornari & Francesco Panconesi)\n\n(published in 2025 by Encore Music).\n\nit started my jazz-era in this 2025. sensational.\n\nPhantom Brickworks,\n\nby Bibio\n\n(published in 2024 by Warp Records).\n\nlistening to this record is trespassing a wall in reality. in the end you come back transformed.\n\nLive Vol. 1,\n\nby Parcels\n\n(published in 2020 by Kitsuné Musique, with Because Music).\n\na live studio album with great energy, a fine record.\n\nThis Christmas, you can support Space of Sound with a special offer, for just 1.5€/month (that's under 2 USD per month).\n\nGet 50% off for 1 year\n\nThanks!\n\nWhatever the Weather II,\n\nby Whatever the Weather\n\n(published in 2025 by Ghostly International).\n\na thermometer for your soul. you will find something floating in the air.\n\nATOMOS VII,\n\nby A Winged Victory For The Sullen & Adam Wiltzie\n\n(published in 2023 by Artificial Pinearch Manufacturing).\n\ndrone music, it will bring you a sudden, discomfortable peace.\n\nPeople Watching,\n\nby Sam Fender\n\n(published in 2025 by Sam Fender, with Polydor Records).\n\nmaybe a hit? anyway, he does not feel like coming from this age - in a good sense.\n\nMusic For a Cosmic Garden,\n\nby Takashi Kokubo & Andrea Esperti\n\n(published in 2023 by WRWTFWW).\n\nhad something in mind for this, then I read the title tracks again: wonderful.\n\nUSA,\n\nby Petey USA\n\n(published in 2023 by Capitol Records, with Crow Island, and UMG Recordings).\n\na solid record which contains some pretty cool songs. liminal is a beautiful word.\n\nThe Disintegration Loops,\n\nby William Basinski\n\n(published in 2002 by Temporary Residence).\n\nit will shred you to pieces. is each and single one of us nothing but temporary?\n\nThis Christmas, you can support Space of Sound with a special offer, for just 1.5€/month (that’s under 2 USD per month).\n\nGet 50% off for 1 year\n\nThanks!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_010-my-favourite-songs-of-2025.md": "Disclaimer: Space of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the page by clicking here.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/07fd819b-8f56-4855-b7ec-42c402844de8_1080x1350.png)\n\nIn this episode, a list of songs I found and listened to in 2025.\n\nIt does not contain exclusively songs published in this year.\n\nFor every song, there will be a one-line comment that (hopefully) will make you listen to that song.\n\nEnjoy!\n\nFirst, some songs that you probably already know, if you follow this newsletter.\n\n- There’s a Rhythm, by Bon Iver. Listen it here. Read it here.\n\n- Forest Encyclopedia, by Beirut. Listen it here. Read it here.\n\n- Sun in the Morning, by Future Islands. Listen it here. Read it here.\n\n- About Today, by The National. Listen it here. Read it here.\n\n- Fourth of July, by Sufjan Stevens. Listen it here. Read it here.\n\nNext, some \"new\" songs (at least for me)!\n\nNews from Verona , by Portico Quartet\n\n(track #1 of Knee-Deep in the North Sea , published in 2007 with Real World Productions).\n\nIt’s a warm, mesmerising blanket of sounds.\n\nMy Heart is Buried in Venice , by Ricky Montgomery\n\n(track #7 of Montgomery Ricky , published in 2016 with Warner Music).\n\nIt’s an open-hearted song on nostalgia towards things that haven’t happened yet.\n\nKandaiki , by Mammal Hands\n\n(track #3 of Animalia , published in 2014 with Gondwana Records).\n\nJust put this song on and follow wherever it’ll lead you.\n\nKin , by Tourist\n\n(track #9 of Wild , published in 2019 with Monday Records).\n\nIt leads you nowhere, entertaining you all the while.\n\nToo Many Birds , by Bill Callahan\n\n(track #5 of Sometimes I Wish We Were an Eagle , published in 2009 with Drag City Records).\n\nProbably Americana, surely you’ll picture a clear sky at some point during the song.\n\nAlbert Ross (Acoustic Version) , by Wild Pink\n\n(single published in 2017 with Tiny Engines).\n\nIndie song, little song, delicate song. What songs in the tiniest form should be.\n\nQuietest Town in England , by Tom Rosenthal\n\n(track #5 of Zz-Sides , published in 2023 with Tinpot Records).\n\nOne of the most beautiful lullabies you’ll hear.\n\nThis Christmas, you can support Space of Sound with a special offer, for just 1.5€/month (that's under 2 USD per month).\n\nGet 50% off for 1 year\n\nThanks!\n\nwe fell in love in october , by girl in red\n\n(single published in 2018 with AWAL Recordings).\n\nA song from another room is playing. It probably is this very one.\n\nEarth (Rey&Kjavik remix) , by Mogli\n\n(single published in 2021 with Studio Ewig).\n\nWater as the ocean, this song as the natural world.\n\nGreen Green Grass of Tunnel , by múm\n\n(track #2 of Finally We Are No One , published in 2002 with FATCAT RECORDS).\n\nAn electronic soundscape for the elves. Also for humans.\n\nAnother Song Called Tonight , by Fort Atlantic\n\n(single published in 2021 with Hot Garbage Music).\n\nDrive while this song is playing, it’ll make something to you.\n\nMt. Washington , by Local Natives\n\n(single #9 of Hummingbird , published in 2013 with Infectious Music).\n\nDrive while this song is playing, it’ll make something to you.\n\nSit Around the Fire , by Jon Hopkins (with Ram Dass, East Forest )\n\n(single #9 of Music For Psychedelic Therapy , published in 2021 with Domino Recording).\n\nSheer meditation, it heals your mind.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_011-live-sound-4-i-cani-teatro-della-concordia-venaria.md": "# live sound #4: i cani @ Teatro della Concordia - Venaria\n\nDisclaimer: Space of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the page by clicking here.\n\nSpace of Sound è anche su Instagram. Puoi raggiungerlo seguendo questo link.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!1J4o!,w_640,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/__ss-rehost__IG-meta-DRudYXhjByS.jpg)\n\nSpace of Sound è anche su Spotify e Apple Music con una playlist.\n\ni cani sono Niccolò Contessa , ma Niccolò Contessa non è stato solo i cani .\n\n\"Vedi Niccolò, la gente non è il mestiere che fa\".\n\nil concerto di ieri (al Teatro della Concordia di Venaria) è l’inizio e la fine - non finirà , finirà - del concetto degli artisti generazionali.\n\ni cani lo sono stati, generazionali.\n\nforse quella generazione è finita.\n\nchi è il colpevole? il tempo?\n\nNiccolò Contessa inizia il concerto con \" io \": forse c’è qualcosa sotto.\n\nsempre fotografati, lui che girava con una busta di carta in testa.\n\ncosa è diventato il rito del concerto dell’artista nascosto ?\n\nuna seduta fotografica per immortalarlo.\n\nqualcuno urla “ah ma allora esiste davvero!”.\n\na un certo punto dal vocoder esce una voce, mi dico “avrà scoperto Bon Iver ”, poi lo lascia stare e anch’io lascio stare.\n\naltre magie altri misteri altri dubbi questioni domande:\n\nil fuoco brucia e resta carbone .\n\nquesta esperienza viene raccontata come involuta\n\nsi fa mitologia ma non è chissà cosa;\n\nnon è questo il punto non importa:\n\nrisuonare per qualcosa io non credo sia un caso\n\nla verità forse non c’è\n\nforse è inesistente inventata dimenticata\n\neppure è lì, in ogni nuova esperienza, nascosta in piena vista.\n\nritornano le coppie, non erano riuscite a dividersi,\n\nsi erano lasciate e poi si cercavano, ma non esistono più i romantici,\n\nanche i pariolini di diciott’anni ora sarebbero più che trentenni.\n\nnessuna paura, qui si balla\n\nl’unica nostalgia che ( non ) ho .\n\nuna volta Vasco Brondi parlava con (la ragazza di) qualcuno,\n\nora Lucio Corsi (s)parla da solo:\n\ndiventiamo atomi anche metaforicamente.\n\nl’AI avanza, Internet è morto, chi usa più Google ?\n\nnon serve più a nulla supplicare di non essere ricercato .\n\nc’erano altre canzoni.\n\nc’era un’ultima canzone,\n\nma Niccolò Contessa ha chiesto che non si registrasse più nulla,\n\nper lasciarsi guardandosi e riconoscendosi.\n\ntanto era una cosa stupida .\n\ntutti a registrare tutto: chissà quanto dovremo aspettare per sentirlo di nuovo dal vivo. potrebbe anche finirla qua,\n\nle generazioni passano,\n\nchi lo ascoltava dall’inizio ha cambiato vita.\n\ncon nostalgie, rimorsi, rimpianti, più per cose che non sarebbero mai potute accadere che per qualcosa di realizzabile. ma ho un groppo in gola, e le mani in tasca al freddo.\n\nQuesto dicembre, puoi supportare Space of Sound con una offerta speciale, che equivale a 1.5€/mese.\n\nGrazie!\n\nInoltre, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_012-space-sound-23-we-had-everything-but-time-by-the-field-index.md": "# space sound #23: We Had Everything But Time, by The Field Index\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!1YPm!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/53d6a0f9-ef24-4200-94d7-6cd0b8b92d0e_1572x1048.png)\n\nWe Had Everything But Time , the new EP by Michael Chau ’s new project The Field Index, has come out on November 14th, 2025.\n\nWe already talked about the single released last month, and in that occasion I promised to deliver some thoughts on the EP. Here they are.\n\nhere the playlist on Apple Music.\n\nThe record starts with Catch , which reminds me of something coming from Beach House.\n\nThe drums are entertaining, flowing through during the song, along with a line of bass, and I’m already there, but anyway \" take me with you when you disappear ”.\n\nTrouble in Mind is a silhouette, like the first word of the song itself states. It is a recurring theme for me with this record, you feel like waves, the ambience (we’ll return to that with the last song) Chau creates embodies you, it gets to know you and then it transcends into something that could have come from a distant star, reaching on to you because you’ve been chosen.\n\nAnd that’s just by listening one record, so you have to give them that.\n\nThe song fades, and another starts playing.\n\nCannibals is a song about “ something else ”, and the lyrics make their way through the music, the music is like heavy curtains and Chau’s voice appears to come behind them. The music has a rhythm that the lyrics can’t sustain, and at some point the lyrics end and all you’re left with is a drapery of sound, and you can’t peek through the fabric.\n\nAt that point, the song ends.\n\nChau comes from ambient and soundscape music, and My Inner Goth Girl in the first second gives you that; then, it transforms into 80s music in the way someone actually living in the 2020s would make it: you get the synths, and the drums, and the chords, in this order, plus a delicate voice, calling you to answer to one liminal phone call - in this times of social networks on a phone that does not ring anymore - and you’re all set.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Ts3s!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/fda7d654-0278-41c0-a5aa-7dcecd68aedb_1036x1036.png)\n\nPress photo of Michael Chau. Credits here.\n\nNever “ surrender to the emptiness ”, because this single is full of surprised: it seems an undoing, a stripping of clothes to reveal who you really are after a run, to save yourself or maybe just to sweat a bit.\n\nThis November, you can support Space of Sound for a special offer, equivalent to 1.5€ (under 2 USD) per month.\n\nThank you!\n\nNonetheless, “ The past is done, release the harm / we made it out alive ”, and this is all it matters. The songs builds on itself, it grows and becomes larger, the instruments make waves, they create an ocean of sound, Chau’s voice surfs on it, it reaches you from multiple places, it makes you yearn for more.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!QsYk!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d738ea60-5252-4f29-b55f-f16a818a2193_2500x2500.jpeg)\n\nI said of My Inner Goth Girl that it is a good song if you like night calls, or even that bright part of the sunset just before sun goes off in the west.\n\nIt seems that is the mood of the whole record, and in cold November days it create an atmosphere you can feel, you can touch with your hands and breath in with every inhale.\n\nIf we’d listen to it, we ’d have everything - including time .\n\nMy Inner Goth Girl on Spotify.\n\nMy Inner Goth Girl on Apple Music.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_013-live-sound-3-m-m-hiroshima-mon-amour-torino.md": "# live sound #3: MÚM @ Hiroshima Mon Amour - Torino\n\nDisclaimer: Space of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the page by clicking here.\n\nSpace of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the profile following this link.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!6lPd!,w_640,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/__ss-rehost__IG-meta-DRAcKz5jHLD.jpg)\n\nI went to Iceland a few months ago, and the experience was both transcending and deeply rooted in nature. I’m constantly thinking back to those moments, and frequently picturing the places I’ve been, with the soundtrack of the music we listened to while driving - many of those songs are in this newsletter, by the way.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!zv1A!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b02420fc-759a-4cb0-b849-114977e8d9c9_4032x3024.heic)\n\nmúm on stage @ Hiroshima Mon Amour, Torino (November 12, 2025).\n\nI’m not the only one to think that the performance by múm , Icelandic folk-rock band yesterday in concert in Turin, was the bridge that allowed us to go back to those moments not just picturing images in our minds, but also listening to otherworldly sounds.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!1r7v!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/46ed9569-eb4f-484d-98cd-525cd1761b20_3024x4032.heic)\n\nThe opening act was performed by Bjorn Daniel, an Iceland artist now living in Turin. A raw, intimate performance, and a passionate one, because Daniel was opening for one of his adolescence’s dream bands. Hiroshima Mon Amour, Torino (November 12, 2025).\n\nLet me explain.\n\nThis November, you can support Space of Sound for a special offer, equivalent to 1.5€ (under 2 USD) per month.\n\nThank you!\n\nMusic can be encoded and decoded, like a message. And it is a message, which contains information about the sender, and - hopefully - should also contain some message for the receiver.\n\nmúm perform in a way that openly labels them as something different from bands from other places: like Sigur Rós, to say of another Icelandic band, you hear there is a different background.\n\nmúm sing and play like a delicate ensemble, only to explode in a shoegaze-like conundrum of sounds: one moment the stillness of a glacier, the next lava roars and a mountain erupts.\n\nThe songs are long exposure photos, they stay on the retina of your ears, they impress on your listenings.\n\nThey are both lullabies and marches, both quiet and explosive.\n\nFire and ice, like the Iceland they come from.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!0mHo!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/00c0090a-6c6d-493f-a6c2-3bc57dfb8e37_4032x3024.heic)\n\nmúm on stage at the end of the concert @ Hiroshima Mon Amour, Torino (November 12, 2025).\n\nBelow, my favourite song by múm, Green Green Grass of Tunnel .\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_014-live-sound-2-mammal-hands-jazzmi.md": "# live sound #2: Mammal Hands @ JAZZMI\n\nDisclaimer: Space of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the page by clicking here.\n\nSpace of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the profile following this link.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!vYFl!,w_640,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/__ss-rehost__IG-meta-DQtv6I6jDZD.jpg)\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!hnZK!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/276dbcea-c2ad-4c19-99f5-79219b9775c0_1080x1350.png)\n\nGetting to know a band one day and attending their concert eight days later: that’s what happened to me with Mammal Hands , a jazz group based in London and formed in Norwich in 2012, with five albums with Gondwana Records.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!YwWX!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/bf9d478f-fb32-4316-9199-f5f8d967d731_3024x4032.heic)\n\nthe stage for Mammal Hands @ JAZZMI, Nov 5, 2025 (Triennale Milano, Milan)\n\nThis November, you can support Space of Sound for a special offer, equivalent to 1.5€ (under 2 USD) per month.\n\nThank you!\n\nIn the last week I had listened to all the songs, created a playlist with all the tracks from the first album to the last, and had my favorite.\n\nFrom the moment they stepped on stage, the atmosphere became mystical and it felt like being in a time outside of time, the atmosphere that the three musicians created built a spiral of sounds that carried you away and drew you in. Both at the same time, music is a special thing.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Q4GN!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/10b83648-c47d-43e5-b00a-9c6b753c29fe_3024x4032.heic)\n\nMammal Hands on stage @ JAZZMI, Nov 5, 2025 (Triennale Milano, Milan)\n\nIt felt like breathing with them, keeping time, jumping hunched over the piano.\n\nI don’t know much about jazz - actually, I don’t know much about music in the technical sense, I talk about it insofar as it seems to convey something to me and when that happens I like to share it - but from what I saw, from what I heard!, there’s a formidable technique.\n\nThe songs are complex structures, rhythmic, coherent and fractal: a marvel for the ears.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!bpjD!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ecb8f892-8499-46ff-a4fe-4fcd9528d374_4032x3024.heic)\n\nMammal Hands members at the end of the concert @ JAZZMI, Nov 5, 2025 (Triennale Milano, Milan)\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Uhcv!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/cb55cf46-3265-4382-99d0-71f0c789805c_4032x3024.heic)\n\nMammal Hands members at the end of the concert @ JAZZMI, Nov 5, 2025 (Triennale Milano, Milan)\n\nAt the end of the concert, lasting just under an hour and a half, I bought a vinyl with my favorite song by the group, and with the three - Nick Smart , Jordan Smart , and Rob Turner - I chatted a bit, just long enough to get the cover signed, and compliment them on the spectacular concert.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!IABc!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2e5237ce-711b-4fd0-9455-1e3ba99f321d_4032x3024.heic)\n\nmy copy of Captured Spirits vinyl, composed by Mammal Hands with Gondwana Records.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!O_Bh!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/91e3c75e-88c1-47d1-bbbd-380064fda587_4032x3024.heic)\n\nmy copy of Captured Spirits vinyl, composed by Mammal Hands with Gondwana Records.\n\nBelow, my favourite song by Mammal Hands, Riddle .\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_015-space-sound-22-2-costellazioni-by-le-luci-della-centrale-elettrica.md": "# space sound #22.2: Costellazioni, by Le Luci della Centrale Elettrica\n\nDisclaimer #1: this piece is in English. The Italian version is here.\n\nDisclaimer #2: Space of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the page by clicking here.\n\nSpace of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the profile following this link.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!bssC!,w_640,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/__ss-rehost__IG-meta-DQRRwV8DCsC.jpg)\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!rsSu!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/137c4899-2ae4-46a1-9f2c-34d89810c400_1080x1350.png)\n\nIt is not easy to talk about this record, and at the same time it’s all so easy. It’s talking about something you recognize, but is nonetheless foreign to you. It’s not yours, but it’s in every place of your memory; you’ve listened to it so much that you feel a part of you is also defined in relation to it. It’s the record you return to, that you leave before departing, that you find again when you return, from which you distance yourself when you distance yourself from everything. It contains everything and all the rest it doesn’t yet contain, it is the haven of what you have lived that makes room for what you have not yet experienced. It contains places where you have already been but which you visit to connect them to this sound map.\n\nSound constellation .\n\nThe songs within it are stars, which create constellations if you look at them from a specific point - Earth, life: they are not necessarily there to form those symbols, but your perspective gives you those meanings.\n\nYou create them, the artist creates them, they are different, they are the same.\n\nLe Luci della Centrale Elettrica is Vasco Brondi, and it was his project from 2007 to 2019; now he continues to tell stories producing music with his own name, after having abandoned the name of the project with a farewell concert tour - even though every now and then he lights one up in individual concerts, and these small events remain there to form a memory.\n\nTime constellation .\n\nCostellazioni was published in 2014 with the label La Tempesta Dischi .\n\ndammi solo quello che mi disorienta\n\nLa Terra, l’Emilia, la Luna opens the record, and it already seems like night, with the fireflies, crickets, grasshoppers (?), among the fields between Ferrara and the Moon. Apart from this, there is silence tonight (c’è silenzio stasera) . Under a silver sky (cielo d ’argento ), a sky that covers the night, we have coordinates: a railway , a recently built mosque , and then a church , a castle , a road ; we have music that disorients the silence, and that music comes from a machine, or from North Africa , or from Eastern Europe , or from a machine in one of these two places so far away. We are in a place between the Moon and Northern Italy, we might as well be alone with the memory of the earth, Emilia and the Moon elsewhere, in Poland, in Krakow . There are two torn (strappati) hearts, thank goodness they’re not ours. There is a monument that remembers the suffering that men are capable of inflicting on other men. We promise not to tear out our hearts, but to safeguard them.\n\nIt’s a song of geographical references, of places like pins on a map, of memories and relationships and connections like a thread linking those points. It’s a surface without a center, it has no direction, and so we search for a meaning, a direction: we create a new theory of gravity, the first version of this theory is only momentary , for now it’s enough for us.\n\nWe are every place we fly to, every place we visit: we let ourselves be disoriented, we only want what disorients us, we are the action of desperation and the thought of hope. We pray, if we do, for all of this, to arrive in Germany , in Turkey , in Greece , driving in shifts and resting in shifts, a chant to doze off (appisolarci) , water to cross our deserts - and how much water is truly needed, by those who traverse real deserts!\n\nWe want the means to lift ourselves above them, to make them sufficient so that we die.\n\nfelicemente, felicemente, felicemente al di sopra dei loro mezzi\n\nqui sono le undici, ci sono meno tre gradi, chiamami quando vuoi\n\nMacbeth nella nebbia is missed waits, eyes that change, conquests from across the Channel. Your eyes were green (verdi) , now after thirty they seem to welcome fires , trees and flames, Venus and Mars - will they be red? None of this, nothing more depends on the alignment of the planets . All the attentions, pressures, aspirations, objectives, you distance yourself from them in flight, with transparent wings , with strong winds toward England, the night is inside you, your England too, what you defeat outside of you you defeat first in a small part inside you , the dirty air is like your thoughts, clouding your sight is a prerogative of the mind.\n\nNow everyone has aged, the musicians, your eyes, yourself, time, odd, in four-four time, postmodern . Macbeth cannot save himself, you cannot either, the night arrives, your inner fathers and mothers are not the three witches. So don’t wait for the night, fly, keep flying: nothing can reach you , beyond the fog and dirty air you will find that\n\nil futuro era sempre lì a sorriderci\n\nl’interpretazione dei sogni che non riesco a ricordarmi\n\nLe ragazze stanno bene is the entire life, the future and everything that will happen. The girls feel great now, they have been vulnerable, they have made mistakes, waited, accepted themselves and their weak points, they have fallen, they have burned everything, setting the sky on fire like a meteorite . They wait for each other at the station , they wait for each other in the car , on trips that are too long, in the white spaces left for the figure of the other, for the missing pieces that the other will have to find and use to build the future together. Without knowing it, the future, having forgotten it, as in a postwar period, being able to rebuild it without instructions of any kind.\n\nTheir home is a collection of noises and voices, and going outside the fire escape is an astronomical observatory , they see everything, everything might not have a meaning, nothing could have a meaning, the meaning of dreams is you, when I don’t find one, they tell each other this. At night we are all tired, but Chiara, but Sara, I am even more beautiful in the evening, when you are very tired .\n\nThis song is perfect, everything is perfect, there is nothing different.\n\nhai visto il loro non era un amore poi tanto diverso\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!5Fjt!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/03e811cb-393a-4940-9e7a-b2375bff1970_1080x1350.png)\n\ne le parole di quel giorno mentre ti spogliavi in mezzo ai campi\n\nI destini generali is an anthem, an anthem to economic drift , to the very poor homeland , to luminous nature , to the girl at the computer .\n\nEverything falls, the stars from the sky down into the Adriatic Sea, to explore the leagues that are still twenty thousand, the strikes will be a bit fewer, the strikers many more, the results are not visible: it’s the crisis that is passing, it’s not a star, the star illuminates, the computer illuminates, the crisis however traces new paths, and so let’s cross it, let’s meet the penitentiaries, the avenues in Bologna, the barracks, let’s listen to the girls who sing to the soldiers, who sing to the boys, in the penitentiary there are only people locked up, there is no difference. What do they sing to the soldiers? Perhaps “Un bel morir...” by Álvaro Mutis, with their own words, with words all their own.\n\nsaranno argomenti più memorabili nei nostri lunghi abbracci\n\npensa ai giorni sacri che abbiamo passato assieme\n\nI Sonic Youth speaks of tears full of hopes, of indifferent cyclones, of limits and infinity, of deserts and fields (soccer fields), of progress, of moving away, of work, of small southern towns, of foreign music. It speaks of getting up at dawn to go to work, of crying so hard as to break the dams , it speaks of wanting to go away just to measure how far you can be without you, of all the days spent together that are like sacred activities to remember and celebrate, of interstellar journeys to visit other planets reachable from here , it speaks of storms and lightning, of flashes that illuminate and of cyclones that don’t move us from here. There is always another cyclone that doesn’t move you from where you are but leaves you something; there is always a record that turns your life upside down even in a small southern town .\n\npuoi rispiegarmi il perché delle maree\n\nva tutto bene ma solo se è irraggiungibile\n\nFirmamento is a scream in the night, with the full moon in the square behind the hotel , it’s a city to abandon after a concert, after a hug, the arms are still open. It’s the collection of all things that illuminate, it’s the collection of the luminous stars of our life, the laughter the hopes the dreams everything that is too far away to touch describe define: it’s enough that it be unreachable . It’s the union of lives turned upside down (vite stravolte) , that are now well , that see the rain transform into snow , the snow melt: the water from rain is not the water from melting snow, explain this to me too. Everything is fine, if it’s too dark there’s nothing to photograph , even if there’s the moon, I already said that. And now I wish this record would never stop .\n\nadesso vorrei che la pioggia non si fermasse mai\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!1z5E!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5c5eac2f-e4dd-4b7f-8cf2-348e3cd95f7b_900x900.jpeg)\n\nArtwork di Gianluigi Toccafondo.\n\nin una notte limpida con molte più stelle di queste quattro o cinque\n\nUn bar sulla via lattea is perhaps on via Emilia , but we are quite sure there was a red star - from an advertising agency , what else did you imagine? It’s the bar where we meet, but you’re pretending to sleep , you sleep on the floor , the story changes, we don’t meet there anymore, we are everywhere, a little further away, in a work of art , of contemporary architecture , we are in a place where an artist can think, in a place where a person can think, in a desert place on an island, we are not in Italy, how do we orient ourselves? We follow the stars, but the stars follow us, they are attached to the window , I can’t ask you for help because you’re pretending to sleep, the night is clear, the planes depart from a terminal , our bar is really on the Milky Way (via Lattea) , the planes take you there, they only divert to reach desert planets - Corsica ? let’s meet at the terminal, at the end of this still clear night.\n\nStars stay always there.\n\nche dal finestrino mi seguono sempre\n\nè una giornata fredda e luminosa / è una notte buia e meravigliosa\n\nTi vendi bene is an anthem, with a red flag left alone solitary before a stormy sea. Only there it will triumph , and the moon that is unreachable someone was shouting give it to the people , but it stays where it is, indeed it gives way to a new day, a new morning where you return to work. Everyone except the artists, because Debussy has fallen into the Seine , and Mozart is in bed because he has a high fever .\n\nThere remain then the workers the waiters the students the idlers , there remain the saints the poets the navigators (satellite navigators, navigatori satellitari ) the florists ; there remains the dark and marvellous night, the Moon perhaps the people really obtained it, now it’s in a discotheque , which has become a place of the soul, now it’s empty because everyone returns to work, and because at night people are asleep , everything is confused, there is immense bewilderment (immenso smarrimento) . But from there immense freedom (immensa libertà) is born.\n\nThe red flag fades , but its meaning endures. The Moon fades, eclipses, but its meaning endures.\n\nimmenso smarrimento, immensa libertà\n\ne adesso che non lavori potrai dormire quanto ti pare\n\nUna cosa spirituale are the speeches that I tie to my wrists , they are all the confirmations you give me, the shell bracelet you have is more than anything (più che altro) worthless, the bracelet I built with your speeches has an inestimable value; your bracelet is more a spiritual thing, you say.\n\nWe couldn’t manage to stay together, now you sleep as much as you like, you live where there aren’t many people, but more than anything many insects.\n\nYou can’t explain the life they lead - those few people, those many insects, that shell bracelet - perhaps it’s time to call the saints experts in everything we live through and don’t know. An operation, a prayer, an exorcism, a therapy, hearts are in flames , hearts are open , from fast cars comes English post-punk . We open the windows, the wind wouldn’t gather us, it would scatter us (ci disperderebbe) .\n\nper te più che altro è una cosa spirituale\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!4EmW!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/077041fd-1c5f-4e31-a3f5-808e13ddd4a1_640x640.jpeg)\n\nArtwork by Gianluigi Toccafondo. Credits qui.\n\ne Dio onnipotente, dammi un lavoro qualunque e una linea della vita bella e illeggibile\n\nPadre nostro dei satelliti is a prayer for the internet connections that give us YouTube , for passwords short and unforgettable as much as we want our life to be long and illegible ; it’s an invocation to the lords of satellites and streaming news, who always find us, flood us with sacred information, with debates , with the useless opinions of others .\n\nIt’s a sweet and desperate lullaby, hard and resolute, we don’t ask for protection from anything , except to leave traces of our youth blurred , in digital , on YouTube, for eternity.\n\nLet this youth end, then. Thy will be done, in heaven and in downtown bars.\n\nhai visto, gli infelici possono essere pericolosi\n\nè davvero così bello tutto questo disincanto questo ironico distacco?\n\nQuesto scontro tranquillo it doesn’t work, or at least in Milan it doesn’t work , what to do with all this disenchantment (disincanto) , with all this ironic detachment (ironico distacco) ? Everything is suspended, at piazzale Loreto , near Ostiense , but I’ll arrive so happy it’s disgusting , everything will be resolved, my happiness opens the taps of your eyes, will release all your held-back tears .\n\nThen the Moon arrives in Milan , the Moon in Rome , or is it one o’clock in Milan, one o’clock in Rome?1 I want to know what my happiness has done, if it has made the dreams of our friends come true, if it has made the songs imprisoned inside the buildings escape.\n\nI don’t know, I don’t know. If it’s really beautiful, all this disenchantment, this detachment.\n\nparlami di tutti i miei amici / dei nostri sogni assurdi che si sono avverati\n\nStrano sentirsi forti nei corridoi degli ospedali\n\nPunk sentimentale is observing the sky, observing the mechanisms , as in the sky so between two human beings. We are a punk steam engine, we are steam-punk, we only need someone to start the engine, touching us in the conventional place - how strange the familiar intimate touch on a technical robotic body of iron for us who are clay; then we breathe for our whole life, then we stop breathing .\n\nHow strange. Love, the sea, the sky, move individually, and together tremendous harmony.\n\nPeople’s dreams brief and in black and white , or very long and in color. We are waves, we move like waves, we overwhelm we drown we roar we crash we return. The constructions we create prepare us for surprise, distance us from others, then like a flow we travel, we recover, we desire, we hope, then we explode.\n\nHow strange. Everything is strange, beauty becomes less beautiful and makes bearable the pain of hospitals of bombs of massacres of economic disparities. It’s also strange to fall in love in Milano - Milano 2 though2, times change.\n\nWe are waves.\n\nstrane ancora a casa mia le cose tue\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!EUHC!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/db8598d1-d624-4e1c-b279-8cef4d8e478f_1024x1250.webp)\n\nCredits: Ilaria Magliocchetti Lombi\n\nha capito che tutto andava bene, che poteva partire\n\nBlues del delta del Po is Bolaño, it’s the Mississippi Delta here in Italy. It’s an anthem to the Po Delta, for sure: it’s running on the embankment to escape and then return, it’s an entire year and an entire week, it’s making love in an Ape car , it’s making love outdoors in the February sun , it’s a now uninhabited village, it’s dancing on Saturday night , it’s reading the newspaper on Monday , it’s leaving the village, leaving school, being a little girl when your little girl is born, it’s driving a car and looking at the cars ended up in the canals, it’s the black that isn’t only black, it’s the sky that expands in the water, it’s the clear water and the Moon that reflects and the three hundred meters of a rainy street because it just rained, it’s the cats and the patron saint , it’s the cat patron saint.\n\nha capito che tutto andava male, che poteva partire\n\nda qui tutto bene, di quest’epoca non resteranno neanche delle belle rovine\n\nUna guerra lampo-pop is a thunderstorm that nobody asked for, but there’s nobody in the illuminated skyscrapers and in the empty transparent offices , they’re all in the fields , they’re all on the hills , they desert this life they enjoy these flashes of lightning, they are fast, they are pop .\n\nIt’s still a war, the boys lose silver blood , they are mythological because nobody has ever seen them, now they’re on the ground, now they can’t see anything anymore, there is no future there are only dreams, their beautiful eyes worked poorly . They look at houses , churches , discotheques , everything is fine, everything was fine, will ruins remain? Then let’s go down to the capital.\n\nThe thunderstorm destroys the plans of the empire of the lesser evil , the sky is in disarray , the sky is large, the capital too will be in ruins, the president no longer has power, the revolution is made by the boys, no longer in October , March , April , the sky must open to let the future pass through.\n\nThey still want to dream, but now white butterflies fly compact , now a peaceful jet flies toward the north, flies toward the east, there there are no places to work , there are no places even to survive, today they are no longer jets, now they are drones.\n\nOn the ground there are always boys, also in the north also in the east.\n\nThe incomprehensible writings on the walls here are graffiti, in the east and in the north they are unknown languages, languages we don’t know.\n\nA language in which war is called peace?\n\nanche se fecero un deserto e lo chiamarono pace\n\nbrillano le insegne che hanno perso delle lettere\n\n40 km closes the record, it’s a farewell, it seems like a farewell, it isn’t, the music is here. Walk for forty kilometers, run on a Ciao for twenty kilometers, it’s in Mexico , it’s between Ferrara and the Moon , only seventy kilometers left, or maybe thirty ? Roots make you stumble only if you look at the ground, if you look at the sky the stars explode, they explode every year. You’re not the only one leaving, New York, San Francisco, Bologna, Milan, you go back home to your family, he/she goes back home to his/her family, give me the coordinates of the sky to find you again .\n\nDuring the journey you gain work experience , it was life that is a journey, no, and it’s also the hardest work to complete - you fall, especially if you run. See you tomorrow, just outside the city . The resonances of our time are marketing -proof, the guitar and the computer are two things you take with you, there are two who kiss in secret, you carry inside every kiss, lonely is every single truck that passes; all together even the swallows leave this place.\n\nThey’ll all return with the same rain , until the trees move.\n\nThe stars don’t shine, the stars explode. The signs shine, the hotel windows shine, the routes of the swallows shine, the triangulation of your position and my position - we made it, it’s time to go to start over, we have a love scene now.\n\nEverything is unforgettable. It seems to me .\n\nche cos’è che tiene insieme il sistema solare e tutte ‘ste famiglie?\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!j22g!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1598876c-bd23-4008-908f-ba7d76a95598_1080x1350.png)\n\nThe Moon and via Emilia, transparent wings, Chiara who falls like a meteorite, the distance of the planets, the full Moon, four or five stars, the Milky Way, the Moon to the people, falling stars, the Moon of Milan, a dead star with a violent explosion, the hotels without stars.\n\nThere are celestial objects above us, and then there are terrestrial objects around us. This record is made to fly beside us, to enter our heads, to flood our hearts, to inundate our bodies, to wash our eyes with limpid tears and our mouths with relaxed smiles.\n\nListening to it we transform into stars, and together into constellations.\n\n1 T his is due to the fact that one o’clock in Italian is “l’una”, which sounds like “luna”, the word for Moon .\n\n2 Milano 2 is a part of the city of Milan built during the 1970s.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_016-space-sound-22-1-costellazioni-di-le-luci-della-centrale-elettrica.md": "# space sound #22.1 : Costellazioni, di Le Luci della Centrale Elettrica\n\nDisclaimer #1: this piece is in Italian. I will publish the English version next Wednesday.\n\nDisclaimer #2: Space of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the page by clicking here.\n\nSpace of Sound è su Instagram. Potete arrivarci da qui.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!bssC!,w_640,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/__ss-rehost__IG-meta-DQRRwV8DCsC.jpg)\n\nSpace of Sound ha anche una playlist su Spotify e su Apple Music.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!rsSu!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/137c4899-2ae4-46a1-9f2c-34d89810c400_1080x1350.png)\n\nNon è facile parlare di questo disco, e al contempo è tutto così facile. E’ parlare di qualcosa che riconosci, ma ti è comunque estraneo. Non è una cosa tua, ma è in ogni cassetto della tua memoria; lo hai ascoltato talmente tanto che senti che una parte di te è definita anche in relazione ad esso. E’ il disco a cui ritorni, che lasci prima di partire, che ritrovi quando torni, da cui ti allontani quando ti allontani da tutto. Contiene tutto e tutto il resto che ancora non contiene, è il ricettacolo di quello che hai vissuto che fa spazio a ciò di cui non hai ancora esperienza. Contiene luoghi in cui sei già stato ma che visiti per collegarli a questa mappa sonora. Costellazione sonora .\n\nLe canzoni al suo interno sono stelle, che creano costellazioni se le guardi da un punto specifico - la Terra, la vita: non sono lì a formare necessariamente quei simboli, ma la tua prospettiva ti regala quei significati.\n\nLi crei tu, li crea l’artista, sono diversi, sono gli stessi.\n\nLe Luci della Centrale Elettrica è Vasco Brondi, e lui è stato il suo progetto dal 2007 al 2019; ora continua a raccontare producendo musica con il suo nome, dopo aver abbandonato il nome delle Luci con un concerto d’addio - anche se ogni tanto ne accende qualcuna in singoli concerti, e questi piccoli eventi restano lì a formare una memoria. C ostellazione temporale .\n\nCostellazioni è pubblicato nel 2014 con l’etichetta La Tempesta Dischi .\n\ndammi solo quello che mi disorienta\n\nLa Terra, l’Emilia, la Luna apre il disco, e sembra già notte, con le lucciole, i grilli, le cavallette (?), tra i campi tra Ferrara e la Luna. A parte questo, c’è silenzio stasera . Sotto un cielo d’ argento , un cielo che copre la notte, abbiamo delle coordinate: una ferrovia , una moschea costruita da poco, e poi una chiesa , un castello una strada ; abbiamo della musica che disorienta il silenzio, e quella musica viene da una macchina, o dal Nord Africa , o dall’ Est Europa , o da una macchina in uno di questi due luoghi così lontani. Siamo in un luogo tra la Luna e il Nord Italia, tanto vale essere da soli con il ricordo della terra, dell’Emilia e della Luna altrove, in Polonia, a Cracovia . Ci sono due cuori strappati , menomale che non sono i nostri. C’è un monumento che ricorda le sofferenze che gli uomini sono capaci di infliggere verso altri uomini. Ci promettiamo di non strapparci i cuori, ma di custodirli.\n\nE’ una canzone di riferimenti geografici, di luoghi come puntine su una carta, di ricordi e di rapporti e di collegamenti come un filo a legare quei punti. E’ una superficie senza un centro, non ha una direzione, e allora cerchiamo un senso, un verso: creiamo una nuova teoria di gravità, la prima versione di questa teoria è solo momentanea , per ora ci basta.\n\nSiamo ogni luogo in cui voliamo, ogni posto che visitiamo: ci facciamo disorientare, vogliamo solo quello che ci disorienta , siamo l’azione della disperazione e il pensiero della speranza. Preghiamo, se lo facciamo, per tutto questo, per arrivare in Germania , in Turchia , in Grecia , guidando a turni e riposando a turni, una cantilena per appisolarci , dell’acqua per attraversare i nostri deserti - e quanto serve l’acqua davvero, a chi percorre veri deserti!\n\nVogliamo i mezzi per sollevarci al di sopra di essi, per farceli bastare in modo da morire\n\nfelicemente, felicemente, felicemente al di sopra dei loro mezzi\n\nqui sono le undici, ci sono meno tre gradi, chiamami quando vuoi\n\nMacbeth nella nebbia è attese mancate, occhi che cambiano, conquiste d’oltremanica. I tuoi occhi erano verdi , ora dopo i trent’anni sembrano accogliere degli incendi , gli alberi e le fiamme, Venere e Marte - saranno rossi? Niente di tutto questo, nulla più dipende dall’allineamento dei pianeti . Tutte le attenzioni, le pressioni, le aspirazioni, gli obiettivi, te ne allontani al volo, con le ali trasparenti , con i venti forti verso l’Inghilterra, la notte è dentro di te, la tua Inghilterra pure, quello che sconfiggi al di fuori di te lo sconfiggi prima in una piccola parte dentro di te, l’ aria sporca è come i tuoi pensieri, annebbiare la vista è una prerogativa della mente.\n\nOra tutti sono invecchiati, i musicisti, i tuoi occhi, tu stessa, il tempo, dispari, in quattro quarti , postmoderno . Macbeth non può salvarsi, neanche tu puoi, la notte arriva, i tuoi padri e madri interiori non sono le tre streghe. Allora non aspettare la notte, vola, continua a volare: niente può raggiungerti , oltre la nebbia e l’aria sporca troverai che\n\nil futuro era sempre lì a sorriderci\n\nl’interpretazione dei sogni che non riesco a ricordarmi\n\nLe ragazze stanno bene è la vita intera, il futuro e tutto quello che avverrà. Le ragazze si sentono benissimo ora, sono state vulnerabili, hanno sbagliato, aspettato, accettato sé stesse e i loro punti deboli, sono cadute, hanno bruciato tutto, incendiando il cielo come un meteorite . Si aspettano in stazione , si aspettano in macchina , nei viaggi troppo lunghi, negli spazi bianchi lasciati per la figura dell’altra, per i pezzi mancanti che l’altra dovrò trovare e usare per costruire insieme il futuro. Senza conoscerlo, il futuro, avendolo dimenticato, come in un dopoguerra, potendolo ricostruire senza istruzioni di nessun tipo.\n\nLa loro casa è un insieme di rumori e di voci, e uscendo fuori la scala antincendio è un osservatorio astronomico, vedono tutto, tutto potrebbe non avere un senso, nulla potrebbe avere un senso, il senso dei sogni sei tu, quando non ne trovo uno, questo si dicono. La notte siamo tutti stanchi, ma Chiara, ma Sara, sono ancora più bella la sera, quando sei stanchissima .\n\nQuesta canzone è perfetta, è tutto perfetto, non c’è nulla di diverso.\n\nhai visto il loro non era un amore poi tanto diverso\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!5Fjt!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/03e811cb-393a-4940-9e7a-b2375bff1970_1080x1350.png)\n\ne le parole di quel giorno mentre ti spogliavi in mezzo ai campi\n\nI destini generali è un inno, un inno alla deriva economica , alla poverissima patria , alla luminosa natura , alla ragazza al computer .\n\nTutto cade, le stelle dal cielo giù nel mare Adriatico, ad esplorare le leghe che sono ancora ventimila, gli scioperi saranno un po’ di meno, gli scioperanti molti di più, i risultati non si vedono: è la crisi che sta passando, non è una stella, la stella illumina, il computer illumina, la crisi traccia però nuovi sentieri, e allora attraversiamolo, incontriamo i penitenziari, i viali a Bologna, le caserme, ascoltiamo le ragazze che cantano ai militari, che cantano ai ragazzi, nel penitenziario non ci sono che persone rinchiuse, non c’è differenza. Cosa cantano ai militari? Forse “Un bel morir…” di Álvaro Mutis, con parole sue, con parole tutte loro.\n\nsaranno argomenti più memorabili nei nostri lunghi abbracci\n\npensa ai giorni sacri che abbiamo passato assieme\n\nI Sonic Youth parla di lacrime piene di speranze, di cicloni indifferenti, di limiti e infinito, di deserti e campi (da calcio), del progresso, dell’allontanarsi, del lavoro, dei piccoli paesi del Sud, della musica straniera. Parla di alzarsi all’alba per andare al lavoro , di piangere così forte da rompere le dighe , parla di voler andare via solo per misurare quanto lontano si può stare senza te, di tutti i giorni passati insieme che sono come attività sacre da ricordare e festeggiare, dei viaggi interstellari per visitare altri pianeti raggiungibili da qui , parla di tempeste e di fulmini, di lampi che illuminano e di cicloni che non ci spostano da qui. C’è sempre un altro ciclone che non ti sposta da dove sei ma ti lascia qualcosa; c’è sempre un disco che ti stravolge la vita anche in un paesino del sud .\n\npuoi rispiegarmi il perché delle maree\n\nva tutto bene ma solo se è irraggiungibile\n\nFirmamento è un urlo nella notte, con la luna piena nel piazzale dietro l’hotel, è una città da abbandonare dopo un concerto, dopo un abbraccio, le braccia sono ancora aperte. E’ l’insieme di tutte le cose che illuminano, è l’insieme delle stelle luminose della nostra vita, le risate le speranze i sogni tutto ciò che è troppo lontano da toccare descrivere definire: basta che sia irraggiungibile . E’ l’unione di vite stravolte , che ora stanno bene , che vedono la pioggia trasformarsi in neve , la neve sciogliersi: l’acqua della pioggia non è l’acqua della neve che si scioglie, spiegami anche questo. Va tutto bene, se è troppo buio non c’è niente da fotografare , anche se c’è la luna, l’ho già detto. E adesso vorrei che questo disco non si fermasse mai .\n\nadesso vorrei che la pioggia non si fermasse mai\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!1z5E!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5c5eac2f-e4dd-4b7f-8cf2-348e3cd95f7b_900x900.jpeg)\n\nArtwork di Gianluigi Toccafondo.\n\nin una notte limpida con molte più stelle di queste quattro o cinque\n\nUn bar sulla via lattea forse è sulla via Emilia , ma siamo abbastanza sicuri che ci fosse una stella rossa - di un’ agenzia pubblicitaria , cos’altro immaginavi? E’ il bar dove ci incontriamo, ma tu dormi per finta , dormi per terra , la storia cambia, non ci incontriamo più lì, siamo ovunque, poco più lontano, in una opera d’arte, d’ architettura contemporanea , siamo in un luogo dove un artista può pensare, in un luogo dove una persona può pensare, in un luogo desertico di un’isola, non siamo in Italia, come ci orientiamo? Seguiamo le stelle, ma le stelle seguono noi, sono attaccate al finestrino , non posso chiederti aiuto perché dormi per finta, la notte è limpida, gli aerei partono da un terminal , il nostro bar è davvero sulla via Lattea , gli aerei portano lì, deviano solo per raggiungere pianeti desertici - la Corsica ? vediamoci al terminal, al termine di questa notte ancora limpida.\n\nLe stelle sono sempre lì.\n\nche dal finestrino mi seguono sempre\n\nè una giornata fredda e luminosa / è una notte buia e meravigliosa\n\nTi vendi bene è un inno, con una bandiera rossa rimasta sola solitaria davanti un mare in tempesta. Solo lì trionferà , e la luna che è irraggiungibile qualcuno gridava datela al popolo , ma resta lì dov’è, anzi lascia il posto a un nuovo giorno, una nuova mattina dove si torna al lavoro. Tutti tranne gli artisti, perché Debussy è caduto nella Senna, e Mozart è a letto perché ha la febbre alta .\n\nRestano allora gli operai i camerieri gli studenti i nullafacenti , restano i santi i poeti i navigatori ( satellitari ) i fiorai; resta la notte buia e meravigliosa, la Luna il popolo forse davvero l’ha ottenuta, adesso è in una discoteca , che è diventato un luogo dell’anima, adesso è vuota perché tutti tornano a lavoro, e perché la notte la gente è addormentata , tutto è confuso, c’è immenso smarrimento . Ma da lì nasce immensa libertà .\n\nLa bandiera rossa scolorisce , ma resiste il suo significato. La Luna sbiadisce, si eclissa, ma resiste il suo significato.\n\nimmenso smarrimento, immensa libertà\n\ne adesso che non lavori potrai dormire quanto ti pare\n\nUna cosa spirituale sono i discorsi che mi lego ai polsi , sono tutte le conferme che mi dai, il braccialetto di conchiglie che hai tu è più che altro senza valore, il braccialetto che ho costruito con i tuoi discorsi ne ha uno inestimabile; il tuo braccialetto è più una cosa spirituale, dici.\n\nNon siamo riusciti a tenerci uniti, ora dormi quanto ti pare, vivi dove non c’è molta gente, ma più che altro molti insetti.\n\nNon sai spiegarti la vita che fanno - quella poca gente, quei molti insetti, quel braccialetto di conchiglie - forse è il caso di chiamare i santi esperti di tutto quello che viviamo e non sappiamo. Un’operazione, una preghiera, un esorcismo, una terapia, i cuori sono in fiamme , i cuori sono aperti , dalle macchine veloci arriva post-punk inglese . Apriamo i finestrini, il vento non ci raccoglierebbe , ci disperderebbe .\n\nper te più che altro è una cosa spirituale\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!4EmW!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/077041fd-1c5f-4e31-a3f5-808e13ddd4a1_640x640.jpeg)\n\nArtwork di Gianluigi Toccafondo. Credits qui.\n\ne Dio onnipotente, dammi un lavoro qualunque e una linea della vita bella e illeggibile\n\nPadre nostro dei satelliti è una preghiera per le linee internet che ci regalano YouTube , per le password brevi e indimenticabili tanto quanto la nostra vita vogliamo sia lunga e illeggibile ; è una invocazione ai signori dei satelliti e dei notiziari in streaming , che ci trovano sempre, ci inondano di sacra informazione, di dibattiti , delle inutili opinioni degli altri .\n\nE’ una nenia dolce e disperata, dura e risoluta, non chiediamo protezione da niente , se non di lasciare tracce della nostra gioventù sfocate , in digitale , su YouTube, per l’eternità.\n\nChe questa gioventù finisca, allora. Sia fatta la tua volontà , in cielo e nei bar del centro .\n\nhai visto, gli infelici possono essere pericolosi\n\nè davvero così bello tutto questo disincanto questo ironico distacco?\n\nQuesto scontro tranquillo non va, o almeno a Milano non va , cosa fare di tutto questo disincanto , di tutto questo ironico distacco ? Tutto è sospeso, a piazzale Loreto , vicino a Ostiense , ma arriverò io felice da fare schifo , tutto si risolverà, la mia felicità apre i rubinetti dei tuoi occhi, libererà tutti i tuoi pianti trattenuti.\n\nPoi arriva la Luna a Milano , la Luna a Roma , o è l’una a Milano, l’una a Roma? Voglio sapere cosa ha fatto quella mia felicità, se ha avverato i sogni dei nostri amici, se ha fatto evadere le canzoni rinchiuse dentro gli edifici .\n\nNon lo so, non lo so. Se è davvero bello, tutto questo disincanto, questo distacco.\n\nparlami di tutti i miei amici / dei nostri sogni assurdi che si sono avverati\n\nStrano sentirsi forti nei corridoi degli ospedali\n\nPunk sentimentale è osservare il cielo, osservare i meccanismi , come nel cielo così tra due esseri umani. Siamo un motore a vapore punk, siamo steam-punk, abbiamo solo bisogno di qualcuno che azioni il motore, toccandoci nel posto convenzionale - che strano il tocco familiare intimo su di un corpo tecnico robotico di ferro per noi che siamo argilla; poi respiriamo per tutta la vita, poi smettiamo di respirare .\n\nChe strano. L’amore, il mare, il cielo, si muovono singolarmente, e insieme tremenda armonia.\n\nI sogni della gente brevi e in bianco e nero , o lunghissimi e a colori . Siamo onde, ci muoviamo come onde, travolgiamo anneghiamo scrosciamo sbattiamo ritorniamo. Le costruzioni che realizziamo ci preparano alla sorpresa, ci allontanano dagli altri, poi come un flusso viaggiamo, recuperiamo, desideriamo, speriamo, poi esplodiamo.\n\nChe strano. E’ tutto strano, il bello diventa meno bello e rende sopportabile il dolore degli ospedali delle bombe delle stragi dei divari economici. E’ anche strano innamorarsi a Milano - Milano 2 però, i tempi cambiano.\n\nSiamo onde.\n\nstrane ancora a casa mia le cose tue\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!EUHC!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/db8598d1-d624-4e1c-b279-8cef4d8e478f_1024x1250.webp)\n\nCredits: Ilaria Magliocchetti Lombi\n\nha capito che tutto andava bene, che poteva partire\n\nBlues del delta del Po è Bolaño , è il Delta del Mississippi qui in Italia. E’ un inno al delta del Po, sicuro: è le corse sull’argine per scappare e poi tornare, è un intero anno e un’intera settimana, è fare l’amore in Ape car , è fare l’amore all’aperto nel sole di febbraio , è un paese ormai disabitato , è ballare il sabato sera , è leggere il giornale il lunedì , è lasciare il paese, lasciare la scuola, essere una bambina quando nasce la tua bambina , è guidare un’auto e guardare le auto finite nei canali , è il nero che non è solo nero, è il cielo che si espande nell’acqua, è l’acqua chiara e la Luna che si specchia e i trecento metri di una via piovosa perché è appena piovuto, è i gatti e il santo protettore , è il gatto santo protettore.\n\nha capito che tutto andava male, che poteva partire\n\nda qui tutto bene, di quest’epoca non resteranno neanche delle belle rovine\n\nUna guerra lampo-pop è un temporale che nessuno ha ordinato, ma non c’è nessuno nei grattacieli illuminati e negli uffici vuoti trasparenti , sono tutti nei campi , sono tutti sulle colline , disertano questa vita godono di questi lampi, sono veloci, sono pop .\n\nE’ comunque una guerra, i ragazzi perdono sangue d’argento , sono mitologici perché nessuno li ha mai visti, ora sono per terra, ora non vedono più nulla, non c’è futuro ci sono solo sogni, i loro occhi bellissimi funzionavano male . Guardano case, chiese, discoteche , va tutto bene, andava tutto bene, rimarranno delle rovine ? Allora scendiamo nella capitale.\n\nIl temporale distrugge i piani dell’ impero del male minore , il cielo è in disordine , il cielo è grande, la capitale anche sarà in rovina, il presidente non ha più potere, la rivoluzione la fanno i ragazzi, non più a ottobre, marzo, aprile , il cielo deve aprirsi per far passare il futuro.\n\nVogliono ancora sognare, ma ora farfalle bianche volano compatte , ora un jet pacifico vola verso nord, vola verso est, lì non ci sono posti dove lavorare , non ci sono posti neanche dove sopravvivere, oggi non sono più jet, ora sono droni.\n\nA terra ci sono sempre ragazzi, anche a nord anche a est.\n\nLe scritte incomprensibili sui muri qui sono graffiti, a est e a nord sono lingue sconosciute, lingue che non conosciamo.\n\nUna lingua in cui guerra si chiama pace?\n\nanche se fecero un deserto e lo chiamarono pace\n\nbrillano le insegne che hanno perso delle lettere\n\n40 km chiude il disco, è un addio, sembra un addio, non lo è, la musica è qui. Cammina per quaranta chilometri, corre in Ciao per venti chilometri, è in Messico, è tra Ferrara e la Luna , mancano solo settanta chilometri, o forse trenta ? Le radici fanno incespicare solo se guardi a terra, se guardi in cielo le stelle esplodono, esplodono ogni anno. Non sei il solo ad andare via, New York, San Francisco, Bologna, Milano, torni a casa dai tuoi, torna a casa dai suoi, dammi le coordinate del cielo per ritrovarti.\n\nDurante il viaggio fai esperienza lavorativa , era la vita che è un viaggio, no, ed è anche il lavoro più duro da portare a termine - si cade, soprattutto se corri. Ci vediamo domani , appena fuori città . Le risonanze del nostro tempo sono a prova di marketing , la chitarra e il computer sono due cose che ti porti dietro, sono due quelli che si baciano di nascosto, ti porti dentro ogni bacio, solo è ogni singolo camion che passa; tutti insieme vanno via persino le rondini da questo posto.\n\nTorneranno tutti con la stessa pioggia , fin quando gli alberi non si muoveranno.\n\nNon brillano le stelle, le stelle esplodono. Brillano le insegne , brillano le finestre degli alberghi , brillano le rotte delle rondini, la triangolazione della tua posizione e della mia posizione - ce l’abbiamo fatta, è tempo di andare di ricominciare, abbiamo una scena d’amore ora.\n\nTutto è indimenticabile. Mi sembra .\n\nche cos’è che tiene insieme il sistema solare e tutte ‘ste famiglie?\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!j22g!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1598876c-bd23-4008-908f-ba7d76a95598_1080x1350.png)\n\nLa Luna e la via Emilia, ali trasparenti, Chiara che cade come un meteorite, la distanza dei pianeti, la Luna piena, quattro o cinque stelle, la via Lattea, la Luna al popolo, stelle che cadono, la Luna di Milano, una stella morta con un’esplosione violenta, gli alberghi senza stelle.\n\nCi sono oggetti celesti sopra di noi, e poi ci sono oggetti terrestri attorno a noi. Questo disco è fatto per volarci affianco, entrarci in testa, allagarci il cuore, inondarci il corpo, lavare i nostri occhi con limpide lacrime e la nostra bocca con disteso sorriso.\n\nAscoltandolo ci trasformiamo in stelle, e insieme in costellazioni.\n\nInoltre, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_017-rising-sound-my-inner-goth-girl-by-the-field-index.md": "# rising sound: My Inner Goth Girl, by The Field Index\n\nToday is a day of fresh music reviews!\n\nThis is what I got in the mail: the possibility to share with you the review of a song by musician Michael Chau, currently based in Brooklyn .\n\nhere the playlist on Apple Music.\n\nWe Had Everything But Time , the new EP by Chau’s new project The Field Index will be out on November 14th, 2025, and today is available to stream everywhere the first song, My Inner Goth Girl .\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!dpvV!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/05c8abab-444d-446e-884e-85cf316fc48f_1080x1350.png)\n\nChau comes from ambient and soundscape music, and My Inner Goth Girl in the first second gives you that; then, it transforms into 80s music in the way someone actually living in the 2020s would make it: you get the synths, and the drums, and the chords, in this order, plus a delicate voice, calling you to answer to one liminal phone call - in this times of social networks on a phone that does not ring anymore - and you’re all set.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!Ts3s!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/fda7d654-0278-41c0-a5aa-7dcecd68aedb_1036x1036.png)\n\nPress photo of Michael Chau. Credits here.\n\nNever “ surrender to the emptiness ”, because this single is full of surprised: it seems an undoing, a stripping of clothes to reveal who you really are after a run, to save yourself or maybe just to sweat a bit.\n\nNonetheless, “ The past is done, release the harm / we made it out alive ”, and this is all it matters. The songs builds on itself, it grows and becomes larger, the instruments make waves, they create an ocean of sound, Chau’s voice surfs on it, it reaches you from multiple places, it makes you yearn for more.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!QsYk!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d738ea60-5252-4f29-b55f-f16a818a2193_2500x2500.jpeg)\n\nIn the other songs of the EP, there will be more of that. You only have to listen to it when it will be out.\n\nFor now, that’s a good song if you like night calls, or even that bright part of the sunset just before sun goes off in the west.\n\nSee you on the review for the full EP! Bye!\n\nMy Inner Goth Girl on Spotify.\n\nMy Inner Goth Girl on Apple Music.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_018-rising-sound-i-knew-everything-but-i-forgot-it-by-zac-vanacoro.md": "# rising sound: I Knew Everything But I Forgot It, by Zac Vanacoro\n\nOctober will bring you fresh records, new song reviews - you’ll see very soon, starting from today.\n\nZac Vanacoro is a music artist, singer, bass player and member of rock bands based in New York and halfway the world: Velvet Weekend, Plane Station, Austin Kopec, Christine Chanel and Smooch.\n\nToday his new solo album comes out: I Knew Everything But I Forgot It .\n\nThe surprise I had when I received my first press kit mail , presenting the artist and its work, with a link to listen to the tracks before the publication, was a wonderful feeling - and I thank you readers for that, too.\n\nThat mail came through the Internet, crossing half the world1, and I got to work immediately. Meaning, I listened to the songs over and over.\n\nThis is what I think of it.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!PM6Y!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d48c4852-4832-473c-94ff-454d034cca34_1080x1350.png)\n\nhere the playlist on Apple Music.\n\nThere and Back Again is a morning call, an alarm clock ringing alone: we know where we’re going, but “something doesn’t feel quite right”. And where has the time gone, that keeps running away? The questions and doubts dissolve into a final chorus, which like a circle returns to where it came from, there and back again, precisely.\n\nIn Troubled Mind someone heals our mind full of problems, and everything falls back into place: the chorus keeps repeating it, and the finger-picking in the second part seems to paint a smile between two cheeks. Everything’s alright, then.\n\nWith Chianti and Fava Beans it feels like turning on a radio to a different decade, having just turned onto a noir street, and ending up in a jazz club. The notes played and immediately withdrawn, the chorus sung in company, and the general spirit of the song, together with the horns in the second part, accompany the end of an afternoon while we prepare a party. With a bottle of Chianti, of course.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!P4H4!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/63e5f655-a7d1-45ff-8dda-4b4463b89912_4802x6159.png)\n\nEverything Stays is more delicate, slower, we’re full of thoughts as we listen to it: all our experiences stay in their place, the lyrics suggest. The piano notes accompanying the second verse are a brief window opened, but immediately closed again, onto the river of our thoughts. If it were a house, this song would have two windows open facing each other, and the wind would pass between them. Is it a current, if it doesn’t pass through you? Really, it passes through the final chorus, with full and moving strings.\n\nApril wasn’t born in April, but feels that’s their home, wants to return there. But it talks about what happens in the meantime, between November and April again, and the journey is metaphorical, but we feel spring in the choruses and guitars.\n\nOver and Over begins with a guitar, continues with a guitar, two voices join in, we’re in a room, or we’re around a bonfire, then a piano is added, and then we’re in front of a fireplace, because we still feel that warmth. The guitar strumming wraps around us, over and over again.\n\nDaisy starts straight, in the evening, a drum kit, the usual full guitar and again a voice that cascades from one verse to another: but it’s not the usual song, an electric guitar is introduced, and the distortions reconstruct it. A live song, it would seem.\n\nAmen talks about having lost your head in the sand, on the shoreline. And having lost your head, in a metaphorical sense, up in the sky. And then the prayer to find a god in wine, and the song becomes almost an electric-gospel-for-Friday-night. I’d go to that bar, if I knew which one it was.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!8WR-!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/bb234961-b4ad-4774-9e12-f4f0f38bc22c_1125x1299.jpeg)\n\nOnly Losers Left Alive is advice, an open letter, you have to be careful: you only fall when you’ve climbed somewhere. Its eight minutes are a journey, a procession, a band in celebration, a fair, a festival. They’re a soundtrack and end credits, the ending and the whole journey. In this journey, it’s normal to feel “ tired “. The song never tires though, with the second part being an incredible ride, worth the entire album. Truly remarkable.\n\nWhen I Get To Heaven is a blues vocal, in brevity and style.\n\nLady In The Radiator reassures us, everything’s fine in heaven. And everything seems to suggest it, but with a slightly eerie twist: the processed voice, the suspended rhythm, overflowing and somewhat nocturnal drum beat recalls a ghost you might have encountered at night at the end of October. It fully belongs to the songs you might have heard coming-from-the-bathroom-of-a-nightclub.\n\nMy Oh My talks about growing up “Oh, fuck!”. The older you get the fewer people you know. It seems like a singer’s song in a sing-along at the end of a concert. Maybe it’s too delicate in the final part for that kind of thing, but I wouldn’t mind.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!NLsc!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5dea597f-3545-4533-8f6b-052c4478499a_6397x6397.jpeg)\n\nI got surprised when I got that mail, as I said before. The surprise grew bigger while listening to the record, gaining a fresh angle with respect to my usual listenings. Not that this is completely an alien sound, but it gave me new perspectives.\n\nThe idea I got from the whole record is one of dedication and love to play in order to experiment , and this is certainly a plus. Music, as all art, must replicate the world, which is ever-changing.\n\nThis record does so sincerely and open-heartedly, and I hope to listen to Zac’s string live soon to change one more time.\n\nI Knew Everything But I Forgot It on Spotify.\n\nI Knew Everything But I Forgot It on Apple Music.\n\n1 I live in Italy.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_019-single-space-21-about-today-by-the-national.md": "# single space #21: About Today, by The National\n\nI said I would be back in September: a promise is a promise. But I didn’t sit idly by.\n\n![](https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!GJXU!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d07706c9-ebf4-4dfb-bb41-8b7c0b3a0b26_1080x1350.png)\n\nAbout Today is the distance, the distances we don’t travel and those that unfold between us, the walls we erect, the bridges that collapse after our words transform into boulders.\n\nIt is an avalanche, a landslide, a slow inexorable rapid invincible defeat, without truce without hostages, it is a massacre of souls united dissolved singular diluted, in complete indifference.\n\nIt is remorse, the impossibility of communicating, the tremendous sense of despair, the dawning awareness, the irreversible actions that drive us apart, the splendid irreverent sublime terrifying laughter that accompanies a long goodbye, the hysteria of letting go, the tears that feed the end.\n\nIt is the long wait for the nothing that does not change, for everything still and immovable and imposing and asking for nothing, it is the repetition of our mistakes, the representation of our hopes, our dreams in the mirror destroyed and cracked and then reunited and this film will be projected once again, what can we ever do about it, you are far away .\n\nIt is a heartbreaking beautiful powerful vulnerable poem.\n\nIt is a question never asked, a place and time unspecified, the future, the past, they blend together. It is the realisation of fears, visualising the affront, abandonment and recovery, the individual and the couple, the community of two, the isolated abandoned independent autarchic state of singularity.\n\nIt is a river, a torrent, a flow that rests on a cold glacial lake of sadness. It is the inversion of change, the calm and the storm, the calm within the storm not before not after.\n\nIt is a thread that one tries to retie, work that’s never finished, a project that’s never completed, it’s a will that dies, that’s reborn, killed torn apart mocked humiliated.\n\nIt’s the most beautiful song by The National.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_020-single-space-20-ohio-by-andrew-mcmahon-in-the-wilderness.md": "# single space #20: Ohio, by Andrew McMahon in the Wilderness\n\nAndrew McMahon is an American songwriter and music artist from Concord, Massachusetts. He also lived in New Jersey, Ohio, and California.\n\nOhio was released as a single in 2018, and then was included in the album Upside Down Flowers in the same year, under Fantasy label.\n\nOhio is a song on new directions, fleeing from Ohio to California, to “ start a new life ”. It’s also a song of new travels, and reminiscing old ones.\n\nA car (station wagon) covers many states, crosses many state lines, makes you miss your old state, but you’re full of hopes to “ get it right ” this time.\n\nAndrew is not alone, there’s his sister “ counting crows ” looking outside the car.\n\nNot just life, also music might be “ better on the west coast ” (on the radio, at least).\n\nHe makes some references to some “ men ” who “ never change ”, so it’s safe to suppose that they’re fleeing some form of abusive behaviour, presumably from their father.\n\nThey leave a “ blue house” , a “ red door” , and they feel a pull from the ocean (on the west coast they’re reaching).\n\nThe song has evidently a personal touch, and that’s the main quality it has. But it is not shy in terms of rhythm: the chorus comes with a good crescendo, and the lines of drums are well executed, and in the bridge section a sort of depth to the song is reached.\n\nSee you next time!\n\nAnything makes a big difference! Thanks :)\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_costellazioni-by-le-luci-della-centrale.md": "Disclaimer #1: this piece is in English. The Italian version is here.\n\nDisclaimer #2: Space of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the page by clicking here.\n\nSpace of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the profile following this link.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/137c4899-2ae4-46a1-9f2c-34d89810c400_1080x1350.png)\n\nIt is not easy to talk about this record, and at the same time it’s all so easy. It’s talking about something you recognize, but is nonetheless foreign to you. It’s not yours, but it’s in every place of your memory; you’ve listened to it so much that you feel a part of you is also defined in relation to it. It’s the record you return to, that you leave before departing, that you find again when you return, from which you distance yourself when you distance yourself from everything. It contains everything and all the rest it doesn’t yet contain, it is the haven of what you have lived that makes room for what you have not yet experienced. It contains places where you have already been but which you visit to connect them to this sound map.\n\nSound constellation .\n\nThe songs within it are stars, which create constellations if you look at them from a specific point - Earth, life: they are not necessarily there to form those symbols, but your perspective gives you those meanings.\n\nYou create them, the artist creates them, they are different, they are the same.\n\nLe Luci della Centrale Elettrica is Vasco Brondi, and it was his project from 2007 to 2019; now he continues to tell stories producing music with his own name, after having abandoned the name of the project with a farewell concert tour - even though every now and then he lights one up in individual concerts, and these small events remain there to form a memory.\n\nTime constellation .\n\nCostellazioni was published in 2014 with the label La Tempesta Dischi .\n\ndammi solo quello che mi disorienta\n\nLa Terra, l’Emilia, la Luna opens the record, and it already seems like night, with the fireflies, crickets, grasshoppers (?), among the fields between Ferrara and the Moon. Apart from this, there is silence tonight (c’è silenzio stasera) . Under a silver sky (cielo d ’argento ), a sky that covers the night, we have coordinates: a railway , a recently built mosque , and then a church , a castle , a road ; we have music that disorients the silence, and that music comes from a machine, or from North Africa , or from Eastern Europe , or from a machine in one of these two places so far away. We are in a place between the Moon and Northern Italy, we might as well be alone with the memory of the earth, Emilia and the Moon elsewhere, in Poland, in Krakow . There are two torn (strappati) hearts, thank goodness they’re not ours. There is a monument that remembers the suffering that men are capable of inflicting on other men. We promise not to tear out our hearts, but to safeguard them.\n\nIt’s a song of geographical references, of places like pins on a map, of memories and relationships and connections like a thread linking those points. It’s a surface without a center, it has no direction, and so we search for a meaning, a direction: we create a new theory of gravity, the first version of this theory is only momentary , for now it’s enough for us.\n\nWe are every place we fly to, every place we visit: we let ourselves be disoriented, we only want what disorients us, we are the action of desperation and the thought of hope. We pray, if we do, for all of this, to arrive in Germany , in Turkey , in Greece , driving in shifts and resting in shifts, a chant to doze off (appisolarci) , water to cross our deserts - and how much water is truly needed, by those who traverse real deserts!\n\nWe want the means to lift ourselves above them, to make them sufficient so that we die.\n\nfelicemente, felicemente, felicemente al di sopra dei loro mezzi\n\nqui sono le undici, ci sono meno tre gradi, chiamami quando vuoi\n\nMacbeth nella nebbia is missed waits, eyes that change, conquests from across the Channel. Your eyes were green (verdi) , now after thirty they seem to welcome fires , trees and flames, Venus and Mars - will they be red? None of this, nothing more depends on the alignment of the planets . All the attentions, pressures, aspirations, objectives, you distance yourself from them in flight, with transparent wings , with strong winds toward England, the night is inside you, your England too, what you defeat outside of you you defeat first in a small part inside you , the dirty air is like your thoughts, clouding your sight is a prerogative of the mind.\n\nNow everyone has aged, the musicians, your eyes, yourself, time, odd, in four-four time, postmodern . Macbeth cannot save himself, you cannot either, the night arrives, your inner fathers and mothers are not the three witches. So don’t wait for the night, fly, keep flying: nothing can reach you , beyond the fog and dirty air you will find that\n\nil futuro era sempre lì a sorriderci\n\nl’interpretazione dei sogni che non riesco a ricordarmi\n\nLe ragazze stanno bene is the entire life, the future and everything that will happen. The girls feel great now, they have been vulnerable, they have made mistakes, waited, accepted themselves and their weak points, they have fallen, they have burned everything, setting the sky on fire like a meteorite . They wait for each other at the station , they wait for each other in the car , on trips that are too long, in the white spaces left for the figure of the other, for the missing pieces that the other will have to find and use to build the future together. Without knowing it, the future, having forgotten it, as in a postwar period, being able to rebuild it without instructions of any kind.\n\nTheir home is a collection of noises and voices, and going outside the fire escape is an astronomical observatory , they see everything, everything might not have a meaning, nothing could have a meaning, the meaning of dreams is you, when I don’t find one, they tell each other this. At night we are all tired, but Chiara, but Sara, I am even more beautiful in the evening, when you are very tired .\n\nThis song is perfect, everything is perfect, there is nothing different.\n\nhai visto il loro non era un amore poi tanto diverso\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/03e811cb-393a-4940-9e7a-b2375bff1970_1080x1350.png)\n\ne le parole di quel giorno mentre ti spogliavi in mezzo ai campi\n\nI destini generali is an anthem, an anthem to economic drift , to the very poor homeland , to luminous nature , to the girl at the computer .\n\nEverything falls, the stars from the sky down into the Adriatic Sea, to explore the leagues that are still twenty thousand, the strikes will be a bit fewer, the strikers many more, the results are not visible: it’s the crisis that is passing, it’s not a star, the star illuminates, the computer illuminates, the crisis however traces new paths, and so let’s cross it, let’s meet the penitentiaries, the avenues in Bologna, the barracks, let’s listen to the girls who sing to the soldiers, who sing to the boys, in the penitentiary there are only people locked up, there is no difference. What do they sing to the soldiers? Perhaps “Un bel morir...” by Álvaro Mutis, with their own words, with words all their own.\n\nsaranno argomenti più memorabili nei nostri lunghi abbracci\n\npensa ai giorni sacri che abbiamo passato assieme\n\nI Sonic Youth speaks of tears full of hopes, of indifferent cyclones, of limits and infinity, of deserts and fields (soccer fields), of progress, of moving away, of work, of small southern towns, of foreign music. It speaks of getting up at dawn to go to work, of crying so hard as to break the dams , it speaks of wanting to go away just to measure how far you can be without you, of all the days spent together that are like sacred activities to remember and celebrate, of interstellar journeys to visit other planets reachable from here , it speaks of storms and lightning, of flashes that illuminate and of cyclones that don’t move us from here. There is always another cyclone that doesn’t move you from where you are but leaves you something; there is always a record that turns your life upside down even in a small southern town .\n\npuoi rispiegarmi il perché delle maree\n\nva tutto bene ma solo se è irraggiungibile\n\nFirmamento is a scream in the night, with the full moon in the square behind the hotel , it’s a city to abandon after a concert, after a hug, the arms are still open. It’s the collection of all things that illuminate, it’s the collection of the luminous stars of our life, the laughter the hopes the dreams everything that is too far away to touch describe define: it’s enough that it be unreachable . It’s the union of lives turned upside down (vite stravolte) , that are now well , that see the rain transform into snow , the snow melt: the water from rain is not the water from melting snow, explain this to me too. Everything is fine, if it’s too dark there’s nothing to photograph , even if there’s the moon, I already said that. And now I wish this record would never stop .\n\nadesso vorrei che la pioggia non si fermasse mai\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5c5eac2f-e4dd-4b7f-8cf2-348e3cd95f7b_900x900.jpeg)\n\nArtwork di Gianluigi Toccafondo.\n\nin una notte limpida con molte più stelle di queste quattro o cinque\n\nUn bar sulla via lattea is perhaps on via Emilia , but we are quite sure there was a red star - from an advertising agency , what else did you imagine? It’s the bar where we meet, but you’re pretending to sleep , you sleep on the floor , the story changes, we don’t meet there anymore, we are everywhere, a little further away, in a work of art , of contemporary architecture , we are in a place where an artist can think, in a place where a person can think, in a desert place on an island, we are not in Italy, how do we orient ourselves? We follow the stars, but the stars follow us, they are attached to the window , I can’t ask you for help because you’re pretending to sleep, the night is clear, the planes depart from a terminal , our bar is really on the Milky Way (via Lattea) , the planes take you there, they only divert to reach desert planets - Corsica ? let’s meet at the terminal, at the end of this still clear night.\n\nStars stay always there.\n\nche dal finestrino mi seguono sempre\n\nè una giornata fredda e luminosa / è una notte buia e meravigliosa\n\nTi vendi bene is an anthem, with a red flag left alone solitary before a stormy sea. Only there it will triumph , and the moon that is unreachable someone was shouting give it to the people , but it stays where it is, indeed it gives way to a new day, a new morning where you return to work. Everyone except the artists, because Debussy has fallen into the Seine , and Mozart is in bed because he has a high fever .\n\nThere remain then the workers the waiters the students the idlers , there remain the saints the poets the navigators (satellite navigators, navigatori satellitari ) the florists ; there remains the dark and marvellous night, the Moon perhaps the people really obtained it, now it’s in a discotheque , which has become a place of the soul, now it’s empty because everyone returns to work, and because at night people are asleep , everything is confused, there is immense bewilderment (immenso smarrimento) . But from there immense freedom (immensa libertà) is born.\n\nThe red flag fades , but its meaning endures. The Moon fades, eclipses, but its meaning endures.\n\nimmenso smarrimento, immensa libertà\n\ne adesso che non lavori potrai dormire quanto ti pare\n\nUna cosa spirituale are the speeches that I tie to my wrists , they are all the confirmations you give me, the shell bracelet you have is more than anything (più che altro) worthless, the bracelet I built with your speeches has an inestimable value; your bracelet is more a spiritual thing, you say.\n\nWe couldn’t manage to stay together, now you sleep as much as you like, you live where there aren’t many people, but more than anything many insects.\n\nYou can’t explain the life they lead - those few people, those many insects, that shell bracelet - perhaps it’s time to call the saints experts in everything we live through and don’t know. An operation, a prayer, an exorcism, a therapy, hearts are in flames , hearts are open , from fast cars comes English post-punk . We open the windows, the wind wouldn’t gather us, it would scatter us (ci disperderebbe) .\n\nper te più che altro è una cosa spirituale\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/077041fd-1c5f-4e31-a3f5-808e13ddd4a1_640x640.jpeg)\n\nArtwork by Gianluigi Toccafondo. Credits qui.\n\ne Dio onnipotente, dammi un lavoro qualunque e una linea della vita bella e illeggibile\n\nPadre nostro dei satelliti is a prayer for the internet connections that give us YouTube , for passwords short and unforgettable as much as we want our life to be long and illegible ; it’s an invocation to the lords of satellites and streaming news, who always find us, flood us with sacred information, with debates , with the useless opinions of others .\n\nIt’s a sweet and desperate lullaby, hard and resolute, we don’t ask for protection from anything , except to leave traces of our youth blurred , in digital , on YouTube, for eternity.\n\nLet this youth end, then. Thy will be done, in heaven and in downtown bars.\n\nhai visto, gli infelici possono essere pericolosi\n\nè davvero così bello tutto questo disincanto questo ironico distacco?\n\nQuesto scontro tranquillo it doesn’t work, or at least in Milan it doesn’t work , what to do with all this disenchantment (disincanto) , with all this ironic detachment (ironico distacco) ? Everything is suspended, at piazzale Loreto , near Ostiense , but I’ll arrive so happy it’s disgusting , everything will be resolved, my happiness opens the taps of your eyes, will release all your held-back tears .\n\nThen the Moon arrives in Milan , the Moon in Rome , or is it one o’clock in Milan, one o’clock in Rome?1 I want to know what my happiness has done, if it has made the dreams of our friends come true, if it has made the songs imprisoned inside the buildings escape.\n\nI don’t know, I don’t know. If it’s really beautiful, all this disenchantment, this detachment.\n\nparlami di tutti i miei amici / dei nostri sogni assurdi che si sono avverati\n\nStrano sentirsi forti nei corridoi degli ospedali\n\nPunk sentimentale is observing the sky, observing the mechanisms , as in the sky so between two human beings. We are a punk steam engine, we are steam-punk, we only need someone to start the engine, touching us in the conventional place - how strange the familiar intimate touch on a technical robotic body of iron for us who are clay; then we breathe for our whole life, then we stop breathing .\n\nHow strange. Love, the sea, the sky, move individually, and together tremendous harmony.\n\nPeople’s dreams brief and in black and white , or very long and in color. We are waves, we move like waves, we overwhelm we drown we roar we crash we return. The constructions we create prepare us for surprise, distance us from others, then like a flow we travel, we recover, we desire, we hope, then we explode.\n\nHow strange. Everything is strange, beauty becomes less beautiful and makes bearable the pain of hospitals of bombs of massacres of economic disparities. It’s also strange to fall in love in Milano - Milano 2 though2, times change.\n\nWe are waves.\n\nstrane ancora a casa mia le cose tue\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/db8598d1-d624-4e1c-b279-8cef4d8e478f_1024x1250.webp)\n\nCredits: Ilaria Magliocchetti Lombi\n\nha capito che tutto andava bene, che poteva partire\n\nBlues del delta del Po is Bolaño, it’s the Mississippi Delta here in Italy. It’s an anthem to the Po Delta, for sure: it’s running on the embankment to escape and then return, it’s an entire year and an entire week, it’s making love in an Ape car , it’s making love outdoors in the February sun , it’s a now uninhabited village, it’s dancing on Saturday night , it’s reading the newspaper on Monday , it’s leaving the village, leaving school, being a little girl when your little girl is born, it’s driving a car and looking at the cars ended up in the canals, it’s the black that isn’t only black, it’s the sky that expands in the water, it’s the clear water and the Moon that reflects and the three hundred meters of a rainy street because it just rained, it’s the cats and the patron saint , it’s the cat patron saint.\n\nha capito che tutto andava male, che poteva partire\n\nda qui tutto bene, di quest’epoca non resteranno neanche delle belle rovine\n\nUna guerra lampo-pop is a thunderstorm that nobody asked for, but there’s nobody in the illuminated skyscrapers and in the empty transparent offices , they’re all in the fields , they’re all on the hills , they desert this life they enjoy these flashes of lightning, they are fast, they are pop .\n\nIt’s still a war, the boys lose silver blood , they are mythological because nobody has ever seen them, now they’re on the ground, now they can’t see anything anymore, there is no future there are only dreams, their beautiful eyes worked poorly . They look at houses , churches , discotheques , everything is fine, everything was fine, will ruins remain? Then let’s go down to the capital.\n\nThe thunderstorm destroys the plans of the empire of the lesser evil , the sky is in disarray , the sky is large, the capital too will be in ruins, the president no longer has power, the revolution is made by the boys, no longer in October , March , April , the sky must open to let the future pass through.\n\nThey still want to dream, but now white butterflies fly compact , now a peaceful jet flies toward the north, flies toward the east, there there are no places to work , there are no places even to survive, today they are no longer jets, now they are drones.\n\nOn the ground there are always boys, also in the north also in the east.\n\nThe incomprehensible writings on the walls here are graffiti, in the east and in the north they are unknown languages, languages we don’t know.\n\nA language in which war is called peace?\n\nanche se fecero un deserto e lo chiamarono pace\n\nbrillano le insegne che hanno perso delle lettere\n\n40 km closes the record, it’s a farewell, it seems like a farewell, it isn’t, the music is here. Walk for forty kilometers, run on a Ciao for twenty kilometers, it’s in Mexico , it’s between Ferrara and the Moon , only seventy kilometers left, or maybe thirty ? Roots make you stumble only if you look at the ground, if you look at the sky the stars explode, they explode every year. You’re not the only one leaving, New York, San Francisco, Bologna, Milan, you go back home to your family, he/she goes back home to his/her family, give me the coordinates of the sky to find you again .\n\nDuring the journey you gain work experience , it was life that is a journey, no, and it’s also the hardest work to complete - you fall, especially if you run. See you tomorrow, just outside the city . The resonances of our time are marketing -proof, the guitar and the computer are two things you take with you, there are two who kiss in secret, you carry inside every kiss, lonely is every single truck that passes; all together even the swallows leave this place.\n\nThey’ll all return with the same rain , until the trees move.\n\nThe stars don’t shine, the stars explode. The signs shine, the hotel windows shine, the routes of the swallows shine, the triangulation of your position and my position - we made it, it’s time to go to start over, we have a love scene now.\n\nEverything is unforgettable. It seems to me .\n\nche cos’è che tiene insieme il sistema solare e tutte ‘ste famiglie?\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1598876c-bd23-4008-908f-ba7d76a95598_1080x1350.png)\n\nThe Moon and via Emilia, transparent wings, Chiara who falls like a meteorite, the distance of the planets, the full Moon, four or five stars, the Milky Way, the Moon to the people, falling stars, the Moon of Milan, a dead star with a violent explosion, the hotels without stars.\n\nThere are celestial objects above us, and then there are terrestrial objects around us. This record is made to fly beside us, to enter our heads, to flood our hearts, to inundate our bodies, to wash our eyes with limpid tears and our mouths with relaxed smiles.\n\nListening to it we transform into stars, and together into constellations.\n\n1 T his is due to the fact that one o’clock in Italian is “l’una”, which sounds like “luna”, the word for Moon .\n\n2 Milano 2 is a part of the city of Milan built during the 1970s.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_costellazioni-di-le-luci-della-centrale.md": "Disclaimer #1: this piece is in Italian. I will publish the English version next Wednesday.\n\nDisclaimer #2: Space of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the page by clicking here.\n\nSpace of Sound è su Instagram. Potete arrivarci da qui.\n\nSpace of Sound ha anche una playlist su Spotify e su Apple Music.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/137c4899-2ae4-46a1-9f2c-34d89810c400_1080x1350.png)\n\nNon è facile parlare di questo disco, e al contempo è tutto così facile. E’ parlare di qualcosa che riconosci, ma ti è comunque estraneo. Non è una cosa tua, ma è in ogni cassetto della tua memoria; lo hai ascoltato talmente tanto che senti che una parte di te è definita anche in relazione ad esso. E’ il disco a cui ritorni, che lasci prima di partire, che ritrovi quando torni, da cui ti allontani quando ti allontani da tutto. Contiene tutto e tutto il resto che ancora non contiene, è il ricettacolo di quello che hai vissuto che fa spazio a ciò di cui non hai ancora esperienza. Contiene luoghi in cui sei già stato ma che visiti per collegarli a questa mappa sonora. Costellazione sonora .\n\nLe canzoni al suo interno sono stelle, che creano costellazioni se le guardi da un punto specifico - la Terra, la vita: non sono lì a formare necessariamente quei simboli, ma la tua prospettiva ti regala quei significati.\n\nLi crei tu, li crea l’artista, sono diversi, sono gli stessi.\n\nLe Luci della Centrale Elettrica è Vasco Brondi, e lui è stato il suo progetto dal 2007 al 2019; ora continua a raccontare producendo musica con il suo nome, dopo aver abbandonato il nome delle Luci con un concerto d’addio - anche se ogni tanto ne accende qualcuna in singoli concerti, e questi piccoli eventi restano lì a formare una memoria. C ostellazione temporale .\n\nCostellazioni è pubblicato nel 2014 con l’etichetta La Tempesta Dischi .\n\ndammi solo quello che mi disorienta\n\nLa Terra, l’Emilia, la Luna apre il disco, e sembra già notte, con le lucciole, i grilli, le cavallette (?), tra i campi tra Ferrara e la Luna. A parte questo, c’è silenzio stasera . Sotto un cielo d’ argento , un cielo che copre la notte, abbiamo delle coordinate: una ferrovia , una moschea costruita da poco, e poi una chiesa , un castello una strada ; abbiamo della musica che disorienta il silenzio, e quella musica viene da una macchina, o dal Nord Africa , o dall’ Est Europa , o da una macchina in uno di questi due luoghi così lontani. Siamo in un luogo tra la Luna e il Nord Italia, tanto vale essere da soli con il ricordo della terra, dell’Emilia e della Luna altrove, in Polonia, a Cracovia . Ci sono due cuori strappati , menomale che non sono i nostri. C’è un monumento che ricorda le sofferenze che gli uomini sono capaci di infliggere verso altri uomini. Ci promettiamo di non strapparci i cuori, ma di custodirli.\n\nE’ una canzone di riferimenti geografici, di luoghi come puntine su una carta, di ricordi e di rapporti e di collegamenti come un filo a legare quei punti. E’ una superficie senza un centro, non ha una direzione, e allora cerchiamo un senso, un verso: creiamo una nuova teoria di gravità, la prima versione di questa teoria è solo momentanea , per ora ci basta.\n\nSiamo ogni luogo in cui voliamo, ogni posto che visitiamo: ci facciamo disorientare, vogliamo solo quello che ci disorienta , siamo l’azione della disperazione e il pensiero della speranza. Preghiamo, se lo facciamo, per tutto questo, per arrivare in Germania , in Turchia , in Grecia , guidando a turni e riposando a turni, una cantilena per appisolarci , dell’acqua per attraversare i nostri deserti - e quanto serve l’acqua davvero, a chi percorre veri deserti!\n\nVogliamo i mezzi per sollevarci al di sopra di essi, per farceli bastare in modo da morire\n\nfelicemente, felicemente, felicemente al di sopra dei loro mezzi\n\nqui sono le undici, ci sono meno tre gradi, chiamami quando vuoi\n\nMacbeth nella nebbia è attese mancate, occhi che cambiano, conquiste d’oltremanica. I tuoi occhi erano verdi , ora dopo i trent’anni sembrano accogliere degli incendi , gli alberi e le fiamme, Venere e Marte - saranno rossi? Niente di tutto questo, nulla più dipende dall’allineamento dei pianeti . Tutte le attenzioni, le pressioni, le aspirazioni, gli obiettivi, te ne allontani al volo, con le ali trasparenti , con i venti forti verso l’Inghilterra, la notte è dentro di te, la tua Inghilterra pure, quello che sconfiggi al di fuori di te lo sconfiggi prima in una piccola parte dentro di te, l’ aria sporca è come i tuoi pensieri, annebbiare la vista è una prerogativa della mente.\n\nOra tutti sono invecchiati, i musicisti, i tuoi occhi, tu stessa, il tempo, dispari, in quattro quarti , postmoderno . Macbeth non può salvarsi, neanche tu puoi, la notte arriva, i tuoi padri e madri interiori non sono le tre streghe. Allora non aspettare la notte, vola, continua a volare: niente può raggiungerti , oltre la nebbia e l’aria sporca troverai che\n\nil futuro era sempre lì a sorriderci\n\nl’interpretazione dei sogni che non riesco a ricordarmi\n\nLe ragazze stanno bene è la vita intera, il futuro e tutto quello che avverrà. Le ragazze si sentono benissimo ora, sono state vulnerabili, hanno sbagliato, aspettato, accettato sé stesse e i loro punti deboli, sono cadute, hanno bruciato tutto, incendiando il cielo come un meteorite . Si aspettano in stazione , si aspettano in macchina , nei viaggi troppo lunghi, negli spazi bianchi lasciati per la figura dell’altra, per i pezzi mancanti che l’altra dovrò trovare e usare per costruire insieme il futuro. Senza conoscerlo, il futuro, avendolo dimenticato, come in un dopoguerra, potendolo ricostruire senza istruzioni di nessun tipo.\n\nLa loro casa è un insieme di rumori e di voci, e uscendo fuori la scala antincendio è un osservatorio astronomico, vedono tutto, tutto potrebbe non avere un senso, nulla potrebbe avere un senso, il senso dei sogni sei tu, quando non ne trovo uno, questo si dicono. La notte siamo tutti stanchi, ma Chiara, ma Sara, sono ancora più bella la sera, quando sei stanchissima .\n\nQuesta canzone è perfetta, è tutto perfetto, non c’è nulla di diverso.\n\nhai visto il loro non era un amore poi tanto diverso\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/03e811cb-393a-4940-9e7a-b2375bff1970_1080x1350.png)\n\ne le parole di quel giorno mentre ti spogliavi in mezzo ai campi\n\nI destini generali è un inno, un inno alla deriva economica , alla poverissima patria , alla luminosa natura , alla ragazza al computer .\n\nTutto cade, le stelle dal cielo giù nel mare Adriatico, ad esplorare le leghe che sono ancora ventimila, gli scioperi saranno un po’ di meno, gli scioperanti molti di più, i risultati non si vedono: è la crisi che sta passando, non è una stella, la stella illumina, il computer illumina, la crisi traccia però nuovi sentieri, e allora attraversiamolo, incontriamo i penitenziari, i viali a Bologna, le caserme, ascoltiamo le ragazze che cantano ai militari, che cantano ai ragazzi, nel penitenziario non ci sono che persone rinchiuse, non c’è differenza. Cosa cantano ai militari? Forse “Un bel morir…” di Álvaro Mutis, con parole sue, con parole tutte loro.\n\nsaranno argomenti più memorabili nei nostri lunghi abbracci\n\npensa ai giorni sacri che abbiamo passato assieme\n\nI Sonic Youth parla di lacrime piene di speranze, di cicloni indifferenti, di limiti e infinito, di deserti e campi (da calcio), del progresso, dell’allontanarsi, del lavoro, dei piccoli paesi del Sud, della musica straniera. Parla di alzarsi all’alba per andare al lavoro , di piangere così forte da rompere le dighe , parla di voler andare via solo per misurare quanto lontano si può stare senza te, di tutti i giorni passati insieme che sono come attività sacre da ricordare e festeggiare, dei viaggi interstellari per visitare altri pianeti raggiungibili da qui , parla di tempeste e di fulmini, di lampi che illuminano e di cicloni che non ci spostano da qui. C’è sempre un altro ciclone che non ti sposta da dove sei ma ti lascia qualcosa; c’è sempre un disco che ti stravolge la vita anche in un paesino del sud .\n\npuoi rispiegarmi il perché delle maree\n\nva tutto bene ma solo se è irraggiungibile\n\nFirmamento è un urlo nella notte, con la luna piena nel piazzale dietro l’hotel, è una città da abbandonare dopo un concerto, dopo un abbraccio, le braccia sono ancora aperte. E’ l’insieme di tutte le cose che illuminano, è l’insieme delle stelle luminose della nostra vita, le risate le speranze i sogni tutto ciò che è troppo lontano da toccare descrivere definire: basta che sia irraggiungibile . E’ l’unione di vite stravolte , che ora stanno bene , che vedono la pioggia trasformarsi in neve , la neve sciogliersi: l’acqua della pioggia non è l’acqua della neve che si scioglie, spiegami anche questo. Va tutto bene, se è troppo buio non c’è niente da fotografare , anche se c’è la luna, l’ho già detto. E adesso vorrei che questo disco non si fermasse mai .\n\nadesso vorrei che la pioggia non si fermasse mai\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5c5eac2f-e4dd-4b7f-8cf2-348e3cd95f7b_900x900.jpeg)\n\nArtwork di Gianluigi Toccafondo.\n\nin una notte limpida con molte più stelle di queste quattro o cinque\n\nUn bar sulla via lattea forse è sulla via Emilia , ma siamo abbastanza sicuri che ci fosse una stella rossa - di un’ agenzia pubblicitaria , cos’altro immaginavi? E’ il bar dove ci incontriamo, ma tu dormi per finta , dormi per terra , la storia cambia, non ci incontriamo più lì, siamo ovunque, poco più lontano, in una opera d’arte, d’ architettura contemporanea , siamo in un luogo dove un artista può pensare, in un luogo dove una persona può pensare, in un luogo desertico di un’isola, non siamo in Italia, come ci orientiamo? Seguiamo le stelle, ma le stelle seguono noi, sono attaccate al finestrino , non posso chiederti aiuto perché dormi per finta, la notte è limpida, gli aerei partono da un terminal , il nostro bar è davvero sulla via Lattea , gli aerei portano lì, deviano solo per raggiungere pianeti desertici - la Corsica ? vediamoci al terminal, al termine di questa notte ancora limpida.\n\nLe stelle sono sempre lì.\n\nche dal finestrino mi seguono sempre\n\nè una giornata fredda e luminosa / è una notte buia e meravigliosa\n\nTi vendi bene è un inno, con una bandiera rossa rimasta sola solitaria davanti un mare in tempesta. Solo lì trionferà , e la luna che è irraggiungibile qualcuno gridava datela al popolo , ma resta lì dov’è, anzi lascia il posto a un nuovo giorno, una nuova mattina dove si torna al lavoro. Tutti tranne gli artisti, perché Debussy è caduto nella Senna, e Mozart è a letto perché ha la febbre alta .\n\nRestano allora gli operai i camerieri gli studenti i nullafacenti , restano i santi i poeti i navigatori ( satellitari ) i fiorai; resta la notte buia e meravigliosa, la Luna il popolo forse davvero l’ha ottenuta, adesso è in una discoteca , che è diventato un luogo dell’anima, adesso è vuota perché tutti tornano a lavoro, e perché la notte la gente è addormentata , tutto è confuso, c’è immenso smarrimento . Ma da lì nasce immensa libertà .\n\nLa bandiera rossa scolorisce , ma resiste il suo significato. La Luna sbiadisce, si eclissa, ma resiste il suo significato.\n\nimmenso smarrimento, immensa libertà\n\ne adesso che non lavori potrai dormire quanto ti pare\n\nUna cosa spirituale sono i discorsi che mi lego ai polsi , sono tutte le conferme che mi dai, il braccialetto di conchiglie che hai tu è più che altro senza valore, il braccialetto che ho costruito con i tuoi discorsi ne ha uno inestimabile; il tuo braccialetto è più una cosa spirituale, dici.\n\nNon siamo riusciti a tenerci uniti, ora dormi quanto ti pare, vivi dove non c’è molta gente, ma più che altro molti insetti.\n\nNon sai spiegarti la vita che fanno - quella poca gente, quei molti insetti, quel braccialetto di conchiglie - forse è il caso di chiamare i santi esperti di tutto quello che viviamo e non sappiamo. Un’operazione, una preghiera, un esorcismo, una terapia, i cuori sono in fiamme , i cuori sono aperti , dalle macchine veloci arriva post-punk inglese . Apriamo i finestrini, il vento non ci raccoglierebbe , ci disperderebbe .\n\nper te più che altro è una cosa spirituale\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/077041fd-1c5f-4e31-a3f5-808e13ddd4a1_640x640.jpeg)\n\nArtwork di Gianluigi Toccafondo. Credits qui.\n\ne Dio onnipotente, dammi un lavoro qualunque e una linea della vita bella e illeggibile\n\nPadre nostro dei satelliti è una preghiera per le linee internet che ci regalano YouTube , per le password brevi e indimenticabili tanto quanto la nostra vita vogliamo sia lunga e illeggibile ; è una invocazione ai signori dei satelliti e dei notiziari in streaming , che ci trovano sempre, ci inondano di sacra informazione, di dibattiti , delle inutili opinioni degli altri .\n\nE’ una nenia dolce e disperata, dura e risoluta, non chiediamo protezione da niente , se non di lasciare tracce della nostra gioventù sfocate , in digitale , su YouTube, per l’eternità.\n\nChe questa gioventù finisca, allora. Sia fatta la tua volontà , in cielo e nei bar del centro .\n\nhai visto, gli infelici possono essere pericolosi\n\nè davvero così bello tutto questo disincanto questo ironico distacco?\n\nQuesto scontro tranquillo non va, o almeno a Milano non va , cosa fare di tutto questo disincanto , di tutto questo ironico distacco ? Tutto è sospeso, a piazzale Loreto , vicino a Ostiense , ma arriverò io felice da fare schifo , tutto si risolverà, la mia felicità apre i rubinetti dei tuoi occhi, libererà tutti i tuoi pianti trattenuti.\n\nPoi arriva la Luna a Milano , la Luna a Roma , o è l’una a Milano, l’una a Roma? Voglio sapere cosa ha fatto quella mia felicità, se ha avverato i sogni dei nostri amici, se ha fatto evadere le canzoni rinchiuse dentro gli edifici .\n\nNon lo so, non lo so. Se è davvero bello, tutto questo disincanto, questo distacco.\n\nparlami di tutti i miei amici / dei nostri sogni assurdi che si sono avverati\n\nStrano sentirsi forti nei corridoi degli ospedali\n\nPunk sentimentale è osservare il cielo, osservare i meccanismi , come nel cielo così tra due esseri umani. Siamo un motore a vapore punk, siamo steam-punk, abbiamo solo bisogno di qualcuno che azioni il motore, toccandoci nel posto convenzionale - che strano il tocco familiare intimo su di un corpo tecnico robotico di ferro per noi che siamo argilla; poi respiriamo per tutta la vita, poi smettiamo di respirare .\n\nChe strano. L’amore, il mare, il cielo, si muovono singolarmente, e insieme tremenda armonia.\n\nI sogni della gente brevi e in bianco e nero , o lunghissimi e a colori . Siamo onde, ci muoviamo come onde, travolgiamo anneghiamo scrosciamo sbattiamo ritorniamo. Le costruzioni che realizziamo ci preparano alla sorpresa, ci allontanano dagli altri, poi come un flusso viaggiamo, recuperiamo, desideriamo, speriamo, poi esplodiamo.\n\nChe strano. E’ tutto strano, il bello diventa meno bello e rende sopportabile il dolore degli ospedali delle bombe delle stragi dei divari economici. E’ anche strano innamorarsi a Milano - Milano 2 però, i tempi cambiano.\n\nSiamo onde.\n\nstrane ancora a casa mia le cose tue\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/db8598d1-d624-4e1c-b279-8cef4d8e478f_1024x1250.webp)\n\nCredits: Ilaria Magliocchetti Lombi\n\nha capito che tutto andava bene, che poteva partire\n\nBlues del delta del Po è Bolaño , è il Delta del Mississippi qui in Italia. E’ un inno al delta del Po, sicuro: è le corse sull’argine per scappare e poi tornare, è un intero anno e un’intera settimana, è fare l’amore in Ape car , è fare l’amore all’aperto nel sole di febbraio , è un paese ormai disabitato , è ballare il sabato sera , è leggere il giornale il lunedì , è lasciare il paese, lasciare la scuola, essere una bambina quando nasce la tua bambina , è guidare un’auto e guardare le auto finite nei canali , è il nero che non è solo nero, è il cielo che si espande nell’acqua, è l’acqua chiara e la Luna che si specchia e i trecento metri di una via piovosa perché è appena piovuto, è i gatti e il santo protettore , è il gatto santo protettore.\n\nha capito che tutto andava male, che poteva partire\n\nda qui tutto bene, di quest’epoca non resteranno neanche delle belle rovine\n\nUna guerra lampo-pop è un temporale che nessuno ha ordinato, ma non c’è nessuno nei grattacieli illuminati e negli uffici vuoti trasparenti , sono tutti nei campi , sono tutti sulle colline , disertano questa vita godono di questi lampi, sono veloci, sono pop .\n\nE’ comunque una guerra, i ragazzi perdono sangue d’argento , sono mitologici perché nessuno li ha mai visti, ora sono per terra, ora non vedono più nulla, non c’è futuro ci sono solo sogni, i loro occhi bellissimi funzionavano male . Guardano case, chiese, discoteche , va tutto bene, andava tutto bene, rimarranno delle rovine ? Allora scendiamo nella capitale.\n\nIl temporale distrugge i piani dell’ impero del male minore , il cielo è in disordine , il cielo è grande, la capitale anche sarà in rovina, il presidente non ha più potere, la rivoluzione la fanno i ragazzi, non più a ottobre, marzo, aprile , il cielo deve aprirsi per far passare il futuro.\n\nVogliono ancora sognare, ma ora farfalle bianche volano compatte , ora un jet pacifico vola verso nord, vola verso est, lì non ci sono posti dove lavorare , non ci sono posti neanche dove sopravvivere, oggi non sono più jet, ora sono droni.\n\nA terra ci sono sempre ragazzi, anche a nord anche a est.\n\nLe scritte incomprensibili sui muri qui sono graffiti, a est e a nord sono lingue sconosciute, lingue che non conosciamo.\n\nUna lingua in cui guerra si chiama pace?\n\nanche se fecero un deserto e lo chiamarono pace\n\nbrillano le insegne che hanno perso delle lettere\n\n40 km chiude il disco, è un addio, sembra un addio, non lo è, la musica è qui. Cammina per quaranta chilometri, corre in Ciao per venti chilometri, è in Messico, è tra Ferrara e la Luna , mancano solo settanta chilometri, o forse trenta ? Le radici fanno incespicare solo se guardi a terra, se guardi in cielo le stelle esplodono, esplodono ogni anno. Non sei il solo ad andare via, New York, San Francisco, Bologna, Milano, torni a casa dai tuoi, torna a casa dai suoi, dammi le coordinate del cielo per ritrovarti.\n\nDurante il viaggio fai esperienza lavorativa , era la vita che è un viaggio, no, ed è anche il lavoro più duro da portare a termine - si cade, soprattutto se corri. Ci vediamo domani , appena fuori città . Le risonanze del nostro tempo sono a prova di marketing , la chitarra e il computer sono due cose che ti porti dietro, sono due quelli che si baciano di nascosto, ti porti dentro ogni bacio, solo è ogni singolo camion che passa; tutti insieme vanno via persino le rondini da questo posto.\n\nTorneranno tutti con la stessa pioggia , fin quando gli alberi non si muoveranno.\n\nNon brillano le stelle, le stelle esplodono. Brillano le insegne , brillano le finestre degli alberghi , brillano le rotte delle rondini, la triangolazione della tua posizione e della mia posizione - ce l’abbiamo fatta, è tempo di andare di ricominciare, abbiamo una scena d’amore ora.\n\nTutto è indimenticabile. Mi sembra .\n\nche cos’è che tiene insieme il sistema solare e tutte ‘ste famiglie?\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1598876c-bd23-4008-908f-ba7d76a95598_1080x1350.png)\n\nLa Luna e la via Emilia, ali trasparenti, Chiara che cade come un meteorite, la distanza dei pianeti, la Luna piena, quattro o cinque stelle, la via Lattea, la Luna al popolo, stelle che cadono, la Luna di Milano, una stella morta con un’esplosione violenta, gli alberghi senza stelle.\n\nCi sono oggetti celesti sopra di noi, e poi ci sono oggetti terrestri attorno a noi. Questo disco è fatto per volarci affianco, entrarci in testa, allagarci il cuore, inondarci il corpo, lavare i nostri occhi con limpide lacrime e la nostra bocca con disteso sorriso.\n\nAscoltandolo ci trasformiamo in stelle, e insieme in costellazioni.\n\nInoltre, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n\nCiao and a presto!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_i-cani-teatro-della-concordia-venaria.md": "Disclaimer: Space of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the page by clicking here.\n\nSpace of Sound è anche su Instagram. Puoi raggiungerlo seguendo questo link.\n\nSpace of Sound è anche su Spotify e Apple Music con una playlist.\n\ni cani sono Niccolò Contessa , ma Niccolò Contessa non è stato solo i cani .\n\n\"Vedi Niccolò, la gente non è il mestiere che fa\".\n\nil concerto di ieri (al Teatro della Concordia di Venaria) è l’inizio e la fine - non finirà , finirà - del concetto degli artisti generazionali.\n\ni cani lo sono stati, generazionali.\n\nforse quella generazione è finita.\n\nchi è il colpevole? il tempo?\n\nNiccolò Contessa inizia il concerto con \" io \": forse c’è qualcosa sotto.\n\nsempre fotografati, lui che girava con una busta di carta in testa.\n\ncosa è diventato il rito del concerto dell’artista nascosto ?\n\nuna seduta fotografica per immortalarlo.\n\nqualcuno urla “ah ma allora esiste davvero!”.\n\na un certo punto dal vocoder esce una voce, mi dico “avrà scoperto Bon Iver ”, poi lo lascia stare e anch’io lascio stare.\n\naltre magie altri misteri altri dubbi questioni domande:\n\nil fuoco brucia e resta carbone .\n\nquesta esperienza viene raccontata come involuta\n\nsi fa mitologia ma non è chissà cosa;\n\nnon è questo il punto non importa:\n\nrisuonare per qualcosa io non credo sia un caso\n\nla verità forse non c’è\n\nforse è inesistente inventata dimenticata\n\neppure è lì, in ogni nuova esperienza, nascosta in piena vista.\n\nritornano le coppie, non erano riuscite a dividersi,\n\nsi erano lasciate e poi si cercavano, ma non esistono più i romantici,\n\nanche i pariolini di diciott’anni ora sarebbero più che trentenni.\n\nnessuna paura, qui si balla\n\nl’unica nostalgia che ( non ) ho .\n\nuna volta Vasco Brondi parlava con (la ragazza di) qualcuno,\n\nora Lucio Corsi (s)parla da solo:\n\ndiventiamo atomi anche metaforicamente.\n\nl’AI avanza, Internet è morto, chi usa più Google ?\n\nnon serve più a nulla supplicare di non essere ricercato .\n\nc’erano altre canzoni.\n\nc’era un’ultima canzone,\n\nma Niccolò Contessa ha chiesto che non si registrasse più nulla,\n\nper lasciarsi guardandosi e riconoscendosi.\n\ntanto era una cosa stupida .\n\ntutti a registrare tutto: chissà quanto dovremo aspettare per sentirlo di nuovo dal vivo. potrebbe anche finirla qua,\n\nle generazioni passano,\n\nchi lo ascoltava dall’inizio ha cambiato vita.\n\ncon nostalgie, rimorsi, rimpianti, più per cose che non sarebbero mai potute accadere che per qualcosa di realizzabile. ma ho un groppo in gola, e le mani in tasca al freddo.\n\nQuesto dicembre, puoi supportare Space of Sound con una offerta speciale, che equivale a 1.5€/mese.\n\nGet 40% off for 1 year\n\nGrazie!\n\nInoltre, puoi condividere questa pubblicazione con chi vuoi.\n\nCiao and a presto!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_live-sound-james-blake-ogr-torino.md": "On July 2, 2025 James Blake has performed in Turin , at OGR (Officine Grandi Riparazioni, a huge hub for art and creativity, as well as for tech and innovation.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/7ea3bdb9-a6a3-4285-a98e-d975ce02af1a_3024x4032.heic)\n\nJames Blake @ OGR Torino. July 2, 2025. Photo credits: EB\n\nThe show was a piano solo, where Blake was surrounded by a sequencer, a keyboard, a piano and a full set of technological “stuff”, as he called them.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/c03f889c-2449-4ffa-a701-5b77b57b135a_3024x4032.heic)\n\nJames Blake @ OGR Torino. July 2, 2025. Photo credits: EB\n\nThe show was experimental, as Blake himself intended, to “change things up” after years of all too similar shows.\n\nBlake played some singles by his recent years ( Like the End , You’re Too Precious) , with some covers ( The Limit to Your Love , Godspeed , A Case of You ) and even one to this date unreleased song that will feature on his next album ( Trying Times ).\n\nAt some point, Blake performed Life Round Here , from his album Overgrown (2013), which then became, after an almost techno moment, Retrograde .\n\nBlake was determined to concoct a real experience in this show, with a clear vision of the songs he wanted to play, and the way he wanted to perform them.\n\nAt some point, people started shouting their favorite songs, hoping he’d pick up one. Which he did, only to state immediately after that he chose that song because it came on his mind, “not because you said it”.\n\nWhen that song ended, someone else tried their luck. “This is not a wedding, bruv”, Blake answered.\n\nJames Blake experimented with this concert, rendering old songs in new ways, and producing new experiences that only a live concert can convey.\n\nFresh air and the usual warmth are some way to describe this concert: something new, with a firm grasp on who James Blake is, and what is becoming.\n\nWhat you read has no intent of being a review of the concert, it merely represents an invitation to discover live music. I hope you felt even slightly invited to this experience, too.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/c99499f1-036a-4d48-b76b-3e5034be9632_3024x4032.heic)\n\nJames Blake @ OGR Torino. July 2, 2025. Photo Credits: EB\n\nSetlist James Blake @ OGR Torino\n\n(there could be some songs in the middle I didn’t quote down here):\n\nLike the End\n\nThe Limit to Your Love\n\nSéance\n\nTrying Times\n\nGodspeed\n\nSay What You Will\n\nMulholland\n\nLife Round Here\n\nRetrograde\n\nA Case of You\n\nAre You in Love?\n\nYou're Too Precious\n\nMeasurements\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_mammal-hands-jazzmi.md": "Disclaimer: Space of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the page by clicking here.\n\nSpace of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the profile following this link.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/276dbcea-c2ad-4c19-99f5-79219b9775c0_1080x1350.png)\n\nGetting to know a band one day and attending their concert eight days later: that’s what happened to me with Mammal Hands , a jazz group based in London and formed in Norwich in 2012, with five albums with Gondwana Records.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/bf9d478f-fb32-4316-9199-f5f8d967d731_3024x4032.heic)\n\nthe stage for Mammal Hands @ JAZZMI, Nov 5, 2025 (Triennale Milano, Milan)\n\nThis November, you can support Space of Sound for a special offer, equivalent to 1.5€ (under 2 USD) per month.\n\nGet 40% off for 1 year\n\nThank you!\n\nIn the last week I had listened to all the songs, created a playlist with all the tracks from the first album to the last, and had my favorite.\n\nFrom the moment they stepped on stage, the atmosphere became mystical and it felt like being in a time outside of time, the atmosphere that the three musicians created built a spiral of sounds that carried you away and drew you in. Both at the same time, music is a special thing.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/10b83648-c47d-43e5-b00a-9c6b753c29fe_3024x4032.heic)\n\nMammal Hands on stage @ JAZZMI, Nov 5, 2025 (Triennale Milano, Milan)\n\nIt felt like breathing with them, keeping time, jumping hunched over the piano.\n\nI don’t know much about jazz - actually, I don’t know much about music in the technical sense, I talk about it insofar as it seems to convey something to me and when that happens I like to share it - but from what I saw, from what I heard!, there’s a formidable technique.\n\nThe songs are complex structures, rhythmic, coherent and fractal: a marvel for the ears.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ecb8f892-8499-46ff-a4fe-4fcd9528d374_4032x3024.heic)\n\nMammal Hands members at the end of the concert @ JAZZMI, Nov 5, 2025 (Triennale Milano, Milan)\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/cb55cf46-3265-4382-99d0-71f0c789805c_4032x3024.heic)\n\nMammal Hands members at the end of the concert @ JAZZMI, Nov 5, 2025 (Triennale Milano, Milan)\n\nAt the end of the concert, lasting just under an hour and a half, I bought a vinyl with my favorite song by the group, and with the three - Nick Smart , Jordan Smart , and Rob Turner - I chatted a bit, just long enough to get the cover signed, and compliment them on the spectacular concert.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2e5237ce-711b-4fd0-9455-1e3ba99f321d_4032x3024.heic)\n\nmy copy of Captured Spirits vinyl, composed by Mammal Hands with Gondwana Records.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/91e3c75e-88c1-47d1-bbbd-380064fda587_4032x3024.heic)\n\nmy copy of Captured Spirits vinyl, composed by Mammal Hands with Gondwana Records.\n\nBelow, my favourite song by Mammal Hands, Riddle .\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_mum-hiroshima-mon-amour-torino.md": "Disclaimer: Space of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the page by clicking here.\n\nSpace of Sound is on Instagram. You can reach the profile following this link.\n\nI went to Iceland a few months ago, and the experience was both transcending and deeply rooted in nature. I’m constantly thinking back to those moments, and frequently picturing the places I’ve been, with the soundtrack of the music we listened to while driving - many of those songs are in this newsletter, by the way.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b02420fc-759a-4cb0-b849-114977e8d9c9_4032x3024.heic)\n\nmúm on stage @ Hiroshima Mon Amour, Torino (November 12, 2025).\n\nI’m not the only one to think that the performance by múm , Icelandic folk-rock band yesterday in concert in Turin, was the bridge that allowed us to go back to those moments not just picturing images in our minds, but also listening to otherworldly sounds.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/46ed9569-eb4f-484d-98cd-525cd1761b20_3024x4032.heic)\n\nThe opening act was performed by Bjorn Daniel, an Iceland artist now living in Turin. A raw, intimate performance, and a passionate one, because Daniel was opening for one of his adolescence’s dream bands. Hiroshima Mon Amour, Torino (November 12, 2025).\n\nLet me explain.\n\nThis November, you can support Space of Sound for a special offer, equivalent to 1.5€ (under 2 USD) per month.\n\nGet 40% off for 1 year\n\nThank you!\n\nMusic can be encoded and decoded, like a message. And it is a message, which contains information about the sender, and - hopefully - should also contain some message for the receiver.\n\nmúm perform in a way that openly labels them as something different from bands from other places: like Sigur Rós, to say of another Icelandic band, you hear there is a different background.\n\nmúm sing and play like a delicate ensemble, only to explode in a shoegaze-like conundrum of sounds: one moment the stillness of a glacier, the next lava roars and a mountain erupts.\n\nThe songs are long exposure photos, they stay on the retina of your ears, they impress on your listenings.\n\nThey are both lullabies and marches, both quiet and explosive.\n\nFire and ice, like the Iceland they come from.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/00c0090a-6c6d-493f-a6c2-3bc57dfb8e37_4032x3024.heic)\n\nmúm on stage at the end of the concert @ Hiroshima Mon Amour, Torino (November 12, 2025).\n\nBelow, my favourite song by múm, Green Green Grass of Tunnel .\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_rising-sound-i-knew-everything-but.md": "October will bring you fresh records, new song reviews - you’ll see very soon, starting from today.\n\nZac Vanacoro is a music artist, singer, bass player and member of rock bands based in New York and halfway the world: Velvet Weekend, Plane Station, Austin Kopec, Christine Chanel and Smooch.\n\nToday his new solo album comes out: I Knew Everything But I Forgot It .\n\nThe surprise I had when I received my first press kit mail , presenting the artist and its work, with a link to listen to the tracks before the publication, was a wonderful feeling - and I thank you readers for that, too.\n\nThat mail came through the Internet, crossing half the world1, and I got to work immediately. Meaning, I listened to the songs over and over.\n\nThis is what I think of it.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d48c4852-4832-473c-94ff-454d034cca34_1080x1350.png)\n\nhere the playlist on Apple Music.\n\nThere and Back Again is a morning call, an alarm clock ringing alone: we know where we’re going, but “something doesn’t feel quite right”. And where has the time gone, that keeps running away? The questions and doubts dissolve into a final chorus, which like a circle returns to where it came from, there and back again, precisely.\n\nIn Troubled Mind someone heals our mind full of problems, and everything falls back into place: the chorus keeps repeating it, and the finger-picking in the second part seems to paint a smile between two cheeks. Everything’s alright, then.\n\nWith Chianti and Fava Beans it feels like turning on a radio to a different decade, having just turned onto a noir street, and ending up in a jazz club. The notes played and immediately withdrawn, the chorus sung in company, and the general spirit of the song, together with the horns in the second part, accompany the end of an afternoon while we prepare a party. With a bottle of Chianti, of course.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/63e5f655-a7d1-45ff-8dda-4b4463b89912_4802x6159.png)\n\nEverything Stays is more delicate, slower, we’re full of thoughts as we listen to it: all our experiences stay in their place, the lyrics suggest. The piano notes accompanying the second verse are a brief window opened, but immediately closed again, onto the river of our thoughts. If it were a house, this song would have two windows open facing each other, and the wind would pass between them. Is it a current, if it doesn’t pass through you? Really, it passes through the final chorus, with full and moving strings.\n\nApril wasn’t born in April, but feels that’s their home, wants to return there. But it talks about what happens in the meantime, between November and April again, and the journey is metaphorical, but we feel spring in the choruses and guitars.\n\nCoffee!\n\nOver and Over begins with a guitar, continues with a guitar, two voices join in, we’re in a room, or we’re around a bonfire, then a piano is added, and then we’re in front of a fireplace, because we still feel that warmth. The guitar strumming wraps around us, over and over again.\n\nDaisy starts straight, in the evening, a drum kit, the usual full guitar and again a voice that cascades from one verse to another: but it’s not the usual song, an electric guitar is introduced, and the distortions reconstruct it. A live song, it would seem.\n\nAmen talks about having lost your head in the sand, on the shoreline. And having lost your head, in a metaphorical sense, up in the sky. And then the prayer to find a god in wine, and the song becomes almost an electric-gospel-for-Friday-night. I’d go to that bar, if I knew which one it was.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/bb234961-b4ad-4774-9e12-f4f0f38bc22c_1125x1299.jpeg)\n\nOnly Losers Left Alive is advice, an open letter, you have to be careful: you only fall when you’ve climbed somewhere. Its eight minutes are a journey, a procession, a band in celebration, a fair, a festival. They’re a soundtrack and end credits, the ending and the whole journey. In this journey, it’s normal to feel “ tired “. The song never tires though, with the second part being an incredible ride, worth the entire album. Truly remarkable.\n\nWhen I Get To Heaven is a blues vocal, in brevity and style.\n\nLady In The Radiator reassures us, everything’s fine in heaven. And everything seems to suggest it, but with a slightly eerie twist: the processed voice, the suspended rhythm, overflowing and somewhat nocturnal drum beat recalls a ghost you might have encountered at night at the end of October. It fully belongs to the songs you might have heard coming-from-the-bathroom-of-a-nightclub.\n\nMy Oh My talks about growing up “Oh, fuck!”. The older you get the fewer people you know. It seems like a singer’s song in a sing-along at the end of a concert. Maybe it’s too delicate in the final part for that kind of thing, but I wouldn’t mind.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5dea597f-3545-4533-8f6b-052c4478499a_6397x6397.jpeg)\n\nI got surprised when I got that mail, as I said before. The surprise grew bigger while listening to the record, gaining a fresh angle with respect to my usual listenings. Not that this is completely an alien sound, but it gave me new perspectives.\n\nThe idea I got from the whole record is one of dedication and love to play in order to experiment , and this is certainly a plus. Music, as all art, must replicate the world, which is ever-changing.\n\nThis record does so sincerely and open-heartedly, and I hope to listen to Zac’s string live soon to change one more time.\n\nI Knew Everything But I Forgot It on Spotify.\n\nI Knew Everything But I Forgot It on Apple Music.\n\n1 I live in Italy.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_rising-sound-my-inner-goth-girl-by.md": "Today is a day of fresh music reviews!\n\nThis is what I got in the mail: the possibility to share with you the review of a song by musician Michael Chau, currently based in Brooklyn .\n\nhere the playlist on Apple Music.\n\nWe Had Everything But Time , the new EP by Chau’s new project The Field Index will be out on November 14th, 2025, and today is available to stream everywhere the first song, My Inner Goth Girl .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/05c8abab-444d-446e-884e-85cf316fc48f_1080x1350.png)\n\nChau comes from ambient and soundscape music, and My Inner Goth Girl in the first second gives you that; then, it transforms into 80s music in the way someone actually living in the 2020s would make it: you get the synths, and the drums, and the chords, in this order, plus a delicate voice, calling you to answer to one liminal phone call - in this times of social networks on a phone that does not ring anymore - and you’re all set.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/fda7d654-0278-41c0-a5aa-7dcecd68aedb_1036x1036.png)\n\nPress photo of Michael Chau. Credits here.\n\nNever “ surrender to the emptiness ”, because this single is full of surprised: it seems an undoing, a stripping of clothes to reveal who you really are after a run, to save yourself or maybe just to sweat a bit.\n\nNonetheless, “ The past is done, release the harm / we made it out alive ”, and this is all it matters. The songs builds on itself, it grows and becomes larger, the instruments make waves, they create an ocean of sound, Chau’s voice surfs on it, it reaches you from multiple places, it makes you yearn for more.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d738ea60-5252-4f29-b55f-f16a818a2193_2500x2500.jpeg)\n\nIn the other songs of the EP, there will be more of that. You only have to listen to it when it will be out.\n\nFor now, that’s a good song if you like night calls, or even that bright part of the sunset just before sun goes off in the west.\n\nSee you on the review for the full EP! Bye!\n\nMy Inner Goth Girl on Spotify.\n\nMy Inner Goth Girl on Apple Music.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_rising-sound-we-had-everything-but.md": "![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/53d6a0f9-ef24-4200-94d7-6cd0b8b92d0e_1572x1048.png)\n\nWe Had Everything But Time , the new EP by Michael Chau ’s new project The Field Index, has come out on November 14th, 2025.\n\nWe already talked about the single released last month, and in that occasion I promised to deliver some thoughts on the EP. Here they are.\n\nhere the playlist on Apple Music.\n\nThe record starts with Catch , which reminds me of something coming from Beach House.\n\nThe drums are entertaining, flowing through during the song, along with a line of bass, and I’m already there, but anyway \" take me with you when you disappear ”.\n\nTrouble in Mind is a silhouette, like the first word of the song itself states. It is a recurring theme for me with this record, you feel like waves, the ambience (we’ll return to that with the last song) Chau creates embodies you, it gets to know you and then it transcends into something that could have come from a distant star, reaching on to you because you’ve been chosen.\n\nAnd that’s just by listening one record, so you have to give them that.\n\nThe song fades, and another starts playing.\n\nCannibals is a song about “ something else ”, and the lyrics make their way through the music, the music is like heavy curtains and Chau’s voice appears to come behind them. The music has a rhythm that the lyrics can’t sustain, and at some point the lyrics end and all you’re left with is a drapery of sound, and you can’t peek through the fabric.\n\nAt that point, the song ends.\n\nChau comes from ambient and soundscape music, and My Inner Goth Girl in the first second gives you that; then, it transforms into 80s music in the way someone actually living in the 2020s would make it: you get the synths, and the drums, and the chords, in this order, plus a delicate voice, calling you to answer to one liminal phone call - in this times of social networks on a phone that does not ring anymore - and you’re all set.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/fda7d654-0278-41c0-a5aa-7dcecd68aedb_1036x1036.png)\n\nPress photo of Michael Chau. Credits here.\n\nNever “ surrender to the emptiness ”, because this single is full of surprised: it seems an undoing, a stripping of clothes to reveal who you really are after a run, to save yourself or maybe just to sweat a bit.\n\nThis November, you can support Space of Sound for a special offer, equivalent to 1.5€ (under 2 USD) per month.\n\nGet 40% off for 1 year\n\nThank you!\n\nNonetheless, “ The past is done, release the harm / we made it out alive ”, and this is all it matters. The songs builds on itself, it grows and becomes larger, the instruments make waves, they create an ocean of sound, Chau’s voice surfs on it, it reaches you from multiple places, it makes you yearn for more.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d738ea60-5252-4f29-b55f-f16a818a2193_2500x2500.jpeg)\n\nI said of My Inner Goth Girl that it is a good song if you like night calls, or even that bright part of the sunset just before sun goes off in the west.\n\nIt seems that is the mood of the whole record, and in cold November days it create an atmosphere you can feel, you can touch with your hands and breath in with every inhale.\n\nIf we’d listen to it, we ’d have everything - including time .\n\nMy Inner Goth Girl on Spotify.\n\nMy Inner Goth Girl on Apple Music.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-sound-anybody-out-there-by.md": "Here comes the sound of silence\n\nYoung Mister is the moniker behind Steven Fiore , a music artist and songwriter from Gastonia, North Calorina.\n\nAnybody Out There is track #5 on Young Mister, the self-titled album from 2016, published with the music label Refresh Records .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/79525ade-d4b2-46e1-b650-33977cbc2c42_1000x1000.jpeg)\n\nThis is a song and a constant questions, it’s a message of hope mixed with roots of initiating fear: when you care about someone, you might end up walking on broken glass, with fear of harming yourself, or making too much noise and startling the other person.\n\nAre you finding this newsletter interesting? Share it with your friends!\n\nIt doesn’t help that you end up “ holding [someone] with one [hand]” and “ holding [them] back with the other ”.\n\nA lot can be done then, many roads lie ahead: you could “ slow down ” and regain control on your “ movement ”; exit the road and the race (is it really a race, though?); or accelerate every decision you previously made. That’s your choice: “ I’m leaving it up to you ”.\n\nThe question then arises naturally: however personal and subjective those actions are, “ isn’t there something we can both do? ”\n\nAnd here come other questions, those we ended up in the first place: is there “ anybody out there ” who is willing to commit to the same idea of love, with the same amount of courage it necessitates, properly understanding “ what I mean ”, that could make our “ chemicals balanced ”?\n\nThere are no simple and direct answers. What seems to be intertwined with that quest is the need to find that same “ burning question ” in someone else’s eyes.\n\nAnd then, when “we finally think” “the same thing at the same time”, well, you can say found someone “ there for me ”. Or did you?\n\nThis song has a festive and summer-y rhythm vibe, perfect for a pool-kind-of-retreat. Drums are plain and simple, and there’s even space for an orchestral brass section in the second part of the song.\n\nA pleasant addition to our playlist (that you can reach here).\n\nIsn’t it always like this\n\nSee you next time!\n\nAnything makes a big difference! Thanks :)\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-sound-harvest-moon-by-poolside.md": "When we were strangers I watched you from afar\n\nFrom the band's name alone, a chill, sun-kissed, summery and refreshing imagery is evoked.\n\nAnd the expectations are all met, in Harvest Moon , track #4 on Pacific Standard Time , the first album by Poolside , a band from Los Angeles, California.\n\nThe band was formed in 2011 by Jeffrey Paradise and Filip Nikolic (Turbotito) ; it now comprises the former, plus Vito Roccoforte , Mattie Safer , Alton Allen , and Casey Butler as tour members.\n\nThe song is a cover of Neil Young's, and it's produced with a new disco touch in mind: a beat bursts from the beginning, bass lines come to support the rhythm, and Nikolic's voice arrives muted, then opens up more in the chorus.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/535ea2ea-bf9c-4eb2-aa25-9b18f5f4d6d7_640x640.jpeg)\n\nThe lyrics are a classic love song - I mean, an excellent love song.\n\nThe distinctive feature of the track, which made me turn up the volume on the speakers, is all in the sound that the cover conveys: it always seems on the verge of exploding, and it sustains itself for all six minutes tremendously well.\n\nA song to listen to in the evening, at sunset, at night: it's worth staying awake for.\n\nWhen we were lovers I loved you with all my heart\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-sound-life-as-one-by-skinshape.md": "We come in numbers, we come with need\n\nI stumbled upon this song thanks to YouTube's algorithm, which brought me here.\n\nSkinshape is the solo project of British artist William Dorey , formerly of Palace.\n\nLife as One is track #6 on the album Filoxiny , self-released in 2018.\n\nThe track begins with a drone sequence and a drum line; then Dorey talks about an ocean of cement, and stars that can be observed by looking where we are now, and far up in the sky.\n\nWe lie in an ocean of lights, we reach toward an ocean of lights.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d79d0a93-af31-4774-809b-fe8e70370600_800x800.jpeg)\n\nAfter the interlude that becomes almost lyrical, with psychedelic sounds and an even more drone-like sequence than the initial part, Dorey speaks of humanity as a single entity, uses a \"we\" but addresses himself; and gradually becomes aware of looking within, to cast a glance at his now outdated image (could the lights be involved, softening our shadows?).\n\nBut our strength is in being One.\n\nJust take a look, don't look too hard\n\nYou’ll see your image, yourself surpassed\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-sound-myiami-by-christian.md": "Christian Löffler is a German musician. After some field recording , he processed (without expensive studio equipment) various sounds on the drum machine1.\n\nThis song comes from Mare , his second album published in 2016 with the self-created record label Ki Records.\n\nIt starts with glass-like sounds, then a beat appears from the drum machine.\n\nThe song is instrumental, there are no lyrics.\n\nThe beat become more persistent, the sound starts to build up.\n\nThere is a reverb, now.\n\nThe music surrounds you, the rhythm increases, now it feels like a run.\n\nYou’re questioning where this is going.\n\nThe song is completed in itself.\n\nIt’s fading now, the wave has passed, “Mare” is now calm (but the record just started).\n\nI didn’t even noticed the song was on repeat, the flow of the song comes in circles and cycles.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b6f33bc9-e6ea-4fd6-a517-96e37a56b1cd_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nSee you next time!\n\n1 https://www.ndr.de/kultur/musik/pop/New-York-Tokio-Graal-Mueritz-DJ-Star-zwischen-den-Welten,christianloeffler106.html\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-sound-pda-by-interpol.md": "something to say\n\nsomething to do\n\nPDA is the first track released by Interpol , an American rock band founded in 1997 in Manhattan, New York.\n\nThe band was initially formed by Paul Banks as lead singer and guitarist, Daniel Kessler as guitarist and backing vocals, Carlos Dengler (who left the left in 2010) on bass and keyboards, and Greg Drudy on drums. After Drudy left the band, Sam Fogarino replaced him.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/31f4c593-4b8d-4920-844d-4e386e594e65_2000x1270.jpeg)\n\nThe album is Turn On the Bright Lights , and was produced by Matador Records . PDA is track #4 on this record. The lyrics were written by Paul Banks.\n\nPDA was also on Interpol’s third EP, self-titled Interpol ( 2002 ) .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a6dcdd30-5869-4893-bcf7-7146fb7ff1fc_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nBanks speaks of his partner's desertion, which he can do nothing but accept, transforming her memory into past dinners, remembering her as a winner.\n\nAnd second thoughts, considerations, efforts of will aren't enough: there are too many things that have changed since then, and \" now there is this distance, so \" the only thing he can do is offer her a place to \"crash\": maybe a couch, one of the many you can find at a party in Manhattan, where you still can't say anything to each other.\n\nAnd so only the rhythm remains, a classic straight rock, with drums reigning supreme, with bass and guitar lines supporting the driving rhythm of this song not of anger, not even of frustration: simply, \" there's nothing here to be into \" anymore.\n\nNot a disappointment at all, this song, which somewhat speaks of disappointment. Quite the contrary.\n\nNothing to say\n\nWhen there’s nothing to do\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-sound-perfect-dark-by-flyte.md": "Eyes almost closing\n\nFlyte is a project from London created in 2013 by Will Taylor and Nicolas Hill , that featured for a while Jon Supran and Sam Barrage .\n\nThe style of the band could defined as “chamber-folk”, and the songs are gentle brushes of warm voices and delicate sounds.\n\nPerfect Dark - New York version was published in 2024 under Nettwerk Music Group , and makes no exception. Another version is track #5 of the self-titled album from 2023.\n\nThere’s someone under her spell (but who is she ?), there’s a red room and a low moon entering that very room.\n\nIt is quite possible that we will fall under that spell, because “ eyes ” are “ almost closing ”, and there’s not much time.\n\nThe chorus displays the choice to resist to “ her perfect dark ”, where everywhere else there’s a blackout, and only the moon casts its light into that room.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/8084fb14-62d3-4ba8-90d4-a5611145fc1d_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nAnd maybe her trap is simply love, a kind of love that tangles sheets, and makes you forget everything else; then, sirens will woke us up from our dreams.\n\nThe song is a gentle and warm lullaby, with a piano and a delicate drum line which blends everything together, along with the guitar picking.\n\nA wonderful song to play on serene nights.\n\nTime's almost up\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-sound-shield-your-eyes-by.md": "I wish you could’ve warned me\n\nDry the River were an English band, formed in London in 2009 and separated in 2015. The band was composed of Peter Liddle , Scott Miller , Matt Taylor , Jon Warren and William Harvey , who left the band before it separated.\n\nToday’s song is Shield Your Eyes , track #3 on Shallow Bed, the band’s first album, published in 2012 on Sony.\n\nThe song starts with a climate-change-like metaphor: summer has come, he’s “ burning like an effigy ”, and he didn’t expect this. He is probably talking about some change in his life (and potentially his relationship) that struck him by surprise.\n\nHe then uses a mythological metaphor (the Phrygian lions that could supposedly see the future) to explain that maybe their love was bound to come to an end since from the start, from the gate.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ec690ebf-9254-4f9a-8fa9-90af5a15b6aa_640x640.jpeg)\n\nThe singer says he tried to change, to transform and create a mixture of change and love to make it work, but that solution was deemed unfit, and he was covered in “ warpaint ”, humbled.\n\nTimes change, and the relationship comes to an end in autumn, not in the summer.\n\nThat’s something lions could have foreseen, after all.\n\nDry The River create a solid rock song, with a classic line of drums accompanying the lyrics, to stress the chorus and haunt us with doubt: will there be another season? In life, every year leads to another.\n\nAt the gate of our love\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-sound-when-you-were-made-by.md": "A life of love is a long time\n\nThe Growlers is a project from Orange County, California. It now comprises one of its founders, singer Brooks Nielsen, and Kyle Straka on keyboard and guitars.\n\nWhen You Were Made is a song on City Club (2016), the seventh album from the band, published by Cult Records .\n\nThe song is a psychedelic ballad on two people who are “not in love anymore”.\n\nIt might be because they're afraid, stuck by worries. But Nielsen reassures, with her scratchy voice, that \" a life of love is a long time \".\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/89f2a5eb-b5b2-42dd-b7ad-425faffa3bdb_1000x1000.jpeg)\n\nAnd this happens because you have only one life, so you need to make the world \" less cruel \", and not get too down.\n\nThe song is a perfect hit for driving-at-sunset-after-you've-broken-up-and-still-feel-something, something strange that still hits you.\n\nAfter all, we're in California, a cinematic representation of love never hurts. Especially with a bass line and electric guitar like that.\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-sound-yoke-by-medium-build.md": "I guess it was better than the alternative\n\nYoke is a song written by Medium Build , the moniker of Nicholas Carpenter (Anchorage, Alaska) and produced with Laiko . It also features Julien Baker .\n\nIt is track #3 on Marietta , the EP from 2024, and it was released as a single some weeks in advance.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ab1e95c8-2ef5-417b-9690-a7fdefdfcc0d_1000x1000.png)\n\nIt's a sour song, in which Carpenter and Baker have poured all their nostalgia for something they never had, or had only briefly.\n\nThe love they sing about is full of stigma, caused by dogma. The weight they feel unites them, like it unites two beasts of burden - with a yoke.\n\nAnd this is the \" invisible man \" who guides them, and who guides the progression of this song, which begins with a reverberating guitar, before expanding with the chorus, where the air thins out and is traversed by an electricity that unites the two, and reaches us.\n\nA song that is also an experience, of unlived life, of broken loves, of broken singularities.\n\nMade some lifelong friends\n\nWho no longer acknowledge me\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-space-17-by-youth-lagoon.md": "it is a space I no longer inhabit, nor want to inhabit. Youth Lagoon is complete. I’ve reached the top of a mountain, only to then be able to see a much larger one I want to ascend\n\n17 came from a complete project: it’s the fourth track on the first album produced by Trevor Powers under the moniker Youth Lagoon , The Year of Hibernation (2011). The LP was followed by Wondrous Bughouse (2013) and Savage Hills Ballroom (2015) .\n\nPowers sings that the day you stop imagining is the day you die (or at least this is what his mother told him): should this be connected to the publication of two new LPs since 2023, eight years after the statement that ended Youth Lagoon?\n\nIt’s not why we’re here though - let’s not speak of the future.\n\nBut where’s here, and when is it? The year is 2013 and the place is Boise, Idaho (coming - running away? - from San Diego, California).\n\nPower finds himself with a brain that can think faster than [he] can but not fast enough , and with thoughts that he’s sure would lock [him] up if spoken out loud.\n\nHe flees to his younger memories, where life was as fun as can be, going out hunting for snakes (too dangerous? - maybe that’s part of the fun), going out camping and swimming in lakes.\n\nProduced alongside Jeremy Park , the song is delicate yet cadences the dreamy beat it also conveys in the lyrics: you can instantly imagine Powers reminiscing his younger years, and when the drum beat comes in you get his thoughts piling up and exploding, not too loud to make a scene, though.\n\nMaybe we’ll come back to talk about one of Youth Lagoon’s last LPs, but for now, let’s hope he’s still having fun, like when he was 17 .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/85932fb5-1070-4ba3-919b-9e0d6cff4764_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-space-cant-keep-saying-goodbye.md": "I can't hold on forever\n\nI need you to decide\n\nCan’t Keep Saying Goodbye is a single written by Spencer Ian Rakela of Animals in the Attic , a band from Sacramento, and produced with the contribution of Madi Sipes & The Painted Blue , from San Francisco, and Dent May , from Los Angeles.\n\nAn entirely Californian creation, which delivers that sound right from the beginning.\n\nIt's a song in which one can't manage to say goodbye: perhaps because we return to where we felt good, perhaps because we still can't tell you \" I hate you \" after having said \" I love you \".\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f42db343-caca-4851-b731-c323a5d33b23_1280x720.jpeg)\n\nAnimals in the Attic\n\nThe sound is a fresh - not icy - wave from the Californian Pacific, and the voices involved are all warm, well balanced: they immediately make you want to hear them live.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/858dc9f3-e245-48f4-9101-4a4214a166b7_3648x2369.jpeg)\n\nMadi Sipes & The Painted Blue\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/e249334f-a59f-4794-b1d9-cd8e1a62c1a6_1500x1000.jpeg)\n\nDent May\n\nDespite seeming like a not very layered song, in reality beyond the standard equipment of electric guitars, synth, drums and drum pedals there are also voices used in varied ways, especially in the pre-choruses.\n\nAnd the outro is worth the price - especially live!\n\nYes, no, maybe\n\nDo you love me or do you hate me?\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-space-halloween-store-by-andy.md": "Hi, I’m Norm\n\nAndy Shauf seems like a nice guy. He has a gentle voice, a good demeanour and seems to be someone you could relate to.\n\nNot to confirm the stereotype, but Andy Shauf comes from Regina, Saskatchewan, Canada. His first published record is from 2006, and he was born in 1987.\n\nThe thing is, he’s a really good songwriter, so he’s maybe more a complex character that appears.\n\nHalloween Store is track #7 on Norm, the 9th studio album by the Canadian songwriter.\n\nThe song is a song that could fit in a short movie. It tells the story of Norm, but he’s not actually narrating anything. He’s recalling what he forgot to do after he got high: to get the keys to go check whether he locked the house or not, to get the car keys from the car he got out of to check the house, and so on.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/0d028c7a-e643-40e6-bf86-9f83185fe45a_500x500.jpeg)\n\nAndy Shauf - Norm (Anti Records, 2023)\n\nIt’s a song that lives to get to the Halloween Store, where Norm checks a car to see whether it’s someone’s car or not; he then imagines to enter the store, to navigate the aisles and to approach said someone.\n\nBut then he finally realizes that he is still in the car, and there actually is someone in the “ blue car”, smiling at him.\n\nThat’s it. A little piece of everyday life, narrated and sang with a vibrant self-consciousness.\n\nI think we’ve maybe met once before\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-space-here-i-dreamt-i-was.md": "And just to lay with you\n\nThere's nothing that I wouldn't do\n\nYou can be anyone you want when you dream.\n\nWhy dream of being a soldier, on the “ streets of Birkenau” ? Or of being a Spaniard in Spain “ buried with [your] marionettes” ?\n\nMaybe because you built a balustrade with angles and corners unparalleled, and you cannot keep safe those you care about, all you are left to do is to “ travel without seatbelts on / To live this close to death ”.\n\nThe Decemberists are an indie folk band from Portland, Oregon. They formed in 2000 when Colin Meloy (vocals and guitar) met with Nate Query (bass) and Jenny Conlee (keyboards). Soon came and went Ezra Holbrook , then Rachel Blumberg , then John Moen (all on drums).\n\nHere I Dreamt I Was an Architect is the second track on Castaways and Cutouts (2002), their first studio album.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/311980ad-e00e-447a-af09-f3a9bbfc127d_2500x2000.jpeg)\n\nThe Decemberists\n\nThe rhythm is plain drums and keyboards, with some lines of bass to make volume. Meloy sings like he is in some sense only playing a part (multiple parts, when you count the soldier, the spaniard, the vagabond).\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/8045dfb7-32e5-48bc-8ffc-c0d6014a9e1f_640x640.jpeg)\n\nHere I Dreamt I Was an Architect Castaways and Cutouts (Hush Records, 2002)\n\nAnd after a while, when you “ try one” , and “ try two” , you end up winning (and someone loses), and you make end meet: be them angles of your barricade, or a relationship with a “ soiled […] girlfriend” who “ furrow[ s]” like a “ lioness” .\n\n“ Guess it always comes down to” the way you live (“ close to death” ).\n\nAnd we are vagabonds\n\nWe travel without seatbelts on\n\nTo live this close to death\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-space-lovely-times-by-suburban.md": "You've done it again\n\nCrossed a line\n\nriffs + synths. This is what you find on Suburban Living’s Bandcamp profile.\n\nAnd this is what you get, in Lovely Times, the fourth track on their fourth album, Almost Paradise (2016).\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/4597e80f-abfc-4fbc-8ea5-a6bfb5098af6_700x700.jpeg)\n\nSuburban Living, Almost Paradise (6131 Records, 2016)\n\nThe shoegaze makes the sounds layer on onto the other without space in between, so Wesley Bunch ’s voice is not entirely detachable from his guitar, Michael Cammaratand ’s drums, the bass played by Pete Pantina and the other guitar by Christopher Radwanksi .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/e2f44fc9-b9dc-46d7-8eeb-7d00f695cf26_700x700.jpeg)\n\nThe record is produced by Jeff Zeigler, who puts a little of his previous works with War on Drugs in this songs too, to make this band sound like a source of noisy sound.\n\nThe lyrics are well screamed, and “ all that’s left is an empty apology ”, but “ no one cares ”. Undisclosed sadness permeates this song, with some attention to the past (“ Our lovely times, were they lonely times? ”) which displays that they, like everyone, are also “ getting older ”.\n\nI'm tired of lying\n\nI miss you all the time\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-space-ohio-by-andrew-mcmahon.md": "Andrew McMahon is an American songwriter and music artist from Concord, Massachusetts. He also lived in New Jersey, Ohio, and California.\n\nOhio was released as a single in 2018, and then was included in the album Upside Down Flowers in the same year, under Fantasy label.\n\nOhio is a song on new directions, fleeing from Ohio to California, to “ start a new life ”. It’s also a song of new travels, and reminiscing old ones.\n\nA car (station wagon) covers many states, crosses many state lines, makes you miss your old state, but you’re full of hopes to “ get it right ” this time.\n\nAndrew is not alone, there’s his sister “ counting crows ” looking outside the car.\n\nNot just life, also music might be “ better on the west coast ” (on the radio, at least).\n\nHe makes some references to some “ men ” who “ never change ”, so it’s safe to suppose that they’re fleeing some form of abusive behaviour, presumably from their father.\n\nThey leave a “ blue house” , a “ red door” , and they feel a pull from the ocean (on the west coast they’re reaching).\n\nThe song has evidently a personal touch, and that’s the main quality it has. But it is not shy in terms of rhythm: the chorus comes with a good crescendo, and the lines of drums are well executed, and in the bridge section a sort of depth to the song is reached.\n\nSee you next time!\n\nAnything makes a big difference! Thanks :)\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-space-season-of-the-shark.md": "Sure I know it’s hard\n\nit’s not just one way of expressing my feelings, whenever I have to write a new piece for this newsletter, it’s also something Ira Kaplan asks in Season of the Shark , a song written by himself along with the other two-thirds of Yo La Tengo , Georgia Hubley, and James McNew .\n\nSeason of the Shark is track #4 in Summer Sun, released in 2003.\n\nYo La Tengo was already 20 years old, having been formed in 1984 in Hoboken, New Jersey.\n\nSometimes happens that a song has a construction, a rhythm, a way of presenting when you listen to it for the first time, that you know that has to be more to it than you can grasp at a first glance.\n\nThat is why I’m listening on repeat this song while I’m writing this, and so many things are there to be said!\n\nThis is a song about shadows: those cast by people behind whom you nestle (“ do you need someone to hide behind?” ), those created by the sun when you step outside, and those that reach you when you’re among four walls.\n\nShadows as reflections, sometimes not perfect ones, in which we dump our insecurities, casting them away not realizing they are what we reflect, nothing more yet nothing less.\n\nAs soon as you realize that, you could use them to connect with others, to realize that “ they’re not as bad as they appear” , and that if “ you need someone to help you through?”, “someone to take questions for you”, you can count on one another.\n\nAnd “ no matter how much out there scares you so ”, the shadows on the wall are like sharks: they seem scary for a while, then the sun sets, the season of the shark ends, and you end up being alone to unwind .\n\nKaplan’s voice is at once silky and sharp, smooth and decisive: his performance is aided by McNew’s keyboards and Hubley’s drums, to create a dreamy and warm atmosphere, a well composed lullaby that helps go through the periods when you sink so low, you even “ blame the sun” for “ the shadows on the wall” .\n\nIt helps remember that sometimes the only thing you need to know is that if you\n\njust look around\n\nIf it's not me, then someone else you know\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/98d5d842-67fc-426b-aaa6-6509f43ddae5_903x900.webp)\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-space-space-sound-by-beach.md": "I don’t really know which part of a song I prefer, choosing between the lyrics and the rhythm.\n\nIn the case of Space Song , by Beach House , I feel like I don’t have to choose: the song is wholly built with synths and drums as walls, and these walls are connected by Victoria Legrand , half of Beach House along with Alex Scally .\n\nThe song is contained in the fifth album, Depression Cherry , published in 2015.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/41a7d79b-a0d1-499a-a11f-d00d1be52546_1280x1280.webp)\n\nTender is the night , Legrand sings, but it’s a late night . She sings about a long night, one of those nights where you still haven’t grasped that your relationship is ending, or maybe you’re getting it now, while this song is playing.\n\nEyes are all that matter here: maybe you wish to find a smile in those eyes, among all those tears.\n\nAnd what will make […] this fragile world go ‘round ?\n\nIt’s a song that perfectly fits in a dream-pop scenario, playing in another room while you’re in the bathroom wiping away your tears, to come out while Legrand’s voice fades away.\n\nEverything will “fall back into pieces”, don’t you worry.\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-space-the-trapeze-swinger.md": "Please, remember me happily\n\n“ Do my best to make a drawing of God and Lucifer ”: as you may have grasped solely from this line, it’s not easy to write something linear out of this song.\n\nIt’s a long one, full of words, images, metaphors, and recurring themes of the “great American song”.\n\nThe project was formed in 2002 by Samuel Ervin Beam (Chapin, South Carolina), with an handed four-track recorder and all the instruments played by himself. The song I am talking about here, recorded at his home studio in Florida, is one of the last songs in the All Around the Well (2009, Sub-Pop) LP, made of rare and previously unreleased songs.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/beabebc2-1a3c-449a-a6c6-2158dd58173c_880x1100.jpeg)\n\nIron & Wine can be considered “ americana ”: Beam blends folk sounds and indie introspection, and his songs often display idyllic landscapes and personal struggles. There is a sense of spirituality in his songs, and The Trapeze Swinger does not fall short of this.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1320af09-04de-4a11-a294-3d5b151c979e_1000x1000.jpeg)\n\nThe song was initially published as the soundtrack of a movie called “In Good Company”, and it’s about someone who’s in between life and afterlife, or maybe they’re already dead and only looking back.\n\nBeam asks to remember him “ happily” , “ fondly” , to remember the morning after “ Halloween” when he was “ ashamed” , maybe to have forgotten someone he was with that night.\n\nAnd how many people we forget only to remember them when they are not here with us anymore!\n\nBeam acts as someone who asks to be remembered in a dream, as a dream of youth: now he’s like a trapeze swinger, floating in a fleeting moment in the air as between life and death.\n\nBut there are not only good memories, there is also “ misery” and rejection, on and around the circus with someone the “act” could not last anymore; and now life has ended, he finds himself in front of the “ pearly gates” .\n\nThe song features in his release version Beam who plays guitar and performs the layered vocals; in the instrumental part at the end there is what seems to be a flute.\n\nStripped down, this song is a man asking not to be forgotten.\n\nEvery human could relate, if you ask me.\n\nThe trapeze act was wonderful\n\nBut never meant to last\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_single-space-yr-love-by-roosevelt.md": "We’ll never be the same again\n\nMarius Lauber is a young artist from Viersen, Germany; under the moniker Roosevelt he has published in 2018 Young Romance, the second LP, and the one Yr Love comes out from.\n\nThe song comes out from a record that presents as a Young Romance form the title, but the result is not a simple crafter song to shout at concerts; yes, the lyrics are not exactly layered, but the sound is solid and has diverse influences.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b0e60293-6bd5-4546-868a-0f8131d5807f_1200x800.jpeg)\n\nThere’s electronic music and the drum machine kicks in throughout the song; the end has some synth-y sprouts in it, and the guitars are rock solid.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/8857230f-ecbb-45d5-8878-614d732e74a6_640x640.jpeg)\n\nThe loop of the song is hypnotic, and Lauber’s voice is convincing enough - you would probably recognize this on the radio.\n\nA good catchy song - is this not enough?\n\nAll I ever know is the look in your eyes\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_singular-space-fourth-of-july-by.md": "As you know, this newsletter is composed of one piece published on Tuesdays dealing with single songs, and another in which I “review” (It would be better to say that I ramble on) full albums, LPs or EPs.\n\nWell, tomorrow will come out a review on a beautiful record from Sufjan Stevens, which contains a song titled “Fourth of July”.\n\nWhat better occasion that to share it with you exactly on the fourth of July?\n\nHave a read, and don’t forget to share this with music lovers!\n\nIt's a conversation between Sufjan Stevens and his dying mother.\n\nStevens speaks of an illness that spread like a fever, remembers that his mother died one night, like a firefly.\n\nHe wonders what he could have ever done to bring her back, compares her to a sky crossed by fireworks, wonderful but ephemeral.\n\nAnd his mother responds to him, almost reproaches him (\" you do enough talk \"), asks him in a sweet tone why he's crying, if he's learned anything from the fires, which explain with clear images that things fade away, people like trees, their ashes like fireworks.\n\nAnd for the first time she states something obvious, which no one really thinks about: \" we're all gonna die \".\n\nStevens speaks again now, wonders if the memory he has of his mother isn't packaged, modified somehow, if it will ever fade.\n\nAnd his mother responds to him again, once more compares him to a bird, asks him again why he's crying, apologizes for having disappeared.\n\nAnd then come the formalities, the hospital's request about how to treat his mother's body, the strange effect of dressing a dead body.\n\nHis mother speaks to him again, to give him one last piece of advice, to live his life to the fullest, to do it while he can.\n\nFew songs are as heartbreaking as this one, few encapsulate in a sweet and delicate voice the entirety of emotions that such a loss entails.\n\nThe version that closes the record has a choir at the end that, repeating \"We're all gonna die\", the mother's caring warning, builds an emotional outro: listen to it one evening, late at night, don't do anything else, and you'll find yourself in places perhaps a bit sad, maybe a bit haunting, maybe not completely pleasant, but that will surely know how to cradle you.\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_singular-space-sable-fable-by-bon.md": "Hear me out. Let me explain.\n\nWe will not talk about the new Bon Iver record here today, because it just came out and it will require time.\n\nTake this very brief newsletter as an invitation to experience SABLE, fABLE .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/bcf8bce7-89f5-4e07-b924-1588aac58bd3_3000x3000.jpeg)\n\nOur work week is almost over, or maybe it just came to an end: let us treat ourselves with this beautiful record.\n\nIf you’re in a hurry, listen to this song:\n\nSee you next time (tomorrow)!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-single-una-noche-mas-by-blanco.md": "*this email was already sent to you, but this time the header is correct. I apologize for the spam.\n\nSo I hope for signs\n\nAny time, I lie awake\n\nJosh Edwards is an english artist who studied flamenco guitar in Cadiz, Spain, and charango in Sucre, Bolivia. He came back in Europe and started a project with the moniker Blanco White , after some Anglo-Spanish of the XIX century.\n\nUna Noche Mas is track 4 on Tarifa , which is the second studio album, published in 2023.\n\nThe song reminds me of a time travelling experience I didn’t have: to travel back in time to assist to some muezzin singing on some night in the XIV century in Baghdad, Damascus or Tyre. But, instead of chanting the Quran, those people could have sung love letters to young princesses in faraway castles.\n\nAnd I have “ no reason to doubt ”, because with songs you can do whatever you want.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/508a7ed1-f1df-471c-a7f3-29ced001a3d6_750x750.jpeg)\n\nUna Noche Mas, Blanco White\n\nEdwards’ voice is naturally soothing and warm and calm: he could sing you to sleep quite easily every night.\n\nAnd the next morning, “ let the sun take you down ”, just to “ lie awake ”. And since you’re there, you should reassure your loved one that “it’s alright to stay”, just this time, “ una noche mas”.\n\nAnd though you're tired of it all\n\nYou said it's alright to stay\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-a-study-of-losses-by.md": "God is the garden\n\nI tend to believe\n\nWhoever you are\n\nI'll leave you the keys\n\nA Study of Losses is the last (and seventh) studio LP by Beirut . It was produced by Zach Condon , and published on April 18, 2025, by Pompeii Records .\n\nThe project was born in 2006 in Santa Fe, the city where Condon is from. The first album was substantially produced and recorded by himself, and the multi-instrumental and individual nature of the project remained a trademark of Beirut for a long time, despite the presence of band members, both in the studio and on tour.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a3f43055-8ff1-40ee-8d78-21ac4b8f1512_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nDisappearances and Losses opens the album, and it's a heart-wrenching instrumental track that immediately transports us into a world of memories, of disappearances and losses .\n\nForest Encyclopedia is a song full of questions, full of doubts and hopes.\n\nWhat will happen when I'm gone, when it will be \"long past the time,\" and what will happen to everything I've \"hidden in the trees\"?\n\nWill my legacy be betrayed? And again, what will I find, should I return?\n\nAnd return how, like a breeze, through the leaves, a little here and a little there, everywhere and intangible?\n\nOceanus Procellarum is yet another orchestral track, in which the chamber-folk nature of the project returns.\n\nIn Villa Sacchetti Condon speaks of a house that he no longer knows where it is, and that he seeks among the ivy lines and the fallen stones , and finds it in Rome, among alleys and tombs .\n\nAn elegant and heart-wrenching motif, intimate and personal, permeates the instrumental part of this song, as in Forest Encyclopedia, accompanying the transitions between verses and chorus.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/e4245e94-3b36-4555-8e31-cd1ec9208c15_1920x1080.jpeg)\n\nMare Crisium - the stress on the various seas are an explicit reference to the various floors that are present on the Moon - is yet another instrumental interlude, with strummed guitars and cello lines, violas and violins that create a musicality that permeates the entire record.\n\nGarbo's Face speaks of hair turning gray , of time passing and settling around the eyes , of habits changing, of now-sporadic encounters, of people drifting apart.\n\nAnd in all of this, are you waiting for me?\n\nOr am I mistaken, and you've forgotten your dreams?\n\nCondon's performance is heart-wrenching and inquisitive, mournful and pressing.\n\nMare Imbrium continues the instrumental alternation, and does so by conceptually continuing where Mare Crisium left off.\n\nThe violin rises, rises and then settles where Tuanaki Atoll begins, which opens with a selfish request, to forget about the world.\n\nAfter all, what if I drowned ?\n\nAnd although sometimes you can neither win nor lose , I still don't know if I should […] run or […] turn .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1fe14516-5ebb-4d9d-9263-1f9968662321_1200x800.jpeg)\n\nMare Serinitatis is another instrumental track, delicate and from which some of the serenity of the title emerges; it is followed by Guericke's Unicorn , the most upbeat of the tracks, with a more evident percussion line compared to the others: Condon wonders if this thing, whatever it is, can make sense.\n\nBut life, like lies, always finds - and they find - a way to present themselves - full of consequences, it seems.\n\nAfter a brief instrumental break, the verses repeat, to emphasize the inevitable truth of the cycle of truth, lies, of life and its end that one must face - sooner or later.\n\nMare Humorum is the next instrumental track, but this time a humming Condon appears, supporting the guitars and violins, and sustains the song until delivering it to the next one, Sappho's Poems , which is truly a poem that could have been written on a Greek island on a day without shadows, while two eyes scrutinize you, two eyes like razor blades.\n\nAnd you, are you aware of my plan? Condon asks whom - us, Sappho, his muse? Eros ?\n\nIn Ghost Train the lies return, something returns after death, when we will be free. Then the text slows down, dwells on dispensing advice - leave me now to be free - and to be able to think freely.\n\nA nice beat, strings and brass accompany this track - a beautiful announcement you will never hear in a train station - a ghost train, indeed.\n\nCaspian Tiger is an ode to the futility of battle, which, however holy, always leaves hunger. But it also speaks of watching one's enemies, and that something changes when we realize that they too die, that they too will be saved.\n\nAnd we can then say that \" I feel your pain \".\n\nMani's 7 Books speaks of the unknown, of the wild, of what you encounter when you set sail. It speaks of those who are not sung in the deeds, of those who are not saved.\n\nAnd there is only waiting for one's turn, being guided by the brass and drums of this track, which seem built specifically \" to keep [us] going \".\n\nMoon Voyager is an invitation to conquer every place, every space, every city: \" I'll be ready \" sings Condon, since he too is almost finished (nearly over).\n\nMare Nectaris is cosmic, spatial, extraterrestrial in its sounds - it seems like we are no longer on Earth. But immediately Condon sings \"You can't be above all this\", and repeats it, so probably it won't be so.\n\nAfter all, Mare Tranquillitatis continues in this vein, takes us to a place - Neverland - from which we don't remember at all the way back. Had we perhaps come to observe the sea of the title? Condon \"can't remember\", and all that remains for him is to be.\n\nA Study of Losses is a gem of introspection, a pearl of reflections on the nature of things we create and those we leave when we go away, when we embrace the unknown that will remain there forever, and that has forever waited for us.\n\nCondon is capable of creating a recognizable sound, of transporting us from the very first notes to a place different from wherever we are when we begin to listen - it is truly magic, a secular miracle.\n\nA complete listening cannot leave one indifferent, and a nocturnal listening might leave you a little more complete, a little more connected to the journey we all live, only once.\n\nWait out your trouble\n\nI'll make space for, I will wait for\n\nHeaven above this time\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-about-today-by-the-national.md": "I said I would be back in September: a promise is a promise. But I didn’t sit idly by.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d07706c9-ebf4-4dfb-bb41-8b7c0b3a0b26_1080x1350.png)\n\nAbout Today is the distance, the distances we don’t travel and those that unfold between us, the walls we erect, the bridges that collapse after our words transform into boulders.\n\nIt is an avalanche, a landslide, a slow inexorable rapid invincible defeat, without truce without hostages, it is a massacre of souls united dissolved singular diluted, in complete indifference.\n\nIt is remorse, the impossibility of communicating, the tremendous sense of despair, the dawning awareness, the irreversible actions that drive us apart, the splendid irreverent sublime terrifying laughter that accompanies a long goodbye, the hysteria of letting go, the tears that feed the end.\n\nIt is the long wait for the nothing that does not change, for everything still and immovable and imposing and asking for nothing, it is the repetition of our mistakes, the representation of our hopes, our dreams in the mirror destroyed and cracked and then reunited and this film will be projected once again, what can we ever do about it, you are far away .\n\nIt is a heartbreaking beautiful powerful vulnerable poem.\n\nIt is a question never asked, a place and time unspecified, the future, the past, they blend together. It is the realisation of fears, visualising the affront, abandonment and recovery, the individual and the couple, the community of two, the isolated abandoned independent autarchic state of singularity.\n\nIt is a river, a torrent, a flow that rests on a cold glacial lake of sadness. It is the inversion of change, the calm and the storm, the calm within the storm not before not after.\n\nIt is a thread that one tries to retie, work that’s never finished, a project that’s never completed, it’s a will that dies, that’s reborn, killed torn apart mocked humiliated.\n\nIt’s the most beautiful song by The National.\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-asphalt-meadows-acoustic.md": "At the gate, you handed me\n\nPieces of the plan\n\nBellingham, Washington. 1997. Ben Gibbard has so many things to say, and he starts a solo project. The name Death Cab For Cutie comes from the title of a song performed in 1967 by Bonzo Dog Doo-Dah Band.\n\nIn 2002, Chris Walla joined on guitar, Nathan Good on drums, and Nick Harmer on bass guitar. Jayson Tolzdorf-Larson and Michael Schorr appeared and left around 2000, mostly on tour. Jason McGerr joined the band in 2003, and Zac Rae in 2015 on keyboards and guitar, along with Dave Depper.\n\nAsphalt Meadows is the band’s tenth album, and I’m writing about the acoustic version, released in 2023, a year after the original version.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/40d367a6-3bf8-4ea9-a322-6be67c5fbf17_1400x1400.jpeg)\n\nAsphalt Meadows (acoustic) - Death Cab For Cutie (2023, Atlantic)\n\nYou should “listen to the ringing in your ears / the scrambled voices of your fears / whispering, whispering” , Gibbard sings in the song that opens the record, I Don’t Know How I Survive . He doesn’t know how to survive, and the song is a gentle introduction to that refrain. The song is “ gaining speed ”, and while it does, you start listening “ to the sound of your heartbeat” .\n\nGibbard knows you’ve been struggling, and Roman Candles is a follow-up to the night before, to the song before.\n\nIt’s one of those mornings where it’s “ a battle just to wake and greet the day” , but you have to “learn to let go” , not to let all the things you “ tried to hold” “ explode like roman candles ”. And maybe he should use some “ flames” , because now he can’t “ feel anything” , he’s like a rock in a river, “ standing still” while everyone else is moving.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d9f4ce96-f247-4165-a504-15ddc46abb68_1581x1054.webp)\n\nHe may need someone else, someone from whom to get a “ kiss” as “ a lonely prayer” . He would cherish that kiss and hold it in his eyes and his mind, although you can “ only know half of” that person. Asphalt Meadows does exactly that, and it’s a beautifully written song; it should be written on bathroom walls to let someone make good decisions. The chorus is worth the entire record, and you should do yourself a favor and listen to it.\n\nAnd people are like planes, always “ drifting off into the sky” : and what if you have a “ ticket” to board, but you lack the name of the plane you should take?\n\nYou should ride a wave of “ white noise” when the city is sleeping, and find light through the concrete of those buildings, or board a train instead, before the doors close. Beware not to get “trampled under your own feet” .\n\nRand McNally is an American technology company, and the name of the next song. An atlas of such a company is something Gibbard does not “ know how to use”; but he made a sweet song about it, so I have to correct him. In a sense, he carves meaning out of such an ordinary book like it were the “ Old Testament” . And this song has verses, too.\n\n“Here to Forever” is not only a beautiful promise, it’s also what Gibbard sings to want to “ know the measure” of: it’s a daring desire, something that would put a lot of pressure on you, be it “ God or whatever” .\n\nFoxglove Through The Clearcut is a declaration about the settlers, the frontier man who explores until the edge of America, only to realize there is “ nowhere left to go” , and that everything has been “ broken” and that this “ great land” “ slowly slip[ s ] away”.\n\nIs it a funeral without the flowers? Are clear-cut trees in a forest like “ tombstones” ? At least, they are “ reaching for the sky” .\n\nPepper is a song with a faster pace and has a great rhythm. You should end a relationship on this song, while you decide on one another\n\nKiss me just this one last time\n\nTell me that you oncе were mine\n\nand one kiss after another, you may end up being together until forever.\n\nI Miss Strangers is a song about the punk war (“ you were by my side on the frontlines / do you remember?” ), and on the realization that sometimes you can “ miss strangers” more than you “ miss [your] friends” .\n\nWheat Like Waves is a song that “I could not pretend to comprehend […] as a childless man”, but the violin and a gentle drum follow Gibbard’s voice into a lulling song you could play on a road trip where you want to stop being alone.\n\nFragments From the Decade is for those who “ in photos […] are were always staring through the lens / To some distant place […] would rather have been”. And beware: “ if you stare too long they almost seem alive ”.\n\nI’ll Never Give Up On You is an ode to leaving out of your life all the fake aspirations you can have, to remain with one another. The Plan is a gift someone gives to Ben Gibbard before he boards a plane, and he gives it back to us, in a beautiful little song that closes the record.\n\nCan I hold it\n\nFor a week?\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-bathing-beach-by-novo.md": "fade me away,\n\nI won’t ever be the same\n\nOne must love multi-instrumentalists. Recording your songs multiple times not just to score them in a decent way, but to record one instrument at a time. All of that without being carried away too easily by the fact that is your music - and only yours.\n\nBathing Beach is the second EP by Novo Amor , moniker of Ali John Meredith-Lacey , an artist from Wales. This record came out in 2017, while his first songs where recorded in 2014.\n\nLacey sings in a “profound falsetto”. This may sound counter-intuitive, so let me explain what I mean: it is similar to the way Justin Vernon sings in his first works under Bon Iver (which is a good thing, if you ask me - I didn’t explain what I meant? Don’t worry, soon we’ll talk about him).\n\nCarry Me opens the record, “ full of aching ” and with a finger-picked guitar.\n\nAnd how could one carry a doubt? “ Hollowed” , “ borrowed” , “ shadowed” , the only thing you’re left to do is to follow “ every other shade ” and to never “ stray” in “ your love”, a love that “never came” .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ee3e692d-3c48-400e-b404-a2f2723c8522_1707x2560.webp)\n\nAli John Meredith-Lacey\n\nColourway should be played at dusk. But “ I don’t know where we went” , “ dear” , so we should be glad to be “ coloured in” again, me and you altogether.\n\nAnd beware, that love can also be another person, but that person could “ lock” you “ in […] heaven” . But you’ll always remember them, for the “ wave” they “ have made” .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1f6938f7-3be1-4078-a0af-890d105b3b44_1000x1000.jpeg)\n\nAnchor is a chord away to be disrupted by pain (listen to the first seconds and you’ll get why). There is an ocean, a storm, circles leading nowhere, while you search for “ someone else ”. There is a “ ship” , that’s coming for you and me, for us, and we’ll create a sea with our “ tears ” where “ I’ll swim ”.\n\nAnd while you’ll swim in circles, I’ll need you to stay near our boat, so please “ anchor up to me, love ”.\n\nThe record ends with Embody me, which is a prayer you should learn by heart for those nights in life when you’re all alone, longing for someone, when your “body needs” their “body heat”. You’ll be in a “ decorated bed” , “ separated [not only] in your head”.\n\nThat someone that stays in agony when not with you will come back, and you will ask “ Oh, where’ve you been ” and will answer that he was navigating “ every present that you had” , where you are not a “ wreck” .\n\nThis record is so intimate it could have been composed inside an oak tree, but there is an ocean in it, and it certainly feels like that when you listen to these songs one after another.\n\nwhat a way\n\nto be living with all of your pain\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-big-red-machine-by-big.md": "Well, ya better not fuck this up\n\nWell, ya better not fuck this up\n\nBig Red Machine was an idea before it became a project. It was 2008 and MySpace was still a thing, and Aaron Dessner of The National contacted Justin Vernon of Bon Iver and proposed to write a song for Dark Was the Night, a record for the Red Hot Organization. The song was self-titled.\n\nThe two of them began a collaboration that ten years later led to this first record, the self-titled Big Red Machine (2018). The two artists produced this LP, along with Brad Cook and Jonathan Low .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/751f9578-a9da-47e4-948b-ac48a2ed4768_1400x1400.jpeg)\n\nBig Red Machine, Big Red Machine (PEOPLE / ‎Jagjaguwar‎, 2018)\n\nDeep Green opens the record, and the sound is so well engineered that you feel, it is engineered . J.T. Bates on drums, Dessner on virtually every other instrument, Vernon on vocals (along with Lisa Hannigan ) and on guitar, and you get a two-to-three men band that seems to arrive on Earth from Alpha Centauri, having collected every experience from every planet in between. They’re not aliens though (“ not amounting to your mother or your father ”) and they’re not here to teach: I mean, they do teach, but “ when you teach, you better teach ‘em to share ”.\n\nGratitude is even more layered if you ask me, with a wall of drum machine and bass pedal that hits you, and a performance from Vernon that’s so visceral (even more so in a live performance). Also Bates on drums is so good at arranging a sound that’s more and more changing throughout the song, and it’s a joy to see him smile.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2bc6c410-4463-4004-bfe2-a16b25f31150_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nJustin Vernon (left) and Aaron Dessner (right)\n\nLyla is so funny, so disciplined in making you move off your couch and dance wihtout knowing how, it’s moving (“ I’m landing ”).\n\nAir Stryp is a brief trip in an acid session that’s “ fucking up your classic ”, with a beautiful and unexpected ending:\n\nin the light of the room / in an old canoe\n\nwhat’s a girl to do? / in a world like you\n\nHymnostic is a farewell song, but the record is not done with you. It justs suggests you to “lay down right beside me?”.\n\nNew songs\n\nthat are old songs for us\n\nWould you trust someone that is only “ an apparition” , but swears to “ haunt you” , to “ hold you” ? What if they are “ a tree” ? Maybe you should, at least someone will be “ singing for your health ”.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/e706cff0-35ac-4891-bad5-8d50f51b2780_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nForest Green would have been great it were instrumental, but it’s great anyway. “ More and more time” in those 5 minutes and 49 seconds lingers for answers ( How I’m gonna get you outta my mind?), remembers carpenteering work (“ Ya remember when we took apart your closet? ”) and in the end succumbs.\n\nOMDB is a song built on accumulating drums and bass interactions, and to shape Vernon’s voice through Chris Messina ’s engineered vocoder (the Messina ). It’s treat to watch Vernon’s performance on this song live. The instrumental part in the middle of the song it’s worth as much as the entire record, if you ask me. The end? Even more so. If you have to pick just one song (why, though?) pick this one here. “Over My Dead Body.”\n\nPeople Lullaby , as the name suggests, is a lullaby. Shut the lights, put this song on and enter in another dimension of acoustic feeling: you’re touching grass that’s thousands of kilometers away, you’re in the forests near Long Pond, water is streaming from some river in the background. “ Use your [lover’s] heart to calm [your] bed ”.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1a49210b-96e9-4ed9-9c6d-c91cbd22a1f9_599x598.jpeg)\n\nBig Red Machine, Big Red Machine (PEOPLE / ‎Jagjaguwar‎ 2018)\n\nI Won’t Run From It feels like the view you get after a night in a cave, when you climb to the exit and look on a bright new day. And “ maybe you know, or maybe you don’t” , that sometimes you have to take things in your hands, “ took the matter to house” , “ to mouth” , and you have to go “ fishing in a harbor ”.\n\nMelt is where the record ends, although “ we wanted to keep” the songs “ on [our] stay on our sea” a bit more. But sometimes it’s a struggle, a debacle.\n\nWell, you are who you are\n\nThe record has ended, I hope these almost 47 minutes stuck with you.\n\nWhen you don’t know what to do, maybe it’s safe, wise, and sweet to yourself to just “ follow your feet” .\n\nI gave you all of my time\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-carrie-and-lowell-by.md": "what is that song you\n\nsing for the dead?\n\nSufjan Stevens probably need no introduction.\n\nThis is what I meant to write in the first draft of this newsletter, then I thought that this project is to make people unaware of such artists be made aware.\n\nSufjan Stevens is an American artist, singer, songwriter and multi-instrumentalist from Detroit, Michigan.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/11e4c055-096d-4c96-ab8a-5cf21515ef66_1500x1000.jpeg)\n\nSufjan Stevens in 2023\n\nHis debut album is “ A Sun Came ”, published on Asthmatic Kitty Records in 2000. By then, he published more than 10 studio albums, and several among compilation albums, live albums and EPs.\n\nAt the end of the piece there is the live for the album, recorded at The North Charleston Performing Arts Center, in Charleston, South Carolina.\n\nCarrie & Lowell was initially published in 2015, as the seventh studio album by Stevens, and was then published again for the 10th anniversary of the release, on May 30, 2025.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/12722cb0-0cf7-49fd-9b9f-c16e0d716658_2560x2560.webp)\n\nthe cover of Carrie & Lowell - 10th anniversary edition (Asthmatic Kitty Records)\n\nAnd I don’t know where to begin\n\nDeath With Dignity is a delicate guitar and Stevens' voice. Stevens speaks to his silence, but \" I don't know where to begin \".\n\nHe talks about oases in the desert, lush fields, but for a man without strength, what is there to do? And what is that song that is sung to the dead?\n\nStevens speaks to his mother, with whom he has a complicated relationship, but to whom he is close in the hours preceding her death.\n\nAfter all, \" every road leads to an end \".\n\nThe only thing I want to believe\n\nShould Have Known Better is a sequence of regrets, which Stevens realizes after having removed his \" shroud \". Because with that on, you can't see clearly what's important, you can't grieve, there's no time for it, and he remembers: \" Nothing can be changed \".\n\nStevens is afraid of his feelings: he says it, he sings it, he would just like to be a \"relief\". But he is not the \" captain of [his] feelings \".\n\nAnd even if nothing can be changed, or perhaps precisely because of this, Stevens has a regret: \"I should have wrote a letter\". But it wouldn't have been enough, because it would have told of an \"empty feeling\".\n\nHe receives light from his niece, his brother's daughter: \" the beauty that she brings, illumination \".\n\nI’m just a ghost you walk right through\n\nAll of Me Wants All of You is a poignant song about a complicated but human, deeply human romantic relationship, or perhaps it only speaks of a casual encounter. Nevertheless, it remains a very sweet love song about the sensuality of bodies, about their force of attraction that doesn't really exist, but that we feel as if it were so (and if it weren't so, it doesn't matter, someone else will do it for us). Even though in the end, if things change, from \" all of me wants all of you \" to \" all of me thinks less of you \" is just a moment.\n\nNow, how did this happen?\n\nDrawn to the Blood is a continuous questioning (there are many questions that no one knows how to answer, in this album) of how all this happened, and what our fault is when something occurs that we (don't) want. It's also a song full of biblical references, between Delilah, Elijah, a dragon, a \"winged dove\".\n\nEugene talks about the place where Stevens lived with his mother (Carrie) and stepfather (Lowell). It speaks of loneliness, of his childhood memories, of his mother's death, of the fact that now \"I'm drunk and afraid\", of his being a singer, wondering if the songs he writes and plays and sings - won't they listen to them?\n\nWe’re all going to die.\n\nI'll talk about Fourth of July regarding \"Version 4\", the new version in this album reissue, just under 14 minutes long (the first was just under five minutes).\n\nIt's a conversation between Sufjan Stevens and his dying mother.\n\nStevens speaks of an illness that spread like a fever, remembers that his mother died one night, like a firefly.\n\nHe wonders what he could have ever done to bring her back, compares her to a sky crossed by fireworks, wonderful but ephemeral.\n\nAnd his mother responds to him, almost reproaches him (\" you do enough talk \"), asks him in a sweet tone why he's crying, if he's learned anything from the fires, which explain with clear images that things fade away, people like trees, their ashes like fireworks.\n\nAnd for the first time she states something obvious, which no one really thinks about: \" we're all gonna die \".\n\nStevens speaks again now, wonders if the memory he has of his mother isn't packaged, modified somehow, if it will ever fade.\n\nAnd his mother responds to him again, once more compares him to a bird, asks him again why he's crying, apologizes for having disappeared.\n\nAnd then come the formalities, the hospital's request about how to treat his mother's body, the strange effect of dressing a dead body.\n\nHis mother speaks to him again, to give him one last piece of advice, to live his life to the fullest, to do it while he can.\n\nFew songs are as heartbreaking as this one, few encapsulate in a sweet and delicate voice the entirety of emotions that such a loss entails.\n\nThe version that closes the record has a choir at the end that, repeating \"We're all gonna die\", the mother's caring warning, builds an emotional outro: listen to it one evening, late at night, don't do anything else, and you'll find yourself in places perhaps a bit sad, maybe a bit haunting, maybe not completely pleasant, but that will surely know how to cradle you.\n\nI wanna save you from your sorrow\n\nThe Only Thing starts with throwing oneself off a cliff with a car, then being \"buried where you are found\", wondering if he really cares - about continuing to live - if \"all of this\" (life, his career, his affections, his memories?) doesn't please him.\n\nHe answers himself that there is a reason, and places his faith in it. But then again, \"should I tear my heart out now?\", because everything \"brings me back to you\". And so for what I see, so for what I feel, for what I touch?\n\nWhat is life if our life becomes another person, when that person is no longer there?\n\nsuch a long time ago\n\nCarrie & Lowell is a dialogue between Stevens and himself, with a double voice that continues throughout the entire track. And there are also two characters who enter the song, the two parental figures (who however didn't both raise him): Stevens' stepfather and his mother.\n\nThe song is a succession of images, (\" cottage grove shade \", \" covered bridge \", \" head on the floorboards \"), that bring Stevens back to a childhood that wasn't exactly pleasant, but also of trips taken in the state of Oregon, whose state animal is the meadowlark, which is mentioned in the first verse.\n\nThe dual nature of this song is also felt in the rhythm, in the continuous bouncing back and forth of the guitars, and of the drum-pedal.\n\nWhat can be said of my heart\n\nJohn My Beloved is a prayer, metaphorical to a lover, and real to Jesus Christ. The track opens with Stevens at the bar, drunk or just awkward, talking to the \" beloved of John \", that is Jesus, apologizing for reading his word as if it were a poem.\n\nAnd the song speaks of mystery, of life after death, of this one before it, of loneliness and greed, of awareness (\" I am a man with a heart that offends / With its lonely and greedy demands \"), of the fact that in a certain sense we are (already) dead, of the fact that the dove is perhaps the Christian version of the myth of Icarus.\n\nThe track is packed full of Scripture citations, and has an extremely high density of meanings; Stevens' delicate voice, the gentle piano touch make this song almost a confession (which perhaps it is, after all, because it ends invoking Jesus, to be \"near me\").\n\nFuck me, I’m falling apart\n\nNo Shade in the Shadows of the Cross is the account of how Stevens lived with his mother's passing, of the things he did and those he felt like doing, all mediated by the religious sentiment that drives and penetrates him.\n\nHe speaks of the way he felt he had to self-destruct in order to feel close to her, to emulate her self-destructive behaviour in life; he speaks of the brief moments of awareness after episodes of self-harm, substance and alcohol abuse. It's a heartbreaking lament, funereal in melody and rhythm, that delivers the most human and wounded version of Stevens.\n\nLord, touch me with lightning\n\nBlue Bucket of Gold is the album's closing song (not in the 10th anniversary version, which also contains demos and new versions of old tracks). It's a song in which Stevens searches for his mother like one searches for a treasure (the blue bucket of gold is a treasure rumored to be present in Oregon).\n\nHe would like to be part of someone's life, he would like something to admire, something to love, he desires a conversion: he asks the Lord to strike him like lightning, like Paul of the Scriptures.\n\nThe song, and side A of the record, close with angelic vocalisations, but at the same time lugubrious, divine but heartbreaking.\n\nDeath With Dignity (Demo) , Should Have Known Better (Demo) , The Only Thing (Demo) , Eugene (Demo) are less structured versions than those present on side A, but Stevens' voice strikes even more; the last one features the collaboration of S. Carey, among other things a member of Bon Iver.\n\nOh, will wonders ever cease?\n\nMystery of Love (Demo) , a song composed by Stevens for Luca Guadagnino 's movie Call Me By Your Name , is published here in a version similar to the previous demos: voice and guitar. It speaks of Hephaestion and Alexander the Great separated by death, of not being able to find anyone else. It's a not particularly happy love song, of that love that dare not speak its name.\n\nBut have you heard the story of my mother’s fate?\n\nWallowa Lake Monster (Version 2) is the account of the way Stevens imagines (or remembers) taking care of a mother, like a heroic undertaking, while another battle was being fought: that of the mother against a monster (abuse?) which in the end, this dragon, got the better of her. \" When the dragon submerged we knew she had died \". The instrumental outro is incredible.\n\nFourth of July (Version 4) closes the record. We talked about it previously in the piece. Listen to it again, if you want.\n\nmy brother had a daughter\n\nthe beauty that she brings, illumination\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-crack-up-by-fleet-foxes.md": "so it’s true, I’ve gone\n\ntoo far to find you\n\nCrack Up by Fleet Foxes is not an easy album.\n\nBut for sure it’s a beautiful one, so I’ll give it a try.\n\nRobin Pecknold created Fleet Foxes in 2005 along with Skyler Skjelset , whom he knew since high school. They were originally from Seattle, Washington, where the band officially formed with Casey Wescott on keyboard, Bryn Lumsden on bass and Nicholas Peterson on drums. Some of them would, along with some other band members ( Craig Curran replaced Lumsden on bass, and was later replaced by Christian Wargo ; Josh Tillman - Father John Misty - took the place of Peterson; Morgan Henderson later joined the band). On tour, the band also featured - Matt Barrick on drums, and now features Christopher Icasiano .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/bec5bcb6-8974-473f-8ba4-809db3f4502c_790x395.webp)\n\nthe band in 2008.\n\nPecknold is the main singer in the band, with some backing vocals by various members; he’s also the writer of the songs, that are frequently evocative of historical and geographical references, and not so easy to decipher.\n\nCrack-Up came in 2017, after a six-year hiatus since the previous record, Helplessness Blues . It was produced by Pecknold and Skjelset, and features 11 tracks.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f1b37b2f-ca91-44e5-a142-83c2cdc053cf_1000x1000.jpeg)\n\nFleet Foxes, Crack-Up (Nonesuch Records, 2017)\n\n[Sixth floor, alone]\n\nCrack-Up opens with “ I Am All That I Need / Arroyo Seco / Thumbprint Scar ” and a whisper.\n\n[The band kicks the loner off the stage][Into the city]\n\nNot only a whisper, also on the Bb / F chord that is the exact chord the last album ends on.\n\n[Exit out of the city][Now memory]\n\nThen the songs opens with up-tempo guitars.\n\n[Out of memory]\n\n(Distant light, distant dancer)\n\nThe place in the second part, almost like a teather piece, goes into the city.\n\n[Back into the city][At the edge of the ocean]\n\nThe rhythm is more rapid, everything is electric, and in this atmosphere “It was all just water, winding by you”, Pecknold asks whether he could survive and resist to the night.\n\nWhat if you say to me “ I don't need you”: do I have to hope that you’re not meaning it? Or maybe it will be like “ I never knew you” , and all will be behind us, like the sea?\n\n[Under the water] [Rain]\n\nIn Cassius, - you’re [ under the water] , or maybe in the [ rain ]. The song is a reference among the others, to Cassius Clay (Muhammad Ali).\n\n[Above the surface]\n\nIt starts underwater, where you feel difficult to breathe; in the first verse it opens up a bit and Pecknold’s voice starts to come out, only to explode in the first chorus. This movement is surrounded by guitars, bass drums, particularly in the choir.\n\n[Under the water again]\n\nThe different sounds one encounters are also produced by instruments such as glass harmonica, harpsichord and organ. The song closes with a drone-y tail and a loop, to which are layered what sounds like a flute and an encore of drums.\n\n[Above the surface]\n\n[At sea, in a storm]\n\nThe natural prosecution of this song is the next, - Naiads, Cassadies .\n\n[The storm suddenly breaks] [In a car, on the coast]\n\nHere we encounter once again the superb writing style of the band’s lead singer, with an ode to the nymphs, which represent women whose “ life was stolen from ”. It’s a song that asks “Who”, and we can imagine it’s referred to all those things that happen between man and woman, that constitute a relationship.\n\n[At night]\n\nKept Woman is about Anna, a woman that in the song is “ lost in a shadow ” of “ cinder and smoke ”.\n\n[It bloomed]\n\n[It wilted]\n\nThe singer acknowledges the bold nature of this woman, although she is “ nameless ”. But they’re “ meant to be reconciled” , so he keeps his hope.\n\n[It bloomed]\n\n[It wilted]\n\nThird of May / Ōdaigahara is a song that starts with a song that does exactly what I think songs do: it remains even when “ light end [s] the night ”. Now the rhythm is less tense, the sound is more open, guitar and drums go hand in hand to provide a compelling sound.\n\n[It rose]\n\nWhat happened on the third of may? “ Everything fell in line” , Pecknold sings, “ as it was designed” : but things are “ painted in sand” , so the shore and the waves and water wash them away swiftly.\n\nAren’t we made to be crowded together, like leaves?\n\nThe song is like a journey, divided into phases, like Pecknold himself writes: first comes the upbeat, then the realisation of a doubt and the second part kicks in, with fraught sounds and instruments played solely by the wind, it appears.\n\n[January 20th, 2017]\n\nIf You Need to, Keep Time on Me is a wonderful song. It is stripped down, comes deep from Pecknold’s experiences and relationships, and speaks of the necessity to be each other’s “time giver”, i.e. to lead in a song and set the rhythm during songs. Of course it’s a metaphor, but we must not be “ too sure of the sun ”.\n\n[At sail on open ocean]\n\nMearcstapa is a song to be played on a boat in the ocean, “ on an open sea ”, to fear it once again, and even more. There is so much sea you can find its “ eyes ” everywhere, but you’ll find nothing, no sound the “ foam” (the waves) makes, no phone ringing to save you, to comfort you.\n\nEveryone is alone in their constant sea sailing. So who knows, “ what will you find” ?\n\n[January] [Dorian]\n\nIn On Another Ocean (January / June) Pecknold talks about no matter how far away you sail with the previous song, you’ll “ see all you leave behind you ”. The same eyes that were all around the ocean are now “ behind you ”.\n\nBut then this conversation Pecknold is having with himself changes, and the mood and the rhythm change too.\n\n[Alright, time to get over it, buddy] [Fuck this noise]\n\n[Cut to June]\n\nThe song wraps you around comforts you while repeating too many “ If only ”, because life is also made of thinking and re-thinking about things.\n\n[Major]\n\n“Fool’s Errand ” reminds me of a Christmas song I never listened to (must be the marimba). Pecknold creates one of the best sounding chorus of the record\n\nIt was a fool's errand\n\nWaiting for a sign\n\nBut I can't leave until the sign comes to mind\n\nA fool's errand\n\nand then compares a lover to all life one can see. Not a fool, not at all.\n\nThe piano outro leaves us on the steps of “ I Should See Memphis ”, where Cassius comes back with a sybarite woman. This Cassius is more evidently a reference to Gaius Cassius Longinus, a Roman senator who plotted to kill Caesar, and Muhammad Ali, born in Kinshasa.\n\n[...I don't think he got it]\n\nPecknold misses “ the highway ”, and now I do too, only to drive to Memphis.\n\nThe song ends on a drone sequence, and finally we arrive at the end, on the song which gives the name to the record.\n\n[Iceberg]\n\n[Iceberg]\n\nCrack-Up is a song for which the words “ won’t come” , but then Pecknold quotes Cicero, and then “all things change”, because the song hits a refrain which leads directly to the outro, where the sea comes back, “ rising over me ”.\n\n[Exit]\n\nThis record is a profound experience, but it certainly is not an easy one.\n\nPecknold’s lyrics are cryptic and layered in significance, the sound is rarefied and diverse, and the song structure is not plain. It seems like a diary, a conversation, a confession, all in once.\n\nAt the end on the last song there is a recording of someone taking the stairs, or maybe just walking rapidly: where are they going? who are they?\n\nGuess we’ll never know, but probably they’re going out in the sun, “ facing the day” .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b6875aeb-ef4b-4df5-af46-f80a6697f532_2048x1536.jpeg)\n\nthe band in 2017\n\nCan’t I just go to sleep?\n\nYou’re no more so blind to me\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-dancing-for-the-answers.md": "Nick Mulvey is an artist from Cambridge, England. He founded the band Portico Quartet , then left in 2011.\n\nAs a solo composer and musician, he published several albums and singles.\n\nDancing For The Answers was released in 2018, under Fiction Records Label .\n\nI would regard his style as chamber-folk, with a hint of electronica and ethereal arrangements, but I’m open to discussion.\n\nThe first song is eponym to the record name, and in over eight minutes many things happen: the song gently starts with a guitar-picking with the purpose of introducing the “ wonder ” which “ comes along ” “ every ” new “ day ”; with Mulvey’s voice also arrives a line of drums.\n\nThe lyrics are almost spoken, and they feel like a prophecy\n\nyou'll do all the things for which you came\n\nand there's no such thing as time\n\nnothing is lost and no one is saved\n\nand there’s a sense of discovery, it reads like a poem.\n\nwhen you find greatness in the peace that you do not claim\n\nyou will have it all\n\nWhen the lyrics end, there is a sense of suspension, almost like when you’re waiting for rain to come in the summer, and then the electronic nature of the song is unveiled, and the song erupts in a techno-ish ending.\n\nGive It To Kali comes next, and here guitar riffs arrive since the start. The song isa bit shorter that the previous, but longer then the next (a pattern repeated throughout the record) and it takes its time to build.\n\nAlso in this song, an important part of the lyrics are spoken rather than sung, and the start is a sample devoted to introduce “ all the things ” that you should offer to Kali, which is the Hindu Goddess of Time, Creation, Power and Destruction.\n\nAnd it’s a prayer to give her, “ really giving it to her ”, not faking it and taking it all back. You must be completely devoted (do you remember, “t here's no such thing as time”?).\n\nThe spoken song is sustained by percussions and bass lines that bring you to another place, a different place from where you started. A magical thing for a song to do.\n\nThe Doing Is Done is a song on “undoings”: parents shaped by their sons, darkness defined by the day - if you ask me, darkness is also defined by the absence of light, but the sense goes the same.\n\nBut it’s also a song about purpose, and the question concerning that purpose: “ where could I go? ”, what is left for a mother or a father?\n\nWhat comes next is to live “ full cost ”, embrace the woods as the place in nature to come back to, or the darkness , that embraces the Earth and the whole Universe. “ Pouring honesty” every day.\n\nPunta Cometa (Dancing For The Answers Alt Version) is an alternative version of the first song, and a line that closes on itself.\n\nIt’s a shorter version, and a more strained one: it looks like the whole journey Mulvey has anticipated in this short EP he eventually has crossed it to reach the end, only to be surprised by the same cycle of birth, life, death and destruction which comes with the goddess Kali and with a cyclical idea of time.\n\nA rather sophisticated notion, or maybe a narrative expedient and nothing more. Still, the song serves as a reminder, a suggestion or a proposition to endure, go on and continue one’s life.\n\nIf you put this record in loop, you’ll start wandering too.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/52d1aa6f-e158-425a-a6c9-bd45ca4cfe77_999x999.jpeg)\n\nSee you next time!\n\nAnything makes a big difference! Thanks :)\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-dragon-new-warm-mountain.md": "would you live forever, never die\n\nwhile everything around passes?\n\nI hope you have a cup of tea for this one. The last LP published by Big Thief is an ode to the cosmic infiniteness of space and time. There is love, death, grief, jealousy, but ultimately we all are pervaded by peace and calmness.\n\nStillness peaks, Change fades away, and we’ve only played the first song.\n\nDragon New Warm Mountain I Believe in You was published in 2022, produced by the drummer of the band James Krivchenia ; Big Thief also consists in Buck Meek at the guitars and bassist Max Oleartchik (who later departed the group, in 2024).\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b23f518a-1817-40b2-922d-6e403071a265_870x870.jpeg)\n\n“there is no reason to go down alone” is what Adrianne Lenker sings in Time Escaping , where “each dimension breaks in two” and “only the winter wind survives” . So let’s follow her voice through Spud Infinity , where she plans to free the celestial body, and learns that the past is not linear, life is a cycle, life has a cycle: drums surround her voice as we arrive at Certainty , where among other things we listen to sine wave is a particle ride, and the guitar is lavishingly laying on a plane next to us.\n\nThe track that shares the same name as the LP is a prayer, a spell, a love letter, a farewell to be read where the dust goes dancing . It’s a song of brush guitars, bells, icicles, and it’s beautiful on a silent night as on a bright morning.\n\nSparrow is a sweet lullaby held by gentle drums and Lenker’s voice.\n\nI love the complexity of Little Things , I love how you say when you say what you do , when you’re a little strung out . I could go on by quoting this song, you’d better listen to it (the song I recommend if you only have time for one of these). Claps are a fun touch.\n\nHeavy Bend seemed strange, then I learned it’s the combination of shaker, nylon string guitar and synthesizer. Flower of Blood continues that new sound, blooming on my tongue . Blurred View plays exactly how the title suggests: you have to wipe the windshield to listen to it properly; Red Moon seems to be reddened by the fire camp you’re playing this song around, and it feels exactly like that. Dried Roses starts with a surprisingly good health recommendation, and the fiddle plays harmoniously with Lenker’s voice.\n\nThere’s no reason to skip No Reason , where the sound is as complete as the lyrics, the flute and the tambourine propagate through the air like a fallen eyelash . The drum machine in Wake Me up to Drive would make me doze off, as this song is indeed powerful in lulling you, just like Promise is a Pendulum continues to do, although it can never make the earth turn . 12000 Lines are those I hope not to have to read while waiting for my woman to call , and Simulation Swarm is another great track made complete by multiple guitars, drums, and a shaker that matches Lenker's voice ups and downs - although it’s the electric guitar that sticks to you. In Love Love Love starts with a glitch, and then proceeds to ask us to release [her] love. The Only Place has so much to share , but so little to sustain itself: we end up listening to the lyrics, and we learn that when all material scatters / the only place that matters / is by your side .\n\nBlue Lightning closes the LP with a wish to be [a] mountain and kiss the sky .\n\nThat is sound advice, if you ask me, because\n\nI wanna live forever ‘til I die\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-english-noise-by-night.md": "have you recovered\n\ndo you know what to say?\n\nNIGHT FLIGHT are a London-based band formed by Sam Holmes , Harry Phillips , Nick Holbeck , Dan Webb , and Andy Leishman . Their first album was released in 2018, while this EP, English Noise , was published in 2024 by Roof Jump Records .\n\nEnglish Noise begins with a bohemian spirit, a written letter, a former lover, a request to know, to have news.\n\nThen there's the letter that Holmes writes: he asks even though he knows the other person won't care, because perhaps \"you were never really here\".\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/bbcdaa21-6c10-4515-9f6e-e6974c4ebc7c_630x630.jpeg)\n\nHolmes asks, and wonders, how they managed to survive the whole summer, and maybe only in summer, only in that season of life, could their relationship have developed: when everyone, boys, girls, are busy going out, going here and there, looking for a place from which to listen to some \" english noise \". But then, of course, a year passes, and maybe it's true that you were never really here.\n\nMonster is a desperate ballad in which we can hear from the beginning, and almost see, the pain of someone trying to forget, but whose mind does nothing but present them with the face of the one they would like, precisely, never to see again.\n\nAnd so the mind becomes a monster, thoughts its tentacles, and even if thoughts grow old, the body remembers, and creates memories.\n\nAnd if you remember a night at the pool, the memories make you drown, and if you used to talk at night, those same thoughts will make you sleepless (\" what kind of love is this ?\").\n\nThe Wheel is an impatient song, it seems to be in a hurry, but it's committed \"both hands on the wheel\", not to swerve, because we don't know where the mind is going, we no longer have control over it.\n\nWe'll just have to \"wait and see\".\n\nYoung is a tale of the bourgeois dream that's shattered by doubts about things that could happen within that very dream: a construction that's not bourgeois at all, in fact.\n\nSo it's better to take refuge in memories built when young, \" the Christmas eves and the trips to LA \", and all the other things that, you know, you do when you're young.\n\nSeasons closes the EP, and it's a magnificent album-closing song.\n\nIt seems winter has arrived, not only upon us, but also upon our love, Holmes sings. Seasons speaks of loves many times ended and then relived, because with time everything can be revived, in which case \"we'll see\".\n\nThen the song moves to summer, where the air suggests that anything can happen. Despite this, if even in summer \" you lack of any colour \", then no memory can hold.\n\nPerhaps what remains is to dream a life we might have found, within the folds of a time that no longer exists (and did it ever exist?).\n\nand it’s starting feel like\n\nyou were never really here\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/59cfa20e-e9c9-4050-b88e-2839ca4ac64d_1200x800.jpeg)\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-everything-we-see-will.md": "At The End of Times, Nothing is not just a cosmologically accurate prospect, it's also the title of an instrumental project by Sven Karlsson , a Swedish musician and producer.\n\nEverything We See Will Die is the second EP produced under this name, and it was published in 2016 with the label Epidemic Sound ; the songs are indeed instrumental, composed with electric guitars, drum beats and impetuous crescendos.\n\nThe Ground After a Summer Rain has a title with a cyclical meaning connected to the last track (we'll discuss this at the end); after a timid entrance of the drums accompanying the electric guitar, the two chase each other, growing more and more until they reach the point of explosion, doing so and leaving the same instruments on the road, tired, destroyed, tested by the effort.\n\nThe Sky is No Limit starts slowly, and here the drums support the rhythm of the guitar, until the opposite happens, and it's the beat that remains confined by the small guitar riffs.\n\nLast Sunrise in the Wasteland is in anxious anticipation of fulfilling itself from the moment the drums enter the scene: and when it does explode with a roar that leaves few seconds before moving on to the next, Once Every 20 Years , which is perhaps the most classic of all, almost restoring a sense of normality that ultimately, once every twenty years, is acceptable. Then a chorus comes to dampen this statement, and the electric guitars rise up and so no, it's not a normal song. A nice discovery.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/dac99829-156e-4f24-8011-ee514ba5dc9d_750x754.jpeg)\n\nSven Karlsson, creator of the project At The End of Times, Nothing\n\nStuck in the Apocalyptic Vision is the most \"hard\" song of the album, with a metal sound that suits the title well.\n\nPetrichor is the last song of the album, and completes a circle creating a loop of meanings with the first song, since petrichor is the scent that earth has after an intense rain - a summer one.\n\nCongrats! If you arrived here, share this post with others. Thanks!\n\nThe sound becomes a bit more lulling than usual - certainly more than the previous track - and it's truly the right song to listen to in the rain. Which when it ends, will have the scent of Petrichor, and its sound too.\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-first-light-by-dustin.md": "I'm in as far as one can fall\n\nDustin Tebbutt is a musician from Armidale, New South Wales (Australia).\n\nFirst Light came out in 2016 as his second album, produced alongside Karl Cash , also producer of Gangs of Youths.\n\nThe sound generally comprises of an alternative folky music, with sprouts of electronic music that will flourish in Tebbutt’s subsequent works - more on that later.\n\nAbove this record lie the shadows of Bon Iver and Sufjan Stevens: this is not necessarily a bad thing, it just speaks volumes about the influence these artists have had on the independent music movement.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/8a2768c5-0356-4edd-8a97-61b06a970da8_600x600.jpeg)\n\nFirst Light is also the name of the first song on the record, and Tebbutt here talks about being in love “ as far as one can fall”, evidently hoping not to fall. It’s also a song about waking up and witnessing two sunrises: one outside the window, the other in someone’s eyes.\n\nWooden Heart is a solid song from the beginning, with the direct line of drums. And it’s direct in addressing that there must be physical signs of your love: a name carved on a tree, for example.\n\nGive Me Tonight is what made me draw a comparison with some works from James Blake. It definitely is the most electronic influenced song in the record, and speaks of the “ sacred” moments in which you tell each other your names on a bed: it’s a sensual song about not making love, but in celebrating it. Works as well.\n\nWild Blood is an invitation to be together, a song to plead “ that you should stay this time ”. Tebbutt evidently speaks about love in his songs, and this is the main thread: here he speaks about wild blood that maybe is the reason his loved one is running away, and it’s the same thing that draws him to them.\n\nBecause they’re “ Still in My Heart ”, as he says in the next song. His love is now an “ open road ”, where the “ colours start to run” .\n\n“ See Your Gold ” opens the second half of the record with a delicate track of piano, and then a plain guitar-picking. It seems an encore of Wild Blood in the lyrics, because here Tebbutt assures his lover that “ I told you, you are enough ”, because he sees “ gold through the shadows ”. It’s a good song to drift away to sleep, as I sometimes recall saying in this newsletter.\n\n“ Hawlett’s Comet ” is not Halley’s, but indeed it comes back once in a while to remember you that “ This is our love ”, assuring Tebbutt that “ the charts and stars were right ”.\n\n“ In Too Deep” is the next song, and also the feeling we all have when listening to another love song. But love is not a finite thing for Tebbutt, as it seems, and he’s “ drift [ing] away from the surface ” of this love, only to come back and state, in the next song, that his love is “ Brighter Than The Sun ”, which is also the title of the next song. Here Tebbutt speaks about his lover as a lake, as a coast, as the entire nature Australia has, that draws him into his love, enduring and accreting it as a forming star.\n\nI Only Have Good Memories (Of You) closes the record, and from the title it could appear as a sad song (would be the first on the record). And indeed it is an instrumental track, but it’s not necessarily a sad song: it has something that seems unresting, in seamless motion, though. It his a good ethereal song to end a record, and it shows that Tebbutt is also a good composer, other that a delicate singer.\n\nBut I can't change the way we love\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-harmless-melodies-by.md": "Oh don't you see it now?\n\nI'm staying for a little while\n\nYellow Days is the project of George Van Den Broek , from Manchester.\n\nHarmless Melodies is an album released in 2016, when Van Den Broek was 17 years old, on the Good Years Music label.\n\nAnd here lies the first particular note: it doesn't seem to be a young, inexperienced, raw record.\n\nIt doesn't have the usual characteristics of a debut work.\n\nIntro begins with a recording of a BBC podcast held by Donald Winnicott, English paediatrician and psychoanalyst, in 1964. At the end comes Van Den Broek's voice, rough, almost broken.\n\nIt won't be the only time.\n\nYour Hand Holding Mine follows, with Van Den Broek speaking to someone he knows has suffered, who he knows has felt \"blue\". And his hands are ready to hold theirs, always.\n\nThe chorus is a repetition of this vision, and his voice repeats \"Oh, holding mine\" with this scratchy voice, almost a voice from another time.\n\nA Little While begins almost psychedelic, then a sweet guitar riff and a Bukowski quote open to a straight beat and a vocal performance by Van Den Broek unmatched in the entire album.\n\nThe chorus is spectacular, and we'd gladly \"stay for a little while\" to listen to it.\n\nBecause after all, we told ourselves that \"This is just you and I\".\n\nInterlude (It's alright) begins by replicating that elevator music just before the start of a live streaming, but immediately becomes more complicated, varied, between the drums, Van Den Broek's voice, the bass. An excellent interlude. (It's alright).\n\nGap in the Clouds disproves my statement about the vocal performance of Your Hand Holding Mine: here we're on the same level, maybe even a bit above.\n\nIt talks about finding yourself observing the sky and seeing only clouds, and then meeting someone who thins out a couple and lets some light filter through, and your heart is no longer cold, it warms up, and you go back to really looking .\n\nThe distinctive trait of these songs is the incredible way they transition from verses to choruses, each one better than the last.\n\nPeople shows the artist's vocal range, who displays an incredible voice, and once again here the chorus is a spectacle when it arrives.\n\nIt's a conversation between Mama and George, and an awakening to how the world works, and how human beings work.\n\nHere and there are scattered small guitar solos that show all the artist's style, who seems impossible to have that age.\n\nOutro (Baked in the Sunshine) is an August morning by the pool, or an early May afternoon, when the heat mitigated by the weather or the water shows you only the positive side of being surrounded by sunlight. This is the feeling that Van Den Broek gives, especially in the final part, which seems like the disc's final soundtrack, as well as being its last song.\n\nA crazy debut album, for an artist who makes his voice an instrument, but doesn't disdain playing excellent incredible arrangements.\n\nWe are all just people just runnin' 'round […]\n\nDon't let it get you down\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/442121fe-f960-4aca-aaa9-2f41f4bd5d26_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-live-at-electric-lady.md": "Now you’re just the stranger that I know best\n\nBleachers is a rock band from New Jersey, formed in 2013 by musician Jack Antonoff . Other members of the band include Mikey Freedom Hart , Evan Smith , Michael Riddleberger , Sean Hutchinson , and Zem Audu.\n\nLive At Electric Lady is from 2021, published with RCA Records . Electric Lady Studios is a recording studio in Greenwich Village, in New York.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/e2015f96-965c-47be-b9c5-6e6d913e8f9f_1000x1000.jpeg)\n\nThe record starts with Drive , written by Ric Ocasek. The song is a one-hit classic (it’s not the only hit on this record, if you ask me) where Antonoff lists a series of questions to his partner, the kind of questions we all should ask ourselves, because they deal with the faith we put in each other, to be able to fall, to err, to do stuff wrong, knowing we have someone on our side, that “ pay [s] attention to [our] dreams ”.\n\nDoesn’t matter that the same person we can count on to drive us home, also “ plug [s] their ears up when you scream ”: we’d do the same.\n\nNext comes 45 , like the vinyl format record, when Antonoff in another splendid performance takes us to a stranger’s garden, with blessings and flowers all on their side, having lost (Antonoff) all those provided by that someone he’s referring to in the song.\n\nBut like a 45 vinyl that keeps spinning after the end of the record, he’s “ still on your side ”, Antonoff sings.\n\nAnd analogies with the music are not all in the vinyl format: Antonoff talks about “ praying at the ‘90s' “ while everybody else moves on. All that remains is a shadow, both of that East Coast music , and of a love now lost.\n\nDon’t Go Dark is a song written by Antonoff and Lana del Rey, and is about keeping on during difficulties, when all you want to do is have a good cry; but it’s also a song that it’s direct in advising that help is not coming, at least not from Antonoff (“ If you're holdin' on to me, you're holdin' on to nothing ”). All you get from him is an advice to “ run like the wild” .\n\nChinatown is a song written by Antonoff and Evan Smith, and performed with Bruce “the Boss” Springsteen , and it’s a love ballad with a great rhythm and solid lines (“ And I’ll wear your sadness like it’s mine ”) where in Chinatown there is a Chinatown girl, that apparently “ rip [s] [Antonoff’s] head off ”, and with whom he wants to run away, to find “ tomorrow” together, “ out of the city” , “ right into the shadow” .\n\nHow dare you want more comes next, and it’s written by Antonoff with Patrik Berger (who also co-wrote track #7). The song is a sustained rock-infused and jazz-y influenced parenthesis with nice brass instruments and a genuinely felt atmosphere of companionship and love-in-making-music - notice the ( Alright! I like that take ) ( That was a good one ).\n\nWell, like Antonoff says, “ how dare you want more? ”\n\nBig Life is the one Antonoff is after, like he sings since the first chorus. It’s a song on cars, bikes, on wheels that feel free, on big lights as things to become, as ideas to indulge. It’s also a song on the desire to live a big life with someone and find their secrets, those parts “ that light doesn’t touch” .\n\nWhat’d I Do With All This Faith? features St. Vincent , and it’s a delicate ballad - plumbous for sure - on a love that can’t be, because no one ever met while one was searching on a “ crowded street” and the other hadn’t “ left [their] room that night ”.\n\nStrange Behavior closes the record, and it’s the perfect closing for a live record that could be played at sunset, and thus could end at night. The strange behavior is of a kind where you think that a girl, a boy, or anyone could save you, and you follow them “ around the world ”. That faith you put in that quest could be just “ hollow space ”, and you’d end up “ chasing shadows ”.\n\nIn any case, good luck.\n\n'Cause ain't no faith could take your place\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-mahal-by-glass-beams.md": "Glass Beams is a project created by Rajan Silva , multi-instrumentalist of Indian-Australian heritage.\n\nThe band was formed in 2020 in Melbourne, Australia, and released a first EP titles Mirage in 2021.\n\nMahal , the band’s second EP, was released in 2024, with the music label Ninja Tune.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/eb76777f-6f00-4670-a2f4-e165a3157883_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nHorizon sets the mood, it's an intro to Mahal , and immediately we're catapulted into a vibrant, melodious world, rich with sounds carried by the sands of Asia. Silva’s vocalisations punctuate a new jazz full of beats, with delicate yet decisive transitions.\n\nOrb is like looking into a mirror that multiplies reality. Then everything recomposes itself, and the result is a straight bass piece that hooks onto a pressing drum kit and guitars and percussion that support the structure. The second half has a sonic distortion that is also spatial - it drags us into a new environment, but only for a while: the ending reprises the initial theme, with some more electronic intrusions.\n\nSnake Oil starts more slowly, takes its time to fully begin. The piece's intro is devoted to introducing the instruments, and right after the drums enter, a bass line slips in, but then everything grows, and the ending touches on the territories of light but structured post-rock.\n\nBlack Sand is the EP's last song, and a magnetic closing with its own gravitational force. The bass interrogates the rhythm, the drums explain it, Silva's voice interprets it.\n\nThe EP is a breath of fresh air on a leaden (or sandy) day. An excellent showing from refined musicians.\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-maribou-state.md": "I don’t exactly like electronic music. That is probably not true, but I like it blended with some other genre.\n\nI don’t really know where I’m going with this, so I’ll go straight to the point.\n\nI stumbled upon Maribou State through their first studio album, Portraits (2015) .\n\nI saved one song in my Spotify favourite songs, then lost track of this duo.\n\nI caught myself listening in loop their second LP, Kingdoms in Colour (2018) , this fall, but I did not connect the dots that those two LPs came from the same group.\n\nLast January, Chris Davids and Liam Ivorym , the two English musicists behind Maribou State released Hallucinating Love (2025) , and it got in my feed (by then I had switched to Apple Music).\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/22f4dba1-93d9-437f-81bd-16767ddb1735_1000x1000.jpeg)\n\nHallucinating Love seems festive since its beginning ( Blackoak ). It promises to go somewhere, and it delivers in the second part of the song.\n\nOtherside is exactly how I imagine clubs in the 1930s in a retrofuturistic utopia, and shares with Peace Talk the presence of Holly Walker , longtime collaborator of Maribou State. II Remember feels exactly like something you try to remember when someone clicks their fingers in front of you after you zoned out while they were talking; it blends into the next song (All I Need) that carries you once again in a safe space.\n\nDance on the World starts almost Daft Punk-ish, then becomes the most danceable track on the record.\n\nBloom is another track where the rhythm and the cadence take you without hitting anything in particular to the next one. Peace Talk starts almost announcing some blending of Middle Eastern music with electronics, and it seems to exist only to be embellished by the voice of Holly Walker.\n\nPassing Clouds is an instrumental, and its position in the tracklist escorts you out of the club from which they will play the next song, Eko’s , that maybe should be listened to from a different room.\n\nRolling Stone closes the LP, and it’s a hymn you should not be afraid to sing, together with those you listen to music with.\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-middle-farm-session.md": "Sad music is so good to listen to.\n\nI think many can relate, and it is particularly true when it is produced by someone that you can imagine are listening to their own sad music.\n\nDaughter falls in this category: the trio formed by Elena Tonra , Igor Haefeli , and Remi Aguilella is always on the verge of cracking you up and making you cry, and does so by warmingly encouraging you to accept that not everything must be happy to be beautiful.\n\nThey formed in 2010 and recently released an EP registered at the Middle Farm Studios in Dartmoor, Middle Farm Session .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f999b62d-d2ae-49a0-ad0c-fdbd197cf915_1900x1900.jpeg)\n\nIt starts as a conversation with Future Lover , where we get caught\n\nlistening for sweet nohings from ghost in the room\n\nand Tonra presses us to answer her questions, “ what’s the future like?” , to which someone replies “ wait another year”, and we’re just happy to be interrogated by her voice.\n\nParty is not a song you could party with, but could be the perfect score for an end-of-relationship-kind-of-conversation, making that night “ the worst night of [your] life”.\n\nTo Rage is the perfect sequel to Party, where we’re left tracking the pieces left by those exhausting conversations that explode, when someone storms out of the room and you end up “ distraught” .\n\nBe on your way is the perfect therapy session you need after that, when you make sense of what happened, of the planets that mark the distance between you two; and as long as you try to “ be on your way” , you’ll find it difficult to “ reconstruct the scene ”.\n\nDandelion exits from that loop, and the music of Haefeli and Aguilella follows that more than ever, lifting a bit up the rhythm: and it’s not “ a shame” like Tonra sings, because it’s a brief parenthesis that closes on Isolation , where we feel the coming to an end of the EP, “ full-knowing we’re incomplete ”; and indeed the last song is Neptune , where we come back almost full circle to the Tonra of If You Leave (2013), but Tonra here seems to be a bit more liberated to experiment with her voice.\n\nIf you need to put some faith in a record, you should start with this one: in the end, there’s no-one out there to whisper answers .\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-river-calls-by-message.md": "My lungs on fire\n\nJerome Alexander is a British composer and multi-instrumentalist. He published under the moniker Message to Bears his first EP ( EP1 ) in 2007, and on June 2025 has published River Calls , under Lost Birds Records .\n\nRiver Calls starts with track #1 with the same title, and immediately comes to mind Alexander’s other works ( Maps in particular, if you ask me).\n\nThere’s electronica, and a constant beat, rain is falling it seems, echoes are travelling through air, and Alexander’s vocalisations guide us through this forest, one layer after the other, to reach the deeps of his intent.\n\nIt’s a wonderful first track, that sets the mood for the entire record, and makes it worth the whole run.\n\nAfter that comes Disquiet , where I recall echoes of I Know You Love to Fall, from the record Maps.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5382343b-a5e7-4e9f-9e35-84771888ac09_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nWhen I first heard this song, I travelled back in time, and arrived to a place in space where I felt grateful to Alexander to bring those sounds to life: it’s an emotional ladder which feels on the brink to explode and make you tremble, but then lulls you into a delicate outro.\n\nOpen Lungs is the only song properly “sung” in the EP, and what a song that is! My lungs are on fire , Alexander sings, and that is due to the moon colliding, creating a hole, now filled with snow and stone. Whatever planet Alexander is guiding us to, I’d be joyful to burn my lungs to sing this song (or maybe not, but let’s assume for a bit that I’m a poet - Alexander surely is - and that that it’s just a metaphor).\n\nHalf Light closes the EP, but the end does not come too soon. It still gives us goosebumps thanks to its layering delicate sounds and electronic-filled beats which resound now more than ever a heartbeat, making full circle with the first song on this record.\n\nRiver Calls is another great album by British composer Jerome Alexander, and I’m grateful to him for all those nights I spent listening to these sounds, travelling standing still.\n\nWhen moons collide\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-sable-fable-by-bon-iver.md": "disclaimer: this post will be too long for Gmail to post it in its entirety. So please follow the instructions of your mail provider to view it fully. Thanks!\n\nNothing’s really happened as I thought it would\n\nBon Iver is a project started in 2007 by Justin Vernon , an artist from Eau Claire, Wisconsin. After four full length albums, one EP and two singles published in the last years, on October 18, 2024 SABLE was published, an EP consisting of four songs. Then on February 11, 2025 it was announced that SABLE was only a prologue to the fifth LP, SABLE, fABLE , published on April 11, 2025.\n\nThe cycle of seasons.\n\nThere will be a time to talk about Bon Iver’s discography, dissecting every album and every song. But what excites me right now is the sense of joy in observing that after four LPs, each ascribable to a different season, the cycle has not stopped: it has changed, because this new record seems more “complete” than the others; maybe it finally shrugged off the label of “one LP for one season” and started representing for everyone a new era.\n\nAnd for Vernon in particular.\n\nThe near-blackness of SABLE\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5b04ba5b-8697-4306-b2b7-07d45d761400_3000x3000.jpeg)\n\nRings within rings within rings\n\nThe prologue EP published on October is composed of four songs, but the first, “…” , is twelve seconds of high -pitched drone that blends in the next, “Things Behind Things Behind Things” . A first version of this song was performed in 2020 during a virtual rally for progressive candidate for U.S. Presidency Bernie Sanders.\n\nThe EP/LP version starts with strings and drums, you could see some similarities to some FEFA songs. But the song is more spacious, the vocals are sung by Vernon is his profound baritone voice, the rhythm is sustained by the pedals. Vernon wrote this song after talking to his friend and fellow artist Phil, where they talked about dealing with life as with like a garage with too much shit, where there are “things behind things behind things”.\n\nVernon sings about not being able to discard his feelings to have become “his own news”, to be “afraid of changing” and to exit his zone of “dis-comfort” and to feel happy again.\n\nThe black and white video published with the song shows him barefoot and dressed in black, with a black rodeo hat, playing his guitar and traveling in a car while looking outside. It’s his version of Johnny Cash , as he said in an interview at the New York Times, Popcast.\n\n(Not) a waste of wood in Speyside\n\nSpeyside starts with a beautifully recorded picking of guitar strings, in a way that reminds us that Justin Vernon can also beautifully play without room for error. As the place that gives the song its name, Vernon distills words and chords in his falsetto mixed with his bass voice.\n\nHe wishes to make good although he thinks he can’t, and he thinks that his words and works are “ a waste of wood ”. He seems not to be able to make peace with his “ dynasty ”, and that feels wrong.\n\nHe’s desperately trying to know what “had hold on [him] ” , with its legacy as a musician and as a person.\n\nThe video starts in the same place as the first song: the dress is the same, and also the hat. The guitar is different, and he’s apparently arrived where he was driving before, because now he’s in the ocean, and stands there and swims and looks at seagulls flying by, all in black and white.\n\nAwards season is upon him\n\nThe EP/prequel ends with Awards Season , and here the video seems to show the return of a new Justin from the ocean he visited in Speyside, to the same cabin he was in during Things Behind Things Behind Things.\n\nHe sings from a black and white TV, then at some point the TV turns off and he’s sitting in his chair singing with his hands clasped. He leans to the back of his chair as the song ends, then sits up and comes out the door placed in the right of the image, from which filters a white light. He does not have to “ reach […] for the handle” anymore, he can live again.\n\nThis song is the realisation that no matter the difficulties,\n\nYou can be remade / You can live again\n\nWhat was pain now’s gained / A new path gets laid\n\nAnd you know what is great? / Nothing stays the same\n\nAnd he’s a sable , but he’s not alone ( honey, us the fable ). Now “ it’s the season” , and from black and white, there “ comes in gray” .\n\nBut you know what will stay? Everything we’ve made\n\nVernon was “cooking with the same stuff [he’s] used to” as he said in a conversation with Lil Yachty.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a06f0c82-f316-4bbd-af6b-81af838d2cec_760x942.jpeg)\n\nThis EP was him looking back to his last 18 years, and the culmination of his work as “the voice of a generation”, as he does not like to be called (but he is).\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1f569c60-8f66-42cd-b060-adc85d89e4bb_600x900.jpeg)\n\nIn the meantime he got happy, he felt “the boot he had on [his] chest go away”, and he felt in service of music: so he gave us this new record, SABLE, fABLE, and in his words it’s “my version of Bob Seger’s “Against the wind” ”.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/022a2eb2-ae37-4f92-b8a6-d4118e8165c3_3000x3000.jpeg)\n\nA long (Short Story)\n\nThe second part of the LP, which has a specular choice of colors as opposed to the EP, starts with Short Story keyboards and drones and gets brighter as it prolongs the first verse in the bridge\n\nThat January ain’t the whole world\n\nIt’s an acceptance that human are not made to be complete, that you can find sweetness in thirstiness and strain, and that ultimately you’re never really, really on your own. There is a huge amount of hope in this song, and the sound it is composed of explodes and then heals, and then […] repeats.\n\nKacy Hill backs up Vernon in this song, and a deer shows up in the video.\n\nSo much love, it’s everywhere\n\nJustin Vernon has become happier even more so in this next song, Everything Is Peaceful Love , that he sings\n\nAnd damn if I’m not climbin’ / up a tree right now\n\nHe’s steady on a rock , he’s not slipping , he’s right at home .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/03a20ad1-a451-498c-ba1d-95d9c7928308_1080x1485)\n\nHe’s embracing change, and that we can all change someday, and we’re parting ways, but “ every little thing is love” .\n\nThe video is directed by John Wilson from “How To with John Wilson”, and feels like a summer camp reel from the ‘00s. There are pedal steels, synthesizers, and all the village (in Vernon words, all the people that are creating Bon Iver alongside him) comes together in what is the most “pop” song on the record. Which is a great song, by the way.\n\nClose the curtains for this one\n\nAlthough Vernon sings in Walk Home that “ we don’t need” them, so that light can “ come in / and we can shed your earthly burdens” . Vernon himself said that\n\n“Walk Home” is a romp where you can’t wait to pull your clothes off fast enough and jump inside bed with your true lover.\n\n“ There’s just no more I can say sometimes” , to quote another part of the song.\n\nDon’t let shit rip you apart\n\n“Day One” comprises of a collaboration with Dijon and Flock of Dimes , and if the latter features Jenn Wasner , which is also a band member of Bon Iver when they are in tour, Dijon Duenas is a young artist from Baltimore that collaborated among others with boygenius and Kanye West.\n\nWell, can I get a rewind?\n\nJust this once, if you don't mind\n\nVernon got definitely a rewind, and let’s hope not just this once.\n\nGive me time\n\n“From” is a great, plain song, with a line of drums that is the best you can get in this record (Vernon is on drums on this one).\n\nI’m beset with what we could become\n\nThis song features a collaboration with STOUT and Jacob Collier, and the voice arrangements is spectacular, it seems they go back and forth in a three-minute conversation.\n\nVernon “ got time” now, he says. He doesn’t seem to be troubled in any way (he at some point imagined to have a wife and a family at his age now, but that seems not to bother him anymore: “ Just take my love in your time ”.\n\nI'm from somewhere far from here\n\nKeep the sad shit off the phone\n\n“ I’ll be there ” has an almost gospel-y vibe, and it is intertwined with the voices of Vernon and Danielle Haim , with the samples by Jim-E Stack , long time collaborator and producer of this album along with Vernon himself.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/8dade200-4ea0-440c-8add-321d6b27c804_1581x1054.jpeg)\n\nVernon moved (he really did, he went from Eau Claire to East Los Angeles), although here he sings “ I’ll be there / I won’t move” .\n\nHe wants someone to tell him something, not to tell him nothing.\n\nBut what if the place you’re moving to is occupied by someone else? Well, you’ll end up being “ no more alone ”.\n\nOh, babe / I'll take the pain\n\nIn “ If Only I Could Wait” Haim joins once again Vernon, and the two talk about the states they’re in, where “summer are charades now”, and dream about praying in a “ norther bar ”, where there is a good winter and light rays don’t hit you. But maybe that is long gone now.\n\nBut what a taste\n\nOh, babe\n\nIn every way\n\nNot for the freight\n\nI'll best alone\n\nIn high ways\n\nNow things really are arranged\n\nThe next song, “ There’s A Rhythm ” is basically the end of the record, although technically there is also “ Au Revoir” , which is an instrumental encore of the final part of this song.\n\nThe song is that song you have to listen to while watching the video.\n\nIt’s a laid back song, it knows it’s coming after a rollercoaster of emotions and different styles. It’s exquisite, and these verses explain his entire musical journey\n\nCan I feel another way?\n\nOr are less and more the same?\n\nCan I really still complain?\n\nTo be back here once again\n\nThere are miles and miles of tape\n\nYou can watch it, it's been saved\n\nThere's a rhythmn to reclaim\n\nGet tall and walk away\n\nhe created a new way of dealing with music, he was an oracle, not only a voice of a generation, for an entire generation.\n\nAnd now it appears he’s back. He left the only home he “ knew ”, “ for a land of palm and gold ”,\n\nA profound, vivacious record\n\nHe really seems to be centered, happier and in a new space, allowing others to take the scene. He said that his team is now more of a village, and I figure him as the man who founded the construction company to build all those houses in that village. Now he’s collecting all those different views from the diverse styles of music he embraced during his career.\n\nSparkles of FEFA and in particular of re:stacks are placed here and there in the record, and that really described the idea Vernon embraces: he outgrew himself from that period, he did not repudiated that person. That is growing.\n\nLet’s hope he continues this journey. In LA, back in Eau Claire, wherever: there will be a rhythm.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/d5429e69-fdf8-41f9-b653-52b6a88795e1_1240x690.jpeg)\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-singles-by-future-islands.md": "sun in the morning\n\nmy sun every morning\n\nSome songs are buried deep and then come out; it’s the case with a song we will talk about below on this album by Future Islands . The record is Singles (2014) and it’s the third of the band from Greenville, North Carolina.\n\nSamuel T. Herring (vocals), William Cashion (bass and guitar), and Gerrit Welmers (keyboards, programming, guitar) formed the band in 2006, with other members who later left the group. In 2014 Mike Lowry ( Lake Trout , Mt. Royal , The Far Field ) joined the band (drums).\n\nFuture Islands sound like wind through clouds, a light cone outside a station, a warm blanket on the first nights of winter.\n\nThe LP opens with Herring’s voice already “ waiting on [us]” in Seasons (Waiting on You) , and we immediately learn that his voice will be a fundamental part of this record. The synth atmosphere is poised in this first song and comes out more predominantly in Spirit , which you could experience while crossing multiple times the revolving doors of a discotheque restroom. This song is an invitation to be more than words and strength, but also more than […] kind.\n\nHerring almost cries or shrieks here: it’s a dynamic song, as he described in an interview; that “ create [s] tension and bring [s] people close, then blast [s] them with a message ”.\n\nSun in the Morning cuts you through like the first sunlight after a long night in which you had almost any rest; the sound surrounds you, Herring sings such sweet verses and you wish to pass them on to someone next to you. The only thing is you would end up waking her up: how lucky those who know that after all, “ she’s always coming home” !\n\nDoves has a warmongery for peace in the first two verses, then it’s a repeated beg sung by Herring and sustained by the band; Back in the Tall Grass opens with a firm bass and drums, then echoes into a song entirely devoted to “ thinking of you ”.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2cb1bbab-32c9-44b4-bba7-7ba1133acf3e_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\nA Song for Our Grandfathers has a similar opening, with bass and keyboards; it feels like a constant reminder of the one “ grandfather looking over me ” could have given; Light House is a little gem, I really think this could span different generations and reach them all. Maybe the great sound, the strong and sweet voice of one docile Herring, “ when I showed you the dark ” that gets me everytime, or the little growls in the voice in the second half: it’s a go-to for a great summary of Future Islands’ sound.\n\nLike the moon feels like when you walk on a beach at night, the drum machine as the waves, and the bass as passing light from a lighthouse, with someone you say “ I can call you friend / But I won’t be around ”.\n\nFall From Grace is nothing like its title: when I listened again for this piece I wondered “This could become almost shoegaze, why it didn’t?”, then the second part arrived and I corrected myself. “ Was it all inside of me? ” No, the song goes exactly there, I caught nothing fancy that was there but my memories.\n\nYou’ve been to the beach, you’ve laid on the bed at dawn looking for the first sunlight, you’ve gathered with family in the fields to sing about your forefathers; but “ don’t you believe what you’ve been told / people lie, people love, people go ”.\n\nAnd that is indeed true: you should not even listen to me. “ Wait for the morning ”, going to the beach “ staring at the sea ”, and finally “ ask […] [yourself] for peace \". As Herring sings, “ beauty lies in every soul ”.\n\nmy star of the evening\n\nmy moon always beaming\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-sun-divider-by-talos.md": "Take those tears to dry\n\nSomeday we will own our darkest nights\n\nSun Divider is an EP by Talos in collaboration with Atli Örvarsson . The former, moniker of Eoin French , was a musician from Cork, Ireland, while the latter is a composer from Iceland.\n\nThe record was produced by the two artists and published in 2024.\n\nThe EP starts with Baltimore , a gentle ballad made of piano and dreamy electronic beats, murmured like the singing voice itself.\n\nIt is a love song to curl up in bed with (it may be a recurring theme this, maybe due to the fact that I use to write this newsletter at night - that is, now you have had a peek behind this newsletter’s curtain. Back to the song, now).\n\nTalos pleads his lover to tell him what “ I’ve become ”, to remind him of all those times he left when they called him to stay.\n\nNonetheless, he keeps faith that the burning skies will clear someday, if only we “ hold our hearts in tight” .\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a259e39e-fa09-4b48-a420-0c4821f0e6bf_2000x1450.jpeg)\n\nMatter is a song sustained by French’s voice and what I think is Örvarsson on the piano.\n\nIt’s a wonder how this song, simple in its construction - at least in the first part - is an ode to what one can and cant’ do: are you able to darken lightning, to make contact with a star?\n\nMaybe you’ll fail, nonetheless you’ll end up “ feel[ ing ] alive, feast, recognize ”, and “ seize ” love. And who knows, maybe a star will rise up on your earthly “ broken, bright, ready ” lungs, now full of love.\n\nFireworks starts where Matter ended, “ but I’m weaker now that I’d begun” , although this does not translate in a weaker song: with the first chorus enter a sustained beat, a drum machine prepares us to “ those wars ” that “ were ours ”: all we are left to is to conceal and hide the bleed we inflicted each other.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/60fc24f6-c6a1-472c-b750-4f9063214b34_1176x1200.jpeg)\n\nThe EP ends with Landing , which is composed of a single verse and then fades in a chorus/ambient-y instrumental tail that should be rendered in a loop.\n\nWe had to darken lightning, but we didn’t succeed and now\n\nwe’re lightning\n\nand we hope not to\n\nfall apart\n\nlike stars in sight.\n\nThis EP is small and brief, but the 15 minutes spanned over these four songs are a precious gift.\n\nBut if you knew how to keep me, I would wait here\n\nWith all we lost, yet I was there when you were down\n\nSee you next time!\n",
  "../posts/space_of_sound/ss_post_space-sound-these-semi-feelings-they.md": "dné is a project founded by Ondřej Holý , a dedicated instrumentalist from the Czech Republic , and the album we’re talking about today is These Semi Feelings, They Are Everywhere (Majestic Casual Records, 2016).\n\nThe title already sounds heart-wrenching on its own, and right from the first track, “Meeting Points at 2 AM,” the tone is set with a subtle and delicate piano line, accompanied by distant drones that gradually approach, channeling the sound into a reverberation that lasts just under three minutes.\n\nToward the end, it shifts slightly into an even more stripped-down atmosphere, and the track transitions into “Public Making Out is Like Ugh,” which builds upon the previous one by adding some electronic elements, glockenspiel-like chimes, and stereo loops that disorient you until they fade out in the second half, only to return after a gentle drop. It feels like a song that was written and forgotten, then remembered and rewritten again.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/171038ee-6f45-4b62-b09b-d23234ab0d7c_1200x1200.jpeg)\n\n“ Driving a Car While Listening to Bill Burr’s Podcast ” is carried by new piano loops, and the sensation here is that of going around in circles while watching a small fire contained in a box. “ Stay Clothed Though ” is the only non-instrumental song on the album, and the only featuring, with C. Monts. The track flows with the words of the Anglo-Czech feature, with a hint of something Daft Punk–ish.\n\n“ Friends Cleanse ” is the musical equivalent of rummaging through old boxes to find pictures of a friend who’s now far away. And while you’re doing that, you find at least a dozen more photos you didn’t even remember taking.\n\n![](https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/0c0e5bec-f2eb-4ae3-b34f-1f8541089e36_1200x1015.jpeg)\n\n“More Like It” brings back the vocal distortion from Stay Clothed Though : the title is repeated at the beginning almost like a commentary, then makes room for piano lines that build into delicate and comforting waves of sound. Later, the loops and returning voice rebuild a tonal unity that completes the track.\n\n“ Reality Swallows Pusheen Cats ” follows the uncertain vocalizations of [artist], along with their murmurs and soft “mmmmh-like” sounds. The piano — a constant throughout the record — is present here as well, just as it is in “ Asos Model Crush ” , where percussive and ambient sounds are added, making the listening experience three-dimensional. It’s one of the most touching tracks on the album.\n\n“Unnecessary Conversations” offers a drone-like aerial view of the entire record, almost as if to photograph it as a single entity. Not obvious in the least — definitely essential. Toward the end, glitchy sounds transform this track into the final one on the record, “ Kitchen City ” , which, in its anticlimactic nature, could actually be seen as the trailer for this album, as it contains everything: from glitches to loops, to piano, to the spatial and temporal depth that emerges from this work.\n\nThis debut LP, arriving seven years after the first EP, already feels like a mature piece. It certainly contains ideas that are still in an embryonic form, but the work is packaged with care, consistency, and depth. In any case, it’s an album that gives its best when listened to in one sitting — 30 minutes of sweet disorientation.\n\nSee you next time!\n"
};
